<HEADLINE>
GEORGE W. BUSH: THE GOP'S MARIO CUOMO  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)   (This excellent 725-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 23 January 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, TEXAS _ The band played ``The Eyes of Texas are Upon
You,'' yet nobody who attended George W. Bush's second inauguration
as governor on Jan. 19 could pretend that only Texas was watching.
</P>
<P>
   Mixed in with a day full of speeches, parades and thousands of
pounds of roasted meat was a buzz of excitement about the future of
Bush, who currently enjoys state approval ratings eclipsing 80
percent and yet, for now, is keeping his presidential aspirations
secret.
</P>
<P>
   With the Bush clan assembled on the platform, Bush used his
inaugural address to build on the idea of ``compassionate
conservatism'' which he introduced on election night last November.
</P>
<P>
   It was a clear attempt both to distance himself from the actions
of his Republican counterparts in Washington and to broaden the
appeal of his party. Bush spoke (in both English and Spanish) of
rallying ``the armies of compassion'' to give hope to all segments
of society.
</P>
<P>
   Extolling the virtues of economic progress, free markets and
free trade, the governor also issued a warning against putting too
much faith in material comforts at the expense of sacrificing
society's moral and spiritual core.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has the next 140 days, the length of the Texas legislative
session, to prove that he can make good on these cloudy maxims and
keep some of the policy promises he made during the governor's
race.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of his agenda are plans to cut property taxes and end
``social promotion'' in public schools, whereby students move on to
higher grades without meeting basic standards.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Texas Education Agency, although over 40,000
children aged nine or ten failed the state's standardized reading
test during the 1996-97 school year, all but 4,400 of them were
promoted to the next grade.
</P>
<P>
   The governor says he is also willing to support school vouchers,
a more controversial scheme both locally and nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Happily for Bush, Republicans dominate Texas for the first time
since the Civil War. With a majority in the state senate and, in
Rick Perry, the first Republican lieutenant-governor in Texan
history, the party is well-set to push its agenda through.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats, too, have become vocal supporters of Bush,
making it more difficult for a unified Democratic opposition to
block the governor's proposals.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush successfully navigates the legislative mine fields over
the coming months, while at the same time defining his political
philosophy for a national audience, he could then activate his
already formidable network of supporters and financial backers.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire (still, despite the maneuvers of bigger states,
the starting-point for any presidential campaign) he has a large
group of loyalists simply waiting for his word to start mobilizing.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, in a letter to a supporter in that state, he
requested that the Bush faithful ``keep their powder dry.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bush keeps his party (and the rest of the country) in
suspense. He muses openly about the effect of a presidential run on
his family life, and his wife candidly admits that she is
reluctant.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, like Hamlet, Bush seems driven to assume a family
responsibility of a different sort: to pick up the standard which
fell when his father, President George Bush, lost his reelection
bid in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   There is a time factor, too. At a press conference on Jan. 20 he
was asked whether, if he decided against running this time around,
he would consider doing so in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   He answered that he was very conscious of ``the tides of
history'' creating ``windows of opportunity.'' ``Should I wait,''
he said, ``the window would probably be closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Some questions still hover over the governor's past, especially
his reckless youth. Yet, for the time being, Bush can enjoy the
benefits of being an undeclared front-runner without answering the
nagging questions that lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   There were no allusions to the goings-on in Washington during
his inauguration and, in the 80-degree Austin heat, it was easy to
forget them. Just when President Clinton had to confront his
accusers and jurors to report on the state of the union, Governor
Bush and his First Lady were waltzing across a stage to the
enthusiastic cheers of a crowd decked out in black ties and cowboy
hats. &QL; 
