<HEADLINE>
DALE BUMPERS MAKES ELOQUENT DEFENSE OF CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS 4th graf to change `indictment' to `impeachment'; subs 17th
graf to correct `Javier's' to `Javert's'; 2ndtake, subs 5th graf to
delete `congressional.' No other changes.) 
(ATTN: Ark.)  (Eds: See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-REPUBS,
IMPEACH-CLINTON) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a speech of rare eloquence, former Sen. Dale
Bumpers of Arkansas concluded the defense of President Clinton on
impeachment charges Thursday night, coupling an admission of
Clinton's sins and weaknesses with a plea for his acquittal for the
good of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people now and for some time have been asking to
be allowed a good night's sleep,'' the silver-haired Bumpers told
the 100 senators, who hung on his every word as they very rarely do
for anyone. ``They're asking for an end to this nightmare. It is a
legitimate request.''
</P>
<P>
   Recalling that James G. Blaine of Maine had concluded, 20 years
after voting to convict President Andrew Johnson in 1868, that he
had ``made a bad mistake,'' because conviction would have created
chaos, Bumpers cautioned: ``So it is with William Jefferson
Clinton. If you vote to convict, in my opinion, you're going to be
creating more havoc than he could ever possibly create. After all,
he's only got two years left.''
</P>
<P>
   His warning gained weight from his excoriation of the
president's conduct with Monica Lewinsky, the former White House
intern. Their illicit sexual affair underlies the two articles of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton may not have welcomed Bumpers' description of his
behavior as ``indefensible, outrageous, unforgivable, shameless,''
or his acknowledgment that perhaps the president deserved no
compassion. But that surely undercut any thought that he was
standing up for Clinton out of unquestioning friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Relaxed and discursive, strolling back and forth in the well of
the Senate, not standing stock-still behind a lectern as many
others have done, and eschewing legal fine points, Bumpers
introduced humor into the sober proceedings for the first time in
six tense days. Several of his self-deprecating sallies drew
guffaws. But he also spoke feelingly of the emotional devastation
Clinton has caused to his wife and daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons ``have been about as decimated as a family can
get,'' the former senator said, in one of the most explicit
comments any friend has made to date on the psychological toll of
the president's conduct. ``The relationship between husband and
wife, father and child, has been incredibly strained, if not
destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Bumpers' powerful presentation may or may not have changed many
Republican minds, and Republicans have a majority in the Senate.
But he surely stiffened the backs of any Democrats who may have
thought even fleetingly of deserting the president, and that is all
Clinton ultimately needs _ the votes of 45 Democrats, which would
make it arithmetically impossible for the Senate to muster the
two-thirds vote it needs to oust the president.
</P>
<P>
   A highly technical two-hour appearance by the president's
personal attorney, David Kendall, was reduced almost to the status
of a footnote by the Bumpers speech.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, Kendall rebutted five separate charges of
obstruction of justice contained in Article II. Many of them were
also covered in Article I, the perjury article, and so Kendall
plowed relatively little new legal ground. His strategy was to
contrast in every instance the sworn testimony of the principals _
Clinton, Ms. Lewinsky and Clinton's lawyer friend Vernon Jordan Jr.
_ with the ``mere suspicion and speculation'' on which he
disdainfully said the Republicans' circumstantial evidence rested.
</P>
<P>
   He accused the House managers who last week outlined the case
against Clinton of ``a concerted, partisan distortion'' of the
facts in the case.
</P>
<P>
   In a faint echo of the ill-concealed hostility to the special
prosecutor, Kenneth Starr, that dominated Clinton's defense in
months gone by, Kendall introduced himself with the archly
understated comment ``Since 1993, it has been my privilege to
represent the president in the tortuous and meandering Whitewater
investigation, which approximately a year ago was transformed in a
remarkable way into the Lewinsky investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Acid also crept into his tone when he described Linda Tripp, who
taped conversations with Ms. Lewinsky at the behest of Starr, as
``that paragon of faithful friendship,'' and when he repeatedly
referred to the House managers as ``able'' or ``very able'' while
denouncing their arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Part of his presentation dealt at length with Jordan's search
for a job in New York for Ms. Lewinsky, which the Republicans see
as an effort to buy her silence. When he insisted that all of the
executives whom Jordan called told investigators that they felt no
pressure to hire her even though Jordan is universally known as the
president's best buddy, several Republican senators had difficulty
in concealing their disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   Bumpers began by mocking himself. He said his audience on
Thursday was about the same size as all the audiences he had drawn
in his 24 years as a senator combined. His fourth term expired only
a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can take some comfort, colleagues, in the fact that I'm
not being paid,'' he said. ``And when I'm finished, you'll probably
think the White House got its money's worth.''
</P>
<P>
   He, too, spoke caustically of the length and scope of Starr's
``five-year, relentless, unending investigation,'' describing it as
``maybe the most intense investigation not only of a president but
of anybody, ever.'' Javert's pursuit of Jean Valjean in ``Les
Miserables'' ``pales by comparison,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the time, his rhetorical aim was much higher.
</P>
<P>
   Why, Bumpers asked, did Clinton, by his own admission deceive
his family, his friends, his Cabinet and the American public?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Bumpers said, answering his own question, ``he knew
this whole affair was about to bring unspeakable embarrassment and
humiliation upon himself, his wife, whom he adored, and a child
that he worshipped with every fiber in his body and for whom he
would happily have died to spare her this or to ameliorate her
shame and her grief.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are none of us perfect. Sure, you say, he should have
thought it all out beforehand, and indeed he should, just as Adam
and Eve should have.''
</P>
<P>
   Bumpers responded directly to those, including Rep. Henry Hyde
of Illinois, the chief prosecutor, who have suggested that the
United States is diminished as a force in the world by having ``a
presidential perjurer'' in office. In truth, he said, ``this nation
has never enjoyed greater prestige in the world than we do right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   In support, he cited comments made recently by President Carlos
Menem of Argentina, President Vaclav Havel of the Czech Republic,
King Hussein of Jordan, and President Nelson Mandela of South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Like others on Clinton's defense team, he took the House
managers to task for having stretched evidence beyond the bounds of
common sense. But he softened his criticism with the comment ``It's
wanting to win too badly.''
</P>
<P>
   Bumpers, who spoke from notes scrawled on a yellow legal pad,
argued at some length that there was perjury and perjury, that some
lies told under oath were worse than others. There is ``a very big
difference,'' he said, between perjury about marital infidelity in
a divorce case and perjury in a murder case about buying the murder
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``To charge somebody with the first, and punish them as though
it were the second, stands our sense of justice on its head,'' he
told the senators, many of whom are also lawyers. ``There is a
total lack of proportionality, a total lack of balance in this
thing. The charge and the punishment are totally out of sync.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Like others, Bumpers traced the deliberations in Philadelphia in
1787 that produced the Constitution and its impeachment article.
But he added two arguments applicable to the question of whether
impeachment deals with public actions exclusively or both public
and private actions. The Republicans say the latter, and even the
White House counsel, Charles Ruff, said on Tuesday that he could
conceive of impeachable private actions.
</P>
<P>
   Not Bumpers.
</P>
<P>
   First, he said that the phrase ``high crimes and misdemeanors,''
whose definition has been so hotly debated, had been found at the
last minute in the English law ``under a category which said
`distinctly political offenses against the state.''' Second, he
said that in the penultimate constitutional draft the words ``high
crimes and misdemeanors'' had been followed by the phrase ``against
the United States.'' That phrase was dropped from the final text
for stylistic reasons, he contended, ``because it was redundant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we doing here,'' Bumpers demanded of the senators.
</P>
<P>
   A former Marine, he urged that Hyde, who suggested that keeping
Clinton in office was an affront to those who fell on battlefields
from Bunker Hill to Saigon, talk to some of the Senate's own
``certified war heroes'' _ John Chafee of Rhode Island, who fought
at Guadalcanal, and Daniel Inouye of Hawaii, who lost an arm in
Italy, and Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, who won a Medal of Honor in
Vietnam. None, he implied, shared Hyde's view.
</P>
<P>
   He concluded by calling on his former colleagues not to set a
precedent they would regret.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't, for God's sake, heighten people's alienation that is at
an all-time high toward their government,'' Bumpers said. ``The
people have a right, and they are calling on you to rise above
partisanship. They're calling on you to do your solemn duty. And I
pray you will.''
</P>
<P>
   A question-and-answer period will start Friday and probably run
through Saturday. It is not to exceed 16 hours, and senators are
required to submit all questions in writing, to be put to the
prosecutors and defense lawyers by Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist, presiding.
</P>
</TEXT>
