<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS' MARTIN COMES MARCHING HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM DESERT, Calif. _ Smoke from the NBA post-lockout signing
derby has lifted to reveal what Darrick Martin and the Clippers may
have needed all along:
</P>
<P>
   Each other.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the team itching to make a much-publicized
``upgrade'' at point guard re-signed the '98 model, Martin, to a
one-year deal worth $500,000. He made a jump shot or two more than
$400,000 last season.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who arrived at College of the Desert just in time for
the opening of training camp, insists he isn't bitter about the
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the nature of this business,'' said the former UCLA
star, who waited while the Clippers' flirtation with other
available point guards ran its course. ``I've been able to overcome
obstacles ever since I started playing the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who averaged 10.6 points and 4.1 assists per game in his
two seasons with the Clippers, is eager to prove he should have
been at the top of the team's shopping list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really enjoy proving people wrong,'' said Martin, whose deal
includes what the 5-foot-11 lefty refers to as ```attainable''
incentives. ``I'm not trying to throw anything in anybody's face;
I'm just very happy to have a chance to play and to be able to stay
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said his chances of returning to the Clippers were
``50-50'' on Wednesday, with Orlando and Sacramento active in the
bidding. Along with the opportunity to be a starter, conversations
with new coach Chris Ford and Elgin Baylor, the team's vice
president of basketball operations, were key factors in his
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``In professional sports, you never say `no', you never shut a
door, you never burn a bridge behind you,'' said Ford after the
Clippers' door seemingly closed for Sherman Douglas, a New Jersey
free agent who played for him in Boston and Milwaukee. ``We've
always been talking about Darrick and the possibility of bringing
him back. A lot of people, including himself, didn't think he had
the kind of year he hoped for last year. Hopefully, we can find a
way to bring him back to the way he played his first year here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers now are $3.2 million under the salary cap, and
Baylor didn't rule out the possibility of additional moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll continue to talk to teams,'' said Baylor. ``But the
deals some people wanted to make we didn't find acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Baylor center-power forward Brian Skinner, the Clippers'
choice with the 22nd pick in the 1998 NBA Draft, signed a contract
that pays the $653,000 per season allowed by the league's new
collective bargaining agreement.... James `Hollywood' Robinson
arrived late but was in attendance for the evening practice
Thursday.... The team's five-man, free-agent invitee list includes
former Long Beach State forward Juaquin Hawkins. The others are
veteran NBA guard Scott Brooks (UC Irvine), guard Chris Smith
(UConn), a veteran of foreign hoop wars, 7-0 center Mark Blount
(Pitt) and ex-Nevada-Las Vegas forward (Tyrone Nesby)....
Single-game tickets will go on sale Saturday at noon at the Sports
Arena and at TicketMaster outlets, except those at Robinsons-May.
The Clippers will lower each $15 seat at the Sports Arena and
Arrowhead Pond of Anaheim (a combined total of about 5,000 seats)
to $10 for the entire season. Free tickets for the Clippers'
exhibition game with the Lakers on Jan. 30 at the Sports Arena will
also be available then.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
