<HEADLINE>
TOM DASCHLE: THE DEMOCRATS' UNLIKELY SAVIOR-IN-CHIEF  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent ``separate buy'' article is from the current (week
beginning 23 January 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SLIGHTLY SHORTER VERSION, THIS
ARTICLE STANDS IN 900 WORDS; FULL UNCUT VERSION IS 1,000 WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in the summer of 1995, Tom Daschle hit on an idea that now
bears remembering.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle was half a year into his job as the Democratic leader in
the Senate, and he was casting about for a way to resist the
formidable momentum of the Republican Contract with America.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of discussions with Mark Mellman, his pollster,
Daschle decided that the Republicans were most vulnerable on the
issue of Medicare, the popular government health program for the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   No matter that the Contract did not actually propose cuts in
Medicare, only cuts in its rate of growth: if Democrats screamed
``Cut!'' loudly enough, electoral comeback seemed certain.
</P>
<P>
   Over the ensuing year, all Democrats from President Clinton on
down adopted Daschle's clever ``Mediscare'' idea. It worked
brilliantly.
</P>
<P>
   Today the Contract with America has been replaced, in some ways
at least, by the grand spectacle of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Just as in 1995, the House Republicans have united behind a
radical scheme, and are clamoring for the Republican majority in
the Senate to endorse it. Just as in 1995, the Senate Republicans
may be observed wincing at the zeal of their House counterparts,
but agreeing, more or less, to go along with them.
</P>
<P>
   And, just as in 1995, it falls to Daschle to organize the
Democrats' counterattack. The question is whether Daschle's
spectacular success with Medicare will now be repeated.
</P>
<P>
   At first sight, Daschle seems unsuited to the role of
saviour-in-chief of the Democratic Party. He is a plain man from
the South Dakota prairie; his staunchest admirers concede that he
is not especially clever or charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   He became the Democrats' leader in the Senate partly thanks to
luck: one opponent lost his seat just before the leadership contest
in 1994, the other challenged him too late to beat him.
</P>
<P>
   He has never given an exciting speech, and stands for no
particular policies. One adviser, asked what motivates the man,
falls silent for a while, then says lamely that he wants to improve
the country.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, in a curious way, Daschle's plainness distinguishes
him. All senators, the saying goes, see a future president when
they look in the mirror; but Daschle, judging by his appearance as
well as by his controlled ego, uses mirrors sparingly.
</P>
<P>
   He stands out by not trying to stand out; and his modesty
endears him to the big egos that surround him.
</P>
<P>
   His colleagues appreciate the fact that Daschle does not hog the
limelight, or put his own image before that of his party; they
trust him to listen to their ideas without rushing to the nearest
microphone to take credit for them.
</P>
<P>
   And so Daschle is able to act as an honest broker, finding
common ground among fellow Democrats in the Senate. In a private
meeting last year, one senior senator declared that ``this little
sucker has done an amazing job of uniting us.''
</P>
<P>
   Daschle's quiet skills are now on display in the impeachment
battle. A month ago, the betting was that the Senate Democrats
would speak with many tongues: some would be happy to see Clinton
strung up, others would be determined to obstruct the impeachment
process.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, many tongues have spoken: last Sunday, for example,
fully 19 senators popped up on the television talk shows. But,
remarkably, nearly all the Senate's famously independent souls have
conformed to party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans want an extended trial with witnesses; Democrats
want a truncated trial without them.
</P>
<P>
   This is an embarrassment for the Republicans, and a victory for
Daschle. At the beginning of this month, Trent Lott, the Republican
leader in the Senate, promised a bipartisan process; and Daschle
encouraged him to believe that this was possible by striking a deal
(despite White House protests) on how the first stage of the trial
should be conducted.
</P>
<P>
   But, having staked his credibility on bipartisan comity, Lott
finds himself trapped. He can either cave in to Democratic demands
for a short trial, or he can go ahead without Democratic support _
and so lay himself open to the charge of rank partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   Having trapped Lott in this way, Daschle is now torturing him
mercilessly. Lott invited Democrats to attend a meeting with
President Clinton's prosecutors from the House; Daschle declined
the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Lott suggested that a bipartisan group work on the prickly issue
of witnesses; Daschle called this premature and refused Democratic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterwards Daschle was subtly accusing Republicans of
railroading their schemes through the Senate. ``Given the comments
of Republicans, it appears to be inevitable that witnesses will be
deposed,'' he said meekly.
</P>
<P>
   So long as Daschle keeps his caucus together, there is no way
that the Senate's 55 Republicans can muster the 67 votes needed to
