extend the impeachment trial, they may remove some of themselves
from office.
</P>
<P>
   Voters will see impeachment as a partisan witch-hunt, and may
make their displeasure known at the polls; if this happened in a
big way, the Democrats might even retake control of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Next year 13 Republican senators are up for reelection in states
that voted for Clinton in 1996. If the Democrats pick up six seats,
Daschle will become the Senate majority leader. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 900; OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   All of which leaves Republicans spitting with fury. Back in
1995, they attempted to enact a Contract with America full of
(mainly) sensible ideas; but, when the Democrats got in the way,
and the Republicans let the government close down rather than give
in, voters rounded on Republicans for their ``extremism.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, Republicans are trying a president who has shown
contempt for the law; but, when they suggest that the trial should
