<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSAL-LAYOFFS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAGRAM LAYS OFF HUNDREDS IN UNIVERSAL MUSIC GROUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The long-expected hammer has fallen on about 500
employees at Universal Music Group in the first round of job cuts
at what has become the world's largest music company.
</P>
<P>
   Hardest hit Thursday were two well-known Hollywood-based labels
that were left with little more than skeleton staffs. A&AMP;M Records
saw about 170 of its 200 employees depart and Geffen Records lost
115 of its 145 employees, according to sources who asked not to be
named.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts had been rumored for months, dating back to Seagram
Co.'s announcement last spring that it would buy Dutch music giant
PolyGram for $10.4 billion. Specifics began to emerge last month
when Seagram announced it would significantly reduce employment as
part of a reorganization of the new Universal Music Group, placing
its 15 labels in four groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's surprised,'' said a Geffen employee who asked to not
be identified. ``Honestly, it was like we came into work today to
get laid off. Right now, everyone's out celebrating at the Rainbow
Room across the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Montreal-based Seagram, which bought control of Universal
Studios and MCA in 1995, announced last month that A&AMP;M and Geffen
would be combined with Los Angeles-based Interscope Records. In
recent weeks, insiders reported, some functions at A&AMP;M and Geffen
were turned over to Interscope employees.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram's slashing within its music group is far from over, with
the next round expected to start within seven to 10 days, possibly
targeting the sales staff. Further moves could cut up to 2,500 of
the remaining 15,000 jobs in the combined music-group work force, a
level of layoffs needed to meet Seagram's goal of generating $300
million in annual cost savings.
</P>
<P>
   Senior executives, including A&AMP;M chief Al Cafaro and Geffen
chairman Eddie Rosenblatt, began receiving departure notices
earlier this week. On Thursday, which had been dubbed ``D-Day,''
most affected employees received pink slips on arriving at work and
were asked to clear out by the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M's headquarters on La Brea Avenue and Geffen's on Sunset
Boulevard are expected to be put up for sale shortly.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M, founded in a garage in 1963 by trumpeter Herb Alpert and
Jerry Moss to sell Tijuana Brass albums, was sold to PolyGram in
1990 for $700 million. Key artists expected to remain include
Sting, Sheryl Crow and Bryan Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Geffen was launched in 1980 by entertainment mogul David Geffen
and sold to MCA in 1990 for $550 million. Top acts include Beck,
Hole and Guns n' Roses.
</P>
<P>
   Deep cuts also came Thursday in New York as Island lost half of
its 100 employees, Mercury saw 90 of its 150 staffers let go and
Motown's work force dropped from 75 to about a dozen. Island and
Mercury are being combined with Def Jam, while Motown will become
part of Universal Records.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said no decisions have been made on dropping acts from
rosters but speculation has placed the number of cuts as high as
250. Rumors emerged that cuts would include any act that failed to
sell at least 200,000 copies of its most recent album.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
