<HEADER>
A3896 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-REPUBS-1STLED     01-22 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-REPUBS-1STLEDE-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERTSON'S REMARKS DRAW FIRE AT CONSERVATIVE PAC MEETING
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS 2nd graf to correct `Conservative Political Action COMMITTEE'
to `Conservative Political Action CONFERENCE'; adds editorial
refinements to last sentence of that graf. No other changes.) 
(ATTN: Va.) (bl) 
By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Va. _ Pat Robertson's remarks that the impeachment
trial might as well be halted set off a firestorm among
conservatives meeting here Thursday. They condemned the television
evangelist and asserted that Republicans should not retreat from a
full trial.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there were indications at the annual conference of the
Conservative Political Action Conference that some of the most
vociferous detractors of President Clinton are pulling back from
the impeachment controversy. Few of the speakers concentrated on
impeachment or on the president's ethics _ a departure from similar
gatherings recently. Two candidates running for the Republican
presidential nomination _ the publisher Steve Forbes and former
Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander _ preferred to take shots at the
early front-runner, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, rather than Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   And several conservatives at the convention _ the same setting
where Paula Jones first emerged in 1994 to tell reporters that she
fended off a sexual advance from Clinton _ said they shared
Robertson's impatience with how the White House scandal has
dominated the capital. For example, Joyce Terry, a retired nurse
from Woodbridge, Va., said she agreed with him: ``That's my
concern. I feel they should move a little faster. They know the
facts. They know what's going on. Let's get with it and get it over
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite those misgivings, the overwhelming sentiment of dozens
of rank-and-file conservatives and their leaders was that the
Senate has a duty to pursue Clinton no matter the political
consequences. Most people said they were puzzled _ if not outraged
_ by the comments Wednesday by Robertson, the chairman of the
Christian Coalition, that Clinton had won ``from a public relations
standpoint'' and ``they might as well dismiss'' the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Pat Robertson said, in fact, it's time for the Republicans
to give up _ and give in _ to Clinton, my membership in the
Christian Coalition is over,'' said Hazel Staloff, a computer
worker from Brooklyn. ``I don't think the party can be hurt when it
stands for what is right. It can only be hurt when it compromises
with evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Kroeger, a former staff member in the Reagan White
House, said of Robertson, ``I think he should have kept quiet
because he carried a lot of weight with conservatives. I don't know
why he said that because Congress has a duty there. To drop it,
where does that leave us?''
</P>
<P>
   The feelings of this potent wing of the Republican Party are
important because many politicians, particularly in competitive
races, are loath to alienate conservatives whom they need to get
elected.
</P>
<P>
   Across the river at the Capitol, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the
lead prosecutor, said Robertson's comments ``shows that we're not
tools of the Christian Right. We don't necessarily always agree
with everything that Pat Robertson says.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Robertson sought to defend his comments on his television
program, ``The 700 Club'': ``What I was saying essentially is that
the president scored a public-relations triumph, and the
Republicans in the Congress gave him the platform to do that, and
consequently they undercut their own authority.'' He added: ``In a
sense, it's like saying it's the third quarter and the score is 50
to nothing and there's another quarter to play. The outcome seems
at this point settled, but I wasn't saying I favored that.''
</P>
<P>
   In Virginia, many participants at this conference said they
favored a full trial with a parade of witnesses. ``It doesn't
matter to me if it goes on for a year,'' said Dan O'Brien of Falls
Church, who teaches character to corporate executives. ``I'm not
deceived by the notion that the country's going to stop running
because of the impeachment trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Mingling among vendors selling T-shirts with slogans such as
``Another Member of the Vast Right Wing Conspiracy,'' Preston
Noell, who heads a Catholic civic organization said he was eager
for the Senate to delve deeper into the impeachment matter. ``I'm
not sick and tired of it,'' he said. ``I don't think it's gotten
going yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Helen Chenoweth, R-Idaho, an outspoken conservative who
addressed the convention, said of Robertson after her speech: ``I
was surprised. We wouldn't have even fought the war of independence
if we had taken a poll.''
</P>
<P>
   David Keene, chairman of the American Conservative Union, said
flatly of Robertson: ``He's wrong.'' But he conceded that
``conservatives are of two minds _ they want it to go through the
process, but they'd like it to be over to the extent that it's all
that's talked about. Conservatives have always won when we can make
divisions based on the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The presidential candidates also stayed relatively clear of
Clinton. Without mentioning him directly, Forbes assailed Bush and
his ``compassionate conservative'' ideology, saying,
``Mealy-mouthed rhetoric and poll-tested cliches are no substitute
for a muscular substantive agenda.'' Forbes and Alexander also
attacked Bush by criticizing his father, former President George
Bush, and his slogan about a ``kinder and gentler'' America.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, a social conservative who is also preparing to run
for president, took issue with Robertson in an interview. ``There
are two issues that ought never have to do with PR,'' he said.
``Declaring war and the profound question of whether the president
has violated the Constitution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 0009EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
