<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_NOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUMMINEN TO START IN ALL-STAR GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Defenseman Teppo Numminen became the first Coyotes player in
franchise history to be named a starter in Sunday's NHL All-Star
Game when he was selected to replace injured Detroit defenseman Uwe
Krupp on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Numminen joins World All-Stars Teemu Selanne of Anaheim; Peter
Forsberg of Colorado; Jaromir Jagr of Pittsburgh; Nicklas Lidstrom
of Detroit; and Dominik Hasek of Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Krupp had earned a starting spot in NHL All-Star balloting.
Numminen was selected by the NHL's hockey operations department,
after consultation with the league's general managers.
</P>
<P>
   Numminen, who is making his All-Star Game debut, leads Coyotes
defensemen in scoring with 24 points. He has appeared in 256
consecutive regular-season games, the longest current streak among
defensemen.
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star Game is scheduled for 2 p.m. Sunday at the Ice
Palace in Tampa. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Frequent flyer &QL; 
 &QL; 
When you've spent most of your career in the minor leagues,
everything about the NHL seems faster. Including road trips.
</P>
<P>
   ``We usually travel everywhere by bus,'' said center Trevor
Letowski, who was recalled from the American Hockey League
affiliate in Springfield, Mass., on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 21-year-old's third trip to the Coyotes since making
his NHL debut on Jan. 1. Not that he's complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I come for a day or a week or a month, it's all exciting
and part of the learning experience,'' Letowski said. ``I try not
to take it hard when I'm sent back. I look at it as when I'm here,
it's good for me, a bonus. I'll just keep taking little steps, and
maybe one day I'll be a regular.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm just happy to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Letowski, who was the Coyotes' sixth pick in the 1996 draft,
lasted about a day and a half during his first call-up. His second
visit kept him with the team a week, from Jan. 10-17.
</P>
<P>
   He scored his only goal on Jan. 13 against Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like him. That's why he keeps coming back,'' Coach Jim
Schoenfeld said. ``He has real good hockey sense. That's Number 1.
That's very difficult if not impossible to teach. He has good
vision of the ice, so that makes him a good playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he's very quick with his deceptive shots. He's a real good
goal scorer at the American League level and potentially at this
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Letowski's quickness helps compensate for his lack of size (5
feet 10, 173 pounds).
</P>
<P>
   ``The game's definitely a lot quicker up here,'' he said. ``But
the biggest difference that I've noticed is the work ethic. Guys
are always going 100 percent.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Record pace &QL; 
 &QL; 
The team's 24 victories entering Thursday's game are the most at
the season's midway point in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   The previous best was 19 set by the Winnipeg Jets in the 1984-85
and 1985-86 seasons. Those teams finished with 43 and 40
victories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quick checks &QL; 
 &QL; 
Anaheim left wing and former Coyote Jim McKenzie missed his fifth
straight game Thursday because of a cut above his right eye.
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes center Bob Corkum (hip flexor) and left wing Brad
Isbister (groin strain) did not return to the lineup Thursday and
will take advantage of the All-Star break to heal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 0016EST &QL; 
