r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGSNOTES-LADN     01-22 0464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBINSON HOPES BREAK REJUVENATES TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Los Angeles Kings coach Larry Robinson said
Thursday he is hoping the All-Star break will rejuvenate his
players, not just physically but mentally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys have nagging injuries and their groins are a little
tight,'' Robinson said. ``It's a great time for them to get a
little break and get away from the rink.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said he may try to give his players more time away from
the ice when the season resumes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get stale,'' he said. ``And how many different ways can
you explain the game of hockey? If you just keep harping on them,
doing the same things, after awhile you do get stale. It's great to
get away from the rink once in awhile. We're going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   In place of practices on some days, Robinson said the Kings may
work on weight training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Athletes don't lose their conditioning in one day,'' he said.
``We're going to look at doing a lot of gym work, especially guys
who play a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Team Tipsy (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   After he scored his 500th goal earlier in the month, Luc
Robitaille's teammates presented him with a home-entertainment
system.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, Robitaille returned the favor by showing up at
the dressing room with Dom Perignon, which unfortunately for the
Kings is not the name of a high-scoring forward but a fancy brand
of champagne. Robitaille gave each of his teammates a bottle of
bubbly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys have been great,'' Robitaille said. ``I was trying to
think what to get them. What do you get guys who have everything?''
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille gave them the champagne with one caveat.
</P>
<P>
   Said Robitaille, ``I told them, `Not on game day.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Scoring drought: The Kings' defensemen entered play Thursday
with a combined 10 goals, among the fewest of any team in the
league and two fewer than Dallas' Darryl Sydor (an ex-King) and St.
Louis' Al MacInnis.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to have more rounded goal-scoring,'' said Rob
Blake, who began the night leading Kings defensemen with three
goals despite missing 18 games this season due to injury and
suspension. ``Right now, the only guy scoring consistently is
Luc.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake led NHL defensemen with 23 goals last season, 11 on the
power play. Asked about his drop in goal scoring this year, Blake
said, ``Most of my goals come on the power play, and the power play
hasn't been that good. You need your defensemen scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   Is he tough enough?: Robinson said this week that he has
questioned whether he is hard enough on his players, but Blake said
he doesn't buy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry can say all he wants,'' Blake said, ``but it's up to the
guys on the ice to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 0018EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3905 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-CAMP-AZR &LR;      01-22 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-CAMP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANYBODY FOR SOME ONE-ON-ONE?  
 UNCERTAINTY RUINS AINGE'S PLANS FOR SUNS CAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are fantasy camps, army camps, summer camps and the
Republican camp. Just when you think you've seen them all, along
come the Suns. They are about to go camping in a strange,
unexpected way. It's no place to pitch a tent. More like a fit.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Camp Chaos.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns are about to embark on the very difficult task of
preparing for a 50-game season.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty starts with the beginning. The Suns plan to open
training camp today. That's a day late. Practice was canceled on
the first day that NBA teams were allowed to start practicing.
That's not a promising sign.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns weren't the only team to sit out the opening day of
business after the lockout. The Chicago Bulls, post-Michael Jordan,
joined them on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is a matter of manpower. On Thursday, the Suns
simply didn't have enough. With only Jason Kidd, Danny Manning and
Luc Longley under contract, the Suns didn't have enough bodies for
shirts vs. skins.
</P>
<P>
   Suns Coach Danny Ainge and assistants Scott Skiles and Frank
Johnson could boost the number to six for some three-on-three
scrimmaging. But they aren't planning to be player-coaches. Not
yet, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost humorous,'' Ainge said Thursday amid the bizarre
twists of Antonio McDyess' hesitancy to sign a contract in Denver.
``It's funny, but it can be hard to laugh if you're in my position.
I don't know what else to do except cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's either that, or I just find myself laughing a lot lately.
I'm going: `Where am I? ``The Twilight Zone''?' ''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, at least, Ainge had no idea whether his roster
would include McDyess, or Tom Gugliotta, or Rod Serling. He was not
able to schedule a practice because NBA rules prohibit organized
workouts with unsigned players.
</P>
<P>
   Free agent guard Rex Chapman and rookies Pat Garrity and Toby
Bailey have been in town. They are expected to sign but can't until
the McDyess-Gugliotta saga is settled.
</P>
<P>
   There are further indications that the Suns have designated
players who they expect to complete the roster. Chapman, Garrity,
Bailey, George McCloud, Horacio Llamas, Marko Milic and Gerald
Brown underwent physicals Thursday. That is the first step toward
signing a contract. But, they, too are waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been frustrating,'' said Garrity, a first-round pick from
Notre Dame. ``Actually, annoying is a better word. For a first-year
player, there's just no way of knowing what to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrity doesn't even have the comfort of asking veterans for
advice on what a rookie can expect in camp. There never has been a
camp quite like the one that is about to begin.
</P>
<P>
   For Ainge, there's the further frustration of watching a summer
full of work get trashed. Ainge said he and his staff had planned
every detail of camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had practice schedules and drills, everything like that,''
he said. ``We were more than prepared.'' Much of Ainge's planning
was based on the assumption that McDyess would return. With him,
the team would revolve around a fast-paced game with an emphasis on
Kidd's passing and his high-flying dunks.
</P>
<P>
   But if Gugliotta moves into the lineup, the philosophy may take
a turn toward a more deliberate, half-court style.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the roster's makeup, at this point the Suns appear to
be caught in a losing battle with time. NBA training camps are the
place where teams develop cohesion. But at this point, the Suns
have an unknown roster and only two weeks to get ready for their
season opener on Feb. 5 against the Clippers in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could be a little bit of a struggle out of the gate,''
Suns President Jerry Colangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   That could be an understatement.
</P>
<P>
   The hectic negotiations have left Ainge with little time to
consider training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly have not given it (camp) a thought yet,'' said
Ainge, who intends to conduct two-a-day practices throughout camp.
``I had everything planned. But now, we are on such a fly. It just
depends on when we can get together and when I can have all my
signed guys on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know when that will that be, or how that will be. I'm
just going to have to adjust on the run. Hopefully, we'll have a
team running up and down the floor within 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this a zoo, or what?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
