<HEADLINE>
L.A. LAND DEVELOPER HAS RECORD YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- A surging real estate market propelled The
Newhall Land and Farming Company to its best sales year ever in
1998, the developer said.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said on Thursday it sold a record number of
residential and industrial lots at prices well above 1997 appraised
values.
</P>
<P>
   For the year ended Dec. 31, Newhall Land's net income increased
44 percent to $64.1 million, or $1.86 per partnership unit. This
compares with net income of $44.5 million, or $1.28 per unit, in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues soared 47 percent to $304.7 million. Newhall Land's
sales were $207.7 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's revenues got a big boost from the second-quarter
sale of the Valencia Marketplace to Samuel S. Mevorach, a private
investor, for $111 million. The deal contributed $98 million to
revenues and $35 million, or $1.02 per unit, to earnings.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth quarter, Newhall Land earned $1.8 million, or 5
cents per partnership unit, on revenues of $53.6 million. In the
1997 fourth quarter, the company earned $4.3 million, or 12 cents
per unit, on revenues of $55.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth-quarter results just about matched analysts expectations
on a per unit basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like they have some good things in line for 1999 but
probably not much in the way of closings for the first half of the
year. It doesn't look like they have very much in escrow right
now,'' said Katherine Flores, an analyst at Sutro &AMP; Co. in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings probably will be weighted toward the third and fourth
quarters, she said.
</P>
<P>
   On the industrial side of the ledger, Newhall Land closed escrow
on 111 acres, with some parcels fetching the highest price ever per
square foot for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Escrow also closed on 1,232 residential lots and homes in
Valencia, the most in the community's history, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The largest single contributor to our record year was the
strategic sale of Valencia Marketplace,'' Thomas L. Lee, Newhall
Land's chairman and chief executive officer, said in a statement.
``Each of our core real estate segments -- residential, commercial
and industrial -- is benefiting from California's growing
diversified economy, low interest rates and a population expected
to increase by almost 18 million people over the next two
decades.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the area is well-positioned to take advantage of
future growth trends, and continued development of industrial and
office-space parcels will create synergy with the housing and
retail markets.
</P>
<P>
   Newhall Land plans to complete about 150,000 square feet of
retail and office space along Town Center Drive. It will also
market about 1,400 residential lots this year, a key step in
reaching an annual absorption rate in Valencia of 1,500 homes,
including apartments, by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
