<HEADLINE>
NO STYLE POINTS, BUT ASU HANGS ON 
</HEADLINE>
 ST-ARIZ STATE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Winning no points for style, the Arizona State women's
basketball team came up with two critical defensive stops down the
stretch to edge Oregon State, 57-53, on Thursday night at Wells
Fargo Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ASU (8-7, 2-4 Pac-10) won its first conference game at home in
advance of a 7 p.m. Saturday meeting with Oregon (14-4, 5-2), which
moved into the Associated Press national ranking at No. 25 this
week and promptly lost to Arizona, 78-74.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did it with defense,'' ASU Coach Charli Turner Thorne said.
``We did focus on defensive mentality this week, that when we play
good defense consistently we're going to blow teams out.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't happen _ ASU lost a nine-point lead in the final
6:11 of the first half to fall into a halftime tie _ but the Sun
Devils were able to lead for the final 12:42 and most of all stifle
the Beavers (10-6, 2-5) at crunch time.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead 54-51, coming out of a timeout at 1:07, ASU forced Oregon
State to work the perimeter until Vanessa Morris missed a running
15-footer. The Sun Devils' Kristine Sand had good rebound position
and was fouled by Ericka Brosterhous, her fifth, but made only 1 of
2 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern then repeated: Morris missing a wild bomb, and
Oregon State's Sissel Pierce fouling Rachel Holt as they went for
the rebound. Holt, with 17 points, made 1 of 2 to put ASU up,
56-51, with 22.5 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Syesha Thomas, a 5-foot-6 senior guard who bothered ASU while
only playing 13 minutes, blew past Kitch Kitchen for a layup at the
14-second mark.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State pressed off a timeout, but Arnold fouled before ASU
could inbounds. Kitchen made one of her free throws to clinch the
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the stops we needed in the second half,'' Holt said.
``We still need to work together in attacking.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-3 Holt, for instance, got only seven shots and made six.
Including her, the Sun Devils shot 33.3 percent and were outscored
by four buckets. Without her, that percentage drops to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to do a better job of getting her (Holt) more
looks,'' Turner Thorne said. ``We've got a lot of good scorers, but
we need to be a little smarter and see her a little better.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the Sun Devils had only 19 turnovers, nine fewer
than their average in conference games and one less than the
Beavers. They went into the game at a minus-7 in turnover margin in
the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the guard is not confident of making that pass, I'd rather
not have her make it,'' Turner Thorne said.
</P>
<P>
   ASU has four consecutive wins over Oregon State, its first
streak of that length against a Pac-10 opponent since the 1992 and
1993 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas led the Beavers with 11 points as she and Felicia
Ragland, with 10 points, were much more effective than the Wiersma
twins, Chassie and Cherrith, who combined for nine points. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OREGON STATE _ Cha. Wiersma 2-10 3-4 7, Salea 2-3 0-0 4,
Brosterhous 1-3 0-0 2, Che. Wiersma 1-3 0-0 2, Ragland 5-9 0-0 10,
Arnold 0-0 0-0 0, Thomas 4-4 3-5 11, Morris 2-12 2-2 7, Pierce 4-9
2-2 10, Kakeranaite 0-1 0-0 0, Wade 0-0 0-0 0. Totals 21-54 10-13
53.
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA STATE _ Newman 4-10 2-3 12, Sand 3-10 3-4 10, Holt 6-7
5-6 17, Kitchen 0-5 4-6 4, Tucker 1-6 0-0 3, Lang 1-2 0-0 2,
Edwards 0-0 0-0 0, White 0-1 5-6 5, Jantzen 2-5 0-0 4, Bennett 0-0
0-0 0. Totals 17-51 19-25 57. &QL; 
 &UR; Oregon State 31 22 _ 53 &QC; 
 &UR; Arizona State 31 26 _ 57 &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Three-point goals _ Oregon State 1-6 (Morris 1-4, Ragland 0-2),
Arizona State 4-15 (Newman 2-4, Tucker 1-3, Sand 1-5, Kitchen 0-1,
Tom 0-2). Fouled out _ Brosterhous. Rebounds _ Oregon State 41
(Brosterhous, Pierce 5), Arizona State 44 (Sand 8). Assists _
