<HEADLINE>
MCCLENATHAN STEERS TOWARD TOP FUEL TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If this is the season Cory McClenathan finally escapes another
driver's shadow, it all begins today in the ``Hot Rod Magazine''
PRO National Time trials at Firebird International Raceway Park.
</P>
<P>
   The three-day event, which ends Sunday with final eliminations
beginning at 11 a.m., has attracted several National Hot Rod
Association Top Fuel, Funny Car and Pro Stock drivers searching for
last-minute clues on how best to approach the Feb. 7 season opener
at Pomona, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Other drivers committed to the Firebird event include John
Force, Eddie Hill, brothers Cruz and Tony Pedregon, Mike Dunn, Whit
Bazemore, Dean Skuza, Doug Herbert, Del Worsham and Gary Densham.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all looking for the same thing, which is to go quick and
fast,'' said McClenathan, a four-time Top Fuel runner-up. ``We'll
be testing a different fuel pump, a different blower and different
tuning deals. The chassis also is a little different. The body is
probably three or four inches higher in the nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll make a couple easy passes at first. We want to make sure
the new car is working like we want it too. By Sunday, I think
we'll be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Two-time defending NHRA Top Fuel champion Gary Scelzi,
McClenathan said, has set the current benchmark, forcing other
teams to beef up their programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we get to Pomona, you want to be on top of your game
because it seems like nowadays we're counting points from right out
of the box,'' said McClenathan, driver of the Joe Gibbs-owned
dragster. ``It's just so competitive now.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, the Winston car (Scelzi) is running really
big speeds. And look at (Joe) Amato and Bernstein. Bernstein
really, really came on strong toward end of the season, so (crew
chief) Lee Beard is doing some good things over there.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we have to do. We have to become more consistent
in terms of (elapsed time) and speed. It used to be you'd get one
and not the other. We'd like to find both. We need to make a good
run in the middle of the track and also run in the 320 (mph) range
at the end of track.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
