<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS_CACTUS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS DELAY DECISION  
 LIKE FT. MCDOWELL, BUT WANT 2 MONTHS  
</HEADLINE>
  LEAGUE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL SOWERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Los Angeles Dodgers official says plans for a $20 million
spring training camp on the Fort McDowell Indian Community east of
Phoenix ``look fantastic'' but said the team probably won't make a
decision on relocating to the reservation for two months.
</P>
<P>
   That is disappointing news to tribal officials who were hoping
for an answer in a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The 8,500-member tribe, which has used generous casino profits
to build new homes and medical facilities on the reservation, now
wants to cash in on the Cactus League.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal Council President Clinton Pattea has said the community
can't predict the future of gaming and must find other profitable
enterprises to sustain the tribe's new-found prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the tribe in November proposed the Fort McDowell
Four Peaks Sports Complex, a 12,000-seat stadium and six practice
fields, to lure the Dodgers out of Vero Beach, Fla., where they
have trained since 1948.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe's proposal promises to have the six practice fields
ready for spring training in 2000. The stadium and five more
practice fields would be built over the next two years. Should the
tribe lure another team to share the facility with the Dodgers,
five more fields would be built and the cost would rise to
approximately $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   But Gilbert Jones, a longtime tribal council member, said if the
decision lags too long, ``we won't be able to make that date.''
</P>
<P>
   He said many of the tribe's business moves hinge on the Dodgers'
decision.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe recently announced plans to build a 250-room hotel and
18-hole golf course. But Jones said that if the Dodgers come, the
tribe will need to double the size of both.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Wymbs, the team's special projects director, said the
Dodgers were impressed by the tribe's plans and the proposed
training facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe's proposed training facility was designed by the HOK
architectural firm, which has designed major league stadiums around
the country and spring training facilities in Peoria and
Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the team's enthusiasm, Wymbs said, ``We're still a
couple of months away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to gauge as to a definite time. There are a
lot of issues involved. There are the potential lease terms and the
shoring up of funding to be considered,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pattea said tribal casino profits could build the camp or be
used as collateral for loans. He said the tribe also may sell bonds
to help pay for the stadium, practice fields and clubhouse. The
tribe would build the facility at no cost to the team and share in
revenue generated by stadium events.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money part is no problem,'' Jones said. ``Our investment
firm has done a great job for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have considered other sites in Arizona and Las Vegas
but have narrowed their choices to Fort McDowell, whose training
facility would include a view of the Four Peaks Mountains and would
be one mile from the Verde River, or staying in Vero Beach. They
are considering the move because the Cactus League makes more sense
geographically than continuing to train in Florida. All four of the
Dodgers' rivals in the National League West _ Diamondbacks, San
Francisco Giants, San Diego Padres and Colorado Rockies _ conduct
their training in Arizona, as do the American League's three West
Coast teams: the Anaheim Angels, Oakland Athletics and Seattle
Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   The team will report for spring training in Vero Beach in
mid-February in preparation for its April 5 regular season opener
against the Diamondbacks in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Wymbs said, the team's owners, Fox Broadcasting and
publication mogul Rupert Murdoch, are considering renovating Dodger
Stadium, which would be another large project.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Peterson, a marketing executive for US West, said the
Valley's business community is excited about the prospect that the
Dodgers will relocate their spring home to Fort McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us are keeping our fingers crossed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   US West hosted a November meeting among the Dodgers, other
businesses and Fort McDowell and wants to be the training camp's
most visible corporate backer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
