<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-VALLEY-CHEST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERT EXAMINING CHEST SUPPOSEDLY LEFT IN GOLD RUSH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY CHARLES F. BOSTWICK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With new doubts raised about the authenticity of a
battered chest found in Death Valley, a National Park Service
expert painstakingly examined its contents Thursday to determine if
they were really left behind 150 years ago by a lost Gold Rush
expedition.
</P>
<P>
   Western Archeological and Conservation Center conservator
Gretchen Voaxs began analyzing the objects _ including gold and
silver coins, ceramic bowls and a flintlock pistol _ at about 9
a.m., but no word was released on her findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's probably going to be a million questions from all of
us as to what should be our next step,'' said Terry Baldino,
supervisory ranger at Death Valley National Park's main visitors
center.
</P>
<P>
   Park Service officials said it's likely that scientific analysis
will be necessary to verify the find, made by archeologist Jerry
Freeman of Pearblossom as he researched the possible route taken by
the lost gold miners trying to escape Death Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, one noted Death Valley authority expressed new doubts
about the chest's authenticity because of a term _ ``grubstake'' _
used in a list of its contents purportedly written by pioneer
William Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   A gold seeker of the time would never have called the $52.75
left in the chest a grubstake, a concept that developed in the
waning years of the Gold Rush, said Richard Lingenfelter, a
research physicist at the University of California, San Diego, who
in 1986 wrote a comprehensive history of Death Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Merchants, not wanting to be left behind as miners left
played-out gold fields in search of richer strikes, were willing to
provide supplies and food, or grub, for a stake in whatever was
found, Lingenfelter said. The earliest reference he has seen to the
term came from the late 1850s.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my way of thinking ... him writing `grubstake' is like
writing, I'll phone home when I get there,'' Lingenfelter said.
``It's a concept that just wasn't in existence.''
</P>
<P>
   The chest was found in a rocky alcove high on 7,510-foot Pinto
Peak, in the Panamint Mountains that form Death Valley's western
rim. Inside it was a letter signed by Robinson, who ended up dying
200 miles and 26 days later on the outskirts of what is now
Palmdale.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was one of a group who called themselves the Jayhawkers
_ a band of Illinois men who were one of several bands of pioneers
who got lost in late 1849 while seeking a shortcut to California's
gold fields.
</P>
<P>
   Too late that year to make it across the snowy Sierra Nevada,
several parties of gold seekers decided to take the southern route
from Salt Lake City across the California and Nevada desert to Los
Angeles. But instead of traveling all the way to Los Angeles _ a
long way from the gold _ most of the group headed for what they
thought was a shortcut across the southern Sierra Nevada discovered
several years earlier by mountain man Joe Walker.
</P>
<P>
   They were hundreds of miles from the real shortcut, however, and
ended up stumbling down into Death Valley, becoming the first
whites to see the lowest, hottest, driest place in North America.
Several died before they reached safety.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman, who with his adult daughters and a friend traced the
path of the lost ``forty-niners'' from Utah into Death Valley in
1996, said he believes the chest went undiscovered for 149 years
because it was hidden two miles from the Jayhawkers' generally
accepted route.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman believes Robinson was alone and lost from the group when
he hid the chest after his last ox died on the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   (EDITORS, FOLLOWING IS THE TEXT OF THE LETTER FOUND IN THE
PANAMINT MOUNTAINS, PURPORTEDLY LEFT BY A MEMBER OF A LOST BAND OF
FORTY-NINERS TRYING TO ESCAPE DEATH VALLEY.) &UR; !dlim! &LR;  &QL; 
(ITAL) My dear Edwin
</P>
<P>
   Knowed now we should have gone arowned but am thankful not to be
sick with the agir cause others are worse ofen me. My last ox
falled in his checks afor morn and I caint carry down the steep.
The locket was your mahs. The boles and the wagon shrod were the
preachers wife. I toted her youngen. If you shouldove already seen
my Lydia, tell her my heart beats with hers. Kindly leave me a half
stake and my short gun. Ifen I don't raturn by end of fifty I wont
never come. Lord be precious to your soul. &QL; 
William &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Propity manafest of &QL; 
William Robinson second &QL; 
Day of the Lords year 1850 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 grub stake $52.75 &QL; 
1 short gun &QL; 
1 looken glass &QL; 
1 small bole &QL; 
1 large bole &QL; 
1 metal one &QL; 
1 shrod &QL; 
1 hym book &QL; 
1 law book &QL; 
1 water &QL; 
1 injun basket
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
