<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZ </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUN DEVILS KNOCKED SILLY BY SURPRISING BEAVERS 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-OREGON ST-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORVALLIS, Ore. _ Talent helps, but it sometimes takes more.
UCLA found out after coming into Gill Coliseum a couple of weeks
ago and leaving with a loss to Oregon State. Arizona State should
know this by now, too.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently, the Sun Devils forgot. ASU supposedly has better
players than the Beavers, but that mattered little Thursday in a
stunning, 81-51 Oregon State victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Beavers (9-7, 3-4 Pac-10) outfought and out-thought the Sun
Devils, keeping their poise throughout. The Sun Devils (10-8, 2-4),
on the other hand, lost theirs. Emotions finally boiled over when
Coach Rob Evans, conducting a running dialogue with the officials
the entire game, stalked onto the court screaming with 5:53 left,
drawing a technical. But it didn't matter. ASU was long out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State had five players score in double figures. ASU had
just one, forward Bobby Lazor, who had 14 points. ASU made 20 of 62
shots (32.3 percent).
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils were without junior swingman Derrick Davis, who
stayed behind in Tempe because of academic difficulties and might
be lost for the season. But they did have sophomore point guard
Alton Mason, who flew to meet the team after learning he will be
academically eligible for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant coach Dan O'Dowd picked up Mason at the airport in
Portland, and they arrived at the team hotel in Eugene at about 5
p.m., 20 minutes before the team bus left.
</P>
<P>
   Mason was the third ASU player this season to hop a flight and
join his teammates on the road on the day of a game. Freshman Kenny
Crandall and senior Mike Batiste also did it after gaining their
eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Mason's classroom struggles have been compounded by personal
tragedy. Since the start of the school year, his grandmother,
grandfather, aunt, and most recently, his father, have died. Mason
will leave today for his father's funeral in Nebraska and miss
Saturday's game against Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Mason played solid defense on the Beavers' ace point guard,
Deaundra Tanner, but otherwise looked shaky in the first half. So
did his teammates. Oregon State plays a unique brand of ugly ball _
the Beavers lead the Pac-10 in field-goal percentage defense and
are last in shooting percentage _ but it often works, especially at
home.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils missed nine of their first 10 shots, settled down
and took a 16-11 lead. Then they played perhaps their worst stretch
of the year, looking disoriented and out of synch, as the Beavers
went on a 20-4 run to open a 31-20 lead with 2:21 left in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   The feisty Beavers swarmed after every rebound, bringing Evans
off the bench several times to complain. The Beavers led at
halftime, 33-24. It was the Sun Devils' lowest first-half output of
the year, richly deserved. They made 9 of 31 shots (29 percent),
missing from inside, outside (0 for 7 from three-point range) and
everywhere in between.
</P>
<P>
   Batiste, whose play was especially uninspired, started the
second half on the bench _ and stayed there. The other Sun Devils
played with more of a purpose and began to execute their offense
and make some shots, pulling within two. But with a chance to tie
the score, Mason lost the ball and ASU failed to get even.
</P>
<P>
   All this did was make the Beavers play harder, and a 20-7 surge
pushed the lead to 55-40 with 10:10 to go. Then things got really
bad for the Sun Devils. Batiste had finally come in with 12:24, but
contributed little. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
