<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3927 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-MCDYESS-AZR &LR;      01-22 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-MCDYESS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CASE OF COLD FEET STRIKES MCDYESS  
 BALKS IN DENVER; SUNS-GUGLIOTTA ON HOLD? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   While trying to explain Wednesday why Antonio McDyess had
spurned his team to sign a contract with the Denver Nuggets, Suns
President Jerry Colangelo said he was reminded of the Broadway hit,
``A Funny Thing Happened'' ``on the Way to the Forum.''
</P>
<P>
   Turned out he had only seen Act I.
</P>
<P>
   With McDyess apparently history, the Suns turned their attention
Thursday to Minnesota Timberwolves free agent Tom Gugliotta.
Several NBA sources told ``The Arizona Republic'' that Gugliotta is
prepared to sign with the Suns, and two said he was on a flight to
the Valley on Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   But then the curtain went up on Act II.
</P>
<P>
   Only hours after arriving in Denver to sign a six-year, $67
million contract with the Nuggets, McDyess apparently learned that
the Nuggets had renounced the rights to his friend and former
teammate, LaPhonso Ellis, to fit McDyess under the Denver salary
cap.
</P>
<P>
   Although it had been reported in Denver for days, McDyess had
been sequestered in Houston. The press conference was initially
pushed back 2{ hours, then postponed indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid is having second thoughts,'' a source told ``The
Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver General Manager Dan Issel confirmed that when he told
reporters in Denver ``It doesn't look good'' and walked away.
</P>
<P>
   And so an already bizarre story took another weird twist.
</P>
<P>
   McDyess and his agents went to dinner, then were holed up in a
locker room at McNichols Sports Arena, the home of the Nuggets and
Colorado Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, three Suns players flew into Denver to speak with
McDyess. Suns General Manager Bryan Colangelo confirmed that Rex
Chapman, Jason Kidd and George McCloud made the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, we have players who care,'' Colangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo said he had been contacted by McDyess's agent Tony
Dutt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked if we're still interested,'' Colangelo said. ``The
answer is obvious. As long as we waited? Yes. Having said that,
we're always exploring our other options. We're not in a panic
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Nuggets officials were on standby and willing to wait all night
for a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Suns had announced that the rights to 10 players
had been renounced earlier in the day, including those to McDyess _
which would preclude the club from re-signing him under the Larry
Bird exception. But the team had not actually submitted that list
to the league, so McDyess could still be re-signed.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Suns faced a dilemma. What if McDyess changed his
mind? The trip by the Suns' players indicates the club would
welcome him back.
</P>
<P>
   But what about Gugliotta?
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Gugliotta has not yet agreed to terms, but a person
familiar with the negotiations who asked to remain anonymous, told
``The Republic'' early Thursday that ``I think something will be
done sometime soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta's agent, Richard Howell, told the ``Minneapolis
Star-Tribune'' newspaper that ``no deal is done.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Timberwolves inked Philadelphia free-agent power
forward Joe Smith to their $1.75 million cap exception in a
three-year deal, which indicates they're not expecting to keep
Gugliotta.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns have this to consider if McDyess changes his mind: By
re-signing McDyess under his Bird exception, they can fill their
salary cap before adding his contract. Gugliotta must fit below the
cap. Thus, keeping McDyess would afford the club the chance to add
another significant free agent.
</P>
<P>
   They're different players, but both are All-Star caliber
performers.
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta had been offered a six-year $67 million deal by
Detroit, but turned it down. The Timberwolves were dangling a
seven-year, $86.5 million package. Denver also had pursued
Gugliotta with terms similar to Detroit's.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns could offer a contract about the same as those that
Denver and Detroit could put on the table. Houston, the only other
team with competitive salary cap room, traded for Scottie Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   With McDyess in Denver, the Suns are Gugliotta's logical choice,
unless he decided to stay in Minnesota. And all indications are
that he wanted out of Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   All of this just when it appeared the Suns' roster might be
falling into place in this whacky, lockout-shortened season.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, center Luc Longley signed his contract to complete a
sign-and-trade deal with Chicago. The deal still had to go through
the NBA office, which was swamped by contract signings Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford Robinson's agent, Bradley Marshall, told KTAR radio in
Phoenix that his client has agreed to terms on a six-year contract
that would pay him $30 million and would sign it after Gugliotta
signed. But a Suns source said the report was erroneous, and terms
have not been reached.
</P>
<P>
   League sources told ``The Republic'' that the Robinson contract
can be done with the salary cap room the Suns have available, but
the deal could be part of a sign-and-trade scenario that would send
Robinson elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation that Robinson would go to Miami for
guards Brent Barry and Voshon Lenard. Barry was working out for the
Chicago Bulls Thursday in Chicago and could sign a straight
free-agent deal rather than agree to a sign-and-trade. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
