<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3928 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-MIGHTYDUCKS-COYOT     01-22 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-MIGHTY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEPPO CINCHES A TIE  
 COYOTES FAIL TO SCORE IN OT 
</HEADLINE>
 DUCKS-COYOTES-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teppo Numminen demonstrated why he was named to the World
All-Star team's starting lineup Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The defenseman knocked in the tying goal with 10:16 left in
regulation as the Coyotes held on for a 3-3 tie in front of 16,210
at America West Arena on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes had several opportunities to score in overtime, but
Anaheim goalie Dominic Roussel made several key saves, including a
one-handed grab of a Numminen shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes also survived Keith Tkachuk's slashing penalty in
overtime as the NHL's second-best penalty-killing unit endured.
</P>
<P>
   The tying goal came when Keith Carney flipped the puck into a
crowd in front of the Anaheim goal and it bounced out to Numminen,
who knocked it in for his eighth.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes (24-11-7) maintain some momentum entering the
All-Star break. They have only one loss in their past six meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks, which had lost three of their last four coming in, go
to 17-19-8 and look forward to the second half, when they are
traditionally a better team.
</P>
<P>
   When asked early Thursday what special problems Anaheim posed,
Coyotes Coach Jim Schoenfeld named three: Teemu Selanne, Paul
Kariya and Steve Rucchin.
</P>
<P>
   ``They warrant special attention every time they're on the
ice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes learned that firsthand. The Mighty Ducks' top line,
which has accounted for 49 points in its past 11 games, was at the
heart of Anaheim's goal that made it 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes, playing without Jeremy Roenick, who was ejected
after a game misconduct early in the second period, had tied it,
2-2, late in the second.
</P>
<P>
   For 32 seconds of a two-man advantage, the Coyotes worked
patiently to set up a play, and Mike Stapleton's slap shot was
tipped in by Greg Adams.
</P>
<P>
   But Anaheim bounced right back by sending in its No. 1 line.
Their speed resulted in a feed from Rucchin to Koriya, who scored
his 20th goal and gave the Ducks a 3-2 lead with 1:09 remaining in
the second.
</P>
<P>
   It was Anaheim that asserted itself in the early going.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks' first score started out as a nice save by Nikolai
Khabibulin, but Anaheim's Ted Drury caught it on the rebound and
tapped it past the Coyotes' goalie with 14:28 remaining in the
opening period.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes tied at 10:34 on a 2-on-1. Oleg Tverdovsky used his
speed to break away from the Ducks and feed Mike Stapleton, who
slapped it past Roussel for his fifth goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare moment, the Coyotes' penalty-killing unit faltered.
With Jim Cummins on the bench for hooking, Fredrik Olausson's slap
shot was tipped near the crease by Marty McInnis to give the Ducks
a 2-1 lead that held through the first period.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't what Schoenfeld wished for before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see us have a strong first period,'' he said.
``When we were playing our best hockey, we were a very aggressive
team, we were attacking, we were generating a lot of scoring
chances and we were finishing checks in the offensive zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would put our opponents back on their heels. I would like
to see us get back to that, especially against a team with an
explosive line like the Ducks.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld saw some of that aggression in the second period, but
it turned ugly on an incident that started with a solid hit by
Roenick on Drury. Drury unloaded on the nearest man, Deron Quint,
and it mushroomed. Roenick ultimately tangled with Anaheim center
Travis Green, and the result was a game misconduct that means
automatic disqualification. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
