<HEADER>
A3929 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBITS-NYT &LR;      01-22 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN FREDERICK NIMS, 85, POET AND TRANSLATOR  
 ERNEST SCHIER, 80, NATIONAL CRITICS INSTITUTE HEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Mich., Ind., Mass., Fla., Vt., Conn., Pa., S.D.)  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Frederick Nims, a poet, translator and author, died on
Tuesday at Northwestern Memorial Hospital in Chicago. He was 85 and
lived in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Nims wrote eight books of poetry, beginning in 1947 with ``The
Iron Pastoral,'' in which he addressed life in Chicago. One poem,
``Penny Arcade,'' read in part:
</P>
<P>
   ``Here heaven ticks: the weariest
</P>
<P>
   tramp can buy
</P>
<P>
   Glass mansions in the juke-
</P>
<P>
   seraphic sky.''
</P>
<P>
   His other books of poetry include ``Knowledge of the Evening,
Poems 1950-1960,'' nominated for a National Book Award; ``A
Fountain in Kentucky and Other Poems,'' ``The Kiss: A Jambalaya,''
``Of Flesh and Bone,'' ``Zany in Denim'' and ``The Six-Cornered
Snowflake.''
</P>
<P>
   In the introduction to his ``Selected Poems,'' published in
1982, he wrote: ``From the time I was 5 or 6, I thought poems were
a part of the natural world, as real certainly as the rabbits and
collies we kept.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Muskegon, Mich., Nims was a graduate of the University
of Notre Dame and received a Ph.D. in comparative literature from
the University of Chicago. He taught poetry at Notre Dame, the
University of Toronto, the University of Illinois at Urbana,
Harvard University, Williams College, the University of Florida and
the University of Illinois at Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   He also taught abroad, as a visiting professor in Florence,
Milan and Madrid, and taught poetry at the annual Bread Loaf
Writers' Conference in Vermont, for more than 10 years. He was the
author of ``Western Wind,'' a textbook for introductory poetry and
creative writing courses.
</P>
<P>
   Nims' books of translations included ``Sappho to Valery: Poems
in Translation,'' ``The Poems of St. John of the Cross'' and, last
year, ``The Complete Poems of Michelangelo.'' He was editor of
Poetry magazine from 1978 to 1985 and editor of ``The Harper
Anthology of Poetry'' (1981).
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Bonnie; a son, Frank, of Chicago;
two daughters, Emily Nims of Kalamazoo, Mich., and Sally Martin of
Gainesville, Fla., and three grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Schier, 80, National Critics Institute Head
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Schier, director of the National Critics Institute at the
Eugene O'Neill Theater Center in Waterford, Conn., died on Tuesday
at Lenox Hill Hospital in New York. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Schier was well equipped for his position at the Critics
Institute, having been drama critic of The Philadelphia Bulletin
from 1958 to 1982. Starting in the early 1940s, he covered theater
and film for several other newspapers, including The Times-Herald
in Washington from 1946 to 1954 and The Philadelphia Daily News
from 1956 to 1958. He was a founder and first chairman of the
American Theater Critics Association.
</P>
<P>
   He was also the director of the International Young Playwrights
Project at the O'Neill center and served as dramaturge for the
National Playwrights Conference at the center from 1983 to 1989. He
was a consultant for the American College Theater Festival in
Washington (1978-89) and the Opera and Music Theater Conference at
the O'Neill center (1980-89).
</P>
<P>
   He was an adjunct professor in playwriting and performance
criticism at Villanova University and starting in 1985 he also
taught play writing and production at the O'Neill center.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by two daughters, Johanna Hall of Saugerties,
N.Y., and Jennifer Cole of Langhorne, Pa.; two sons, Harry, of
Rapid City, S.D., and William, of Levittown, Pa., and three
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
