<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA_OREGON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILDCATS NEED LATE PUSH TO TIP DUCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. _ From his archrival's home to the Pit to the Mac,
Arizona guard Jason Terry doesn't care how loud it gets, how much
time is left, what the score is. Just give him the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Terry swooped inside and pulled outside to score and helped the
ninth-ranked Wildcats burn Oregon, 85-83, on Thursday night in
front of 9,087 screaming fans at McArthur Court. Terry scored 37
points, 21 in the first half, and knocked in five three-pointers to
keep the Wildcats on pace to catch first-place Stanford in a huge
Pac-10 showdown next week in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Terry didn't need any last-second heroics for the
Wildcats. This time, his last shot didn't fall.
</P>
<P>
   His three-point attempt with 30 seconds left could have sealed
it, but clanked off the rim and the Ducks, down by one, had a
chance to regain the lead with four seconds left and Frederick
Jones at the line to shoot two.
</P>
<P>
   Jones missed the first, and the second, and freshman forward
Richard Jefferson muscled the rebound and was fouled with 2.6
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson hit one of two foul shots and Oregon called time with
2.2 seconds left to set up one last shot.
</P>
<P>
   A.D. Smith's long inbounds pass was broken up by Jefferson and
the Ducks weren't able to get off a shot.
</P>
<P>
   It should have figured the game would come down to the wire. No
two teams have been in more games decided in the final seconds that
Oregon and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Terry's defense against Arizona State's Eddie House in the last
seconds sealed Arizona's one-point victory in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   He pulled up for a shot with four seconds left at New Mexico on
Saturday but the Lobos came back to win by one on buzzer-beater.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first time in four games that the Wildcats weren't
involved in a game that came down to the last shot, the last tick
of the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Senior forward A.J. Bramlett, despite playing with four fouls,
scored on two straight drives that gave UA an 81-76 lead with 3:48
left. Comfortable, no.
</P>
<P>
   Darius Wright hit a three-pointer for the Ducks that brought
them to within two and then fed Frederick Jones inside that tied it
at 81 with three minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   After freshman forward Richard Jefferson threw the ball away,
Wright hit two free throws with 1:03 left to cut the deficit to
84-83.
</P>
<P>
   Terry worked the clock down to 30 seconds, before launching a
three-pointer that bounced off the rim and to a Duck.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon lives by the three-point shot and had five in the first
15 minutes. UA combatted that strategy with a barrage of
three-pointers, connecting on six and taking a four-point lead at
the half.
</P>
<P>
   Terry had 3 of 4 three-pointers and 21 points in the first 20
minutes. He scored all but 18 of the Wildcats' first-half points.
</P>
<P>
   When the Ducks took a 22-16 lead the 10-minute mark of the half,
there was Terry driving and pulling up for a jumper to cut into the
hard-hat section's enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   After a three-pointer by Alex Scales gave Oregon a 27-20 lead
with seven minutes left in the half, freshman forward Richard
Jefferson, Terry and freshman guard Ruben Douglas all drilled
three-pointers in a 45-second span that gave Arizona its first
lead, 31-29. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
