<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3936 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      01-22 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
  
 SONICS TO CLOSE OUT '90s WITH RETURN TRIP TO '80s  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Bewildered by Thursday's train wreck of a start by the
NBA?
</P>
<P>
   Here's all you need to know:
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan is gone. Latrell Sprewell is back.
</P>
<P>
   Good night, everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm, some of you ghouls are still hanging around. Well, if
you're still hungry for a fix of the basketball macabre, check out
this ghostly scene from Seattle's hoops past at Thursday night's
first practice by the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   Battling under the basket, for position for the rebound as well
as for the starting lineup, were Olden Polynice and Chris Welp.
</P>
<P>
   The mind reels.
</P>
<P>
   Polynice, a Sonic first-round draft choice three presidents ago,
washed out of here in 1991 to the Clippers when the Sonics had to
package him with two first-round picks just to get Benoit Benjamin.
You might recall that one of the most familiar pieces of American
furniture was named after Benjamin: The La-Z-Boy recliner.
</P>
<P>
   In Polynice's travels among three more teams since then, the
only thing certain about him is that he has gotten older.
</P>
<P>
   Husky basketball fans recognize Welp from the DeutscheDawg era
of Washington basketball, when he and fellow German native Detlef
Schrempf took the UW to a couple of NCAA tournaments. Since then,
Welp has played basketball in Europe, been an artist, read many
books, traveled the world and missed about three generations of NBA
evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Polynice and Welp in the Sonic middle. I swear, it's true.
Heading into the new millennium , the Sonics have armed themselves
from the '80s. It's as if Microsoft bundled an abacus with Windows
98.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, who knows? The way the NBA game is played in this
broken season, it's like an Emerald Downs claiming race for
maidens: No charts, no Racing Form, no real clues.
</P>
<P>
   As the post-lockout, post-George Karl era began in Seattle
Thursday night with a 6 p.m. workout, chaos was king. Practice
began without either Polynice or Dale Ellis, both of whom wandered
in later after signing contracts and passing physicals.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters along the sidelines wondered, Whozzat? Where's
what's-his-face? How do you spell that name?
</P>
<P>
   Because the club signed seven fringe free agents, mostly for
practice fodder, the media relations department didn't have a list
of names and jersey numbers until after practice had begun.
Saturday mornings at the YMCA are better organized.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he managed the free-for-all, new coach Paul Westphal
agreed that he ``got most of the names, most of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the few guys who could help a little this season,
Sacramento free agent Billy Owens, hasn't made up his mind on a
team. The mysterious European rookie draft choice, Vladimir
Stepania, hasn't signed a contract. Don MacLean, the forward
acquired in the Jim McIlvaine deal, can't practice until the trade
is official. Michael Cage, the other guy in the swap, wasn't even
coming because the Sonics probably will waive him to free up space
under the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Shirts and skins to 10 buckets, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, that's how it was,'' said a grinning Nate McMillan
after the first practice in his new career as assistant coach.
``It's been a headache, trying to get people signed, all the
decisions to be made, waiting on your boys to get here.
</P>
<P>
   ``But actually, it turned out to be be a real good practice,
considering.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, considering that this season shouldn't even be, a
game of 52-card pickup might have been considered OK.
</P>
<P>
   Since Thursday night's snapshot of the Sonic talent is
incomplete, it's a little hard to make any conclusions. But there
is some amusement in reflecting upon the basketball rhetoric in the
eight months since pro ball was last conducted in these parts.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen, Charles Barkley, Vlade Divac, Jayson Williams,
Jason Caffey, Matt Geiger _ all were talked up as potential Sonic
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   But the reality of the new labor agreement coupled with the
handsome salaries already being paid to the current roster has left
the Sonics with Polynice. And Owens, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Polynice is 34 and wasn't cutting it last year in the backwater
of Sacramento. Should he make it here, Owens, another Kings
refugee, has the unusual distinction of having his scoring average
decline in each of the last six seasons. Not an easy feat for
someone, at 29, entering his prime.
</P>
<P>
   And whatever roster Westphal ends up with, it will be on a
forced march through two segments of the schedule that has five
games in six nights. During one stretch, they will play 16 games in
23 days.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, McIlvaine is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like the best marketing slogan available.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 0102EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3937 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--PIPPEN-HNS &LR;      01-22 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--PIPPEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
The weirdest NBA season just couldn't turn normal. The plan to
squeeze an entire offseason of deal-making, contract-writing,
trades, and signings into one afternoon with timing as precise as
the Manhattan subway system, all with 28 other teams rushing
through the same convoluted maze, somehow hit a snag.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen will join the Rockets, the team and his agent
pledged, likely sometime early this morning.
</P>
<P>
   But it did not happen Thursday, and all the subsequent player
signings were placed on hold so the Rockets and Pippen's attorneys
could make their way through the new collective-bargaining
agreement to write a contract the NBA could approve.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a problem with the collective-bargaining agreement as
it was written last year and is written this year,'' Rockets owner
Leslie Alexander said at a news conference Thursday at Westside
Tennis Club. ``Because of that problem, we have to get it agreed to
by the league. It's going to take some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say how proud and happy we are to have him here.
We're working toward a good resolution. This guy does want to be a
Rocket real bad.''
</P>
<P>
   With Pippen unsigned, the Rockets remained under the salary cap
and as such did not officially sign their own free agents _ Othella
Harrington, Matt Maloney, Matt Bullard and Eddie Johnson _ or Hawks
free agent Anthony ``Pig'' Miller and former Suns player John
Coker.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley, who needed to be the first Rockets free agent
under contract, did sign Thursday in Palm Springs, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets forwarded clarification on part of that deal to the
league but as of late Thursday had not received league approval.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets renounced their rights to their other free agents _
Mario Elie, Joe Stephens, Emanual Davis, Charles Jones and Clyde
Drexler _ to clear salary-cap room to sign Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Pippen deal did not go through the league's
approval process, everything else ground to a halt. The Rockets
needed to sign Pippen to fill the remaining salary-cap space before
they could sign their own free agents as Larry Bird exceptions to
the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Coker and Miller were to be signed to league-minimum contacts,
permissible for teams over the cap.
</P>
<P>
   When Pippen could not complete the cap space, the rest of the
team could not be signed.
</P>
<P>
   There were reports Roy Rogers, dealt to the Bulls as part of the
Pippen deal, did not pass his physical.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not affect the trade for Pippen or the delay on
gaining approval on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have a deal completed sometime this evening (late
Thursday or early Friday),'' said Pippen's agent, Jimmy Sexton.
``It won't be a problem with the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just some issues with us getting the
collective-bargaining agreement so late we have to work through and
get it corrected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has nothing to do with the trade.''
</P>
<P>
   But it did have to do with parts of the contract as they relate
to Pippen's acquisition in a sign-and-trade deal with the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new sign-and trade deals are a little different,'' Sexton
said. ``There haven't been near as many of those done as this year
because of the new collective-bargaining agreement. So that makes
his deal a little bit different.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sexton minimized the issues holding up the deal as typical,
only made more difficult by the logjam of contracts and deals
needing NBA approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely backed up right now,'' Sexton said. ``It's a
situation (in which) you have to wait until they have time to deal
with you. We have to wait until we get that accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last 10 days are what's frustrating. Trying to cram six
months of work into 10 days is tough. This part isn't bad. Every
contract, this happens. This is not unusual. You have this on every
deal you do getting into the league office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been going through different things on the contract,
things like that. This is not a surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was a nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   It canceled not only the news conference to introduce the team
but the practice Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich scheduled for
Thursday night to start training camp.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the latest twist in the NBA's strange season still
in lockout knots, Pippen spoke as if the fine print would not
prevent what he had come to town to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to be a Rocket,'' he said as if he already were.
``I'm happy to be in the city of Houston, and I'm looking forward
to bringing a championship here to this basketball team. I want to
thank all the fans that have been very warm to me around the city
in the little time I've been here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can just see I'm going to have a wonderful career here in
the city of Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   After six months of lockout limbo, and two weeks of deal-making
that followed, the rest of his teammates-in-waiting just had to
wait a night longer to begin the wonderful part.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 0107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
