<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3938 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IOC-NBC-NYT &LR;      01-22 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-NBC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC MEMBER WEARS A SECOND HAT: NBC'S 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah, Australia)  (js) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For many years, NBC Sports was virtually a forgotten network
when it came to carrying the Olympics. Its competitor, ABC Sports,
led by Roone Arledge, had made the Olympics virtually its own. But
that changed in 1988 when NBC carried the first of three
consecutive Summer Games, and was transformed in 1995 when a
startling pair of deals brought it the rights to carry all five
Olympics from 2000 to 2008.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic bounty cost NBC a bundle. For next year's Summer
Olympics in Sydney, Australia, NBC is paying $705 million in cash.
For the scandal-scarred 2002 Winter Olympics in Salt Lake City, NBC
will pay $545 million. The price tag for the next three after that,
including the 2004 Athens Summer Games, is $2.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A constant presence for NBC, from the fallow years to the fat
years, has been an Israeli named Alex Giladi. A confidante of Juan
Antonio Samaranch, the president of the International Olympic
Committee, Giladi has been an NBC executive since 1981, assigned to
build its international business.
</P>
<P>
   ``He developed relationships for us in Europe so we weren't
perceived as strangers,'' said Dick Ebersol, the chairman of NBC
Sports.
</P>
<P>
   Giladi, 56, has also served as a member of the IOC's radio and
television commission, an advisory panel with no role in television
negotiations, since 1985. In 1994 he became the first Israeli
elected to the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   There are no rules against Giladi's arrangement, nor any charges
from competing networks that Giladi helped NBC secure its
blockbuster Olympic deal. His presence in both hierarchies is
viewed as a coincidence, but it nevertheless provides a glimpse
into the business of the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an engaging fellow, smokes big cigars, is very charming,
and is fond of quoting Samaranch,'' said Neal Pilson, a former
president of CBS Sports. ``But I don't think there's anything
improper. The question of whether Giladi should be an NBC employee
and an IOC member is up to the IOC.''
</P>
<P>
   A.D. Frazier, the former chief operating officer of the Atlanta
Committee for the Olympic Games, said he observed no unusual
influence from Giladi's being both part of Samaranch's inner circle
and an NBC executive. NBC's $456 million payment for the 1996
Summer Olympic television rights greatly exceeded ABC's when sealed
bids were opened in 1993, a year before Giladi became an IOC
member.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I think Alex's situation is weird? Yes,'' said Frazier.
``But did NBC save our bacon? Yes, thank God.'' He added: ``If Alex
used any undue influence, it sure cost NBC a lot. They got no
advantage from Alex.''
</P>
<P>
   Giladi was traveling Thursday and unavailable for comment, but
in 1995 he said his dual positions constituted ``a wonderful
combination.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol said that Giladi has never negotiated an Olympic
television contract or has been part of creating a bid. ``Because
of my phobia for secrecy, I kept him completely out of that
stuff,'' Ebersol said.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol did note that Giladi accompanied him and other NBC
executives to present their sealed bid for the Atlanta Games, but
said that Giladi did not know how NBC's $456 million bid was
reached.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol also said Giladi played no role in NBC's deal that
brought it the rights to both the Sydney and Salt Lake City Games.
Neither, he said, did NBC get inside information about Fox's $701
million offer for Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Alex knew about it, he didn't tell me,'' Ebersol said.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol said that he and a few NBC executives, but not Giladi,
crafted a single Sydney-Salt Lake blockbuster in the summer of
1995, as a possible alternative to a planned joint NBC-ABC bid for
the Sydney rights alone. While discussing the NBC-ABC proposal with
Robert Wright, the NBC president, Ebersol said that Randy Falco,
another NBC executive, suggested that NBC bid solo for Sydney and
Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol said that Giladi accompanied him and Falco on an Aug. 2
flight to Goteborg, Sweden, for a meeting with Samaranch to make
the 2000-2002 offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alex was going with us as our liaison to the World Track and
Field Championships,'' Ebersol said. ``Alex asked, `What are you
going to pitch?' I outlined it for him and he said, `Not a chance.'
I got very angry and said, `I'm not going to deal with skepticism,
you'd better get positive.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting with Samaranch did not include Giladi.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, Aug. 4, after Ebersol and Falco flew to Montreal to
meet with Richard Pound, the IOC member who negotiates television
contracts, the Sydney-Salt Lake deal was wrapped up. Ebersol said
that only after the deal was done did Pound tell him about Fox's
$701 million offer for Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was not something Alex knew about,'' Pound said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the timing of Fox's attempt to buy the Sydney
Games and NBC's two-Olympics coup, each coming in the same week,
was coincidental. Later that year NBC made its successful
pre-emptive bid for the three Olympics after that, an unprecedented
acquisition that reversed a bidding practice begun for the 1988
Olympics in which each network submitted sealed bids.
</P>
<P>
   Fox made its bid to Pound late on Monday, July 31, 1995, but it
did not conform to the IOC's bid contracts, said Pound, who did not
follow up with Chase Carey, the chairman of Fox Television, because
of NBC's interest.
</P>
<P>
   Days later, NBC trumped Fox and any other network that hoped to
bid for future Olympic rights, including CBS, which had committed
$913 million for the rights to the 1992, 1994 and 1998 Winter
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after NBC's deal was announced, Francois Carrard, the
IOC's director general, said Fox's bid ``was not credible enough.''
The IOC, some industry executives believe, regards Rupert Murdoch,
whose News Corp. owns Fox, with suspicion for the racy reputation
of his newspapers and his aggressiveness in bidding for sports .  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 0108EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3941 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--BARKLEY-HNS &LR;      01-22 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--BARKLEY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
LA QUINTA, Calif. _ Charles Barkley ducked into the scorer's tent
at the 10th tee at Tamarisk Country Club on Thursday and began
scribbling autographs, one after another.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But these signatures weren't for kids or memorabilia hounds.
They were on his new one-year contract with the Rockets. Barkley
rapidly signed and flipped pages.
</P>
<P>
   Then he raised up and said, ``This is an awful lot of signing
for such a little bit of money.''
</P>
<P>
   By NBA standards, Barkley, 35, couldn't have been more correct.
He signed for the minimum salary for veterans with 10 years of
experience or more, $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   That a golf game had to be interrupted for Barkley to sign his
contract is appropriate. After the NBA lockout wiped out three
months of the season, Barkley has played a lot more golf than
basketball since last season ended for him with a torn triceps
tendon. He's playing in the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic with Michael
Jordan as he puts a lid on his golf season.
</P>
<P>
   As Barkley was penning his pact, a voice from the gallery
yelled: ``You should have held out for more.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley said, ``There wasn't that much to hold out for.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, he was accurate. Barkley knew that if the Rockets were to
combine Scottie Pippen's talents with those of Hakeem Olajuwon and
himself, Barkley had to sign a contract that is worth less than
what he was making 10 years ago. That was so other dominoes could
fall as the roster was to be filled.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley said he thought he had to sign the contract because of a
pledge he made to the Rockets. He also knew that signing Thursday
was necessary because until he signed, the Rockets were hamstrung
and couldn't make any other deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure it's a good deal for me,'' he said. ``But I made
a promise to the Rockets a long time ago that if they got Scottie
Pippen, I would be back. And I didn't want to go back on my word.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley's salary will rank him in the lower half of the NBA's
pay scale, but it gives the Rockets a chance to be serious
championship contenders, something they were not in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team is pretty damn good,'' Barkley said. ``We're a lot
better this year than we have been the past two years. There's no
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we the favorites? I don't know about about that. We're
going to have to beat all the usual suspects in the West _ the
Lakers, Utah and Seattle. But with me, Hakeem and Scottie, that's a
damn good foundation. I like my team a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley added that his close relationship with coach Rudy
Tomjanovich was the primary factor in him returning to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudy is the only reason I'm coming back,'' Barkley said. ``He
was the underlying factor for everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley was all smiles after signing the contract, even though
he had some anxious moments, even as late as Thursday morning, when
he went through a series of frantic cellular-phone calls with his
agent and the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad to be back,'' Barkley said. ``When's the first
practice?''
</P>
<P>
   Informed it was to start in a few hours in Houston, Barkley
said: ``Tell everybody I'll see them Sunday or Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Barkley may yet make the first practice. A
bottleneck in the NBA office caused by a deluge of signings and
other transactions led to the Rockets being forced to cancel
Thursday night's practice.
</P>
<P>
   Another bottleneck came when the league office requested the
Rockets to provide a series of unspecified clarifications regarding
Barkley's contract. The team provided the information and was
awaiting a response from the league office late Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets' season will begin Feb. 5 against the Los Angeles
Lakers. Barkley said he anticipates no problems getting ready for
the opener of the abbreviated season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in great shape,'' he said. ``I'm in a lot better shape
this year than I was last year before camp.''
</P>
<P>
   It shows. Barkley has lost the paunch that had become his
trademark during training camps past. He believes good conditioning
will be crucial this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing for us is that we stay healthy,''
Barkley said. ``In a 50-game season, you can't afford to have key
people miss many games. So we've got to have Hakeem's knees in good
shape, and Scottie's back has to be OK. And I've got to stay
healthy, too. We're going to be playing three games in three nights
sometimes, which is stupid. So we have to stay healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley added he believes the trio of himself, Olajuwon and
Pippen will be stronger than the one Clyde Drexler was a part of
the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a great player like Scottie Pippen, you can find a
way to help your team,'' Barkley said. ``He'll fit in fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Before signing his contract, Barkley had given every indication
he was wrestling with his decision. Seattle was offering twice as
much money.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived on the putting green at 9:40 a.m. His cellular phone
rang within minutes. It was his agent. After a 10-minute
conversation during which Barkley was overheard saying, ``I'm
either going to sign with the Rockets or Seattle today,'' he was
instructed to call the Rockets, which he did.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley's group for Thursday's round at the Bob Hope Chrysler
Classic _ including Michael Jordan, Roy Green and John Daly _ was
due on the tee at 9:58 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley teed off, then kept the cell phone to his ear throughout
the first hole, handing it off to a security guard only long enough
to hit his shots. Clearly, his mind wasn't on golf.
</P>
<P>
   By the fourth tee, Barkley still wasn't concentrating on golf.
</P>
<P>
   After his tee shot, he said to caddie Brett Tyson: ``Can you
believe I'm getting screwed out of a million dollars?''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But Barkley's agreeing to a one-year deal also
reinforces what he has said many times: that money is not the
driving force for him to play basketball anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got enough money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after making a bogey on No. 9, Barkley was waved to the
scorer's tent in between the ninth green and 10th tee. Mike Wells,
an assistant to Tomjanovich, presented Barkley with a document that
was about one-quarter-inch thick. Barkley said the signing was a
lot more than just a formality. He considered joining the
SuperSonics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was close with the Sonics,'' Barkley said. ``Vin Baker and
Gary Payton did a good job last weekend in Las Vegas working on me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm breaking their hearts right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though $1 million is not an NBA star's idea of big money,
the signing must have eased Barkley's nerves. On the back nine, he
birdied a par-5, giving him a net eagle on the hole for his team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
