<HEADER>
A3942 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-22 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IT'S unofficially official, which fit on this day.
</P>
<P>
   This was not a day for the cut-and-dried. This was not a simple
case of crossing the last few ``t's'' and dotting the final few
``i's.'' This wasn't simple at all.
</P>
<P>
   If it had been, Scottie Pippen would have been an official
Rockets star Thursday. Instead, he is only waiting and waiting.
Like we all are.
</P>
<P>
   He is only another transplanted house-hunter, trying to tell the
West Loop from the East Belt, the Katy Freeway from the Gulf
Freeway, and waiting for that first day of work to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   But he is someone this city finally laid eyes upon Thursday,
presumably becoming an instant Rockets hero, unofficially.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Pippen became the local media's newest best friend _
a guy who knows how to make a first impression and nudge his way
into hearts, even as the Rockets jersey was all but pulled off his
back with the lights on and the cameras rolling.
</P>
<P>
   As the day got longer and the deal shakier _ something about
contract wording and league-office hang-ups _ Pippen apologized for
the long wait and splurged for the refreshments.
</P>
<P>
   Free cheese sandwiches. Free cheese sticks. Free cheese pizza.
And beer. Angioplasties will be extra at a date to be named, but
why worry about such things like that now?
</P>
<P>
   Pippen will be a Rocket. Don't worry about a thing, the Rockets
told us. Don't worry about a thing, Pippen told us. It probably
will become official today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long night, and it will be longer,'' Rockets owner
Leslie Alexander said. ``But here's Scottie.''
</P>
<P>
   And sure enough there was Pippen, talking about being happy to
be here, about looking forward to the season and eventually
``having a wonderful run here.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was all unofficial, of course. It was all pending league
approval, which was expected to come at some point early this
morning.
</P>
<P>
   It all fit perfectly on this all-day, well-into-the-night frenzy
of waiting for the final piece of the puzzle to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   The day that would be Pippen's began for some in the Rockets
organization at 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   It proved to be like a strange sort of crash course on
franchise-building come to life.
</P>
<P>
   It was a kind of NBA 12-step program on how to put together a
potential NBA champion, with the Rockets' staff spending most of
the day skipping two or three steps at a time on the way to
hopefully finally putting a team on the court.
</P>
<P>
   But somehow, everything was tripped up on the last step.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley was a Rocket, then he wasn't. Matt Bullard and
Matt Maloney were Rockets, then they weren't. Pippen put on his
best suit, then he undid his tie and walked away.
</P>
<P>
   First, things were put off because of Pippen's travel itinerary.
There also was the search for Barkley amid the out-of-bounds stakes
at the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic.
</P>
<P>
   There was the ever-present NBA litigation and Alexander
occasionally having to stop to rub the cramps out of his
contract-signing hand.
</P>
<P>
   Details, the Rockets said.
</P>
<P>
   Picture Alexander sitting behind his desk Thursday afternoon,
giddily smiling and signing deal after deal, like Mel Brooks in
Blazing Saddles, knowing that by the end of the night all his
dreams would come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Work, work, work. Work, work, work.''
</P>
<P>
   It's tough being kings of the NBA world, but that's exactly what
Alexander and the Rockets seemed to be putting the finishing
touches on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers were sent back and forth, picking up players and agents.
A makeshift stage was put together at midcourt of Westside Tennis
Club. Caterers were called; sound people checked microphones.
</P>
<P>
   A Rockets staffer and notary even flew to Los Angeles, hopped on
a golf cart and tracked down Barkley at the Chrysler tournament so
he could sign his new Rockets contract.
</P>
<P>
   Cell phones chimed. Fax machines buzzed. Players gathered at the
Westside locker room and talked about how great it was that the
season finally was set to begin.
</P>
<P>
   But then, it didn't. First practice was canceled, and then the
grand announcement about Pippen was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   The season was put off one more time, meaning the Rockets might
be the last NBA team to start this strange 1999 basketball season,
which might also be appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   After all, judging from everything that became unofficially
official Thursday, the Rockets might be the last ones standing in
late June.
</P>
<P>
   We should expect it all to happen officially today. We should
expect in about 90 days for Pippen and the Rockets to pick up where
Pippen and the Bulls left off.
</P>
<P>
   We should expect a championship run. The wait will be worth it.
And then maybe we should expect more pizza and beer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
