<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3943 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-ISLANDERS-MILBURY     01-22 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLANDERS-MILBURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS ISLES' FREE FALL CONTINUES, MILBURY STEPS ASIDE AS COACH 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Less than 24 hours after hearing chants of ``Mike
must go! Mike must go!'' during a listless loss at Nassau Coliseum,
Mike Milbury resigned Thursday as the Islanders' coach for the
second time in two years.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement, which came two and a half hours before
Thursday night's 5-2 victory over the Pittsburgh Penguins, was the
latest development to rock the franchise this decade. Unsteady
ownership, frequent coaching changes, a revolving-door roster, rare
playoff appearances and shrinking attendance have plagued the
franchise, which won four consecutive Stanley Cups beginning in
1980.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Stewart, the Islanders' first-year assistant coach,
replaced Milbury, who will remain as the team's general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Milbury, who signed a five-year coaching contract last May, said
he made his decision after Wednesday night's 5-2 loss to the
Florida Panthers. The Islanders had not won a game since Dec. 26
before winning on Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big-time statement,'' Milbury said, referring to
the game Wednesday night. ``I told them I've been around a long
time, and last night was as listless a performance as any that I
can remember. Right now motivation is the main thing. They seem to
be feeling sorry for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Islanders' season-breaking 0-10-1 streak, it had
become apparent that some, if not most, of the players had begun to
tune out Milbury. The trade of Bryan Berard, a talented 21-year-old
defenseman who was popular with his teammates, for the goaltender
Felix Potvin, may have further weakened his relationship with the
players.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if pressures of coaching hurt his ability to direct the
team from a general manager's standpoint, Milbury said,
``Absolutely not.'' However, in public and private conversations,
people close to Milbury said that he told them he did not want the
dual roles, but was forced into them by the new owners.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Milbury; Ed Milstein, a member of the team's
ownership group; David Seldin, the president, and Steven
Gluckstern, a co-owner, discussed making a change over lunch at
Milbury's house, but no decision was made until Thursday when
Milbury called Gluckstern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this was the way to go,'' Milbury said. ``You can't
go on a streak like this. It happened to Rick Bowness last year. He
couldn't turn them, and I can't turn them on right now. If the them
team quits on the coach, it's an awful tough thing to get them
back.''
</P>
<P>
   That responsibility now belongs to the 41-year-old Stewart, a
defensive strategist. Stewart, a 10-year veteran as a defenseman in
the National Hockey League, last season coached St. John of the
American Hockey League to the Calder Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not into this rah-rah stuff,'' said Stewart, who is
described by players as a good communicator and as very intense.
``I'd rather get results _ it's all about winning. Winning and
losing, nothing more, nothing less.''
</P>
<P>
   About the decision to promote Stewart instead of the assistants
Wayne Fleming or Lorne Henning, Milbury said, ``We hired Bill
Stewart over the summer knowing that he had been successful at
every level that he coached and that someday he might get the
opportunity here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Isles are 14-29-3 and on course to miss the playoffs for the
fifth consecutive year. Zigmund Palffy, Trevor Linden, Lachance and
Tommy Salo, to name a few, have not played to their ability. Since
returning from a 32-game holdout, Palffy has 3 goals and 6 assists
in 13 games. Linden, the captain, has 11 goals, 15 assists and a
minus-9 rating and does not have a goal since Dec. 26. Defenseman
Scott Lachance has struggled all season and is minus-16.
</P>
<P>
   Milbury, 46, was named coach on July 5, 1995, adding the general
manager's title five months later. He reluctantly relinquished the
coaching job in January 1997 and hired Bowness. He went 37-50-12
and was fired by Milbury last March 11, not long after a 10-game
losing streak. Milbury went back behind the bench for last season's
final 19 games.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over all, Milbury was 57-111-24 in parts of four seasons as
Islanders coach. He also was the coach of the Boston Bruins for two
seasons, with a pair of Adams Division titles and a trip to the
1990 Stanley Cup finals.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Milbury's resignation is the latest turmoil in the Islanders'
organization in the past two and a half years.
</P>
<P>
   John Spano, who was announced as the team's buyer in late 1996,
pleaded guilty to fraud charges last January for lying to banks and
the National Hockey League by saying that he had enough money to
buy the team.
</P>
<P>
   New owners were found in September 1997 _ Gluckstern, an
insurance executive, and Howard Milstein, a real estate executive.
Before this season, however, they expressed concerns about Nassau
Coliseum's safety and sought to play the games in other arenas. The
Islanders moved out of the Coliseum and sued their landlord. But
the plan to play elsewhere was struck down in court, and
negotiations over a new arena foundered. Progress was reported this
week, however, on reaching an agreement on a new arena.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
