<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Q&AMP;A LIABLE TO BE `FREE-FOR-ALL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate impeachment trial could be headed for a
free-for-all today because cooperation among Democrats and
Republicans has faltered again, this time over key procedures for
how senators will pose questions to the parties, says Sen. Jon Kyl,
R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats have refused to agree to anything, so we go to this
questioning period wide open. It's literally a free-for-all,'' Kyl
told ``The Arizona Republic'' on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Kyl and Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said one key point
had been decided: Republicans and Democrats are to alternate
questions.
</P>
<P>
   But virtually everything else was left unsettled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could the respondent take an unlimited time to answer? Should
a response of the other side be permitted?'' Kyl asked. ``I hope my
fears of confusion are ill-founded.''
</P>
<P>
   Questions may be directed either to House managers or to the
White House legal team.
</P>
<P>
   Kyl said Republicans had already filed 80 questions by midday
Thursday. Ten of them are Kyl's own. It could not be determined
Thursday how many questions had been submitted by Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's defense team concluded its case Thursday
with a presentation by former Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark. Democratic
senators said they hoped to end the trial soon with an up-or-down
impeachment vote, but Republicans cautioned against a rush to
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment trial calendar says the next step is this:
``Senate questions parties, not to exceed 16 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were few rules in place to guide the senators. It may
be left to Chief Justice William Rehnquist, who has thus far not
played a significant role, to halt responses that seem too long.
</P>
<P>
   The trial began two weeks ago with Lott and Minority Leader Tom
Daschle, D-S.D., proudly announcing a framework in which to
proceed. Lott and Daschle said it was critical that the parties
work together.
</P>
<P>
   But the civility began to fall apart when Democrats accused
Republicans last week of holding private meetings with House
managers on the witness issue. Republicans countered that Democrats
had indeed been invited, albeit belatedly, and that nothing was
decided behind their backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bipartisan agreement was to be a framework, and the
assumption was that we would continue to meet on a bipartisan basis
and work out details,'' Kyl said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as of (Thursday night), they (Democrats) wouldn't agree to
something as basic as, `Republicans would ask questions for an
hour, and Democrats would ask questions for an hour,' or something
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Daschle, the Democrats' lead spokesman, was unavailable Thursday
night to respond to Kyl's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans began submitting their questions this week to Sen.
Orrin Hatch, R-Utah. Hatch has been busy organizing the questions
into logical order and eliminating duplicates.
</P>
<P>
   After the question-and-answer phase, Democrats are expected to
seek a dismissal of the case. At that time, Republicans may push to
summon witnesses for depositions or public appearances. The
witnesses could include Monica Lewinsky, the former White House
intern whose affair with Clinton led to the impeachment charges. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
