A3949 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-PANTHERS-     01-22 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-PANTHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAGUED BY PAVEL, RANGERS LOSE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Rangers begin the All-Star break the way they
began the season: with a four-game losing streak. Thursday night's
defeat was particularly aggravating. After coming from behind to
tie the score, they lost by 2-1 in Madison Square Garden to the
Florida Panthers. The winning goal, at 18 minutes 17 seconds of the
third period, was scored on a long slap shot by defenseman Bret
Hedican, who intercepted John MacLean's clearing pass and drilled
the puck past goalie Mike Richter.
</P>
<P>
   Hedican was acquired earlier this week in a trade with Vancouver
that also brought Pavel Bure, who scored the other Florida goal.
</P>
<P>
   This was a tense and rugged game with an edge to it between two
Eastern Conference rivals who would not be among the eight to
qualify for the playoffs from their half of the league if the
post-season were to begin today.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the low goal total, scoring chances were plentiful and
both goalies were serenaded by the ringing of their goal posts.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Stevens of the Rangers tied the score at 1-1 at 7:47 of
the third period when he beat Florida goalie Sean Burke with a low
wrist shot from the dot of the right-wing faceoff circle. Stevens
sprang loose behind the defense and took a bank pass off the boards
from Brent Fedyk. It was Fedyk's first point of the season. Moments
before, Burke denied Fedyk on two close-in chances.
</P>
<P>
   With 7:34 remaining in the third period, the Panthers called a
timeout to plan strategy for a two-man advantage that lasted for 43
seconds. The Rangers killed it off, drawing chants and cheers from
their fans, who increased the volume when the home team killed off
the remaining one-man advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Bure scored two goals in his season debut on Wednesday night, a
5-2 victory over the Islanders at Nassau Coliseum. Thursday night,
he gave the Panthers a 1-0 lead at 6:45 of the second period when
the teams were each playing with one man in the penalty box.
Breaking loose ahead of the play and taking a long pass from Rob
Niedermayer, Bure raced in alone on Richter, made a couple of fakes
and put the puck between Richter's legs and over the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   Bure refused to report to the Vancouver Canucks this season and
forced a trade that occurred last Sunday. He traveled from Moscow
to New York on Tuesday and played limited minutes in both games.
The Rangers were one of the teams negotiating for Bure all season,
but Brian Burke, the Canucks' general manager, turned the Rangers
down when they refused to include Manny Malhotra, the rookie
center, in the package.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers came into Thursday night's game with only two goals
in their previous three games. They thought they scored twice early
in the second period, but they were foiled once by a video review
and the other time when an official mistakenly blew his whistle.
The first was on a power-play shot by Petr Nedved, who took Wayne
Gretzky's pass and beat Sean Burke over the shoulder on the stick
side, but the puck hit the cross bar and the goal post before
bouncing back.
</P>
<P>
   On the second play, Adam Graves crowded the crease and knocked a
rebound over the line. But Paul Stewart, one of two referees, waved
it off because he had blown the whistle, apparently thinking the
goalie had covered the puck.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Mellanby, the Panthers' captain, left the game in the
second period and appeared to be in great pain with a pinched nerve
sustained in a collision with Ranger defenseman Ulf Samuelsson. It
happened while Mellanby manned the left point on the power play.
Samuelsson, who was playing with the flu, appeared to hit Mellanby
in the face with his left hand. But it was just a glancing blow and
the injury apparently was caused by something else.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Lindsay, Florida's scrappy left wing, seems to play his
best against the Rangers. Lindsay had five hits in the first
period, most of them against Nedved. In response, Lindsay was
slammed to the ice by Jeff Beukeboom, the big Ranger defenseman. In
the second period, Lindsay was penalized for roughing Nedved. In
the final minute before the second intermission, Lindsay took a
two-minute minor for interfering with Richter behind the Rangers'
net.
</P>
<P>
   That would have given the Rangers another power play, but it was
negated when Graves came to Richter's defense and hit Lindsay with
a couple of punches, and both men were sent off with minors. The
Rangers' power play had led the league for much of the season, but
they had only one goal in 18 chances with the manpower advantage in
the previous four games. In the first two periods Thursday night,
the Rangers had no power-play goals in six chances over a span of
10:54.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Mathieu Schneider was out for the fourth time in the
last five games with a groin strain. Gretzky played despite neck
spasms that have bothered him all week. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
