<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-STADIUM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CSUN HEAD GETS STADIUM ALTERNATIVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The future home of Cal State Northridge football
will be decided by university President Blenda Wilson, but without
the aid of a singular recommendation from a site committee.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of recommending one site for a football field, the site
committee reverted to a previous plan and suggested an on-campus
site and an off-campus site during the final meeting Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The site committee voted 6-2 to recommend an 8,000-seat facility
on the North Campus for its on-campus selection. The location for
the $8million to $10million project is approximately 75 yards south
of the current stadium and would be just north of Lassen Street.
With a unanimous 8-0 vote, the committee recommended a renovation
of Pierce College as its off-campus site.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a motion passed with a 7-1 vote to have the final
site committee's recommendation include the surrounding community's
site preference.
</P>
<P>
   The evening's events didn't offer a lot of solace to residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what President Wilson wants, which is an on-site
stadium,'' said committee member Bob LoPresti, a CSUN graduate and
member of the Lindley West Coalition. ``I believe this committee
would be used as a scapegoat, and she could blame it on them, (if
we voted for one site). This is where we were a year ago. That
stadium started right at (the North Campus) location a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the 11 committee members who held votes attended the
meeting. Joining LoPresti for a ``nay'' vote for the on-campus site
was Bob Galletly, who represents Northridge Townhome Estates.
</P>
<P>
   Residents representing the Zelzah Coalition and La Villa Nueva
Homeowners were also in attendance. The homeowner groups are
concerned about noise pollution, increased crime and traffic if a
facility is erected on the North Campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community was heard and I think they made a clear and
unambiguous statement,'' Galletly said. ``This committee is not
going to be the scapegoat, and we should be as objective as
possible in making a recommendation for on-site or off-site.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee chairman David Honda, who didn't hold a vote, said it
would take him approximately 30 days to complete the report and
turn it over to Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   However, a potential snag exists for the Pierce site. Honda, who
had a conference call with Pierce administrators Thursday morning,
said the school didn't want CSUN as a permanent tenant.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have no money and they don't want Cal State Northridge
for more than four or five years,'' Honda said. ``This makes
(Wilson's) job very high profile.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the same manner in which the previous meeting ended _
with two sites selected. But when the committee adjourned on that
November night, Honda said they would return for a final meeting
and recommend one site for the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   That was nearly two months ago, and though this meeting was much
more controlled and lacked the venom of the last, approximately 125
residents were in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN needs a venue for football. Its current home _ North Campus
Stadium _ is scheduled to be demolished following the 1999 season
because the land has been leased to Alfred Mann for a MiniMed
biotech facility. But the school did leave enough space to build an
8,000-seat stadium, which is needed to meet Big Sky Conference
standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleasantly surprised with the passion the community has
with regards to the opposition of the stadium,'' LoPresti said. ``I
think the residents have to gear up for phase two of the fight. I
think there's obviously litigation, but first is the (environmental
impact report) process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
