<SLUG> BC-INVEST-FRAUD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDS SUING TELEMARKETING FIRM IN INVESTOR FRAUD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The federal government is suing a telemarketing
company and its principal for allegedly defrauding investors out of
about $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission charged Assured
International Inc. and its principal, Sam E. Harris, a repeat
securities laws violator, with luring 82 investors into buying
shares in a fake business that claimed to make disposable latex
gloves.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC alleges that the company never made gloves. Instead, the
company has misused invested funding, including paying $202,422 to
Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach Harris' attorney for comment Thursday were
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Since February 1998, Assured International has received at least
$828,000 from investors nationwide. They sold common shares in the
company for 50 cents, and told investors that it was going public
in early 1999. The SEC said Assured International told investors
that they could sell their shares later for $5 to $8 each.
</P>
<P>
   The smallest investment was $5,000. Most investors gave $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities said these telemarketing boiler rooms are
becoming more prevalent. For some reason, they're clustering in the
San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing more of it. More and more (of these boiler
rooms) are moving to the (San Fernando) Valley -- Woodland Hills is
kind of popular,'' said Lisa Gok, assistant regional director for
enforcement at the SEC. ``We are aware of the boiler rooms and the
telemarketers who are in the Valley, and we will go after them with
the full force of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris is a repeat offender, the SEC said. Seven states have
sued him for various securities violations -- California,
Pennsylvania, Missouri, Kansas, Montana, Texas and Oregon. Illinois
and Indiana are suing Assured International for the latex glove
scheme.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC is seeking fines and a permanent injunction against
Harris' company. The agency also wants the court to order Harris to
return money they say he stole.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC has frozen his bank accounts, but authorities aren't
sure investors will get their money back. Typically, investors
rarely get back more than 10 percent to 20 percent of money they've
given to a boiler-room operation.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 0158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
