<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS GET EARLY JUMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. _ Minutes into the first practice of
training camp, the Lakers appeared the clear favorites in the NBA,
and not just because they have three All-Stars and the big genie at
center. No, their advantage lies in a simpler axiom: They've got
players.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen players donned the purple and gold Thursday at UC Santa
Barbara's Robertson Gym, and a 14th man, Rick Fox, was on the way,
delayed only by the 405 freeway. Contrast that to Phoenix, where
the poor Suns had just enough players for a game of bridge and it's
clear the Lakers have a 10-meter head start in the 50-game sprint
that starts Feb. 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got teams that ain't even got a team yet,'' forward
Robert Horry said, ``and we've got our whole team, plus some. We've
got a lot of guys who have been here before, a lot of guys who have
played together. And that's the key in this league, learning how to
play together.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's re-signing with the Lakers means all five starters from
last May are back, as are four bench players. And even one of the
new Lakers, Travis Knight, is an old Laker _ back after a year in
Boston. Add three rookies and veteran Derek Harper, and the Lakers
are both talented and deep, ready to embark on a season that
squeezes 50 games into 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   Schedules were released Thursday, and some guys got winded just
looking at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In-!ital!sane!off!,'' Eddie Jones said, poring over the
calendar.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers open Feb. 5 against Houston at the Forum and play
five games in seven nights, ending with a back-to-back at Denver
and Minnesota. They'll have three sets of back-to-back-to-backs
(three games in three nights) and a muscle-melting stretch in
mid-March of six games in six cities in nine nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not much time to breathe,'' noted Lakers executive Jerry West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crazy. Crazy,'' said Jones. ``I like stuff like this. That's a
tough schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gonna be who wants it the most, man. Looking at this
schedule, you gotta want it real bad.''
</P>
<P>
   All the more reason for the Lakers to be confident in the
returning nucleus that won 61 games and the newcomers who join
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a long, bruising season, so you really need
depth,'' Horry said. ``A team without depth is gonna be dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The familiar roster could get one more wrinkle, however.
</P>
<P>
   Denver's deal for Antonio McDyess and Phoenix's related deal
with the coveted Tom Gugliotta were on hold, and the Lakers
continue to hover on the edge of the Gugliotta situation.
</P>
<P>
   If Minnesota sees it will lose Gugliotta _ who can get more from
the Timberwolves than anyone else _ the Wolves might still work a
sign-and-trade with the Lakers to assure getting something in
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're kind of a last resort for Minnesota,'' West
said. ``If they get in trouble with (Gugliotta), then maybe we'll
have some reason to talk. But I think they feel confident they can
still sign him.''
</P>
<P>
   So Elden Campbell's name will continue to surface in trade
rumors for at least a few days, if not right into March and the
NBA's trade deadline.
</P>
<P>
   West said nothing was planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's on our team. He's here, and I assume he's going to remain
here,'' West said of Campbell. ``We're going to explore
possibilities up to the end, and if there's something we can do we
feel can help our team, we'll try to do that. We like what we have,
and it's really dangerous to tinker with something that's pretty
good already.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the Lakers could have difficulty finding enough
minutes to go around. With several players able to play two
positions, they're practically three deep all the way around.
</P>
<P>
   That means a tough time-management job for coach Del Harris, but
he was just thrilled to be back at work after a 204-day lockout and
countless delays this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my wife this morning that last night was like the first
day of school. I kept waking up about every hour,'' Harris said.
``I kept looking at the clock. It was like that all night.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The Lakers will hold a scrimmage Monday at 5 p.m. at
UCSB's Thunderdome. The public is invited, and admission is
free.... Tickets to all Lakers home games go on sale Sunday at the
Forum box office and all TicketMaster outlets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
