<P>
   Others, like AltaVista, read and index every word of every file
they can find on the Web. Conducting a complete search on AltaVista
could be your life's work.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing shows the variations among search engines better than a
hunt for information about 401(k) retirement plans.
</P>
<P>
   Ask HotBot to search for two different keywords _ ``40l(k)'' and
``401k'' _ and it will return with 10,866 documents containing
``401k'' and 92,115 documents with the more precise ``401(k)''
phrasing. AltaVista retrieves 70,120 documents containing ``40lk''
and 40,556 containing ``401(k).'' Yahoo! yields a mere 60 sites.
</P>
<P>
   The moral: How far you can go depends on where you start. Start
with Yahoo! and you will probably be frustrated at the paucity of
choices. Start with AltaVista and there is a good chance you'll be
overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   Excite (www.excite.com) offers a comfortable middle course. When
I searched for ``40lk'' or ``401(k),'' the engine returned with a
list of 20,218 Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on where I wanted to go, I could visit sites put up by
corporate giants, such as www.quicken.com and
www.fidelityatwork.com (Fidelity's omnibus site for tax-deferred
savings plans), or sites maintained by individual enthusiasts such
as economist William Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other sites worth visiting, arranged according to
the three main issues in 401(k) saving:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RETIREMENT PLANNING &LR;  &QL; : Am I saving enough and getting enough
return to
retire at the appointed age?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASSET ALLOCATION &LR;  &QL; : How should I invest my money? How much risk
should I
take for a given return?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PLAN FEES &LR;  &QL; : Is my employer's 401(k) plan a good one? The
central issue
here is how much the plan costs and who pays for it. Diligent
saving and smart asset allocation won't mean much if a plan sinks
from the weight of its expenses or the mediocrity of its choices.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with retirement planning. One of the most attractive
basic retirement calculator sites belongs to an individual, Tracy
Paul, on America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Her site (members.aol.com/tracy/paul/private/index.html) offers
a 401(k) accumulator and a retirement withdrawal plan. But like
other simple calculators, it omits factors like Social Security,
private pensions, and spousal earnings, so its usefulness is
limited.
</P>
<P>
   The online retirement calculator offered by Fidelity combines
your expected Social Security benefits, your expected private
pension, if any, and the projected results for your 401(k) plan.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard's site has no provision for private pensions, but it
does allow you to specify expected future living expenses, which
are just as important to a successful retirement as investment
returns.
</P>
<P>
   Many people can substantially improve their retirement outlook
by moving into housing that costs less or by moving to a part of
the country that is less expensive to live in.
</P>
<P>
   As a general rule, your retirement plan will work when your
accumulated financial assets equal about 20 times the annual
expenses not covered by other income sources. You get to that point
through asset allocation. The question is how to mix your
investment choices to get the highest return at the lowest risk.
</P>
<P>
   For a primer on how asset allocation can help produce a higher
return or lower risk, check out the Index Investor,
www.indexinvestor.com. Then look at William Bernstein's ``Efficient
Frontier: An Online Journal of Practical Asset Allocation''
(www.efficientfrontier.com), a site that combines dark humor with a
solid grounding in statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Another good site is Nobel Prize winner William Sharpe's new
venture, Financial Engines, at www.financialengines.com. Intended
as a service for 401(k) plans, Financial Engines forecasts the
chances that a saver will reach his or her goal with a given asset
allocation.
</P>
<P>
   And my own site, www.scottburns.com, provides a Couch Potato
Portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the investment community regularly complained
that people were too conservative as investors. But a new study by
the Employee Benefit Research Institute, www.ebri.org, indicates
that 401(k) holdings are now invested much as conventional pension
portfolios are, with just more than 60 percent in equities.
</P>
<P>
   To see if that trend holds true in the future, check in every
once in a while at www.hewitt.com/401kindex, an index of activity
in 401(k) plans; this site is maintained by Hewitt Associates, an
employee-benefits consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the cost of 401(k) plans was a non-issue for
most savers, but that's beginning to change.
</P>
<P>
   The shift from traditional, defined-benefit pension plans to
defined-contribution 401(k) plans has transformed money management
from a wholesale business into a retail one. In many cases, the
price of managing retirement assets has risen from less than 1
percent a year to more than 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To learn more about how these costs can affect long-term
performance, read the reports on fees from the Pension and Welfare
Benefits Administration at www.dol.gov/dol/pwba.
</P>
<P>
   A site that discusses the subject with, well, a good deal less
objectivity is 401k Scam at
http://members.aol.com/scam401k/index.html. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Contributing editor Scott Burns is the
personal-finance columnist for the Dallas Morning News. His e-mail
address is scott &LR; scottburns.com and his Web-site address is
www.scottburns.com.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
