<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-DEVILS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS FALL TO DEVILS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The NHL's All-Star break is here, a time
for most players to rest and relax after more than three months of
hockey.
</P>
<P>
   If the Los Angeles Kings wish to maximize their enjoyment of
this idyllic interlude in their season, they will do well to avoid
pondering their recent record, and they will cover their eyes
anytime anyone shows them the Western Conference standings.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a pair of goals by Jozef Stumpel, the Kings entered the
break Thursday night with a 3-2 loss to the New Jersey Devils
before an announced crowd of 11,267 at the Forum. Referee Mick
McGeough disallowed a goal by Donald Audette with 1:02 remaining
because Audette directed the puck into the net with his stick above
his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Kings (16-25-4) to 1-4-1 in their last six
games and 1-3 on their four-game home stand. Next up is a difficult
four-game trip to Dallas, Washington, Buffalo and Philadelphia, and
the Kings will be fortunate if they return from that trek only five
points out of a playoff berth, the distance that separates them
from the postseason at the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of the importance of the game against the Devils
(25-14-5), coach Larry Robinson juggled his lineup Thursday night.
He benched right wing Pavel Rosa and defenseman Steve Duchesne, and
dressed defensemen Philippe Boucher and Mark Visheau, moving
Visheau to a forward position as he has done several times this
season.
</P>
<P>
   For Boucher, it was his first appearance after 13 consecutive
games as a healthy scratch, and he responded with one assist and
two fights.
</P>
<P>
   For Duchesne, a major disappointment this season since signing
with the Kings as a free agent last summer, being benched probably
was a meant to give him something to think about during the
upcoming hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, though, nothing is imminent in terms of a
transaction involving Duchesne. General Manager Dave Taylor denied
a report on ESPN of a possible deal sending Duchesne to
Philadelphia for disappointing center Alexandre Daigle.
</P>
<P>
   As for the lineup changes, they had no positive effect on the
Kings' play for the game's first 20-odd minutes. The Devils piled
up a 23-4 advantage in shots on goal in the first period and pushed
the margin to 28-4 in the first two minutes of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils' first goal was one Jamie Storr would have liked to
have had back, an unscreened slap shot from the top of the right
faceoff circle that beat the Kings' goalie between the pads.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings got a break one minute later when Stumpel scored
his first goal of the game, a slap shot from the left circle that
should have been stopped by Martin Brodeur. The Devils' goalie got
only a piece of the puck with his glove, and it trickled into the
net.
</P>
<P>
   But that was the only noise the Kings would make in a first
period dominated by the Devils, who took a 2-1 lead when Bobby
Holik scored from the slot on a power play at 12:21.
</P>
<P>
   Things almost got much worse, when Luc Robitaille received a
double-minor penalty for high sticking late in the period. The
Devils fired 10 shots at Storr during the ensuing power play, but
he stopped them all.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't much he could do 42 seconds into the second period,
however, when Scott Niedermayer tucked in the rebound of a shot
from the right point by Brendan Morrison.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Kings' good fortune that after New Jersey amassed its
two-goal lead, the Devils gradually became more passive on the
attack. In their new role as the aggressors, the Kings began to get
scoring chances, and at 15:31, after Brodeur left a long rebound of
a shot from the left boards by Vladimir Tsyplakov, Stumpel fired
the rebound into the net from the high slot.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Kings trailed by only a goal heading into the final 20
minutes, but the Devils are not a team you want to try to rally
against, given their 18-1-2 record when leading after two periods.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were kept in check by Brodeur and the Devils' defense,
and were unable to score in the final 1:10 with Devils defenseman
Ken Daneyko serving a high-sticking penalty and Storr off for an
extra skater, coming closest on Audette's disallowed goal. For the
final 12.8 seconds the Kings had a three-man advantage, when
Niedermayer was sent off for tripping.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
