<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE BEATS WEBER STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Time for a quick evaluation of the Cal State
Northridge men's basketball team, courtesy of starting forward Jeff
Parris.
</P>
<P>
   So Jeff, which is the real team, the one that nearly blew a
20-point lead to winless Sacramento State on Wednesday night, or
the team that handled the second-best team in the Big Sky
Conference a loss Thursday night?
</P>
<P>
   ``We show two sides. We play with emotion and we play without
emotion,'' Parris said. ``When we play with emotion, we play a lot
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Well put. And blatantly obvious after the fired-up Matadors led
nearly wire-to-wire in a 78-68 victory over Weber State in front of
an announced crowd of 755 at Matador Gym.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN (12-8 overall, 4-4 in conference) extended its winning
streak to three and beat a hot team; Weber State (14-6, 5-2) had a
four-game win streak snapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably the biggest win we've had recently,'' said
junior center Rico Harris, who scored a team-high 15 and also
grabbed six rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said the Matadors ``were active... finding open men down
the court and getting dunks.''
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of rebounding, the Matadors beat the Wildcats
in every meaningful area. CSUN's bench outscored Weber State's
27-9. The Matadors also had 21 assists and shot 53 percent from the
field compared to Weber State's 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys played an all-around good game,'' CSUN coach Bobby
Braswell said, ``on both ends of the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Parris was typical of the effort. He was 6 of 7 from the floor
for 12 points in only 20 minutes, and he also grabbed two important
rebounds in the final two minutes when the Matadors were in the
midst of five consecutive missed free throws.
</P>
<P>
   And Parris made the play of the game with 4 minutes, 8 seconds
left. He blew by a defender on the baseline, dunked while getting
fouled and gave CSUN a 72-61 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Braswell said Parris' effort ``really lit a fire under us.''
</P>
<P>
   Weber State, which beat Eastern Washington 101-100 in four
overtimes last Saturday, couldn't get closer than six points the
rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have crumpled... simply just quit,'' Parris said.
``That's the shot in the arm that we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   There were other sparks. Greg Minor, who was sick with the flu
and didn't suit up on Wednesday, scored nine points and had four
assists in 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Minor made a 3-pointer with 6{ minutes left in the first half
that gave CSUN a 28-18 lead, and the Matadors took his cue. Brian
Heinle made a 20-footer that made it 30-18. Harris made a 3-pointer
from the top of the key to push the lead to 33-21.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN didn't relent. Markus Carr made two consecutive baskets to
give the Matadors a 39-21 lead _ their biggest of the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats only made one significant run, cutting a 51-35
deficit to 64-60 with 5:54 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each team is going to have a streak at one point,'' Braswell
said. ``We were ahead when they made theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Weber State forward Harold Arceneaux, the Big Sky's leading
scorer, had a game-high 26 points. But he was only 2 of 9 in first
half.
</P>
</TEXT>
