<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DRUNK-DRIVERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVING DRUNK TO MEAN LOSS OF THE VEHICLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Starting within the next month, the cars of people
arrested on drunken driving charges in New York City will be seized
on the spot and later forfeited if the drivers are convicted,
Police Commissioner Howard Safir announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to drive drunk,'' Safir said, ``you're going
to face a serious penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   State law currently allows the forfeiture of vehicles owned by
repeat offenders, but it is rarely enforced, officials said. And
critics warned that with forfeiture practices coming under
increasing scrutiny because of abuses by law enforcement agencies,
any attempt to expand forfeiture was likely to face tough legal
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the new plan withstood those challenges, it would
probably prove so cumbersome in practice that, like the state law,
it would almost never be enforced, said a lawyer who has instructed
prosecutors and police departments around the state on
drunken-driving enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sounds to me like something that's done to inspire the
public awareness of DWI,'' said the lawyer, Peter Gerstenzang,
author of the book ``Handling the D.W.I. Case in New York.'' ``But
I think once they get into it, they won't forfeit too many cars
because it's not worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir said the police would be using what he called a
``creative'' interpretation of the city's forfeiture laws, which
give the police the power to seize property used in the commission
of crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The cars of people arrested on drunken driving charges are now
held by the police until someone comes to pick them up. Under this
plan, Safir said, the impounded vehicles will be returned only if
the driver is acquitted or if the vehicle belongs to someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Upon conviction of a car's owner, the city will begin forfeiture
proceedings to assume ownership of the seized vehicle, Safir said.
Forfeited vehicles could be added to the city's fleet or sold at
auction. Several top city officials drive vehicles that were
forfeited by convicted drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   And, Safir said, because more than 6,000 people are arrested
each year on charges of driving while intoxicated, the city would
have to find room for all the confiscated vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Fisher Ricardella, who heads the New York City chapter
of Mothers Against Drunk Driving, praised the new initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we're concerned, these drunken drivers are using
their cars as 4,000-pound weapons and are causing a tremendous
amount of carnage on our streets and highways,'' she said. ``A cop
wouldn't walk in on a holdup in a grocery store, take away the
knife and then give it back later.''
</P>
<P>
   While stepped-up enforcement is not part of the plan, Mayor
Rudolph W. Giuliani said forfeiture would be a welcome addition to
his administration's arsenal of weapons against dangerous driving,
which has included speeding crackdowns and cameras that catch
drivers who run red lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will help us build on the success we had in reducing
traffic fatalities,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   Seizing cars may sound tough, he said, ``but anything we can do
to convince people not to get behind the wheel of the car after
they have had a drink is good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If it takes taking their car from them to convince them that
they should not get behind the wheel of the car after they've had a
drink,'' Giuliani said, ``we're probably saving them a lot of
problems in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Gradess, the executive director of the New York State
Defenders Association, said that the city and Safir were picking an
inopportune time to try to expand the uses of forfeiture.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing it at a moment in history when forfeiture laws,
even those used to attach property used as the direct instrument of
a crime'' _ such as burglars' tools _ ``are under intense
scrutiny,'' Gradess said.
</P>
<P>
   He cited cases where police departments and prosecutors' offices
were accused of seizing cars willy-nilly to expand their fleets.
</P>
<P>
   Forfeiture laws, he said, ``have been criticized by the Supreme
Court, by the Congress, and state legislatures are slowing down on
the use of forfeiture. Any law enforcement official who is
tinkering with the borders of forfeiture is probably making a
gigantic mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, the executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, also said he had some concerns about the legality
of the initiative. ``Clearly drunk driving is a serious criminal
offense, but this plan raises serious legal questions,'' Siegel
said. ``What the Giuliani administration wants to do is add a
punishment to the existing punishments for drunk driving. Generally
it is the legislative branch that has to amend the law to add a
punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir said that the city's administrative code gives the Police
Department the power to seize property used as a means of
committing a crime, adding that it should allow the police to seize
cars used by drunken drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 31 people were killed by drunken drivers in New York
City, down 40 percent from 1997, when 52 were killed, the police
said. Arrests on charges of driving while intoxicated also
decreased slightly last year to 6,368, down from 6,836 arrests in
1997, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear how many other states, if any, have
enacted similar seizure practices. According to information
compiled in November 1997 by the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration, 23 states have vehicle confiscation or impoundment
laws for drunken drivers, but most apply only to repeat offenders
or drivers 18 and under.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
