<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING THAT FAIR DAY'S PAY  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 24)
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS? (AT) in e-mail address in last graf should be replaced with
typographical symbol.) 
(af) 
 By MICHELLE COTTLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I love my job, but after five years, I am still making the
minimum pay for my position as a data-entry clerk though my
workload has increased significantly. In addition to continued
responsibility for my normal duties, I have been ``granted'' _ for
being such an excellent employee, my boss said _ three grandiose
titles that carry huge new responsibilities. But when I requested a
raise, my boss declined, saying that if she gave me one, she would
have to give all my co-workers one, too. Yet most of them earn more
than I do. So, do I quit a job I love because I am being taken
advantage of, or do I ask to be relieved of some of my duties and
risk angering management? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: Let's see. You make less money than your colleagues and you
do the work of several employees, yet your supervisor claims she
can't give you a raise because then everybody would expect one.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to take that ``kick me'' sign off your back.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the boss recognizes your abilities, and even talks
about your ``excellent'' performance. Your job now is to get her to
put her money where her mouth is by making her realize just how
valuable you are to the organization. And one of the surest ways to
do that, experts say, is to confront your employer with the
possibility of losing you.
</P>
<P>
   ``What she needs to do is look like crazy for another job,''
said Barbara B. Reinhold, career counselor and director of the
career development office at Smith College. Once you have a couple
of offers in hand, ask the boss for a tete-a-tete.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly A. Potter, an author and workplace psychologist in
Berkeley, Calif., advised: ``Go in and say, `Gee, I really love
being here; however, I've got these other offers. I'd really prefer
to stay, but this is what I need.' They may decide that they can
give one individual a raise after all.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps your boss doesn't realize how overworked you are. To
enlighten her _ and to improve your bargaining position _ compile a
list of your achievements and of the duties you perform that are
above and beyond the job you're being paid for, Ms. Potter said.
This will help you to present a compelling case for a raise, she
added, and to avoid going in with your ``head bowed like a puppy
asking, `Can I have a bone?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Keep the discussion focused on your commitment to the company
and the strength of your contributions. Asking to be relieved of
some duties would send the wrong message. ``It makes it sound like
there's something wrong with her,'' Ms. Potter said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if this process takes awhile, just getting out there and
looking around at other job options can provide a big boost for
morale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will make her feel like she has some control,'' Ms.
Reinhold said. ``She can't fall into a victim state. When people
stay in a position over which they feel they have no control, it's
a quick and slippery slope to emotional and physical illness.''
</P>
<P>
   No job is worth that. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she responds
to readers' questions about career and workplace issues. Send them
by e-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by mail to Working, Money &AMP;
Business, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd Street, New York, N.Y.
10036. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
