<HEADLINE>
DOWN BUT NOT OUT ON THE FAMILY FARM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 24) 
(af) 
 By ANDREA ADELSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the last days of 1998, W. Michael Bennett, a citrus grower
and cattle rancher in California's San Joaquin Valley, began a
frenzied race against the thermometer.
</P>
<P>
   As sunset temperatures slipped below freezing, Bennett threaded
his truck through 150 acres planted with fruit and vines. In the
glare of headlights, he switched on irrigation pumps and wind
machines that spewed out clouds of warming moisture. After a quick
bite and a few hours' sleep, he returned to the groves to repeat
the process.
</P>
<P>
   It was all to no avail; the entire crop of navel oranges and
lemons, valued the previous year at $115,000, failed. State
agriculture officials estimate that the weather damage to the
state's citrus crop reached $634 million, and Tulare County, where
Bennett's farm is located, was the hardest hit. ``As cold as it
got, we needed more help,'' Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   Nasty weather is the ancient enemy of farmers, of course, and
even in this age of high-technology, nobody has yet figured out how
to end a drought or stave off wind and freezing rain. The victims
can only do what they have always done: tighten their belts and
hope for better luck next season.
</P>
<P>
   For the Bennetts, that means making lists of trips to forgo,
purchases to postpone and farm operations to put off. While
disaster insurance and savings give them a safety net against
foreclosure, the couple are determined to get expenses in line with
income _ and everybody in the family, including the two of their
four children who still live at home, is expected to pitch in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a game plan,'' said Bennett, 52, whose father is also
a Central Valley grower. But, he adds, ``I don't know if it's going
to work out.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Marti, 47, isn't about to sink into self pity. The
couple's home, a 3,000-acre ranch in the Sierra Nevada foothills,
five miles from the citrus farm, was part of an original homestead
staked out in 1887 by her great-grandparents, and she displays a
stoicism born of four generations of harsh experience. ``It doesn't
do a thing to pound your head against the wall,'' she said. ``We'll
work with the hand we got.''
</P>
<P>
   So, in addition to the long hours she spends on the ranch, she
will do substitute teaching at the high school 15 miles away in
Porterville, a drive she makes anyway to drop off and pick up her
two teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the couple have postponed improvements they planned for
the ranch. They won't buy an $8,500 computer-connected digital
scale, and so will have to continue hauling their cows to the
nearby ranch of Mrs. Bennett's brother to be weighed. Paying $7,000
to increase their stock of bulls from six to eight, in a herd of
200 cattle, will also have to wait another year.
</P>
<P>
   The Bennetts have shelved plans to remodel their home, which was
built by Mrs. Bennett's grandparents in 1953, and will let the
energy-efficient windows they purchased for the remodeling collect
dust in storage. ``That stopped dead. We're going to use that money
on the ranch for operating funds,'' Mrs. Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   Another spending cut will be borne by the children, who raise
their own mini-herds of show cows to make money for college. With
weekend livestock fairs charging entrance fees of $30 a head,
Brooke, 14, and her brother Casey, 15, will be taking only four
calves, instead of eight, to competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Catastrophic crop insurance, made available to California
growers from the federal government after an even harsher freeze in
1990, will ease the Bennetts' financial pain but will not erase it.
The insurance pays half of a grower's production costs, which
average $1,500 an acre, said Shirley A. Batchman, a spokeswoman for
the Exeter-based California Citrus Mutual, a grower's association
whose 800 members farm 40 percent of the state's citrus acreage.
</P>
<P>
   For most growers, that will not even cover payments for the
land, she said. Moreover, she said, ``It doesn't give you a penny
to live on.''
</P>
<P>
   Applying that formula, Bennett would qualify for $112,000
(though he hopes to salvage some fruit and would thus receive less
aid). Even so, that won't cover all his debt on his 35 acres and
the 115 acres he owns jointly with his brothers, Robert and
Richard. ``I'll have to go to the lender to ask for a
postponement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Bennetts are unusual among farm families in that they
have saved a year's worth of income, Bennett is reluctant to
liquidate what he had mentally stashed away for retirement to meet
operating needs. So he is considering refinancing some land to
preserve that capital.
</P>
<P>
   He is also reluctantly weighing cuts in citrus operations, like
fertilizer feedings and pruning, which are likely to curb future
crop yields and revenue. He has already temporarily let go two
employees, a foreman who worked for him for 15 years and another
farmhand, both eligible for emergency aid.
</P>
<P>
   Few crop failures force farmers from their land, said Mark L.
Prendergast, a certified financial planner in Fresno. Instead, they
end up with higher debt. ``When they have good years, they buy
tractors; when they have a bad one, they fire their foreman,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Prendergast calculated that if the Bennetts sold their land and
invested the proceeds, they would make more in interest and
dividends than they make from farming in the best years.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect seems unfathomable to Bennett, though. ``That would
be one of my last choices,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
