<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3999 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-MIDSTREAM-$ADV24-     01-22 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-MIDSTREAM-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DELICATE FAMILY AFFAIR  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 24)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Conn.)  (af) 
 By JAMES SCHEMBARI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baby boomers seem to be focused on three economic issues: their
homes, their retirements and their children's college educations.
But a fourth potential drain on their resources tends to sneak up
on them: their parents.
</P>
<P>
   The parents of the baby boom generation are getting older, and
not all of them are prepared for the financial strains of declining
health. President Clinton addressed this problem last month by
proposing a $1,000-a-year tax credit for the chronically ill and,
in some cases, for the relatives who care for them, but that kind
of money would hardly make a dent in most such health care bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our generation doesn't have a clue to what caring for a parent
is all about,'' said Virginia Morris, author of ``How to Care for
Aging Parents'' (Workman Publishing, 1996). ``I think in the next
10 years we're all going to get a shock. Not only are people living
longer now, but living longer with disabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   How do you know if your parents have adequate insurance and
savings to handle a medical crisis? And how do you ask? My parents
are in their mid-70s and very independent. How much should I pry?
And should a ``That's none of your business'' be allowed to end the
discussion?
</P>
<P>
   True, it is none of my business right now, but it may become my
business if, say, my father has a stroke and my mother is
overwhelmed by the demands of caring for him. In that case, I
wouldn't hesitate to open my wallet, even at the expense of my four
children.
</P>
<P>
   But I would like to avoid having to make such a choice. My
parents tell me they're fine, and I don't doubt their sincerity.
But do I know how much they have in reserve or how extensively they
have planned? No, and I have never asked. For many families, it's
the same: ``Don't ask, don't tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael P. Mayko, 44, of Milford, Conn., never asked. His
parents are in their 80s, and when his father developed Alzheimer's
disease, Mayko helped his mother care for him. Then his mother had
a heart attack, and overnight he became responsible for the care of
both parents.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he spends some mornings before work and much of his time
on weekends at their house a few towns away. And while his parents
can still cover most of their health care costs, Mayko knows their
funds are limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it coming, but I tried to keep it out of my mind,''
Mayko said. ``They had no wills and made no arrangements for
long-term care. Now, I'm making decisions on their lives that I'm
not comfortable making.''
</P>
<P>
   For Angela Scott, 46, of Sag Harbor, N.Y., it wasn't so sudden.
One day her mother turned to her and said, ``I think I'm getting
Alzheimer's disease.'' She was right. Her mother moved in with her,
but as the disease progressed, she needed constant custodial care.
While she had some savings and insurance, Ms. Scott and her two
siblings are stuck with bills totaling tens of thousands of dollars
a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize we can't afford to keep her at home much longer, so
we will have to place her in a nursing home,'' Ms. Scott said.
``Financially there isn't a choice. I'm dreading that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Morris, the author, says she doesn't think people realize
how expensive care can be. ``Average nursing home care is $40,000 a
year, but you can easily spend $80,000,'' she said. She added that
children need to discuss finances with their parents early, before
they become ill, vulnerable and frightened. The best way to begin
the conversation, she said, is to simply ask them about their
goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask them what are their concerns, what are their worries,''
Ms. Morris said. ``The big issue is where are they going to live if
they need long-term care. It lets them take the conversation where
they feel safe. You'll have to bring it up a couple of times.
You're not going to sit down in one conversation and sort this
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Some sensitive topics that need to be addressed, she said, are
whether the parents have or should buy long-term care insurance;
who should have power of attorney over their affairs, if that
becomes necessary; whether they have made a ``living will'' that
designates who should make medical decisions for them when they
can't make their own; what sort of estate planning they have done,
and what benefits they can expect from Medicare and Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on family dynamics, parents may refuse to discuss any
of this with their children, or may be willing to talk with one
child but not another. For those who prefer to talk with an
outsider, suggest that they consult with a financial planner or an
attorney who specializes in laws affecting the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute of Certified Financial Planners (800-282-7526 or
www.icfp.org) will provide you with a free list of certified
planners in your area. The National Academy of Elder Law Attorneys
(520-881-4005 or www.naela.org) sells directories for $15 that list
its members by region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soon, our parents are going to be the dinner-table
conversation,'' Ms. Morris said. ``When we say `day care,' we won't
be talking about our children, we'll be talking about our
parents.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
