<HEADER>
A4004 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-VOLVO-ART-     01-22 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-VOLVO-ART-2TAKES-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLVO S80: BEST SOLO PERFORMANCE: NEXT, A SUPPORTING ACT? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 24) 
(af) 
 By DAN NEIL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Press kits, the glossy bundles of information that car
manufacturers send to journalists, are typically triumphal
documents, harking sales records broken and heralding new products
born. Somewhere in the files I am sure there is a press packet that
begins, ``It promises to be another banner year for Yugo.''
</P>
<P>
   Volvo's press kit for 1999 begins on a more measured note,
soberly observing that the company nearly succumbed to ``economic
Darwinism'' earlier in the decade, when it was almost devoured by
Renault SA of France.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Volvo AB has again appeared on the corporate
dinner table; Fiat SpA, the Ford Motor Co. and possibly others have
been weighing a purchase of the Swedish company's automotive
division. The buzz has sent Volvo's stock shooting up, then down,
then up again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a a decade of auto mega-mergers, Volvo and Porsche are,
for now, the last two independents of consequence left standing. GM
bought Saab; Ford bought Aston Martin, Jaguar and control of Mazda;
Fiat bought Ferrari and Maserati, Hyundai bought Kia; Volkswagen
bought Bentley, Bugatti and Lamborghini; BMW bought Rover and
Rolls-Royce; Mercedes bought Chrysler _ or was it the other way
around?
</P>
<P>
   However much business sense these mergers make, it is hard not
to mourn the loss of diversity they augur. Imagine an international
potluck dinner where everybody brings a tuna casserole.
</P>
<P>
   Seen in this light, the Volvo S80 is more than just a roundly
excellent car; it is a declaration of la difference. It proves that
a relatively small car company can compete against the merged
global mastodons.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad there are not more small car companies left to take
heart at this.
</P>
<P>
   When the swoopy C70 came out last year, you might have imagined
the designers shouting ``Eureka!'' and running, like Archimedes,
through Volvo's hometown of Goteborg, their French curves held
aloft. But the S80 proves that they have not forgotten how to draw
a straight line. An elegant crease in the sheet metal travels from
the blunt nose to the taillights, creating rounded shoulders across
the doors.
</P>
<P>
   Trimmed in matte black, with crystal-like headlamps flanking the
familiar grille, the S80 has a look that is formal but functional
(though compared with the S90 it replaces, it seems positively
wanton). In fact, with a 0.28 drag coefficient _ a measure of
aerodynamics _ it is one of the most slippery shapes in the big-car
market.
</P>
<P>
   At 189.8 inches in length, the S80 is roughly the size of a
Mercedes E-Class. At night, when you activate the ``home safe
lighting'' _ a security system that surrounds the parked car with
pools of light _ it looks more like a full-size UFO.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the S80 is spacious and quietly elegant, and the leather
seats have the quality of a good Italian sofa. I drove the test
car, a turbo-charged T6, more than 1,200 miles over a holiday
weekend, and at the end I could have happily gone another 1,000 or
so. Those are some great seats.
</P>
<P>
   The instrument panel has a strict aeronautic look, with
white-on-black analog dials and a useful trip computer (so many are
not) tucked in the corner. The center console presents climate and
audio controls in banks of logically placed soft-touch switches.
The materials range from pebbled vinyl on the dash to a
Chippendale-like walnut wainscotting that circles the cabin.
</P>
<P>
   You can almost smell the midnight oil; thoughtful touches greet
you everywhere. Air outlets on the center pillars provide lots of
circulation in the back. Cup holders spring from every armrest.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect some will buy the S80 for the trunk alone. There are
hooks from which to hang plastic supermarket bags, nets to secure
loose cargo and a retractable strap that will hold a paper grocery
bag snugly in the corner. (Somebody in Volvo's design department
may have an eating disorder.)
</P>
<P>
   For the trips to the wholesale warehouse store, the rear seats
fold individually, and there is a pass-through for skis.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the S80 seems safe. In addition to front and side air
bags (using a new gas that is said not to irritate eyes or skin),
the S80 features an ``inflatable curtain'' that pops out of the
headliner in a side collision.
</P>
<P>
   The S80 also has what Volvo calls a whiplash protection system.
If the car is rear-ended, the front seatbacks move backward with
the occupant, then tip a bit to counter the force of the rebound.
The Insurance Institute for Highway Safety concluded, after testing
the system at Volvo's request, that it significantly reduced the
neck movements that cause whiplash injuries.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Add to that five sets of three-point harnesses with pyrotechnic
pretensioners, smart air bags (they deploy with variable force
depending on whether one is belted) and a rugged body structure,
and the Volvo S80 has the goods to appeal to the most chronically
apprehensive.
</P>
<P>
   Driving the Volvo, I half-wished somebody would hit me so I
could see some of this exotic equipment in action. I have no such
dark thoughts at the wheel of, say, a Ferrari.
</P>
<P>
   Other active-safety measures are in place, as well: four-wheel
anti-lock disk brakes, a traction control and, this month, an
electronic stability control that makes handling on slippery
surfaces more secure.
</P>
<P>
   Previous Volvos were noted for their safety features, too. What
is different is that the S80 feels a lot tighter and heftier than
past Volvos _ a sense of gravitas that makes you trust the car the
moment you sit in it.
</P>
<P>
   Powering the S80 is a 2.9-liter, multi-valve, in-line six
cylinder ladled with high-tech controls, including variable valve
timing and an electronic ``drive by wire'' throttle. The T6 has
light-pressure twin turbos, bumping horsepower from 201 to a stout
268.
</P>
<P>
   This engine, backed by a four-speed automatic transmission
(produced by GM, interestingly) sends the 3,690-pound car to
V8-caliber speeds _ 0 to 60 m.p.h. takes 6.5 seconds and the top
speed, limited by a computer chip, is 133 m.p.h. At lead-footed
cruising speeds the S80 T6 can travel an astounding 550 miles on 20
gallons of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   The walnut-topped shifter can be slipped into a semi-manual
Geartronic shift gate. Deft stirring of the shifter will prompt the
S80 T6 to spurt through city traffic like a bottle rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Steering is light and accurate at speed, but around town the
turning radius is limited by the wide six-cylinder engine mounted
sideways in the engine bay, leaving rather less room for the wheels
to operate. Parallel parking is more delicate than usual.
</P>
<P>
   The ride is saddle-stiff in the European mode, but comfortable.
The suspension (rear multi-link, front struts) absorbs jolts and
recovers quickly. Shoed with 16-inch Michelin Pilot tires, the T6
grips corners and keeps its poise in abrupt maneuvers, wh
limited-slip differential compensates for any spin on the front,
driving wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Global in appeal, the car's heart is rooted in Scandinavia. You
see it in the dual-mode heated seats, heated outside mirrors,
headlight washers and a defroster that will blast your hair into a
Don King 'do.
</P>
<P>
   As a brand, Volvo has needed to wriggle out of the ``boxy and
safe'' handcuffs it fashioned for itself. The finely finished,
athletic S80 should help. The base-model 2.9 starts at $36,395, and
the T6 at around $40,000; the test car had a lot of content for
$43,755.
</P>
<P>
   The S80 is so good it could open up new vistas of snob appeal
for the company. Enjoy it while you can. The S80 may be the last
hurrah of a free, Swedish-controlled Volvo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 0217EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 02:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4006 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-EMERGE-MARKETS     01-22 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-EMERGE-MARKETS-ART-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSESSING THE RISK FOR ACTIVE MANAGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Mo., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Graphic of performance of Vanguard Emerging Market funds;
Performance of emerging market stock funds is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 24) 
(af) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even with the sharp rebound in Brazilian stocks, the world's
emerging markets are still down nearly 50 percent from their 1997
highs, bringing more than a few fund managers' reputations down
with them. Another casualty of the selloff: the widely held notion
that emerging markets are fertile ground for active fund managers.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, emerging markets remain a place where many investors
believe actively managed funds have an edge. Some experts who
concede that few large-cap mutual funds will consistently beat the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index of large-capitalization stocks insist
that over time, stock pickers can still outperform indices in
out-of-the-way foreign markets by buying undiscovered stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The inefficiencies of such markets, they argue, make them ripe
for the cherry-picking style of active management. Moreover, when
emerging markets plummet, active managers have the option of
fleeing to the safety of cash or, in some cases, less volatile
locales.
</P>
<P>
   But the carnage of late in emerging stock exchanges suggests
otherwise. Consider: The 164 actively managed emerging-market funds
tracked by Morningstar Inc. fell 26.9 percent last year, far more
than the 18.2 percent loss by the Vanguard Emerging Markets Stock
Index fund, the only emerging-market index fund tracked by
Morningstar, the Chicago financial publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Why would this be? The price of research on emerging-market
stocks is one probable culprit. But even more important are the
enormous trading costs such stocks carry. A round-trip purchase and
sale of a block of stock on a typical emerging market usually costs
about 4.5 percent of the value of the stock, said Joshua Feuerman,
manager of the State Street Global Advisors Emerging Markets fund
in Boston. ``It's a disgustingly expensive asset class to trade
in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And because turnover at actively managed funds is more than four
times that of the Vanguard offering's 19 percent, such costs are
bound to hit active managers harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question is not whether the market is inefficient or
not, it's whether you can overcome any inefficiency and add value
beyond the costs of obtaining information and the bid-offer
spreads. That is probably why active managers fail in the emerging
markets,'' said Larry Swedroe, a financial author and principal at
Buckingham Asset Management in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Indexing the emerging markets is a very subjective discipline,
involving different component companies and country weightings.
``You can have perfect correlation with the S&AMP;P 500, but to have
perfect correlation with a Russian index is totally different,''
said David Masters, an analyst at Standard &AMP; Poor's Micropal, a
research firm in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Vanguard fund is a good example: It doesn't track any
benchmark emerging markets index stock for stock; instead, it
parallels a custom Morgan Stanley index that excludes countries
with liquidity, foreign-exchange or settlement problems. That
helped the fund last year when Russia and other countries that
didn't meet the fund's criteria encountered serious problems, but
it made for bigger losses in 1997 when the fund's overweighted
investments in more liquid Southeast Asia were pummeled by currency
devaluations.
</P>
<P>
   Is the Vanguard fund simply lucky it beat actively managed funds
because the particulars of its custom index kept it from the worst
trouble? That is a ``potentially valid argument'' when it comes to
beating the benchmark Morgan Stanley emerging markets free index,
which fell 25.3 percent last year, said Gus Sauter, who runs the
fund and about two dozen others at Vanguard.
</P>
<P>
   But ``insofar as how we outperformed active managers, it doesn't
hold, for most active managers are not in those countries for the
same reason we're not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The second big selling point of active management, that a fund
can sidestep market drops by selling when a market starts to
tumble, has also proven problematic. Liquidity dries up quickly,
leaving managers two choices: sit tight or sell into a falling
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``In aggregate, active managers can't get out of the market,''
Sauter added. ``For everybody who gets out, there's somebody who
must get in.''
</P>
<P>
   Active managers defend emerging-market stock-picking, noting
that while they lagged the benchmarks during last year's downdraft,
``active managers have beaten the indexes handily'' in some years,
said Robert Pozen, president of Fidelity Management and &UR;  &LR; Research,
who oversees all of Fidelity Investment's fund managers.
</P>
<P>
   But other support exists for indexing. According to Micropal,
the United States global emerging-market equity funds it tracks
fell an average of 26 percent last year and had annualized losses
of 8.3 percent and 10.5 percent, respectively, for the three- and
five-year periods ended Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, the Barings emerging market extended index fell
by 18.8 percent last year and reported annualized losses of 7.23
percent and 6.3 percent, respectively, for the three- and
five-years periods. Another emerging-market index, the
International Finance composite, fell 22 percent for the year and
lost an annualized 10.1 percent for both the three- and five-year
periods.
</P>
<P>
   It is worth noting that of the few emerging-market funds that
beat Vanguard last year, two are somewhat passively managed, have
low portfolio turnover and use some quantitative techniques:
Dimensional Fund Advisors Emerging Markets Portfolio, which fell
9.4 percent, and State Street Global Advisors Emerging Markets,
which fell 15.9 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
