<SLUG> BC-BKC-SYRACUSE-BOSTONCOLLEGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYRACUSE POUNDS BC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ Boston College coach Al Skinner knew there
would be nights like this. Nights when everything he drew up on the
sidelines would unravel the minute his players took the floor.
Nights when the opposition would appear that much bigger, that much
stronger, that much more menacing and physical than his team. And
nights when the flaws of his undersized and inexperienced team
would be exposed and exploited for an unrelenting 40 mintues.
</P>
<P>
   In short, nights when all would seem like a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night was such a night.
</P>
<P>
   Desperately looking to snap a six-game losing streak by winning
its first Big East game of the season, BC instead wound up
absorbing its worst loss of the season and worst ever in conference
play _ a 90-51 thrashing by No. 20 Syracuse before a Carrier Dome
crowd of 18,161 that witnessed the third-most lopsided game in
league history.
</P>
<P>
   With a team that returned no starters and no one over 6 feet 8
inches, Skinner was braced to take his lumps.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't know when it's going to happen,'' said Skinner,
whose team had only two starters score in double figures, Kenny
Harley (14) and Michael Cotton (10). ``I've always said there's two
sides to this coin. We're going to have nights like this and
there's going to be nights when we're going to put it together. And
tonight was that other side of the coin.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles, who trailed, 45-19, at intermission after converting
just 7 of 29 field goal attempts, dropped to 3-13 overall and 0-8
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, Syracuse (13-5, 5-4) rebounded from a 74-71 loss at
Rutgers Monday by recording its most lopsided conference victory,
surpassing a 36-point romp over BC at the Carrier Dome Feb. 20,
1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to have a game like this, no question,'' said
Syracuse coach Jim Boeheim. ``You don't want to have to slug it out
every time you play, which will be the case just about every game
the rest of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of the Feb. 24 rematch with BC at Conte
Forum, one supposes.
</P>
<P>
   Etan Thomas, Syracuse's 6-9 junior swatmeister, led the
Orangemen with 14 points, 7 rebounds, and 6 blocked shots, giving
him 72 rejections for the season. Thomas scored 11 points and got
all of his blocks in an 11-minute cameo in the first half to help
Syracuse storm to a 28-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles, who managed to score just 9 points in the first
10:06, faced their biggest halftime deficit of the season. And it
only got bigger in the second half, thanks in large part to Eric
Williams, who chipped in 10 of his 12 in the second half to help
the Orangemen lead by as many as 40, 81-41, with 5:11 to go.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse's decided height advantage translated into an easy
victory on the boards, where it outrebounded BC, 56-36.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between the rebounding and the aggressive play on the
perimeter, they were just too physical and we were not prepared for
that,'' said Skinner, whose team must regroup before Miami visits
Conte Forum Sunday. ``It was just that simple. It was a very
physical basketball game and, right now, we just couldn't stand up
to them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
