<HEADER>
A4011 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-SENATORS-B     01-22 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-SENATORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAGGED BRUINS HIT LULL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins went into the All-Star break Thursday night
at a loss, literally.
</P>
<P>
   They fell to the Ottawa Senators, 3-1, at the FleetCenter, and
some players feel there are times when some members of the club
aren't on the same page or the same bookshelf or even in the same
library.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins are going to make it to the postseason, they're
going to have to do a better job of reading _ each other, the
coach, whomever. Coach Pat Burns is clearly frustrated by the
overly fancy play of the top line, Jason Allison, Sergei Samsonov,
and Dmitri Khristich.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't skate up the ice and try to be fancy and dance
around with the puck in the neutral zone,'' said Burns. ``You can't
do that with that club. You've got to put it in behind them and
grind them. That's what you have to do and we didn't do it. All
lines didn't do it. Some did, some didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time Boston took a tumble at the hands of the Senators
was March 22, 1997, when Ottawa took a 5-4 decision. Boston's 5-0-2
streak had been its longest current unbeaten run against one
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your good players have to play,'' said Burns. ``If your good
players don't play, you're not going to win. Our good players have
to rise to the top.''
</P>
<P>
   The first period was scoreless, with the Bruins outshooting the
Senators, 8-6. In the second, the clubs traded late goals 47
seconds apart.
</P>
<P>
   The Senators struck first with forward Bruce Gardiner scoring
his fourth of the season at 18:06. Alexei Yashin had the puck in
the right circle and managed to fight off defenseman Hal Gill to
keep control. He found Gardiner in the slot and Gardiner fired a
shot past goalie Byron Dafoe for the 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins responded right away, with Khristich scoring his
20th. Khristich gained the blue line and dished a pass over to
Allison. Allison ripped a shot that goalie Ron Tugnutt kicked out
with his right pad. But Khristich charged in and snagged the
rebound, beating the netminder with a forehand shot at 18:53.
</P>
<P>
   That deadlock didn't last long, as the Senators took the lead
for good in the first minute of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Former Bruin Shawn McEachern got the puck behind the net and
fired it out to the right side. Sami Salo, who was at the right
point, blasted a shot that sailed past the glove of Dafoe for a 2-1
lead at the 55-second mark. McEachern added an empty-netter at
19:19 to seal it.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins had their opportunities, especially in the second
period, with a five-on-three advantage for 24 seconds. But they
couldn't manage a shot on net during that time. The closest they
came was when Ray Bourque passed the puck down to Allison, who had
a hard time controlling the redirect attempt and shot wide.
</P>
<P>
   The tone in the dressing room was one of frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to either be overly skilled or very disciplined,''
said right wing Rob DiMaio. ``I don't think we're overly skilled. I
think we have to be very disciplined to win. I thought at times we
played well but we make the crucial mistake at the wrong time and
they're a very opportunistic team. They capitalize on mistakes, and
every one we made, they seemed to score on.''
</P>
<P>
   Through 43 games, the Bruins are actually on a slightly better
pace than last season. A year ago, they were 19-16-8. Now they're
20-16-7. However, to some it doesn't feel like improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was such a new experience for everybody,'' said
DiMaio. ``This year, we're a group of guys who know what the
capabilities are and for some reason we're slipping a little bit in
certain areas and we're not being that solid team that you knew
last year was going to come out and do the same thing every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it's like we're taking some shortcuts or being fancy or
doing things uncharacteristic of this team. Until that changes,
we're going to have these problems once in a while.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 0230EST &QL; 
