<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 02:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4013 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-SENATORS-MCEACHER     01-22 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SENATORS-MCEACHERN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCEACHERN A SENATOR IN A GREAT STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The summer of 1996 had just begun and Shawn McEachern
was coming off a nice season with the Bruins. And he was headed out
of town.
</P>
<P>
   He was not thrilled about the idea. His wife, Andrea, was
pregnant. The Ottawa Senators looked to be going nowhere. After
growing up in Waltham, playing at Matignon and Boston University,
then bouncing around the National Hockey League, McEachern had been
home for just a bit and now he was gone again. He was traded by the
Bruins to Ottawa for Trent McCleary and a draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it didn't work out,'' McEachern said. ``I
thought I had a pretty good year here and they wanted to go in a
different direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Money was going to be an issue.
</P>
<P>
   Off to the Senators he went.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little nervous about going to Ottawa,'' McEachern
said. ``They were the worst team in the league at the time. But
things have worked out well.''
</P>
<P>
   Very well.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night was the latest example.
</P>
<P>
   McEachern, who turns 30 next month, was a major pain in the
Bruins' backside all evening. When Ottawa's 3-1 victory was over,
he had a goal and an assist, and his red-hot team had run its road
unbeaten streak to seven games at 6-0-1.
</P>
<P>
   The speedy McEachern set up the winner after a steal behind the
net and late won a footrace to score into an empty net with 41
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The Senators, after a busy and highly successful January, are
rolling along at 25-15-6 and McEachern is rolling with them. The
empty-netter was his team-leading 21st goal, and he now has 18
assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shawn has played very well,'' said Senators coach Jacques
Martin. ``He's been a key performer for us for the last two years.
It's not only his scoring, but his speed. He's improved his defense
tremendously and he's provided us with some leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, on a new line, he provided a bit of everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's played all year with (Alexei) Yashin,'' Martin said.
``But they like to check that line. That's why I broke them up.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't seem to bother McEachern.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the second period, he and Vaclav Prospal pestered
Ray Bourque into coughing up the puck while the Bruins were
shorthanded. The Bruins lucked out when McEachern was called for
interference on Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   The next time he stole the puck, the Bruins were not so
fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   He was behind the Bruin net, intercepted a pass and threw it out
front, and it deflected to Sami Salo, who was moving in. Salo let
go a blast that beat Byron Dafoe high.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was his first goal, but he's got a bomb, that guy, for a
shot,'' McEachern said.
</P>
<P>
   That killer goal came with 55 seconds left in the second period
and made it 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   McEachern's scoring totals have him headed for a career year;
his best was 1992-93 with the Penguins when he had 28 goals and 33
assists.
</P>
<P>
   He loves the fact that the team is doing so well. He likes being
with a team for a third straight year (a first for him) and with a
coaching staff that has been stable as well.
</P>
<P>
   And while his family comes back to Massachusetts for the
summers, Ottawa is a good place to spend the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fun team to play for,'' McEachern said. ``We're in a
small town and I've got the kids up there. I'm enjoying myself. We
see each other a lot. You go to the grocery store or to rent a
video and you run into Bruce Gardiner. It's small.'
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, things have worked out pretty well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
