<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For FRIDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, Jan. 22.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-SALINAS (Mexico City) _ After a tangled four-year trial,
Raul Salinas de Gortari, the brother of Mexico's former president,
was convicted on Thursday of ordering the 1994 assassination of a
prominent politician and sentenced to 50 years in prison. It was a
stunning verdict that shattered the impunity that has shielded
powerful Mexicans for decades. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Washington) _ International monitors who discovered the
bodies of 45 ethnic Albanians shot execution-style have concluded
in their official report that the attack in the Kosovo village was
an act of revenge by Serbian forces for the killing of four of
their men. The report, which has not been made public, described a
scene of bodies with wounds from gunshots at close range. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-MEXICO (Rome) _ Much has changed since the pope's
ground-breaking first trip to Mexico in 1979 when he spoke out
sternly against the Marxist- liberation theology then polarizing
the Roman Catholic church in Latin America. As he returns to
prepare the Americas for the third millennium, the pope finds
himself once again battling an ideology that he feels oppresses
much of humanity, only this time it is capitalism. By Alessandra
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ A former model and successful
cosmetics company owner, Pnina Rosenblum is an Israeli sex symbol,
tall, leggy, blonde, glamorous and independent. She is also a new
political party. By Deborah Sontag. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-U.S. (Washington) _ The Clinton administration, having
announced its intention to devote $10.5 billion to missile defenses
over the next six years, faces a major diplomatic and military
quandary in Asia where the potential deployment of interceptor
missiles risks increasing tensions with China over Taiwan and
Japan. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   BOMB-PAKISTAN (New Delhi, India) _ A Pakistani official in New
Delhi strongly denied that a man arrested in a bomb plot against
U.S. targets has any link to Pakistani intelligence. By Celia
Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-BACKLOG (Undated) _ One year after immigration officials
in Washington declared that the reduction of a national backlog of
almost 2 million people waiting to become Americans was their top
priority, the agency has just revealed new, concrete steps to meet
that goal. By Mirta Ojito.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CELLS (Undated) _ Scientists studying mice have discovered
that certain adult cells long presumed to have irrevocably chosen
what kind of body part they will eventually develop into can change
direction, go back to the starting line and grow into something
else. If this finding is confirmed, and occurs in people as well,
the implications are potentially vast. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-ELDERLY (Tampa, Fla.) _ Surrounded by 200 elderly and
disabled people and those who provide care for them at a center for
the elderly here, Vice President Al Gore disclosed details of the
administration's $6 billion dollar package of tax and budget
proposals for long-term care. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   NY-ONEIDAS-LAND (Verona, N.Y.) _ Five years ago, people in this
quiet, rural community gazed with envy and amazement at the instant
success of the Oneida Indian Nation's new Turning Stone Casino, an
economic juggernaut that created thousands of jobs and lured
millions of visitors to this desolate area halfway between Syracuse
and Utica. But that was before it got personal. By David W. Chen.
With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INTERVIEW-GERM (Washington) _ President Clinton said
Thursday that it is ``highly likely'' that a terrorist group will
launch or threaten a germ or chemical attack on U.S. soil within
the next few years. In an interview, Clinton said he had been
persuaded by intelligence reports that the United States needs to
bolster its defenses. By Judith Miller and William J. Broad. With
photos.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIAL (Washington) _ President Clinton's private lawyer
charged Thursday that House impeachment prosecutors had ignored
evidence that would exonerate the president in an ``attempt to fit
some of the facts into a sinister pattern'' of obstruction of
justice. ``The direct evidence disproves the charges,'' he argued
as the Clinton team completed its opening presentation. By R.W.
Apple Jr. With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLINTON (Washington) _ Bill Clinton has answered the
question chewed over by his aides and friends after his last
election: What would this instinctual campaigner do without another
campaign? The answer is that he found one. He is running again for
his second term, as hard as he can. By James Bennet. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-REPUBS (Alexandra, Va.) _ Pat Robertson's remarks that
the impeachment trial might as well be halted set off a firestorm
Thursday among conservatives meeting here. Most condemned the
influential television evangelist and asserted that Republicans
should not turn back from a full-blown trial. By Richard L. Berke.
With photo.
</P>
<P>
   STATEOFUNION-PROMOTE (Undated) _ When President Clinton
announced in his State of the Union Address this week that he
wanted the federal government to press schools to end ``social
promotion,'' he was stepping into a longstanding, mine-laden
educational debate: When students fail, is it better to have them
repeat the school year or promote them to the next grade anyway? By
Ethan Bronner. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-STATEOFUNION-SOCSEC (Washington) _ Republicans were quick to
criticize President Clinton's proposal to invest a portion of
Social Security's reserves in the stock market, but they have been
slow to lay out an alternative, largely because the options
available to them have serious political and economic drawbacks. By
Richard w. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-REPORT (Undated) _ In a sign of how fast the U.S. economy
was growing at the end of the year and how quickly the rest of the
world was slowing, the U.S. trade deficit widened sharply in
November and set a record for the year. By Sylvia Nasar. With
graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-FOREIGN-BANKS (Guangzhou, China) _ China's decision to
force one of its largest state-owned companies, Guangdong
International Trust and Investment, into bankruptcy has stunned
foreign creditors and signaled a sharp change in the climate for
foreign investment. By Mark Landler. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-EARNINGS (Dearborn, Mich.) _ Ford Motor Co. reported
fourth-quarter earnings on Thursday that were stronger than
expected, as the giant automaker also pressed ahead in its efforts
to buy the car business of Sweden's Volvo. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   UAL-AMERICA-WEST (Undated) _ To many in the industry, the
chances that United Airlines would acquire America West Airlines,
the United States' ninth-largest carrier, seemed slim on Thursday,
one day after United declared its interest, even as it appeared
that Delta Air Lines Inc. might also be interested in doing a deal
with America West, and Southwest Airlines refused to rule out the
possibility of making a bid. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   SOUNDALIKE-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ To those who have been watching
football on television in recent weeks, it seems as if the hottest
voice-over talent in corporate America today is John Facenda. The
fact that he has been dead for almost 15 years makes little
difference. By Greg Farrell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Listening to President Clinton's
perfectly focus-grouped State of the Union speech the other night,
I really felt sort of cheated. I mean, he left almost no
constituency untickled by his 77-minute goody-bag of proposals.
There was something for everyone except me _ except for
foreign-affairs columnists who still care about things like Russian
nuclear weapons aimed at us. By Thomas L. Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENTHAL-COLUMN (Undated) _ I was a resident reporter in Poland
only 13 years after the Germans lusted for one last orgasm of hate
and ordered as many Jews as possible killed before Allied troops
could rescue them. So what could I write about ``The Last Days,''
Steven Spielberg's new documentary, that I had not written before,
I thought. By A.M. Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-WOJNAROWICZ (New York) _ David Wojnarowicz (1954-1992) was a
near-mythic figure in New York a decade ago, and for many people
who knew him, he still is. Artist, writer, filmmaker and performer,
he gained fame during the brief East Village art boom of the
1980's. kept himself outside the hype and went his own force. A
retrospective titled ``Fever: The Art of David Wojnarowicz'' has
opened at the New Museum of Contemporary Art in SoHo; several
Manhattan galleries are showing his work. A book of excerpts from
his diaries has just appeared. By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   ELGAR (Undated) _ Americans march to Elgar at commencements as
they march to Mendelssohn at weddings, but they probably don't
think about him most of the rest of the year. But Elgar deserves
respect for more than just those ``Pomp and Circumstance'' marches;
some listeners have found a core of deep humanity in his work, even
under the occasional bluster. And now, for no reason apparent in
the stars, a confluence of events has brought the composer to
attention. By James R. Oestreich.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SCANDAL (Undated) _ A senior official of the International
Olympic Committee acknowledged Thursday that corruption in the Salt
Lake City bribery scandal was extensive and that the expulsion of
some members of the committee would be sought this weekend. By Jere
Longman
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ARATON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on the
NBA, comparing the fresh, fan-friendly Nets with the corporate,
not-exactly-lovable Knicks. By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-TRADES (New York) _ Karl Malone and Charles Barkley are
staying put, Latrell Sprewell and Scottie Pippen have moved on to
New York and Houston, respectively, and Dennis Rodman still has no
idea where he will end up. On what may be remembered as the most
chaotic day in modern NBA history, a flurry of transactions flooded
the league's offices as teams scrambled to fill out their rosters
in the lockout-shortened season. By Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-AUSTRALIA (Melbourne) _ What started on Thursday with the
Stanford man Paul Goldstein and the Austrian baseliner Barbara
Schett continued Friday with the mountain man Marc Rosset and the
Spanish baseliner Maria Antonio Sanchez Lorenzo. By Christopher
Clarey.
</P>
