<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-DEVILS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS FALL TO DEVILS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The NHL's All-Star break is here, a time for
most players to rest and relax after more than three months of
hockey.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Los Angeles Kings really want to maximize their
enjoyment of this idyllic interlude in their season, they will do
well to avoid pondering their recent record, and they'll cover
their eyes if someone shows them the Western Conference standings.
</P>
<P>
   Left wing Luc Robitaille was added to the North American team
for Sunday's All-Star Game in Tampa after Detroit captain Steve
Yzerman's nose was broken Thursday against Carolina when he was hit
by a pass from Carolina's Paul Coffey. Robitaille joins Kings
teammates Rob Blake and Mattias Norstrom in the game.
</P>
<P>
   But Robitaille was not thinking about his latest honor after the
Kings' 3-2 loss to the New Jersey Devils (before an announced crowd
of 11,267 at the Forum) on a night when disappointing defenseman
Steve Duchesne was benched by coach Larry Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not good,'' Robitaille said after the Kings (16-25-4)
dropped to 1-4-1 in their past six games. ``We're going to have to
play really desperate now. We need everybody to play better.''
</P>
<P>
   After the All-Star break, the Kings embark on a difficult
four-game trip to Dallas, Washington, Buffalo and Philadelphia. The
Kings will be fortunate if they return from that trek only five
points out of a playoff berth, the distance that separates them
from the postseason at the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the Kings fell despite two goals by Jozef Stumpel.
Referee Mick McGeough disallowed a goal by Donald Audette with 1:02
remaining because Audette directed the puck into the net with his
stick above his shoulders. Thus, the Kings concluded a four-game
homestand with a 1-3 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt we needed to win all four to keep our momentum going
and keep everybody feeling positive about themselves,'' Robinson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils got first-period goals from Randy McKay and Bobby
Holik, with Stumpel's first goal sandwiched between them. Kings
goalie Jamie Storr should have had McKay's goal, an unscreened
40-footer that beat him between his pads. On the other hand, the
Kings were outshot 23-4 in the first period, but trailed by only a
2-1 margin afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Niedermayer made it 3-1 at the 42-second mark of the
second period, but Stumpel brought the Kings within a goal 15
minutes later. The Kings had Storr off for an extra skater and were
on a power play when Audette appeared to tie the score in the final
minute, but there was no argument from the Kings on McGeough's
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson juggled his lineup for the game, benching right wing
Pavel Rosa and defenseman Steve Duchesne, and dressing defensemen
Philippe Boucher and Mark Visheau, then moving Visheau to a forward
position as he has done several times this season.
</P>
<P>
   For Boucher, it was his first appearance after 13 consecutive
games as a healthy scratch, and he responded with one assist and
two fights.
</P>
<P>
   For Duchesne, a bust this season since signing with the Kings as
a free agent last summer, being benched clearly was intended to
give him something to think about during the upcoming hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, though, nothing is imminent in terms of a
transaction involving Duchesne. General Manager Dave Taylor denied
a report on ESPN of a possible deal sending Duchesne to
Philadelphia for disappointing center Alexandre Daigle.
</P>
<P>
   Of Duchesne, Robinson said, ``I spoke to (Duchesne) about it. I
thought a couple of times he could have been more physical (in
Tuesday's 5-4 loss to Colorado). ... I don't say he's got to be a
physical player. But when the opportunity is there, you've got to
play the body.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
