A4020 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GUNS-LIABILITY-NYT     01-22 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GUNS-LIABILITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE TO DECIDE ON AN AFFIDAVIT IN GUN LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge is expected to decide Friday whether
criticism of the gun industry by a former gun company executive
will be presented to a jury in a case that seeks to hold the
industry liable for shootings with illegally obtained handguns.
</P>
<P>
   The former executive, Robert I. Hass, who until 1989 was a
senior vice president of marketing and sales for Smith &AMP; Wesson
Corp., the nation's largest handgun manufacturer, has charged in an
affidavit and a deposition that gun makers and wholesalers do not
do all they can to keep their products from falling into the hands
of criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Hass charged that his former company, and the firearms industry
as a whole, knew that the ``black market in firearms is not simply
the result of stolen guns but is due to the seepage of guns into
the illicit market from multiple thousands of unsupervised'' gun
dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs in the case _ a lawsuit in which relatives of six
people killed by illegally possessed handguns and a seventh person
wounded by one _ are seeking in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn to
hold more than 40 gun makers and wholesalers, including Smith &AMP;
Wesson, liable for the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs contend that the companies have marketed and
distributed handguns so negligently that dealers in states with
weak gun control laws are oversupplied and that many of the excess
guns end up with illicit traffickers who resell them to criminals
in states with strong gun laws, like New York.
</P>
<P>
   The companies deny that they oversupply the states with weak gun
laws and say they cooperate in every way they reasonably can to
curb illegal gun trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the plaintiffs had hoped to call Hass, who has been
portrayed as a gun-industry whistle-blower, as a witness in the
trial, but they say that a heart ailment prevents him from
testifying and that they want his affidavit and deposition to be
read to the jury. Lawyers for the company oppose this, saying any
testimony by Hass should be in person to allow for
cross-examination in front of the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Anne G. Kimball, a lawyer for Smith &AMP; Wesson, also said Thursday
that Hass' years at the company _ 1978 to 1989 _ were not ``within
the relevant time frame'' of the case. She said in an interview
that under earlier rulings in the suit, the activities by the
companies to be considered are those from 1989 to 1994, the last
year in which any of the shootings in the case occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs' lawyers asserted that Hass's testimony remained
relevant because the practices he described continued from 1989 to
1994. Judge Jack B. Weinstein is expected to decide Friday whether
his affidavit and deposition may be presented to the jurors.
</P>
<P>
   In his deposition, available since it was made last April, Hass
said that one step gun manufacturers could take to keep their
handguns from getting into the illicit underground trafficking
market would be to use the information they got from law
enforcement officials, regarding guns of theirs that might have
been used in crime, to cut off retail dealers who have sold large
numbers of such guns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 0254EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 02:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4022 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANYON-AZR &LR;      01-22 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANYON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND CANYON LOGGING WOULD BE FIRST FOR PARKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the first time ever in an American national park, Grand
Canyon National Park officials plan to log trees to reduce the
possibility of catastrophic forest fires.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists are worried that the experiment could set a
precedent and lead to large scale logging in the nation's 52
national parks, which have been off-limits to timber firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the public ready to support logging trucks rolling out of
our national parks? That's a significant question,'' said Sharon
Galbreath of Flagstaff, a forest specialist for the Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   She said public outrage stopped a proposal to conduct salvage
logging after the 1988 fires in Yellowstone National Park.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Canyon park officials released a draft environmental
assessment Thursday indicating that more than 8,000 trees would be
removed from four 20-acre plots: two on the North Rim along Swamp
Ridge, about 15 miles northwest of Grand Canyon Lodge; and two on
the South Rim near Grandview Point, about 10 miles east of Grand
Canyon Village.
</P>
<P>
   If the environmental assessment is approved after public
hearings, the logging could be conducted this summer and fall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; R.V. Ward, the park's biologist, said the $900,000 project
would remove only smaller trees, the ones that compete with larger
old-growth pines and firs that make up essential habitat for many
kinds of wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those young trees can out-compete the older ones,'' Ward said.
</P>
<P>
   A side-by-side aerial view of Grand Canyon National Park and
adjacent Kaibab National Forest can make the park look like a lush
paradise, Ward said. The forest has been over-logged, while the
park contains a chokingly high number of trees, he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 years of fire suppression, along with cattle
grazing, predator controls and growth in mule deer populations,
have changed the forests surrounding the Canyon, according to the
environmental assessment.
</P>
<P>
   Human actions have resulted in thick stands of sapling ponderosa
pines, a lack of grass, shrinking meadows and thick pine needle
duff, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The possibility of stand-replacing, catastrophic fires is very
high,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the report's findings are based on the research of Wally
Covington, a forestry professor at Northern Arizona University. He
has pioneered research into the likely condition of Southwest
forests before European settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Covington's work has shown that natural wildfires occurred every
few years, burning quickly through the forest grasses, consuming
excess small trees, while passing by the fire-resistant bark of
larger old-growth trees.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a relatively open, parklike forest with grasses
that could reach the belly of horses, according to Covington. His
research supports the use of intentionally set small fires and
selective logging as ways to eliminate small trees and return the
forest to a more natural condition.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists contend that Covington's findings, much of
it based on anecdotal information, can't be applied throughout the
forests.
</P>
<P>
   A forest restoration project supervised by Covington on U.S.
Bureau of Land Management forest on Mount Trumbull, northwest of
the park, has been praised by Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, a
former Arizona governor.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists have criticized the Mount Trumbull
experiment for cutting too many large trees, leaving a landscape,
they say, not far removed from the clearcuts that the work is
designed to replace.
</P>
<P>
   The first phase of the park study already has shown that
wildfires once raced through portions of the park every three to
eight years, Ward said.
</P>
<P>
   But Galbreath suggested that park officials should allow the
absolute minimum human activity in trying to restore natural
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Public hearings on the proposed park logging are scheduled for
Flagstaff on Feb. 11 at 6:30 p.m. at the Museum of Northern
Arizona, 3101 N. Fort Valley Road; and in Kanab, Utah, on Feb. 12
at 6 p.m. at the Shilo Inn on U.S. 89. &QL; 
Steve Yozwiak can be reached at 444-8810 or at
steve.yozwiak(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
