<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 08:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4139 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-WILLIAMS-PICK-TEX     01-22 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-WILLIAMS-PICK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICKY WILLIAMS MAKE PITCH TO CLEVELAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ In his polite way, Ricky Williams is insisting that he
be the No. 1 overall pick in the upcoming NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any reason I shouldn't be the No. 1 overall
pick,'' said Williams, the Heisman Trophy winner from the
University of Texas. ``I'm going to be optimistic about this, and
hopefully, I'll go to Cleveland.''
</P>
<P>
   Others in the fraternity of great running backs are less subtle.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Ricky isn't the top overall pick,'' Hall of Famer Gale
Sayers said, ``somebody ought to be shot. If Cleveland or anybody
else doesn't take Ricky, they ought to be shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams is ranked by many draft experts as the top player
``regardless of position.'' But traditionally, NFL teams value
quarterbacks above running backs. Despite Sayers joining a chorus
of Williams fans who suggest that the trend should be bucked _
other ``sponsors'' include the likes of Tony Dorsett and Earl
Campbell _ the Cleveland Browns, owner of the first overall pick in
the April draft, are open about their apparent intent to select
Kentucky quarterback Tim Couch.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 11, the first day teams were allowed contact with
prospective draftees, Couch and Browns president Carmen Policy
engaged in a lengthy planning session.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Williams said, ``I haven't talked to anyone in
Cleveland. Nobody. Everything I know about the situation is
hearsay.'' Williams said he hopes hopes to communicate with the
Browns in the coming days, however. And what will he say to attempt
to persuade the expansion club?
</P>
<P>
   ``That I do the things that stats don't show, that I do the
little things, that I do the things beyond the norm, that I do
anything to help the team,'' Williams said. ``And that I love the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how persuasive Williams is, Policy seems set on
building the new franchise with quarterbacks first. He said his
plan includes drafting a rookie standout and the acquisition of a
veteran quarterback who will begin the 1999 season as the starter
while he helps tutor the rookie. And the organization has already
included ex-NFL stars Bernie Kosar and Joe Montana _ both former
quarterbacks _ in the quarterback evaluation process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way to build an organization is with the coach and the
quarterback as the foundation,'' Policy said.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland has the first overall pick. The lowly Philadelphia
Eagles choose second. Speculation has Williams using his leverage
as a two-sport star (he recently signed a one-year contract as a
minor-league baseball prospect with the Texas Rangers) to deter the
Eagles from selecting him. That scenario, played out most notably
in 1983 when Stanford quarterback/outfielder John Elway used his
two-sport potential to force his way from the Baltimore Colts to
the Denver Broncos, apparently is not in Williams' future.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles ``probably need me moreso than another team,''
Williams said, shrugging off the NFL system that calls for the
poorer to, theoretically, get richer via the draft. ``The kind of
person I am, I just love to play the game. So wherever I go, I'll
still love to play the game there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 0807EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 08:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4140 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RODEO-TEX     01-22 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RODEO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCKING STOCK HAVE TO BE STARS, TOO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Big deal if world all-around champion Ty
Murray or saddle bronc riding king Dan Mortensen are entered in the
Stock Show Rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   So is the world champion bucking bull King Kong and an
up-and-comer dubbed as Dodge Durango.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a century, the Southwestern Exposition and
Livestock Show Rodeo's cornerstone has been to cultivate the
livestock industry's elite. The stars of the 103rd Stock Show range
from the grand champion steer to the prize pig to the toughest bull
in the Professional Rodeo Cowboys Association.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 11 stock producers have been contracted to bring
their best bulls and broncs to Fort Worth for the 17-day rodeo,
which begins its run tonight at Will Rogers Memorial Coliseum.
Hiring those high-profile producers is confirmation that bull and
bronc power can dramatically affect a competitor's score, and
bucking stock with a feisty reputation have become a marquee
attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to have an exciting rodeo, you have to put some
people on the ground and it's getting harder and harder to
accomplish when today's contestants ride with such expertise,''
said W.R. Watt, the Stock Show's president and general manager.
``People like to see a good ride, but they also like to see people
bite the dust. It's like NASCAR racing, if they didn't have wrecks,
it wouldn't be as popular.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior rodeo producer Neal Gay of Mesquite and his son Jim have
coordinated the stock for the 30 performances at Will Rogers
Memorial Coliseum. The Gays, who have produced the Mesquite
Championship Rodeo since 1958, own several prize animals, such as
Dodge Durango, which shut out all of its riders at the weekly
Mesquite Rodeo and in Las Vegas during the Professional Bull Riders
World Championships and the National Finals Rodeo last year.
</P>
<P>
   And in an effort to stock up for the Fort Worth show, the Gays
have reached as far as Minnesota, from which producer Joe Simon has
come with a herd.
</P>
<P>
   ```He called me up and said he had some good horses, but in his
part of the country, there are no big rodeos like Fort Worth, and
therefore his horses don't get good exposure,'' Neal Gay said. ``So
he's bringing 10 of his top horses down here. I don't think this
trip to Fort Worth per se will be a money-making deal, but
hopefully it will help him in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the Gays also have recruited high-profile
producers such as Californian Dan Russell, who has owned a PRCA
world champion bull for five of the past 10 years; Mack Altizer of
Del Rio who last year was billed as the association's top stock
contractor; and Oklahoman Dell Hall, who owns King Kong, the PRCA's
defending champion bull.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crucial that a stock contractor hire subcontractors to
get the better horses,'' five-time world saddle bronc champion
Mortensen said. ``That makes it more of a riding contest between
competitors than a drawing contest. You need a lot of good horses
to give everybody a good chance, and I've been fortunate to get on
good horses in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is, we pay an entry fee to come to Fort Worth.
Unlike the stock contractor who gets paid, we have to pay a $362
entry fee and may spend $2,000 on total expenses after paying
travel costs, so it's crucial that a stock contractor supplies a
competitor a good bronc.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the multiple-stock-contractor concept at major contests
such as Denver's National Western Stock Show Rodeo and the Houston
Livestock Show Rodeo is common practice. For cowboys, top stock is
imperative, especially in the bucking stock events; a contestant's
score partially is based on how difficult the animal is to stay on
for the required eight seconds. Money scores usually are in the
high 70s, the 80s and 90s.
</P>
<P>
   But finding a blue-chip animal is the equivalent of finding a
Michael Jordan or a Troy Aikman. In an attempt to improve their
herd, the Gays, who ranch near Terrell, now have more than 400
horses and about 230 bulls that roam on about 5,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   Within their massive herd, Gay also has leased and purchased
breeding stallions from other pro rodeo companies. He has also used
some of his former star bucking bulls such as Red Rocker, which was
voted as the top bull on the PRCA's Texas Circuit in the 1980s, in
the breeding program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like the racehorse business,'' Gay said. ``You
produce a young colt out of a great stallion and mare, and it
doesn't run fast at all. But generally speaking, breeding to the
great bucking horses and bulls helps.''
</P>
<P>
   Testing potential bucking stock is like critiquing NFL rookies
during training camp and the preseason. The Gays' tests range from
holding buck-outs at their ranch using both dummy riders and live
cowboys and then slipping the more promising animals into their
weekly Mesquite Rodeo during the spring and summer months.
</P>
<P>
   If a bronc or bull passes the tests, only then will it be
considered for a slot at the Fort Worth rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding great bucking stock is a pretty tough racket,'' Neal
Gay said. ``You have to have a certain amount of luck.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 0808EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0085 </DOCNO>
