<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVS LOSE THOMAS, GAIN `HOT ROD'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The mood on the opening day of training camp for the
Mavericks was gloomy after free-agent power forward Kurt Thomas
went back on his word and signed a two-year contract for $3.625
million with the New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' actions surprised Mavericks coach/general manager Don
Nelson and sent him scurrying to the telephone in search of another
enforcer to help patrol the middle. But the Mavericks' spirits were
lifted later in the day when they found that enforcer in free-agent
center John ``Hot Rod'' Williams, who has agreed to a three-year,
$5.775 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks have scheduled a news conference today to
introduce the 6-foot-11, 245-pound Williams as the newest member of
their organization. Williams, a 13-year veteran, is 36. He was with
the Phoenix Suns when Mavericks assistant coach Donnie Nelson,
Don's son, was on the Suns' staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great rebounder and a great shot-blocker, and he's
going to have a Reggie White effect on our team,'' Donnie Nelson
said. ``He's a great influence and a real leader in the locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game he took a cab on his own to the arena, before the
bus got there, to get his body ready for the games. He is the
ultimate professional, and he's such a smart player. We're lucky to
get him.''
</P>
<P>
   Utah, Houston, Miami, Portland, Atlanta, Boston and Milwaukee
all wanted Williams. He will earn $1.75 million this season, $1.925
next season and $2.1 million in 2000-01.
</P>
<P>
   Don Nelson hopes to start Williams at center, and start A.C.
Green at power forward. But he said he will discuss that scenario
with Williams first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he likes to come off the bench,'' Nelson said. ``So I
want to see if he's comfortable as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very smart basketball player, and he's a perfect fit
for us. Considering the kick in the teeth that we got this morning,
we came out great.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Nelson also said he will continue to pursue Cedric Ceballos,
another free-agent forward who was with the Mavericks last season.
Ceballos is shopping his wares elsewhere after turning down the
team's offer of a three-year contract for $6.75 million.
</P>
<P>
   Don Nelson had already named Thomas as his starting power
forward before yesterday's turn of events.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson was visibly upset that he didn't receive a call from
Thomas or his agent, Dallas' Jerry Hicks, for two days notifying
him of their new plans. Hicks called Nelson yesterday morning to
tell him the unpleasant news.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Nelson said a reporter first tipped him off Wednesday
night that Thomas was about to renege on the oral agreement he gave
the Mavericks on Tuesday. The contract was a one-year deal for $1
million, with incentives that could have included another $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's seen anything stranger than this whole setup,''
Nelson said. ``And I've dealt with David Falk. ... You name the
toughest guys, and I've never dealt with a guy as unprofessional as
I was treated \Rby Hicks\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said the 48 hours he was left hanging by Hicks and Thomas
were precious hours he could have used pursuing other players.
</P>
<P>
   ``To let me hang for two days and lose out on people that would
help us, that just wasn't right.''
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks forward Samaki Walker, who said he expects to receive
a proposal for a contract extension from Nelson within the next
five days, could see his playing time increased with Thomas now
gone.
</P>
<P>
   As for Ceballos, Nelson believes once the free-agent smoke
clears around the NBA, the eight-year veteran will sign with the
Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've offered Ced more than anybody else at this point, but
it's less than he made last year,'' Nelson said. ``So at this point
he wants to see if there's something else out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks open the season Feb. 5, a Friday, at Seattle, and
will play nine of their first 11 games on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure you want to take a young team and play nine out
of your first 11 games on the road,'' Nelson said. ``That's hard
for us. But if we can somehow survive that and scratch out some
wins, then we could be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks' home opener is Feb. 9 against Utah. Dallas plays
eight sets of games on back-to-back days, and on three occasions
they play three games on three consecutive days. In all, the
Mavericks will play a game every 1.78 days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
