<HEADER>
A4170 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALLROOM-LIFEBEAT-ART     01-22 1467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLROOM-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALLROOM FEVER
</HEADLINE>
  Includes three color photos of dancers Suzie Hardt and Phil Jensen
at the Sapphire Ballroom in San Francisco. They are avaialble via
e-mail in JPEG format. Call Joe Applegate at 212-499-3342. 
 By MEG MCCONAHEY 
 c.1998 New York Times Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suzie Hardt rushes into San Francisco's Fairmont Hotel, all
adrenaline, anticipation and loose ends.
</P>
<P>
   She has slathered sunless tanning lotion on her legs, twisted
her black hair into a bun, swapped her glasses for contact lenses
and waged a 35-minute battle to glue false lashes over her brown
eyes. Any other day this no-fuss anthropology graduate wouldn't
even bother with mascara.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after maneuvering her Toyota through a rush-hour
bottleneck, she's left with only minutes to complete her Cinderella
transformation.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing on a sequined gown and making hurried fixes in the
mirror of the ladies' changing room, Hardt breathlessly shoots down
the hall, onto the ballroom floor and into the arms of partner Phil
Jensen.
</P>
<P>
   The neo-Baroque ballroom is decked out like a wedding reception.
Tiny cocktail tables dressed up with red and white centerpieces,
mixed drinks served up at a wet bar. Electric blue icicles shimmer
down a wall and couples, immaculately moussed, manicured, coiffed
and outfitted like Barbie and Ken at the prom, mill around in a
filmy swirl of rhinestones, tails and chiffon, nervously waiting
for their numbers to be called.
</P>
<P>
   But beneath the glamor and sometimes garish glitz, the Sapphire
Ball, one of many ballroom dance championships held around the
country, is serious competition.
</P>
<P>
   In the back of the room, vendors peddle the required gear:
$3,000 gowns, $100 pairs of shoes, hairpieces, falsies, even
on-the-spot massages.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it as basketball with feathers, baseball with a
cummerbund, track in heels. When Jensen and Hardt take to the floor
it's with the focus and drive of athletes. They dance not for
romance, but to win.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs is not a singular obsession. According to the
International Dancesport Federation, some 1.5 million couples
around the world, from Australia to Germany, from Canada to Japan,
are redefining social dancing into the new ``sport'' of competitive
ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   Hardt is a 27-year-old office worker with a boyfriend; Jensen's
a single, 23-year-old engineer for Hewlett-Packard. Off the floor
they are almost social strangers, but Phil and Suzie need each
other. They both have it bad for ballroom. And in ballroom, you
can't do it alone. Finding the right partner, many dancers joke,
can be harder than finding a mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both over 6 feet tall, we're both under 40 years old and
we're both obsessive dancers,'' Hardt says of their strictly
ballroom alliance, forged, so to speak, across a crowded room at a
dance studio.
</P>
<P>
   Those caught up in the sequined magic maintain that it's a
high-aerobic activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do one round of a professional dance competition, five
dances of a minute and a half, is like running at full speed for 10
minutes. You have to be in really good shape to do this. If you're
good at it and putting effort into it, you're sweaty,'' says
Christine Rinne-Flores, who co-owns Stars Ballroom in Novato,
Calif., a place where competitive dancers converge for private and
group lessons, weekly parties and special events that are part of
the colorful ballroom community.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1997, the International Olympic Committee
recognized the federation as the official governing body overseeing
the fledgling sport, a first milestone on the road to the Olympics.
Boosters have hired a high-powered agency to promote the image and
increase the profile of competitive dancing, a fusion of spectacle
and sport seen to outsiders mainly through the quirky, half-mocking
lens of movies like Australia's ``Strictly Ballroom,'' Japan's
``Shall We Dance'' and last summer's ``Dance With Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Years of lobbying, negotiating and politicking, both with
Olympic officials and within their own ranks, remain ahead. Key,
some observers say, is getting major TV exposure of ballroom.
That's already happening in countries like Germany, where
dancesport can be front page news.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the main TV exposure has been on PBS,
which airs the annual Ohio Star Ball the weekend before
Thanksgiving. But ballroom got a major network break recently when
NBC broadcast the International Dancesport Championships, with
Broadway diva Debbie Allen as hostess.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dance sport now. It's totally international, all over
the world. It's in Taiwan, in Japan, Norway, Denmark, England,''
says Rhona Pick, whose Pick School in San Francisco has been
training dancers since 1963. She believes ballroom will easily
cross the Olympic hurdle because of its worldwide appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as exciting, definitely, as ice dancing, if not more,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest dancers could ever expect to go for the gold
however, is 2008, and to make even that deadline, the Federation
will have to convince Olympic officials by 2003 to accept ballroom
onto the program.
</P>
<P>
   That pretty much locks even young, hungry dancers like Jensen
and Hardt out of an Olympic dream. But even without the big,
14-karat gold carrot to shoot for, the ballroom dance scene thrives
within its own intricate, arcane web of competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm just happiest when I'm dancing. When I look back
in my life, all my happiest moments have been spent dancing,'' says
Hardt, struggling to explain the compulsion to dance six days a
week, sweating through some 12 hours of practice and lessons, both
group and private.
</P>
<P>
   Hardt pares her living costs down to the barest essentials,
sharing a house with five roommates. ``I basically don't spent
money on anything except for dancing,'' she admits. ``I don't have
any payments on my car and my rent is pretty cheap. I never buy new
clothes. I just go to yard sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many novices, her two ball gowns are hand-me-downs, one a
black-and-white formal that set its first owner back $1,700. She
similarly lucked into her dance shoes when a shoe store, going out
of business, donated its remaining stock to Rice University, where
Hardt competed on the ballroom team. The 2-1/2-inch-heeled slippers
are a little loose, and Hardt, hours before the Sapphire Ball,
found herself gluing on elastic straps. Having shoes fly off during
a fox trot is one of the hazards of competition, along with the
occasional collision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's not going to be too tacky,'' she giggled. ``But I
haven't got any other shoes for competition. They're really
expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most sports, which can be measured by tangibles like
speed or distance, ballroom is highly subjective. Judges have only
a minute and a half to size up a floor full of couples, all in
motion, for form, technique and some inexplicable charisma.
</P>
<P>
   ``A judge is paid to give their first impression. We're not here
to study them. Sometimes it's just the way they walk on the floor,
and make you look at them, or look at them longer,'' says Enrique
Ramon from Houston, Texas, one of the network of professional
judges who ride the circuit. Ramon says in the '60s, when he was
first competing, there were only three to four major competitions
in the United States. Now there are that many in any given weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The drive to get better, to best themselves, to out-dance
everyone on the floor can become consuming. Hardt vows to enter
every competition she can and someday take it all the way, which in
the world of ballroom is the ultimate championships in Blackpool,
England.
</P>
<P>
   At the Sapphire, she and Jensen make it to the finals in both
categories of competition they enter, and waltz away with a
second-place trophy in the pre-novice division, edging out seven
other couples, and place a respectable fourth in the higher novice
division. But they're more disappointed than elated about what
looks, to an observer, like a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't dance my best,'' Hardt says, looking stricken when
she comes off the floor, fighting tears behind the forest of
eyelashes.
</P>
<P>
   Jensen, whose mother and brother and sister have come to watch,
is only a little less defeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have danced better,'' he adds. ``I got off on my
timing but then we did fairly decent in the rest of it. But we
don't know that many dance steps and it was a little ahead of our
level. We do have a ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   (Meg McConahey is a staff writer for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif.)
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call New York Times
Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480 or
fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
