<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 09:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4194 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEBANON-ISRAEL-$ADV24     01-22 1443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-ISRAEL-$ADV24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OPPOSITION IS BUILDING, BUT NO END IN SIGHT FOR LEBANON WAR
 &HT;    EDs: Contains optional trims.
 &HT;    With LEBANON-FIGHTERS-$ADV24.
 &HT;    With Photos in the International folder on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Jan. 24 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRASHEET, Lebanon _ Nimreh Farhad's Arabic name means,
``Tigress,'' but if that kind of spirit ever lived in the old
woman's soul, it was pounded out long ago by the war in south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The 84-year-old Lebanese peasant lives in the rocky hills dotted
with olive trees and farmland near territory occupied by
neighboring Israel for 17 years. It is the battleground between
Israel and the Hezbollah guerrillas, and she is shell-shocked.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Israel has stepped up its air raids. As the rumble of
bombing many miles away echoed harmlessly through Farhad's village
recently, she jumped up in fright from the small stone wall where
she sat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clear the way! Clear the way!'' she yelled, shuffling with her
weathered wooden cane toward the door of her whitewashed block
house. Her daughter tried to calm her, and neighbors explained that
she just can't take war any more.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, they are tired of the war here in Brasheet, where
dozens have died either fighting or from persistent shelling. But
so are they tired in Israel. They are tired of their youth dying in
what some consider Israel's Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure to end the war has steadily increased. On one side,
Hezbollah is gaining strength. On the other, Israeli public
opposition is building. A November Israeli newspaper poll showed a
high of 40 percent supporting a withdrawal, even without a peace
treaty.
</P>
<P>
   But, this is a complex proxy war. Syria, which borders Israel
and controls Lebanon, uses Hezbollah to pressure Israel into
returning the Golan Heights -- which Israel captured from Syria in
1967. And, Hezbollah is backed by Iran, with its own agenda for
spreading Islamic fervor. Even if Israel were to withdraw from
Lebanon, there is no guarantee that Hezbollah -- with encouragement
from Syria -- will not attack over the Israeli border.
</P>
<P>
   Peace talks between Israel and Syria have been suspended for
more than two years, and are on hold now at least until after the
May elections for Israeli prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, until a soldier is killed it isn't in the
headlines,'' says Lynn Griver, a member of the Israeli group, Four
Mothers, which has lead Israeli opposition to the war. ``This is a
stagnant time.''
</P>
<P>
   Griver, originally from New York City, used to protest against
the Vietnam War. Now, at 48, she has a son drafted into the Israeli
army who will soon head to south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   There, Israel occupies a roughly nine-mile wide band of
territory tracing back to June 1982, when Israel launched an
invasion that then-Defense Minister Ariel Sharon billed as a quick
strike against Palestine Liberation Organization terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   But, Israel kept pushing north until it placed the Lebanese
capital of Beirut under siege, killing more than 17,000 Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the PLO fled and Israel withdrew to the southern
strip that Israelis now call their ``security zone.'' From the
occupation grew a more formidable foe than the PLO; the Lebanese
who fight for the ``Party of God,'' or Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   By now, the war has settled into a blood-soaked routine.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli commandos search out guerrillas, who wait for them with
ambushes or remote-controlled, camouflaged bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese civilians build their homes with small windows for
safety. They occasionally need United Nations escorts to pick their
olives, and they can distinguish the sounds of bombs, mortar fire
or artillery.
</P>
<P>
   When civilians are killed, a five-nation committee assigns the
blame. Israel and Hezbollah occasionally exchange prisoners and
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   When Israeli forces kill civilians -- an air raid killed a
mother and six children in December -- residents in northern Israel
know to head for bomb shelters in preparation for the Hezbollah
response.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Hezbollah fired 120 rockets into Israel, killing none
but prompting Israeli strikes in return.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Israeli army, 894 of its soldiers have been
killed in Lebanon since 1982. That does not include deaths outside
the war zone, such as the 73 soldiers who died in a 1997 helicopter
collision south of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah officials say they have lost about 1,400 fighters in
the war.
</P>
<P>
   As for Lebanese civilians, the war claimed 15 civilian lives in
1998, about 30 the year before and more than 200 the year in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim begins here.)
</P>
<P>
   Brasheet is a small farming community just outside of
Israeli-held territory. Within sight are mountain-top Israeli
forts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there is shooting, I can go up and look out the window,
see where the operation is and then go to the other side,'' said
34-year-old nurse Khadeja Shahab(CQ). ``Many times, we're stuck in
the house for hours and can't go out.''
</P>
<P>
   When shelling broke some of her windows recently, Hezbollah
showed up to pay for repairs.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim ends here.)
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah, one of the world's best-financed, best-organized
guerilla organizations in the world, gets about $200 million a year
from Iran. It is also a political party and social network with
members in the Lebanese parliament, three major hospitals, hundreds
of health clinics and schools.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the radical Shia Islamic movement that took off in the
late 1970s, Hezbollah fights Israel on behalf of the rest of
Lebanon -- the Lebanese army stays out of the war -- with an
estimated 5,000 fighters. Most are not full-time, but they showed a
leap in skill after increased training in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Israelis) are unable to hurt us badly,'' Sheikh Nabil
Kaouk, Hezbollah leader for southern Lebanon, told the Cox News
Service. ``We will keep the south here like an oven . . . until
they withdraw, they will burn.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, the Israeli Cabinet voted to accept an old U.N.
resolution calling for an Israeli withdrawal. But, the plan
requires a Lebanese commitment to stop Hezbollah from attacking
over Israel's border.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that Lebanon does not call the shots. Syria,
which has more than 35,000 troops in Lebanon, controls the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any negotiation with Israel, we are the weaker party . . .
with Syria we are much stronger,'' Lebanese Prime Minister Salim
el-Hoss told the Cox News Service in a recent interview. ``Peace
will have to wait until Syria is ready for it.''
</P>
<P>
   What Syria wants is the Golan Heights, land seen as strategic by
many Israelis. Hezbollah is Syria's vehicle for pressuring Israel,
and Syrian leaders vow not to restart peace talks until Israel
agrees it will eventually turn over the Golan, now home to some
15,000 Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a Byzantine situation where everyone is holding their
cards close to their chests and quoting the highest price,'' said
Uri Lubrani, Israel's coordinator for Lebanese affairs. ``The
parties will have to find common ground to negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Israelis fear that pulling out would let Hezbollah could come
right to its borders and launch an attack. Hezbollah purposely does
nothing to assuage those fears.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not our duty to tell Israel what will be (after a
withdrawal),'' Hezbollah's Sheikh Kaouk said. ``We are not going to
give the occupier a present when they leave.''
</P>
<P>
   That line helps Syria keep on the pressure for the Golan. It
also highlights the question of whether Hezbollah will ever give up
war to become just a political party.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with these complexities, small wonder that a growing
number of Israelis want to just leave Lebanon and see what happens.
They argue that that would both save lives and deny Syria leverage
over the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   One withdrawal plan would require a fence and radar network on
the border. If Hezbollah attacked Israel, it could use
international pressure or the threat of military attacks directly
against Syria until it reigns in Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, several leading politicians, including now-Foreign
Minister Sharon, have backed variations on the idea.
</P>
<P>
   But, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and his chief
opponents in the elections see that as too risky.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli negotiator Lubrani notes that only six Israeli civilians
have died on the Lebanon border since the mid 1980s. For now, he
said, the ``security zone,'' is working.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
