<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4209 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN23-CO     01-22 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Where the roads get narrow in the
Deep South
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD _ Everybody knows about the Deep South. Not so many
people, perhaps, know about the deep, dark South.
</P>
<P>
   The quickest way to get there is to get yourself lost on some
backwoods road where the magnolias leave off and the bayous begin.
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, most travelers don't take the time to take
in the surroundings. All they care about is finding a road that
will deliver them back to the main highway and away from
Deliverance country, all the while whistling ``Dixie'' past the
graveyard.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that I found myself halfway lost midway on a day trip
into Louisiana, trying to stay on old U.S. Highway 190 eastward
from Jasper, Texas _ the jumping off place for civilization, of all
places.
</P>
<P>
   Just before leaving Texas, I passed the Three Flags Truck Stop.
If I had to guess, I'd say those were the Lone Star flag, the
Confederate flag and the U.S. flag, the last one included as an
afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   Please note that as you cross the Sabine River into Louisiana,
the speed limit falls off along with the condition of the highway _
55 mph compared to 70 mph in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Obey the law. They have ways of making you obey the law.
</P>
<P>
   I once got stopped by a constable in Mississippi, a long ways
from nowhere, for suspicious behavior, a compound felony in my case
seeing as how I was driving a car with Texas plates.
</P>
<P>
   What I'd done to disturb the peace officer was stop to take a
photo of a quaint old building. I was required to explain exactly
why and what for the photograph had been made.
</P>
<P>
   I said not a word about constitutional rights. The main word I
stuck with was ``Sir.'' I count myself lucky to have escaped with
only a warning ticket _ shooting pictures out of season, or some
such offense.
</P>
<P>
   When you step back into time, watch your step. Southern
hospitality has a way of turning hostile.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, this is God's country. Old-time religion is still
very much up to date, as spelled out on the front of such worship
places as the New Testament Holiness Church, the True Light Church
and the Jesus Church.
</P>
<P>
   But it's like they say: It takes a Christian to burn a cross in
your yard.
</P>
<P>
   Other signs that, catching my eye, made me catch my breath:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Quicksand Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Merryville Cemetery.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Help Prevent Woods Arson.''
</P>
<P>
   That last one in particular serves as a reminder, pilgrim, that
you're in outlaw territory where old feuds flame up in a very real
way.
</P>
<P>
   But a good rule of thumb for traveling Louisiana: The worse the
highway gets, the better the food gets _ such is the French
influence.
</P>
<P>
   Where else could you find a St. Germain road, other than the
backwoods of south Louisiana or the Left Bank of Paris?
</P>
<P>
   What I like best is what you don't find.
</P>
<P>
   I drove more than 90 miles, through one little community after
another, and never saw a McDonald's or a Burger King.
</P>
<P>
   C'est bon, y'all.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News,
</P>
<P>
   is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
