<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DONT-SWEAT-IT23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Worried about work? Author says job stress just `small stuff'
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In Richard Carlson's world, ``Don't
Worry, Be Happy'' plays 24 hours a day on the radio. Everyone
smiles. No one has ever heard the word Prozac. Tension headaches
are taboo. And if ever there is heard a discouraging word, well,
it's drowned out by a de-stressing mantra.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the best-selling author of ``Don't Sweat the Small Stuff
... And It's All Small Stuff;'' ``Don't Sweat the Small Stuff With
Your Family;'' and ``Don't Worry, Make Money,'' is back.
</P>
<P>
   This time he takes on the Godzilla of stress inducers, the
workplace, with ``Don't Sweat the Small Stuff at Work, Simple Ways
to Minimize Stress and Conflict While Bringing Out the Best in
Yourself and Others'' ($11.95, Hyperion).
</P>
<P>
   The question isn't whether stress exists in the workplace,
Carlson said during a recentew York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 1031EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4226 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD23-COX     01-22 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woodworkers have sharpnering method preferences
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Last week we talked about sharpening, but only one
method. Fact is, most woodworkers use different methods for
different tools. There is, however, no total agreement on how a
given tool should be sharpened. There are all kinds of ways to do
it.
</P>
<P>
   Chisels and plane irons need to be as sharp as they can possibly
be, which means razor sharp.
</P>
<P>
   My preference here is stones. There are natural and artificial
stones, and there are Western and Japanese stones. Western stones,
especially artificial Western stones, are intended to be used with
oil as a lubricating medium.
</P>
<P>
   This presents a problem. Oil gets into stuff, and when it gets
onto the wood you're working, it can permanently stain it.
</P>
<P>
   So, as I said last week, I use Japanese stones. The artificial
ones are a lot cheaper than the natural and they do a splendid job.
They use water for lubrication, and they can be had in grits much
finer than most American manufacturers produce.
</P>
<P>
   However, some of the greatest of woodworkers have radically
different methods. James Krenov uses a hand-cranked grinder. If you
don't have one, you've surely seen them in stores _ just like an
electric grinder, except there's a handle on the right side. You
get the wheel up to speed with the handle, then slide the tool up
the rest until the edge makes contact. The advantage over a powered
wheel is that there's no chance of overheating or burning the edge.
</P>
<P>
   You cannot, of course, expect decent results with the dismal
stones that come with these wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Tage Frid, on the other hand, sharpens his tools on a stationary
belt sander. He uses a worn belt of the finest grit. Just thinking
of this makes me shudder, but I guarantee you Frid does not use
dull tools. He uses this technique because it's quick; it requires
the least possible break from the work he's doing, and he knows how
to do it.
</P>
<P>
   It's not his only option. Tage had an old-world apprenticeship.
He could probably sharpen a chisel on the bottom of his shoe. It
would just take a little longer.
</P>
<P>
   I generally leave power sharpening options for turning tools.
The idea here is that the superfine edge brought up by waterstone
sharpening will be destroyed in a second or two by the violence of
turning. Here, I think a couple of good wheels turning on a
1700-rpm grinder are ideal. However, there are outstanding turners
who use stones to put the ultimate edge on their tools.
</P>
<P>
   There are some machines that combine the benefits of good jigs
to hold the tools with waterstones turning at slow speeds. The
really good ones, however, tend to be expensive.
</P>
<P>
   _ E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
