<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All that bran for naught
 &HT;    By Roland Nethaway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Health-conscious Americans have been choking down
sticks and twigs for decades based on the theory that a high-fiber
diet will protect them against colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that eating cow food does nothing to prevent humans
from getting colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Like a lot of the diet theories that sweep across America, this
one was never tested.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to diet, health and safety, Americans have a
gullible streak a mile wide.
</P>
<P>
   After years of accepting as gospel-truth the theory that
high-fiber diets help prevent colon cancer, teams of researchers
from Harvard University and Brigham and Women's Hospital in Boston
actually tested this unproven theory.
</P>
<P>
   After tracking the eating habits of more than 88,000 female
nurses over 16 years, the researchers discovered that women who ate
a high-fiber diet were no less likely, or more likely, to develop
colorectal cancer or polyps, which can be precursors to cancer,
than women who ate little fiber.
</P>
<P>
   It also didn't matter if the women smoked, ate fried foods or
dined daily on red meat.
</P>
<P>
   The comprehensive study also found that it made no difference
whether the women were marathon-running vegetarians or couch
potatoes who preferred to vege-out in front of the TV with a big
bag of Hershey Kisses.
</P>
<P>
   The solar-powered fruit-and-nut crowd immediately dumped loads
of fetid tofu all over the study.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps women have different colons. This was one line of
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps nurses have colons that allow them to maintain a diet of
Big Macs and German Chocolate cake without getting colon cancer any
more than roughage-munching nurses who wear out their teeth chewing
indigestible plants. Perhaps all that hospital formaldehyde does
something strange to the colons of female nurses.
</P>
<P>
   Another ``perhaps'' raised by skeptics of the study was that the
nurses could not be counted on to accurately recall their own
eating habits.
</P>
<P>
   This attempt to explain away the study requires a belief that
nurses either can't remember maintaining a high-fiber diet or that
they are somehow motivated to lie about it.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the real reason that a 16-year study of 88,000 nurses
came out the way it did is because the three-decade-old theory by
British missionary Dr. Denis Burkitt was wrong from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   But it sure sounded wonderful to people who thrive on high-guilt
diets.
</P>
<P>
   The diets of these people are many and varied. But the mother of
all their diets is the Spit Diet _ if it tastes good, spit it out.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that coarse, bulky food, such as bran, stimulates and
invigorates the colon to the point that all this activity prevents
the formation of polyps and reduces the likelihood of colorectal
cancer sounds reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   But absent scientific research, practically any crackpot theory
can be made to sound good.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have purchased truck-loads of crystals that were said
to cure everything from colon cancer to depression.
</P>
<P>
   Health food stores are crammed with ``medicines'' made from
roots, berries, old bones, fungi, tree bark or practically anything
that can be made to sound healthy. Each ingredient has its own
theory behind it, which means absolutely nothing unless it has been
tested and proven effective and safe.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of Americans now are buying magnets that are supposed
to prevent or cure various ailments. Curative magnets also are
based on a theory that sounds good.
</P>
<P>
   Americans should be remember that it's healthy to take a dose of
skepticism when they confront good-sounding, but untested, health
and safety theories.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway's column appears Wednesday and Friday in the
Waco Tribune-Herald. E-Mail: RNethaway(at)mail.wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
