<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who says Y2K won't be a blessing instead of a bug?
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ You just can't overestimate the pessimism of
the American people.
</P>
<P>
   Two of last year's most popular movies were about huge asteroids
plummeting
</P>
<P>
   toward Earth, with little the world could do to stop them. Even
in the most optimistic of these films, cheerfully named
``Armageddon,'' Paris is wiped out, New York is half destroyed and
millions of people die.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of fun from Hollywood, huh? Yet the populace flocked to see
these films and if we have an ``Armageddon II _ The Real Thing,''
it will probably do even better.
</P>
<P>
   As a people, we thrive on worrying.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the Y2K frenzy is so hot _ the idea that at one
second past midnight Jan. 1, 2000, every computer is going to
freeze up. Or, if not every computer, at least the ones controlling
the most important parts of our lives are going to crash.
</P>
<P>
   I have friends who are reasonable people (I think) who've taken
to storing up on coal-oil lanterns and bottled water. I realize
some places in the world may be a bit behind the curve in dealing
with the computer changeover, but my guess (save this,
survivalists, in hopes that you can ``tell me so'' next year) is
that most of America on Jan. 1, 2000 will be fighting the hangover
bug more than the Y2K bug.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, it has never been made clear to me why the
nation's water systems, most of which were built before computers
were a gleam in Bill Gates' eye, will suddenly stop delivering
water at the stroke of midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us without lives might consider having a party that
night to flush all the toilets at 12:01 a.m. just to make sure we
still can. The tension leaves me almost breathless.
</P>
<P>
   And who decided that Y2K had to be a bug, anyway? The
pessimists, of course. From now on, I'm going to refer to it as the
Y2K blessing.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, while all you pessimists are out their wringing
your hands about what terrible things might happen when 1999 turns
into 2000, I'm going to be considering all the wonder _ positive _
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, I'm going to consider the possibility that the Y2K
blessing will wipe out the ability of all telemarketers to function
for a good month. Can any of you imagine what it might be like to
actually sit through dinner without someone asking you if you
wanted to change long distance services? Give me the blessing!
</P>
<P>
   I'm hoping that Jerry Springer is not Y2K compliant, what a
wonderful blessing that would be. And maybe the Y2K blessing will
somehow keep all those 400-decibel car stereos from working. Sorry,
but one man's bug is another man's blessing. I think of the quiet
possibilities, what sounds we might begin to hear again.
</P>
<P>
   Because I am pretty sure that the birds are already Y2K
compliant, so is the air, the trees, rain and wind. My children are
not compliant at all, Y2K or otherwise, but that has never given
them any downtime.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 1, 2000, each of them will be waking up, being happy,
being grumpy,
</P>
<P>
   being themselves and it won't have anything to do with
computers.
</P>
<P>
   All the things that are really important don't have single
computer chip inside them.
</P>
<P>
   I know, many people are most worried about what will happen to
the monetary
</P>
<P>
   system and, thus, have been changing their cash into gold.
</P>
<P>
   But, heck, I don't have any money now. I'm not going to lose
anything. The Y2K blessing could only do something positive for me.
I intend to write a bookful of checks on Dec. 31 with that notion
in mind.
</P>
<P>
   You're completely right if you think that I don't know for sure
that something positive will come out of the Y2K blessing, but all
the naysayers don't know for sure that anything bad is going to
happen either.
</P>
<P>
   Given the two options, I'll accentuate the positive any time.
</P>
<P>
   Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (TX) News
Messenger. He may
</P>
<P>
   be reached by email at platham(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
