<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 10:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4230 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MATTRESSES23-COX     01-22 2019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATTRESSES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A royal night's sleep
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Anita J. Finkelstein
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It would be easy to say that selecting a mattress is a
lot like tasting wine. Most people know the steps they are supposed
to take _ swirling the wine, smelling the wine, looking at the wine
_ but they don't exactly know how they are supposed to decide if
it's good or bad other than by tasting the wine. Same goes with a
mattress: Although you should try it before you buy, there are
other factors to consider.
</P>
<P>
   Mattresses are considered both a big-ticket item and a long-term
investment _ a decent one should last at least eight to 10 years.
So picking the perfect mattress is an important decision that will
impact your sleep _ and perhaps your health _ for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Korshak, general manager of the Norcross-based Mattress
King, says there is everything from the Yugo of mattresses to the
Rolls-Royce version out there. ``Every customer has different needs
and a different budget. That's why there are so many different
kinds.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``A queen size mattress can range from $199 to
$4,000,'' said Ellen Fruchtman, spokeswoman for Rich's. ``Price is
very much determined by the quality of what's inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Add to the sheer volume of choices out there, the confusing
marketing tactics and unfamiliar technical jargon that push the
industry, and the consumer can end up feeling intimidated, confused
or sometimes even cheated.
</P>
<P>
   Says Korshak, ``When it comes down to it, the consumer just has
to know what their needs are and be educated on what's out there.''
</P>
<P>
   With a bit of information and some forethought, it is possible
for a consumer to save time and lessen the stress of buying a
mattress.
</P>
<P>
   LYING DOWN ON THE JOB
</P>
<P>
   Shopping for a mattress? Here are some tips from bedding
manufacturers, retailers and industry experts:
</P>
<P>
   _ Plan on spending at least one day shopping for a mattress.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bring your favorite pillow with you and spend at least 5
minutes lying on each bed you're considering. (Don't forget to wear
comfortable clothes.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Buy a mattress that is firmer than you are accustomed to. It
will soften with use. ``A good mattress is like a good quality
shoe. You have to break it in,'' says Ron Wolinski, director of
corporate training for Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ask about edge support. ``Bending a bed often will shorten its
life span, so it's a good idea if you move a lot to get a bed with
good edge support,'' suggested Karrie Auer, area manager for the
Mattress Firm.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mattresses and box springs come as ``sleep sets'' _ you should
buy them together. Place a new mattress on an old box spring and it
will feel different than it did in the store.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't forget to ask about the box spring or foundation. It
acts as a shock absorber, and it's just as important to check on
its quality.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you're worried about a large mattress set fitting through a
narrow hallway, ask about a split box spring.
</P>
<P>
   _ Your salesperson should inform you about turning your mattress
periodically. ``We liken it to rotating your tires. Flipping it and
turning it end to end will extend its life and help it wear more
evenly,'' said Dave Choppa of the Original Mattress Factory. If
your salesman doesn't mention it, be wary.
</P>
<P>
   THE FACTS _ AND THE FEEL _ OF THE MATTRESS MATTER
</P>
<P>
   Before you even step foot in a store, start by answering three
questions: What are you looking for in a mattress? How much are you
willing to spend? Where are you going to shop for it?
</P>
<P>
   _ Assessing your needs. Ron Wolinski, manager of corporate
education for Simmons, says the key question people should ask
themselves is, ``What is important to me in a bed?'' Are you more
concerned about back problems, for example, or that you are able to
sleep undisturbed? ``The first thing I ask a customer is what's
wrong with the old mattress,'' says Jack Korshak, general manager
of Mattress King in Norcross. ``It's a good starting point.''
</P>
<P>
   Other questions: Is it just old and sagging or are you not
getting a good night's sleep on it? Do your partner's movements
wake you up at night? Is it too soft? Is it too firm? Can you not
get comfortable?
</P>
<P>
   It's also good to think about who is going to be using the bed
and how often, says Dave Choppa, vice president of the Original
Mattress Factory in Marietta. If it's for a guest room, for
example, the mattress won't be used as much, and durability might
not be as important.
</P>
<P>
   _ Deciding on a budget. This is important, because if a $199
sale on a brand name is what lures you to a mattress store, you'll
be disappointed if you find it's the lowest-quality version of that
style.
</P>
<P>
   A good rule of thumb to remember is that within each brand name
there are several different styles. And each style is available in
at least three different price points _ low-end, an average and a
better bed. The differences are in the layering and types of
padding and in the kind and number of coils (more on that later).
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has a budget, that's why you'll find a $199 version
of a Beautyrest and a $599 version of the same label. But
generally, the low-price beds are going to be the lowest-quality
ones,'' says Korshak.
</P>
<P>
   If you know the general price range of mattress sets and go with
a set budget in mind, you are more likely to walk away happy with
your purchase. According to Consumer Reports' March '97 issue, the
selling price for well-constructed bedding typically starts at
about $600 for full-sized and $800 for queen-size sets. In Atlanta,
expect to pay $200 to $300 for a twin set and $800 to $1,000 for a
king set.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Fruchtman of Rich's says people need to recognize that in
the end, they get what they pay for.
</P>
<P>
   _ Finding a retailer. It's a good idea to get recommendations
from friends before shopping and it's also smart to visit more than
one store. The key is to go somewhere you trust. People usually go
to a mattress chain, buy from department stores or from independent
mattress retailers, which tend to focus on a few brand names.
Another option is an independent mattress manufacturer, such as the
Original Mattress Factory, which makes the product on site.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that research has shown that 70 percent of
consumers buy the mattress from the first store they visit.
Salesmen know this, so expect most of them to do everything in
their power to keep you from leaving without a purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Also be aware that comparison shopping from store to store is
virtually impossible, because national brands usually have at least
two different product lines, according to Consumer Reports: the
ones that are available everywhere and ones that are exclusive to a
certain store.
</P>
<P>
   The ones that are available nationwide though, don't necessarily
have the same coverings _ and the same mattress can have different
names. For example a Serta Perfect Sleeper Brookhollow in one store
might be called a Serta Perfect Sleeper Escape in another. Even if
the covering (also known as ticking) is the same, and it's made by
the same company, it doesn't ensure it's the same mattress. The
only way to tell is to know the specs of each style, which are not
always listed on the tags. So, ask to see a ``comparable'' mattress
if you have found one you liked at another store.
</P>
<P>
   LEARNING ABOUT BUILD GOES A LONG WAY TOWARD SHOPPING SMART
</P>
<P>
   Once you've determined your needs, it's time to learn more about
mattresses. There are four main things to think about when
selecting a mattress: size, comfort, support and durability.
</P>
<P>
   _ Size. This is the easy part. In general, a mattress should be
at least 6 inches longer than the person sleeping in it. Full size
beds are 75 inches long, where queens and kings are 80 inches.
Finding a longer mattress usually requires custom ordering.
</P>
<P>
   Where a full size bed used to be the norm, more people now opt
for queen size. Dave Choppa of the Original Mattress Factory says
research shows the average person shifts position 40 to 60 times
per night, and the full size bed at 53 inches by 75 inches allows
less than the width of a standard crib (27 inches) per person. Most
stores will offer a 30-day comfort promise, meaning customers can
try the bed out for 30 days, and if they don't feel they are
getting a good night's sleep on it, it can be exchanged for another
bed in the store. The only catch is that often the consumer has to
pay a second delivery charge.
</P>
<P>
   _ Comfort. Yes, Goldilocks had the right idea when she put her
head down on each bed before choosing one that was ``just right.''
The only way to figure out what is most comfortable is to lie down
on a few.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the recent increase in sleep research, doctors don't
have a recommendation of the best sleep surface. Karrie Auer, area
manager for the Mattress Firm, said she has found that people who
sleep on their backs tend to like firmer beds, while people who
sleep on their side or stomach gravitate toward the softer beds.
</P>
<P>
   Try not to ask which ones are ``firm'' and which are ``soft'';
instead feel for yourself. To a manufacturer and retailer, the
terms firm and soft (or plush) refer to how much the bed compresses
when a person lies down on it.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest factor determining firmness and softness is what's
inside and how it is layered. Mattresses are filled with a
combination of flat foam sheets, convoluted or egg crate foam
sheets, cotton batting and shoddy pads (which is matted fabric
scraps). How these sheets are layered creates the feel of the bed.
A firm mattress will conform to your body as well as a soft one _
it will just take some time to break in.
</P>
<P>
   Beds range anywhere from seven to 15 inches in thickness, which
is directly related to the number of layers of padding. A thicker
bed does not necessarily mean a softer bed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Support. Support refers to the flexibility of the mattresses
and how well it handles the weight of the users. It is determined
by the number of coils, the thickness of the coils and the number
of turns in each coil.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Brennan, vice president of material management for Simmons,
recommends a coil count of at least 312 for a full size bed. (The
highest coil count for a Simmons full size bed is 704 coils.) The
thickness of the wire should be 13 or lower _ the lower the number,
the thicker the wire. Also, there should be five or more ``turns''
to the wire (the more turns, the tighter the coil).
</P>
<P>
   ``The more coils you have, the better the bed is going to
conform to your body,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   Although, at some point, if you have so many coils that the wire
being used is thinner than it should be, you are sacrificing both
firmness and durability.
</P>
<P>
   Some manufacturers, like Serta will vary the thickness and
amount of coils in different places in the bed to provide more
support where needed. ``The heaviest part of a person's body is the
middle third. Serta has a bed that has a reinforced center, which
helps people with lower back pain,'' says Mattress King's Jack
Korshak.
</P>
<P>
   If you're confused by the different types of coils, just
remember that it isn't the type of coil so much as the thickness of
it that affects support. In fact, the same company, Leggett &AMP;
Platt, makes 80 percent of the coils found in beds made in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   _ Durability. You want a mattress that will withstand use and
abuse. It's a good idea to take a good look at the mattress to see
if it is a quality product. Most stores have cutaways of their
mattresses so you can see how the mattress is constructed. But also
look at the exterior: Are the seams straight? Is the quilting tight
and uniform? Are there any broken threads?
</P>
<P>
   The industry standard is for all mattresses to carry a 10-year
warranty. Some come with more.
</P>
<P>
   Auer said it is important to recognize that a warranty covers
the structure of the mattress and foundation only. It doesn't cover
how long it is going to last. ``Keep in mind what you are buying as
you go up in price is comfort life.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
