<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4233 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALLSPACES23-COX     01-22 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALLSPACES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Living large in small spaces
 &HT;    By Norma Martin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas, _ Living space comes at a premium price in this
town. Diminutive homes have castle-size pricetags and tiny
apartments rent for a square foot on the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to cramp anyone's sense of style.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean Central Texans have skimped on home decor
just because their shelters are of modest dimensions. They've
turned their small spaces into personal havens that showcase
everything from cowboy funky to midcentury art in less than 800
square feet.
</P>
<P>
   They have met the challenge by making use of every inch of their
dwellings, sometimes packing things in despite the view of many
interior designers that compact living requires one to edit, edit,
edit.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Ball knows about editing. She had to reduce 50 years
worth of furniture to a handful of pieces when she moved into a
652-square-foot apartment in the Grand Court, a Round Rock
retirement community.
</P>
<P>
   She incorporated a single visual theme. ``It has to flow from
room to room. You have to know your stuff,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Ball know what she had, she knew exactly where each
picture, accessory and stick of furniture was going in her two-room
residence. Her grandmother's mahogany credenza is in a corner next
to a draped picture window and is topped with an ornate English
mirror. A pair of velvet chairs flanks a pine Welsh piece in the
living-dining-kitchen area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my daughter if it (the dresser) didn't fit, I wasn't
moving,'' said Ball. ``There was a lot of measuring.''
</P>
<P>
   She exchanged a large antique bed for a smaller version with a
Bishop headboard. It shares the bedroom with a mahogany secretary
Ball purchased as a young bride.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to select pieces that are versatile,'' said Ball, who
has a small chest of drawers in her tiny bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Although her place is compact, Ball said she designed it so that
from any sitting position the eye can view her collectibles and
artwork.
</P>
<P>
   While floor space is a major concern when living in a small
home, vertical space is crucial too, says Stephanie Villavicencio,
a licensed interior designer with Cohagan Hall Design Associates.
</P>
<P>
   For most small-space dwellers, maximizing the walls and windows
gets items and accessories off the floor. For others, such as
Charles Peveto, it's the difference between showing his artwork or
putting it in storage.
</P>
<P>
   Peveto lives in a downtown apartment that is slightly less than
800 square feet. It comes with a loft connected by a spiral
staircase, but the area is mainly used for storage because of the
lack of natural light, said Peveto.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wall space is most definitely important,'' he said. Most of
his collections are of midcentury Texas artists, pre-Columbian
artifacts and chrome furniture from the 1930s and 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   The dining niche is dominated by a chrome and black table that
once graced a Texaco gas station's women's lounge. His
living-dining area is so miniscule that in an effort not to crowd
the floor he got rid of his sofa, keeping two chrome chairs. An
Everett Spruce painting entitled ``Broken Tree'' hangs over the
fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   Peveto included the kitchen in his decorating scheme, using his
bar counter to display part of his pre-Columbian art collection.
</P>
<P>
   A large collection can be a challenge in small spaces and that's
why functional diversity is a must, says Kathy Borth, a member of
the American Society of Interior Design and owner of KTB Designs.
</P>
<P>
   In South Austin, Pamela Hawthorne knows the meaning of
multifunction. She lives in an apartment that's roughly 390 square
feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't feel small,'' she said. ``I feel that I live
large.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne said she didn't hesitate moving into her ground floor
home because it was bigger than her previous residence in Mexico.
She lived in the former maid's quarters in a home she shared with
two other couples.
</P>
<P>
   Within her small space, Hawthorne has carved out a dining area,
home office and entertainment spot. Her one-bedroom, one-bath
apartment is home to Hawthorne's most treasured possessions,
including her cowboy collectibles, an extensive assortment of glass
and dinnerware and a 1930s-era living room suite with matching
tables.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have much, but everything I have means so much to
me,'' she said. ``If I love it I'll find a place for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne's home requires that her storage is often in sight.
The kitchen cupboard is open. A wooden cutting table is her main
countertop, but the wheeled cart holds a set of fine glassware and
Hawthorne's colorful assortment of shopping bags.
</P>
<P>
   A white wicker console table covered with a swatch of lace is
used to display framed photographs and a shelf underneath showcases
Hawthorne's cowboy boots. ``I call it my memory table. All the
people I love are on there and even the boots have stories,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tips for small space decorating
</P>
<P>
   Storage
</P>
<P>
   _ Use shelving and storage units that maximize the wall space.
Shelving can be used to subdivide a small space into versatile
areas.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't waste the space above your head. A narrow shelf at
picture-rail height can be used to display accessories. Don't
forget about the vertical space inside cabinets or closet doors.
</P>
<P>
   _ Organize similar items together, such as books, pictures or
china, in one place, either stacked or shelved. Personal items in
such a collection give a small home a personality.
</P>
<P>
   _ A decorative screen can hide everything from exercise
equipment to an on-going hobby project.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture
</P>
<P>
   _ Place your furniture where it makes the most sense. Do not
automatically exclude large pieces, because they can serve as focal
points in a tiny room.
</P>
<P>
   _ Select multifunctional furniture as much as possible, such as
an ottoman that works as a coffee table and a storage chest, or a
stool or chair that turns into steps. Use trolleys and trays that
double as side tables. The idea is to make your furniture do double
or triple duty, so you won't have to buy so much of it.
</P>
<P>
   _ When selecting furniture, try not to get too many pieces that
sit heavy on the floor. Furniture that you can see under and around
allows light to pass through, eliminating visual barriers.
</P>
<P>
   Color
</P>
<P>
   _ White isn't the only color to use in a small space. There are
a hundred shades of pale that will work just as well as white in
reflecting light. You might want to paint only the walls, leaving
the ceiling white. The pastel colors can offer a compact place a
sense of expansiveness.
</P>
<P>
   _ If using a monochromatic color scheme, remember to use texture
in fabrics, coverings and objects.
</P>
<P>
   _ Daytime rooms look best in light, airy colors to make them
appear bigger. Night-time rooms can be painted strong, dark colors;
they make a room more formal.
</P>
<P>
   _ To ``raise'' a low ceiling, use a cool color. To ``lower'' a
high ceiling, paint it two to three shades darker than the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Sources
</P>
<P>
   _ Kevin Alter, assistant professor of architecture and associate
director of the Center for American Architecture and Design at the
University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Making the Most of Small Spaces'' by Anoop Parikh (Rizzoli
International Publications).
</P>
<P>
   _ Kathy Borth, ASID interior designer and owner of KTB Designs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stephanie Villavicencio, ASID interior designer with Cohagan
Hall Design Associates
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Designing for Small Homes'' by Dylan Landis (PBC
International Inc.)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Less is More: A Practical Guide to Maximizing the Space in
Your Home'' by Elaine Lewis (Penguin Studio Books)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
