<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 10:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4239 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-TAX-SITES-1STLD-W     01-22 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TAX-SITES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAXES MAY STILL BE CERTAIN, BUT ON THE WEB IT'S AT LEAST EASIER 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Corrects and clarifies Intuits market share in 14thgraf, which is
the 1stgraf of the 2ndtake)   By STEVEN E. BRIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Web sites that deal with tax information have become more
sophisticated and capable. Even the venerable Internal Revenue
Service web site has tax forms that can be filled out online and
printed, a far cry from the days when everything had to be
downloaded, printed and then filled out by hand.
</P>
<P>
   Some of this change comes about as a result of the IRS e-file
program, in which tax returns can be filed electronically, whether
by telephone or through a computer. This has spurred an increase in
Web sites that can handle tax calculation and filing through a
browser, something unheard of just a few short years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, about 25 million returns were filed electronically,
about one in five according to the IRS. This year, the agency
expects that number to climb to about 30 million. This is a
significant change for the IRS, which still has its employees
retyping all the information that comes in on paper returns,
whether it was done by hand or computer _ and even if it comes in
on the 1040PC form. Every return that comes in electronically is
one less that has to be retyped and, according to the IRS, the
money saved will be redirected to customer service and upgraded
computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   There is room for improvement. According to the IRS, half the
professionally prepared personal returns are prepared on computer
but less than a quarter of those are filed electronically. A paltry
28,000 of the approximately 9 million individual extensions
requests, seeking permission to file late returns, are filed
electronically. A picayune 1,000 of the 23.8 million payments that
accompany individual returns are received electronically, leaving
the IRS awash in a sea of paperwork and perpetuating a process that
is prone to error.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional tax software providers like Intuit and H&AMP;R Block
have jumped on the e-file bandwagon. They have been joined by
companies such as One Tax, Tax Act and Secure Tax that provide
information as well as software and online filing services. The
incentive for consumers to use such services is the promise of
easier filing, faster refunds and fewer contacts with the IRS
</P>
<P>
   The sites that have the Web-based tax programs uniformly offer
tax advice of high quality. H&AMP;R Block's Kiplinger Tax Cut,
www.taxcut.com, mple, offers a handy section titled ``50 ways to
cut your taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web site put together by the Internal Revenue _
Servicewww.irs.ustreas.gov. _ contains tax forms, information
sheets and explanations of the many arcane rules of the tax
business. The tax rules are available on line in what the IRS
claims is plain language; it is offered on CD-ROM for tax
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS has expanded its use of what it calls fillable forms.
The forms are based on Adobe Acrobat's Portable Document Format
(P.D.F.). Unlike the other forms, which must be downloaded, printed
and filled in by hand, these allow users to view a form with a Web
browser, type information in the appropriate fields and then print
or save.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the forms do not have a computation engine built
in, so it is still necessary to do all that troublesome math on
your own and carry the results from one field to the next.
</P>
<P>
   Younger taxpayers, or those who want the tax code explained in
English, may want to check out the Taxi, or Tax Interactive,
section of the site. This explains how the tax system works, where
tax money goes and what many of those obscure terms mean. The
explanations are a bit simplistic, but if you don't know the
language, Taxi is a good place to start. Another useful section is
the site's FAQ page. Like much in the world of taxes, it depends
heavily on numbers, but it still contains useful information.
</P>
<P>
   When tax time is past, some people may want to take a look at
the Statistics of Income section of the Web site. This contains
demographic information about taxpayers that may be of some use to
businesses that need to target their products or marketing or to
people trying to better understand their community. By the way,
people perusing the entire site can also rest easy, according to
the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't count visitors or individual users,'' said Linda
Wallace, the agency's chief of electronic information services.``We
feel everyone wants to be anonymous.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The undisputed king of the hill for personal tax software is
Intuit, with the various versions of Turbotax grabbing well over 70
percent of the federal tax software market, according to PC Data of
Reston, Va., a market research company. Intuit also makes a
Macintosh version, Macintax, and several versions of the program to
handle state taxes.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Intuit is taking that background to the Web with Web
Turbotax.
</P>
<P>
   The Web offers advantages over desktop tax software. First, you
don't have to worry about software conflicts, running out of disk
space or any of the problems that arise when installing software.
Second, the program and data are available through any Web browser:
just take out your W-2 statement of annual earnings, open the
browser, go to the site and enter the information. The drawbacks,
as for any Internet service, are slow connections and concerns
about security.
</P>
<P>
   Intuit provides extensive notes about the security of its
encryption (128-bit secure socket layers) and about the penalties
the company would face if it misused tax data. Concerns over speed
are addressed by allowing users to do much of the work without
charge and requiring a fee only when it comes time to print, view
or send the return.
</P>
<P>
   The product will handle federal returns as well as those from
any one of the 44 states (and the District of Columbia) that have
income taxes. But you can't file in two states.
</P>
<P>
   The site charges $9.95 for a 1040EZ form or the state equivalent
and $19.95 for a 1040 or its state equivalent. Finished documents
can be printed to be mailed or sent electronically. Taxpayers who
earn less than $20,000 can use the program free under an IRS
program intended to encourage electronic filing.
</P>
<P>
   The information for the return is collected during Web
Turbotax's interview process.
</P>
<P>
   As the interview process proceeds, an outline down the left side
of the screen changes to let you know where you are in the process;
FAQ's appear on the right to answer questions relevant to that part
of the interview. Although helpful, these additions slow down the
process. Entering the assets needed for Schedule C was painful; a
single question was answered on each screen, with three or more
screens for each new asset. Users who have outfitted a home office
with a computer, television, scanner, fax, desk and related
equipment might find this too much trouble.
</P>
<P>
   When finished with the federal return, the program asks if you
wish to prepare a state return.
</P>
<P>
   Onetax.com is relatively new to the consumer market, though not
to tax and financial information. It is an offshoot of Thomson
Investors Network, which produces First Call financial earnings
estimates, software for professional tax preparers and other
financial products.
</P>
<P>
   Like Web Turbotax, One Tax allows you to do federal and state
taxes using a Web browser, limiting users to a single state. The
price is low, $9.95 &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Web Turbotax, One Tax takes more of a minimalist
approach.
</P>
<P>
   The site is designed for speed and for the average taxpayer.
``We don't do the business,'' said Jane Moynihan, a company
spokeswoman. ``We don't do Schedule C. We don't do multiple
states.'' &UR;  &LR;  Everything is clearly labeled, and every field has
either a Help button or a Tax Tip button next to it. A quick click,
and more information on that field is available. Another click, and
you are back at the form.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a lot of time doing a robust help engine and making
help easy,'' Ms. Moynihan said. ``We also don't give out tax
advice. We do give advice like, `This is what this means.'''
</P>
<P>
   One Tax allows the user to switch between the standard ``guided
entry'' process and an ``independent entry'' system. Independent
entry allows you to click on a menu at the top of each page,
choosing items like W-2, 1099, dependents and similar items, and
then enter the information you happen to have at that time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 1043EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 10:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4241 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     01-22 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE EDGES TO THE HEART OF IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds, because of its timely nature, this column is being
distributed ahead of its normal Monday filing. It is for immediate
release.)  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c. 1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, one of the House impeachment managers referred to the
removal of former federal judge Alcee L. Hastings _ in order to
buttress the notion that perjury is serious enough to warrant
impeachment. In 1989, Hastings was impeached for bribery and
numerous counts of perjury in regard to his testimony as a
defendant in a criminal case. The House manager neglected to
mention that Alcee Hastings is now a colleague, a member of the
House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, being a scoundrel while serving as a judge is
unacceptable, but isn't a barrier to joining the ranks of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Probably that isn't news to most people.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment clauses in the U.S. Constitution grant the
Senate the power to remove the president, vice president, federal
judges, and all civil officers of the United States. The Senate is
also given the authority to disqualify those convicted of articles
of impeachment from holding elected or appointed public office. The
Senate rarely votes in favor of disqualification although it only
takes a simple majority, not a two-thirds majority, to add this
restriction.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to President Clinton's impeachment, the U.S. House had
impeached 15 individuals: a president, a senator, a Cabinet member,
and 12 judges.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate convicted seven _ all judges. Only two of those seven
were disqualified from holding office in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after his impeachment, Hastings ran as a Democrat
for a House seat from his home state, Florida. He's been a member
of Congress ever since. And last September, Hastings introduced a
resolution to impeach Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr for ``high
crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastings accuses Starr of violating his oath of office, misusing
the powers granted to an independent counsel, and unlawfully
disclosing grand jury material for the purpose of embarrassing
Clinton. The House voted to table Hastings' resolution.
</P>
<P>
   An added note: Prior to his impeachment, a jury in a criminal
trial had acquitted Hastings of conspiring to solicit a bribe.
Nevertheless, the House voted in favor of 17 articles of
impeachment against Hastings, including the bribe for which a jury
had found him not guilty. The Senate convicted him of seven
articles.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Flynt sticks in GOP's craw
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 15, Republican National Committee Chairman Jim Nicholson
called for a criminal investigation of Larry Flynt. The RNC's Web
site (www.rnc.org) was filled with invective against Flynt for
nearly a week, reviling him as a smut peddler and Clinton's
pornographer.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson claims Flynt is ``obstructing a congressional
investigation'' for digging into the sexual escapades of Republican
hard-noses who want Clinton impeached. Apparently, the RNC's
chairman doesn't see the delicious irony of his statements.
</P>
<P>
   Starr couldn't find a shred of evidence against Clinton in the
Whitewater probe and found nothing to show Clinton might have been
involved with illegal use of FBI files, but the Paula Jones lawsuit
promised some sexual hanky-panky that a zealous prosecutor might be
able to finesse into an article of impeachment _ if he played his
cards right. After all, Starr had a $40 million deck.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, it's OK for Starr to dig into Clinton's sex-capades,
but it isn't OK for a private citizen to dig into the dalliances of
those Republicans who have been aiming to bring the president down
since he was re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson calls Flynt's outing of hypocrites ``the politics of
personal destruction.'' And it is. But who started it? Suddenly,
this tactic has become very personal. It could be a married
Republican senator who has his private life smeared across the
tabloids.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back to the darker era of the FBI, one cannot find the
Republican Party calling for the dismissal of director J. Edgar
Hoover for secretly recording and publicizing the sexual revelry of
certain civil rights leaders. The politics of personal destruction
was used with a vengeance against black leaders. But now, used
against the conservative establishment, it is finally considered
dangerous and wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The Nixon impeachment standard
</P>
<P>
   On July 27, 1974, when the House Judiciary Committee voted on
articles of impeachment against President Nixon, the committee
passed three: obstruction of justice, abuse of power and contempt
of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The committee rejected two articles, one of which should be at
issue in the Clinton impeachment trial. Article 4 accused Nixon of
tax evasion and illegally using government funds to improve his
private residences.
</P>
<P>
   The article reads, in part: 1) ``He ... unlawfully received
compensation in the form of government expenditures at and on his
privately-owned properties ....'' and 2) ``He knowingly and
fraudulently failed to report certain income and claimed deductions
... which were not authorized by law ....''
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee voted 26-12 against Article 4.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and Republicans alike agreed that Congress should only
impeach a president for actions taken against the Constitution or
against our form of government. Although Nixon might have been
guilty of tax evasion (a felony) and misappropriating government
funds for his own use (another felony), the committee felt that
these crimes were personal and not crimes against the nation;
therefore, not impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   If the Senate of the 106th Congress used the standard applied to
Nixon, all fair-minded Republicans would have to vote to acquit
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The actions that brought impeachment articles against Clinton
were certainly personal, even private, and do not jeopardize our
nation.
</P>
<P>
   That raises questions: Do we have two or more standards of
impeachment for presidents? If so, can this process ever be fair?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
