<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Saturday, January 23 and Sunday,
January 24, 1999 are moving today to clients of the New York Times
News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ MARSHALL, Texas _ From now on, I'm going to
refer to the Y2K bug as the Y2K blessing. That's right, while all
you pessimists are out their wringing your hands about what
terrible things might happen when 1999 turns into 2000, I'm going
to be considering all the wonder _ positive _ possibilities.
(Latham, Marshall News Messenger) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Americans should be remember
that it's healthy to take a dose of skepticism when they confront
good-sounding, but untested, health and safety theories. (Rowland
Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ ON THE ROAD _ Everybody knows about the Deep
South. Not so many people, perhaps, know about the deep, dark
South.
</P>
<P>
   The quickest way to get there is to get yourself lost on some
backwoods road where the magnolias leave off and the bayous begin.
(Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Dear U.S. Senate: Reporters say you are thinking
of calling me to testify to you about my relationship with
President Clinton. Let me save you some bother: Don't even try.
Love, Monica. (Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox
Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ I keep seeing signs that humans continue to
be on the decline when it comes to job opportunities. Last week
Delta Air Lines announced it was adding a $2 surcharge to all
domestic bookings not made on Delta's Web site. If everyone
switches to the Web to save two bucks, there's going to be a lot
less need for people to take reservations over the telephone.
(Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox News Service.) MOVED
THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ ASHINGTON In 1964, as Lyndon Johnson campaigned
in Ohio, his motorcade drove by an elderly woman propped in a
wheelchair. Somebody had put in her lap a photo taken of her as a
new-born baby while being held by Abraham Lincoln. LBJ, who didn't
miss much, ordered his caravan halted. To the delight of all, he
had the White House photographer take his picture with the old
lady. That poignant scene, spanning a century, came to mind when
President Clinton, closed his State of the Union address by evoking
the image of another American president standing ``a 100 years from
tonight ... in this place to report on the State of the Union.''
(Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox News Service in the Washington
bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
