<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Saturday, January
23 and Sunday, January 24, 1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors won't have to look at every day's budget,
Cox's features budgets have daily themes according tothis schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   Thursday for Friday: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   TODAY for the weekend: Religion, science &AMP; health, and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK ON THE WEB: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available
for purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ ATLANTA _ Last week we talked about sharpening,
but only one method. Fact is, most woodworkers use different
methods for different tools. There is, however, no total agreement
on how a given tool should be sharpened. There are all kinds of
ways to do it. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   BATS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Only some bats deserve a bad
name. There is a lot people don't know about these ``evolutionized
animals,'' and some conservation groups have made it a point to
provide information and safely remove the creatures. (Lomartire,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   DONT-SWEAT-IT _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Richard Carlson, the
best-selling author of ``Don't Sweat the Small Stuff ... And It's
All Small Stuff;'' ``Don't Sweat the Small Stuff With Your
Family;'' and ``Don't Worry, Make Money,'' is back with a book
about beating stress at the workplace. (Houck, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   ABBY _ A day with Abby Banks to update how the 4-year-old
Franklin girl is getting along with spacesuit donated by supermodel
Christy Turlington. Abby has rare skin disorder that made it
impossible for her to be outside in daylight. We follow her at play
outside, with her friends, with her pony. (Budd, Dayton Daily
News). 22. WITH PHOTOS. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS
</P>
<P>
   SPOLETO-PROGRAM _ Spoleto Festival USA releases final
programming details, including the jazz program (Sonny Rollins,
Oregon, Cuban pianist Frank Emilio Flynn, and singer Denise
Jannah); dance by flamenco star Antonio Canales; and Charles
Wadsworth's 70th birthday party (with Peter Serkin, Pinchas
Zuckerman and champagne). (Brock, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
24. WITH PHOTOS. FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   ACTORS _ When Chris Paul and Lorilyn Harper, married actors from
Dallas, Tx. , leave their temp jobs on a Thursday afternoon for a
weekend of even lower-paid acting, ``We feel like the lucky ones,''
says Paul, ``because we get to do what we love.'' But what about
the physical toll of burning the candle at both ends? We look at
the state of acting in Atlanta. (Hulbert, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH COLOR PHOTOS. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ACTORS-FACTS _ Chart with Actors spelling out the brutal facts
of thespian pay. (Hulbert, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR
SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET SCIHEALTH _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet SCIHEALTH page for
the current week. This layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   MOONROCKS _ What's it like to take care of a national treasure
for a week? Ask Jennifer Feiler of the Trinity School in Atlanta,
who's holding moon rocks from the Apollo missions during the week
of Jan. 25. She completed a special training seminar to learn about
the security and handling of the rocks, which are stored in a
special facility at the Johnson Space Center. (Cauley, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   RELIGIONRELIGION-Y2K _ Shaunti Christine Feldhahn, a former
federal reserve financial analyst who lives in Atlanta, has started
a project and written a book to help churches get ready for Y2K.
She's no survivalist nut who's piling up bottles of water and dried
food in the basement. Feldhahn explains the problem and offers ways
individuals, businesses and churches can prepare to prevent major
problems so that services to the poor and needy go on despite
computer problems. She also offers ways churches and synagogues can
be available to help communities that may have temporary power
outages, food shortages or business closures at New Year 2000. We
interview her and two or three people involved in local chapters of
the Joseph Project, helping people get ready. (GWhite, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   HOME &AMP; GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   ORCHIDS _ Orchids have been given a bad rap. Like roses, they
have the reputation for being tempermental. But professionals and
amateur gardeners alike contend they're one of the easiest plants
to grow indoors _ and one of the most effective ways to bring
garden color inside during the gray days of January. To whet your
appetite, the Atlanta Botanical Garden is sponsoring an exhibit of
more than 1,500 varieties of orchids, and next Saturday visitors
will be treated to a guided tour of the greenhouse where they're
grown. (Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH COLOR PHOTOS.
FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ORCHIDS-TIPS _ Tips for growing orchids and demonstration on how
to repot an orchid. (Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   HOME-ACCESSORIES _ New designs in home decorating accessories
take their cue from furnishings. Some of today's most popular
themes and motifs for furniture manufacturers are retro, Asian and
garden. And when it comes to accessories, nowhere were those
categories more evident than at last week's Atlanta International
Gift &AMP; Home Furnishings Market. (Flanders, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   LEEMAY-COLUMN _ Columnist Lee May muses on hummingbirds and
life: ``One day, Lyn and I sat idling, counting the number of times
a bird stuck its icepick beak into the little feeder hole during
one trip. Thirty-six times, we counted. A minute or so later it
returned, only to get buzzed by another hummingbird. Back and forth
they went, taking turns dive-bombing each other away from the
feeder. The result: Neither tasted the sweetness. So it goes in the
garden of life.'' (May, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   SMALLSPACES _ Austin apartment rents are high. Some places are
asking for nearly $1 a square foot. And so for many folks a large,
rommy place to live is out of the question. But how do residents
live with style and comfort in a small place--not a dorm room. How
have they applied their creativity to transform a need into
nice-looking nest. Several new books are out on how to decorate
small houses, some no larger than 440 square feet, and apartments.
(Martin, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
