<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4270 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     01-22 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, Jan. 22, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Saturday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence
at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EL-NINO (Schenectady, N.Y.) _ El Nino appears to have been an
active climate force since the time human beings developed writing,
a Union College geologist theorizes in an article published in the
journal Science. The findings by a team of researchers add to a
growing body of knowledge about El Nino, which has affected weather
systems from South America to the U.S. Northeast. By JAY
JOCHNOWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   COP-SHRINKS (San Francisco) _ These days, San Francisco police
have people to go to help them cope with a range of emotions _
anger, fear, frustration and sadness. The humble name they call
themselves: cop docs. More formally they are the Behavioral Science
unit. By MARSHA GINSBURG.
</P>
<P>
   HORSE-MEAT (San Francisco) _ Backers of Proposition 6, an
initiative passed by California voters in November making it a
felony to sell horses for human consumption, say the new law
appears to have significantly lowered the number of horses sold at
auction in the state. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-FAMILY (Anaheim, Calif.) _ Despite awful home and school
environments that thwart many kids from growing up well, other
children in seemingly similar circumstances come out OK. Some
researchers have identified those kids as resilient, singling out a
trait that seems to keep them on an even keel. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FAMOUS-COP (Clifton Park, N.Y.) _ Many years ago, Dick Clemens
had his likeness captured by a great artist for future generations
to admire. But Clemens, depicted in his police uniform in a classic
1958 Saturday Evening Post cover by artist Norman Rockwell, doesn't
think of it as conferring any kind of immortality. ``He's the
important one, not me,'' the retired Massachusetts officer says. By
MIKE HUREWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   SHOWER-HEADS (Albany, N.Y.) _ The shower head has become a
state-of-the-art fixture in most homes and apartments. If you
prefer a shower to a bath, you can now select from a large variety
of shower heads, from water-saving and pulsating water-massage
models to safety anti-scald devices. By FRANCES INGRAHAM. (For
release Sunday, Jan. 24.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Undated) _ In this time of solid wage increases,
a good many workers have seen their wages fall. An economist says
get ready for more of the same: This will become more common as
corporate profits are squeezed. By L.M. SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ Microprocessor makers are engaged in
a power and price war. What this means for the cash-strapped PC
buyer is that computers that would have sold a year ago for
$2,500-$3,000 are now going for $900-$1,500. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ A reader wants to know about WebTV
and if he can talk to several of his friends who are on America
Online. The answer is no. A Q&AMP;A. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-DOCUMENTARY (Undated) _ ``A Murder in Texas: Hate on
Trial,'' a one-hour documentary to air Monday night on Discovery
Channel, chronicles white supremacists in the United States. The
documentary focuses on James Byrd Jr., a Texan who was beaten and
dragged behind a pickup in the small East Texas town of Jasper. By
MIKE McDANIEL
</P>
<P>
   TV-CABLE (Pasadena, Calif.) _ The cable industry knows you're
out there. It even brags _ heavily _ about your rising numbers. But
either those lucky Nielsen families aren't keeping good diaries or
they just can't remember anything beyond the Big Four, because
network television is finding it pretty easy these days to mock the
numbers claims of cable. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-PLAN (Undated) _ Until now, Sam Raimi's best-known
films were three involving murderous demons: ``The Evil Dead,''
``The Evil Dead 2'' and ``Army of Darkness.'' With his new film,
``A Simple Plan,'' he's found something else _ a cold, murderously
mean little B-movie that takes a more conventional approach to
telling the same old story. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-HEART (Undated) _ Some bits and pieces of ``Playing
by Heart'' are delightful. Some bits and pieces are not. As proof,
here are a few of the delightful bits . By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-PARADISE (Undated) _ Larry Clark is a filmmaker who
never lets up in his quest for ``realism,'' and after relentlessly
and sadistically pounding his audience into submission with
non-actors in ``Kids,'' he proves he can pulverize us with big
stars in ``Another Day in Paradise.'' By G. ALLEN JOHNSON.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-FLIGHT (Undated) _ There's a lot of metaphorical
weight to ``Theory of Flight,'' a pleasing, nicely executed movie
that suffers from not being ambitious enough _ odd for a movie
about frustrated dreams and fatal diseases. By G. ALLEN JOHNSON.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-CRAZY (Undated) _ Iit would be a shame if ``Still
Crazy'' was lumped into the ``Spinal Tap'' genre simply because it
was about a reunion of old rockers. ``Still Crazy'' involves the
'90s reunion of the '70s rock band Strange Fruit, an English band.
By CRAIG MARINE.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-VALENTINES (Undated) _ With Valentine's and President's
days falling back-to-back next month, say the word that special
person most wants to hear ... ``pack.'' By SYD KEARNEY. (For
release Sunday, Jan. 24)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SNOWSHOES (Gabriels, N.Y.) _ Arms pumping, legs kicking, Birger
Ohlsson huffs and puffs his way through the chilly powder. Ohlsson,
a teacher, is like more and more elite runners. He discovered the
sport of snowshoeing and embraced it with the enthusiasm of a
cocker spaniel. By BUZZ GRAY.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ This has to be the ultimate Web
site for Southern California. It combines pagers and freeway
pursuits, and was inspired by O.J. Simpson's Bronco chase. By ROB
MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVATIZING-SOCIAL-SECURITY (Washington) _ The big campaign to
``privatize'' Social Security is rolling along, with a bipartisan
bunch of Democrats and Republicans succumbing to the siren call of
Corporate America. It's a nutty idea. By RALPH ESTES.
</P>
<P>
   SEX-CLUB (Undated) _ The impeachment trial of President Clinton
is of even greater historical significance than that of O. J.
Simpson. While the charges are grave _ perjury and obstruction of
justice _ it all began with inappropriate sexual conduct. Despite
his track record, inappropriate presidential sexual behavior was
not invented by Bill Clinton. Let us look at the record. By GUY P.
BEACH.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
