<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 11:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4296 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-HELL-$ADV24-K     01-22 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-HELL-$ADV24-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JUDGE MADE AN APPALLING SITUATION EVEN WORSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1999 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been several weeks since I read the outrageous _ if
understandable _ comments a judge made when sentencing a despicable
man, but I can't get them out of my mind. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the whole case made me sick. And what the judge said
simply made a horrid situation worse. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The defendant, Brian Stewart, 32, of Columbia, Ill., stood
convicted of an almost-unthinkable crime: injecting his own
11-month-old son with HIV-tainted blood old to avoid child-support
payments. The boy, now 7, suffers from the disease HIV causes,
AIDS, Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine a punishment severe enough for ruining the
life of an indefensible baby. As a volunteer in the struggle
against AIDS, I have seen dozens of people die of this evil
disease. To give it to a child intentionally is unfathomable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But there's a difference between expressing justifiable outrage
at illegal and immoral acts and using a judge's secular authority
to set forth theological conclusions that don't belong in a court
of law. The latter is exactly what St. Charles, Mo., County Circuit
Judge Ellsworth Cundiff offered to the defendant and the world when
he sentenced Stewart in early January. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cundiff, calling himself a religious man, said this: ``I believe
when God finally calls you, you are going to burn in hell from here
to eternity.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I don't object to the judge holding that opinion. He's free to
believe a Manichean vision of ultimate reality if he chooses. It's
a free country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But as a public servant, Cundiff has no right to afflict anyone
in his courtroom with his myopic brand of theological certainty, no
right to take upon himself the grandiloquent role of eternal judge
and jury. It's an assault on the constitutionally mortared wall
separating church from state. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cundiff may well believe Stewart will burn in hell. I suppose if
Cundiff were a minister in Stewart's church, if any, he might have
a right to say that to Stewart, though even there such certainty is
misguided. But Cundiff isn't clergy. He's a county judge, and some
judgments are beyond his competency. The eternal destiny of Brian
Stewart is one of them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most religions offer one or more theories of what happens to us
when we die. But none, so far as I know, leaves anyone's eternal
fate up to a county judge in St. Charles, Mo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In my own Reformed Tradition of Christianity, in fact, there is
a much-misunderstood Calvinistic doctrine called
double-predestination that can be unpacked fully, if at all, only
with delicately nuanced language. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In oversimplified _ and almost certainly misleading _ words, the
doctrine says God irresistibly designates some people for heaven
and some for hell, and there's nothing really to be done to change
that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to argue either for or against this idea here. In
fact, I bring up the doctrine simply to point out how it can
prevent people who pledge some allegiance to it from making the
sort of judgment about others that Cundiff made about Stewart. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Author Kathleen Norris best explains this ironic truth in her
recent book ``Amazing Grace: A Vocabulary of Faith'': ``To me, the
most intriguing thing about John Calvin's doctrine of
predestination (inherited from Augustine) is not his belief that
some are gratuitously predestined by God to eternal salvation and
some to damnation but that no one but God knows who is who. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There,'' she says, ``among the heroin addicts, is one destined
for eternal joy. There, among the faithful widows of an ordinary
church, is one destined for damnation. It strikes me that only a
French lawyer could have come up with so complex, if not bizarre, a
justification for treating all people as if they could be among the
elect, the chosen of God.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I do not wish upon Cundiff the burdens of being a Calvinist or
of explaining the hard doctrine of predestination. But I do wish he
had been influenced by the doctrine's implications that Norris
points to and that he would be, thus, more reluctant to judge
others' eternal destiny. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For, in the end, none of us should put up with hearing anyone
damned to hell by a county judge. That ruling requires at minimum a
change of venue. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This column is for use Sunday, Jan. 24, and thereafter.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
