<HEADER>
A4307 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-US-$ADV24-COX     01-22 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-US-$ADV24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S.-RUSSIAN RELATIONS SUFFER OVER IRAQ, MISSILES
 &HT;    EDs: Albright departs for Russia on Sun.; holds meetings in
Moscow Mon.-Wed.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Jan. 24 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ It is not the Cold War, but it is chilly.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-Russian relations are filled with friction these days,
perhaps more than at any time since Russia became an independent
state after the fall of the Soviet Union in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright arrives in Moscow on
Monday for meetings with senior Russian officials amid strains over
policy toward Iraq, the Balkans, disarmament and U.S. sanctions
against Russian institutions allegedly supplying help to Iran to
build its nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
   Russian foreign ministry officials promised frank talks over
what they are politely terming ``the accumulation of agitations.''
</P>
<P>
   But the widely held notion in Moscow is that the Clinton
administration is kicking Russia while it is down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has gone from bad to worse,'' said Andrei Piontkovsky, of
the Moscow-based Strategic Studies Center. ``For the past two
months almost every action the U.S. takes provokes anger in Moscow.
It is a conceptual challenge for Washington -- how do you handle a
former superpower?''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. policymakers have struggled with that question since the
fall of the Soviet Union. It has become increasingly difficult as
the gap widens between America, with its robust economy and firm
superpower stature, and Russia, its superpower status long ago
faded and currently in the midst of an economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Russia's media have denounced Washington over
the perception in Moscow that the United States is seeking world
hegemony while deliberately humiliating Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the very start of the year Washington has led a massive
attack against Russia with the aim of overcoming the last remaining
barrier to American world domination,'' the politically moderate
newspaper Nezavisimaya Gazeta said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The always-sensitive relationship between Moscow and Washington
took a turn for the worse in December when the United States and
Britain launched air attacks on Iraq without prior consultations
with Russia or other members of the United Nations Security
Council. In protest, Russia recalled its ambassadors to Washington
and London.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent controversy came this week when the White House
proposed changes to the terms of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile
(ABM) Treaty. The proposal for amending the treaty is based on a
new American defense doctrine that recognizes a need for new
anti-missile systems to counter threats from rogue states such as
North Korea and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Economically and politically weak, Russia has little pressure to
bring to bear on the Clinton administration to counter its
international policy. Russia depends on economic aid from the
United States and Europe, including food aid this winter to help
Russia through its economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said Friday that damage
control is necessary during the Albright visit. ``The essential
thing is to prevent sliding from certain differences to outward
confrontation. That we will not allow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ABM proposal, put forward in a letter from President Clinton
to Russian President Boris Yeltsin, was met with a negative
response from the Russian government. ``We proceed from the
assumption that it must not happen, and will actively be trying to
convince our American partners,'' Ivanov said Friday in a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   It prompted howls of protest from Russia's press.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States invites Russia to take part in a new arms
race,'' announced a front-page headline in the newspaper Sevodnya,
adding that Russia's economic crisis would prevent it from
competing.
</P>
<P>
   Also fueling Russian ire was the White House decision this month
to impose sanctions on several Russian companies and scientific
institutes which the United States alleged were supplying weapons
technology to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Russian officials denied the allegations, though Yuri
Maslyukov, the first deputy prime minister, admitted in a
television interview Wednesday that there was a basis for the U.S.
charges. ``Some of the cases that they have presented have turned
out to be true,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The troubled Yugoslavian province of Kosovo also will be high on
the agenda, and ripe for disagreement as NATO threatens possible
air strikes on Serbia, a longtime ally of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   In another development certain to trouble Moscow, NATO is
scheduled to expand eastward later this year, adding three new
members formerly under the umbrella of the Soviet Union -- Poland,
Hungary and the Czech Republic. Russia is concerned about the
related buildup of military forces in the three countries.
</P>
<P>
   Albright is carrying what she has called ``a very large briefing
bag'' for the Moscow trip. She is scheduled to meet with Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov and Ivanov. It was not clear whether she
would hold talks with Yeltsin, who is in a Moscow hospital
recovering from a bleeding ulcer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the Russians will be surprised by anything she
has to say. But clearly she will seek to clarify our position on
these matters,'' said a U.S. official speaking on the condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Even a U.S. proposal to provide more aid to Russia to cope with
its aging nuclear arsenal was derided in the Russian press and
among some opposition political leaders as disingenuous and
unworkable.
</P>
<P>
   In his State of the Union speech, President Clinton called on
Congress to spend $4.5 billion over the next five years to help
Russia disarm and safeguard its vast nuclear arsenal. The United
States has spent about $2 billion over the past eight years on
disarmament programs in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   While welcomed by the Kremlin, some Russian politicians doubted
whether Clinton could win approval in Congress for the proposal and
said it was a thinly disguised effort to win ratification in the
Russian parliament for the long-delayed START II arms treaty.
</P>
<P>
   The Communists and nationalists who control Russia's lower house
of parliament, the Duma, had been ready to vote on START II last
month. But they canceled the vote to protest the U.S. bombing of
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government supports ratification of START II --
which would reduce U.S. and Russian arsenals by half -- to
3,000-3,500 warheads each -- arguing that budget cutbacks will
force Russia to reduce the numbers of its aging nuclear missiles
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
