<SLUG> BC-GAYS-MILITARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP SAYS AIR FORCE AND ARMY KICK OUT GAYS IN RECORD NUMBERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Army and Air Force discharged homosexual
personnel in record numbers last year despite a controversial
policy that allows gays and lesbians to serve, the Servicemembers
Legal Defense Network (SLDN), a gay rights legal organization,
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The number of discharges in the two military branches represents
huge increases over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force discharged 414 gay and lesbian personnel in 1998,
compared with 309 in 1997, 282 in 1996, 234 in 1995 and 180 in
1994, according to figures provided by the service.
</P>
<P>
   The Army also discharged record numbers of homosexuals in 1998,
according to unofficial figures provided to the gay rights
organization. In the Army, 317 enlisted personnel were dismissed
compared with 197 enlisted and officers in 1997, 206 in 1996, 182
in 1995 and 136 in 1994. The group wasn't provided 1998 figures for
the number of Army officers discharged.
</P>
<P>
   An Army spokesman could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Lackland Air Force Base in San Antonio led the way in the Air
Force, accounting for 271 basic trainees severed from the service
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The new figures, first reported by the San Antonio Express-News
in an article by Sig Christenson, represent the greatest number of
homosexuals discharged from the Air Force since President Clinton's
controversial ``don't ask, don't tell, don't pursue'' policy went
into effect in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But T'Jae Gibson, an Air Force spokeswoman at the Pentagon, said
a majority of the discharges in 1998 _ 391 cases _ were because the
service member voluntarily came forward and described his or her
sexuality to a commander.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people walked into their boss and said, `I am gay' or `I
engage in homosexual or bisexual activity,''' Gibson said,
</P>
<P>
   SLDN officials countered that the Air Force actively roots out
gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have also heard that spin before from the Air Force,'' said
Michelle Benecke, co-director of SLDN, which provides legal aid to
troops tossed from the military under the policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real reason for gay discharges is that commanders continue
to ask, pursue and harass people whom they suspect are gay,'' she
contended.
</P>
<P>
   Figures were not available Friday for the Navy and Marine Corps,
but the number of homosexual discharges in those branches has risen
since the policy's inception, according to Benecke.
</P>
<P>
   The result of a bruising battle among the White House, the Joint
Chiefs of Staff and Congress, the ``don't ask, don't tell, don't
pursue'' policy means that homosexual activity is banned in the
military, but that gays and lesbians may serve as long as they keep
quiet about their sexual orientation and aren't caught engaged in
homosexual acts.
</P>
<P>
   Commanders may not inquire of a service member's sexual
orientation, according to the rules. However, they may do so if
they have ``credible information'' that a service member engages in
homosexual conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Pentagon efforts to clarify the policy, homosexual
rights organizations maintain that gays and lesbians in the ranks
who conceal their sexuality are routinely drummed out.
</P>
<P>
   C. Dixon Osburn, co-executive director for SLDN, said, ``The new
numbers suggest that rather than providing any kind of relief for
gay people under this policy, commanders are going after people
even more fervently.''
</P>
<P>
   The policy ``has intensified the ousting of people thought to be
gay or lesbian,'' said Rob Blanchard, a San Antonio-based state
vice president of the Log Cabin Republicans, a nationwide group of
15,000 gays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
