<HEADER>
A4338 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-JASPER-DOCUMENTARY     01-22 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JASPER-DOCUMENTARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS DEATH SPARKS TV REPORT ON WHITE SUPREMACY IN U.S. 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Documentary airs Monday night) 
 
By MIKE McDANIEL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It started with a small article in a London newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   BBC journalist Zab Chughtai read the story last June about the
horrific death of Jasper, Texas, resident James Byrd Jr. How he was
walking home from visiting relatives. How he was accosted, beaten
and chained by his ankles to a pickup. How he was dragged for two
miles, leaving a trail of blood and flesh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born after the civil rights struggle,'' said Chughtai,
31, ``and I didn't expect to read the story of a dragging-to-death
of a man apparently because of the color of his skin. Not in my
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a story that crossed national boundaries _ racial
problems are not only something Americans are suffering from. James
Byrd's murder led me to research the white supremacy movement in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   The product of her research is ``A Murder in Texas: Hate on
Trial,'' a one-hour documentary to air Monday night on Discovery
Channel. The report is remarkably deep in sources and includes rare
interviews with William Pierce, author of the notorious ``The
Turner Diaries''; Richard Butler, founder of the neo-Nazi group
Aryan Nations; and Charles Lee, grand dragon of the Texas Knights
of the Ku Klux Klan.
</P>
<P>
   Even more remarkable: Chughtai got those racists to speak to
her, the daughter of Pakistani parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I rang the white supremacy organizations and got through
to their leaders, I obviously had to be straight with them, and I
told them my name was Zab,'' said Chughtai. ``It's clearly not an
Anglo-Saxon name, despite my English accent. (She was born in
northern England.) In fact, the English accent comes with a brown
face.''
</P>
<P>
   Her concern, she said, was not a fear for her safety as much as
a fear that the project would be jeopardized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not want to lose the interviews, nor did I want the
interviewees to self-edit when they had to sit and answer questions
from someone with black hair, black eyes and a brown face,'' she
said. (Her crew _ producer, cameraman, sound man _ was white.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the characters I spoke to were interested in whether I
was dark-skinned or olive-skinned or pale-skinned.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Chughtai won them over. She believes she succeeded
because she was straight with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them that I'm a storyteller trying to tell a story,
that my race is completely irrelevant as far as I am concerned and
it should be irrelevant to you.''
</P>
<P>
   She guaranteed them nothing, and no money changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she said, ``the issue of money was raised, but you
can't pay these people to talk, nor can you promise that certain
things will not be used. You have to be completely straight. I
couldn't afford not to be. Ultimately they will see this
documentary, and they're dangerous characters.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from espousing the views of white supremacists, ``Murder in
Texas'' is balanced by interviews with the likes of NAACP chairman
Julian Bond, Southern Poverty Law Center counsel Morris Dees,
Jewish Defense League chairman Irv Rubin, New Black Panthers
founder Aaron Michaels, and Bob Blizter, chief of the FBI's
domestic terrorism bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Chughtai visited with Patrick Petrick, a former member of the
Aryan Brotherhood _ he has the white-power tattoos to prove it _
who has become a Christian and today calls prison in Huntsville,
Texas, home. She talked with the Rev. Claude E. Payne, bishop of
the Episcopal Diocese of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Powerfully and purposefully, ``Murder in Texas'' leads with the
murder of Byrd; we retrace the yellow-chalked road on which he was
dragged. Using footage from KPRC-TV, Houston's NBC affiliate, we
are introduced to his alleged killers, one of whom _ John William
``Bill'' King _ is facing trial next week.
</P>
<P>
   The report also begins with brief remarks from James Byrd's
sister, Clara Taylor, and daughter, Renee Mullins. Mullins recounts
how her father's body was so torn up _ his head and right arm were
dismembered _ that his casket had to be closed at the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Said Chughtai, ``She said to me _ this is not in the film _ `I
served in the U.S. military because I felt that the enemy was
outside my borders. But the enemy is within.'''
</P>
<P>
   The documentary then dives in deep, demarcating battle lines
separating sides of what NAACP's Bond calls a ``low-level race
war.'' Though small in number _ estimates are that the white
supremacist movement has 100,000 U.S. members, ``with a reach to
sympathizers of 1 million'' _ civil rights proponents treat their
rhetoric with deadly seriousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be black in America today is to be constantly on the alert
for real and sometimes imagined slights that come your way,'' says
Bond.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because they're seen less often, the appearances of
Pierce, Butler and Lee leave an indelible impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a patriotic person,'' says Pierce, ``but I feel no sense
of loyalty to government. I'm only concerned with my own people,
people of European ancestry.''
</P>
<P>
   Messages of hate come from both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to strangle them (his opponents) if I can,'' says
Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   The report, disturbingly illustrated with modern-day
cross-burnings and salutes to Hitler, also taps into the
supremacists' use of the Internet, and the Christian Identity
church movement, which says racial purity is Bible-based.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, it also recounts the Branch Davidian fiasco of
1994 in Waco, Texas, and the Oklahoma City bombing of 1995. ``The
Turner Diaries'' comes up here, with Dees linking the book to the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The book, the story of a race war in America targeting blacks,
Jews and the government, has been called by the FBI ``the bible of
the racist right.'' Timothy McVeigh, convicted in the Oklahoma City
bombing, is said to have had many copies of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised if the people who have engaged in strikes
against the government have in many cases read `The Turner
Diaries,''' says Pierce. ``In the case of the three ex-convicts in
Texas,'' he says, speaking of the men charged with Byrd's death,
``I may be surprised that any of them can even read. They seem
pretty much like a low-life crew ... I don't believe in many cases
(The Turner Diaries) inspires people to violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Chughtai said she was surprised she found the supremacists
``charmingly disarming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These men lead the movement because they inspire, and you can
see from the film that some people may think what they're saying is
frighteningly possible. It's because they're charmingly disarming
that they're dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   They were charming, but they could also be combative ``during
moments when they clearly didn't like the line of questioning that
I had to pursue,'' she said. ``I mean, this is not a propaganda
film, a platform for them to advertise their views.''
</P>
<P>
   The white supremacy movement, Chughtai warned, ``doesn't simply
target the lone African-American walking home late at night. They
are anti-Semitic, anti-abortion, anti-affirmative action, anti-race
mixing and anti-gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The First and Second Amendments (of the Constitution) define
the dream of democratic freedom, but the consequence of that kind
of freedom is that you do have a constitutional right to hate,''
she said. ``You don't have a constitutional right to hurt somebody.
It's the gray area in between that I think we should address.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 1301EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
