<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4353 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS     01-22 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEBTV'S CHAT ABILITIES LIMITED SINCE DEVICE CAN'T RUN PROGRAMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I just got WebTV, and several of my friends are on America
Online. Is there any way that we can talk to each other in chat
rooms or with instant messages?
</P>
<P>
   A: The short answer is no. WebTV, while a computer of sorts, is
not one that has all the capabilities of a traditional PC. It
cannot run programs other than the specialized software used to
access the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   However, this may change with future versions of WebTV. And
there are ways you can communicate _ other than via e-mail _ though
they're somewhat klunky.
</P>
<P>
   If you had a traditional PC, and you were not on America Online,
you could chat with your AOL friends using Instant Messenger. This
program, which I've touted before, is an excellent piece of
freeware that lets you chat one-on-one with AOL subscribers, or
with anyone who has the program. The latest version, 2.0, lets you
set up multi-person chats. You can get it at www.aol.com/aim/. It's
free, but you do have to register to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Once you do, you can also use another feature called QuickBuddy,
at www.aol.com/netmail/quickbuddy/about.html. This uses Java _ a
programming language supported by most PC Web browsers _ to run a
streamlined version of Instant Messenger.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the browser on WebTV doesn't support Java. WebTV
executives, after first saying they would not offer Java support,
said in December that they are trying to find a way to add it. If
it comes, it will only be available on WebTV Plus, not the older
WebTV Classic boxes.
</P>
<P>
   One thing to keep in mind: WebTV is owned by Microsoft, which is
involved in a bitter court dispute with Java creator Sun
Microsystems over Java. As a result, it's questionable just how
hard Microsoft will try to get Java into WebTV.
</P>
<P>
   There's a workaround, however. There are several sites on the
Web that offer chat rooms that don't require a Java-capable
browser. For example, Talk City at www.talkcity.com has an area
called EZ Talk Web. Have your AOL friends go there and meet you.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You recently discussed the differences in various kinds of
removable drives, like a Zip or an LS-120. I just bought a new
computer with a big hard drive, and I wanted to look at one of
these as a backup system. But to back up a 14-gigabyte hard drive
with a Zip drive, which uses just 100-megabyte disks, would be
almost as bad as using floppies! What do you think is the best
solution for backing up a big hard disk?
</P>
<P>
   A: Neither a 100-megabyte Iomega Zip drive nor a 120-megabyte
LS-120 drive are suitable for a full backup of a drive that big.
While you likely won't fill it all the way up right at first, even
1 gigabyte of space requires 10 Zip disks. At about $10-$15 apiece,
that gets pricey.
</P>
<P>
   You could go with an Iomega Jaz drive, which holds 1 or 2
gigabytes, but those are expensive, too. A 1-gigabyte disk costs
about $100; a 2-gigabyte disk about $125.
</P>
<P>
   A tape drive may be your most cost-effective choice, though tape
is notoriously flaky when it comes to restoring from a backup, and
you can't use it for general storage. A 10-gigabyte tape cartridge
will run about $35, making it a real bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Some readers have suggested that buying a second big drive and
using it only to backup a main drive is a good idea, given how
cheap new hard drives are today. This makes backing up easy: just
drag and drop between drives to store a backup. Or, you can use
commercial backup software to create a compressed backup on the
extra drive.
</P>
<P>
   However, hard drives have a siren song _ eventually, you'll want
to put other things on that drive, and use it for day-to-day
computing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
