<HEADER>
A4363 &Cx1f; taf-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIGS-AS-DRUG-FACTORIE     01-22 0320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIGS-AS-DRUG-FACTORIES-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USING PIGS AS DRUG FACTORIES  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., JAN. 25, 1999)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By PHILIP COHEN  
 Copyright 1999 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Drugs could one day be harvested from the semen of genetically
engineered pigs, Canadian researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   Most people experimenting with transgenic animals that produce
therapeutic proteins are looking at females, with the idea of
purifying the drugs from the animals' milk. But Fran ois Pothier of
Laval University in Quebec believes that male pigs could produce
enough protein in their semen for it to rival milk.
</P>
<P>
   Semen naturally has a much higher protein content than milk,
Pothier says, and a boar can ejaculate up to half a liter at a
time. Boars also begin producing semen at the tender age of 110
days, well before cows or ewes can start producing milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very easy to get a pig to ejaculate,'' Pothier adds.
``They will mount anything that faintly looks like a sow.''
</P>
<P>
   Pothier and his colleagues have already completed a pilot study
in mice engineered to produce human growth hormone. One male
produced more than 10 micrograms of the protein in each milliliter
of his ejaculate. This is still less than levels found in the milk
of transgenic animals, but Pothier is sure it will be possible to
achieve much higher levels by tinkering with the techniques used to
insert the drug-producing genes. He plans to start testing the
technique in boars next month. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 1316EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
