A4374 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-22 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTHY ECONOMY CONCEALS JOB LOSSES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ E.T. Johnson, a lubricator inspector for the new
Pasadena Paper Co., is feeling the pinch of foreign competition.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston-area company Johnson used to work for, the Simpson
Pasadena Paper Co., shut its doors Wednesday after losing money for
years going up against cheaper foreign imports.
</P>
<P>
   The assets were sold to the Belgravia Paper Co. of Canada, which
turned around and rehired 300 of the 660 workers, including
Johnson, to run just one part of the mill.
</P>
<P>
   Though Johnson has a job _ in fact, the same job he used to have
at Simpson _ his salary has been cut almost $2 an hour, going from
$21.31 to $19.35.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not all.
</P>
<P>
   His benefit pension plan was eliminated along with his premium
pay for nighttime work. He lost two weeks of vacation time and
he'll have to pick up a hunk of his health insurance costs after
paying virtually nothing _ benefits that, all together, he figures
are worth another $3 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   All told, Johnson figures he won't make up the shortfall during
the six-year contract, which calls for annual wage increases
between 1 and 2 percent. The loss of the traditional pension is the
most troubling to Johnson, who is 48.
</P>
<P>
   That workers should be facing a pay cut after a year in which
average hourly earnings rose 3.8 percent is ironic.
</P>
<P>
   For most people, that means there is more money to jingle in
their pockets, a fact that isn't lost on Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere you turn, people are talking about the good economy,
he said. Low interest rates, low inflation, solid growth. For lots
of people, that has meant job security and solid wage gains.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson's story shows that statistics aren't everything,
that even in a good economy, some workers will take a hit.
Statistics that show job growth and wages are up or that
unemployment is down are meaningful only in the abstract.
</P>
<P>
   In the real workaday world, workers like Johnson in vulnerable
industries are going to get hurt _ no matter how good the economy
may be.
</P>
<P>
   He has already lived through four downsizings at the plant so
right now, and in this industry, he knows he's lucky that he has a
job.
</P>
<P>
   For most Houstonians today, Johnson's experience is rare.
Compared with the mid-1980s, relatively few can say they know
someone who's been laid off or had to take a pay cut. But Anthony
Chan, managing director and chief economist for Banc One Investment
Advisors in Columbus, Ohio, says Johnson's story is a sign of
things to come.
</P>
<P>
   The low inflationary environment has made it practically
impossible for companies to increase prices, especially when they
go up against lower-priced imports pouring in from economically
depressed Asia. So while consumer prices increased 1.6 percent last
year, the tight labor market forced companies to boost average
hourly wages by 3.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That gap has squeezed profits, Chan said, and companies almost
have no choice but to cut wages or workers.
</P>
<P>
   Look for more signs of wage cuts in a wide variety of
industries, Chan predicted.
</P>
<P>
   The new owners of the paper plant bristle at the idea that
workers are not faring well under the new ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty percent of the plant's profits will go toward increasing
employee wages by 10 percent, said John Cowan, vice president of
Belgravia.
</P>
<P>
   After that, 10 percent of the profits will be distributed to
employees. The company operates a coated paper machine that
supplies between 40 and 50 percent of the paper used for making
labels in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not unreasonable to ask employees to pay 20 percent of
their health insurance coverage, Cowan said. And he touts the
401(k) plan as offering more flexibility in planning for retirement
than the traditional annuity plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to compete, we had to restructure the business here,''
Cowan said. ``We're pleased to work out a business plan that saves
300 jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the economic realities, it's hard to give wages and
benefits back when all you hear is that car sales are soaring, home
sales are at record highs and consumers are spending freely because
they feel confident.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Bray doesn't feel that same confidence. He got a job with
the new plant and, like Johnson, will be earning $2 less an hour as
a lubricator inspector.
</P>
<P>
   Bray said that he and his wife will cut corners where they can:
fewer restaurant meals, fewer weekend jaunts and less money to
spend on Bray's beloved coin and stamp collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of progressing, I'm regressing,'' said the 52-year-old
Bray. ``But what can we do?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
L.M. Sixel can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to lm.sixel(at)chron.com, or call (713)
220-2000 and enter access code 1002. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
