<HEADER>
A4376 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-HEART-HNS     01-22 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-HEART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIXED FEELINGS ABOUT `HEART' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some bits and pieces of ``Playing by Heart'' are delightful.
Some bits and pieces are not.
</P>
<P>
   As proof, here are a few of the delightful bits:
</P>
<P>
   _ Watching Gena Rowlands dance with Sean Connery.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hearing Dennis Quaid, telling a stranger about his failed job
as an ABC exec (``I'm responsible for all those (bleep) shows that
you don't watch on Thursday nights''), complain that his wife left
him for a guy at NBC.
</P>
<P>
   _ Watching Angelina Jolie buzz, beelike, in pursuit of Ryan
Phillippe.
</P>
<P>
   _ Watching an entire magazine rack fall on Gillian Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Next, just to balance things out, here are a few of the
less-delightful bits:
</P>
<P>
   _ Watching Ryan Phillippe mope.
</P>
<P>
   _ Watching Anthony Edwards mope.
</P>
<P>
   _ Watching Gillian Anderson mope (pre- and post-magazine rack).
</P>
<P>
   _ Watching Jon Stewart pine for Gillian Anderson, mopes and all.
</P>
<P>
   _ Watching Jay Mohr die in the arms of Ellen Burstyn.
</P>
<P>
   If you gather from these collected bits that ``Playing by
Heart'' is a hit-or-miss ensemble piece about love and emotional
fragility, you gather correctly. If you gather that Gillian
Anderson is the most irritating thing in the film, you also gather
correctly. (``Call me nuts, but I really like you,'' Stewart's
character tells her. OK, fella. You're nuts.)
</P>
<P>
   If, however, you gather that writer-producer-director Willard
Carroll (``Tom's Midnight Garden'') has a cynical view of the
mating game, you are mistaken. Carroll is above all an optimist,
and where ``Playing by Heart'' shines _ where it rises above
misfired casting and awkward navelgazing _ is in its simplest
moments, in little touches of vulnerability and affection that dot
the landscape of all relationships.
</P>
<P>
   If there's a moral to the story, it's that everybody has a tale
to tell: By the film's close, each character in this romantic
roundelay is given a chance to spill the beans, to face up to (or
face down) some past, festering wound. Honesty breeds hope. Hope
breeds love. And love, as we all know, breeds happy endings.
</P>
<P>
   Riding this swirl of emotion are four couples: Paul and Hannah
(Connery and Rowlands), a comfy older pair whose marriage sports a
few new cracks; Meredith and Trent (Anderson and Stewart), a newly
dating duo who suffer from an advanced case of egg-head
self-analysis (they argue about a relationship they don't even have
yet); Gracie and Roger (Madeleine Stowe and Anthony Edwards), an
adulterous pair who keep each other at a cool emotional distance;
and Joan and Keenan (Jolie and Phillippe), not-quite friends in a
maybe-relationship built on desperate bickering about Keenan's
reluctance to date.
</P>
<P>
   Also getting screen time are Hugh (Quaid, breathtakingly
malleable), a loner who snakes through one bar after another with a
wildly mutating story, and two additional characters thrown in to
squeeze tears: Mark (Mohr), who's dying of AIDS-related illnesses,
and his loving mom, Mildred (Burstyn).
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing by Heart'' has a good deal to recommend it, most of
all a script that's jammed with crisp, asymmetrical dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   (Paul to Hannah: ``Calm down! You're overwrought!'' Hannah to
Paul: ``I am perfectly wrought! I think, under the circumstances, I
am underwrought!'')
</P>
<P>
   Connery and Rowlands deliver their lines with a delicious,
sophisticated wisdom, while Jolie does her perpetual-motion routine
with loopy-innocent zeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't want to see her _ but he doesn't want her to be
dismembered in underground parking,'' she says, as the sullen
Keenan walks her through a shadowed lot.
</P>
<P>
   It's cute; they're cute; the movie's cute. The parts that aren't
struggle from lousy chemistry (the Stewart-Anderson pairing) or
bare-bones plotting (the Stowe-Edwards pairing), an unsurprising
flaw in a movie loaded with primary and secondary characters.
</P>
<P>
   But you have to hand it to Carroll: He's made a sweet film about
the tartness of courtship, and he's made it with an absolute lack
of irony.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ain't no disco, and I don't want no `Cryin' Game'
confusion,'' says a drag queen to the chameleon Hugh. It isn't. And
there won't be. And for the time being, with one small film, that's
just fine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
