<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMOUS-COP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETIRED COP REMAINS CAPTIVATED BY NORMAN ROCKWELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Massachusetts, Vermont)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE HUREWITZ  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLIFTON PARK, N.Y. _ Retired policeman Dick Clemens is not
boastful about his likeness that was captured by a renowned artist
for future generations to admire.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, depicted in his police uniform in a classic 1958
Saturday Evening Post cover by artist Norman Rockwell called ``The
Runaway,'' doesn't think of it as conferring any kind of
immortality.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the important one, not me,'' said Clemens, who is so
modest he declined to have his picture taken.
</P>
<P>
   But his image as a young man has become an American icon. He is
the Massachusetts state trooper shown on a counter stool buying an
ice cream for a grateful and somewhat chagrined young boy.
</P>
<P>
   The illustration has become a symbol of the kinder and gentler
side of police work and an era when law enforcers were widely
respected. Little wonder it can be found hanging in police stations
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   New York State Police Supt. James W. McMahon said the
illustration was a tribute to both police work and Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Norman Rockwell captures the real essence of police work and
public service _ community, concern, compassion and a commitment to
helping others,'' McMahon said. ``Knowing Dick Clemens personally,
I feel Rockwell could not have found anyone more committed to those
values.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably among Rockwell's better known works,'' said Bea
Snyder, a spokeswoman for the Norman Rockwell Museum at
Stockbridge, the Massachusetts institute where the original is on
display.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably all of us at one time in our wild youth had the
fantasy of running away because their mother didn't give them a
peanut butter and jelly sandwich or something. This plays into that
idea plus the other of the policeman as the friendly figure who is
going to befriend and help you.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder said Rockwell never hired professional models. Instead he
used friends and neighbors. He once had his studio on Main Street
in Stockbridge, but he became so distracted looking out the window
for potential models that he had to move it, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens was tabbed to be that figure largely because he was
Rockwell's neighbor in Stockbridge. The artist lived in the village
the last 25 years of his life, and as he had done previously in
Arlington, Vt., painted likenesses of those he encountered in his
daily life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived about three houses apart from him and his dog would
periodically run over and visit my house, and I would return it,''
said Clemens, who gives his age only as ``over 60.'' He said
Rockwell telephoned him one day and said he had an idea for a Post
cover involving a police officer and asked if he would pose for
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very pleased he would ask. He was a very nice man,''
Clemens said.
</P>
<P>
   He got permission from his bosses and in the spring of 1958 sat
with two other people behind the counter of a Howard Johnson's
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell took photographs and oversaw the arrangement of several
poses, the whole session lasting ``a couple of hours,'' Clemens
said.
</P>
<P>
   The artistic process, including sketches, went all the way to
the color study, the last step before painting, when Rockwell
decided to change it, according to Snyder. He changed the young
counterman to an older figure, and changed the Howard Johnson's
into more of a country diner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We chatted a little bit about it,'' Clemens said. ``He said he
wanted it a little more rustic so you would have the impression the
kid got a little further out of town. And he changed the counterman
because he wanted more of an age contrast.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens said he marvels at the craftsmanship in this
illustration as in Rockwell's others.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the ability to portray the small details _ the laces on
my boots, the notebook in my back pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens said his superiors called to thank Rockwell for choosing
the subject, and the artist responded by inviting Clemens and his
boss to dinner. And at the request of the Massachusetts State
Police, he painted Clemens in a winter uniform so the department
could use it for its Christmas cards. A copy of that work is at the
Rockwell Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens retired from the state police around 1975, then he went
to work for the General Electric Co.'s plant in Pittsfield, Mass.
In 1984 he became head of plant security at GE's Power Systems
plant in Schenectady, N.Y., and moved to nearby Clifton Park.
</P>
<P>
   He occasionally lectures at the Rockwell Museum about his
encounters with the artist.
</P>
<P>
   But he guards his privacy when it comes to detailing much of his
personal feelings. He said the reactions of his two married
daughters and three grandchildren are ``personal to me.'' Clemens
has a copy of the illustration in his house. But he said it is not
even his favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of those I like best is `Freedom From Want' where
everybody is sitting around having dinner and mother is bringing in
a turkey and putting it down. If you look closely,'' he said in a
tone of awe, ``everybody sitting at the table has a glass in front
of them. And every glass has water and in the water, there's ice.
That's the kind of detail he could paint.''
</P>
<P>
   But he knows ``The Runaway'' is a favorite of police officers
and that gives him a special joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of that. There are a lot of dedicated people in law
enforcement. They do a very difficult job under very difficult
circumstances. And I hope that this helps build respect for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
