<SLUG> BC-SANDERS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME FOR SENATE TO BRING IMPEACHMENT NONSENSE TO AN END
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB RAY SANDERS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somewhere over the Capitol in Washington, I hear the voice of
former Cowboys quarterback and sports commentator Don Meredith
singing the refrain:
</P>
<P>
   ``Turn out the lights, the party's over.''
</P>
<P>
   This torch the House Republicans have been carrying for
impeaching the president, and having him removed from office, is
about to go out.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few days, we'll see Republicans in the Senate
folding faster than bad poker hands and looking for a way out of
the dilemma in which they now find themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The president should never have been impeached in the first
place, but the majority party was hellbent on ramming this
constitutional charade down our throats in the name of ``the rule
of law.''
</P>
<P>
   For months I've been waiting for the Republicans to come to
their senses, but their blind obsession keeps them from seeing that
they are no match for this popular president. Every time they go
after William Jefferson Clinton with a vengeance, they end up
hurting themselves.
</P>
<P>
   They insisted on a trial so they once again could recount the
sordid details in independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report,
refusing to accept the fact that the public was tired of the
scandal and was ready to see it end. The prosecutors from the House
even demanded witnesses in order to make their weak case more
dramatic because there was no real substance.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time the president's defenders had made it just
halfway through their case this week, it was obvious that the House
managers were just that _ ``managers,'' attempting to manipulate a
conviction based on misleading ``facts'' and the most sinister
accounts of ``the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   As to the law, White House lawyer Cheryl D. Mills poignantly
told the attentive senators:
</P>
<P>
   ``If you love the rule of law, you must love it in all of its
applications. You cannot only love it when it provides the verdict
you seek; you must love it when the verdict goes against you, as
well. We cannot uphold the rule of law only when it is consistent
with our beliefs; we must uphold it even when it protects behavior
that we don't like or is unattractive, or is not admirable, or that
might even be hurtful. And we cannot say we love the rule of law
but dismiss arguments that appeal to the rule of law, as
`legalisms' or legal hair-splitting.' ''
</P>
<P>
   While House managers fought for microphones afterward to offer
some lame rebuttals, it was clear that many Republicans were
looking for a back door out of this last embarrassment for them.
</P>
<P>
   Even though some were still predicting that we'd see witnesses,
and that ``the trial of the century'' would perhaps continue until
early February, there were signs that Democrats would get the votes
to bring down the curtain on this farce _ sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   Even conservative evangelist Pat Robertson on ``The 700 Club,''
his TV program was singing the song from the Meredith hymnal:
``It's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying the president had hit a home run in his State of the
Union speech Tuesday night, Robertson added: ``From a public
relations standpoint, he's won. They might as well dismiss this
impeachment hearing and get on with something else, because it's
over as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Come Monday, expect a motion to dismiss. Then expect that
Republicans with the least to lose politically (and this doesn't
include Texans Phil Gramm and Kay Bailey Hutchison) to join Senate
Democrats in bringing an early end to this national distraction.
</P>
<P>
   It's about time.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ray Sanders is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7775, or e-mail:
bobray(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 1339EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4400 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-22 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL'S PROMISES OF REVENUE DON'T ADD UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1995, the steamrollers of the National Football League
flattened the city of Tampa. The local team, the Buccaneers, wanted
the public to pay for half of a new stadium. At the proper moment,
just when the local newspapers were filled with panic about the
team moving to Baltimore, Cleveland, Orlando or another city
desperate for a team, NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue said if Tampa
shared the costs, the league would give it a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL made Tampa feel it would be showered with dollar bills.
The league claimed that the 1995 Super Bowl in Miami generated
$364.9 million in economic activity for South Florida. Buccaneers
GM Rich McKay said, ``Nobody can argue with the direct impact of
the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   The steamrollers left little argument in their wake. The Tampa
Tribune accepted the NFL's claims to the point of boo-hooing in an
editorial, ``If the Bucs leave, there will never be another Super
Bowl here, with its $350 million boost to the local economy. If the
Bucs leave, we will never again have an NFL team.''
</P>
<P>
   The public passed a sales tax to help build the stadium. The
Buccaneers stayed. There will be a Super Bowl in Tampa in 2001. But
one man in Tampa remained curious about the claim that the Super
Bowl was worth a third of a trillion dollars, and the media's
assumption that this was irreplaceable money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL's argument did not make any sense if you start to
think about it,'' said Philip Porter, an economics professor at the
University of South Florida at Tampa. ``After all, this is the same
NFL that charges $5 for a hotdog. If there was truly $350 million
in economic impact, do you really think the NFL, the same league
that gets cities to pay for stadiums _ when no other businesses
could dream of having cities build factories for them _ would
really leave that money lying around for you and me?
</P>
<P>
   ``No. If there was truly economic impact, the NFL would have
grabbed the dollars before they even hit the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Porter went through 25 years of economic data. He zeroed in on
three Super Bowls in Miami, two in Tampa, and another in Phoenix.
In each case he found that the city's taxable sales or gross sales
in a Super Bowl January were no different than sales from any other
January. There was nothing to suggest that the economic impact of
the Super Bowl was an extra $364.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence showed that the impact was zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Super Bowl does is chase away people who would have
otherwise come for vacations or conventions,'' Porter said. ``Maybe
the Super Bowl brings three days of high-profile, big spenders. But
with no Super Bowl, you would have had people who would have come
to Florida or Arizona for two or three weeks for vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   Porter's study adds to the mounting evidence that publicly
funded stadiums are cash registers for owners and players, but red
tape for taxpayers. Besides tax and sales receipts, Porter found
several other barometers that deflate the NFL's claims of special
economic benefits to Super Bowl host cities.
</P>
<P>
   Porter found no evidence of an increase in tourism. There were
no extra airline flights during the Super Bowl month. Restaurants
reported no major surge in restaurant activity and golf resorts did
not hire extra staff that one would assume would be needed to
handle a sudden flood of wealthy executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that kind of impact was true, it would show up as a huge
spike on a graph,'' he said. In an upcoming study that echoes
studies by other economists, Porter has found no change in jobs,
unemployment or income when a city gains or loses an NFL team.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is going on is the NFL asks the people who come in for a
Super Bowl, `Tell me, what did you spend?' '' Porter said. ``You
get 140,000 people saying they spent $2,500 apiece. The NFL
concludes from that that the Super Bowl provides $350 million in
economic impact. They never look at the impact of the other 140,000
who would have been here anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Studies, of course, have not stopped greedy owners and
supplicant politicians from trying to convince the public that the
NFL is Santa Claus. The NFL claims that last January's Super Bowl
meant $295 million for greater San Diego. South Florida convention
officials say that the Super Bowl on Jan. 31 will pump $380 million
into Miami's local economy.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have not stopped states like Connecticut from throwing a
$374 million, publicly funded stadium at the New England Patriots.
Porter said studies will matter only when the politicians stop
being seduced. ``I don't fault the NFL,'' Porter said. ``They're
just trying to make money. It's the politicians. Right now, it
seems that if you're just a city councilor in a room with these
powerful owners, there is no resisting them, even if they are being
told self-serving lies.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
