<HEADER>
A4401 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-RAGTIME-BOS &LR;      01-22 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-RAGTIME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RAGTIME' WORTH THE WAIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
RAGTIME 
Musical in two acts. Music by Stephen Flaherty. Lyrics by Lynn
Ahrens. Book by Terrence McNally. Based on the novel by E.L.
Doctorow. 
Directed by Frank Galati. Choreography, Graciela Daniele. Set,
Eugene Lee. Costumes, Santo Loquasto. Lighting, Jules Fisher and
Peggy Eisenhauer. Presented by Pace Theatrical Group and Broadway
in Boston by arrangement with Livent. 
At: The Colonial Theatre, through March 28. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ ``Ragtime'' may go down as the musical worth going to
jail for. With Livent, the company that brought it into being, in
bankruptcy and Garth Drabinsky, Livent's cofounder, under
indictment, we should simply be thankful that this magnificent
musical got to Boston at all and that Jon Platt and the Pace
Theatrical Group had the wherewithal to get it to the Colonial
Theatre, where it fits both snugly and majestically.
</P>
<P>
   This has been the musical worth waiting for, one that plugs into
what made the form worth getting excited about in the first place _
glorious melodies you hum for days afterward and characters whose
fates seem as important as those of your family and friends. Add a
healthy respect for the audience's intelligence and you have every
reason to think that ``Ragtime'' has restored the greatness of the
American musical.
</P>
<P>
   E. L. Doctorow's 1974 novel that the musical was based on is one
of the singular achievements in American letters since the end of
World War II. With its clear but distanced prose and fascinating
blend of historical and fictional characters, ``Ragtime'' tells the
story of the American century, from the waves of European
immigration through the legacies of slavery to the celebrity
culture that so envelops us today. Central to the story are the
intersecting lives of three sets of characters: the white
Anglo-Saxon family that has all the benefits of class and power;
the Jewish immigrant Tateh and his daughter; and ragtime artist
Coalhouse Walker and Sarah, his fiancee.
</P>
<P>
   Does the musical do Doctorow justice? Although nuanced
development is now spelled out and what was written with subtlety
is now sung in capital letters, this is still very much Doctorow's
story, both in terms of plot and themes. Perhaps it's the change in
tone that brought forth a minority of naysayers, particularly when
``Ragtime'' was done on larger stages, but this, after all, is
music. One doesn't go to Verdi to find Shakespeare's poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky fielded an all-star team, most of it from off-Broadway
rather than on. He also held a song-writing competition that was
won by the little-known team of Stephen Flaherty and Lynn Ahrens
(``Once On This Island'') and the duo paid dividends. This is a
soundtrack not only loaded with hummable tunes, but the songs twist
and turn into and out of each other thematically with overwhelming
swirls.
</P>
<P>
   The best in this superb bunch is ``New Music,'' which starts out
as a lament by Father, the head of the WASP family. To him, ragtime
represents a loss of understanding about what's happening in
America. His wife picks up the tune, and to her it represents
liberation from stultification. The chorus joins in and croons
appreciatively until the black couple turn it into a passionate
love song that transforms everyone onstage. If you were doing a
medley of great scenes from the history of musicals, this quartet
with chorus would have to be in there.
</P>
<P>
   The music in ``Ragtime'' can be almost too overwhelming. No
sooner have we caught our breath from ``New Music'' than Coalhouse
and Sarah are off on another anthem, ``Wheels of a Dream,'' in
which the couple's optimism in America is boundless. Anyone
familiar with the novel knows what happens to that optimism. What
Doctorow and the musical do so well is dramatize the struggle for
assimilation and identity. Tateh, the Jewish immigrant, has his own
battle in keeping his daughter from starving or freezing, but is
ultimately allowed his corner of success. Walker, as much as he
would love to assimilate, has the door closed on him.
</P>
<P>
   Among the onstage talent in New York were three of the brightest
young musical stars of the American stage _ Audra McDonald, Brian
Stokes Mitchell, and Marin Mazzie. This production doesn't have
that firepower, but it's nevertheless a fine ensemble that belts
these songs out beautifully. Rebecca Eichenberger as Mother and
Theresa Tova as Emma Goldman are particularly impressive. In one
very important regard, ``Ragtime'' is better in Boston than in New
York. The musical fits the Colonial whereas it tended to get
dwarfed by Ford Theatre. Graciela Daniele's choreography is the
chief beneficiary.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the measure, though, this production of ``Ragtime''
delivers the goods. A great American novel has become a great
American musical. As Tateh says, ``I like this music. It makes me
want to do cartwheels.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
