<SLUG> BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEINZ INDEX: HE'S RUNNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can you picture Teresa Heinz as the next Hillary Clinton,
working side by side with her husband, the new president, on the
crucial matters of state such as housing affordability and fixing
the country's retirement system?
</P>
<P>
   It's a good bet she can.
</P>
<P>
   While the political pundits watch to see if John Kerry will
establish an exploratory committee for a presidential run and wait
to see if Al Gore slips in the polls, I've got my eye on another
indicator: Teresa Heinz.
</P>
<P>
   And the Heinz Index is flashing a bright green GO!
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking green as in the color of her money, though
there's no shortage of that either, which could come in handy. No,
the political types have been missing the signals, which have
playing out right under their noses.
</P>
<P>
   In an era when we vote for couples, not just presidents, Heinz
can more than hold up her end of the ticket. She is a serious woman
with serious credentials, and she's adding to them like a candidate
in waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Just before Christmas she was on the Globe's editorial opinion
page, urging employers to give ``the gift of security'' by opening
a retirement account for their employees. ``We are a nation without
a retirement policy,'' she wrote. ``The result: Poverty is turning
many people's golden years into a nightmare of hardship and dashed
expectations.'' Two weeks before the prospective First Couple
virtually owned the Sunday Globe.
</P>
<P>
   The lead story in the paper that day _ a Globe exclusive _
reported how the high cost of living in Massachusetts was driving
away young people and causing a shortage of workers that could
jeopardize the state's economy. The report, funded by the $1.6
billion Heinz Family Foundation and initiated by Heinz herself, was
accompanied that morning by the lead editorial fretting about a
``brain drain'' of skilled workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never mind the Bay State; we have become the Pay State,'' the
editorial worried.
</P>
<P>
   A pretty impressive one-two orchestration, but the Heinz-Kerrys
did even better that day: On the page just opposite the Heinz
editorial was an opinion piece by Senator Kerry, scolding those who
would deny the dangers of global warming.
</P>
<P>
   Can you imagine what it must have been like that Sunday morning
in the antique four-poster bed on Louisburg Squarewith the Globe
spread out all over the goose-down comforter? Bill and Hill must
have had those kind of days back in Little Rock as they plotted
their way to the White House, many years and many Monicas ago.
</P>
<P>
   Heinz's interest in important topics is hardly new. Her causes
have run from the environment to nuclear disarmament to the arts.
The foundations and endowments she oversees give away $70 million
per year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, she weighed running for the Senate after the death of
her husband, Republican John Heinz. The only thing new in
speculation about Heinz's interest in the White House is that this
time she and her husband would be running as Democrats.``Does she
picture herself as an effective Hillary? Sure,'' says one of those
who has worked closely with Heinz recently.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I may have it all wrong. Heinz may not be prepping
for a presidential run at all. Considering her recent focus on
things like housing affordability and the retirement system, she
may be angling for her own column on the business page. But, I
don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cocktail Weenies
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hirsch is a guy who can take a punch. The Boston-based Wall
Street Journal writer who lost his job in a reporting goof during
the Mike Barnicle affair this summer has a new project: He's
writing an authorized biography of Rubin ``Hurricane'' Carter, the
middleweight who went to jail for 19 years for a triple murder he
didn't commit. In all, four publishers bid for the book, which was
sold to Boston's Houghton Mifflin. Hirsch's timing couldn't be
better: His book should be out about the same time a new Denzel
Washington film on Carter is arriving at a theater near you. That
should help sales.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steve Bailey's e-mail address is s(underscore)bailey(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
