<SLUG> BC-TENNIS-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KORDA FINDS LITTLE AMUSEMENT IN CARNIVAL ATMOSPHERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE _ The Carrot Sticks, waddling and wailing in their
Netherlands-orange war paint and sheaths, are in town. So are the
costumed Vikings (Swedish, not Minnesotan), as well as the Mary
Pierce and Anna Kournikova impersonators: blonde-wigged guys in
tennis dresses identical to those worn by their heroines.
</P>
<P>
   Screamers and dancers all, boisterous backers of their
racket-flapping gods and goddesses, they are among the flavors of
fun that make the Australian Open the best take of the four majors.
Stacked up against this carnival, the French, Wimbledon, and US
Open are prayer meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Petr Korda's prayer a year ago was to win a major championship
before his sometimes-brilliant career ran out. He was 30, had been
a French finalist six years before, and needed help _ which he got
from Karol Kucera, eliminator of Pete Sampras, and Marcelo Rios,
swooner in the 6-2, 6-2, 6-2, final.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something I always dreamed of, winning one of the big
titles,'' said Korda. ``I was afraid I might be too late.''
</P>
<P>
   You'd think, then, that his Melbourne reappearance as reigning
king, ranked world No. 21, would be hailed as a glorious return.
Instead it's a nightmare. He's been enveloped in a hailstorm of
disapproval from his colleagues on the men's tour, virtually all of
them feeling that Korda shouldn't be here at all. They think he
should be serving a year's suspension after testing positive for a
steroid called nandrolone at Wimbledon six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   He got off lightly. Convincing investigators that he honestly
didn't know how the stuff _ which usually must be injected _ wound
up in his skinny body, Korda lost only the prize money and computer
points earned at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Courier, the champ of 1992-93 and highly respected in the
locker room, is one of the objectors to Korda's understandably
nervous presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider Petr a friend, the last guy I'd suspect,'' said
Courier. ``But until he can come up with a believable explanation _
which he hasn't _ I think he should be out, the rules followed.''
</P>
<P>
   Then warming to the subject, Courier raised the specter of blood
doping and drugs like EPO of bicycle-racing infamy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are guys playing 35 tournaments, and I know I couldn't
do it _ and I train very hard,'' he said. ``They may be getting
some help, and I'd be very PO'd if they had an illegal advantage
and beat me.''
</P>
<P>
   Denials from officialdom flew, and it is a fact that tennis has
suffered few drug embarrassments. A Spanish nonentity, Ignacio
Truyol, was ruled off for a year after flunking the test. Why not
Korda?
</P>
<P>
   One of his few defenders, No. 6 Andre Agassi, the current
betting favorite (6-1) to win this increasingly toothless,
seed-bleeding men's tourney, astutely points out that most of his
colleagues aren't up to date on the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a change,'' said Agassi. ``You aren't thrown out
automatically as Truyol was. You can appeal, and Korda is
appealing. Maybe he's guilty, but he deserves the appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   In the limbo of an unappealing situation, Korda also suffered a
dissing by his first-round victim, Spaniard Galo Blanco, who
avoided shaking hands at the fifth-set conclusion. Blanco accused
Korda of another kind of ``cheating'' _ faking an injury. If so, it
was a rather elaborate fake. Falling hard in the third set, Korda
twisted his left ankle, requiring strapping by a trainer during a
subsequent injury timeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran like a deer after that,'' said Blanco.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can look at my ankle _ black and yellow,'' said Korda.
</P>
<P>
   It still was after he beat another Spaniard, Julian Alonso,
Thursday to set up a date with American Todd Martin Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A more subtle form of disrespect for Korda has been displayed by
the tournament organizers, denying the champion a main-stadium gig
thus far, keeping him on the outskirts where a few spectators have
taunted him.
</P>
<P>
   Stretching to his full, bristle-haired 6 feet 3 inches, the
embroiled Czech said, ``My father taught me to keep my head up
highest when things are worst. I must face reality, and be glad to
put two wins together. It's been a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Loser of 13 of 14 matches in one post-Wimbledon stretch, and his
position in the top 10, Korda seemed distressed most to learn that
his Davis Cup teammates _ Daniel Vacek, Slava Dosedel, Bohdan
Ulihrach _ said he had disgraced Czech tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Although the male precinct began to come apart even before the
first ball was swatted, that wasn't going to keep record daily
crowds of 40,000-plus away from the good-old-summertime, party-time
atmosphere of Melbourne Park. Pete Sampras, trying to manage a
midlife crisis, was a no-show. Marcelo Rios and Goran Ivaniseveic
pleaded aching backs at the starting gate and the dreaded Spanish
armada of 14 gunboats (Nos. 3-5-14 Alex Corretja, Carlos Moya,
Albert Costa included) sprang early leaks and were on the bottom by
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Then a rookie qualifier from Rockville, Md., No. 187 Paul
Goldstein, toppled 1997 US Open runner-up, No. 8 Greg Rusedski,
6-4, 6-7 (9-11), 7-6 (7-5), 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   The price is right for the hordes. So are their countryman, the
revivalist Aussies led by US Open champ, No. 3 Patrick Rafter, and
finalist, No. 14 Mark Philippoussis, whose rousing,
3-hour-45-minute win over a rejuvenated Michael Chang was the best
match here in years. Not to mention the exciting Lleyton Hewitt, a
17-year-old who demolished No. 15 Cedric Pioline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 1349EST &QL; 
