</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS DON'T KNOW WHAT HIT 'EM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I know they've had record snowload in Buffalo, but how can 6,000
Buffalonians just disappear?
</P>
<P>
   There were ``more than 21,000'' folks cheering the Clintons and
the Gores there the day after the State of the Union speech, said
The Boston Globe. Naw, there were only ``about 15,000,'' said The
New York Times, which still called it ``a rock star reception.''
But who's counting crowds or poll numbers? The only number that
really counts for Clinton is 67 in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   His big speech (98 applause interruptions for 67-odd new policy
announcements in a chamber boycotted by a dozen of his bitterest
Republican enemies) rang up big at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   Hammerin' Henry Hyde had to be throwing up on his recliner at
home. Representative Dick Armey looked as if he'd just scarfed down
a platter of bad clams. Rookie Speaker Dennis Hastert didn't know
whether to sit or go blind and ignore the Prez when Clinton
surprised him with a let's-bury-the-hatchet handshake before
unloading his boffo speech.
</P>
<P>
   From the chaplain of the far right came the first flutter of the
white flag. Pat Robertson tells his electronic flock that Clinton's
speech capped the impeachment volcano. Clinton ``hit a home run. .
. . From a public relations standpoint, he's won,'' said the 700
Club mogul. ``They might as well dismiss this impeachment hearing
and get on with something else, because it's over as far as I'm
concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat's brow is now furrowed deeper over Armageddon than Articles
of Impeachment. He told his network's audience that God is so angry
with the United States he might move up his timetable for punishing
the planet's sinners, maybe sometime right after 2000, unless 700
Clubbers pray hard and keep that toll-free number humming. My hunch
is that Pat is right on Clinton, wrong on the Almighty's schedule.
But, hey, it's a free country.
</P>
<P>
   Much to the regret of The Wall Street Journal, from whose
conning tower came a loud editorial moan. You can always tell how
well Clinton is doing by how viperish gets the Journal. Get the ice
buckets and hose down the editorial pen, fellas: ``It was the most
shameless State of the Union speech any president has ever
delivered,'' sputtered our overwrought brethren at the paper that
sells itself as ``the daily diary of the American dream.''
Clinton's survival is a nightmare for the Journal; Clinton boasts
the longest economic boom ever.
</P>
<P>
   The paper that has packaged the Clinton conspiracy through a
dozen different incarnations (Whitewater _ remember Whitewater? _
Who killed Vince Foster? Travelgate, Filegate, and Whatevergate)
has made cynicism a synonym for Wall Street Journalism. ``An act of
utter political cynicism,'' seethed the Journal's submariners as
the depth charges drive their vessel of indignation lower into the
murk. ``It could all backfire,'' gasps the editorial. Fat chance,
boys. As they say on Wall Street, let's look at the numbers:
</P>
<P>
   Job approval percentages? 76 in NBC's survey, 72 at CBS, 66 at
ABC, the highest since Bush's Gulf War halo effect. Many Americans
wouldn't trust Clinton with their wives or daughters, but 81
percent trust him on the economy. When ABC asked who would do a
better job handling America's major problems, it's Clinton 50
percent, Republicans 32. Case closed, boys and girls.
</P>
<P>
   From North Dakota's Governor Ed Schafer came this glum tribute:
Clinton is a ``great deliverer.'' But who will deliver the Sun Belt
Republicans from their suicidal impeachment course? How do they get
off Trent Lott's runaway train? The Republicans have collectively
grabbed the third rail _ and can't let go.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-Clinton Web sites like Moveon.com testify to the groundswell
building against the GOP lynch mob. Everyone who ever bet their
hopes on Monica has been disappointed: Clinton, Starr, Hyde, now
Lott and the Republican Party. And the TV news mob.
</P>
<P>
   One TV network exec who's tossing in the Monica crying towel is
CBS news president Andrew Heyward. ``Monica fatigue'' is his term
for news shows overdosing on this cheesy scandal. ``We've covered
it so much it has turned off the public in droves,'' he sighs.
That's a lesson Republicans ignore at their peril as they weigh
calling witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's numbers appear bulletproof as long as the economy
keeps roaring. A huge political backlash seems to be building in
the countryside that is invisible to Lott and the D.C. lynch mob.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Republican water-carriers like William Safire have been
through GOP capsizings before. Brother Safire's postspeech column
retreated to the relative safety of linguistic esoterica. Brother
Bill, like any prudent passenger on the runaway GOP train, moves
away from the locomotive as it draws near the derailment.
</P>
<P>
   The morning of Clinton's triumphant speech, I spoke to a group
of mostly retired folk, generally furious at the Republican scheme
to impeach Clinton. Clinton has this giant club in the closet he
hasn't used yet, I said: Social Security. And any time he reaches
for that weapon, he'll get the AARP crowd off their recliners and
ready to burn down the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   That night Clinton took the club out. And with the slim and
imperiled Republican majorities sitting sullenly in front of him,
he beat their roof in. All that's left is for the GOP to collect
their wounded and retreat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
