   MARKET (New York) _ With Brazil worries continuing, stock prices
fall on world markets. At midday, the industrial average was down
111 points, or 1.2 percent, and the Nasdaq index was off 9 points,
or 0.4 percent. Elsewhere, prices fell 0.6 percent in Tokyo and 3.1
percent in Hong Kong. They declined 3 percent in Frankfurt, 2.1
percent in London, 2.9 percent in Brazil and 1.3 percent in Mexico.
On the American debt market, the long bond was up 20/32 point, with
the yield at 5.09 percent. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTV-PRIMESTAR (Undated) _ Hughes's DirecTV buys the assets
of its nearest rival, Primestar, for about $1.82 billion, giving it
increased channel capacity and the potential to add 2.3 million
customers. It will pay $500 million for 11 high-power satellite
licenses, two satellites and a satellite earth station. It also
will pay about $1.32 billion in cash and stock for Primestar's
medium-power business and assets. Primestar, owned by a group of
cable companies and the public, is running out of money because of
high customer turnover and marketing expenses. By Geraldine
Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
