<HEADER>
A4408 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-22 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWIFT SETS HER SIGHTS ON A LONG-IGNORED DSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ She sold a home in North Adams and this month moved to
a two-bedroom apartment on the Boston waterfront. There, her
husband will take care of their three-month-old daughter,
Elizabeth, while Jane Swift reports for duty as lieutenant
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Now what?
</P>
<P>
   The cameras that hovered around an American political oddity _ a
pregnant candidate _ are gone. There's a baby picture on Swift's
desk, but, thankfully, no baby or diaper bag in sight. Motherhood
is a wonderful thing. But now it's time to find out whether Swift
is going to be something more than a poster child for
office-holders who lactate.
</P>
<P>
   She and Shannon O'Brien, the new state treasurer, won election
last November, the first time two women will hold statewide office
at the same time in Massachusetts. But the spotlight was on Swift
from the outset, mainly because she campaigned in maternity clothes
and wouldn't talk about her child-care options.
</P>
<P>
   Much of her new job sounds pedestrian: funerals, chairing the
newly-created Governor's Economic Development Commission and, of
course, presiding over weekly Governor's Council meetings, the sole
official function of the state's lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   But the opportunity to do more is there, as suggested by the
career path of the current governor. And Swift does have one
intriguing interest: to pay more attention to the state Department
of Social Services.
</P>
<P>
   The DSS?
</P>
<P>
   A dangerous world falls within its bureaucratic purview, one
littered with society's tiniest victims. They were largely ignored
during the Weld-Cellucci years. Tax breaks, not broken children,
were the priority. Compassion was reserved for allegedly
overburdened corporate chieftains, not for absolutely overburdened
social workers.
</P>
<P>
   Would Lt. Gov. Swift really be willing to shine a light on the
dark and troubled DSS? Would Gov. Cellucci let her?
</P>
<P>
   Says Swift: ``At the end of four years, if I did not think we
were doing a better job of taking care of kids whose parents can't
take care of them, I would not be able to sleep at night.'' A
former state senator, she points out that during her last
legislative budget session she worked with other legislators to
commit more money to DSS. Yet, ``It doesn't appear the quality of
care has improved.''
</P>
<P>
   Is more money needed? ``Maybe,'' acknowledges Swift. ``Social
workers are demoralized. Kids today are more complicated and
challenging. There is need for structural change . . . I don't
think it's just money.''
</P>
<P>
   Money alone can not solve society's most complex problems. But
for a high Cellucci administration official to concede some more
money might help is close to miraculous, given past ``Welducci''
rhetoric. Can Swift put something tangible, like focus and
resources, behind her good intentions?
</P>
<P>
   Her agenda, so far, lacks specifics. Cellucci spokeswoman Ilene
Hoffer says the governor knows of Swift's interest in DSS and the
two ``will explore what kind of role she wants to take.''
</P>
<P>
   She is poised, articulate and energetic _ a little perky,
perhaps, but that's an acceptable female trait until at least age
35. She was not Cellucci's first choice for lieutenant governor,
but appears to have some influence with him. She played a role in
convincing Cellucci to pick Jane Perlov as the new secretary of
public safety. Perlov, an outsider from New York, beat out two
Massachusetts insiders, Republican Jeffrey Locke and state Senator
James P. Jajuga, a Democrat who supported Cellucci in the last
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Swift's political courage is yet to be tested and is, in fact,
suspect. When she was introduced as Cellucci's runningmate, she did
an about-face on two key issues. As a senator she voted against the
death penalty, but reversed her opinion during the gubernatorial
campaign. She opposed an assault weapons ban in the Legislature,
but now supports it.
</P>
<P>
   But here is a new opportunity to demonstrate real backbone.
After six years at the helm, Linda K. Carlisle will step down as
DSS commissioner. She took over the commissioner's job after the
agency was condemned by a blue-ribbon commission. However good her
intentions, her reign was stormy and lacked credibility with
frontline social workers.
</P>
<P>
   Six children in foster care died last year; 10 the year before.
If we need to be reminded of the horror of child abuse cases, think
of 6-year-old Eric Dawood, beaten to death by Juan E. Cruz, his
mother's boyfriend. A jury this week found Cruz guilty of
second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   There is no money and little glory associated with the DSS
universe. That is why it is so often left to women to fret over _
and write about. Wouldn't it be something if a new mother like Jane
Swift really did something to put the focus back on the forgotten
children of Massachusetts?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Joan Vennochi is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
