<HEADER>
A4410 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-PLAYING-BOS &LR;      01-22 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PLAYING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROWLANDS, CONNERY KEEP `HEART' ON TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
PLAYING BY HEART 
Written and directed by: Willard Carroll 
Starring: Gillian Anderson, Ellen Burstyn, Sean Connery, Anthony
Edwards, Angelina Jolie, Jay Mohr, Ryan Philippe, Dennis Quaid,
Gena Rowlands, Jon Stewart, Madeleine Stowe, Patricia Clarkson,
Nastassja Kinski 
Running time: 120 minutes 
Rated: R (language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Playing by Heart'' is the much blander new title of a film
originally called ``Dancing About Architecture.'' As in, one of the
characters explains, ``talking about love is like dancing about
architecture.'' This, of course, doesn't stop them from talking
about love, or, rather, the difficulty in finding it in
contemporary LA. Intertwining the amatory quests and avoidances of
a handful of Angelinos, it plays something like Robert Altman Lite.
It's saved from writer-director Willard Carroll's increasingly
forced linkages and made watchable by the resourceful acting of its
ensemble, some of whom get more to work with than others.
</P>
<P>
   Pride of place goes to Gena Rowlands and Sean Connery, as a
couple married 40 years, living comfortably from the TV talk show
in which her character, Hannah, stars, and which Connery's Paul
produces. As he puts it, no couple is married 40 years without some
rough patches. The one troubling them at the moment is the question
of his involvement years ago with one particular woman. It's sheer
pleasure to watch Rowlands and Connery tackle their assignments.
Rowlands hits every note, and Connery seems almost relieved to be
acting his age. Between them, they take advantage of their
characters' shared back story to give the film a grounding and
solidity it sorely needs. Charm, too.
</P>
<P>
   Rowlands and Connery fill some gaps left by writer-director
Carroll. Not all the others are able to escape seeming brittle and
superficial. Gillian Anderson, for instance, does all that's
humanly possible, pushing her persona into new realms of
self-consciousness as a theater director named Meredith who'd just
as soon abort the date she just made with Jon Stewart's
never-say-die Trent. At least she comes right out and says she'd
rather not go on for fear of getting in deeper and getting hurt.
But given the fact that Anderson is given virtually nothing but
antsiness to play, you wonder what keeps the smile pasted on
Trent's face and why he keeps coming back.
</P>
<P>
   Madeleine Stowe and Anthony Edwards play lovers who meet in a
hotel suite for sex when they can get away from their respective
marriages. They talk a good game between the sheets, but we feel no
erotic energy from them, just a need to talk at one another, she
about her need to maintain a controlled environment, he about his
need for something more. Dennis Quaid at least is given the
opportunity to seem enigmatic as he plays out a string of seemingly
chance nocturnal encounters, trying different lines on different
strangers, perplexing the likes of Nastassja Kinski and Patricia
Clarkson, and, for quite a while, us. The departure from the
pattern comes from Ellen Burstyn, maintaining a bedside vigil
beside her son (Jay Mohr), dying of AIDS. Both muster some
beautifully gauged acting in the segment that could easily have
imploded from maudlin excess, but doesn't, thanks to their dignity
and restraint.
</P>
<P>
   But the standout performance from the younger set comes from
Angelina Jolie. She and Ryan Phillippe have the toughest assignment
as two clubbers who share more than their respective hair dye jobs
(his blue, hers rust-colored). She's a bit too needy and
motormouthed (you wonder why; she's pretty and spunky!), he's a bit
too taciturn and prone to flight. Obviously, they're made for each
other. She at least sees it and tries to act on it, unafraid to
lead with her heart. They make you buy into a wish to see them dare
love. What does it isn't the dialogue but the yes vibes in their
eyes. They're the ones who seem made for photographer Vilmos
Zsigmond's velvety fairytale LA and they join the older actors to
make the film's simpatico ways exceed its synthetic ones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 1354EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
