<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4411 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-DILBERT-BOS &LR;      01-22 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DILBERT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DILBERT GOES FROM REAL WORLD TO . . . HOLLYWOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ For the past 10 years, captives of corporate
cubicle culture have found in Dilbert a comic-strip version of the
everyday absurdity of their own workplaces.
</P>
<P>
   So naturally, when Dilbert creator Scott Adams went to Hollywood
to create a TV version of the strip for the UPN network, he found a
parodist's paradise of limitless fodder, right? Uh, no.
</P>
<P>
   Adams admits that he was ``kind of expecting that I would be
feeding the comic strip for months just based on going to the
meetings in Hollywood,'' but he ran into the age-old satirist's
dilemma: How do you caricature a caricature?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing down here is like the real world,'' Adams said. ``I
mean, Dilbert (the strip) exists because it's kind of common
experiences, you know, exaggerated, but at least they started with
that common thing. Everything down here starts out exaggerated and
gets worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so there's almost nothing that's kind of `the LA making-TV
experience' that I can go back and say, `Let's build this into a
script.' It just doesn't translate, doesn't work in Cleveland,
really.''
</P>
<P>
   UPN is fervently hoping that the animated version of ``Dilbert''
works, in Cleveland and elsewhere. In fact, the faltering network's
hopes for a turnaround _ after losing a staggering 39 percent of
its already meager viewership in 1998 _ hinge partly on the success
of the series, which premieres Monday at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   However, the creators and cast of the show insisted during a
recent interview session here with TV critics that they are feeling
no corporate pressure to rescue UPN.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a totally external problem,'' said executive producer
Larry Charles, a veteran of ``Seinfeld'' and ``Mad About You.''
``Our problem is doing the show. We have enough pressure just
getting the show right.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to that pressure is the fact that Charles and Adams were
still scrambling to finish the premiere episode as the air date
approached. In fact, Charles predicted that ``we will not be ready
actually until, like, the day before it goes on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   The series has already had a complicated history: It began as a
live-action show at the Fox network before being abandoned and
revived at UPN as an animated series. Adams, who is co-executive
producer of ``Dilbert,'' professed pleasure at the genre change,
saying that animation is ``much more freeing creatively.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he noted, the premiere contains a scene in which
Dilbert's co-workers doff their business suits, adding jokingly:
``We had nude people who actually didn't have genitalia . . . You
can do that live-action, but it costs a lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   The voice cast includes Daniel Stern (``The Wonder Years'') as
Dilbert, the hapless engineer with the inexplicably upturned
necktie; Chris Elliott as Dogbert, the canine companion whose
biting sarcasm is worse than his bark; Kathy Griffin as Alice,
Dilbert's short-fused co-worker; Larry Miller as the Pointy-Haired
Boss; and Gordon Hunt as the work-shirking Wally.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin and Elliott admitted that they were not readers of the
comic strip before being offered the roles. (Griffin will be
competing against herself on Monday nights, since she also appears
in the same time slot on NBC's ``Suddenly Susan.'')
</P>
<P>
   In forging a transition from a comic strip syndicated to more
than 1,900 newspapers across the world (including the Globe) to a
TV series, Charles said the producers tried to fashion a show that
works ``on many levels, like all great cartoons, like `Bugs Bunny'
or `Popeye' or `The Simpsons.' '' That means, he said, endowing the
show with humor that appeals to youngsters, teenagers, and adults
alike.
</P>
<P>
   But clearly, the heart of ``Dilbert'' will remain its satirical
take on corporate life. In the three years since he left his job at
Pacific Bell, the inspiration for much of Dilbert, Adams now relies
on readers to keep abreast of corporate inanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get about 300 e-mail messages a day, and most of them are
cries for help,'' he cracked. ``I'm actually more tapped in now
than when I was in my cubicle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 1355EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
