u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTREAL-STADIUM-BOS &LR;      01-22 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTREAL-STADIUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTREAL STADIUM FALLING ON TAXPAYERS' SENSIBILITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ With its sleek ovoid lines sweeping back to an odd
bristling tower, Montreal's Olympic Stadium looks like a cross
between a scorpion and a spaceship.
</P>
<P>
   A French architect Roger Taillibert, who designed the stadium
for the 1976 summer Olympic games, liked to boast he was giving the
city an edifice for the ages, comparing it to the great medieval
cathedrals of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The cost was originally projected at a $120 million. But
then-mayor Jean Drapeau pooh-poohed taxpayers' alarm over the
bottom line. The games and the centerpiece stadium, he famously
declared, could ``no more lose money than a man can give birth.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a quarter-century and more than $1 billion later, the
huge structure Montrealers unaffectionately call ``the Big Owe'' is
still incomplete, although it has certainly won reknown _ as
Quebec's most spectacular white elephant. It leaks, it creaks, it
sheds chunks and pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Then, this week, the stadium's new $25 million roof caved in.
</P>
<P>
   Workers on Monday were busily setting up exhibits for Montreal's
auto show when someone noticed an ominous inward bulge in the big
Teflon top. As people scattered amid shouts of alarm, the roof tore
open, and hundreds of tons of snow, ice, and debris crashed down.
</P>
<P>
   There were only a few minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like being hit by an avalanche,'' said Adrian Kanernan,
a worker who received a gash on the forehead and was partly buried
beneath a snowpile. ``It just came ripping through the roof.''
</P>
<P>
   As they have so many times in the stadium's tattered history,
officials convened news conferences, giving assurance that the
damage wasn't really so awful and that the place would be up and
running real soon.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, conceded Andre Tetreault, president of the board that
oversees the stadium, it's kind of embarrassing when a brand new
roof collapses in the first snowstorm of the season in the snowiest
major city in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new roof. It's the first snowstorm,'' he said. ``Still,
it's an isolated problem. We're conducting a technical analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   But for many Montrealers, the latest fallen roof was the final
straw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is wrong about the stadium. It's a useless piece of
junk,'' said radio broadcaster Gordon Sinclair, news director for
station CJAD.
</P>
<P>
   Stated the Montreal Gazette in an editorial: ``This is it. It's
time to give up, tear the place down. It's over.''
</P>
<P>
   That seemed to be the prevailing sentiment, although officials
were offended by the suggestion. ``It's impossible to believe we
could just demolish it,'' Tetreault said. ``We've paid $1 billion
for the structure.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, make that $1 billion so far. In fact, when the last loan
is finally repaid in 2006, the stadium will have cost taxpayers at
least $1.7 billion _ counting interest, but not the latest roof.
</P>
<P>
   The first Olympic Stadium roof, a complicated ``retractable''
affair, arrived too late for the Olympics. Six years too late, it
remained in storage in France until 1982 for reasons that have
never been coherently explained. It took another five years to
install, and then, on opening ceremony day in 1987, it was ripped
by a gust of wind.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to 1989: Huge gashes appear mysteriously in the roof,
forcing thousands to flee a monster-truck pull show. Fast forward
to 1991: Winds rip open the roof in April, and tear open gaping new
holes again in June. In September, a 55-ton steel beam falls into
the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there were fires and explosions in the stadium. An
interior wall collapsed. Electric circuits shorted out while rain
and snow more or less constantly drizzled in.
</P>
<P>
   The original $52 million Kevlar roof, at last declared a safety
hazard, was sold for $1 to a scrap dealer, who transformed it into
office curtains and tarpaulins, turning a tidy profit.
</P>
<P>
   Lawsuits are already flying in the latest debacle.
</P>
<P>
   The latest roof, installed last year, was fabricated by Birdair
Inc., a New York firm. ``We are still trying to figure out exactly
what happened,'' said company president Jon Duncan. ``And we
will.''
</P>
<P>
   Some officials have hinted the stadium might sue Birdair not
only for damages but loss of reputation. However Daniel Jutras,
professor of law at McGill University, said that would be a tough
case to make since ``there's not much reputation to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The 10-day auto show, which attracts 250,000 visitors, has
already been canceled. A boat show has also been deep-sixed.
</P>
<P>
   The Montreal Expos expect to play their first home game in the
stadium on April 8, roof or not. But the team hopes to move to a
new stadium in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse, Olympic Stadium has become a Montreal
landmark, and some citizens remain proud of it. ``It's part of our
skyline,'' said Jane McConnell, a lifelong resident. ``If it's a
turkey, it's our own distinct turkey. I'd be seriously upset if
they decide to knock it down.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Montreal's most indefatigable booster, Mayor Pierre
Bourque, wondered aloud whether enough is finally enough. ``It has
cost us so much. It's a huge financial drain,'' he said. ``It
stains the reputation of our proud city.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
