   GOP _ WASHINGTON _ The Republican National Committee, trying to
regain its political footing after last year's setback, appeared to
soften its anti-abortion stance Friday. Newly relected chairman Jim
Nicholson, outlining the party's priorities through the 2000
election, deliberatedly left out abortion, in consultation with GOP
congressional leaders. Ironically, the RNC inched away from banning
abortion, one of its bedrock issues since Ronald Reagan's
presidency, as thousands of anti-abortion marchers staged their
annual protest against the Supreme Court ruling legalizing
abortion. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
