   PANAMA-TRAVEL _ PANAMA CITY, Panama _ In the Panama Canal, ships
are raised like toys, step by step, through three sets of locks to
a height of 85 feet above sea level, on their way from the Atlantic
to the Pacific and back again. Each passage requires 52 million
gallons of fresh water to equalize the water levels in these locks.
Nearly 85 years after its completion, these 50 miles of man-made
ditch are still an engineering wonder to behold, and the most
popular tourist attraction in this Ohio-sized country. (Emling, Cox
News Service).
