<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BEEPER SERVICE FOR EVERY OCCASION 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ This has to be the ultimate Web site for
Southern California. It combines pagers and freeway pursuits, and
was inspired by O.J. Simpson's Bronco chase.
</P>
<P>
   The only things missing are Rollerblades, mineral water and
surfing. And we'll get to surfing and pagers in a minute.
</P>
<P>
   PursuitWatch Network answers one of the most important questions
of life in Los Angeles: How are you going to know when a live
police chase is on television if you're not already watching?
</P>
<P>
   The solution is linking computers to pagers. When there's a
chase being shot by L.A. news helicopters, PursuitWatch subscribers
are beeped and can run to the nearest TV.
</P>
<P>
   It's not all that high-tech, but it fills a big need.
</P>
<P>
   PursuitWatch founder Ken Kuwahara says it takes shows like
``Cops'' to the next level. ``No one, not even the producers, knows
what the ending will be. Perhaps an incredible collision or deadly
confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   All that mayhem, and there's a special bonus. If a subscriber is
the first to call or send an e-mail saying there's a chase on TV,
he or she wins $100.
</P>
<P>
   It's interactive, if you can call being glued to TV chases
active.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there are positive uses for pagers. PursuitWatch isn't
the first or only outfit to use pagers as something other than
electronic leashes.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993 a Ventura, Calif.-based outfit named ``Call of the
Wind'' has provided windsurfers with pagers that give them
information about wind conditions in windsurfing spots from the
Hood River to Baja on the West Coast, in Hawaii, Tahoe and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Windspeed devices at each spot automatically alert the central
computer when wind velocity goes over 10 mph, and that information
is transmitted to windsurfers' pagers. Thus, they don't have to
waste gas and time looking for wind.
</P>
<P>
   They just buy a pager and pay a monthly fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started windsurfing, there was a machine you could call
to get a verbal report,'' said Call of the Wind founder Jim Martin.
``I said `Why can't a machine call me?'''
</P>
<P>
   Martin has expanded his machine-calls-you business to ski
reports, storm reports for fishermen and surf reports. His Web site
(www.windcall.com) has millions of visitors each year.
</P>
<P>
   It got me thinking. There must be many other ways to combine
pagers and computers to make life easier and more enjoyable. These
are a few ideas I'd gladly give away for a small percentage of the
take:
</P>
<P>
   _ ReservationCancellation Network will tell subscribers, via
pager, whenever a table is available at a hot restaurant.
Information will come from reservationists (yes, that's what they
call them) or subscribers canceling reservations. When the pager
beeps, start dialing fast.
</P>
<P>
   _ ThatIsSoFiveMinutesAgo Network will let fashion victims know
about changing fashion as it happens. When Hello Kitty purses
replace Gucci purses, you can ditch the Gucci and run right over to
the Sanrio store _ to use a fashion example that's already so five
minutes ago.
</P>
<P>
   _ The CelebSighting Site will let you know instantly wherever
celebrities appear in public. Subscribers can rush right out and
gawk, and never again have to be passive readers of celebrity
columns.
</P>
<P>
   _ The BarstoolPigeon Network will alert its anti-tobacco
subscribers to anyone lighting a cigarette in a bar anywhere in the
San Francisco area. If the police are unavailable to respond,
smoke-prohibitionists can swarm the smoker and demand that he cease
and desist from his evil habit.
</P>
<P>
   Smokers can join the JoeCamelSentMe Network, which will alert
them immediately whenever a bar is filled with smoke, empty of
cops, and safely hazardous to smokers' health.
</P>
<P>
   _ TheNightmareIsOver Network is the network for those who aren't
following the impeachment trial, but would like to be notified if
Bill Clinton is forced from office or, more likely, if the
Republican Party blows up, leaving no survivors.
</P>
<P>
   All of the above can be done in real time, with pagers. At last
there are uses for pagers besides bringing bad news to adults,
status to the immature and annoyance to orchestra conductors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
