<HEADER>
A4423 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-STILL-BOS &LR;      01-22 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-STILL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STILL CRAZY' A HUMANE LOOK AT '70S ROCK BAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
STILL CRAZY 
Directed by: Brian Gibson 
Screenplay by: Dick Clement, Ian La Frenais 
Starring: Stephen Rea, Billy Connolly, Jimmy Nail, Timothy Spall,
Bill Nighy, Juliet Aubrey, Helena Bergstrom, Bruce Robinson, Hans
Matheson, Rachael Stirling 
Running time: 96 minutes 
Rated: R (language, sexuality and drug content) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Still Crazy,'' in its unexpectedly sweet way, makes up for the
debacle of ``Velvet Goldmine.'' Partly this is because of its
British love of eccentricity and failure, partly it's because
director Brian Gibson and his colleagues convince us they like rock
enough to avoid going the put-down route in their lively and
endearing chronicle of a splintered '70s band trying to get it
together again. It's more invested in liking its characters than in
striking cool poses. You expect a comedy of disaster when Stephen
Rea's keyboard player, Tony, is talked into leaving his profitable
men's room condom concession in Ibiza, overcoming the psychic scars
of the band's flameout 20 years ago at a venue designed to recall
the Isle of Wight, and picking up the pieces.
</P>
<P>
   The first question, of course, is whether the pieces are in any
condition to be picked up. The original lead singer, called Strange
Fruit, is dead. Nobody can find his brother, the band's fragile
lead guitarist. But the others are traceable, especially once Karen
Knowles's Juliet, the oft-abused personal assistant turned likably
and resassuringly efficient manager, gets on the case. Before long,
Juliet and Tony have ascertained that the others need only to have
a few layers of rust and reluctance scraped off before getting a
shot at a second chance. It's about here that you begin to expect a
British ``This Is Spinal Tap.'' But no. Gibson, who did such a
terrific job with the Tina Turner biopic, ``What's Love Got to Do
With It,'' means to go the hey-kids-let's-put-on-a-show route.
</P>
<P>
   Except that the kids in this case are undergoing various
mid-life crises. Funniest, because he seems most shaky and
vulnerable, is Bill Nighy's Ray. He's a spindly narcissist living
beyond his means on an estate with his Swedish wife and onetime
groupie, who has all she can do to wrest the blow-dryer away from
him, and wouldn't except during his yoga breaks. Ray's mix of
vanity and terror is shared to various degrees by the others:
Timothy Spall's lowlife drummer, Jimmy Nail's smoldering bassist
and Luke Shand, representing the younger generation, as the
replacement guitarist and source of envy as the new young girls
flock to him and away from the sagging old men the others are
trying not to admit they've become.
</P>
<P>
   It all makes for a cheerful mix, especially when they're egged
on by their resurrected roadie, a Scotsman with a mischievous eye
played by Billy Connolly. He seems to have a thing for playing
Scotsman, and, in any case, has earned an encore for his
performance as the monarchy-reviving Mr. Brown in ``Mrs. Brown.''
Shortly after you begin laughing as the band stumbles into its
continental break-in tour, which begins in less than grandiose
fashion on a barge in Holland, you find, to your surprise, that you
want them to somehow beat the odds and right themselves both
musically and personally. ``Still Crazy'' is what very few rock
movies are, namely, humane. It's not the kind of film that's out to
knock your socks off. Its ambitions are modest, but easy to
empathize with, and it helps get us through the January dismals
very warmly, indeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
