<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONADVERTISING-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARSHALLS'S MARSHA MORE THAN `SPOKESTOON' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What the Jolly Green Giant is to mixed vegetables, Marsha is
becoming to Marshalls. A few years ago, Marsha began life as
doodles on a cartoonist's sketch pad; today an animated character
with the voice of British comic Tracey Ullman has emerged into a
brand icon for the Framingham, Mass. retail chain.
</P>
<P>
   As befits an icon, Marsha recently got a Betty Crocker-style
makeover. And in spots set to break in a few weeks, TV viewers
could get to see Marsha's husband for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call her our spokestoon,'' says Kerry Hamilton, vice
president of marketing for Marshalls, of Marsha.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has her own life now,'' says Gail Schoenbrunn, one of
Marsha's creators at Hill Holliday Connors Cosmopulos of Boston,
the ad agency that Marshalls uses.
</P>
<P>
   At birth, Marsha had a very specific mission. In 1995, Marshalls
had been acquired by TJX Cos., which is also based in Framingham.
TJX is perhaps best known for its T.J. Maxx chain.
</P>
<P>
   T.J. Maxx and Marshalls are off-price retailers. Both sell the
same merchandise as department stores, only at lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   But in the early 1990s, they had different marketing
philosophies. T.J. Maxx stressed everyday low prices. Marshalls, in
contrast, was highly promotional, using its ads to highlight sales
events and discounts.
</P>
<P>
   For the acquisition of Marshalls to be successful, TJX believed
Marshalls had to adopt the T.J. Maxx everyday-low price marketing
philosophy while keeping its Marshalls identity distinctive and
separate in the minds of its consumers.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Marsha fit in. She would represent the typical
Marshalls customer. And by using an animated Marsha, instead of an
actor or a model, the ads would set Marshalls apart from other
retailers, including T.J. Maxx.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marsha was conceived as a unique way to talk to customers,''
Hamilton says.
</P>
<P>
   Not only were animated TV ads unusual for a retailer, they
offered some other advantages as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes an animated character can get away saying things
that you wouldn't accept from a real person,'' Schoenbrunn says.
</P>
<P>
   In one spot for swimsuits, for example, the ad opens with Marsha
saying something like: ``Sure, I love the beach, but first give me
a few minutes to lose 50 pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Viewers can get turned off by a real pitch person. Is she too
blonde and glamourous? As a cartoon, Marsha avoids such feelings by
becoming a Rorschach ink blot for Every Woman and by letting the
Marshalls message come through loud and clear: ``Brand names for
less. Every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoenbrunn credits Hill Holliday art director Dick Pantano for
coming up with some early sketches for Marsha.
</P>
<P>
   Those sketches were then sent off to Olive Jar Productions, a
Brookline animation house, for further work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at Marsha with a gazillion different hairdos before
we decided on just the right one,'' Schoenbrunn says.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's been occasionally tinkered with, Marsha's signature
coiffure always has a curl obscuring one of her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   What else has changed? Marsha now wears flatter heels on her
shoes for an ``updated look,'' Schoenbrunn says.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other subtle evolutions. In the beginning,
Schoenbrunn and Pantano imagined a woman who drove Saturns and was
fond of daisies. Now Marsha is more likely to be found behind the
wheel of a sport-utility vehicle, and her taste in bouquets is far
more exotic.
</P>
<P>
   Most Marsha TV spots feature a ``doughnut'' format.
</P>
<P>
   A 30-second spot might open with seven seconds of the animated
Marsha, followed by the doughnut's middle _ 30 seconds of Marshalls
merchandise. Then the spot concludes with another seven or eight
seconds of Marsha.
</P>
<P>
   This technique allows Marshalls to frequently change the
merchandise that is highlighted in the middle of a TV ad while
recycling the same Marsha opening and closing sequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a whole library'' of Marsha spots now that can bracket
a pitch for a specific category of merchandise, Schoenbrunn says.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Anheuser-Busch Cos. hinted it may phase out its Louie
the Lizard character in Super Bowl ads because an icon's shelf life
is only two years. Entering her fourth season with no end in sight,
Marsha may be durable because she is so flexible.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can play a lot of different roles,'' says Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   And just as important, Marsha is ``memorable,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come to me out of the blue and mention Marsha to me,''
she says. ``When it comes to recognition, she's getting to be like
the Jolly Green Giant of the Pillsbury Dough Boy.''
</P>
<P>
   In icon terms, that's the next best thing to immortality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
