<HEADLINE>
DECLINES KNOCK INTERNET STOCKS OUT OF ORBIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How often do you read about a quiet $100-per-share stock slide?
</P>
<P>
   The amazing thing in the Internet stock world isn't that you can
find one there on that scale. The stunner: there are several on
display, typically falling off highs set just last week.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Internet stocks are giving ground after unprecedented
climbs, bounding 25 percent or more daily for extended periods. But
you have to wonder: are we in the middle of the big, ugly reversal
investors feared would be inevitable or are Internet stocks just
going to give back a small piece of their heady gains?
</P>
<P>
   Leading Internet issues have fallen 30 percent or more in the
last two weeks, after most of them peaked on Jan. 11. Analysts like
Paul Noglows of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist aren't so sure what will happen
next, in part because they couldn't get their hands around the
forces propelling Internet stocks so high just weeks earlier. But
they are braced for further declines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very possible,'' said Noglows. ``It's hard to
predict, just like it was hard to say why the stocks were going up
$100 a day. What you're looking at is a retail (investing)
phenomena. You have investors pushing stocks up or down not based
on any traditional metrics, not looking at fundamentals.''
</P>
<P>
   Momentum investors, who like to hitch a ride on stocks that are
rising rapidly, are a powerful force when a stock is headed up;
they can be equally forceful on the way down. That is particularly
true when the stocks in question depend on such a tenous conn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
