<HEADER>
A4434 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-DIVA-BOS &LR;      01-22 1448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-DIVA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIVA'S DEBUT _ FINALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Performers become Knights or Dame Commanders of the
British empire not just because of their contribution to English
musical life but because of their international prominence. Most of
England's unparalleled crop of singing Dames have made shining
contributions to Boston's musical life _ Janet Baker, Joan
Sutherland, Gwyneth Jones, Kiri te Kanawa, Josephine Barstow. But
we have missed out on two of them. Dame Margaret Price is now near
the end of her career and sings only occasionally in recital; we've
probably missed out on her. But this week the other holdout, Dame
Felicity Lott, makes her long overdue local debut, singing the
soprano part in a Boston Symphony Orchestra production of Benjamin
Britten's ``Spring Symphony'' _ a work that was premiered by the
BSO. Lott may be the most important singer of the day never to have
performed here.
</P>
<P>
   Dame Felicity's operatic repertory largely coincides with te
Kanawa's, although she hasn't sung any Verdi or Puccini. Lott is
celebrated for her Mozart roles (and recorded her Fiordiligi in
``Cosi fan tutte,''the Countess in ``The Marriage of Figaro,'' and
Donna Elvira in ``Don Giovanni''; earlier this season the Met
broadcast her elegant portrayal of the Countess) and for her
Strauss (she has taken her Arabella, Marschallin, Countess
Madeleine, and Christine Storch to most of the major opera houses
of the world). Despite this overlap, two singers more different
from each other can scarcely be imagined. What Lott has going for
her is intelligence, musicianship, curiosity, and a voice that is
as fresh and as clear as a mountain stream. From the beginning of a
career that has spanned 24 years since her professional debut, Lott
has explored the song and recital repertory, usually with her
schoolmate Graham Johnson, now England's most eminent collaborative
pianist, at her side. Lott has probably appeared on two dozen CDs
of songs and vocal chamber music in French, German, and English;
she may be the best female Poulenc singer of all.
</P>
<P>
   In person Dame Felicity is charming and down-to-earth _ who
could resist a diva who lists ``sleeping'' among her hobbies in her
``Who's Who'' entry, and whose nickname in the profession is
``Flott''? When she rises from her chair in her tailored suit, you
are stuck by her height and grace of bearing; she's built along the
lines of Vanessa Redgrave, and people who have seen Lott's
Marschallin in the video of ``Der Rosenkavalier'' will tell you
that she's an actress in the same class.
</P>
<P>
   Lott may be the only diva in the business who holds a degree in
French literature. ``I had sung all my life, but I didn't think I
had what it would take to claw my way upwards in this terrifying
profession,'' she says. ``I made my first recording when I was 2,
on a little machine in a booth in a store. I sang `Rudolph the
Red-Nosed Reindeer' and `Away in a Manger,' and it's bang in tune.
. . . It may be the only recording I've ever enjoyed. I played
violin and piano and sang all the way through school, and when I
was all of 14 I made my stage debut as Aline Sangazure in a school
production of Gilbert and Sullivan's `The Sorcerer.' Now I have a
daughter who is 14!''
</P>
<P>
   Lott spent a year studying French in Grenoble; that summer she
attended a school for singers in Nice where she was told she ought
to do something about her talent. She then enrolled at the Royal
Academy of Music, where she sang Mozart's Dorabella in ``Cosi fan
tutte'' and Pamina in ``The Magic Flute.'' ``I sang Dorabella
because I still couldn't get the high notes for Fiordiligi; it
wasn't until after I gave up smoking that I got the high notes!''
</P>
<P>
   It was at the Royal Academy in 1970 that she met fellow student
Graham Johnson. ``He's younger than I am _ he won't turn 50 until
next year, so I hate him _ and he was so talented that I was
frightened. I was taking lessons from Flora Nielsen and he would
come to play for my lessons. On our own, he made me learn sheaves
of songs. When he founded the Songmaker's Almanac performing
ensemble in 1977, I was there, and I am still in it _ now it's
mostly young people, but they sometimes trot out the old guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott's operatic career started slowly but rapidly ascended. ``My
debut was as Pamina with the English National Opera. I was the
understudy, and the soprano got sick, and I went on _ I did know it
because I'd sung it in school. Then I did some tour performances. I
did about three auditions for the Glyndebourne chorus, and didn't
get in, but in 1976 I sang the Countess in Strauss's `Capriccio'
for them and the next year Anne Trulove in Stravinsky's `The Rake's
Progress.' Last summer I sang `Capriccio' again in the same
production, and I felt my whole life was passing in front of my
eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott's first operatic recording was a live performance of
Charpentier's ``Louise'' in Belgium in 1982, but she had already
appeared in John Eliot Gardiner's recording of Purcell's ``Come Ye
Songs of Art'' (``my first grown-up recording''). Like te Kanawa
before her, Lott was chosen to sing at a royal wedding. ``Fergie,''
she says with a smile. ``I don't think the sopranos brought much
luck to the royal couples.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Lott has won the esteem of the most prominent
(and picky) conductors, including the late Klaus Tennstedt and
Georg Solti, Pierre Boulez, Bernard Haitink, Charles Mackerras, and
Kleiber, and she's still adding them to her list. This week's
concerts bring her first performances with Andre Previn, and he
leads New York Philharmonic programs with her next week. She was
asked to sing Blanche du Bois in his opera ``A Streetcar Named
Desire'' in Tokyo, but the tour was canceled; the score sits on her
piano at home and she pronounces herself ``fascinated'' by the
role. The Met ``Figaro'' this season marked her debut with James
Levine; and her first concerts with Riccardo Muti and Kurt Masur
are coming up. Seiji Ozawa has eluded her. ``I would love to sing
with him,'' she says. ``Everyone says he's a singer's dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Much as she has done, Lott sometimes wonders about the road not
taken. ``All of my training was toward German music and the German
style and all of my instincts took me towards the French. So
Italian opera sort of passed me by, although I used to sing `Una
voce poco fa' from `The Barber of Seville' as an audition aria. I
hadn't a clue! Not long ago I sang the love duet from Verdi's
`Otello' in a concert, and it made me want to sing the whole role
one day. I've always been tempted by Tatiana in Tchaikovsky's
`Eugen Onegin,' but I'd have to learn Russian to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   But, all in all, there were few regrets. ``I chickened out of a
recording of Leonore in Beethoven's `Fidelio,' and wish I'd done it
now. I've sung Donna Elvira a lot, and I'd like to try Donna Anna _
I wouldn't be as dramatic as some, I know, but in my mind Elvira is
the dramatic role.'' There are some new parts coming up. ``I'm
graduating from Blanche to the Second Prioress in Poulenc's
`Dialogues des Carmelites,' and I will sing my first `Fledermaus'
and my first Offenbach, `La Belle Helene,' next year. I have no
business complaining about my roles, because the ones I do are so
fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott seems not to have disliked anything she has sung. ``It was
sheer heaven to sing Eva in `Der Meistersinger' at Covent Garden,
and I loved every moment of it. But I hate my feet, and this is a
whole, long opera that is all about feet and shoes!''
</P>
<P>
   The soprano lives on the south coast of England, not too far
from Brighton. ``It is not very convenient, but it is very
pretty.'' Her husband, Gabriel Woolf, is an actor and reader. As
``Mrs. Woolf,'' Lott has received a letter addressed to Virginia
Woolf. ``I know you're dead,'' the letter began, ``but I think
you're wonderful.'' A year ago the whole family came to Boston as
part of a holiday trip. ``My daughter kept asking if we could go
somewhere, sometime, when I didn't have to sing. So we came to
America, went to Disney World and Chicago, and came to Boston. We
went on a whale watch, and we went up to Vermont to see the Robert
Frost country. My husband did his Robert Frost program there.''
</P>
<P>
   The soprano says the secret of keeping her voice fresh is that
she never sits down. ``I am always working, and I am careful about
what I do sing. I also sing lots of songs, and that's healthy for
the voice. I do hope one of my pianists will tell me before things
get difficult or unpleasant _ and I hope they won't have to; I like
to be aware of what I'm doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
