<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHL NETWORKING WELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest television gadget to help the NHL draw more eyeballs
has little to do with sight but everything to do with sound.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday's All-Star Game at the Ice Palace in Tampa, the NHL
froze 13 microphones into the ice to capture the sounds of sticks,
skates, and pucks. Whistles and words won't be aired because the
two-inch mikes catch only on-ice sounds.
</P>
<P>
   The mikes are frozen under each of the face-off dots and
creases. Three are stationed along the red line.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is give viewers a you-are-there feeling.
</P>
<P>
   That has been a problem, which Fox recognized four years ago
when it acquired the NHL television rights and tried to enhance
coverage by, among other things, colorizing the puck. Critics and
purists blasted the innovations, but Fox Sports executive producer
Ed Goren defended his network's imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have elevated the awareness of the game,'' said Goren.
``The folks over at Disney realized that the NHL is worth a heck of
a lot of money by picking up the rights fees.''
</P>
<P>
   Goren is right. Last August, ESPN and ABC, both owned by Disney,
paid $600 million to televise the games the next five years, or
about $120 million per season. Fox is in the last year of its
five-year deal. In 1994, Fox paid a total of $155 million to air
five year's worth of games.
</P>
<P>
   Goren said television has done its part to help popularize the
NHL, but it can't do it alone. ``At some point, the league has to
look within itself and ask whether they are doing enough to create
personalities and stars locally and nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerk'' of our own
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Tank McNamara,'' the nationally syndicated comic strip carried
in 200 newspapers throughout the country, awarded Latrell Sprewell
its 1997 ``Sports Jerk of the Year.'' Creators Jeff Millar and Bill
Hinds had a lot of material to work with for its latest award.
</P>
<P>
   David Stern and Billy Hunter were strong candidates. As were
Ryan Leaf and Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Tank hasn't come up with the 1998 winner yet, but Red Sox GM Dan
Duquette has been announced as runner-up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A wash for CBS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CBS claims of breaking even during the first year of its
expensive eight-year NFL contract appear to be accurate. According
to the The Hollywood reporter, an entertainment trade publication,
CBS pulled in an estimated $450 million, including network sales
revenue and ad revenue from the 14 CBS-owned stations, and other
local contributions. CBS paid about $500 million to the NFL, and
while the sports books show a $50 million loss, the NFL helped
boost the ratings of CBS's other prime time programming, leading to
higher ad revenue overall and first-place in the prime-time race .
. . TBS airs the 50th ``Delchamps Senior Bowl'' Saturday at 2:30
p.m. Pregame starts at 2:05 p.m. Kevin Harlan, Mark May will be in
the booth and Craig Sager and Fox's Brian Baldinger on the
sidelines. Ernie Johnson and Marty Schottenheimer, a Senior Bowl
hall-of-famer, will handle the pregame and halftime shows . . .
There's a good piece on internet gambling upcoming on HBO's ``Real
Sports with Bryant Gumbel.'' Jim Lampley reports about the
exploding $600 million a year industry and how some American-based
companies circumvent American laws by conducting business from the
Carribean. ``21st Century Sports,'' for instance, operates in
Aruba, but is located in Bethlehem, Pa. ``Point, Click and Bet''
airs 10 p.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Superfluous coverage
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl hype has always been excessive. Case in point: ESPN.
The self-proclaimed worldwide leader in sports has a staggering
nine days of pregame coverage, with almost 80 programs and a
whopping 150 hours of Super analysis, Super stories, Super
statistics, Super Xs and Os, Super everything. ESPN has dispatched
33 anchors, reporters, and analysts to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Compare that with a mere 60 hours of programming for the cable
station's ``SportsCentury'' project documenting the athletes and
stories of the millenium, and it appears that the annual Game of
the Century is more important than the Century.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN is not alone in its blanket coverage. CNN/SI starts its
coverage Sunday, live from Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, which will televise the game, will present a pregame show
of seven hours, the longest in history.
</P>
<P>
   Does the Boston Globe or any other newspaper publish special
sections when its area team makes the Super Bowl? Of course. But it
is a valid criticism that the media prints and airs every possible
story, covers every possible angle, then turns around and complains
about the excessive amount of coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, they should just say no.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
