</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY'RE PERFECTING THE TURNAROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may be a little early yet, but we already have our two
candidates for Coach of The Year. Or Coach of the Half-Year.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn's Cliff Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   And Ohio State's Jim O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis has made his team the talk not only of the Southeastern
Conference but of the country, Wednesday night's loss at Kentucky
notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, going to basketball games has become the the thing to
do at Auburn, as ``Cliff Dwellers'' are congregating at
Beards-Eaves Memorial Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   It's become so big that after a 17-point win over Arkansas Jan.
6, the trees at Toomers Corner (the social gathering center in
``downtown'' Auburn) were decorated with toilet paper, a custom
almost exclusively reserved for football celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis has worked his magic before, at South Alabama for nine
years and at Clemson for 10. And there were signs that the Tigers
were coming around last season when they won 16 games and made it
to the National Invitation Tournament, their first postseason
appearance in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   This year, led by junior college transfer Chris Porter, the
Tigers feel they can take on anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone doubts this team, they have been in a tunnel a long
time,'' said Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone following college basketball in Boston doesn't need an
introduction to O'Brien _ or a reminder about what has happened to
him the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Headline News'' version is simple and painful for Boston
College fans: O'Brien, a BC graduate, had brought his alma mater
back to respectability and seemed on the verge of making the Eagles
a perennial Top 20 team, a major accomplishment. Recruiting was
going fine. The Eagles were winning.
</P>
<P>
   Then it all came apart, because of the pettiness of a few people
who couldn't see the good in a man who desperately wanted to be a
lifer at the Heights.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien left for Ohio State, BC's top recruits left for other
Top 20 schools, and the program at the Heights became the pits.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, O'Brien resurfaced at Ohio State with a collection
of mediocre athletes and a few bad citizens. Backed by an
administration that offered tangible support, the Buckeyes went
from 8-22 last season (1-15 in the Big Ten) to a 14-5 mark so far
this year, with victories over Wisconsin, Indiana, and, on Tuesday,
a remarkable blowout of No. 16 Purdue. All three teams were ranked,
and all three probably expected to find the same stumbling Buckeye
team from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of BC transfer Scoonie Penn, who along with
Michael Redd makes up arguably one of the best backcourts in the
nation, the Buckeyes are one victory away from a clinching winning
season and, barring a major collapse, they are a lock for
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien has been cautious, maintaining that the Buckeyes are a
year away from being genuine contenders for anything, but he is
naturally delighted to be competing again.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike BC, where making the NCAA tournament is the main
goal, Ohio State eventually wants to compete for the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   With a state-of-the-art new arena, the full backing of the
administration, and a coach as good as O'Brien, the Buckeyes are
just beginning their climb.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Ten is highly competitive this season, but even a late
sag would not dim the prospects of the Ohio State program.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Strength in numbers
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Big East is starting to flex its muscles. Nine of the
conference's 13 teams already have double-digit victory totals, and
Big East teams have nine nonconference victories over Top 25 teams.
But if you think that is impressive, consider the Atlantic Coast
Conference. Every team is above .500, though that can be misleading
because some pick up wins on weak nonconference opponents. But add
this to the equation. As of last Sunday, ACC teams had 17 victories
over 12 different teams that were leading their conferences.
Included on that list were Stanford, which has lost twice to ACC
teams, Kentucky, Oklahoma, Louisville, and Princeton . . . In this
day of specialization, when players are used in spurts, you've got
to love La Salle's Donnie Carr, who has a career average of 38.8
minutes per game (39.3 minutes this year) . . . Rhode Island's
Lamar Odom may have cooled off a bit after his sizzling debut, but
NBA insiders still think he will be a top three pick in this year's
draft. Odom already has been the Atlantic 10 Rookie of the Week
five times . . . It all sounded so nice when it was announced last
spring. Former Houston star Clyde Drexler would come back to his
old school and re-create some magic from the Phi Slama Jama days,
with help from players and sons of players from the Cougars' glory
days. That's what drew Moses Malone Jr. to Houston. Just one
glitch. It didn't work out. Malone played nine games and decided he
didn't like it. He's transferring to that tradition rich school,
Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whistle-blower?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This kind of slipped through the cracks during bowl season. What
was Indiana coach Bob Knight talking about when he mentioned
gambling and officials during his ESPN chat-fest with Digger
Phelps? Said Knight, ``If we only knew the truth about games that
were controlled by officials having gambling interests, I think it
would be amazing.'' Shockingly, Phelps didn't ask him to name names
or cite specific circumstances. Knight has drawn the ire of
officiating chief Hank Nichols, who wants him to either retract the
statement or provide evidence to support it. Neither is likely to
happen, which is unfortunate for the game and for Knight, who
should do better than make such sweeping generalizations . . . Now
that Auburn has lost to Kentucky, we're down to one unbeaten team
in Division 1. The No. 1-ranked Connecticut Huskies . . . Still
looking for their first victory are Sacramento State and Monmouth .
. . Another building with character and history is making its final
go-around. North Carolina State's Reynolds Coliseum will be
deactivated this spring after 50 seasons . . . How's this for a
streak? North Carolina has been ranked for 300 consecutive games.
The ACC record, held by the Tar Heels, is 319, stretching from
December 1973 to December 1983 . . . Duke may be No. 2 in some
polls, but the Blue Devils are No. 1 in the RPI and Sagarin
rankings. According to the RPI, the Blue Devils have the
fifth-toughest schedule, while UConn has the 108th-toughest . . .
Wake Forest coach Dave Odom is earning his pay. In their first 17
games, the Demon Deacons used 10 different starting lineups
involving 11 players . . . Texas coach Rick Barnes didn't take long
to create waves in the Big 12. Seems he wants the conference
tournament moved out of Kansas City. ``I think the Big 12 can have
something real special,'' said Barnes, who came to Texas from
Clemson last season after coming to Clemson from Providence. ``I
just think it needs to be moved to create that.'' Sites that have
been suggested include Dallas, San Antonio, Denver, and Oklahoma
City. But don't look for anything soon, since there is a
north-south battle in the Big 12 between the Texas schools and
their northern counterparts . . . Speaking of Texas schools,
Southern Methodist is considering leaving the Western Athletic
Conference for Conference USA.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from wire service reports was used in compiling this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
