<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-CRAZY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STILL CRAZY': BAD MUSIC WITH A BUZZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CRAIG MARINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would be a shame if ``Still Crazy'' were lumped into the
``Spinal Tap'' genre simply because it was about a reunion of old
rockers. In fact, it's what movie reviewers like to call ``the
feel-good movie of the year,'' which means it's easier than
searching for adjectives and safe to say since it's still January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still Crazy'' involves the '90s reunion of the '70s rock band
Strange Fruit, an English band that broke up acrimoniously after
lightning cut short their final show and gave the group an excuse
to let their lingering animosities explode.
</P>
<P>
   A chance encounter with a concert promoter sets the stage for
the band's re-forming, and if this sounds like hokey business it's
only because it is. However, the movie, for a change, is a lot
better than the plot line sounds, as the eccentric Fruits put aside
their real-life jobs and glance back into what might have been.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason this movie rises above the predictable is the
script of Dick Clement and Ian La Frenais and the excellent
ensemble acting headed by Stephen Rea and Juliet Aubrey. See, you
know it's a real movie if anyone bothers to use the word
``ensemble,'' especially if they take the time to learn how to
spell it.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of the movie is muttered somewhere in the middle,
after a bad comeback show and the ensuing arguments when Rea's
character, Tony Costello, says something about ``We have to bury
the past before it buries us.'' Corny, sure. But also enough of a
truism to merit caring about the internal wranglings of a bunch of
middle-aged folks taking the risk of giving their dream another
crack.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Nighy plays the most complex character in the movie, the
lead singer Ray Simms, who joined the band only after the death of
the original and much-loved lead singer. The elder Ray still hangs
onto his country estate, even though he's broke, and his struggle
to re-capture what fueled his passion as a singer _ especially now
that he partakes of Evian instead of Old Number 7 _ is surprisingly
moving.
</P>
<P>
   Surprising in the sense that ``Still Crazy'' is definitely a
comedy, but it's a comedy with heart.
</P>
<P>
   There are lots of subplots, like the love interest between Rea
and Aubrey, who plays the band's tour manager who has always had a
thing for their guitarist, Brian Lovell. Which introduces another
subplot because when Rea and Aubrey try to round up the band, Brian
is nowhere to be found and presumed dead.
</P>
<P>
   Which leads to another subplot, wherein the group brings in a
young gunslinger to give them relevance and fall in love with
Aubrey's daughter, who goes on tour with the band while they try to
reclaim their chops. What is this, ``The X-Files''?
</P>
<P>
   ``Still Crazy'' suffers, as most rock movies do, because the
music bites. Even though many bands hit it big in the '70s with
crappy tunes, the idea that anyone would really want to see this
group with the kind of songs they play isn't very believable. But
when you bring in a guy from Foreigner and a guy from Squeeze and
put them in charge of the music, you can't really ask for much.
</P>
<P>
   However, this seems to be one of those sleeper films that should
generate a good buzz, and deservedly so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 1409EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
