<SLUG> BC-BKN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALKER CAN BREATHE EASIER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A few minutes before 6 p.m. Thursday, Antoine Walker
sat in his condominium, waiting for a phone call. He napped a
little. He ate a little. He waited, it seemed, infinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually his agent would be on the line, explaining the
``out'' clause in the fifth year of Walker's six-year contract.
Eventually he would be ready to put his signature on pieces of
paper worth $71 million. And then, slowly, the realization would
come to him: He's going to be a rich man. Forever. Who could have
ever imagined that? Who could have guessed that he could get in his
own car and drive to his own condo without worrying about a
creditor taking both away?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe sports fans will find those queries ridiculous. They know
Antoine Walker, 22-year-old Celtics player. They know a pro sports
environment in which million-dollar contracts are commonplace. We
are used to hearing weather and contract updates on the nightly
news. Antoine Walker, son of Diane, used to watch TV and see the
stories of rich people, too. He knows what it means to be one of
them, permanently, because he remembers the days when he was far
from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from nothing,'' he said as he waited for his agent's
phone call. ``You have to understand that I grew up not being able
to see $70 million or $80 million in my future. So to be able to
get a contract like this, I just can't describe what it feels like.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom was a single parent, trying to raise six kids. I
remember taking soda pop bottles to the store for money. I remember
taking jars of pennies to the store, because that was the only
money we had. I remember being a first-year pro and paying $60,000
to take care of the credit problems my mom had over all the
years.''
</P>
<P>
   He was asked about that $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was from all the things my mother tried to do for all of
us,'' he said. ``From furniture, to repossessed cars, to housing
problems . . . a lot of things didn't work out. My mom always kept
a job, but it was hard for us. She was always trying to do things
that would make life better.''
</P>
<P>
   Life is certainly better now. Diane Walker's credit is repaired.
She and her children live in a beautiful home several miles outside
of Chicago. Her children now attend private schools. And her eldest
son, Antoine, recently held a basketball camp where all the
children played and ate pizza and drank soda. For free. Before
that, Diane Walker was given a sport utility vehicle that her son
received from a TV station in Boston. One of Walker's best friends
received a car from him in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always that easy. Walker had several Chicago addresses
when he was younger. He and his family would live in a comfortable
neighborhood for a while but ``then we wouldn't be able to handle
the rent and we'd have to leave.'' There would be some assistance
from Walker's cousin, pro baseball player Chico Walker. ``But if
you remember,'' Walker said, ``most of his career was spent in the
minor leagues.'' And when you spend most of your career in the
minors, it's difficult enough worrying about your own bills, not to
mention someone else's.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Antoine Walker doesn't have to worry about anyone's
bills; he simply takes care of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a major financial burden lifted,'' Walker said.
``Now I know that my little brothers and sisters and my daughter
can all go to college and not have to worry like I did. It's a
blessing to be in the position I'm in. I'll never forget that.''
</P>
<P>
   Those observing Antoine Walker, Basketball Player, expected him
to be upset that he couldn't immediately make $100 million because
of the NBA's new Collective Bargaining Agreement. Not a chance of
that. He has been through too much. He has gone hungry too much. He
has seen too much poverty to worry about the difference between
making $12 million a year and $17 million.
</P>
<P>
   Now he lets his agents haggle over contract details. If he
didn't have an agent, he would not have insisted on ``out'' clause
language after five years. He would have simply signed the contract
and started the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to get all this out of the way as soon as
possible,'' he said. ``I didn't want to wait until the end of the
season and I didn't want to go to another team. I want to play here
my entire career.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Walker mentioned that he could play for 15
or 16 seasons. The only problem, he said, was that he couldn't see
himself playing PitinoBall and ``pressing when I'm 35.'' He laughed
at the thought. But there was also a time when he couldn't see
himself making $70 million, and that is happening. In fact, it may
happen a couple times over because this is far from his last
contract. When his extension is up, he will still be a month shy of
29.
</P>
<P>
   He is 22 now, staying close to his same friends and appreciating
the same things he did as a child. Even when the money was tight,
he always wanted to win. Nothing has changed. Now that his contract
is settled, Walker says he is playing for NBA championship rings.
Best thing about that? You don't have to buy them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 1410EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
