<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4442 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-BOS &LR;      01-22 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLANTA RETURNER DWIGHT LOVES TAKEOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Atlanta's Tim Dwight received his first kickoff of the NFC
Championship game last Sunday 4 yards deep in the end zone and ran
it out, eyebrows were raised. When Dwight caught another kickoff 2
yards deep and ran it out, eyes brightened.
</P>
<P>
   And when the pint-sized Dwight moved to the back line of the end
zone so he could dash forward and catch the next kickoff _ this
time 5 yards deep in the end zone _ on the full run, it was time to
stand up and gape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to take touchbacks,'' the rookie explained. ``And
when my special teams coach (Joe DeCamillis) gave me the go and
said, `Hey, man, catch 'em on the run and it doesn't make a
difference even if they kicked 'em 6 yards deep in the end zone,
because then it's like you're catching them at the goal line,' I
just decided to run 'em out.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second half, when Dwight dashed back toward his end
zone and caught a punt over his shoulder a foot from the goal line,
then turned and ran madly upfield, all pretensions were gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew if I caught that one real quick and swung it out of
there real fast, because their guy had outkicked his coverage, I
knew I could go somewhere with it,'' said Dwight.
</P>
<P>
   He did. Madly, fearlessly, the rookie dashed to the 28-yard
line, giving the Falcons 8 more yards than they would have had on a
touchback.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you were a purple-clad fan of the Vikings, all
objectivity was gone. The Falcons had to win, just so they could
play another game, just so football fans could have a chance to
watch Dwight one more delicious time this season, for he surely is
one of the most fearless returners in recent decades.
</P>
<P>
   Even coach Dan Reeves, heart surgery and all, is not quite as
fearless as his madcap rookie. Dwight and DeCamillis were exulting
on the sideline over that punt return when Reeves ambled over and
tossed in a dose of caution _ a concept unknown to Dwight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were really happy getting it out to near the 30,'' said
Dwight, ``and Joe came over and told me, `Good job, good job!' but
then Coach Reeves came over and said, `What the hell are you
doing?' '' recalled Dwight. ``And Coach was (angry). He told me,
`You've got to know where you are on the field when you catch the
ball.' And I said, `Yeah, I know, Coach.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ha ha.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves's cautious words were all but forgotten when Minnesota
tried its next kickoff, this blast by Mitch Berger going 9.9 yards
deep in the end zone. Even though his back foot was nearly touching
the back line of the end zone, Dwight caught the ball and briefly
considered another mad dash upfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew where I was _ I was, like, 9 yards deep _ and I wanted
to bring it out,'' said Dwight, visions of a 109-yard touchdown in
his head. ``Then I said, `Awww, I better not.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fearless'' is an understatement when describing the football
style of Tim Dwight. Viking after Viking called the 5-foot-8-inch,
184-pounder the most fearless football player they'd seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They list me at 184?'' asked Dwight. ``I weighed in the
morning of the game at 178.''
</P>
<P>
   All the more remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't sit back in football,'' said Dwight. ``You've
got to attack.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not only fearless, but fast. Dwight was on the University
of Iowa track team last spring, good enough to finish second in the
100 meters in the Big Ten championships, finish fourth in the 200,
and run a leg in the 4 x 100 relay. After his football season ends,
Dwight will return to Iowa to compete in track, which NCAA rules
allow because he is considered a professional only in football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to be hell-bent for leather,'' said Dwight. ``Look
how big I am. I've got to play aggressive. The way to play football
is to give it everything you've got, and that's the only way I
know. You can't sit back. You can't be afraid. You can't sugar-coat
things. You've got to take it to your opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   Some football heads look at Dwight's style and wonder how long
he'll survive in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I might not last too long playing this way,'' agreed
Dwight, ``but I can't change. It's the only way I know.''
</P>
<P>
   So, football fans, make sure you're still not at the
refrigerator when Denver kicks off and punts next Sunday. You'd be
missing one of the true treats of football _ little Tim Dwight, the
fearless one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
