A4458 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-PLAN-HNS &LR;      01-22 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-PLAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SIMPLE PLAN' OVERLY SIMPLISTIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until now, Sam Raimi's best-known films were three involving
murderous demons: ``The Evil Dead'' and its two sequels, ``The Evil
Dead 2'' and ``Army of Darkness.''
</P>
<P>
   All are operatically violent horror films in which Good,
embodied by doe-eyed youth, battles Evil, embodied by ancient
spirits who turn human beings into decomposed homicidal maniacs.
Raimi found rapture in the frenzied dismemberment of the human
form.
</P>
<P>
   With his new film, ``A Simple Plan,'' he's found something else
_ a cold, murderously mean little B-movie that takes a more
conventional approach to telling the same old story. In ``The Evil
Dead,'' characters are driven to kill by devils in the woods;
wookie-ookie incantations wake them up. In ``A Simple Plan,'' based
on the novel by Scott B. Smith, characters are driven to kill by
another slumbering devil in the woods, a bag of money stashed in a
plane wreck. The humans in question don't start hacking each other
apart with axes, but they do turn into killers _ and that, in
Raimi's schema, is at the tail end of any struggle with evil.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of it is Hank Mitchell (Bill Paxton), a decent,
barely-making-it Midwesterner with upstanding morals and a load of
responsibility. His wife, Sarah (Bridget Fonda), is pregnant with
their first child, while his brother, Jacob (Billy Bob Thornton),
is a scruffy ne'er-do-well with no job and few friends other than
the big, rough Lou (Brent Briscoe).
</P>
<P>
   The plot gets kicking when, one day, Hank, Jacob and Lou drive
through a snowy nature preserve. They swerve to miss a fox and slam
into a birch tree. Lou and Jacob chase after the fox with a gun;
Hank chases after Lou and Jacob. Together they stumble into a
gnarly corner of the woods where a downed plane harbors two items
of interest: a dead pilot (and attendant crows, picking at his
face), and $4.4 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the American dream in a (expletive) gym bag,'' says Lou,
to which Hank replies: ``You work for the American dream. You don't
steal it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacob and Lou want to abscond with the money. Hank resists _ at
first. After gnawing over the moral implications, Hank finally
agrees to take the entire stash, on one condition: That he holds it
until springtime. If, by that time, they hear no inkling in the
news of the missing money, the trio will split the take and leave
town. If the missing money becomes news, Hank will burn the entire
load.
</P>
<P>
   It's a not-so-good plan that gets even worse when Jacob
inexplicably tells a local sheriff (Chelcie Ross) that the
threesome spotted a plane flying over the preserve. Why does he do
it? Because Lou eggs him on. Why does Lou egg him on? Because if he
didn't, there wouldn't be a movie. There wouldn't be murder.
</P>
<P>
   There is, in fact, a broad strain of illogic that creeps through
``A Simple Plan,'' prompting perplexed viewer head-scratches at
every turn. Why doesn't it occur to anyone that all that stomping
around the woods would leave a few tracks in the snow? Why, when it
becomes clear that the moolah is ransom money for a kidnapped
heiress, is no one worried that the authorities might wonder where
it went? Why don't Hank and company steal part of the money (say,
half), leaving the rest for cops to sort out whenever they find the
plane?
</P>
<P>
   This last question is later addressed by Sarah, who turns out to
have the most actively functioning cerebral cortex in the lot.
Fonda is superb as the hard, smart woman behind Hank's every move;
Hank may be the instigator (and the moral victim) of the plan, but
she's the one pulling the strings.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the cast is just as good: Paxton's performance is
all cool Faust (he sells his soul for a canvas bag), while
Thornton, brilliant as the lonely, stricken Jacob, gives the movie
its single shot of conscience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hank, do you ever feel evil? I do. I feel evil,'' he says, and
we can see the flaccid struggle in his face.
</P>
<P>
   All, in the end, are intelligent characterizations of stupid
people. Jacob's supposed to be dumb, and Lou is no great wit _ but
all of them, even Hank, even (eventually) Sarah, behave with the
mechanized dim-wittedness of stock horror characters. Which they
are.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Simple Plan'' is a terrifically entertaining movie _ black,
nasty, corkscrewed and taut _ but it's entertaining in the way that
all horror films are, as a welcome affront to logic.
</P>
<P>
   Just as ``The Evil Dead's'' doltish teens wander into the woods
knowing full well what demons await them there, Hank and Jacob and
Lou and Sarah make bad decisions as though their lives, or at least
the plot, depended on it. It does. And for the time being, until we
all remember to put our brains back in our skulls, what malicious
fun it is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
