<HEADER>
A4463 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-FLIGHT-HN     01-22 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-FLIGHT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THEORY OF FLIGHT' NEVER GETS OFF THE GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By G. ALLEN JOHNSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a lot of metaphorical weight to ``Theory of Flight,'' a
pleasing, nicely executed movie that suffers from not being
ambitious enough _ odd for a movie about frustrated dreams and
fatal diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The crux of director Paul Greengrass' film is Helena Bonham
Carter's performance as a wheelchair-using victim of Lou Gehrig's
disease, and indeed it is a winning turn. From Robert De Niro
(``Awakenings'') to Tom Cruise (``Born on the Fourth of July'') to
Daniel Day Lewis (``My Left Foot''), A-list actors are always
looking for disabilities to give them a career boost, so Bonham
Carter's slurring voice, crooked neck and jerky movements aren't
things we haven't seen before.
</P>
<P>
   But the natural sense of humor and almost easy-going geniality
she brings to the role are wonderfully effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theory of Flight'' is so called because of the dreams of
frustrated artist and societal misfit Richard (Kenneth Branagh). He
has spent a great deal of time and effort trying to re-create the
Wright brothers' first flight, building a full-scale replica of the
historic plane and trying to lift off from tall buildings at a
single bound.
</P>
<P>
   Richard is arrested after one of these stunts, and sentenced to
community service. Jane (Bonham Carter) is his assignment.
Actually, though they detest each other initially (natch), they
have a lot in common. Both have foul mouths and cynical outlooks,
and the first third of the film has them trying to adjust to each
other's abrasiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Then saucy Jane gets things rolling by announcing one last
request before she dies: To get laid.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly something the Make-A-Wish foundation would grant (or
would they?). Richard agrees to help her _ but because he's
repulsed by her appearance, he won't personally service her. He
instead goes to great lengths to get the job done including an
alternately funny/tragic sequence in which he tries to hire a male
prostitute for her.
</P>
<P>
   As realized by Branagh, who gets to reprise his crusty persona
from both ``Dead Again'' and ``The Gingerbread Man'' (only this
time he gets to use his natural British accent), and Bonham Carter
in a solid follow-up to her Oscar-nominated performance in ``Wings
of the Dove,'' Richard Hawkins' script, refreshingly, does not
depend on melodrama.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's formulaic, but there aren't any sappy violins and
there are some great scenes, such as when Jane programs a frank
description of sexual desire into her voice enhancer, and pumps up
the volume in a crowded restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The weird thing is, when all is said and done, ``Theory of
Flight'' seems like a bit of fluff, as if it were made for
television and not the big screen. It's too much an actors
exercise, and Greengrass overemphasizes Richard's dreams of flight
as an allegory.
</P>
<P>
   OK, life and society have conspired to constrict these two
people, and they can't get off the ground and fly free. We get it.
</P>
<P>
   A little more realism and complexity would have done wonders for
this movie. By the time the pair take their inevitable flight, the
viewer feels metaphored to death, turning something fun and moving
into nothing more than a simple fable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
