<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4467 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEEMAY-COLUMN23-COX     01-22 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEEMAY-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 23
 &HT;    A change is gonna come: Even bird clocks may feed my imagination
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Everything can change. A few years ago, a friend gave
me a hummingbird feeder, one of those with red plastic encasing a
glass bottle. I put it up and waited for the hummers. They never
came. I figured they didn't like the noise and feel of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Part of me was fine with that, as I didn't care much for the
look of the feeder, anyway; it didn't look natural.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last spring, I revisited the idea, buying the same style
feeder and hanging it at the cabin in McCaysville (Ga.). The red
plastic didn't bother me at all. The birds were the thing. Their
frequent hits on the bottle, their zippy arrivals and departures,
fascinated endlessly.
</P>
<P>
   Hummingbirds even illustrated lessons for living. One day, Lyn
and I sat idling, counting the number of times a bird stuck its
icepick beak into the little feeder hole during one trip.
Thirty-six times, we counted. A minute or so later it returned,
only to get buzzed by another hummingbird.
</P>
<P>
   Back and forth they went, taking turns divebombing each other
away from the feeder, each intent on keeping the other away from
the sweetened water, not realizing _ or not caring _ that the
feeder contains three perches and enough food to feed an army of
hummingbirds. The result: Neither tasted the sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   So it goes in the garden of life.
</P>
<P>
   The hummingbirds are gone south this time of year, but the other
birds lend much beauty and interest to the garden. They stand out
most in winter, not because they are more plentiful than in other
seasons, but because most of the plants have moved off center
stage. Now's the time that birds strut their color and lend
movement with minimal competition.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the orange pyracantha berries and purple beautyberries
and red magnolia seeds, leaving only red nandina for bright berry
color in my garden. Too, the tasty tender plants that birds love _
including coneflower, sunflower, pokeberry, butterfly bush, lantana
_ all have died back, taking their color with them.
</P>
<P>
   Among those filling the color void in Atlanta lately are
cardinals, blue jays and a red-bellied woodpecker.
</P>
<P>
   I've always made them and others welcome to drink from the fish
pond, but I never put up feeders, as the plants, insects and trees
(one big oak's acorns could feed the entire bird world) seem quite
adequate. But, in yet another change, I've begun to toss bread into
the garden once in a while. The other day, I saw a blue jay
standing on a bagel, pecking away at it. I got within three feet of
it, as I had with two doves a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there's the woodpecker that tiptoes up the tulip tree,
eating bugs as it goes. Half a dozen times in the last month or so,
it has come within a few feet, too, walking around the porch roof
outside my second-floor office window.
</P>
<P>
   Together, this goes beyond bird-watching; it feels like
bird-communi-cating.
</P>
<P>
   Which reminds me of the mysterious call of a bird up at the
cabin. (As mysterious as what looked like a great blue heron
soaring along Fightingtown Creek one day.) Each morning I hear the
call, from the same spot in the woods, wondering what bird makes
it.
</P>
<P>
   Bird books try to show calls, but there's nothing like hearing
them. I've been thinking about those clocks that mark each hour
with a different bird call, but I like them about as much as I used
to like hummingbird feeders. Maybe it's time for another change.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: leemay(at)bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Lee May' writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
