<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4468 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ORCHIDS-TIPS23-COX     01-22 0350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORCHIDS-TIPS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 23
 &HT;    Caring for orchids
 &HT;    By Danny Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Most orchids are epiphytes, or plants that grow on trees or
rocks in the tropics, so their roots prefer light and air. When
potting an orchid, use a loose mixture of fir bark, charcoal and
perlite, never heavy potting soils, says Becky Brinkman, greenhouse
manager for the Atlanta Botanical Garden. Soak the mixture
overnight and drain before use. Rock chips and sphagnum moss also
can be used.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Orchids prefer a drop of temperatures at night of 10 to 15
degrees to bloom. Most fall into one of three categories. The ones
in the warm group (64 degrees and higher nights), such as
Phalaenopsis and Haemaria, or jewel orchids, like morning light,
preferably from an east window. The ones in the intermediate group
(55 to 60 degrees nights), including Cattleya and Oncidium, prefer
bright afternoon light from a west window. The ones that like cool
nights, or 50 to 55 degrees nights, such as Masdevallia and
Miltonia, aren't recommended for the Southeast, Brinkman says.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The most common mistake is overwatering, says Cathy Meincer of
Florafarm nursery in Cumming. Most orchids prefer to dry out
between waterings. Push your finger 1 inch into the soil. If it's
dry, it's time to water. Water thoroughly until it drains through
the bottom of the container.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In general, orchids are light feeders because their thick
leaves and roots store water and nutrients. Apply a half-strength
20-10-20 fertilizer every two weeks in spring and summer and
monthly during winter, Brinkman says. In October, use half-strength
10-30-20 (high phosphorous) to increase budding for spring flowers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tie the orchid to a bamboo stake early, or when the plants
reach 8 to 10 inches. (Don't turn the plant around as it leans
toward the light because it will make the stem grow contorted,
Brinkman says.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
