<HEADER>
A4469 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ORCHIDS23-COX     01-22 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORCHIDS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 23
 &HT;    Beneath the orchid's delicate facade lies a plant not so
difficult to grow after all
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some plants just can't shake a bad rap.
</P>
<P>
   We shun roses because they're prone to disease. We shut the door
on African violets because our windowsills don't get the right
light.
</P>
<P>
   And pity the poor orchid, whose only invitation is typically the
senior prom, where its delicate petals get rattled all night on the
wrist or bosom of a boogieing teenager.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to set the record straight: Not all things of beauty
are fragile or should be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   Take the orchid.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend to love them to death, and that's what kills
them,'' says Becky Brinkman, greenhouse manager at the Atlanta
Botanical Garden, which is offering an extensive exhibit on the
plants through April. ``It's true some orchids are difficult, but
if you can grow houseplants there's an orchid for you.''
</P>
<P>
   How tough are they?
</P>
<P>
   So tough they flourish in the burly hands of motorcycle-riding
Terry Root (yep, that's his real name), an expert California grower
who breeds some of the world's most exclusive orchids.
</P>
<P>
   So tough that Ron Determan tells his staff at the Atlanta
Botanical Garden that after repotting an orchid they should be able
to grab it by the stem and swing it around, lasso style, without
harming the plant.
</P>
<P>
   So tough that many can withstand the day-to-day neglect and
temperatures of the average home, despite constant thermostat
shifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Brinkman warns, ``you have to pay attention to orchids'
needs.''
</P>
<P>
   The major reasons people fail at growing orchids are they give
them too little light and too much water, says Cathy
</P>
<P>
   Meincer, an American Orchid Society judge and owner of
Florafarm, a Cumming (Ga.) nursery that specializes in orchids.
``People kill them with kindness because they look fragile. They
baby them to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Some orchids prefer subdued morning light, while others love
basking in the afternoon sun. Some like nighttime temperatures at a
brisk 55 degrees; others like it ``hot,'' or 64 degrees and higher.
Some want to snuggle their feet in pots like any other houseplant
because they are terrestrials, but most like to hang out in loose
baskets because they are epiphytes, which means they like to attach
their roots to trees or rocks.
</P>
<P>
   If this family of plants sounds finicky it's because there are
just so many relatives to please _ nearly 25,000 species and
100,000 registered crosses, to be exact. ``They're the ultimate in
diversity when it comes to plants, so you never get tired of
them,'' Brinkman says.
</P>
<P>
   She should know. Her job these days revolves around rotating the
garden's display of more than 150 orchid species vying for
attention inside the entrance to the Dorothy Chapman Fuqua
Conservatory. They are a small sample of the more than 1,500
species _ many rarely seen _ that are grown in its greenhouses. As
one orchid comes into bloom, Brinkman moves it out front to replace
one that's already performed.
</P>
<P>
   And though the exhibit contains many unusual species _ like the
Bucket Orchid that blooms in summer with a pouch that attract bees
_ it also showcases plenty of plants Brinkman and Meincer recommend
for beginners, including:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Phalaenopsis, or the moth orchid, with its arched sprays of
fuchsia and white blooms that can last six months.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Paphiopedilums, or slipper orchids, which contain pouch-shaped
lips and are available in many colors.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cattleyas (known for their use in corsages), with their
fragrance, multiple colors and ruffled petals.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Calanthe, which features a large panicle and goes dormant for
half the year.
</P>
<P>
   The garden grows mostly species orchids instead of hybrids
because it wants visitors to see what already occurs in nature, not
a lab, Brinkman says. The plants hail from the tropics of Asian and
Africa, where many species are endangered by extinction because of
development and thieves, which is why the orchid trade is
regulated.
</P>
<P>
   Permits are required to transport an orchid from the wild, and
customs officials at airports from Miami to New York often call the
garden, one of several orchid rescue centers, when one's been
confiscated.
</P>
<P>
   The orchids are welcomed to a new home in the garden's
greenhouse, where they are divided among three zones based on light
and temperature needs. It becomes such a full house that next year
the garden plans to build an Orchid House, a $3 million facility
that will emphasize research and conservation efforts.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of money, though many orchids are expensive, prices
have come down as more growers propagate the plants through tissue
culture rather than the more costly method of dividing, Brinkman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Just one more reason to invite an orchid home, not just to the
prom.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   ``Splendor Under Glass''
</P>
<P>
   When: 10 a.m.-6 p.m. Tuesday-Sunday though April
</P>
<P>
   Where: Fuqua Conservatory, Atlanta Botanical Garden, 1345
Piedmont Ave. NE, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Cost: With garden's $6 admission
</P>
<P>
   Information: 404-876-5859
</P>
<P>
   Special event: Tour of exhibit and greenhouse operations with
manager Becky Brinkman, 9:30, 10:30 and 11 a.m. Jan. 30. Cost: $20.
To register, call 404-876-5859 Ext. 226.
</P>
<P>
   ORCHID SOURCES
</P>
<P>
   Retail:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Florafarm, Cumming (Ga.), 770-889-3559.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Peach State Orchids, Alpharetta (Ga.), 770-751-8770.
</P>
<P>
   Mail order:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hoosier Orchid Co., Indianapolis, Ind., 317-291-6269.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oak Hill Gardens, Dundee, Ill., 847-428-8500.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  R.F. Orchids, Homestead, Fla., 305-245-4570
</P>
<P>
   Information:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Atlanta Orchid Society, 404-815-7281.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Home Orchid Growing'' (Prentice Hall Press, $45) by Rebecca
Tyson Northen.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Growing Orchids'' (with American Orchid Society membership),
561-585-8666
</P>
<P>
   Repotting an orchid
</P>
<P>
   Repotting an epiphyte form of orchid, one that grows on trees or
rocks, can be tricky. Becky Brinkman of the Atlanta Botanical
Garden recommends choosing a plant with a new shoot 1 to 2 inches
tall because that means the orchid is entering a period of active
growth. Then:
</P>
<P>
   1-Remove the plant from the pot, knock off the excess potting
mix and gently rinse the roots with water to reveal which are dead
and which are alive.
</P>
<P>
   2-Using a razor blade or sharp knife, trim off dead roots and
remove old ``back bulbs,'' leaving three mature bulbs plus the new
shoot.
</P>
<P>
   3-Position the plant with the oldest growth against the edge of
the pot and the youngest toward the center to allow ample room for
new growth. Cover the roots firmly with new potting mix (fir bark,
charcoal and perlite). Allow the new shoot and the rhizome, or
horizontal root, to rest on the soil surface. If the plant wobbles,
use a rhizome clip to steady to it.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
