<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-PARADISE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PARADISE' GOES UP IN SMOKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By G. ALLEN JOHNSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Larry Clark is a filmmaker who never lets up in his quest for
``realism,'' and after relentlessly and sadistically pounding his
audience into submission with non-actors in ``Kids,'' he proves he
can pulverize us with big stars in ``Another Day in Paradise.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again using only natural light _ which makes it worthy for
those cineastes interested in the technical side of things _ and a
hand-held, cinema verite strategy, Clark tells the story of a
makeshift family of thieves who will keep looking for the big score
until either they succeed or their drugs run out.
</P>
<P>
   It's a film that never breathes or lets up. From beginning to
end, in every scene, there is a constant stream of profanity,
vulgarity, drug use (primarily heroin and speed) and cigarette
smoking by all four characters.
</P>
<P>
   The story, adapted to Clark's specifications by Stephen Chin and
Christopher Landon from a novel by former criminal Eddie Little,
centers on a teen-age runaway, Bobbie (Vincent Kartheiser), who
resorts to ripping off vending machines to support his drug habit
and that of his girlfriend, Rosie (Natasha Gregson Wagner). On the
lam after killing a security guard in a botched robbery, he is
taken under wing by veteran thief Mel (James Woods) and his
girlfriend/partner, Sid (Melanie Griffith).
</P>
<P>
   The four look for a big score, which takes them to another town
and a series of slimy contacts, cheap motel rooms and drug deals.
Even gays, as personified by the showy cameo by Lou Diamond
Phillips, are a target.
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear what exactly Clark wants us to get out of this
story. The acting is at times amazing, and the rhythm of the pace
is occasionally effective. But there's no real character
progression in the story, and it's so relentlessly bleak that it
undermines the story's central point: That criminal behavior and
drug use often stems from environment, and such ``lost souls''
constantly struggle with both the desire to run away and the desire
for family and, odd as it may seem, responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, ``Another Day in Paradise'' focuses on the teen-agers. In
Kartheiser, Clark has found almost a genetic cross between Leonardo
DiCaprio and Kate Winslet _ for teenyboppers, this would be the
``Titanic''-like story of young love their parents wouldn't want
them to see. Wagner is the daughter of Natalie Wood and Robert
Wagner, but with her short black hair and pixieish appearance, she
may as well have been cloned from Winona Rider (perhaps the
technology was available on the set of ``Alien Resurrection'').
</P>
<P>
   They're OK, but their characters are entirely predictable. If
anything, their work would serve as a perfect demo tape to send to
producers working on other nihilistic indie projects _ they have
that cigarette smoking and vein-popping down cold.
</P>
<P>
   If there's a revelation in this movie, it's in the performance
of Griffith, in her best acting job since the late '80s and her
``Stormy Monday''/``Working Girl'' days. World-weary,
heroin-shooting, hard-edged and motherly all at once, her Sid
achieves what Woods, with another talented but one-note turn, and
Clark could not: empathy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
