<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4522 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV24     01-22 1463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV24-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING IN HEALTH FUNDS WISE FOR THIS INVESTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, January 24, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 41 years old and I live comfortably within my needs on a
salary of $50,000 a year. I have a 401(k) plan through my employer
in which I now have about $40,000 invested in Fidelity's Magellan,
Asset Manager, and Equity Income funds. I have been contributing 8
percent of my salary, with most of the additions going into
Magellan; in March I plan to move to 10 percent contributions --
the most allowed for me under than plan. I also have $18,000 in
cash saved for emergencies, and $7,000 invested in shares of Home
Depot and Dell Computer. What would be a good place to invest about
$200 to $300 a month so that 20 years from now I would have some
financial security, even if I need to continue working?
</P>
<P>
   P.W., San Diego
</P>
<P>
   A. My suggestion for the first decade or so of this program is
to begin a long-term dollar- cost-averaging program in a mutual
fund invested in health care stocks -- and specifically a fund
focusing on the pharmaceutical and medical supplies end of the
business, to the exclusion of the funds which tend to favor biotech
and health care delivery issues. Good examples are the health care
funds of both Fidelity and Vanguard, both of which have built very
solid long-term records.
</P>
<P>
   Of course there's no question that this isn't a riskier
investment that the portfolio you're building in your 401(k)
program. When I checked with the Morningstar Mutual Funds reports I
discovered, to my horror, that the average health care sector fund
has a portfolio price earnings ratio of 38.3, and that the two
funds I am suggesting had even pricier portfolios, with an average
PE of 39.2 for Vanguard Specialized Health Care and 39.4 for
Fidelity Select Health Care funds. On the other hand, there are two
factors that would calm my jittery nerves if I were embarking on
such a program. One is that the discipline you propose is basically
dollar cost averaging, and over the course of time your regular
sequence of investments should arrive at a reasonable average cost
relative to the eventual market value. The second, of course, is
the very long-term investment time frame -- 20 years by your
specifications, and even longer if you decide you don't want to
retire early.
</P>
<P>
   Why did I say ``for the first decade or so'' back there at the
beginning? That was because despite its attractiveness for a
long-term investor, health care remains a volatile and expensive
sector of the markets, and my guess is that it's likely to remain
so. The chances are good that after about 10 years, the position
you'd have established in this 'extra' retirement account would
have grown to a point where it represents about 25 percent of the
total retirement portfolio. If you let it exceed that level by
much, you would be assuming more risk than I like to see in one
higher-risk market sector.
</P>
<P>
   You might at that point consider an entirely different sector
for some of your further investments -- adding to the health care
position only to the extent that the position doesn't exceed 25
percent of the total retirement portfolio. For the remaining funds
you might look to another sector, such as perhaps computer
technology, or you might decide that in your early 50s it's time to
begin moderating portfolio risk a bit. Who knows what the markets
and your feelings about them will be a decade hence; fortunately,
it's question neither of us have to consider for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, my suggestion is that you use a Roth IRA for the lion's
share of these savings, seeking to balance the larger tax-deferred
account you are building with the 401(k) with money that you can
withdraw on a tax-free basis in retirement, and withdraw without
any mandatory schedules of withdrawals involved. Even if you were
to save the maximum $300 a month, $166 of it -- more than half --
could go into a Roth account. The remainder could be invested in a
taxable account, and when it reaches a critical mass, you could
consider whether you want to put it into a variable annuity account
which would shelter that money from short-term taxes as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My question concerns the difference between investments in
bond mutual funds and investments in individual bonds or bond unit
trusts. As I understand it, bonds are generally more stable and
less risky than equities, the bond market frequently moves in the
opposite direction of equity markets, and bonds generally preserve
the investor's principal. Many financial advisors, yourself
included, recommend using bond funds, arguing that they reduce risk
through diversification. But unlike individual bonds or unit
trusts, mutual funds can also reduce the prospect for preservation
of capital -- a fund's price can fluctuate daily, and there's no
preordained maturity date when the investor is ``guaranteed'' to
recoup his or her original investment. Considering this important
drawback in bond mutual funds, why do you recommend them rather
than unit trusts or individual bonds?
</P>
<P>
   J.W., Austin, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A. You spell out some of the advantages of owning bonds rather
than stocks pretty well, but you omit several of the advantages
that bond funds have over direct purchases of bonds. And for most
people, the advantages of bond funds are considerable. One is the
greater ease of record keeping; this chore can become daunting when
dealing with a portfolio of callable bonds or mortgage-backed bonds
which make periodical returns of both interest and principal to
their owners. If you own a fund, the fund manager and the fund
company deal with all of this. Another advantage of funds is the
considerable greater ease of reinvestment, whether it be of the
yield stream or reinvestment of returns of principal. Much more
important, with a bond fund you should expect that you are buying a
sophisticated management team to keep an eye on the portfolio --
noting investment opportunities and signs of potential trouble
before an individual investor would be likely to.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, you don't mention what I consider to be the
greatest disadvantage of bond funds -- expenses. Typically bond
fund expenses run in the neighborhood of 1.1 percent annually.
That's 1.1 percent of the total assets under management, which is
simply deducted from the income stream before distributions are
made. When you buy individual bonds, you pay a broker's fee when to
them, and after that you pay only whatever account maintenance fees
your broker may levy. If your position is sizable, these costs will
quickly melt into relative obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   To my thinking the variance in expenses is a much more important
factor in deciding whether to own bonds or a bond fund than your
concerns about risk. For one thing, the value of individual bonds
tend to fluctuate almost on a daily basis, just like the value of
bond funds. Investors simply don't tend to notice it, because if
they plan to hold on until maturity, they simply forget about them
and don't check the papers or read their quarterly reports
carefully to see what the principal is worth. Of course, that's all
right -- such an investor is taking a long-term point of view. But
the investor in a good bond fund can also take a long-term point of
view -- calculating that over a decade or so the fund should see
very little in the way of erosion of principal.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, exceptions to that last statement. There
are funds which, in attempts to produce a high yield, frequently
buy bonds at prices above par. If these holdings remain in the
portfolio until maturity, the effect is a gradual erosion in
principal.
</P>
<P>
   Some fund owners, aware of this, counter this effect by
requesting distributions which are a bit less than the expected
income stream, leaving the balance of the distributions to be
reinvested so as to mitigate against loss of principal. A careful
reading of a fund's prospectus should let you know whether erosion
of principal should be a concern over the long haul. (You should
remember, as well, that a fund which typically shows erosion in
principal value isn't necessarily bad -- total returns remain the
name of the game. But the investor has simply to be aware of it,
and adjust withdrawals from the account if maintenance of principal
is a paramount concern.) But this is a tactic you would not have to
adopt only with a few funds. Over a reasonable period of time --
say a decade -- the better bond funds tend to show very little
change in principal value.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
