<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV24-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAZDA PROTEGE _ WHAT YOU SEE IS NOT ALL YOU GET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (For release Sunday, January 24, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRIFFITH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I love sleepers.
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking about trains here. Nor those ``good bets''
lurking deep in the draw of the NCAA Basketball Tournament brackets
_ even though I'm fond of both of those, too.
</P>
<P>
   The sleepers in question today are ones I've loved since I was a
kid: cars that have a bit more power lurking under their
unprepossessing hoods than you'd suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Take the 1999 Mazda Protege ES.
</P>
<P>
   I did _ even though it was for a far shorter time that I would
have liked.
</P>
<P>
   A sleeper?
</P>
<P>
   It looks like something my mom would drive _ slowly. It also
looked like a car she'd keep cleaned and waxed and be able to drive
forever.
</P>
<P>
   Then Mrs. G looked it over. Granted, it didn't look like much,
sitting there covered with salt and road grime after a week of
sloppy weather. It didn't take long for that first impression:
``It's a nice enough little car, but it doesn't have much
personality. Give me my Jag any time.''
</P>
<P>
   She isn't really going highbrow. She drives an '88 rust-infested
Jag of which John White advises: ``Make it into a lawn sculpture;
after all, it's the right shade of green.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, this Mazda is the right shade of green, too. A nice paint
job was resting under all that salt.
</P>
<P>
   A little personality, too.
</P>
<P>
   This vehicle was powered by Mazda's 1.8-liter, 122-horsepower
four-cylinder engine. We didn't take out the stopwatch, but this
gem sure seemed to get to 60 very quickly, the hornets' nest under
the hood revving quickly to just under 6000 rpm before smoothly
shifting.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the first excursion wasn't nearly that exciting.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the Globe, we were stuck in city traffic for 40 minutes,
enough time to check out the intricacies of the radio-CD player. It
had a nice sound, and also offered a neat CD storage compartment
(with door) directly under the radio. Best of all, the unit's
controls were pretty much self-explanatory.
</P>
<P>
   It's always been my contention that the owner's manual will
yield at least one interesting nugget of information.
</P>
<P>
   This manual's gem was the Auto/M button on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   Hit ``auto'' in a strange area and the radio will automatically
seek out and temporarily store as presets the six strongest
stations on the AM and both FM bands. Turn back to Auto/ manual and
your original presets are still there. I'm not an audiophile, but
this seemed like a neat touch.
</P>
<P>
   The sticker wasn't anywhere to be found, not in the spacious
door storage areas, the average-sized glove box or the small area
under the armrest.
</P>
<P>
   So we went to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   With a base price of $14,925, the ES package, automatic
transmission, and sound system pushed the total sticker to $17,775,
maybe not a bargain, but a fair price for a well-equipped car that
packs a ton of performance. Included in all that was cruise
control, air conditioning, power door locks (with keyless remote
entry) and 15-inch aluminum alloy wheels.
</P>
<P>
   If you've never had the experience of keyless entry, you're
missing one of life's little pleasures, one you'll never want to
skip again. I'm hooked. No more fumbling with keys. Just hit the
remote once to unlock the driver's door and a second time to unlock
the other three doors.
</P>
<P>
   Another neat little engineering twist is the cup holder. There's
a little storage area under the heater controls (they're the dial
type). The edge of the storage area is a spring-loaded retainer
that you flip over to create a double cupholder. Of course, if
you're like me, you generally arrive at your destination with
coffee spots on your clothes through no fault of the cupholder.
</P>
<P>
   Staying on the inside, there's adequate room in back, and the
front seats not only were comfortable but had plenty of lumbar
support for a lower back aching mightily from moving snow not only
from my own driveway, but from chopping number one son's Sable out
of a giant frozen ice block where it had been plowed in at the
Wonderland T lot.
</P>
<P>
   Once out on the road, the Protege's power steering has a solid
feel, matching the suspension. Both might be a little harder than
average, but they're perfectly matched to the car's performance
characteristics. The Protege crisply obeyed a quick avoidance
maneuver on Route 93 north, dodging a bumper and trail of debris
from a just-happened accident in the wee hours of Martin Luther
King Day.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't have the car long enough to check the mileage
properly, but the projected 26 city, 30 highway, seemed, if
anything, conservative.
</P>
<P>
   What's not to like?
</P>
<P>
   For one _ and the only _ thing, the door handles. They're too
short to provide enough purchase for proper opening. The handle
generally slipped out of my grip on the first try, then opened fine
on the second attempt.
</P>
<P>
   But then again, this car gets you where you're going fast enough
to allow plenty of time for fiddling with a door.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bill Griffith is assistant sports editor of the Globe and an avid
automobile enthusiast.)
</P>
</TEXT>
