<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4557 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-LANDRY-COX     01-22 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LANDRY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REEVES CREDITS LANDRY FOR HIS SUCCESS
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, JAN. 24
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Dan Reeves played football for the Dallas Cowboys, he
understood the offensive playbook better than some of the coaches.
</P>
<P>
   In Coach Tom Landry's complex system, Reeves was a runner,
passer, blocker and receiver. When there was a trick play to be
made, Reeves usually was part of it. He became the first Cowboy to
score four touchdowns in a game, and some remember him as the most
versatile player to wear the helmet with the star.
</P>
<P>
   Long before Reeves became coaching royalty in the NFL, he was a
player who made the most of his opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves was a quarterback at the University of South Carolina
when he signed with the Cowboys as a free agent in 1965. Unable to
play quarterback in Dallas, he earned points with his willingness
to play a variety of positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan never had great speed, but he was an extremely intelligent
player,'' Landry recalled last week. ``Not only did he know his own
assignments, he knew what every other player was supposed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Landry said the Cowboys were lucky to get Reeves. The Cowboys
had 20 picks in the 1965, but the only two quarterbacks chosen were
Craig Morton and Ernie Kellerman, an unknown player from Miami
(Ohio) who failed to make the team.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves made the roster and quickly became one of Landry's
favorites. He finished his pro career with 1,990 rushing yards, 129
receptions, 25 touchdowns and four knee injuries.
</P>
<P>
   And a burning desire to follow in Landry's footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   It came as little surprise to Landry when Reeves announced his
intention to coach. Reeves played for the Cowboys eight years, long
enough to digest Landry's innovative schemes to football.
</P>
<P>
   He obviously absorbed a lot.
</P>
<P>
   When Reeves leads his Atlanta Falcons in next Sunday's Super
Bowl against favored Denver, he will carry 34 years of NFL
experience. He was a successful player in Dallas, and he been a
winning coach with Denver, the New York Giants and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, who celebrated his 55th birthday on Tuesday, gives
credit to the man with the funny hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I've accomplished as far as coaching is concerned
is related to what I learned from Coach Landry,'' Reeves said. ``I
had no ambitions of ever coaching until I was around him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Landry-Reeves relationship grew during Reeves' 16 years with
the Cowboys. After retiring as a player in 1972, he was hired as a
Cowboy assistant, a position he kept for nine seasons.
</P>
<P>
   During those years the Cowboys were 84-32.
</P>
<P>
   Landry helped his protege get his first head coaching job in
1981. When Reeves was hired by Denver, he became the youngest head
coach _ 37 _ in the history of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 18 years Reeves' teams _ the Broncos, Giants and
Falcons _ have a combined 164-117-1 record. He was named NFL Coach
of the Year for the sixth time last week after leading surprising
Atlanta to the NFC West championship this year.
</P>
<P>
   In the 33-year history of the Super Bowl, Reeves has played or
coached in nine of them.
</P>
<P>
   Landry, who still keeps an eye on the NFL, knows what makes
Reeves successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan's teams are always prepared and ready to play,'' Landry
said. ``When I see his teams, they're all under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Some consider that a hallmark of Landry's old teams. The Hall of
Fame coach was known for having disciplined teams. The Cowboys
rarely were a team that beat themselves, and Landry helped them
reach the Super Bowl five times.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons certainly showed discipline in last week's 30-27
overtime victory against Minnesota in the NFC championship game.
The Falcons finished with only four penalties and two turnovers in
perhaps the league's most exciting game of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   This might be Reeves' best coaching job ever. He has taken a
group that was 3-13 two years ago and placed it in Super Bowl
XXXIII. By comparisons, his teams in Denver and New York had
considerably more talent than Reeves inherited in Atlanta in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   And it Atlanta's most memorable season, Reeves had
quadruple-bypass surgery in December. Showing some of the toughness
Reeves displayed during his playing days in Dallas, he was on his
feet in less than a week, telling reporters of his desire to coach
in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The news of Reeves' sudden hospitalization stunned his former
coach. Landry, 74, spoke to Reeves two weeks ago to make sure his
former assistant was not rushing back to football too quickly.
</P>
<P>
   This was not just another knee injury, Landry told his former
pupil. There are times when rest is the best medicine a workaholic
coach canswallow.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves assured Landry that the heart surgery went well and he
feels great. He did not want to miss the most exciting finish in
Atlanta Falcons history.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves' health was put to the test in the thriller over the
Vikings. Landry, who stays in contact with two of his former
players _ Reeves and New Orleans Sainrs coach Mike Ditka _ admits
he was ``surprised'' by Atlanta's latest victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have advanced to their toughest test of the year,
and Landry promises to watch Super Bowl XXXIII from his Dallas
home. Denver is a seven-point favorite to knock off the Falcons,
but at least one interested viewer gives Atlanta a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised by anything Dan's teams do anymore,'' Landry
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
