A4586 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     01-22 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SECRET OF PRESIDENTIAL SURVIVABILITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How does he do it? How does Bill Clinton take just about the
worst thing that can happen to a president of the United States _
impeachment _ and turn it into a 76 percent job approval rating?
</P>
<P>
   That's the score he racked up in an NBC poll after delivering
his State of the Union address Tuesday night. If the poll truly
reflects public opinion in this country, it means that even as the
president stands trial in the Senate on articles of impeachment
voted by the House of Representatives, three out of every four
Americans are pleased as punch with the job he's doing.
</P>
<P>
   People who don't like Clinton and would like nothing better than
to see his Senate trial end with conviction and removal from office
want to believe that the polls are rigged _ that either the
pollsters are misrepresenting public opinion or the public is being
duped by trick questions that produce pro-Clinton answers.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a news flash, folks: The polls aren't fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans _ even those who believe that Clinton is
ethically and morally inadequate _ are perfectly satisfied with the
job he's doing as president. The same polls that placed Clinton's
job approval in the mid-60s to mid-70s suggested that at least 60
percent of Americans do not want him removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   You might think that such numbers would discourage the
anti-Clinton forces in their relentless campaign to drive him out
of the White House. But it seems that the more the public supports
the president, the more desperate his enemies are to destroy him.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's ability to withstand their attacks makes the
Clinton-haters hate him all the more, which drives them to
intensify their attacks on him, which drives his approval ratings
ever higher, which drives the attackers ever crazier.
</P>
<P>
   None of which answers the question: How does he do it?
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if Clinton's State of the Union speech was a triumph
of spine-tingling rhetoric. It was basically a 77-minute grab bag
of policy proposals, delivered less in the manner of a thoughtful
statesman addressing the nation's future than in the style of a
flashy carnival barker promising spectacular prizes in a ring-toss
game that any fool can see is unwinnable.
</P>
<P>
   Surely those 76 percent of Americans who think Clinton is doing
a great job don't imagine that he will deliver all the goodies he
offered in his something-for-everyone speech.
</P>
<P>
   He vowed to save Social Security and Medicare, reform public
education, solve the race problem, improve health care, increase
the minimum wage, clean up the environment, crack down on crime and
reinvigorate the national defense.
</P>
<P>
   And he was just warming up.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he survives his impeachment trial in the Senate, Clinton
will be in no position to push such an aggressive agenda through a
hostile Congress. Heck, he couldn't turn most of his ideas into
legislation before he was impeached.
</P>
<P>
   So. If most Americans know that Clinton is a scoundrel _ the
polls say they are well aware of his deficiencies _ and they also
know that he can't do all the wonderful things he wants to do, why
do they keep propping him up?
</P>
<P>
   Here's a guess: It's because they actually believe that he cares
about them and their problems. Even this week, as his lawyers were
ferociously battling in the Senate to save his presidency, Clinton
spent his time focusing on the country and on the needs of its
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who don't trust Clinton as far we can throw him
could argue all day long that his devotion to ``real'' issues and
``real'' problems is a ploy _ that it's merely another
manifestation of the con-man charisma that has defined his
presidency from the start. But we'd be wasting our breath.
</P>
<P>
   If people believe that he's sincere, it doesn't matter if he is
or he isn't. Perception is reality _ and countless numbers of
Americans perceive that Clinton cares about them.
</P>
<P>
   They have a right to their perception. And they have a right to
see their president finish the four-year term he won in the 1996
election.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
