A4588 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-     01-22 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND MARQUIS IS BIG AND COMFY
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by CARS-GLANCE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the last big, traditional American sedans, the Mercury
Grand Marquis, is back for 1999, fresh from an update that brought
a more aerodynamic shape and other improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes for the '98 models were new front and rear
fascias, bumpers, grille, hood, deck lid, moldings, park and
turn-signal lights, tail lights and outside mirrors. Sixteen-inch
wheels became standard, second-generation air bags were added, and
the car got a new rear suspension system.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Chevrolet Caprice and Buick Roadmaster have gone away,
the last big rear-drive sedans left in this class are the Grand
Marquis and its Ford counterpart, the Crown Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   Because Lincoln-Mercury dealers sold nearly 110,000 of the Grand
Marquis last year, the vehicle will probably remain in production
for a while; but don't expect them to last much longer. These big
cars will eventually go away, to be replaced by smaller and more
fuel-efficient models (just like Chevy's new Impala, unveiled this
month at the Detroit auto show).
</P>
<P>
   If you really want one, now might be the time to get it.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Marquis reminds baby boomers what cars were like when
we were growing up. Ford understands that the Crown Vic and Grand
Marquis appeal more to our parents than to us, describing the
vehicle as roomy enough to ``take the grandkids to a burger joint
and still feel comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   It is plenty big enough for six adults to stretch out
comfortably, which is tough to do in most other sedans. The trunk
is cavernous, too. A whopping 20.6 cubic feet is available to store
whatever you'd like to take with you on a cross-country cruise.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Marquis comes only with a V-8 engine. The base
4.6-liter single-overhead-cam engine cranks out 200 horsepower and
275 foot-pounds of torque; a dual-exhaust upgrade raises that to
215 horsepower. The engine is connected to a smooth-shifting
four-speed automatic transmission with overdrive; no manual gearbox
is offered.
</P>
<P>
   When you're behind the wheel, the Grand Marquis doesn't feel
like the big boat that it is; it handles pretty well for such a
large vehicle. Still, road handling isn't what a car like this is
all about, so don't expect something that will thrill you on
winding mountain roads. The Grand Marquis is at its best doing 70
mph down the interstate with the cruise control set and Big Band
music playing on the stereo.
</P>
<P>
   I would suggest putting your teen-age children in one of these
as a first car; it's one of the safest vehicles on the road. It
garnered a five-star rating in U.S. government crash tests, ranking
best in class for front-seat occupant safety.
</P>
<P>
   These vehicles don't come cheap, though. The base GS model
starts at $22,220 (plus $605 transportation); our test vehicle, the
uplevel LS model, lists for $24,120 plus transportation.
</P>
<P>
   For that money, the LS comes with power four-wheel disc brakes,
manual air- conditioning, speed-sensitive power steering, keyless
entry, dual power mirrors, rear-window defroster, cruise control,
tilt steering wheel, AM/FM/cassette stereo, power windows and door
locks, eight-way power adjustable driver's seat, luxury cloth
interior, cornering lamps and an automatic parking-brake release.
</P>
<P>
   Our test car came with some options that ran the final sticker
up to $28,745, including transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Ultimate Package'' ($2,400) added electronic instruments,
dual eight-way power seats, antilock brakes, automatic climate
control, leather-wrapped steering wheel, premium AM/FM/cassette
stereo, an electric auto-dim rearview mirror with digital compass
(''Do I go left or right for north, dear?''), and lacy spoke
aluminum wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Other options on our vehicle included leather seats ($735),
trunk-mounted six-disc CD changer ($350), and a handling package
($535) that brought a 3.27 ratio axle, dual exhaust system (this
gave our car the extra 15 horsepower) and rear air suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel economy is a lot better than that of the big cars of the
'60s and '70s. EPA estimates for the Grand Marquis are 17 miles per
gallon in the city and 24 mpg on the highway. With its 19-gallon
gas tank, the vehicle has a range of up to 450 miles.
</P>
<P>
   SILVERADO IS TOP TRUCK: The Texas Auto Writers Association named
the all-new Chevrolet Silverado the ``best truck of Texas'' for
model year 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The pickup won the top honor among 10 awards made by the auto
writers group after testing of 50 trucks and specialty vehicles on
highway, city and off-road courses in Granbury during last
October's Texas Truck Rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the best overall truck honor, the Silverado tied with
its clone, the GMC Sierra, as best large pickup.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the other categories and award winners:
</P>
<P>
   _Best off-road vehicle: Land Rover Discovery II.
</P>
<P>
   _Best luxury sport-utility vehicle: Lexus LX 470.
</P>
<P>
   _Best large sport-utility: Toyota Land Cruiser (a clone of the
Lexus LX 470).
</P>
<P>
   _Best new vehicle and best medium sport-utility: Jeep Grand
Cherokee.
</P>
<P>
   _Best small sport-utility: Isuzu Amigo.
</P>
<P>
   _Best compact pickup: Dodge Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   _Best specialty/all-wheel-drive vehicle: Mercedes-Benz E320 S
wagon.
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III writes on transportation issues for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. His mailing address is
Star-Telegram/Northeast, 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford,
Texas 76021; his E-mail address is chambers(at)star-telegram.com.
Fax: (817) 685-3883. Check out his Wheelin' new-car review column
weekly on the Internet at
ww.netarrant.net/today/news/opinions/necol.htm. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
