<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-GLANCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT A GLANCE: 1999 MERCURY GRAND MARQUIS LS SEDAN
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE PACKAGE: Full-size, four-door, six-passenger, V-8 powered,
rear-drive sedan, which was updated last year along with its Ford
counterpart, the Crown Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHLIGHTS: The Grand Marquis and Crown Vic are the last gasp
for the traditional big sedans carried over from the '60s and '70s;
they are roomy and comfortable, and their trunks are big; they
offer a huge measure of safety.
</P>
<P>
   NEGATIVES: There is nothing sporty or youthful about these cars,
which feel more like police cars and taxicabs than modern family
cars; prices are steep, especially when the most popular options
are added; but they do fill their niche nicely.
</P>
<P>
   MAJOR COMPETITORS: Chrysler LHS, Chrysler 300M, Chrysler
Concorde, Dodge Intrepid, Buick Park Avenue, Pontiac Bonneville,
Toyota Avalon, Oldsmobile Eighty-Eight, Cadillac Deville.
</P>
<P>
   EPA FUEL ECONOMY: 17 miles per gallon city, 24 highway.
</P>
<P>
   BASE PRICE: $24,120 plus $605 transportation.
</P>
<P>
   PRICE AS TESTED: $28,745, including transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD RATING: A.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
