<HEADER>
A4593 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-CYBER-GUIDE-NY     01-22 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-CYBER-GUIDE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SITES OFFER MEDICAL JOURNAL SEARCHES, NARCOLEPSY HELP  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)  
 &HT;    
 BY LINDA CARROLL  
 c.1999 Medical Tribune News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Health information abounds on the Internet, sometimes making it
difficult for the public to find useful, accurate information.
</P>
<P>
   To make this job a bit easier, Medical Tribune News Service
highlights three helpful sites this week.
</P>
<P>
   MEDLINEPLUS
</P>
<P>
   http://medlineplus.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/
</P>
<P>
   For the health consumer who wants to go directly to original
research on a particular topic, MEDLINEPLUS is invaluable.
</P>
<P>
   The site provides easy-to-follow links to search the National
Library of Medicine's huge database of journal articles as well as
links to a variety of other helpful information.
</P>
<P>
   Once you go to the site, you are presented with a list of
medical subjects, from AIDS to menopause to urinary incontinence.
</P>
<P>
   Click on obesity, for example, and you'll be given links to a
Body Mass Index Chart, courtesy of the National Heart, Lung and
Blood Institute; a physical activity and heart disease IQ test,
also courtesy of the NHLBI; and the Weight-control Information
Network's list of the health risks of being overweight.
</P>
<P>
   Click on obesity again and you'll get a listing of the latest
research from 3,900 biomedical journals.
</P>
<P>
   If the subject you're interested in isn't on the list, click on
the word MEDLINE for programs designed to search the journals for
your topic.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond this, the site contains links to dictionaries for
defining medical terms, medical clearinghouses and organizations
devoted to consumer health.
</P>
<P>
   American Medical Association
</P>
<P>
   http://www.ama-assn.org/
</P>
<P>
   The American Medical Association (AMA) site is a curious mix of
consumer-oriented health information and doctor politics.
</P>
<P>
   On the home page, for example, there is a link to an explanation
by the AMA's president of why the Journal of the American Medical
Association dumped its editor after he ``interjected JAMA into a
major political debate that had nothing to do with science or
medicine'' by publishing an article that looked at what American's
mean when they say they've ``had sex.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interesting juxtaposition, the association's webmaster
placed next to this link a pointer to a document entitled the
``AMA's response to the State of the Union Address.''
</P>
<P>
   For members of the general public interested in health
information, the site provides links to JAMA itself and a variety
of health topics, including women's health, men's health and HIV. A
rotating weekly section discusses a health topic tied to a recent
JAMA article.
</P>
<P>
   Click on the women's health section, for example, and you will
be offered a choice of links to abstracts from the latest medical
literature, top news stories, and information on sexually
transmitted diseases and contraception.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the information here is written for the lay person,
while some is highly technical. For example, most of the guidelines
on screening and treatment of sexually transmitted diseases are
lifted directly from Center's for Disease Control and Prevention
Bulletins.
</P>
<P>
   In the men's health section, layperson-friendly articles
describe diagnosis and treatment for a variety of conditions,
including benign prostatic hyperplasia and abdominal hernias.
</P>
<P>
   Center for Narcolepsy at the Stanford University School of
Medicine
</P>
<P>
   http://www-med.stanford.edu/school/Psychiatry/narcolepsy/
</P>
<P>
   If you're one of those people who feels constantly tired and
sleepy, you might want to check out the Center for Narcolepsy's
site. Although experts estimate that one in 2,000 people suffer
from this sleep disorder, many do not get diagnosed until many
years after symptoms first appear.
</P>
<P>
   The site contains lay-person friendly descriptions of narcolepsy
symptoms as well as detailed information on drug therapies and the
latest research into the neurochemical causes of narcolepsy.
</P>
<P>
   Under the topic of research are the latest theories of what goes
wrong in patients with narcolepsy. Discussions are somewhat
technical, but understandable with a medical dictionary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
