u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-22 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIP PRICING WAR PLEASES CONSUMERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the key reasons why personal computers have become so
inexpensive is that the brains within these brains have become much
cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   Microprocessor makers are engaged in a power and price war.
Advanced Micro Devices, with its K6-2 chip, and National
Semiconductor/Cyrix, with its MII processor, are doing battle with
the king of the hill, Intel Corp. In response to those powerful,
low-cost chips, Intel has started selling the Celeron, a variation
of its Pentium II design.
</P>
<P>
   What this means for you, the cash-strapped PC buyer, is that
computers that would have sold a year ago for $2,500-$3,000 are now
going for $900-$1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at two machines that use different, budget chips.
The amount of bang for the buck is impressive.
</P>
<P>
   _ Presario 5190, $1,500, Compaq Computer Corp.: Inside this
mid-priced, mini-tower PC is an AMD K6-2 chip running at 400
megahertz. The K6-2 has some extra code for improving 3-D graphics
and sound called 3D Now!
</P>
<P>
   In theory, that would make this an excellent gamer's machine _
provided the programs being used take advantage of 3D Now! Not all
do.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the machine has plenty of muscle. There's the chip,
which is AMD's fastest so far. It sits on a motherboard that can
pass data to the chip at 100 megahertz. There's a generous 128
megabytes of memory; a 12-gigabyte hard drive; a built-in Iomega
Zip drive; a DVD-ROM drive; a 56K fax modem; an ATI Rage LT Pro
graphics card with four megabytes of video memory; a built-in
Ethernet connection for home networking; Aureal 3D positional
sound; and a connection for a digital flat panel display.
</P>
<P>
   I used this with a 17-inch Presario MV700 monitor, which sells
for only $400.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a system that can handle any kind of software you
want to throw at it, ranging from envelope-pushing 3-D games to
bloatware office suites to Web browsers to graphics editing
programs. It will be a long time before you feel limited in your
capabilities with this system.
</P>
<P>
   With a couple of exceptions, it's a well-designed system. The
Universal Serial Bus ports are on the front of the 5190, which is
smart, because the whole point of USB is convenient connection of
devices. Most manufacturers put these ports on the back of the
case, making it hard to get to.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq has put the graphics adapter on a removable board in an
AGP slot, rather than as a chip on the motherboard. While the ATI
Rage Pro is a decent card, it's not the best out there, but with
this design it can be easily replaced.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pavilion 4450, $900, Hewlett-Packard:  &UR;  &LR; Sub-$1,000 computers
continue to improve as demand for them grows. Computer makers get
smarter about designing them with each product cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard has opted to go with Intel's 366-megahertz
Celeron processor. The Celeron chips, while zippy, run on
motherboards capable of transmitting data only at 66 megahertz.
That makes them less desirable for higher-end applications and
state-of-the-art games.
</P>
<P>
   The Pavilion comes with 64 mebabytes of system memory; a
6.4-gigabyte hard drive; a 32X CD-ROM drive; a 56K fax modem; an
ATI RagePro Turbo video card with 4 megabytes of video memory; and
3-D audio. I tried the 15-inch M50 monitor, which provided an
adequate display at 640-by-480 and 800-by-600 pixel resolution, but
had an annoying flicker at 1,024-by-768.
</P>
<P>
   These specifications are less than the Presario, which costs
almost twice as much. But the Presario doesn't run basic home PC
software noticeably faster.
</P>
<P>
   It's when you begin to demand more of your computer that the
limitations in the Pavilion will show up. If you are the kind of
user who has a Web browser, a word processor and a spreadsheet
going all at once _ and throw in e-mail and maybe a music CD as
well _ then the Pavilion will bog down in performance faster than
the Presario will.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, this is an excellent system for low-impact home
use. It's also fairly well designed, though it lacks some of the
nice touches of the Presario.
</P>
<P>
   The Pavilion has three open slots _ AGP, PCI and ISA. The
graphics adapter is built into the motherboard, but the AGP slot
lets you upgrade the graphics card. You don't have to pull anything
out _ just pop a new card in, and it automatically turns off the
onboard video.
</P>
<P>
   The case is quite small, with an even tinier footprint than the
Presario, and as a result it's fairly cramped inside. I had to
remove the cable for the floppy drive before I could insert a
full-length card in the PCI slot.
</P>
<P>
   I have two minor complaints about this system. It's the second
low-cost HP model I've tried with a very noisy fan. It's very
distracting, and it doesn't need to be that way. Quieter fans don't
add that much cost to a system.
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike the Compaq, the USB connectors are on the back of
the unit. Come on, HP _ move 'em up front!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
