<HEADER>
A4601 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPE-AMERICANCATHOLIC     01-22 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-AMERICANCATHOLICS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. CATHOLICS LOOK FORWARD TO VISIT BY POPE, BUT MANY QUESTION HIS
POLICIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATTHEW BRADY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Next week, hundreds of thousands of people will crowd the
streets of St. Louis to welcome Pope John Paul II to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   But although the pope is widely respected and beloved in the
United States, he is also widely viewed as the chief obstacle to
changes American Catholics would like to see in the church.
</P>
<P>
   That the pontiff finds American excess distasteful is no secret.
He has criticized U.S. military missions in the Persian Gulf and
described Western society as a ``culture of death'' because of its
leanings toward abortion and euthanasia.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, American Catholics chafe under what they consider
John Paul II's authoritarian regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who admire a lot of things about
this pope _ his deep personal piety, the role he has played on the
world stage,'' said John Allen, opinion editor for National
Catholic Reporter, an independent Catholic newspaper based in
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, it is also clear that there is a deep sense
that there are some reforms in the internal life of the church that
are long overdue and that this pope has resisted.''
</P>
<P>
   In the view of observers such as Allen, chief among those
reforms are more inclusive roles for women in the church, increased
freedom to debate church doctrine and increased decision-making
power for local parishes.
</P>
<P>
   But those reforms are unlikely to take place under John Paul II.
Although in form, he is among the most progressive popes in history
_ snow-skiing before health problems forbade it, jetting around the
world, granting an audience to folk/rock star Bob Dylan _ in
substance, John Paul II is stubbornly traditional.
</P>
<P>
   Two events last year highlighted John Paul II's approach.
</P>
<P>
   In June, he issued an apostolic letter tightening restrictions
on theological debate. The letter, titled Ad Tuendam Fidem (''To
Defend the Faith''), outlined penalties ranging up to
excommunication for theologians who questioned church teachings
such as the nonordination of women or abstinence before marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the year, his staff overruled translations of
liturgical texts by U.S. bishops. Critics say it was an effort to
stop gender-neutral language from creeping into the liturgy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just that he has clearly taken stances on certain
issues,'' Allen said. ``He has not allowed conversation to continue
about it. That is incredibly frustrating to people who do not
regard it as a closed issue.''
</P>
<P>
   But Allen and other observers acknowledge that, in many ways,
the pope plays a valuable role. In a world in which the United
States often is seen as the playground bully, doing whatever it
wants whenever it wants, Pope John Paul II has made it clear that
American Catholics are but a fraction _ less than 74 million _ of a
church that counts over 1 billion members worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think we Americans look myopically at the world through
our American lens,'' said Charles Curran, Scurlock professor of
human values at Southern Methodist University. ``I think it is very
helpful to have our position criticized. We've got to recognize
that the church is bigger than us.''
</P>
<P>
   Curran said John Paul II has often achieved uniformity at the
expense of unity, but noted that struggling to strike a balance is
not a problem unique to Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have to realize there have always been tensions in the
church and there always will be,'' Curran said. ``Perhaps the
challenge, which is a very significant challenge, is, `How do we
achieve unity amid so much diversity in the world?' This is not
only a problem for the Catholic Church and the Protestant Church,
it is a problem for the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, if the Christian Church can't accomplish it, no
one can.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
