<SLUG> BC-SHOWER-HEADS-$ADV24-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOOSING THE RIGHT SHOWER HEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 24)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The shower head has become a state-of-the-art
fixture in most homes and apartments.
</P>
<P>
   If you prefer a shower to a bath, you can now select from a
large variety of shower heads, from water-saving and pulsating
water-massage models to safety anti-scald devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time people want a hand-held shower head or a
larger hotel-style shower head that's made of heavy-duty
chrome-plate or brass,'' said Rick DeFries, vice president and
co-owner of Shaker Ace Hardware in Latham, N.Y. ``Most people look
for models that they can get as much water out of as possible,
whether it's in a fine or heavy spray. Personally, I find that the
heavier-weight showerheads and those of solid brass are the most
dependable.''
</P>
<P>
   DeFries said some plastic is basically more resistant to mineral
build-up than shower heads made of metal or inferior plastics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shower heads made of the newer Ceylon pale gray-colored
plastic have less of a tendency to clog up,'' he said. ``But if
you've purchased a shower head that does get clogged up,
restricting water flow, just soak it in any lime-away product or a
50/50 solution of vinegar and warm water.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you live in an area where there is a high sediment content,
you should clean your shower head on a regular basis to maintain
its high performance,'' he said. ``Any little bit of grit will play
havoc with a shower head.''
</P>
<P>
   To prevent burns in the shower, place an anti-scald adapter
between the shower arm and the showerhead. A thin metallic wafer in
the adapter expands at a certain temperature and shuts the water
off if it gets too hot. Anti-scald adapters cost $14.99.
</P>
<P>
   WaterPik makes a showerhead with a 15-inch adjustable snake-like
arm, and claiming to have 124 spray channels, for $53.99 that also
features a pause function to save water while soaping up and
briefly stepping out of the spray.
</P>
<P>
   Shower heads with anywhere from one to six settings cost
approximately $6 to $60 _ and up to $500 in the designer range. A
brass showerhead with adjustable spray sells for $28.99, and a
shower massage model with five settings costs around $55.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 1623EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4630 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-22 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIP PRICING WAR PLEASES CONSUMERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
