<HEADER>
A4636 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRIDE'S-NIGHT-OUT-$AD     01-22 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIDE'S-NIGHT-OUT-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NIGHT THE GIRLS WENT OUT TO PLAY (AND THE BOYS RAN AWAY) 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Jan. 24) 
(JT) 
 By JENNY LYN BADER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My answering machine heard it first: ``Hi! I'm Lucy's maid of
honor. She said the party's up to us, but she definitely wants to
kiss some boys in a bar, and she also wants a stripper, so we're
all chipping in to get him.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows the stuff of bachelor parties: naked women
bursting from cakes, stag films, drunken toasts. Bachelorette
parties, on the other hand, have a reputation for cosmopolitans and
frilly lingerie.
</P>
<P>
   But in a spirit of equality of the sexes, bachelorette parties
seem to be getting more debauched. I have heard of bridesmaids
shopping for sex toys and of parties where women play ``truth or
dare'' in a bar, asking strange men to eat the candy necklaces from
their throats.
</P>
<P>
   And so it happened that we were going to have a stripper at
Lucy's party. But where to hold it? Nobody in our group of
20-something women wanted a strange naked man in her apartment. And
the yuppie bars of the Upper West Side that we asked to play host
to our event turned us down. Offended bar managers hung up on the
maid of honor. ``It was as if I was some kind of pervert,'' she
said. Finally, a dive in the neighborhood said there was room at
the inn. Passing a stuffed bear near the entrance, we found a nook
of tables where we watched Lucy open tasteless gifts, while
awaiting HIS arrival.
</P>
<P>
   The stripper turned out to be a bronzed, pectorally gifted
specimen of Australian descent, complete with business cards that
said ``The Thunder From Down Under.''
</P>
<P>
   Heads turned. Men blushed. Women befriended us. The bride acted
surprised, insisting she'd never requested a stripper. The Thunder
unbuttoned things. He performed suggestive push-ups, then held Lucy
aloft, whispering in her ear.
</P>
<P>
   He gyrated over and asked me to dance. But who wants to lose a
good chair in a crowded bar? I hesitated. He did acrobatics with
the other guests, then looked at me pointedly. What kind of party
pooper was I? A grown man flouncing in leopard underpants was
managing to make me feel ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   So I let the boy toy twirl me around. He inched close and
whispered, ``Now I've got you going.''
</P>
<P>
   That was his sultry spiel? It couldn't have been half as good as
what he kept murmuring to the bride.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing his act, he asked where we were going next.
Dancing, we answered, but didn't say where. The guy was fun, but he
got naked for a living.
</P>
<P>
   We were distracted by the last few minutes of a ball game on the
wide-screen television. I spotted our stripper alone in the corner.
Sweaty and a bit disheveled, he started collecting his belt, socks
and undershirt. Bought, paid for and discarded.
</P>
<P>
   One bridesmaid, after discovering that she and the hired hunk
were both out-of-work actors, invited him to come out with us. He
said he'd have to go home and change first. His trousers were
special stripper's pants with Velcro in lieu of seams. He'd feel
embarrassed wearing them dancing. We lied and told him they looked
normal. He seemed skeptical and never did show up.
</P>
<P>
   At the club, Lucy thought we ought to find kissing partners for
her. This didn't seem terribly hygienic. But more remarkable was
the male reaction. Several asked, ``How many men has she kissed so
far?'' One said, ``I'll only do it if I'm the first.'' Had this
bar-hopper cruising for women been reading Victorian novels? We
just wanted the pure stupid fun we heard the bridegroom's men would
be having. And we wanted it without the guilt. But it was not to
be.
</P>
<P>
   Later, I asked Lucy about the titillating nothings I'd seen
Thunder whispering in her ear. She laughed. ``He kept asking me if
I felt comfortable,'' she said. ``He kept saying, `If any of this
makes you uncomfortable I can stop.'''
</P>
<P>
   Wow. I didn't realize strippers were now politically correct.
Was it possible to harass someone who is paying you to remove your
clothes? I tried to picture a female stripper saying those things.
</P>
<P>
   We've come a short way, baby.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
