<HEADER>
A4639 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV24-     01-22 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO FIND THE PLANTS YOU WANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Jan. 24) 
(JT) 
 By CASS PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ordinarily, I'm a gardener of little design. The vegetables get
some advance planning, because otherwise I might forget I had
already sowed the beets and plant the beans right over the top of
them.
</P>
<P>
   But flower gardens tend just to happen. One perennial bed is a
serendipitous mix of Siberian iris, Russian sage, Carpathian
bellflower and Turk's-cap lily, melded together with drifts of
coral bells, sweet woodruff and forget-me-nots. Most of the plants
were rescued from a garden center's discount shelf at the end of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   A professional designer looks at a garden site, envisions what
it could be, and draws up a list of ideal plants. I look at a plant
in a pot, envision it in the ground somewhere, and go looking for a
place to dig a hole. Garden designers aim for a tapestry effect; my
garden tends more toward sampler. The new raised deck has a
clematis planted at the base of each supporting post, and each
clematis is a different color.
</P>
<P>
   Nuances of flower and foliage inspire collectors, but in the
grand scheme of my oversize yard, these are of secondary
importance. As far as I'm concerned, all hardy azaleas are created
equal, and a day lily of any color or season of bloom is a day lily
worth having. My motto is that if you can't plant what you want _
or you don't know what you want _ plant what you can get. It would
probably sound better in Latin.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, it is occasionally necessary to find a specific
plant, usually at the request of someone else. I'm on the mailing
lists of dozens of nurseries and seed houses, which makes me
something of a neighborhood research facility.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the sleuthing is easy, but often it is not, especially
when the request comes in something like this: ``I want a shrub
like the one Mrs. Phillips has in her front yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed for further information, the plant-seeker recalls that
the shrub blooms in the late spring, with pink flowers, and that
its leaves turn color in the autumn. What color? ``I forget.''
</P>
<P>
   A trip to Mrs. Phillips' yard finds a Kerria japonica, which has
yellow flowers in early spring, and foliage that does not change
color in autumn. Was the plant-seeker thinking, perhaps, of someone
else's yard? ``Oh, no, that's the one. I just forgot what color the
flowers were.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrias are easily acquired, once identified. More troublesome
was a yellow-flowered lilac, tracked down at a wholesale nursery in
the Pacific Northwest that sold them only in groups of 10, at a
price that made the idea of an entire hedge of yellow-flowered
lilacs unappealing.
</P>
<P>
   An orange-flowered rhododendron like the one outside the local
bank could not be identified by cultivar, but the bank people are
friendly and granted permission for a few cuttings to be taken for
propagation purposes.
</P>
<P>
   This business of finding plants used to be more difficult.
Tracking down a specific cultivar, especially on the basis of a
sketchy description, required several large botanical reference
books, a shelf of catalogs and many long-distance telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, the results were hardly guaranteed. A catalog might
describe a particular hibiscus as having lavender blossoms with
rose-colored throats, but the plant itself, once procured, planted
and brought to bloom, might decide that its flowers should be
magenta. This is yet another reason to love what you can get,
rather than yearn for that which you do not have.
</P>
<P>
   At least now, thanks to the humming computer and the Internet,
plant detective work is somewhat easier. The better nurseries even
flash full-color pictures of their wares, the better to tell if
that's really the Euonymus of your dreams or the precise shade of
salmon-apricot-pink azalea needed to set off the house's new
Victorian paint job.
</P>
<P>
   Some quarry remains elusive. Several months ago, I went
cybersearching for a vegetable called crosnes (pronounced crone, as
in a Shakespearean hag) _ a creamy white tuber that looks a bit
like a potato but is wrinkled rather than smooth. It is popular in
Europe, where it is often served creamed, and in Asia, where it is
frequently pickled. A friend had spotted a pile of crosnes in a
grocery store in New Zealand, but was not served any.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary book research turned up its full common name,
crosnes du Japon, although it is' also called Chinese artichoke,
Japanese artichoke and knotroot. Its botanical name is Stachys
affina, although it is' sometimes also listed under Stachys
sieboldii.
</P>
<P>
   It's called a perennial, but that may be because some of the
tubers would naturally escape being harvested. In that sense, it
would be like a Jerusalem artichoke, which isn't an artichoke
either, but another tuberous vegetable that, once planted, is
difficult to eradicate.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet search for Stachys affina, by entering that phrase
in the usual search engines like Yahoo and Alta Vista, turned up
nothing. A search for crosnes found dozens of informative pages,
including recipes for crosnes salad with salsify, crosnes with
bechamel sauce and many others. Unfortunately, all of the pages
were written in French, which I recognize when I see it but do not
read.
</P>
<P>
   I turned to my reliable, if old-fashioned, shelf of catalogs,
and there I found crosnes, listed as Chinese artichokes, in the
estimable catalog from Richter's, herb specialists from Canada
(Goodwood, Ontario, L0C 1A0; 905 640-6677).
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the fine print says the tubers may be shipped only to
Canadians. I will have to be content with Jerusalem artichokes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
