<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4646 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-22 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA PANEL FOULS THE AIR WITH NEW RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R. WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The California Air Resources Board has wrought a lot of misery
in the name of clean air. Now the Specialty Equipment Market
Association, an industry group representing after-market equipment
manufacturers and suppliers to the auto industry, is suggesting
that CARB is ignoring California law in its zeal to destroy old
cars in the name of environmental correctness.
</P>
<P>
   CARB has approved regulations instituting a program to scrap
150,000 cars a year for the next 10 years to meet emissions
reduction goals, SEMA says, but has ignored California law that
dictates parts be recycled under the scrappage rules.
</P>
<P>
   According to Chris Kerting, SEMA vice president of government
affairs, CARB has ignored a San Diego Air Pollution Control
District pilot ``Repair/Upgrade'' program that would achieve
emissions reductions at half the cost of scrappage programs. The
repair/upgrade program allows older cars to be voluntarily
submitted for repair and installation of emissions upgrade retrofit
equipment, SEMA says, thus improving air quality.
</P>
<P>
   The scrappage-only route achieves some unwelcome goals while not
significantly changing air quality. First, it destroys a valuable
parts resource upon which the lower economic classes _ working
poor, we call them _ depend for vehicle repair. The car is
especially important in California, largely devoid of convenient
public transport, for the working poor to get and hold jobs. It
also removes from the planet the sustenance of the old-car hobby _
candidates and parts for restoration.
</P>
<P>
   The cars that are scrapped don't really subtract much dirt from
the atmosphere, SEMA contends, since they are usually vehicles that
have already expired or are on their last legs. Usually they are
replaced by old vehicles that still run and do contribute to poor
air quality _ scrappage alone can be a net loss in air quality.
</P>
<P>
   What SEMA doesn't mention _ and it bears mentioning _ is that
the scrappage program was instituted not simply to clean the air
but to gain ``pollution credits'' for industry. Such credits enable
a business to avoid installing new equipment to reduce its
emissions _ buying time with the credits _ or to make a little
extra cash selling credits it doesn't need to other polluters.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Californians still breathe dirty air. Ever notice how
many antisocial programs are justifed as necessary for the good of
society?
</P>
<P>
   What's important for us in the East to remember is that every
daffy idea CARB floats seems to be embraced in Massachusetts, where
the lads and lasses on Beacon Hill are just as wont to lean on
motorists to take the heat off business.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a similar vein, consider that two Japanese companies, Honda
and Toyota, are about to field low-emissions, high-fuel-economy
hybrid vehicles in the American market. Domestic companies have
been preoccupied with the California-Massachusetts et al. mandate
to peddle electric-only autos and now find themselves one-upped _
again _ by the Japanese. With help from the California
environmental elitists, to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to settle the electric car issue is to mandate that
legislators drive them exclusively during their terms _ especially
in winter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The year 1999 is the centennial of a celebrated automotive event
in New England, the 100th anniversary of the first ascent up Mount
Washington of an automobile. Aug. 31, 1899, Freelan Oscar Stanley
and wife, Flora, drove a spindly little Locomobile up the Carriage
Road to the top of the 6,288-foot peak, New England's tallest and
the place of possibly the freakiest weather in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Locomobile was a 4-horsepower steamer, and the trip to the
mountaintop was both a promotion for the particular make of car and
for the car in general. Freelan and twin brother Francis Edgar
Stanley had founded the steam-car company and sold it to partners
who would run it as Locomobile. Part of the deal was that the
Stanleys promote the car.
</P>
<P>
   The buyers (one a paving contractor whose company is still in
business) fell out within a year, and the Stanleys bought the
patents back and resumed building steamers under the Stanley name.
The Locomobile survived for quite a long time _ as a
gasoline-fueled internalcombustion car.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 8 is the 138th anniversary of the opening of what is now
the Mount Washington Auto Road, and on that date the centennial of
the Locomobile ascent and the opening of the then Carriage Road are
to be celebrated with a reenactment _ sort of. A Locomobile owned
by the road company will be transported to the mountaintop for a
celebration _ but real steamers will drive the route.
</P>
<P>
   Under the auspices of the Stanley Museum, Kingfield, Maine, an
unprecedented gathering for steamers at the mountain is to mark the
event _ mostly Stanleys from just about every year of production
and nearly every model variant, plus a Doble or two, Whites, a
Lane, Locomobiles, and perhaps some other makes. The steam
celebration falls between two other museum events of note, a parts
and car auction on Aug. 7 in Kingfield, and a New Hampshire
steam-car tour following the Mount Washington event.
</P>
<P>
   The public will have access to an exhibit of the steamers at the
mountain during the celebration, and the Mount Washington vehicle
collection. The steamers are to be displayed chronologically by
marque, and the museum is furnishing catalogs with technical
information on the cars to be given visitors as part of the
admission package.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the old steamers are expected to make the ascent, and
they will face the same daunting problem that Freelan and Flora
faced _ getting down again. While Stanley is believed to have used
a log drag to slow his car on the descent, the Stanleys will likely
be using tractors _ other vehicles with tow ropes _ to ease them
down the mountain. The Mount Washington Auto Road is a formidable
ascent or descent, one that some modern cars are prohibited from
attempting, and very hard on brakes; drivers are advised to rely on
the transmission to control descent speed rather than risk
overheating the brakes. But the view is worth it _ terrifying from
a car seat, but still worth it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Touring Club of New England and the New England
Region-Sports Car Club of America have scheduled a winter rally for
Feb. 6. ``Snow &AMP; Ice 99'' kicks off from the Fairfield Inn,
Concord/Bow, N.H. (exit 13 off Interstate 93) at 8:30 a.m.
Saturday, Feb. 6, for a 175-mile time-speed-distance rally _ a
rally is a driving competition, not a race. Beginners are welcome.
Cost is $50 per car (two-person team), $45 for club members. For
information or resgistration, telephone rallymaster David Lewis at
978-386-2268.
</P>
<P>
   It's a great way to shed the cabin fever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
