<HEADER>
A4655 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ON-THE-ROAD-NYT &LR;      01-22 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-THE-ROAD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RV NATION: HITTING THE ROAD AND STAYING THERE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada)  (mk) 
 By TOM CHAFFIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consider them latter-day nomads. Or maybe, come to think of it,
more like venerable turtles, who carry their homes on their backs.
</P>
<P>
   They are the hundreds of thousands of elderly and retired people
who take to life on the road, spending all or much of the year
wandering around North America in assorted trailers, converted
buses, campers and motor homes.
</P>
<P>
   They are full-time RV'ers, say Dorothy Ayers Counts and her
husband, David Counts, anthropologists who have studied what's
known as recreational vehicle culture. And _ please, they add _
don't confuse RV'ers with people who live in so-called trailer
parks; the latter's houses may arrive on wheels, but once hooked-up
in a trailer park, that's the end of their travels. Exclude, too,
those whose migratory work put them in RVs. As Ms. Counts said in a
recent interview, ``We're interested in the ones who live to
travel, not those who travel to work.''
</P>
<P>
   RV'ers in North America, their numbers estimated at 1 million to
2.5 million, inhabit a sort of dispersed republic of aluminum and
rubber. The RV polity seems in many ways as vast, quirky and
diverse as any explored by Alexis de Tocqueville. Like any country,
RV republic teems with organizations. The largest RV support group,
the Good Sam Club, boasts 936,000 member families. Other groups
cater to more specific constituencies, including singles,
baby-boomers, religious denominations and retired submariners.
</P>
<P>
   Avid tent campers themselves, the Counts opened their file on
RV'ers in 1982 out of curiosity about the seemingly ubiquitous
procession of elderly and retired people sojourning in trailers
whom the couple met while traveling. For the two anthropologists,
who ended up writing ``Over the Next Hill: An Ethnography of RVing
Seniors in North America'' (Broadview Press, 1996), the stories the
RV'ers told about life on the road posed more questions than they
answered. How, for instance, do they manage finances during their
wanderings? Or get mail? And what about health care? And don't they
get lonely so far from family and friends?
</P>
<P>
   Tent-trailers, the predecessors of today's larger metal
carapaces, first appeared in the 1920s and were the conveyances of
choice among elite campers. Not until the next decade's Great
Depression, when transients began to use them, did car-campers lose
their once genteel image. Today's RV'ers are typically retired
couples who enjoy travel and owning a home but who cannot afford
both.
</P>
<P>
   Among RV'ers, how best to manage the pursuit of happiness
remains a lively debate. Some prefer developed campsites with
water, electricity and sewage hookups. Others prefer boondocking,
squatting free without the amenities in any open area, whether it
be a Kmart parking lot or a stretch of desert. Some RV'ers like to
stay put for weeks; others are afflicted by ``hitch-itch,'' the
compulsion to hitch up each day for a new destination.
</P>
<P>
   The Counts set off to research RV'ers in 1990 by renting an old
trailer for two and a half months, camping and talking with RV'ers.
A second, longer trek, in 1993-94, took them still deeper into the
RV world. In ``Over the Next Hill,'' RV'ers emerge as a proud,
often stubborn, lot who feel misunderstood, even put upon, by
immobile society. They complain about age and class prejudices: 37
percent of the 369 respondents to a project questionnaire were 66
or older, 64 percent had an annual income of $20,000 or less.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever romantic affection North Americans otherwise display
for life's vagabonds falls short of RV campgrounds. RV'ers complain
that outsiders link them with a host of unsavory societal images.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Counts described most RV'ers as ``profoundly conservative
with a small c.'' The Counts admire what they call the RV'ers ``zen
affluence,'' their ability, mandated by cramped conditions, to live
with few material possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Counts, who is 61, teaches at the University of Waterloo in
Ontario. Counts, 64, teaches at nearby McMaster University. While
both balk at any suggestion that they have, in anthropological
lingo, ``gone native,'' they do readily confess to being
enthusiastic RV converts. They recently bought their second rig, a
20-foot Bigfoot fifth-wheel travel trailer. When time allows,
combining pleasure and research, the couple and Perdita, their
Great Pyrenees dog, enjoy exploring the lower 48's Great Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Why not stay in a motel? ``What people say is, if you stay at a
motel, how many friends do you make?'' Ms. Counts explained.
Devotees, she said, also feel that RVing provides a balance between
freedom and community. ``We think they are willing to extend trust
and help to other RV'ers because they are basically independent and
can move on if the commitment becomes too intense,'' she said.
``When folks get too demanding, they can turn their key and move
on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
