<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLOCK23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OHIO CLOCK STANDS SENTINEL TO HISTORY
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Once again, the Senate's enigmatic Ohio Clock is
standing sentinel to history.
</P>
<P>
   Located in a tiled foyer outside the Senate chamber, the
12-foot-tall mahogany clock overlooks the frantic moments of
interplay between participants and reporters during the brief
breaks in the impeachment trial of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   With the media action having moved from the federal courthouse
here to the Senate, the corridor has become the ``Monica Beach'' of
the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio Clock has long been a key meeting point for journalists
and senators. Ticking faithfully since 1816, the clock was the
official Senate timekeeper in bygone decades. Capitol lore has it
that senators stashed bootleg whiskey in its wooden base during
Prohibition. Terrorists are believed to have hidden explosives near
the clock before a 1983 bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Now still photographers _ banned from the Senate chamber during
the trial _ while away the hours between breaks in portable seats
set up beside the clock. Reporters covering the trial rush down
from the third floor press gallery for hurried interviews when
Chief Justice William Rehnquist approves a respite inside the
second-floor chambers. TV technicians set up for evening press
conferences.
</P>
<P>
   No one is quite sure how the Ohio Clock got its name. In 1803,
Ohio became the 17th state admitted to the Union, and there are 17
stars on the shield carved into to clock casing. Thus, a myth arose
that the clock came to the Capitol in commemoration of the
admission of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   However, when the clock arrived in 1816, there were already 19
states in the growing country. One of the clock's 17 stars is also
different from the other 16, prompting suspicions of Buckeye State
boosterism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real origin of the clock's name is unknown,'' concedes the
official Senate Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   Still photographers are hardly happy with their forced stakeout.
The trial is being covered live by TV, radio and print. Newspaper,
wire service and magazine photographers must make do with hurried
shots of senators, presidential lawyers and House managers walking
past the Ohio Clock on their ways into and out of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might as well be covering the Oscars,'' freelance
photographer Chuck Kennedy complained to Roll Call, a Capitol Hill
newspaper. ``At least at the Oscars, you're covering nice suits and
gowns.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
