<HEADLINE>
SNOWSHOES BECOME HOT FASHION FOR WINTER ATHLETES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUZZ GRAY  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GABRIELS, N.Y. _ Arms pumping, legs kicking, Birger Ohlsson
huffs and puffs his way through the chilly powder. Despite those
sled-like baskets strapped to his Nikes, the man is covering ground
like a racehorse.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to break 60 seconds in 400 meters,'' Ohlsson, 30,
said after finishing first in one of the sprints last Saturday at
the Bobcat Snowshoe Race west of Saranac Lake in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ohlsson is like more and more elite runners. He discovered the
sport of snowshoeing and embraced it with enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people take to it right away,'' said Jim Tucker, who
calls himself Dean of Fun at Paul Smith's College and is a driving
force for the sport. ``I've been enjoying snowshoes all my life.
It's only natural when you live up here.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucker's race last weekend, which attracted more than 30
entrants of all ages and sizes, is but the tip of a snowshoeing
iceberg that has sailed into view during the last few winters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's easy and it's fun,'' said Marta Tebbutt of Rainbow
Lake, a snowshoeing neophyte who was born and raised in steamy
Colombia. ``I moved up here with my husband and soon found out
about snowshoes.''
</P>
<P>
   She mistook them for tennis rackets or oversized fly swatters.
With their bright colors, lightweight aluminum frames and diversity
of design, snowshoes of today barely resemble their wooden
ancestors, which date back centuries. ``I didn't have any trouble
at all,'' said Josh McDougall, 13, who zipped around the
8,000-meter cross-country course at the Bobcat event at the Sports
Annex of Paul Smith's, which teaches winter sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time I've competed in snowshoes and liked it
right away.'' McDougall, who is schooled at home in his rural
community of Peru, is a member of the national Junior Olympic
cross-country running team. Snowshoeing, therefore, was a perfect
fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started as a way of augmentation for my runners, then it
developed its own life,'' Mark Elmore said in explaining the
Beekmantown Eagles, a thriving snowshoeing club near Plattsburgh.
``As a high school track coach, I was looking for a way for the
kids to stay in shape during the winter. Pretty soon, they were
winning more medals at snowshoeing than running.''
</P>
<P>
   As a discipline still in its infancy, snowshoeing doesn't harbor
a large body of rules and records. The North American Snowshoe
Classic, one of the major events in the sport, began only 12 years
ago at Paul Smith's. It was known as the Sherpa World Cup then,
when 135 athletes from 15 countries competed.
</P>
<P>
   George Bosworth, founder of the United States Snowshoe
Association, conceived the event, with Tucker an avid supporter. It
caught the attention of Sports Illustrated magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snowshoeing has become a popular sport at Paul Smith's,'' said
Jeff Langmaid, a student. ``It's readily available.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't hurt that the type of student to attend the remote
college also is likely to be attracted to snowshoeing. Ajith
Fernando of Sri Lanka, an island nation in the Indian Ocean, was a
new student in Tucker's class back in the early 1990s when he was
exposed to snowshoeing.
</P>
<P>
   Several medals later, Fernando is hooked. Now a travel agent in
New York City, he still snowshoes every chance he gets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our events share some of the characteristics of a flea market
and small-town carnival,'' Tucker said. ``Hot food vendors mix with
those selling wool outer garments.''
</P>
<P>
   The low-key nature of events fosters friendships and common
purpose. ``Everyone seems willing to help and make suggestions,''
said Lisa McDougall, a mother of three who quickly found herself
comfortable in a pair of snowshoes. ``I wasn't planning on doing
it, but everyone looked like they were having so much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Good snowshoes aren't cheap (at least $100), but they are almost
indestructible. Some manufacturers even will make repairs free of
charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been wearing the same pair for years,'' Elmore said. ``I
think they're bulletproof. I expect I'll wear out before they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so for the sport, which appears to be on a steep rise.
``Snowshoe athletes race for the competition and opportunity to
measure their conditioning and training, rather than for
international honor and glory,'' Tucker said. ``That's not so bad.
I'll take a quiet walk in the woods any day instead of governing
bodies and their politics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 1657EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4715 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARS-WEBSITES-2NDTAK     01-22 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARS-WEBSITES-2NDTAKE-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: and image.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Her book column is sponsored by Amazon.com. Bolanos said that
more than a million have visited the three-month-old site, and she
already has thousands of members who pay $19.95 a year for a Cindy
CD-ROM and an autographed photo _ ``a $39.95 value,'' the site
exclaims.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Easton, the Los Angeles writer, said Schwarzenegger is
planning to create a top-quality site, which can cost around
$150,000 to start up and about $50,000 a year to run. The site will
be nonprofit and will include such features as a list of
Schwarzenegger's favorite CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, Ms. Easton said, it may offer a high-tech variation
on an old carnival attraction _ photographs of Schwarzenegger
hugging a ``friend'' _ a scanned-in photo of the fan's face. If all
goes well, Ms. Easton said, Schwarzenegger may introduce a
for-profit site based on his favorite sport, skiing.
</P>
<P>
   For the increasing numbers of celebrities who fashion themselves
as entrepreneurial corporations, Web sites are a means of direct
marketing. Ms. Henner intends to sell copies of her new self-help
book, ``30-Day Total Health Makeover,'' (Reagan Books, $22) via her
Web page as soon as copies are ready this spring. Ms. Seymour's
site will help promote a series of children's books, which she
wrote with her husband, James Keach, an actor.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Trumper, who helps run William Morris' new six-person
department to advise celebrities on their Internet presence, said
clients can also benefit from the demographic research a site can
provide. ``Let's say an actor wants to lobby for a particular movie
role and the studio is unsure she has a good enough fan base,'' he
said. ``If she has a Web site, she can actually prove that she has
hundreds of thousands of fans. And she can prove to the studio that
they're the right fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Some celebrities are drawn by the lure of the bully pulpit.
Barbra Streisand was exposed to the Internet when she did a
``chat'' on America Online in October, shortly before the
elections. Her manager, Martin Erlichman, said she was excited by
the reaction she got.
</P>
<P>
   America Online gave her a temporary Web page soon after, on
which she posted the text of her speech in support of Rep. Barbara
Boxer, D-Calif., and a list of other candidates from across the
country she supported. Erlichman said that 80 percent of Ms.
Streisand's political choices triumphed in last November's
elections. She was so excited, Erlichman said, that she decided to
hatch her own site.
</P>
<P>
   Setting up a Web site can be harder for stars than for their
fans. First, there is the issue of ``domain name,'' the identifying
address for every site. Anyone can own a domain name merely by
registering it with a quasi-governmental agency called Internic,
for a small processing fee, on a first-come basis. But often when
celebrities decide to set up their own site, they find that their
name has already been snatched up.
</P>
<P>
   An Internic search shows that BradPitt.com is owned by Khalib
Alzarooni of the United Arab Emirates. When he was setting up his
site, as a safeguard, Schwarzenegger registered 31 variations of
his name to account for potential misspellings.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the name is registered by a fan, but often the culprit
is a cyberheister, as they're commonly called, betting that one day
the celebrity will come calling to make a deal. Alzarooni, for
example, has not put up a site for Pitt. Internic regulators frown
on such tactics, but often celebrities relent.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Henner bought Marilu.com for an undisclosed amount. Ms.
Crawford was luckier, she only had to ask nicely to get Cindy.com
back from the company that had registered the name.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the issue of photo rights. Most photographs are
owned by the publication that printed them or the photographer.
Fans blithely scan them onto their sites, but aren't often
prosecuted since they don't have much money and aren't worth suing.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrities, however, are another matter. ``If I put up pictures
from a magazine, a lawyer would be on the phone to me in a
second,'' Ms. Crawford said. ``I have to go through all the steps
of clearing them. Which means that right now there are some fan
sites that have more pictures of me than my own site does.''
</P>
<P>
   Another lesson some celebrities are learning is that even in
cyberspace, fans can be very demanding. While the medium allows the
celebrities to answer frequently asked questions en masse with a
single posting (``They all want to know how I got started,'' Ms.
Crawford said), most stars also get thousands of private messages a
week on their site. Ms. Crawford answers only a handful.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike old-fashioned letters, which generations of fans sent
with little hope of hearing back, e-mail seems to demand an
immediate response. Ms. Henner said: ``If I don't change the
recipes on my site often enough, I get a ton of nasty mail from
people who take it personally. And if I don't e-mail them back,
they get even madder. It's great in a way, but it's also a little
scary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 1700EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
