</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Jan. 24, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Scheduled for the dress page &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   NEW-WORLD-ORDER-REVIEW (Washington) _ The new world order that
was confidently predicted when communism collapsed a decade ago is
nowhere to be seen. Around the world, crises pile up, and the
resulting headlines are not pretty. International organizations
from the U.N. to NATO seem powerless. Streams of important people
go humbly to the feet of Saddam, Gadhafi, Milosevic, Hun Sen to beg
for a modicum of good behavior. What happened? By Barbara
Crossette. (`i' category).
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD-BLACKLIST-REVIEW (Hollywood) _ Elia Kazan, one of
America's greatest film and theatrical directors, is scheduled to
receive an honorary Oscar at the 71st annual Academy Awards in
March. It will not only serve as the most prestigious honor of
Kazan's career but, in many ways, spell the end of the tormented
legacy of the 1950s Hollywood blacklist. By Bernard Weinraub. (`a'
category)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Also moving in the `a' category: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-WITNESSES-REVIEW (Washington) _ It seems likely that
witnesses will be called at President Clinton's impeachment trial.
In interviews with The New York Times, four lawyers who have
followed the proceedings assess the advantages and dangers for both
sides. By Jill Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   WITCH-HUNT-REVIEW (Undated) _ With all the current hyperbole _
``witches' brew'' was the term used last week by White House
counsel Charles Ruff to describe the impeachment charges against
President Clinton trial _ it might be useful to reflect on the days
back in the 13th through 16th centuries when a witch hunt was
really a hunt for witches.
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORTS-XRAYS-REVIEW (Undated) _ It seemed like a good idea:
Customs Service officials at airports in New York and Miami began
offering suspicious travelers the choice between the traditional
but humiliating strip search or a modern, hi-tech X-ray search. To
officials' surprise, many are opting for the good old strip search.
By Alan Finder.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Also moving in the `i' category: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS-REVIEW (Jerusalem) _ With Labor and Likud facing
deep identity crises and new parties constantly forming, Israel is
producing a new multi-party system that is chaotic and will make it
difficult to build and sustain a lasting government coalition. But
the trend is a political expression of something more deepseated,
what many have called a new tribalism that is eroding the
traditional singleminded unity of an Israeli people devoted to
Zionism above all. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   CASPIAN-POWER-REVIEW (Istanbul) _ With the discovery of great
energy reserves around the Caspian Sea, not only offers oil
companies the prospect of great wealth. It gives outside powers a
place to test their strength. The U.S. States, Russia, Iran and
other countries are waging strong campaigns to win decisive
influence in the Caspian. These grand rivalries have turned the
Caspian into the world's newest stage for big-power politics. By
Steven Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   MISSILES-REVIEW (Washington) _ Ever since Richard Nixon and
Leonid Brezhnev signed it in 1972, the Anti-Ballistic Missile
Treaty has been one of the cornerstones of arms control. Its
fundamental premise, which held throughout the Cold War, was that
limiting missile defenses limited offensive missiles. Now, the
cornerstone has crumbled a bit. A look at the new theory of missile
defense. By Steve Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-PHOTOS-REVIEW (Phnom Penh) _ When the Khmer Rouge
seized power in 1975, cameras were among the artifacts of
technology that were banned. Only a handful of officially approved
photographers were allowed to operate. One of them, Nhem Ein, left
behind a stunning body of work: some 7,000 portraits of horror. By
Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Weekends, Ned Kilkelly (e-mail, kilkelly(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
