<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4727 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACTORS-FACTS24-COX     01-22 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACTORS-FACTS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 24
 &HT;    Atlantans onstage The wages of art
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Below are local theaters' wage scales as set forth by
Actor's Equity, the stage actors union headquartered in New York.
There are 250 Equity members in the Atlanta area.
</P>
<P>
   Equity members are almost always paid more than non-Equity
actors but may find themselves ``overpriced'' for a financially
pinched theater when less expensive actors of comparable talent are
available. Thus, many actors opt not to join the union, preferring
a larger choice of roles to the higher paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   SMALL PROFESSIONAL THEATERS (SPT)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Theaters covered ART Station, Shakespeare Tavern, Horizon
Theatre, Theatre in the Square, 7 Stages
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Typical weekly range, including non-Equity actors $125-$300.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Equity weekly minimum $194-$275, plus benefits. Figures vary
from theater to theater.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Comments These theaters agree to use a set minimum of Equity
actors in every show in return for low-wage minimums. Rehearsal
weeks may be more than 40 hours, performance weeks as short as 16
hours.
</P>
<P>
   GUEST ARTIST (GAC)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Theaters covered Actor's Express, Georgia Ensemble Theatre,
Theatre Gael, Jewish Theatre of the South.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Typical weekly range, including non-Equity actors $100-$250.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Equity weekly minimum $330,
</P>
<P>
   plus benefits.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Comments These are not official Equity theaters such as SPTs,
so although they offer higher minimums it's for fewer actors, and
not in every show. Mostly they use non-Equity actors.
</P>
<P>
   LETTER OF AGREEMENT (LOA)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Theaters covered Georgia Shakespeare Festival, Jomandi
Productions, Theater
</P>
<P>
   Emory, Theatrical Outfit
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Typical weekly range, including non-Equity actors $200-$400.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Equity weekly minimum $300-$440,
</P>
<P>
   plus benefits.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Comments See SPT. Agreement is to work toward the higher actor
wages of the League of Resident Theaters (below).
</P>
<P>
   LEAGUE OF RESIDENT THEATERS (LORT)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Theaters covered Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Typical weekly range, including non-Equity actors $500-$600.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Equity weekly minimum $550,
</P>
<P>
   plus benefits
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Comments These flagship theaters (there is typically one per
major city) agree to draw a high proportion of their actors from
Equity for every show.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Sources The Atlanta office for Actor's Equity and interviews
with actors and producers
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
