<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4730 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACTORS24-1stTAKE-COX     01-22 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACTORS24-1stTAKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 24
 &HT;    As city's theater scene thrives, fiscal recognition remains
thespians' thorniest problem
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the 32 actors of ``The Grapes of Wrath'' take
their bows on the stage of the Alliance Theatre, leading theater of
the Southeast, it's a moving moment _ for reasons beyond the power
of the play itself.
</P>
<P>
   Moving, because 31 of them are Atlantans.
</P>
<P>
   As the ovation swells and these inhabitants of John Steinbeck's
saga stand and gaze back at the audience, their pride is a palpable
force, filling the room. Only a decade ago it would have been
impossible to cast the epic with so many, so talented, who call
this city home.
</P>
<P>
   Across town, at Actor's Express, the acting is no less exciting
in Dostoyevsky's ``The Devils.'' There, too, the curtain calls are
emotional, for among the 15 Atlanta actors are several whose
talents are fully realized for the first time under the brilliant
director Chris Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   These productions are only the leading edge of the groundswell.
There are an estimated 1,000 actors who show up for local
professional theater auditions each year. This week alone, scores
of them all over the metro area will practice the 3,000-year-old
craft of Thespis, the first professional actor. You can see
seasoned pros in Marietta (Ga.), at Theatre in the Square (``Cash
on Delivery,'' a saucy British farce); in Atlanta, at 7 Stages
(``States of Shock,'' an eerie Sam Shepard drama) and the Horizon
Theatre (``Mere Mortals,'' a witty David Ives brain teaser); and in
Roswell (Ga.), at Georgia Ensemble Theatre (``Crimes of the
Heart,'' a warm Southern comedy). Next month, Jomandi Productions
will bring back ``Sisters,'' an original comedy that has won hearts
all over the country thanks to its fine Atlanta players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very strong pool _ we can do almost anything with
the actors in Atlanta,'' says Vincent Murphy, artistic director of
Theater Emory. He should know. The Boston-bred Murphy mounted one
of the fall's best-acted productions, ``Cockfighter,'' at PushPush,
a theater in the Floataway factory complex that's so new and small
it doesn't even have a formal relationship with Actors' Equity, the
stage actors union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta actors have grown to the point where, when I go to New
York, the performances seem more surface-y, actor-y,'' says Lisa
Adler, who runs the 15-year-old Horizon with husband Jeff. ``Our
actors seem more genuine and connected to life, even in a spiritual
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   If Atlanta actors are indeed more grounded, it may reflect an
Atlanta lifestyle that is healthier for the inner life of an artist
than New York (if not always as intellectually stimulating) and may
even be better for the artist's mind than Los Angeles. In those
cities the rat race can consume every conversation, as horrific
rents come due and actors clamor desperately for roles, much like
the Vietnamese civilians begging for a place on the escape
helicopter of ``Miss Saigon.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Stephens, Ma Joad in ``The Grapes of Wrath,'' has
established herself in New York and Chicago enough that she can
field phone offers and live where she chooses. She chooses Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Atlanta, no one's waiting to rip your guts out,'' says
actress-director Shannon Eubanks (Roswell's ``Crimes of the
Heart''), a native Charlestonian who has worked extensively in Los
Angeles. ``Even the actors you're reading against give you hugs.''
</P>
<P>
   The brutal bottom line
</P>
<P>
   So what drives actors away from Atlanta? Often it's money _ or
at the least the illusion of making more of it. Apart from
Broadway, theater wages are woefully, insultingly low. ``This ain't
the NBA,'' cracks actor-producer Tom Key.
</P>
<P>
   Equity reports that its 36,000 members nationally earn an
average of less than $15,000 a year from stage work. In Atlanta _
where there are 250 dues-paying Equity members and hundreds of
actors choose not to join Equity because it limits their choice of
roles _ the average yearly stage income is probably half that.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that during a 12-month period, a local Equity actor in
demand might get one Alliance role (seven weeks at $600 per week),
one medium-theater role (seven weeks at $350) and two smaller roles
(14 weeks at $250) for a grand total of 28 weeks and $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lucky actor. One of the fortunate handful.
</P>
<P>
   True, during performance weeks, an actor may be in the theater
as little as 16 hours (few Atlanta theaters can draw enough
audience on Tuesdays and Wednesdays to even open their doors on
those nights). But the standard three weeks' rehearsal can be
brutal, culminating in the dreaded ``10 out of 12''-hour days, the
theater's equivalent of ``two-a-day'' football workouts. Not only
do some producers pay less for rehearsal than performance, but they
increasingly shave days off rehearsal or replace rehearsal days
with preview performances, arguing that audience feedback helps
actors' preparation more than rehearsal in front of empty seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``But are we ready for an audience?'' asks Lorilyn Harper, who
moved from Dallas two years ago with actor-husband Chris Paul (both
are in ``Cash on Delivery'') because they were so impressed, and
still are, with what they'd seen and heard about the Atlanta
theater market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three weeks is not enough for developing a textured
performance,'' she adds, ``especially in the classics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, these are the '90s,'' cries Eubanks sarcastically. ``It's
all about cost efficiency!''
</P>
<P>
   Nature of the beast
</P>
<P>
   No producer, nor anyone else, is getting rich from this cheap
labor. In order to preserve the intimate experience of theater,
there can only be so many seats (an average of 200 for most Atlanta
houses) and thus only so much revenue. Theater by definition is
labor-intensive: Each performance is created from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   This built-in economic straitjacket ensures that only on
Broadway can stage actors attain middle-class wages ($1,000 a week
minimum) or riches ($30,000 a week for a musical superstar such as
Jerry Lewis or Glenn Close), because higher ticket prices and more
weekly performances support the payroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``An actor friend once told me to go to a producer to demand
more money,'' says La La Cochran, starring in Horizon's ``Mere
Mortals.'' ``And the producer said, `I don't have it.' And I
stopped, took a deep breath, and said, `Of course you don't.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 1706EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4731 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACTORS24-2NDTAKE-COX     01-22 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACTORS24-2NDTAKE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA: course you don't.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Back to reality
</P>
<P>
   So, having resigned themselves to the necessity of a day job,
how do Atlanta actors get by? The short answer: any way they can.
</P>
<P>
   Agnes Harty (``The Devils'') must ``go straight home after the
play, otherwise how am I going to get to work (as an administrative
assistant) by 8:30 every day and still keep my energy up?'' Sean
Daniels, when not serving as artistic director at Dad's Garage or
organizing its ``8 1/2 x 11'' showcase of young directors, can be
found tending bar at that Little Five Points (Ga.) warehouse. Jared
Simon (``Conversations With My Father'' at Jewish Theatre of the
South) has a chiropractic practice and not much spare time, so he
must be selective about his roles. LaParee Young (``Grapes'') has
shot several film and TV roles around the South, but they are so
erratic that the 42-year-old had to wait tables last year.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there's truth to the old waiter stereotype: Scores of
Atlanta actors scrape by on tips. Of course, film, TV and
commercials, which can pay thousands of dollars for a few days'
work, are the day job of choice for most Atlanta actors, but they
are tough to get, and their producers have no patience for ``I have
to be back at the theater by 7.'' Elizabeth Wells laughs as she
recalls the time she slipped away from the Alliance's ``A Christmas
Carol'' on her day off for a movie shoot in Charleston, only to
find that the other actor in her scene was ``Carol's'' Al Hamacher,
similarly moonlighting. Afemo and Elizabeth Omilami used to be
frequently seen performers at such theaters as the Alliance and
Jomandi, but now one of them is on the road almost constantly _
especially up to Wilmington, N.C., hottest film center of the South
_ while the other stays home with the kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love the theater but can so rarely afford to do it,'' Afemo
says.
</P>
<P>
   Family matters
</P>
<P>
   Temp work, especially in word processing, ``fills the gaps,''
Harper says, but she and Paul, in their late '30s, decided not to
start a family because, ``our working schedule would not be fair to
a child.'' Still, many theatrical couples decide to stay in Atlanta
precisely because it's a better place to raise a child on a limited
income than most theatrical markets.
</P>
<P>
   Heidi Cline, actress and artistic director of Soul-stice
Repertory, says that she and actor-director husband Hudson Adams
have a ``dream life'' with an infant daughter, a Decatur (Ga.)
lakeside ranch house and artistic variety. A dream life, if one
doesn't mind a killer schedule. Cline commutes to Rome (Ga.) to
teach at Berry College, Adams works at Kinko's four nights a week
and they trade off babysitting assignments at all hours of the day
and night. ``Our toughest financial time is when we are producing
Soul-stice,'' Cline writes in an e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not think children were an option for us,'' she
continues, ``until I looked around and saw (theater couples) Teri
and Chris Kayser, Teresa DeBerry and Allen O'Reilly, John Ammerman
and Kathleen McManus (the latter two couples do some form of
teaching by day). I think we all kept looking at each other
thinking, `If they can do it, so can we.' And we're making it.''
</P>
<P>
   A modest proposal
</P>
<P>
   Of course, nonprofit theaters by definition do not earn all
their revenue at the box office, often getting up to 40 percent of
their income through corporate and individual gifts. Why are these
gifts almost never earmarked for artist wages?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've asked this of a number of funders,'' says Express
director Chris Coleman, ``and naturally they're concerned that
artists might leave the city. Facilities, bricks and mortar; stay
put. Our job is to convince funders that actors, too, are a vital
community investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Peck, 64, one of the rare actors able to practice his craft
in Atlanta for 30-plus years (crediting his higher-earning wife for
the privilege) has seen many less fortunate colleagues flee Atlanta
for the movie money of the West Coast. He asks: why not corporate
sponsorships for individual actors? Under Peck's modest proposal,
an actor would receive, say, $50,000 for an entire year of acting
assignments at various theaters, relieving those theaters of the
burden of paying him or her. For the rest of the actor's normal
working hours, he or she would teach a master class in acting under
the corporate banner, an even more vaulable role to the community
at large.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work could only get better,'' Peck argues, ``once the
actor isn't living in constant financial anxiety.''
</P>
<P>
   Why they do it
</P>
<P>
   And yet the lack of such grants _ or indeed of any financial
incentive whatever _ cannot stop thespians from coming back to the
purest form of their craft _the stage.
</P>
<P>
   When Harper and Paul finish their temp shifts on a Thursday
afternoon and head off to their theater gigs, ``I feel sorry for
the people in those offices who hate their work and live only for
the weekends,'' Harper says, ``That's when I feel lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Culpepper, who pockets a six-figure income as perhaps the
premier voice-over man in the Southeast _ his is that rugged
baritone extolling the toughness of Ford trucks, for example _ has
announced more retirements from the stage than the late Frank
Sinatra did from singing. Yet he was recently dragged back into
service by independent producer Chad Darnell for a virtually unpaid
gig in ``The Lizzie Borden Story'' as the oft-whacked Mr. Borden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Applause is an enormous high,'' Culpepper says. ``Theater is
so much more alive than a microphone.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
