<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4735 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-Y2K23-COX     01-22 1427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-Y2K23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An Atlanta author is helping churches prepare for 'service and
witness' as Y2K approaches.By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A prudent man foresees the difficulties ahead and prepares for
them; the simpleton goes blindly on and suffers the consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Proverbs 22:3
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Shaunti Christine Feldhahn sits in front of a plate of
Belgian waffles at a Dunwoody (Ga.) restaurant with a copy of her
book, ``Y2K _ The Millennium Bug,'' on the table in front of her.
</P>
<P>
   A waiter approaching with a coffeepot notices the book. ``Y2K,''
he says, ``are y'all worried about that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Interested,'' Feldhahn replies. ``I'd say interested, not
worried.''
</P>
<P>
   At 31 years of age, with a graduate degree from Harvard
University and a background as a financial analyst, Feldhahn has
taken on the mission of preparing the nonprofit community,
especially the church, for Y2K. The results of her efforts are
already remarkable:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Her book, written in only 50 days last summer and released
just three months ago by Multnomah, has sold 165,000 copies and is
in its fourth printing. She has a workbook for churches and a Y2K
book for youth in the works.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Joseph Project 2000, launched by Feldhahn with a rally at
New Birth Missionary Baptist Church in DeKalb County (Ga.) in
September, now has working chapters in 40 cities with contacts in
more than 100 others. (It takes its name from the Old Testament
character Joseph, who learned in a dream of seven years of plenty,
followed by seven years of famine, and led preparations for the
coming shortages.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A Joseph Project 2000 Web site _
http://www.josephproject2000.org _ gets as many as 20,000 hits a
day. And its executive offices in Atlanta take up to 600 telephone
calls and e-mails on the busiest days.
</P>
<P>
   Feldhahn now spends much of her time traveling the country to
speak, meet with other organizations, and make media appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Her message is not the alarmist rhetoric of a religious zealot
who believes the New Year will bring on the end of the world. In
fact, the subtitle of her book is ``A Balanced Christian
Response.'' Her goal, she says, is to give a realistic view of some
of the problems that might occur when the world's computers have to
cope with double zeros, and to give practical advice on how
individuals, nonprofit organizations and communities might help
each other through the difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people in the Christian community don't want to
debate whether this is the end times,'' she says. ``They just want
to see the church ready for what could be a very important time of
service and witness.''
</P>
<P>
   Feldhahn, who was raised Presbyterian outside Washington, gave
her life to Jesus at a Catholic retreat while a senior at William
and Mary. ``That's where my life changed forever,'' she says.
``It's been a growth curve ever since.'' She now worships at
Vineyard Christian Fellowship in Dunwoody.
</P>
<P>
   She worked for the U.S. Senate Banking Committee during part of
the savings and loan crisis, then enrolled in Harvard for a
graduate degree in public policy. While there she met her husband,
who was heading Harvard Law School's Christian Fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   She spent four years in New York as a financial analyst for the
Federal Reserve Bank and moved to Dunwoody a year ago with her
husband, a lawyer in the nonprofit sector.
</P>
<P>
   Feldhahn says she had no intention of becoming a spokeswoman on
Y2K, but began collecting information to satisfy her own curiosity.
A friend suggested that she write about the situation for a
Christian audience. When one thing after another fell into place,
Feldhahn became convinced that God was intervening. The project and
the response to it were far greater than she could have imagined,
she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to stay on board the train as it sped out of the
station,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Several metro Atlanta churches are among those acting on her
advice.
</P>
<P>
   Prayer and Praise Christian Fellowship in Woodstock (Ga.) has
dug a well and a cistern, increased contributions to the church
food pantry, and prepared to turn the church into a community
shelter in case the neighborhood loses power. Hard copies of all
the church's important financial papers are safely stored, and
there are cash reserves for emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Larry Baker, 52, pastor of the 120-member flock and
head of the Joseph Project 2000 in Cherokee County (Ga.), cites
Proverbs 22:3 on the wisdom of being ready for any eventuality.
``We have a responsibility to make preparations,'' he says. ``We're
not moving in fear but in faith.'' Baker says he is also
encouraging his congregation to prepare spiritually for Y2K, so
that they have a ``spirit of hope'' to get them through any
economic or logistical setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   He justifies the actions his church has taken because the
cistern, the well and the food pantry will all be of use without
Y2K troubles. ``We're not being extravagant,'' he says. ``If
nothing happens, we've got a good mercy ministry in place.''
</P>
<P>
   After studying the Y2K issue, Susie Snow says, she realized how
inadequately she was prepared for any kind of disaster _ ``natural
disaster, blackout, I didn't have the provisions I needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Snow, 40, is a stay-at-home mother married to the pastor of the
500-member Atlanta City Church in Fairburn (Ga.). She says she
spends about an hour a day searching the Internet, reading or
talking to people about Y2K preparation. ``The information I'm
obtaining, I'm sharing with our congregation and with other
churches on the Southside,'' she says. ``My goal basically is to
network churches and small businesses on the Southside with current
information on potential Y2K problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Snow is making up a bulk order for supplies such as water
containers, flashlights, battery-operated radios and kerosene
stoves, which she is circulating through the church.
</P>
<P>
   At home, she has a wood-burning stove and a generator. She
recommends considering nine areas of potential difficulty:
communication, finances, food and other basic supplies, health
needs, power, transportation, water, sanitation and safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I'm getting prepared, I have peace of mind,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Snow spoke recently at Braelinn Baptist Church in Peachtree City
(Ga.). Under the leadership of an assistant pastor, the Rev. John
Hamblen, 52, the 730-member church is conducting a series of five
workshops on Y2K preparedness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our approach is that we really want to make people aware
without scaring them to death,'' says Hamblen. ``If we're all
working together, we'll get through it. If you start into
survivalist mode, it creates panic and doesn't do anybody any good.
We think as Christians, we are to be in the midst of any problem
helping and encouraging, not running and hiding and scaring
people.''
</P>
<P>
   For Dunwoody resident Feldhahn, the tornadoes of April 1998
serve as a ``useful reference'' in explaining to people what they
may face.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a tornado hits, what happens?'' she asks. ``Power can go
out. Businesses may have to close. It takes five minutes and you're
still cleaning up five months later. It's not some big, weird
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Y2K bug can bring people together as they prepare, cope
and help each other, then it has served a purpose, she says. ``The
bottom line is that Y2K is just a catalyst I believe God will use
to get the church back to maybe where it should have been all
along.''
</P>
<P>
   Y2K ADVICE
</P>
<P>
   Shaunti Feldhahn and Susie Snow offer the following advice on
how to prepare for Y2K:
</P>
<P>
   Family:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Check appliances, security systems, heating and air
conditioning for date-related functions.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Check personal computer and software.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Consider the preparedness of services such as utilities,
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Store necessities.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make arrangements for back-up phone, power.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Decrease debt or, if possible, be debt-free.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Maintain financial liquidity.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Have copies of important family records.
</P>
<P>
   Church or business:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In logistical preparation, follow advice for families.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Provide information to the congregation and the community.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Examine how to reach out physically and spiritually to the
community in case gasoline distribution is disrupted.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Develop a strategy for working with other churches.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Seek out high-risk households and plan to help meet their
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White is a writer for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
