<HEADER>
A4736 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOLETO-PROGRAM23-COX     01-22 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOLETO-PROGRAM23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spoleto celebration a 70th birthday fete for beloved pianist
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Decked out in a blue seersucker suit and white suede
shoes, Charles Wadsworth has been resident cut-up at Spoleto
Festival USA's chamber-music series for the past 22 years. Tickling
the ivories and audience members' funny bones with equal aplomb,
the Newnan(Ga.)-born impresario has become one of the festival's
most beloved institutions.
</P>
<P>
   So for the maestro's 70th birthday, the Charleston, S.C., fest
will pay homage with a gala benefit starring pianist Peter Serkin,
violinst Pinchas Zukerman and an ensemble of yet-to-be-named
musicians championed by Wadsworth over the years.
</P>
<P>
   The concert, set for June 1 at the historic Dock Street Theatre,
was announced Friday as the festival unveiled final plans for its
$5.5 million shindig, May 28-June 13. With the recent demise of the
Arts Festival of Atlanta, Spoleto is the South's only major
interdisciplinary arts fest this year.
</P>
<P>
   Along with a new work by performance artist Laurie Anderson, the
U.S. premiere of a Kurt Weill opera and a trio of Puccini one-acts,
Spoleto '99 promises to be a mecca for music lovers of every
stripe. And while there is no festival-within-a-festival to compare
to last year's ``Echoes of Africa,'' there's a strong continuum of
Latin-inflected dance and music: Spain's Ballet Flamenco de Antonio
Canales, Cuban jazz pianist Frank Emilio Flynn, Brazilian dance
group Quasar and the Miami City Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Sonny Rollins, widely regarded as the world's best tenor
saxophonist, is the jazz headliner. Also on the roster: Oregon, a
pioneer world-music ensemble, and Denise Jannah, a Surinam-born
chanteuse who sings in the classic style of Sarah Vaughan and Ella
Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   But don't fret if you can't make the Wadsworth champagne soiree.
He'll preside at 34 chamber-music programs over the 17-day
festival. His series, in which he engages audiences with his witty
repartee, often affecting a hilarious faux-Italian accent, is one
of Spoleto's most popular components _ a routine sell-out.
</P>
<P>
   After Leonard Bernstein, Wadsworth, who led the Chamber Music
Society of Lincoln Center for 20 years, has probably done more than
any other American figure to demystify the classical idiom. His
personable style is exactly what the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra is
seeking in a new conductor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, I'm being very selfish,'' says Wadsworth, known for
discovering soprano Jessye Norman, violin virtuoso Joshua Bell and
numerous other celebrity musicians while still in their youth.
``I'm giving myself the present of scheduling my favorite pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   Such as?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dvorak piano quintet, the Mendelssohn string octet ... It
will just go on and on.''
</P>
<P>
   The chamber series is so popular that the Spoleto board of
directors recently decided to take it on the road. On Feb. 26,
Wadsworth and his Spoleto chamber group departs for its second
tour, playing 12 dates across the United States and Canada through
March 22. He says he eventually hopes to bring the group to
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth, whose birthday is May 2, will be toasted April 9 and
April 11 at Lincoln Center. He's doing gigs at Calloway Gardens
(GA.) on April 16-18. And on Feb. 20, he'll be in his hometown of
Newnan for a concert with pianist Stephen Prutsman, cellist
Kristina Cooper and violinst Sunsuke Sato, 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's the greatest young fiddle player to come along
since Midori,'' says Wadsworth, who was honored last year when
Newnan named its municipal auditorium after him. He continues to
live in New York. Meanwhile, Spoleto producer Nunally A. Kersh says
she's eager to see how ``Mamba's Daughters'' _ a 1939 play by
Charleston native Dubose Heyward which has been restaged by New
York director David Herskovits _ will play with the locals.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people in the community feel a really personal
connection to the play,'' says Kersh. The Gullah drama, about an
African-American mother who sacrifices herself for her daughter,
will be performed throughout the festival run in the city where
Heyward wrote the novels ``Porgy'' and ``Mamba's Daughters.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lowcountry imprint can also be seen in a visual arts
installation by Washington, D.C., artist Martha Jackson-Jarvis,
whose ``Rice, Rattlesnakes and Rainwater'' was featured in the 1997
exhibition ``Human/Nature: Art and Landscape in Charleston and the
Low Country.'' Her new piece _ ``Rue, Rooks and Robin Eggs'' _ will
use house forms, oyster shells, historic images and wrought iron.
</P>
<P>
   In the new music series, one program will juxtapose composer
Charles Ives' 1899 music with work written in1999. Other concerts
will showcase compositions by John Luther Adam and series director
John Kennedy. Opera lovers may feast on original productions of
Puccini's ``Il Trittico'' and Weill's ``Die Burgschaft'' (``The
Pledge''). Other notable performances: Compagnie Philippe Genty, a
modern dance group from France; ``Kwaidan,'' a puppet show that
originated at the Center for Puppetry Arts last year; ``Ricky Jay
and His 52 Assistants,'' a one-man sleight-of-hand show directed by
David Mamet, and the Laurie Anderson musical theater production,
``Songs and Stories From Moby Dick.''
</P>
<P>
   Single tickets go on sale Monday. To order: 843-720-0402. To get
a brochure: 843-722-2764. Website: http://www.spoletousa.org.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Brock writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
