<HEADER>
A4745 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLU     01-22 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EITHER WAY, YOU WILL PAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Is there some way to install Win95 (after
formatting the hard drive) with the service packs rather than
standing in line again to download them and the various other
upgrades?
</P>
<P>
   _ Starting Over
</P>
<P>
   DEAR OVER: Yes. It's a three-step process:
</P>
<P>
   1. Become really good friends with a paramedic. Buy him a few
beers one night, and do some male bonding. Open up to him and let
him know you really care about his feelings and fears, his hopes
and dreams. Toast your friendship with five or six boilermakers.
</P>
<P>
   2. Don't stop yet. Take your newest best bud out to the finest
steakhouse in town. Start with 20-year-old single malt-scotch, have
a nice beaujolais with your dinner, then retire to the cigar room
for three or four rounds of Grand Marnier or perhaps Courvoisier _
this choice is up to you.
</P>
<P>
   3. On your way home from the restaurant, pick up a couple of
six-packs of Colt 45, then dare him to chug-a-lug. When he finally
passes out, take his keys, drive back to the firehouse, steal the
Jaws of Life, pry 90 bucks out of your wallet, find an all-night
software store and buy a Windows 98 upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Look, you're starting from scratch, so it doesn't make any sense
to load an ancient version of Windows, then apply a bunch of bug
fixes and patches to it. And that's all Win98 is: a debugged Win95
with some features that should have been in the original, but
weren't.
</P>
<P>
   Your other option _ and it's not exactly legal _ is to find
somebody who has the OSR2 release of Win95 and install that. You'll
be happier with 98.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I leave my machine on all day and only shut it
down at bedtime. I have it set to turn off the monitor after a
half-hour of non-use, the hard-drive after an hour, and often put
the system in standby mode if I know I'll be away from it for a
while. Is this OK to do?
</P>
<P>
   _ Power Ranger
</P>
<P>
   DEAR RANGER: That standby stuff makes more sense for laptops
with limited battery life than it does for desktop PCs. It doesn't
hurt anything, however _ the PC is just sucking up less juice while
it's in standby, helping to preserve our vital natural resources. I
get the feeling, though, that if you're already leaving the thing
on all day, that's not exactly No. 1 on your priority list. Don't
worry, I won't tell the tree-huggers.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: How do you clean the mouse pads and wrist rests
that get full of dirt, dried sweat and whatever else there is while
we spend hours upon hours looking at stuff that we know we are not
supposed to?
</P>
<P>
   _ Big Mess
</P>
<P>
   DEAR BIG: You know, I'm not entirely sure I want to know what
you're trying to clean up.
</P>
<P>
   Come on, guy! These are mouse pads! Mouse pads! Take two bucks
and go buy a new one, because _ believe me _ you're never going to
get all those stains out. And this time, get a wrist rest with a
removable, washable cover, one of those things with a gel filling.
Not only are they extremely comfortable, they also have a certain
sensual quality that I find really ... but perhaps I've said too
much already.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay offers occasionally
accurate advice about most things electronic. He can be reached on
Internet at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com; via snail-mail at Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101; or fax: (817)
390-7257. His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
