<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4747 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     01-22 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID TV'S HYPE, THERE'S HOPE _ `SUNDAY MORNING'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Here in the land of fluff and fantasy, where
most decisions are based on bottom line and buzz, and where youth
and beauty are more valuable than talent, Charles Osgood is an
engaging enigma.
</P>
<P>
   The host of ``CBS News Sunday Morning,'' the acerbic
newsmagazine whose 20th-anniversary show airs at 8 a.m. CST Sunday,
is 65, for one thing. And in the many years he has reported for CBS
News, he has defied network demographics and some ticked-off
consultants by making tightly knotted bow ties his on-air calling
card.
</P>
<P>
   CBS News President Andrew Heyward kicked off a recent news
conference by introducing Osgood and his producer, Missie Rennie,
who made brief comments before opening the floor to questions.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first was about the bow tie. What, someone asked
Osgood, was his take on ``Dress for Success'' author John Molloy's
theory that bow ties undercut credibility?
</P>
<P>
   This obviously has been of constant amusement to Osgood, who
leaned back and smiled. ``Studies have been done on this,
actually,'' he said, sounding like a kid who'd been holding on to a
secret. ``It shows that people do not trust you if you wear a bow
tie. (Molloy) says, if you're going to wear the bow tie, you may as
well wear the rest of the ensemble: a beanie with a propeller.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone laughed, but later, after the news conference, Osgood
took a more serious tone. ``I think once we start attaching those
kind of theories on the human mind and human heart, it can become a
little dangerous,'' he said. ``We're all independent thinkers. We
shouldn't be told that a bow tie, or anything else, cripples
credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Committed fans of ``Sunday Morning'' know that during its
two-decade run, during its first 15 years with host Charles Kuralt
and its transition to Osgood, nothing has disturbed the Sunday
morning peace that is the show's foundation. How, then, could a
fashion accessory?
</P>
<P>
   The fact that in April, Osgood will celebrate his five-year
anniversary as host is a testament to how gently he has moved into
the mix of television's most distinctive and thoughtful series.
</P>
<P>
   For years, ``Sunday Morning'' has represented television's last
great novella of short stories, storytelling and heartfelt
programming. It almost seems like overkill to speak of it in terms
of touching the heart, mind and soul of viewers. But it remains the
only place where you can find slice-of-life and hard-edged stories
on theater, arts, music, literature, sports and history _ all
within a 90-minute program, all told without time constraints.
</P>
<P>
   Even while keeping its pace slow and mood-soothing to align
itself with the leisurely rhythm of a weekend morning, ``Sunday
Morning'' has continued to be intelligent and distinctive and even
current, providing news updates from CBS News correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has, obviously, changed since Charles Kuralt retired,''
Heyward said. ``But one of the things that has been encouraging to
me is how increasingly it has become Charles Osgood's program,
something that reflects his personality and his interests and his
tastes.''
</P>
<P>
   Osgood still opens the show standing next to the Plexiglas
tower, and it still ends with buzzing and chirping from some nature
outpost. Kuralt's ``Milepost,'' a thought of the week to open the
show, has become ``The Osgood File.'' But generally, Osgood has had
a hands-off approach.
</P>
<P>
   It has apparently appeased the ``Sunday Morning'' audience, a
demanding group whose average age is slightly over 55. There was
some audience erosion, which Heyward expected, given Kuralt's
dedicated following. But the audience numbers, almost 4 million,
are finally closing in on pre-Osgood levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that surprises me is that, with all of the
new broadcasts, nobody is doing what we do,'' Osgood said. ``It was
Fred Allen who said, `Imitation is the sincerest form of
television,' but in fact, nobody has really tried to imitate us.''
</P>
<P>
   Why? Osgood paused. ``Because deep down, in their souls,
television people don't believe that people really want this stuff.
They don't really believe that people are intelligent, and that
they care about the arts, and they're interested in nature and the
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Osgood has had a roundabout career. As a student at Fordham, he
worked on the college radio station with actor Alan Alda. He went
to work at ABC Radio after a stint as the announcer for the U.S.
Army Band. At ABC, he was forced to drop his real last name, Wood,
for his middle name, Osgood, because a Charles Wood already worked
there.
</P>
<P>
   At ABC Radio in the early '60s, he met a young reporter named
Ted Koppel. The two became friends and together proposed a morning
show for ABC television that Osgood says was designed to compete
with NBC's ``Today.''
</P>
<P>
   Osgood left ABC for CBS Radio when the network ran with the idea
but passed on him as host. He soon began filling in for TV anchor
Roger Mudd, however, and from then on his name surfaced as a
possibility for a number of high-profile, on-camera jobs, until
Kuralt retired.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder radio continues to be Osgood's first love. Every
weekday morning, he delivers his ``Osgood Files'' commentaries on
CBS Radio. There are four each morning, usually addressing some
offbeat story that Osgood has found on the news wires or some
equally offbeat issue that seemed ripe for his delectable prose.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear people talk of the format and whether you can stick
anyone in it and make it work,'' says Rennie. ``You can't. That
Charles has made the transition seem so effortless is a testament
to his talent, not how tightly formatted the show is.''
</P>
<P>
   All this season, ``Sunday Morning'' has been rebroadcasting
classic segments, such as a Joe DiMaggio interview conducted about
15 years ago, a profile of Yo-Yo Ma at age 20, Tiger Woods at 16.
</P>
<P>
   Rennie counts as one of the extraordinary traditions of ``Sunday
Morning'' its discovery of unique talents and voices early on in
their careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we're really striving to do is present a show
that five or 10 years from now somebody else is pulling from the
archives and saying, `This is an extraordinary piece, an
extraordinary story, and it deserves to go on television again,'''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   And the bow tie? ``I'm certain that'll be a topic of
conversation in the decades to come, as well.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
