<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JERRY FALWELL HAS A LOT OF APOLOGIZING TO DO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another high-profile evangelical, this time the Rev. Jerry
Falwell, has stuck his foot in his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Falwell would like to take back his remarks made recently
stating that the evil Antichrist probably is alive today and, of
course, will be a Jewish man.
</P>
<P>
   Falwell, who made his remarks at a recent pastors conference in
Kingsport, Tenn., has apologized. He said his remarks were not
meant to be anti-Semitic.
</P>
<P>
   They only reflected, he said, a theory that the Antichrist
likely would disguise himself as Jesus of Nazareth, who, of course,
was Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Jesus came to the earth the first time 2,000 years ago
as a Jewish male, most evangelicals believe the Antichrist will, by
necessity, be a Jewish male also,'' Falwell explained in a
statement aimed at clarifying his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   But others saw the comments as millennial madness.
</P>
<P>
   Falwell's statement represents ``an especially vicious tradition
of Christian theological anti-Judaism,'' said Abraham Foxman,
national director of the Anti-Defamation League.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears clear that after years of Christian-Jewish
dialogue, Rev. Falwell hasn't learned a thing,'' Foxman said.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``If Rev. Falwell and others persist in these
statements, they will be instigating an anti-Semitism rooted in
Christian theological extremism.''
</P>
<P>
   Falwell's blunder reminds me of a similar faux pas made almost
20 years ago by another well-known evangelist, the Rev. Bailey
Smith, then president of the Southern Baptist Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Smith declared ``God Almighty does not hear the prayer of a
Jew'' during a speech before 20,000 religious right conservatives
in Dallas. Ronald Reagan, then a presidential candidate, also spoke
at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   When Smith was castigated for his statement, he apologized for
any offense he had caused. He even led his denomination in
establishing a new Baptist-Jewish dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Smith accepted an invitation to attend a Passover Seder
with the family of Mark Briskman of Dallas, the Southwest regional
director of the Anti-Defamation League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember it as if it were yesterday,'' Briskman said this
week of the Bailey Smith controversy. He still is regional director
of the Jewish human rights organization.
</P>
<P>
   Briskman believes _ and I agree _ that Falwell is sincere in
saying that he did not intend for his remarks to be taken as
anti-Semitic.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Jewish leader said Falwell's remarks were
``surprising, troubling and very problematic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What this does, he says, is help to legitimize the Jew haters,
the anti-Semites,'' Briskman said. ``Clearly, I don't think that
was Falwell's intention.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Christian leaders, including the Rev. Clyde Glazener,
pastor of the Gambrell Street Baptist Church in Fort Worth, don't
agree that the Antichrist has to be a Jewish male.
</P>
<P>
   Glazener said no one knows who the Antichrist will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had people in the past identifying Hitler, Mussolini and
other obviously evil people as the Antichrist,'' said Glazener.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I don't have a clue who the Antichrist will be. And
as little as I know about it, I think I know as much as Jerry
Falwell.''
</P>
<P>
   Falwell, pastor of the Thomas Road Baptist Church in Lynchburg,
Va., has traveled to Israel 30 times and has met with every Israeli
prime minister from Menachem Begin to Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, he is strong supporter of Israel as a nation. He
sees himself as a friend of the Jewish people.
</P>
<P>
   But he could undo a lot of the good will he has established
unless he continues to apologize loud and long for his
shoot-from-the hip remarks about the Antichrist.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
