<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUILTS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 24
 &HT;    History-infused quilts showcase fabric of Georgia women's lives'
 &HT;    By Eileen M. Drennen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Even in the 1800s,'' notes an Atlanta History Center
ad, ``women kept diaries. They just slept under them.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracing the lives of Georgia women through the quilts they left
behind is at the heart of the history center exhibit ``Georgia
Quilts: Piecing Together History,'' which continues through Sept.
5. Made up of 80 hand-sewn treasures dating from 1800 to 1920, the
show is bookended by birth and death.
</P>
<P>
   The first section visitors see, contained in two glass cases at
the entrance, is titled Rites of Passage. On the left, beside her
1895 quilt, Lilla Owens Thrash looks out from an old photograph,
posed with a man and two young boys. She made her quilt in
anticipation of the birth of her first child. Because all four of
them died at birth, her family portrait was taken with her husband
and nephews.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Jordan pieced together the orange-red ``Pickle Dish'' in
1910 to commemorate the birth of her first son, Vernard. She
stitched their names into the corner in golden thread, noting that
her boy was ``Age 9 Mo. old When the quilt Was Finished.'' Her
picture is propped under the pieces of her old wooden quilting
frame.
</P>
<P>
   In the case to the right, Elizabeth Grace Jones Dunn's ``Quilt
of Words'' fills the back wall. Made in Arkansas in 1890, her final
project conveys her dying thoughts: ``O THAT I HAD WINGS LIKE A
DOVE THEN WOULD FLY AWAY AD BE AT REST AFTER SEVENTY EIGT YEARS AND
SIX MONTHS E G DUNN FINI.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne McKinne Winter's extravagant ``Tumbling Blocks'' is a
statement of another sort. A luxuriantly geometric field of rich
blues and golds, deep reds and brown, her quilt was made to
commemorate her own widowhood. When her husband died in 1861,
Winter was only 35. Once she put on black to mourn him, she never
took it off. She cut her expensive Paris-made trousseau into bright
cubes of satin for a quilt, anchoring the bottom of each with a
diamond of black velvet. She backed it with the fabric of a red
dress her husband had bought her in New York and that she had never
worn. She died 51 years later.
</P>
<P>
   Co-curator Janice Morrill says it's her favorite quilt in the
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her story is so dramatic,'' she says. ``Talk about a symbolic
gesture!''
</P>
<P>
   Eileen M. Drennen writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
