<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4786 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY24-COX     01-22 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY24-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 24, 1999
</P>
<P>
   By Larry Lipman
</P>
<P>
   c. Cox News Service 1999
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At the heart of President Clinton's answer to
Social Security's long-term fiscal problems is a question: should
the federal government invest in the stock market?
</P>
<P>
   In his State of the Union message last week, Clinton offered two
ways of boosting Social Security by investing in the stock and bond
markets.
</P>
<P>
   One way involves the government directly investing a portion of
the surplus; the other way involves individuals investing part of
the surplus in accounts which they will control.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans hate the first idea but love the second. Democrats,
generally, are receptive to the first idea but wary of the second.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of that dispute could play a large role in
determining whether Congress and the White House fix Social
Security for the next half century or not.
</P>
<P>
   To get the Republican-controlled Congress to accept his plan to
have government investments, Clinton offered to use some of the
projected $4.4 trillion federal surplus for individual investment
accounts, which he calls ``universal savings accounts'' or ``USA
Accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   But before he'll give them those USA Accounts, Clinton wants to
use another part of the surplus _ about $700 billion over 15 years
_ to invest in the stock and bond markets.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of government investment are worried primarily about
two things: how the investments would be made and what happens if
government owns stock in corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Fla., chairman of the Ways and Means
Social Security subcommittee, says he can envision heated
congressional debates over whether to invest in strip mining or
nuclear waste disposal. Ways and Means Chairman, Rep. Bill Archer,
R-Texas, questions whether the government would invest in tobacco
companies or gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morality is in the eyes of the beholder,'' Shaw said, noting
that products shunned by some individuals _ such as cigarettes or
guns _ is embraced by others. ``We'd be putting the Good
Housekeeping seal of approval on some and blackening the reputation
of others.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan expressed similar
concerns about investment decisions being influenced by politics
when he appeared Wednesday before Archer's committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe that it is politically feasible to insulate
such huge funds from governmental direction,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security Commissioner Kenneth S. Apfel acknowledges the
difficulty in insulating investment decisions from politics, but he
said he believes it can be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in the administration believes that it should be the
government that is choosing stocks,'' Apfel said. ``The modest
investment in equities would be done by an independent body from
the private sector shielded from any public influence.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of such models, Apfel said, including the
federal employees' pension fund and virtually every state and local
government employee pension fund.
</P>
<P>
   State and local pension funds nationwide invest an average of 60
percent of their money in the market, rather than in government
securities, Apfel said. At the height of the Social Security
investment _ in about 15 to 20 years _ roughly 15 percent of the
Social Security system would be invested in the private market, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, state and local pension investments account for about
10 percent of the money in the stock market. In about 20 years, the
Social Security investment would account for between 4 percent and
5 percent of the market, Apfel said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan is a sharply reduced version of a proposal
endorsed by six of the 13 members of the government's Social
Security Advisory Council of outside experts two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Robert M. Ball, a former Social Security commissioner under
Presidents Kennedy, Johnson and Nixon, was the lead author of the
council's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Social Security has been handicapped over the years in being
made to invest in low-yield government bonds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under his plan, political influence would be minimized by
investing in broad-based index funds that would include 3,000 to
5,000 stocks. It would be further minimized by appointing a control
board, similar to the Federal Reserve Board, whose members would
serve for long terms that extend beyond the tenure of a
presidential administration, Ball said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents also are concerned with the impact of government
ownership of so much stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's back-door socialism,'' said Michael Tanner, director of
the Cato Institute's project on Social Security privatization.
</P>
<P>
   (Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   He notes that state employee pension funds are increasingly
attempting to influence corporate decisions regarding the
environment, economic development and ``humanitarian problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Arnone, a partner in the accounting and consulting firm
Ernst and Young, said Wall Street firms ``just inherently don't
like the idea'' of government investments in private companies.
</P>
<P>
   But Arnone said ``I don't think there would be significant
opposition to index funds.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
