<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4790 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARIS-HAUTE-FASHION &LR; -     01-22 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-HAUTE-FASHION </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION SHOWS FOR WOMEN WHO SHOP IN ANOTHER STRATOSPHERE
</HEADLINE>
 -$ADV24-ART -2TAKES-NYT   (For release Sunday Jan. 24) 
ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Just about everyone who comes to the haute couture
collections knows that Nan is Nan Kempner, that Deeda is Deeda
Blair and that Liliane Bettencourt, who was seated Wednesday in the
front row at the Yves Saint Laurent show and wearing an orange
muffler, is the richest woman in France.
</P>
<P>
   They may or may not know that the youngest couture customer at
Givenchy is all of 8, or that Dodie Rosekrans, the San Francisco
art patron and couture stalwart, recently bought a full-size
guillotine covered with the Chanel logo for her home in Venice. But
give them time. Paris is probably the only place on earth where the
world's rich, titled and tucked can always count on being
connected, if only through clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Couture separates the small-time fashion player from those who
can play the game at its liveliest, which is to say at the big
Paris houses where a custom-made suit without any detail to speak
of costs about $10,000. Throw in some embroidery, a chiffon blouse,
maybe a coat with feathers around the throat, and suddenly madame
is in a different stratosphere: $30,000, $40,000, $50,000 even
$100,000 for a dress.
</P>
<P>
   But that's why it's called haute. There are only about 300 women
in the world who have the couture life style and the means to
indulge it regularly. Some of them are well known, like Mrs.
Kempner. But most are rich unknowns from Florida or Brazil, whose
husbands made it big in lumber or real estate. As Karl Lagerfeld
said last week, ``They don't want to be known, but they have money
beyond.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, with so many magazine editors running up to see
Josephus Thimister, one of the newer haute couture designers, or
over to the Marais to catch an exhibition by Tom Sachs _ it was
Sachs, a New York artist, who came up with the idea of constructing
the Chanel guillotine, bought by Mrs. Rosekrans, out of police
barricades _ couture is also a scene. Up at Chanel, Lagerfeld was
holding forth, talking to this editor and that, sketching with his
special blend of brown ink, quoting Verlaine, sipping Diet Coke and
saying he thought Sachs' guillotine was amusing _ but not that
amusing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little too obvious, no?'' he said, squinting.
</P>
<P>
   What about the clothes that finished out the spring
haute-couture season on Wednesday?
</P>
<P>
   Lagerfeld's Chanel show on Tuesday had all the lightness that
one has come to expect from modern fashion. He took out the linings
of his mostly short, body-hugging jackets, so that they fitted as
cozily as cardigans and, in one superb number, actually finessed
the question of fabric by embroidering an orange-flecked boucle
check on tulle.
</P>
<P>
   This was a testament to the designer's imagination and the skill
of the Chanel workrooms. But the trouble with so much lightness is
that it lacks substance, and even though these fluid, sporty
clothes were close in spirit to Coco Chanel's ultramodern ideal,
they seemed destined to fade into the woodwork. Women want
something that looks like a skirt or a blouse _ not some drippy,
indecisive silhouette in the bleached-out hues of the seashore.
</P>
<P>
   Lagerfeld also seemed to be having trouble with his bottoms.
Baggy in the rear, loose through the leg, his many trousers pooled
in sloppy folds around the ankles, where they were buttoned.
Giorgio Armani tried this style more than a decade ago, and it may
have worked then, but it's hard to believe that Lagerfeld's
customers can honestly picture themselves going for it now _ and
with cargo pockets, no less.
</P>
<P>
   Before the show, Lagerfeld said, ``In a way, everything that's
interesting has roots.'' This is true, but it's also possible to
get lost in the past. Lagerfeld, bored or merely resting, needs to
shake the dust off those bones.
</P>
<P>
   There was something almost brutal about Christian Lacroix's show
in the opulent ballroom of the Grand Hotel _ brutal in its
single-minded vision, brutal in its attempt to remain true to the
past. Yet it was profoundly, brilliantly alive. Lacroix did this in
a number of ingenious ways. A pale pink bustier, worn with a short
skirt hemmed in lacquered Chantilly lace, came wrapped with thin
bands of taupe velvet that were given a kind of destroyed look by
sewing wisps of frayed denim to each band.
</P>
<P>
   Lacroix is a great post-modernist. He knows how to mix the
street with the luxe, in the same way that Saint Laurent did a
quarter-century ago, but now with the subtlety demanded by a more
jaded, sophisticated world. Here was a collection that was often
sumptuous _ overblown skirts in rose-colored satin, an extravagant
bow, a pile of lace. Then out came a pale-yellow sheath in
stiffened chiffon, its bodice embroidered with tiny strips of
frayed gray and brown gauze, so that it resembled the feathery
remains in an abandoned nest. This was the real thing _ couture
with a pulse.
</P>
<P>
   Although a lot of what turns up on the runways looks old and
bland and safe, it can't be said that couture is dying. New people
keep coming along, designers like Thimister, a Belgian who will
show his first ready-to-wear collection for Genny next month in
Milan, and Viktor Horsting and Rolf Snoeren, who work out of
Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   Viktor and Rolf, as they are called, put on a terrific show on
Tuesday in one of those arty dumps with chipped concrete walls and
ducts running everywhere. The clothes were all black and white _ a
black satin pants suit with tiny pinstripes of ruffled white gazar,
a tuxedo with a preposterously large Flemish ruff in fraying, white
silk.
</P>
<P>
   The designers staged their show in black light, so that all you
could see were the white details, and the audience's teeth. It was
weirdly brilliant and a more modern take on Surrealism than
Galliano's Dali trip the day before. It brought to mind a scene in
Tom Wolfe's profile of Marshall McLuhan, when he and McLuhan were
sitting in a dimly lighted restaurant being served by topless
waitresses, and McLuhan said, ``When you dim the visual sense, you
step up the sense of taste,'' adding: ``You are brought together
sensually and sensorially, forced out of the isolation of the
visual man.''
</P>
<P>
   The Viktor and Rolf show had the same effect, except without the
breasts. It made you think of fashion in a different way.
</P>
<P>
   Thimister's show also was compelling, mainly for its couture
treatment of cheap fabrics like cotton voile. For instance,
Thimister used heat and plastic on long voile skirts and dresses to
make them look crinkled and papery. He recycled two military
raincoats into a strapless gown, folding and draping the lapels and
sleeves of the coats around the hem, so that the original garments
were absorbed into the new one. It was intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Yves Saint Laurent and Oscar de la Renta,
designing for Balmain, brought the season to a close with good,
wearable clothes that are the mainstay of the two houses.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
