<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-UNREST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIOTS IN INDONESIA KILL 45 PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ In the worst violence in Indonesia since
May, 45 people have died in four days of rioting between Muslims
and Christians on the island of Ambon, local officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's rioting, burning, looting,'' said one American who
fled to Australia, in an interview on Australian television. Some
40 foreigners fled to Australia from the island.
</P>
<P>
   Police say more than 100 people have been injured, 88 homes
destroyed along with three mosques, and three churches burned.
Vehicles and shops have also gone up in flame. A curfew has been
imposed on the city and some 2,500 soldiers and police have been
deployed to restore order.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials said more than 4,000 residents had sought
shelter in police and army compounds after riots erupted Tuesday,
sparked by an argument on the street.
</P>
<P>
   In his first response to the Ambon violence President B.J.
Habibie said Friday that the town was now secure. ``The armed
forces commander has reported that the situation in Ambon is
quiet,'' he said. ``Religious leaders and public figures have
discussed it together.''
</P>
<P>
   The airport remains closed and large areas of the city are still
without power.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Ambon, a resident, Demi Luthermas,
said the security forces had gained control of the town. ``Today
there are not so many problems _ the military has taken control.
All shops and offices are closed and the army is patrolling the
streets,'' he said. Ambon, 1,300 miles northeast of Jakarta, is the
capital of Maluku province, formerly known as the Spice Islands or
Moluccas.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's police chief, Lt.-Gen. Roesmanhadi, told a news
conference in Jakarta on Thursday, ``This violence is purely
criminal in nature and has no political background.'' He said that
rioting had also broken out on neighboring Seram island just north
of Ambon and that two churches had been set alight. But the clashes
follow months of unrest, and diplomats warn that the security
situation is likely to worsen before the national elections on June
7.
</P>
<P>
   The rioting, and fears of it spreading, were behind a drop in
the Indonesian currency in trading on Friday, financial analysts
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 1730EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4813 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT23-COX     01-22 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KEY MICROSOFT EXECUTIVE DEFENDS GIANT'S CONDUCT
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington queues
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the Microsoft executive accused of once
threatening to ``cut off Netscape's air supply'' takes the stand
Monday at the company's antitrust trial, he will describe
Microsoft's climb to the top of the software world like a game of
king of the hill.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Maritz's 159 pages of written testimony, released Friday,
portray a brutal business universe in which Microsoft's rivals
relentlessly strive to knock the industry's giant off its high
perch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rapid innovation and strong competition in the computer
industry means that no company, including Microsoft, has a
guaranteed position,'' Maritz wrote. As the company's flagship
product, Windows ``faces intense competition from many sources,''
even as it serves as the operating brain of 90 percent of the
world's personal computer, he added.
</P>
<P>
   As the first of nine Microsoft employees to be called by the
defense, Maritz will seek to persuade U.S. District Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson that a dozen prior government witnesses either
exaggerated or lied.
</P>
<P>
   He brands the teller of the infamous ``air supply'' quote as a
liar. ``I never said, in the presence of Intel (Corp.) personnel or
otherwise, that Microsoft would 'cut off Netscape's air supply,' or
words to that effect,'' Maritz wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Maritz must champion the defense cause in the face of
hundreds of his own e-mail messages already entered into evidence _
with many more to come next week _ each aimed at buttressing the
government's broad charges of illegal conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Firing back, Maritz accuses the government of seeking to
``portray instances of routine interaction between companies in the
computer industry, who inevitably must deal with one another, as
something nefarious.''
</P>
<P>
   As a group vice president for platforms and applications, Maritz
falls in seniority below only Microsoft's multibillionaire
chairman, Bill Gates, and its billionaire president, Steve Ballmer.
A multimillionaire in his own right, the executive who pilots
Microsoft's core operating-systems business has studiously
cultivated a low profile during his 13 years with the Redmond,
Wash., firm.
</P>
<P>
   But all that changed when the federal government, in filing its
antitrust suit last May, focused on his alleged ``air supply''
comments to portray Microsoft as predator that has sought to
leverage its huge market power to crush its competitors, including
Netscape Communications Corp., its main rival in the browser wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to cut off their air supply,'' Maritz was quoted
as having said at a November 1995 meeting in discussing Microsoft's
plans to drive Netscape to the wall. ``Everything they're selling,
we're going to give away for free.''
</P>
<P>
   That testimony came from Intel Vice President Steven McGeady,
who earlier in the trial recalled the conference with Maritz and
other Microsoft brass in Oregon to review technology issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul and some of the other attendees made some fairly colorful
statements that stick out in my memory,'' McGeady said on the
stand. ``... It was Microsoft's plan to cut off Netscape's air
supply. By giving away free browsers, Microsoft was going to keep
Netscape from getting off the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's lawyers accused McGeady of making up the quote. They
confronted McGeady with his own notes about the disputed meeting,
which failed to mention Maritz's purported ``air supply'' comment.
And they produced notes from two other Intel executives, who also
didn't include it.
</P>
<P>
   But McGeady stuck to his account, telling the court: ``The
phrase was so far out of bounds with what I consider to be an
acceptable business practice. It stuck out clearly in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
