<HEADER>
A4823 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDS-FAMILY-HNS &LR;      01-22 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-FAMILY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILD RESEARCHERS QUESTION IDEA OF INBORN ABILITY TO COPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Minnesota)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Despite awful home and school environments
that thwart some children from growing up well, other children in
seemingly similar circumstances grow up just fine.
</P>
<P>
   Some researchers have identified those children as resilient,
singling out a trait that seems to keep them on an even keel.
</P>
<P>
   But a panel of scientists gathered here Thursday disputed the
idea of inborn capacity to succeed against the odds.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they said, studies show that children who get support
and nurturing early in life _ or who get the support when the going
gets tough _ are the ones who best weather adversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way kids come out depends on their experience,'' L. Alan
Sroufe of the University of Minnesota said at the American
Association for the Advancement of Science meeting. ``There aren't
kids who can make it all right no matter what. If experience throws
you enough slings and arrows, you will fail.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past 23 years, Sroufe has followed the successes and
failures of 180 poor children in Minnesota. His findings led him to
call resilience in children a ``developmental achievement'' that
comes from earlier positive experiences, rather than a ``mystery''
that seems to randomly visit one child rather than another.
</P>
<P>
   He said he and his collaborators had been able to predict by age
3 with 77 percent accuracy which children in the sample would later
drop out of school. The predictions were based on environmental
factors such as the responsiveness of caregiver, how well the child
was provided for, and the level of chaos in the home.
</P>
<P>
   Although brothers and sisters from the same family often turn
out differently, Sroufe said, that doesn't mean their home lives
weren't a factor, since parents vary in the way they treat each
child.
</P>
<P>
   ``The child they treat most harshly will be the child that shows
the most problems,'' Sroufe said.
</P>
<P>
   And it seems even well-functioning children, if put in a poor
environment, will fare worse than poorer-functioning children in a
good environment, according to Arnold Sameroff, a researcher at the
University of Michigan who has followed another set of children
from birth through age 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more things going wrong in a family, the worse the outcome
will be,'' Sameroff said. ``Can they overcome their context? The
answer is no.''
</P>
<P>
   Sameroff ticked off more factors that can contribute to a
child's downfall, including poverty, bad schools, discrimination,
family stress and bad neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   He said research shows that a single factor, such as poverty,
does not doom a child, but it is only when several are piled on
that the weight becomes too great.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Masten, a psychology professor at the University of
Minnesota, has followed yet another set of children and has found
some traits _ including good thinking skills and self confidence _
that are markers of children who seem to bounce back. But effective
parents are essential, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the going gets tough, for sure parenting begins to really
matter, and intellectual development matters,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One hopeful sign is that children whose environments improve do
seem to get better. There have been reports of striking recoveries
of some children rescued from awful orphanages in Romania, for
instance.
</P>
<P>
   And Sroufe said there were children in his group who appeared to
be headed down the wrong path but later recovered. It usually
coincided with the child's mother forming a strong, stable
relationship. (Most of Sroufe's subjects came from families headed
by a single mother).
</P>
<P>
   And he said a mother who recovers from depression can have a
positive effect on some children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 1752EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
