<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Jan. 23, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Exceptionally warm, moist air from the Gulf of Mexico to the
eastern Ohio Valley will be lifted by a powerful jet-stream
disturbance resulting in heavy rain with embedded bands of potent
thunderstorms. Meanwhile, unsettled weather will be common west of
the crest of the Rockies as a series of disturbances begin to draw
colder air into the region.
</P>
<P>
   Strong thunderstorms accompanied by torrential rain, hail and
damaging winds will erupt in the tepid air ahead of a cold front
from the southern Appalachians to Florida. Farther north, heavy
rain will gradually move east from the eastern Ohio Valley into the
central Appalachians. On Saturday night, melting snow and ice will
combine with the downpours to heighten the risk of flash flooding
from northern Ohio to Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing winds from the south will displace cool air near the
northeast coast. The milder air will meet resistance over extreme
northern New England where a period of freezing rain and drizzle
will occur. Otherwise, mostly cloudy conditions will prevail
Saturday and Saturday night before heavy rain arrives early Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and a few snow and rain showers will linger over the
northern Mississippi valley as northerly breezes deliver colder
air. Farther west, mainly dry conditions will prevail from the
Plains to the east slopes of the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   A band of rain and heavy mountain snow will accompany a cold
front as it moves south through central and northern California.
The Northwest will be chilly with coastal showers and patchy snow
in the interior.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: The Time for Twisters
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of just eight minutes Thursday evening, two
tornadoes tore across Searcy, Ark. Meanwhile, at Greenville, Miss.,
two tornadoes were reported in a little more than two hours late
Thursday. Tornado season begins along the Gulf Coast in January and
February, when warm, humid air streaming rapidly northward from the
Gulf of Mexico is lifted by cold, potent jet-stream disturbances
from the Pacific Ocean or Canada. North of the Gulf Coast states,
tornado season begins in spring or summer, waiting until the
retreating jet stream and Gulf air simultaneously arrive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 1753EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0266 </DOCNO>
