</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-GUERRILLAS-$ADV24-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELA FEELING THE HEAT OF COLOMBIA'S CIVIL WAR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Jan. 24) 
(Eds.: Accent mark needed over i in Pais) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL NULA, Venezuela _ The creased, handwritten note from the
Colombian guerrilla was cordial, but to Venezuelan rancher Santiago
Moncada, it read like a not-so-subtle threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The objective of this is to find out whether it's possible to
provide us with two head of cattle. If so, please deliver them to
the night watchman,`` said the letter, which was addressed to
Moncada and signed by ``Lenin'' of the National Liberation Army,
known by its Spanish initials ELN.
</P>
<P>
   As Colombia's civil war enters its 35th year, the conflict is
increasingly spilling over into peaceful, oil-rich Venezuela.
Rebels from the ELN, Colombia's second-largest Marxist guerrilla
group, cross the border at will to escape the Colombian army to
treat wounded fighters and to raise money through extortion and
kidnappings, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Ranchers like Moncada risk being abducted unless they comply
with rebel demands to provide them with food and money.
</P>
<P>
   ``You either collaborate with them or you leave the area,''
Moncada explained.
</P>
<P>
   In response, some Venezuelan ranchers have started paying
Colombian paramilitary death squads for protection, according to
human rights activists in both countries.
</P>
<P>
   The Venezuelan government has dispatched thousands of troops to
the zone and has built a ``model city'' to retake control of the
border. But the militarization of the frontier has led to a surge
in human rights abuses. And as ranchers and businessmen pull out,
the local economy has become a shambles.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't want to invest due to the insecurity of the
area,'' said Margarita Urbina, a rancher who lives near the border
town of El Nula in Apure state and has put her land up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela isn't the only nation suffering the fallout of
Colombia's war.
</P>
<P>
   Panama has become a rear-guard safe haven and a gunrunning route
for Colombian guerrillas. The tiny nation, which was once part of
Colombia, has absorbed about 2,000 war refugees. An isolated
Panamanian jungle village was raided by paramilitaries 14 months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, Colombian guerrillas regularly cross into Ecuador
to run guns, hide kidnapping victims and to rest up following
military operations, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela, however, has the most to lose if the conflict
continues.
</P>
<P>
   Part of its border area with Colombia has turned into an ELN
sanctuary. The 3,000-member rebel group, which has kidnapped
hundreds of Colombians each year for huge ransoms to help finance
its war, began targeting Venezuelans in the mid-1990s when
Colombia's economy began to stagnate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colombian ranchers are poorer,'' said Juan Francisco Mesa of
the Bogota group Pais Libre, which counsels the relatives of
kidnapping victims. ``The Colombians also have better
anti-kidnapping capabilities. So, (the guerrillas) crossed the
border.''
</P>
<P>
   Scores of Venezuelans are kidnapped annually, including 72 last
year. Many abductions, however, are the work of common criminals,
said Feijoo Colomine, Venezuela's vice minister for borders.
</P>
<P>
   With its army overextended trying to turn back rebel threats
across its own country, Colombia has paid scant attention to the
problem in Venezuela, Colomine said.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela has beefed up police and National Guard border
patrols, but that may have made matters worse, human rights
officials say. More than a dozen Venezuelan troops have been killed
or wounded in skirmishes with the ELN.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guerrillas know the area better than the armed forces,''
said Alvaro Cattini, who directs a palm-oil project on the border.
``This is their back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is that Venezuelan soldiers aren't always viewed
as the good guys.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, they massacred 14 fishermen in a botched raid on
guerrillas. Constitutional guarantees along the border were
suspended in 1994, giving troops the right to enter homes and
arrest Venezuelans without judicial orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel hostile toward the armed forces because they
mistreat them,'' said Colomine, who was once detained overnight by
soldiers despite the fact that he showed his government ID badge.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Colombian newsweekly Semana, Hugo Chavez, who
will be sworn in as Venezuela's president on Feb. 2, met secretly
with ELN leaders in 1995, urging them to call off their military
attacks and to refrain from kidnapping Venezuelans.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, tensions have eased slightly, but the ELN continues
to operate as a kind of parallel government in remote Venezuelan
municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   Some border residents have grudgingly accepted the rebels'
presence. In return for food or payments, the ELN provides
protection from cattle rustlers and an informal justice system.
</P>
<P>
   Cattini said the rebels demand that Venezuelan ranchers pay
Colombian laborers fair wages. They have also mediated divorces and
recently pressed a drunken driver to pay for damages and medical
costs following a car accident, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People rely on the guerrillas when they have no one else to
resolve their problems,'' said Alfredo Ruiz, a researcher for the
Caracas-based Peace and Justice Network, a human rights group.
</P>
<P>
   Even road contractors for a government-funded highway connecting
the border with the Venezuelan capital of Caracas were forced to
pay ``war taxes'' to the ELN to finish the last leg of the project,
Colomine said.
</P>
<P>
   With little faith in government authorities, large landowners
have considered forming their own paramilitary squads. One group
requested, and was denied, a government permit to import assault
rifles, Ruiz said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Colombian side of the border, such infrastructure is
already in place. Formed in the 1980s to fight the guerrillas and
their civilian supporters, the Colombian paramilitaries number
about 5,000 fighters and have carried out hundreds of massacres.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Venezuelan authorities detained six Colombian
paramilitaries in the Venezuelan border state of Apure. Mesa, of
Pas Libre, has talked with Venezuelan ranchers who have admitted to
paying Colombian paramilitaries for protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that there are paramilitary groups financed by
Venezuelan ranchers,'' Mesa said. ``It's easier for them to pay
Colombian paramilitaries than to rely on the National Guard'' for
help.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there is no evidence that Venezuelans are operating
their own militias, Ruiz said. But Carlos Castano, a self-styled
warlord who heads Colombia's paramilitary umbrella organization,
told Semana last August that Venezuelans have joined one of his
fronts operating along the frontier.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a group of 70 people in the border area with
Venezuela. Half are Venezuelans. They came to our training
schools,'' Castano said.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela's efforts to attract people and private investment to
the frontier have largely failed. Last year, the government built
Ciudad Sucre as a kind of border-town buffer in an area teeming
with ELN rebels.
</P>
<P>
   But during a recent visit, most of the 210 concrete row houses
were empty. A sparsely stocked grocery store had no customers, and
the only sign of life was a salesman who parked his truck on a
deserted street to peddle vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz said that instead of building towns from scratch and
waiting for the people to come, the state should improve
infrastructure and services in existing border communities _ where
the military is often the only government presence.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts say there is little hope that conditions will
improve as long as the fighting goes on. As the war shows signs of
turning into a regional conflict, Colombian President Andres
Pastrana is under growing international pressure to reach a
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   He opened peace talks with the Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia, the nation's largest rebel group, two weeks ago. The ELN
has announced a ``national convention'' in February to discuss an
eventual truce.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of his concern, Venezuelan President-elect Chavez
recently flew to Havana to meet with Pastrana and Cuban President
Fidel Castro about the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling here is: `Why do we have to suffer for a distant
war?''' said Maria Victoria Cristancho, a Caracas-based journalist
who writes for the Bogota daily El Tiempo. ``That's why they say:
Peace in Colombia is peace in Venezuela.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
