</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DILBERT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARGINALLY TASTELESS, MOSTLY FUNNY `DILBERT' DEBUTS ON UPN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you were making a comics sandwich, ``The Far Side'' would be
the scene-stealing ham, ``Peanuts'' the smooth cheese, and
``Dilbert'' the oven-fresh wry.
</P>
<P>
   When transferring these ingredients to TV, wry is always the
hardest to keep fresh. Even ``Seinfeld,'' the pumpernickel of
television comedies, got a little stale after co-creator Larry
David left the show.
</P>
<P>
   UPN is hoping another Larry with ``Seinfeld'' connections _
Larry Charles _ can keep the humor sharp and satirical as
``Dilbert'' goes from the printed page to the TV screen. Charles
was a writer and supervising producer on the early years of
``Seinfeld'' before moving to ``Mad About You'' for a couple of
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Dilbert,'' he is teamed with the strip's creator, Scott
Adams, and their first effort, taking the place of the canceled
``Guys Like Us,'' is amusing, if not exactly knee-slappingly
hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   For UPN, which desperately needs a winner, amusing is good, no
matter what Matt Groening says. Groening, the wisecracking creator
of ``The Simpsons'' and a new sci-fi animation show for Fox called
``Futurama,'' joked last week that in the future there will be
5,000 networks, ``and UPN is still going to be in last place.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, if Charles and Adams can infuse the TV ``Dilbert''
with the same sardonic observational humor that has made the
newspaper version the favorite of millions of working stiffs.
Problem is, there will be more than a half-dozen animated comedies
in prime time soon, and no one is sure if if all of them can
survive.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem, and this might be mine alone, is the
appropriateness of the character's voices. Daniel Stern, who voiced
the adult Kevin Arnold for the entire six-season run of ``The
Wonder Years,'' is fine as Dilbert _ the sometimes assertive,
sometimes wimpy spokesman for the corporately frustrated. But Chris
Elliot as Dogbert, Dilbert's mean-spirited housemate, and Kathy
Griffin as Alice, Dilbert's supportive workplace colleague, don't
strike my ear just right.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this first episode, titled ``The Name,'' is a mostly
funny, sometimes tasteless sendup of corporate behavior as the
nameless company where Dilbert works tries to come up with a name
for a new product that doesn't yet exist. The product is needed
because the most recent product, an organic throat lozenge,
contained anthrax bacteria and, thus, didn't encourage repeat
business. As the pointy-haired boss (voiced by Larry Miller) points
out: ``We have to make up for the revenue shortfall and there are
only two ways to do that: Create a new product or make massive,
painful budget cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Dogbert, hired on as a consultant, informs the group: ``As you
probably know, all the good product names have been trademarked by
companies who are competent.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Wally (Gordon Hunt), the terrified follower, replies:
``Competent! How we gonna compete with that?'' Fortunately, no one
at UPN recognized, or was terribly offended by, the metaphor,
because the line made it to air.
</P>
<P>
   For that, the network should be congratulated. Absent some
needless network meddling, Charles and Adams may actually have
something here, and the last thing they need is more input from a
corporation. As Dilbert warns in the first episode: ``Everyone will
want to have input, because input is easier than doing real work.''
</P>
<P>
   Just ask a TV critic.
</P>
<P>
   Dilbert. Half-hour animated comedy about workplace frustration,
based on the comic strip by Scott Adams. Premieres Monday on UPN.
Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
