<P>
   ATHOME _ AT&AMP;T, the largest U.S. long-distance phone company, is
considering selling its Internet access business, which includes
the WorldNet dial-up service, to At Home Corp. for $1 billion in
stock. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GAGULF _ ATLANTA _ Analysts were surprised by Georgia Gulf's
fourth quarter earnings. An unexpected pair of cost savings moves
by the company added 14 cents per share to the results. (Chambers,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   IRS-CHANGES _ The Internal Revenue Service today reached another
milestone in its major restructuring of the agency by announcing
the headquarters locations for its four new operating divisions. By
mid-1999, new headquarters locations will be set up in the
Washington , D.C., area for the Small Business &AMP; Self-Employed
Operating Division and the Tax Exempt Operating Division.
(Tharpe/Coffee, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-SCAM _ The scam works like this: A person calls senior
citizens, telling them he wants to ''fix their Medicare.'' The
purported Medicare ''official'' may go door to door, asking for the
beneficiaries' Medicare number.
</P>
<P>
   The con artist can use that number to bill the federal health
insurance program for medical services never performed. (Miller,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AIRTRAN _ ATLANTA _ AirTran Airways has agreed to a $5 million
settlement in a shareholder lawsuit stemming from the crash of
ValuJet Flight 592. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PARAGON _ Paragon Trade Brands Inc. (PTB) and Procter &AMP; Gamble
Co. (PG) settled all patent disputes between the two companies.
(Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POULTRY _ On the last day of its annual expo Friday, The U.S.
Poultry &AMP; Egg Association discusses the future of exports,
prospects for imports and impact of international economic
conditions on the poultry industry. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GA-MERITPLAN _ ATLANTA _ The state's plan to move 400,000 state
employees and dependents into managed-care networks apparently is
in limbo until a new department of health is organized. (Miller,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NCR _ Dayton-based NCR Corp. is expected to release its
strongest full-year earnings in years on Wednesday. Meanwhile, its
stock price had nearly doubled in worth to $50 during the past four
months. All of this raises the question: Has NCR, after years of
downsizing and restructuring, finally found a working formula? Has
it turned the corner and once again become a consistently
profitable company? (Bischoff, Dayton Daily News). 30-40. WITH
PHOTOSand GRAPHICS. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
