<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4835 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-0123-COX     01-22 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-0123-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REPUBLICANS OMIT ABORTION AS TOP PRIORITY FOR 2000
 &HT;    730&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican National Committee, retooling after
a disappointing election last fall, backed away from its staunch
opposition to abortion Friday in favor of pocketbook issues aimed
at winning working families back from the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nicholson, who won a spirited but lopsided campaign for
re-election Friday as chairman of the RNC, declared that tax
relief, saving Social Security, improving education and national
security were the party's top priorities through the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Hutchinson, RNC deputy press secretary, said Nicholson
developed the party's list of priorities ``in consultation with the
congressional leadership'' of the GOP, House Speaker Dennis Hastert
of Illinois and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   With narrow majorities in both houses and the Republican Party
facing its lowest approval ratings in decades, GOP leaders appeared
reluctant to press an unpopular issue that seems to have little
chance of surviving congressional opposition and presidential
vetoes.
</P>
<P>
   The RNC decision to move abortion to the back burner was
announced during the RNC's winter meeting at a downtown Washington
hotel even as thousands of anti-abortion demonstrators marched in
protest from the White House to the Capitol on the 26th anniversary
of Roe v. Wade, the Supreme Court decision that legalized abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The new list of party priorities cheered Ann Stone, the leading
advocate of abortion rights in the GOP, but contrasted sharply with
the campaign rhetoric of would-be GOP presidential candidates at
the Conservative Political Action Committee (CPAC) meeting in
suburban Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Stone, whose organization is called Republicans for Choice, said
she felt as if she was ``returning from the wilderness,'' having
promoted abortion rights since the early days of the Reagan
presidency, when the GOP's anti-abortion fervor began.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our number one priority as a party should be winning
elections,'' she said. ``Jim can help us do that by building a
strong grass-roots party and returning us to a party that looks for
real proactive solutions to reduce abortions _ not off-the-wall
anti-choice antics and empty rhetoric.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gary Bauer, a staunch anti-abortion activist who is expected
to announce his presidential candidacy next week, said ``protecting
the lives of children waiting to be born'' is crucial to the
Republican Party. ``To forget the sanctity of life ...must not
happen in the party of Lincoln and Reagan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, millionaire magazine publisher Steve Forbes, a 1996
presidential candidate who is expected to run again in 2000, warned
CPAC that ``establishment'' Republicans think abortion is ``a
losing cause'' for the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would have us walk away from it, drop it, leave it
alone,'' he said. ``But we are a party of principle ... and it is
time to put abortion on the road to extinction.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Slade, the former Florida state GOP chairman who had
challenged Nicholson for the national chairmanship, said Friday he
hoped the national party would follow the lead of the party in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just took the issue off the table,'' he said. ``We decided
we were not going to talk about things we can't do anything about
...and so the issue went away.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Florida legislature enacted a ban on so-called partial
birth abortions and passed a law requiring parental notification
when minors seek abortion, ``I haven't even heard the word
'abortion','' Slade added.
</P>
<P>
   But Rusty Paul, chairman of the state GOP in Georgia, said that
despite Nicholson's speech, ``this party is as committed to our
platform today as it was two and a half years ago when it was
written.'' He added, ``I fully expect that two years from now, that
platform will be no weaker than it is today.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 GOP platform called for constitutional guarantees of
life to ``the unborn child'' and the prosecution of physicians who
perform abortions. The anti-abortion provisions of the platform
prompted Bob Dole, the party's presidential nominee that year, to
assert that he was not bound to run on the platform.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Weddington, the GOP state chair in Texas, insisted that
the Republican Party is not moderating its position on banning
abortion even though Nicholson did not make it a party priority.
``Our respect for life is fundamental to being a winning party,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson, winning re-election to the party chairmanship on a
127-36 vote, acknowledged that the Republican Party had ``sustained
political damage, at least in the short term,'' for its drive to
impeach President Clinton. But he promised that the party would
rebound with an agenda to help working families.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the top of our priority list, we need to give American
families and job creators tax relief _ at least 10 percent across
the board,'' he said. ``This is a matter of fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the GOP's second priority would be ``to protect and
strengthen Social Security.'' He said the GOP would work with the
president, insisting ``only on two things _ that the plan contains
no tax increases and no cuts in benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   The third priority, he said, is ``to make our public schools
work for our children again'' through increased accountability and
more funds for classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The final priority he cited was the renewal of the Reagan
administration's proposal to protect the United States from weapons
of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take more than a few missiles fired at convenient
moments to defeat the growing threat posed by terrorists and rogue
dictators,'' Nicholson said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Nicholson said the GOP is willing to meet the president
and Democrats ``even more than halfway'' on numerous issues, he
also blasted Vice President Al Gore as if the 2000 election
campaign had already begun.
</P>
<P>
   He called Gore the ``chief defender'' of the president and the
``heir apparent as leader of the tax-and-spend wing of the
Democratic Party.'' He also unveiled a ``Gore Spend-o-Meter'' to
keep track of Clinton spending proposals over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle, who will seek the GOP
presidential nomination in 2000, also took aim at Gore. He told
CPAC conference delegates that Clinton's State of the Union address
is ``Al Gore's platform'' for the Democratic Party's 2000
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris LeHane dismissed Nicholson's comments as
``just politics'' and referred to Quayle as ``a medieval
conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
