<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4839 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SCHOLARS-2TAK     01-22 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCHOLARS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE LAWYERS WERE SUCCESSFUL, EXPERTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Va., Conn., Ark., Ill.)  (Eds: See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-ASSESS,
IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-CASE)  
(mk) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the White House completed arguments this week, experts on
impeachment said the president's lawyers had offered constitutional
and factual arguments powerful enough to counter the momentum of
the House's case and blunt the effort to call witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, the experts _ professors of constitutional law at
law schools around the country _ said creative legal arguments and
a risky strategy of challenging some facts in the case against the
president helped counter what were generally considered effective
arguments from the House impeachment managers last week.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the president's fate is a political question. But
from a legal point of view, lawyers defending the president could
not have accomplished much more, said Eric Freedman, a law
professor and expert on impeachment at Hofstra University School of
Law in Hempstead, N.Y. ``The sides now are at least even,'' he
said, ``and if the sides are even, that's neither enough legally or
politically to get a conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gerhardt, an impeachment expert and professor at the
College of William and Mary School of Law in Williamsburg, Va.,
agreed. ``I think the White House argument helped move the ball
back toward the thinking that the need for witnesses on the floor
of the Senate may not be as strong as some people may have
thought,'' he said. ``And it might have alerted the Senate to be
very careful in accepting what the House managers say is
affirmative evidence of wrongdoing.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments of the experts showed that, for all its historic
significance, the impeachment trial is taking on the rhythm of an
ordinary trial, with each side's arguments swaying sentiment only
to see it sway back again.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional experts, many of whom praised the House
managers in interviews last weekend, said this week that the White
House lawyers, with the eloquent help of former Sen. Dale Bumpers
of Arkansas, combined some novel legal arguments with the
rhetorical flourish that can make oratory decisive both in politics
and law.
</P>
<P>
   The president's lawyers provided the necessary counterweight to
their opponents' assertions, said Akhil Reed Amar, a professor of
constitutional law at Yale Law School. ``Just as the House managers
tried to connect the dots, the White House folks poked holes; they
broke the lines of connection,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional scholars said the president's lawyers
presented some new legal arguments that were clearly aimed at
senators concerned about the precedent Clinton's trial will set.
</P>
<P>
   Cass Sunstein, a professor of constitutional law at the
University of Chicago Law School, said he was particularly
impressed by an argument of Gregory Craig, a special White House
counsel. Craig combined two legal points in asserting that the
House managers were unfairly adding to and changing their
assertions against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Craig's first point cited established rules holding that
criminal charges, like perjury, cannot be vague because a defendant
has a right to know details of charges against him. The second
argument was that to the extent that the managers were amplifying
the sparse language of the impeachment articles, they were
improperly taking on powers delegated in the Constitution to the
House alone.
</P>
<P>
   Craig complained that the charges ``have been a moving target
for us throughout this entire process.'' Sunstein said Craig's
legal claims raised that assertion of unfairness to constitutional
proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Sunstein said it was not clear that argument was legally
correct. But he called it ``creative, original, plausible and
new.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Ackerman, a Yale authority on impeachment law, said
Craig's argument was one of the strongest against conviction. ``The
issue is: Can agents of the House usurp the power of the House to
impeach a president and define `high crimes and misdemeanors'?''
Ackerman said. ``They can't,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   A second significant legal step in the White House presentation,
some of the experts said, was a concession by the chief White House
counsel, Charles Ruff, on a constitutional question that has been
central to the impeachment debate.
</P>
<P>
   Citing history and the words of some drafters of the
Constitution, some supporters of the president have argued that
impeachment was not intended as a punishment for what they called
purely private conduct, like lying about a sexual affair. That
absolutist argument was considered a weak point for the White House
because it opened a debate about whether its proponents meant that
a president could not be impeached even for the most serious
private crimes, like murder.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff denied that had ever been the White House view, saying the
managers ``attribute to the president the argument that impeachment
can never reach personal conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ruff then tried to shortcut the debate. ``That is not our
position,'' Ruff said, adding that when a president's ``very
capacity to govern is called into question'' as a result of private
wrongdoing, removal would be warranted. ``Judgments must be made,''
Ruff said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Susan Low Bloch, a professor of constitutional law at Georgetown
University Law Center in Washington, said Ruff's statement made it
clear that the White House lawyers accept the view of most
constitutional scholars that in some extreme cases private conduct
could have enough effect on political matters to be impeachable.
</P>
<P>
   Other experts said the concession also served the strategic
purpose of removing an argument of the House managers that had some
intellectual appeal. ``It was,'' Sunstein said, ``a very
straightforward and honest way of handling a persuasive argument
made by the House managers.''
</P>
<P>
   In his presentation on Thursday, Bumpers seemed to retreat from
Ruff's position, asking, ``What are we doing here?'' and once again
arguing that ``Nobody has suggested that Bill Clinton committed a
political crime against the state.'' But some of the experts said
Ruff's view and Bumpers' could be reconciled, with Bumpers simply
arguing that even if some private behavior might be impeachable,
Clinton's was not that kind of behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the law professors said the riskiest move by the White
House lawyers was their decision to make detailed arguments
challenging some of the facts about the case stated by the House
managers.
</P>
<P>
   As the White House struggles to avoid unpredictable Senate
testimony by witnesses, the tack of quarreling about the House
version of the facts held its own dangers. In court cases, judges
generally rule that sharp disagreements over facts indicate that
witnesses are needed to clear up any disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Gerhardt of William and Mary said the White House lawyers were
``walking along a razor's edge'' by arguing both that no testimony
was needed to acquit and that the evidence so far was not what the
House managers described. ``The potential downside,'' he said, ``is
the more the White House lawyers talk about the facts, the more the
White House helps make the case for witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   But the experts generally agreed that the White House lawyers
had persuasively raised questions about the House managers' version
concerning several pivotal events, including the circumstances
surrounding the decision by the president's friend, Vernon Jordan,
to step up efforts to try to get a job for Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Freedman of Hofstra said it was a traditional defense lawyer's
tactic to suggest that jurors should be suspicious of prosecution
assertions. Defense lawyers often focus on proven errors in a
prosecution case and then urge jurors, Freedman said, to ask: ``I
wonder where else something like that may have happened?'' Freedman
said the president's lawyers were encouraging the senators to ask
the same question.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the experts said the final statement by Bumpers
appropriately moved the White House presentation away from the
legalisms that dominated many of the presentations. Because
impeachment is a unique mixture of legal and political decisions,
Bloch said, the president's case was strengthened by Bumpers'
sweeping arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brought a sense of what the role of the Senate is in the
process; a sense of history and the role of precedent and what this
case may mean in the future,'' Bloch said. ``And he made people _
he certainly made me _ step back from the minutiae.''
</P>
</TEXT>
