<SLUG> BC-GAYS-MILITARY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON FIGURES SHOW RECORD NUMBERS OF GAYS KICKED OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Updates throughout.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The armed forces discharged homosexual personnel in
record numbers last year, despite a controversial policy that
allows gays and lesbians to serve under certain conditions,
Pentagon data showed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The new figures represent the largest number of homosexuals
discharged from the military in any year since President Clinton's
controversial ``don't ask, don't tell, don't pursue'' policy went
into effect in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The number of discharges in 1998 _ 1,145 personnel in all four
branches of the military _ compares with a total of 997 in 1997 and
was the highest level since 1987 when 1,380 men and women were
released, according to a report by Rudy de Leon, undersecretary of
defense for personnel and readiness.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force outpaced the other military services last year,
letting go a record of 414 gay and lesbian personnel, compared with
309 in 1997, 282 in 1996, 234 in 1995 and 180 in 1994, according to
Air Force figures.
</P>
<P>
   Lackland Air Force Base in San Antonio led the way in the Air
Force, accounting for 271 basic trainees severed from the service.
</P>
<P>
   The Army discharged record numbers of homosexuals in 1998,
according to Pentagon figures, with 310 personnel dismissed
compared with 197 in 1997, 206 in 1996, 182 in 1995 and 136 in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy released 345 sailors in 1998 compared with 413 in 1997,
302 in 1996, 260 in 1995 and 245 in 1994, according to the Pentagon
figures.
</P>
<P>
   The Marine Corps, the smallest military branch, released 76
homosexual troops in 1998, 78 in 1997, 60 in 1996, 46 in 1995 and
36 in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   T'jae Gibson, an Air Force spokeswoman at the Pentagon, said a
majority of the Air Force's discharges in 1998 _ 391 cases _ were
because the service member voluntarily came forward and revealed
his or her homosexuality to a commander.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people walked into their boss and said, `I am gay' or `I
engage in homosexual or bisexual activity,''' said Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson said an internal Air Force report conducted at Lackland
found that most of those at the facility who said they were
homosexual did so ``solely for the purpose of self-eliminating from
basic training and the Air Force.''
</P>
<P>
   The increase in gay discharges in the Air Force was first
disclosed by the San Antonio Express-News.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Servicemembers Legal Defense Network, a leading
gay rights legal organization, complained that the Air Force
actively roots out gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have also heard that spin before from the Air Force,'' said
Michelle Benecke, co-director of SLDN, which provides legal aid to
troops tossed from the military under the policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real reason for gay discharges is that commanders continue
to ask, pursue and harass people whom they suspect are gay,'' she
contended.
</P>
<P>
   The current Pentagon policy of ``don't ask, don't tell, don't
pursue'' _ the result of a bruising battle among the White House,
the Joint Chiefs of Staff and Congress in 1993 _ means that
homosexual activity is banned in the military, but that gays and
lesbians may serve as long as they keep quiet about their sexual
orientation and aren't caught engaged in homosexual acts.
</P>
<P>
   It also means that commanders may not inquire of a service
member's sexual orientation, according to the rules. However, they
may do so if they have ``credible information'' that a service
member engages in homosexual conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Pentagon efforts to clarify the policy, homosexual
rights organizations maintain that gays and lesbians in the ranks
are routinely drummed out even though they comply with the rule.
</P>
<P>
   C. Dixon Osburn, co-executive director for SLDN, said, ``The new
numbers suggest that rather than providing any kind of relief for
gay people under this policy, commanders are going after people
even more fervently.''
</P>
<P>
   The policy ``has intensified the ousting of people thought to be
gay or lesbian,'' said Rob Blanchard, a San Antonio-based state
vice president of the Log Cabin Republicans, a nationwide group of
15,000 gays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
