<HEADER>
A4851 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOORMAN-MOVIE-LADN     01-22 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOORMAN-MOVIE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASY COME, EASY GO...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; John Boorman puts little value on possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Good thing, too. It's enabled the 65-year-old English director
to follow a particularly distinctive career that has always been
blessedly free of the commercial considerations _ and high-living
materialism _ that can drive even the most independent movie
artists toward hit-hungry compromise.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, it kept Boorman from holding a grudge against
Martin Cahill, the Irish criminal mastermind who once stole a
number of Boorman's valuables and is now the subject of one his
best films, ``The General.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I became aware of him was in 1981, when he
broke into my house and took a few things,'' says the trim,
snowy-haired Boorman, who has lived in Dublin for many years.
``Amongst them was this gold record that I had for the music from
`Deliverance,' `Dueling Banjos.' He must have thought it was made
of real gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police told me they knew who'd done it; even then, Cahill
was always flaunting his robberies and taunting the police to prove
he'd done it. I was very angry, in a way, at the time. But if you
saw `Hope and Glory,' that was my childhood. We lost our home and
everything during the London Blitz; everything was rationed, we had
nothing. Ever since then, possessions have never meant that much to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Anarchy, on the other hand, has always rated high on Boorman's
list. ``Hope and Glory,'' after all, was a schoolboy's celebration
of how Hitler's bombs shattered England's strict, inhibiting social
control.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Hollywood hits (``Point Blank,'' ``Deliverance''),
personal projects (``Glory,'' ``Excalibur'') or the strange stuff
that fell somewhere in between (``Zardoz,'' `Exorcist II: The
Heretic,'' ``The Emerald Forest,'' ``Where the Heart Is''), Boorman
has always been fascinated by what happens to people when their
familiar world falls apart. And he's especially intrigued by the
unconventional rebels who facilitate that, especially ones that
subvert civilized authority.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Cahill, then, was a dream come true. A congenital thief
from early childhood, he grew up in a Dublin slum to which he was
fiercely loyal _ he even camped out on its rubble after the
buildings were bulldozed for urban renewal. Cahill recruited a gang
from his old neighbors, which he ruled with a combination of
brilliance, brutality and the sheer force of his larger-than-life
personality.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a 20-year gross of some $60 million worth of loot
helped maintain gang loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Cahill made a point of not only taunting the police, but also
the Catholic Church (he fathered children with his sister-in-law as
well as his wife, reportedly with the ongoing consent of both
women) and the Irish Republican Army (which ultimately took credit
for Cahill's assassination). As played by the pugnacious Brendan
Gleeson in the movie, Cahill's audacity was matched only by his
charisma.
</P>
<P>
   Some have complained that the movie lionizes a violent criminal.
Typically, though, Boorman takes a wider, if no less subversive,
view. He covers Cahill's ruthless cruelty, self-destructive egotism
and moments of crippling self-doubt as thoroughly as he does the
character's latter-day Robin Hood qualities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of the film, for me, was to humanize the criminal,
to make you feel like you could get inside of him, like you could
actually be this character,'' Boorman says. ``Of course, he was
something of a folk hero. If you mention his name in Dublin, people
will smile _ except, of course, his victims and the people who
suffered under him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there definitely was this grudging admiration people had
for someone who was prepared to stand up against the whole of
society and take everything on.''
</P>
<P>
   There's some of that spirit in Boorman himself. A determined
individualist, he's been known to walk away from projects he's put
years into developing _ the currently in release, widely acclaimed
``A Simple Plan'' was the last example _ when studio interference
grew too great.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The General's'' case, Boorman organized shaky independent
financing that guaranteed him creative freedom, and he used it to
cast the unknown (though brilliant) Gleeson rather than a star name
and shoot the thing in uncommercial black and white. No effort was
made to alter authentic Irish accents for a large potential
audience of American ears, either.
</P>
<P>
   For his uncompromising efforts, Boorman earned the Cannes Film
Festival's directing award and a raft of glowing reviews. But the
movie, which was released on a limited basis at Christmastime in
the United States, has been greeted by indifferent box-office
figures and few year-end awards and nominations.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Boorman isn't the kind of guy who cares about such
things. Maybe it's a philosophy. More likely, it's an outgrowth of
the reckless exuberance he's always associated with filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Voight, who plays Cahill's primary police pursuer in
``General'' and is a longtime friend of the director, tells a story
that illustrates Boorman's approach to his craft.
</P>
<P>
   ``In `Deliverance,' we had this pool the size of a football
field, surrounded by cliffs,'' Voight recalls. ``They had a dam up
top that they could let water through. The day before this
particular incident, John had asked for half a gate's worth of
water, and that was plenty enough for us to do all these stunts
under this huge waterfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next morning, John gets on the walkie-talkie and says,
`Gimme a gate. No, a gate and a half! Gimme two gates!' We hear
this sound and all of a sudden, thundering over this cliff, is a
huge amount of water. The water in this football field-sized pool
is visibly rising. He's got a camera in there and he's standing
behind it with a hat on. I dive in and I'm not acting, because I
see the water rising up the legs of the tripod _ fast! It goes
right up across the lens, over tha [Ux
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
