<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4858 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV24-B     01-22 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV24-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ATTACK ON NORTHEASTERN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, January 24, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The ugly little episode of the public threat to
Northeastern University by what the Globe refers to as ``one top
Cellucci aide'' raises the question of political thuggery by an
administration that should consider itself lucky to have just won
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the Goon Squad motif that we'd hoped was just part
of the usual election tomfoolery, this top aide was quoted
anonymously in last Sunday's ``Political Capital'' collection of
tidbits.
</P>
<P>
   First came a warning to potential contributors who might be
thinking of writing a check to former Atty. Gen. Scott Harshbarger,
who lost the governor's race by 3.4 percent. Harshbarger had a
$205,000 debt, after raising some $5 million, and prior to starting
to teach at Northeastern and its Law School, the Democrat wanted to
retire his debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some like to play it both ways but we're keeping an eye on
that,'' said the ``top aide'' to Cellucci. In other words, anyone
writing a check to Harshbarger might incur the ire of the
Republican administration, which is fast developing a post-Weld
reputation for squalid political ballgames. But then came the
threat to Northeastern _ an important educational institution that
is on the rise under President Richard Freeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's become a liberal resting place,'' said the anonymous
Cellucci aide, and Northeastern officials ``are going to find some
doors shut to them around here if Harshbarger becomes a public
policy spokesman there.'' This must have been a reference to
Michael Dukakis, a part-time teacher at Northeastern who spends
part of the academic year in California and also has a presidential
appointment to Amtrak.
</P>
<P>
   The double-edged threat seems to have kept some donors away from
Harshbarger's fundraiser at the Sonesta in Cambridge Thursday
night. Some big-name civic leaders who'd initially agreed to come
shied away from the event. But approximately $125,000 was raised
nevertheless from the 300 or so on hand.
</P>
<P>
   It was left to Suffolk County Dist. Atty. Ralph Martin _ a
Republican _ to crack that he might have put himself in the
Republican doghouse by showing up. ut he was not the only
Republican who spoke. Former Attys. Gen. Jane Brady of Delaware and
Jeff Pine of Rhode Island delivered testimonials to Harshbarger, as
did Mike Moore, the former attorney general of Mississippi who
enlisted Harshbarger in the landmark tobacco settlement which is
giving Massachusetts some $300 million a year to spend on health
care.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger's successor in the AG's office, Tom Reilly,
announced an award to be made in his predecessor's name. Also on
hand: Martha Coakley, new Middlesex County DA, and, like Martin and
Reilly, a prosecutor who got hired by the guy who'd have been
elected governor, if he only could have changed one vote out of 50.
</P>
<P>
   The intention of the anonymously quoted ``top Cellucci aide''
was obviously to make it harder for Harshbarger to get rid of his
debt and get on with his life. Petty, mean-spirited, cheap-jack,
sure; but no big deal. The big deal is the nasty dig at
Northeastern, where Freeland is well on his way to putting the
school on the map the same way John Silber did at BU beginning 20
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The campus is hopping, graceful new buildings sprout, the
student body has been slimmed down and test-scored up, and when
Freeland announced Harshbarger would teach and work on the school's
criminal justice programs and the Tobacco Products Liability
Project, it was considered a smart move by a school that's on the
move. ``He will be a valuable voice on public policy issues,'' said
Freeland. Oops.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the Cellucci Goon Squad, with threats and bluster. On
Thursday, Cellucci tried to duck responsibility: ``I did not make
the comments, and I would not make them,'' he said. ``I think it is
great that Scott Harshbarger will be at Northeastern.'' Yeah.
Right, Governor. That's your story, and you're sticking to it, even
while the Globe quoted a Cellucci operative as repeating the
threats to the school, that ``if Northeastern is going to give him
a perch to launch another race for governor, they can't expect to
get away scot-free.'' Or should that be Scott-free?
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci knows a good deal about politicians on academic
payrolls. He was on the Boston College payroll for $30 K a year for
teaching one two-hour class once a week for 28 weeks; that's $535
per teaching hour. When that proved controversial, Cellucci's wife
went on the BC payroll at $42,000 a year as preservation manager
for the library.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of politicians moonlight at local colleges. Harshbarger for
a time taught at BU Law School, though he was and is a political
foe of BU Chancellor John Silber, with whom he frequently clashed.
But for the Cellucci crew to start mucking about with threats to
important institutions at this level of pettiness raises unsettling
questions about how Cellucci will conduct his office for the next
four years.
</P>
<P>
   No one expects him to be in Bill Weld's neighborhood as an
intellect nor as a political innovator; Cellucci's victory is
attributable to a local economy going gangbusters, his virtual
incumbency as acting governor, Harshbarger's inability to nudge his
way over the goalline, and defections by some key Democrats who had
an ax to grind on Harshbarger's neck. Fair enough; that's politics.
But would a Weld have countenanced his henchmen thus browbeating a
prominent university? No way.
</P>
<P>
   The unabashed vendetta against Northeastern, affirmed in the
Globe first Sunday and then reaffirmed in comments made Thursday,
both times anonymously, by spokesman for the same governor who
disavows such thuggery, leaves a whiff of hypocrisy in the air. If
just one voter in 50 had switched, it would be Cellucci who's
looking for work.
</P>
<P>
   Threatening Northeastern _ twice in five days _ is stupid.
Because at least two of Northeastern's trustees raised a lot of
money for Cellucci. And for his hirelings to bluster in his name,
while he issues only pale and wan disclaimers, means we will all
have to keep a much closer watch on this lowbrow crew from here on
in.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
