<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4860 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATHOME23-COX     01-22 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATHOME23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AtHome considers WorldNet buy to boost its Internet access
service
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Internet industry is like the weather. If you
don't like it, wait a minute.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Wall Street Journal, AtHome, the high-speed
Internet access arm of cable TV giant Tele-Communications Inc., is
considering the acquisition of WorldNet's estimated 1.3 million
consumer subscribers and its one million business customers.
</P>
<P>
   That comes on the heels of an announcement Tuesday that AtHome
would acquire Internet search engine Excite for $7.5 billion in
stock. Both companies, along with hoards of analysts and most media
outlets, said the deal trumpeted the arrival of a new age of high
speed Internet access for ordinary users. AtHome specializes in
high speed access to the Internet using cable TV modems.
</P>
<P>
   But if the rumors are true that AtHome is considering purchasing
WorldNet's conventional telephone dial-up service in a $1 billion
stock swap, it may mean Web surfers will have to wait a bit longer
before the busy signals stop.
</P>
<P>
   AtHome's possible acquisition of the WorldNet service is being
described as an attempt to make it more competitive with the No. 1
online service provider, America Online. AOL has 15 million
subscribers and is the largest dial-up Internet service in the
world. AT&AMP;T's WorldNet service ranks third behind CompuServe and
Microsoft Network. Each of those companies has roughly 2 million
subscribers. MindSpring, Earthlink and WorldNet are in a virtual
dead heat for third with about 1 million consumer subscribers each.
</P>
<P>
   AtHome delivers Internet access over cable TV lines using
special modems to 330,000 customers nationwide, a drop in the
bucket compared with Internet providers that offer service using
modems and conventional telephone lines. It's likely AtHome would
eventually want to upgrade the 1 million-plus WorldNet subscribers
to the high speed cable modem service once it becomes widely
available.
</P>
<P>
   Reports are that the deal won't go through until AT&AMP;T completes
its $41 billion acquisition of TCI in February. If the TCI deal
goes through, AT&AMP;T will be AtHome's major shareholder.
Representatives for AtHome and AT&AMP;T declined to comment.
Atlanta-based Cox Communications, which along with Comcast, has a
minority stake in AtHome, referred all inquiries to AtHome. Cox
Communications is a public company controlled by Atlanta-based Cox
Enterprises, which owns The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about rumors that AtHome would acquire WorldNet
subscribers, Zia Daniell Widger, an analyst for Jupiter
Communications, said, ``I think it would be a logical step, not
inevitable step, but it does make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Wigder, the AT&AMP;T-AtHome deal is similar to AtHome's
deal with Excite. ``It's a way for AtHome to market its service,''
she says. ``It's also about
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T trying to shift its assets around and make AtHome the
center for its consumer Internet business and push up the valuation
of AtHome.''
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter Communications estimates that more than 80 percent of
all 'Net users will still be using the dial-up connections such as
those provided by AOL, MindSpring and AT&AMP;T WorldNet. ``Dial-up is
not going to disappear anytime in the near future,'' Wigder says.
``The people who can afford the $40-50 per month for cable modems
or ADSL (high-speed Internet access provided by telephone
companies) is a very small and elite audience right now,'' she
says, ``That number will grow as prices come down and access
becomes readily available.''
</P>
<P>
   The alliance would also give AtHome a significant subscriber
base of more than 2 million consumer and residential customers, but
Wigder says its hard, if not impossible for any ISP to catch up to
AOL's 15 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``AOL is too far ahead right now,'' she says. ``Nobody can catch
them. (AOL founder) Steve Case has developed an easy-to-use service
and a strong online community. AtHome has a similar model of
combining ease of use and community only for high-speed access. As
the price comes down, there will be people coming to cable modem
service who will need a bit more hand holding.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
