<HEADER>
A4861 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRS-CHANGES23-COX     01-22 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRS-CHANGES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IRS workers will stay employed after reorganization, official
says
 &HT;    By Gene Tharpe
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Internal Revenue Service workers in Atlanta should not
fear losing their jobs because of a reorganization that will phase
out the regional and district offices here, John Stocker, an
assistant deputy commissioner of the IRS, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS employs about 6,500 people in Atlanta _ 1,600 in the
regional and district offices downtown and 4,900 in the Atlanta
Processing Center and the Atlanta Customer Service Center in
Chamblee.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no decrease in employment,'' because the
regional and district employees are expected to become part of the
headquarters of the new IRS operating division to be established in
Atlanta, Stocker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in the current organization is needed in the new
operating organization. There will be a job for everyone, and we
will try to make natural fits,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One reason Atlanta was selected for the new headquarters was
the many good employees we have in the processing and customer
service centers there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta was named headquarters of the IRS' Wage and Investment
Income Operating division, one of four new divisions established by
the agency to fulfill a congressional mandate to improve customer
service.
</P>
<P>
   The headquarters, expected to be operational in late 2000, will
oversee IRS offices and employees across the nation that deal with
wage and investment income taxpayers. With about 88 million
taxpayers in that category, the Atlanta division will be the
largest of the four.
</P>
<P>
   The headquarters will be based in current IRS space in Atlanta,
although new facilities might have to be leased or constructed
later.
</P>
<P>
   The other three new IRS divisions are the Tax Exempt Operating
Division, based in central New Jersey, and the Small Business and
Self-Employed Division, and the Large and Mid-Size Operating
Divisions, both based in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The divisions were established because the IRS Restructuring and
Reform Act of 1998 directed the IRS to replace its geographically
organized structure with one based on units serving particular
groups of taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
