<HEADER>
A4862 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-MERITPLAN23-COX     01-22 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-MERITPLAN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ga. State Merit switch to PPOs faces delays
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The state's plan to move 400,000 state employees and
dependents into managed-care networks apparently is in limbo until
a new department of health is organized.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Gov. Roy Barnes said the proposed super-agency
would decide on the State Merit System changes. Legislation to
create the new agency will be introduced in the next two weeks,
spokesman Gary Horlacher said.
</P>
<P>
   The health agency is Barnes' brainchild. It would combine the
Department of Medical Assistance, State Merit System, State Health
Planning Agency, and possibly some Department of Human Resources
units, including the Division of Public Health. The University
System's health plan could come under the agency as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still options on what to include in the agency,''
Horlacher said. ``Some (units) are borderline.''
</P>
<P>
   But the agency's formation could delay the projected July
startup of the State Merit System's plan to shift members from
traditional insurance into preferred provider organizations (PPOs).
</P>
<P>
   The State Merit System has turned to managed care in order to
halt troubling losses. For the current fiscal year, 1999, the plan
is projected to lose $83.5 million, after losing about $32.4
million in fiscal 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A PPO allows more freedom than an HMO. A patient can choose a
physician or hospital outside the network, but must pay more for
that choice.
</P>
<P>
   The State Merit System, dividing the state into nine regions,
was set to award PPO contracts in December, culminating a
high-stakes competition among insurers and hospital-based groups.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, State Merit covers about 263,000 Georgians, including
teachers and school employees. Along with dependents, the total
reaches 546,000; about 138,000 belong to HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Even if it retains its traditional insurance option, the state
benefits program still plans to raise employees' deductibles and
out-of-pocket spending limits, which would also come under the PPO
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increasing them will dampen unnecessary utilization of medical
services,'' said Merit Commissioner Dana Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Also expected: an 8 percent increase in premiums that employees
will pay. School systems and other state agencies will also be
charged higher premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, in his supplemental and regular budget, has devoted $80
million to State Merit to sustain the program through fiscal 2000,
including about $55 million from higher premiums from agencies,
Russell said. The deductible and other increases will bring another
$20 million, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
