<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4865 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      01-22 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROVIDENCE THREE ASSESS THE EXPERIENCE IN THE BIG LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Their bags were packed. They were ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   While Ray Bourque and Dmitri Khristich offered their views on
their roles in Sunday afternoon's NHL All-Star Game in Tampa and
some of their teammates lamented the way the Bruins had just played
in a 3-1 loss to Ottawa heading into the weekend break, defensemen
Terry Virtue and Brandon Smith and forward Andre Savage went about
their business in the Boston locker room Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Providence Three _ the latest cavalry called to fill in for
injured players _ were heading back down Interstate 95 that night.
They were to join the Providence Bruins for a game Thursday night
at home against Fredericton, then Savage was off to Monday's AHL
All-Star Game in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   After that, with defensemen Dave Ellett and Grant Ledyard and
forward Chris Taylor among the Bruins on the mend, their NHL
futures are a bit up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's going to happen from there,'' Smith said
as he finished packing his bag. ``I've just got to keep working and
hopefully get another shot. They said go down and keep working. You
don't want to see anybody get hurt again, but fortunately, we got a
shot here. They gave us a good opportunity, and you try to make the
best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   All three got their first taste of the NHL in the last couple of
weeks. All have something to take back to the AHL. Savage, 23,
scored his first goal against Nashville Monday and played six
games. Smith, 25, made his NHL debut in Toronto and played in four
games. Virtue, 28, played in three, and the two defensemen usually
were paired together, each compiling a plus-3 here.
</P>
<P>
   For all of them, with NHL expansion coming, any exposure and
experience are a plus.
</P>
<P>
   For Virtue, it was a delayed debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of years ago, I was called up by St. Louis and I was
supposed to play in a game in Toronto,'' Virtue said. ``That's
where I was born. I took warmups and they told me I wasn't playing.
That was kind of a big letdown, so it was nice to get up here and
get a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Savage, Smith, and Virtue were all signed as free agents last
summer to add depth to the organization. Savage finished four years
at Michigan Tech last year, Smith had been in the minors with
Detroit, and Virtue spent the last couple of seasons in Worcester
with the St. Louis organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ended up taking a buyout,'' Virtue said. ``They kind of
basically told me they didn't have many plans for me. Larry Pleau
was coming in and he wanted to bring in his guys, and that's
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtue shopped around, talked with Providence coach Peter
Laviolette, against whom he had played and whom he had known for
some time, and signed with Boston Aug. 28.
</P>
<P>
   All three played key roles in helping Providence to a big first
half. Savage was second on the team in scoring and led AHL rookies
with 16 goals and 22 assists when he was called up. Smith (8 goals,
22 assists) and Virtue (4 goals, 21 assists) were 1-2 in team
scoring for defensemen.
</P>
<P>
   All three have now had a taste of the highest level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got an idea of what it's like up here, how I have to play,
work on my defensive game maybe,'' Smith said. ``Now it just makes
me more hungry to want to be up here.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtue, making what he hopes is his NHL breakthrough, takes
inspiration from the likes of Rob Murray, called back to the NHL
recently from Springfield after a long tour of duty in the minors.
The day before Virtue was called up, in fact, he read about
Murray's goal and assist, which earned him first star in his first
game up with Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at that and figured I still do have hope here,''
Virtue said with a laugh. ``Twenty-eight is older, but some teams,
that's what they're looking for, some older guys that can jump in
and play right away.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Virtue, Smith, and Savage zipped up their
black-and-gold Providence Bruins bags and zipped back down the
highway together.
</P>
<P>
   Savage spoke for all of them: ``It was great, a good experience
up to now. Hopefully, I'll get back up here soon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
