<HEADLINE>
COURT TO RESOLVE LOUISIANA CASE INVOLVING VOTING RIGHTS ACT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La.)  (mk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In time for the next round of post-census
redistricting, the Supreme Court agreed Friday to resolve a
long-running dispute over how the Voting Rights Act applies to new
district lines that, while not making matters worse for minority
voters, nonetheless fail for discriminatory reasons to make things
better.
</P>
<P>
   The case is a joint appeal by the Justice Department and by a
group of black voters in Bossier Parish in northwestern Louisiana.
The 12-member Bossier Parish school board, with members elected
from separate geographic districts, has never had a district with a
black majority and, as of the 1992 redistricting at issue in the
case, never had a black member. The population of the parish, or
county, is 20 percent black, with black residents concentrated in
two areas.
</P>
<P>
   In drawing new lines after the 1990 census, the school board
rejected a proposal from the local chapter of the NAACP that would
have created two majority-black districts. Instead, it adopted the
same lines that had already been drawn for the Police Jury, the
local governing body, which had 12 majority-white districts.
</P>
<P>
   After the Department of Justice refused in 1993 to approve the
new school board lines, the board appealed, under provisions of the
Voting Rights Act, to a special three-judge U.S. District Court
here. The court approved the redistricting, ruling that the absence
of intent to make the plan ``retrogressive'' _ to dilute black
votes to a greater extent than they already were _ was sufficient
to pass Voting Rights Act review.
</P>
<P>
   In their Supreme Court appeal, the Justice Department and the
black plaintiffs are arguing that even in a situation without
actual or attempted retrogression, the Voting Rights Act bars
approval of a plan that shows intent to entrench a status quo that
has limited black electoral power.
</P>
<P>
   ``A voting change must be denied preclearance if it was enacted
with a discriminatory purpose,'' the department's brief told the
court, ``even if that purpose was not necessarily retrogressive,
i.e. intended to make the position of minorities worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue in the case, Reno vs. Bossier Parish School Board, No.
98-405, is important in light of the coming round of redistricting,
in which actual retrogression is less likely than the more subtle
goal of entrenching an existing discriminatory system.
</P>
<P>
   The legal context for this dispute is Section 5 of the Voting
Rights Act, which applies to Southern states and parts of states
outside the South, including parts of New York and California. In
these ``covered jurisdictions,'' no change may be made in an
election practice without either the permission of the attorney
general, known as preclearance, or a declaration from the U.S.
District Court here that the change ``does not have the purpose and
will not have the effect of denying or abridging the right to vote
on account of race or color.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the meaning of the word ``purpose,'' which the
lengthy litigation in this case, including a 1997 Supreme Court
decision, has yet to clarify. The precise question is whether the
purpose that the law prohibits is one that is discriminatory but
non-retrogressive.
</P>
<P>
   The school board, asking the justices to dismiss the appeal,
said recent developments proved that there was no discriminatory
purpose behind the board's choice of district lines in 1992. Two
black candidates were elected to the school board in 1994, one from
a district that was only 26.7 percent black. Both were re-elected
to four-year terms last year in an election in which a third black
candidate was also successful in a district that is only 21 percent
black.
</P>
<P>
   By any measure, this was not a typical day at the court. Not
only was the chief justice, William Rehnquist, across the street
for the impeachment trial in the Senate chamber, but thousands of
anti-abortion demonstrators converged on the court in their annual
march to mark the anniversary of the court's decision in Roe vs.
Wade, issued 26 years ago Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Police barricades blocked the streets around the court, and the
building itself, with access limited to those who had business
there, was ringed by helmeted officers. Inside, however, aside from
the televisions turned on in some offices for the unusual sight of
the chief justice in another venue, there was no sign that anything
out of the ordinary was taking place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
