<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-REHNQUIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEF JUSTICE IS LENIENT ON SPEAKERS' TIME LIMITS
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The face was familiar, the voice was familiar, the
robe with the four gold stripes was familiar _ but could this
really be the chief justice of the United States allowing House
impeachment managers and White House defense lawyers to run way
past their allotted times in answering senators' questions?
</P>
<P>
   In his own domain across the street from the Capitol, Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist is the exacting keeper of the clock.
In this role, he is following tradition; Charles Evans Hughes,
chief justice in the 1930s, is said to have cut lawyers off in the
middle of the word ``the'' if that was when their time expired.
Rehnquist usually lets lawyers complete a word, if not an entire
sentence, once the red light comes on.
</P>
<P>
   His role as presiding officer of the Senate is decidedly more
deferential. At the beginning of the question phase of the
impeachment trial Friday, he announced a ``rebuttable presumption''
_ legal jargon for a rule with wiggle room _ that answers should be
no longer than five minutes. But there was no red light, and it
quickly became apparent that no one was really counting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
