<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SYMPHONY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYMPHONY HALL DECLARED A NATIONAL LANDMARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Friday Bruce Babbitt, Secretary of the Interior,
designated Symphony Hall a National Historic Landmark.
</P>
<P>
   The news surprised most music lovers, who have considered
Symphony Hall a national treasure all along. According to Boston
Symphony Orchestra managing director Mark Volpe, ``This is a nice
distinction _ we join a select list of only 2,000 other structures,
including Carnegie Hall and Jordan Hall. We feel this designation
confirms the place Symphony Hall holds in history. Also we hope it
will ultimately help access funds that we haven't been able to tap
into before. We've very happy about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Volpe, too, was surprised that Symphony Hall had not previously
been named a National Historic Landmark. John Marksbury, the BSO's
former director of development specializing in government, did the
paperwork for this project.
</P>
<P>
   Symphony Hall celebrates its centennial in the fall of 2000. Two
years ago the electrical systems were completely overhauled, and
this year work was undertaken in the public areas, chiefly the
renovation of the restrooms. Volpe says that the organization will
take 6-12 months to study what needs to be done to keep the hall
fully functional while doing nothing to adversely affect the
internationally celebrated acoustics.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe said, ``We have to look at all the functions, the
orchestra's use, the requirements of other users, staff issues,
artists' needs, public amenities, and merchandising. We want to
stop the process of encountering problems and then dealing with
them in an incremental kind of way; we want to understand the whole
picture of what needs to be done, and to learn from what other
orchestras have done with their historic halls, like Orchestra Hall
in Chicago and Severance Hall in Cleveland. Another factor we have
to consider is that Symphony Hall is one of the busiest facilities
in the country, with only 6-7 weeks of down time a year, so we will
have to work around that. It is not our intention to leave the
hall, the way the Cleveland Orchestra did so that the work could be
done in Severance. All of this means that the restorative work in
Symphony Hall will not be complete by the centennial, although we
will have made progress by then.''
</P>
<P>
   Volpe said the designation will not ``box in'' the BSO's plans
for the hall. ``The guidelines are well within what we can live
with.'' The advantage is that ``there are many funds set aside to
preserve our national historic landmarks,'' he said. ``This
designation helps us make our case that the government and private
donors should invest in Symphony Hall because it not only serves
the Boston Symphony Orchestra but also the entire community.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
