A4870 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-SOCIAL-GUIDES-     01-22 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-SOCIAL-GUIDES-ART-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING BY CONSCIENCE IS PAYING OFF THESE DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of Domini Social index is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 24)  
 (af)  
 By JOANNE LEGOMSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems to have become easier for a camel to slip through the
eye of a needle. That is the implication behind the proliferation
of a particular kind of investor: one who considers social values
as well as returns.
</P>
<P>
   Growth of assets in managed portfolios and mutual funds screened
for social issues of all kinds has snowballed. From mid-1995 to
mid-1997, such assets under management grew 227 percent, to $529
billion _ almost three times faster than all assets under
management, according to the latest data from the Social Investment
Forum, a trade group.
</P>
<P>
   These days, it isn't just ecological or tobacco issues that are
being factored into investment decisions, although such traditional
screens are still the most common. Investors are increasingly
screening for, say, drug companies that supply products used in
abortions, or a company's contributions to political action
committees.
</P>
<P>
   Current research suggests that at least some social screens, in
themselves, have no adverse effect on performance. Indeed, the
performance of the Domini Social Index of 400 companies has gone a
long way to mute skepticism. The index, which screens for dozens of
kinds of corporate behavior, from ownership of nuclear power plants
to good employee relations, returned an average 21.5 percent a year
from its inception in May 1990 through December 1998. The Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 index of large-capitalization stocks returned an
average of 19.4 percent a year in that period.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is convinced. A. Michael Lipper, chairman of Lipper
Inc., the Summit, N.J., research firm, thinks social investments
have just been lucky. ``The Domini index has done well because it's
underweighted in basic industries and energy, sectors with lower
social standing'' and, recently, lower returns, he said. ``And it
emphasizes technology and services,'' sectors that have led the
bull market, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the credible performance of the Domini benchmark is just
one factor that has brought more investors into the fold. Steve
Schueth, president of the Social Investment Forum, said much of the
increase stemmed from investor antipathy toward Big Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   But the trend has been aided by the mushrooming of options.
There are now 66 socially screened mutual funds tracked by
Morningstar Inc., the Chicago financial publisher, versus 12 in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   While such funds are often lumped together, many now use very
different criteria. Some bond funds that do not support military
spending will not hold United States Treasuries but instead hold
agency bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Others will not buy gambling stocks. And the Women's Equity
fund, with less than $10 million in assets, screens by the number
of senior-executive women at a company.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who buy individual stocks through brokerage firms have
the most flexibility in how they screen stocks. Lisa Leff, a
portfolio manager with Salomon Smith Barney Asset Management who
runs the social awareness investment program, says a broker at her
firm can create a customized, screened portfolio for an account
with $50,000 or more, and the fees are comparable to nonscreened
equity portfolios. Assets managed using these screens have risen
from $310 million in January 1996 to $1.4 billion now.
</P>
<P>
   Piper Jaffray, among others, recently set up a similar service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 1824EST &QL; 
