<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4882 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAPTISTS-TCU-TEX     01-22 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-TCU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU PROGRAM OFFERS AN ALTERNATIVE TO CONSERVATIVE BAPTIST
SEMINARIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Tony Morgan is not exactly a Southern
Baptist in exile.
</P>
<P>
   But the ministerial student left a highly conservative Southern
Baptist seminary to enroll in the Baptist Studies Program at Texas
Christian University's Brite Divinity School, which is affiliated
with the Christian Church (Disciples of Christ).
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted a place where I could study free from all the
political power playing'' between Baptist conservatives and
moderates, said Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, 29, is still a loyal Southern Baptist. But he felt out
of place studying for three semesters at Southern Baptist
Theological Seminary in Louisville, Ky., which in recent years has
seen a revolution from moderate to conservative control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I was told, `People like you don't belong here now
that we are in control,' '' said Morgan, who is a theological
moderate. He is one of 38 students in the Baptist Studies Program
at TCU this year. Almost all of the students are receiving
financial aid through the Christian Church (Disciples of Christ).
</P>
<P>
   The Baptist Studies Program, established in 1995, is a moderate
alternative to more conservative Southern Baptist seminary
training, said William Hendricks, a longtime Southern Baptist
educator who was called out of retirement to be director of the TCU
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strong point is that we are ecumenically oriented and we
are intentional about seeking to train women in the ordained
ministry,'' Hendricks said. About half of the Baptist students are
women.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Baptist conservative leaders in recent years have
enforced a strict conservatism on professors in the six Southern
Baptist-supported seminaries, including Southwestern in Fort Worth.
All support women in ministry, but some teach that it is unbiblical
for a woman to serve as a senior pastor.
</P>
<P>
   Growing prohibition of women in the ordained ministry by
Southern Baptist conservatives was one reason that Linda Ford chose
Brite for her doctoral program. She is one of 10 Ph.D. students in
a new program at Brite. Five of the Ph.D. students are Baptists.
</P>
<P>
   Ford also wanted to attend a non-Baptist school to broaden her
education, since she received a bachelor's at Southwestern Baptist
University in Bolivar, Mo., and a master's at Golden Gate Baptist
Theological Seminary in Mill Valley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was concerned that if I had a Southern Baptist Ph.D., I
might be limited to Southern Baptists seminaries to teach,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She also is worried that Southern Baptists in the conservative
camp may be moving toward a doctrine of prohibition of women in the
ordained ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been limited in my ministry so far. I've been
encouraged by Southern Baptists,'' she said. ``But I'm afraid that
the prohibitions may become more pronounced five or six years from
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Baptist Studies Program gets financial support from moderate
churches and organizations, including the Cooperative Baptist
Fellowship and the Alliance of Baptists. Participants study Baptist
history and theology and have firsthand interviews with many
Baptist leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan said it is beneficial for Brite students of other faiths
to realize that there are Baptists who are not so conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people when they hear the word `Baptist' these days,
think of people who targeted the Jews for evangelism, or those
people who said you should not go to Disney movies,'' he said.
``People need to know that there are Baptists who are not rigidly
fundamentalist.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan is president of the Baptist students group at Brite,
which is sponsoring church-state lectures Feb. 1-2. The principal
speaker will be James Dunn, director of the Baptist Joint Committee
on Public Affairs. Conservative Southern Baptists withdrew funding
from Dunn's organization, saying it took liberal stands on
political and social issues.
</P>
<P>
   Another Baptist touch will come during TCU's Ministers Week,
Feb. 8-11, when Molly Marshall will deliver the Scott Lectures.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall, the first woman to teach theology at a Southern
Baptist seminary, was forced out of her position at Southern
Baptist Theological Seminary when conservatives took over. Now she
is professor of theology and spiritual formation at Central Baptist
Theological Seminary in Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Other Baptists associated with Brite Divinity School include
Andrew Lester, professor of pastoral theology and pastoral care,
and Jeff Pool, director of Brite's annual fund and lecturer in
theology. Also, Darren J.N. Middleton, a Baptist, teaches in TCU's
religion department.
</P>
<P>
   Hendricks said TCU's Baptist program, with its small numbers of
students, is no threat to Baptist seminaries, such as the
3,000-student Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary in Fort
Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be complementary rather than competitive,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
