<SLUG> BC-KERRY-DEBT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KERRY SAYS CAMPAIGN DEBT MOSTLY PAID BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Senator John F. Kerry has nearly wiped out his campaign debts
from the 1996 election, according to papers that will be filed next
week with the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   By whittling down the debt, Kerry said he is in a position to
decide whether to engage in a presidential bid, as well as the
fund-raising that comes with a national campaign.
</P>
<P>
   According to the documents, Kerry raised $1.2 million from 4,400
donors for the second half of 1998, and a total of $2.9 million
during the last 18 months. During the past six months, he received
donations from more than 1,400 first-time contributors, said
William Elsbree, Kerry's campaign treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry said he expects to wipe out the remaining $480,000 debt
during the first quarter of 1999. He also said he would expand his
fund-raising operation, bringing in an additional person to work
with Peter Maroney, who used to raise money for former US
Representative Joseph P. Kennedy II.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel elated, relieved,'' Kerry said Friday. ``I feel as if
I'm back in control over that portion of my life again.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry said he has continued to hold meetings with friends and
advisers to discuss a presidential run. One concern, he said, is
whether his donors overlap with Vice President Al Gore and former
New Jersey Senator Bill Bradley, diminishing his ability to raise
enough money.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the analyses that has to be made,'' said Kerry,
eyeing a February decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 1835EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4888 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV24-NY     01-22 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL'S WAR OF ECONOMISTS PITS STUDENT AGAINST TEACHER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 24) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the last few weeks the Microsoft antitrust trial has heard
warring economists provide sweeping overviews of each side's case.
These two particular economists have a history.
</P>
<P>
   The government's witness, Franklin M. Fisher of the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, was the thesis adviser of
the chief Microsoft economics witness, Richard L. Schmalensee, also
of MIT. Perhaps that is why Schmalensee appears to take impish
delight in poking fun at his mentor.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher's case, he says, boils down to arguing that ``consumers
will be made better off if they are deprived, by court order, of
Web-browsing functionality that Microsoft wishes to provide at zero
marginal cost and that consumers are free to ignore or replace.''
Put that way, the government's case does sound vapid.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, counters Fisher. He traces the steps by which Microsoft
crossed the line between fierce competition and illegality.
Microsoft, he argues, has attempted to use its Windows monopoly to
seize control of the market for browsers. The threat is not merely
that Microsoft will wrest the browser market away from the current
leader, Netscape Communications. Worse, he says, Microsoft might
well use browser domination to eliminate potential competition in
operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   The latest browsers have the potential to replace the operating
system as the platform from which computers run word processors and
other application programs. With a browser like Netscape's that can
work with many operating systems, a user might soon be able to do
without Windows. Microsoft perceived the threat and, Fisher argues,
pounced.
</P>
<P>
   First, it bundled its browser into Windows without charge and
forced computer manufacturers to sign contracts that prohibited
them from substituting Netscape's browser for Microsoft's. These
contracts cut Netscape off from one large channel of distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Microsoft wrote contracts with Internet companies like
America Online, putting short cuts to their Web sites in a
prominent spot on Windows computers in exchange for the companies'
tilting their customers toward Microsoft's browser. These contracts
cut Netscape off from another distribution channel.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher's point is that, other than setting the browser's price
at zero, these contracts did not benefit consumers, though they did
hurt Netscape. He goes on to label the zero price ``predatory'' _
set to lose money in the short run just to drive a competitor out
of business. So what appears to be a wondrous gift to consumers is
in fact a manipulative ploy to protect Window's monopoly position.
</P>
<P>
   The antitrust laws permit Microsoft to prosper by selling
superior products. They do not allow a monopolist like Microsoft to
use tactics that serve only to impose costs on potential rivals.
With Microsoft behaving that way, it is impossible for
entrepreneurs who want to develop a rival product to find financial
backing.
</P>
<P>
   So by crushing competition, Microsoft crushes innovation _ a
dire threat to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a compelling argument, except for one inconvenient
fact. When asked during cross-examination whether Microsoft's
tactics had harmed consumers, Fisher said, ``On balance, I'd think
that the answer is no up to this point.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not, however, a devastating admission, since. under the
antitrust laws, the government doesn't have to prove that consumers
have been harmed, only that Microsoft's tactics pose a substantial
threat of harm.
</P>
<P>
   Schmalensee labels his former teacher's ruminations about
consumer harm ``sheer speculation.'' Microsoft keeps the price of
Windows low and steadily improves the product, he says, and its
contracts have not shut Netscape off from potential customers. In
fact, the number of users of Netscape's browser increased by about
20 million from early 1996 to last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Schmalensee stingingly accuses his teacher of elementary error.
Microsoft's zero price for the browser cannot be labeled predatory,
he argues, because even at a zero price, the browser makes money by
bolstering sales of Windows and other products.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Schmalensee's testimony falls flat in key places, too. He
breathlessly asserts that bundling the browser with Windows helps
consumers. But Fisher's complaint is less with the bundling than
with the no-substitution contracts and the fact that Microsoft made
the technical task of replacing its browser with Netscape's
needlessly difficult. Schmalensee says that Netscape enjoys ample
distribution channels, but Fisher's point is that Microsoft's
contracts deny Netscape the most lucrative ones.
</P>
<P>
   So who wins this battle of wits? Fisher has made a compelling
case that Microsoft's tactics are illegally anticompetitive.
Schmalensee has made the case that the threat of harm is
speculative. That may leave the court to rule cautiously in favor
of the government, but to tread even more cautiously when it
designs remedies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
