A4892 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-JOBS-BOS &LR;      01-22 0360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-JOBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
9,000 NEW JOBS CREATED IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts added 9,000 jobs in December and
continued a trend of declining unemployment rates every year since
1992, the state reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The state's jobless rate rose slightly last month, to 3.1
percent from 2.9 percent in November.
</P>
<P>
   But December's job gain was the biggest one-month increase since
last spring. Employers increased their payrolls in order to meet
the usual seasonal hiring demands for the holidays as well as an
unusually warm month that contributed to job gains in the
construction industry.
</P>
<P>
   For all of 1998, the state averaged a 3.3 percent unemployment
rate, the lowest annual rate since the economic boom of 1988. The
average annual rate has declined every year since peaking in 1991
at 9.1 percent, according to the monthly jobs report released
Friday by the Massachusetts Department of Employment and Training.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the nation's longest-running peacetime boom, Massachusetts
has fared even better than the nation as a whole. The state's
unemployment rate has been below the national rate for five
consecutive years. US unemployment was 4.3 percent in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Massachusetts economy is setting the pace for the
nation,'' Gov. Paul Cellucci said in a statement released with the
state's report.
</P>
<P>
   There were more people employed in December than in November,
though the number of unemployed also rose. Last month, 3,174,900
people were working.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 9,000 jobs added last month, nearly half _ 4,100 _ were
in the services sector, including business and engineering
services. These two groups accounted for more than half of the new
service jobs created over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   The construction industry added 1,700 jobs in December. The
manufacturing sector, which has lost export volume due to global
economic shocks, lost only 200 jobs last month as the pace of
decline slowed.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech, non-manufacturing companies added 900 jobs last
month, more than offsetting a slight loss of 300 tech manufacturing
jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 1838EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
