<HEADLINE>
AMA BACKS AWAY FROM REPORT IT WOULD REHIRE EDITOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Medical Association sought Friday to quash
speculation that the editor it fired last week ever will work for
the group again.
</P>
<P>
   While AMA officials have had discussions with Dr. George D.
Lundberg, the former editor of the Journal of the American Medical
Association, those did not involve any possibility of Lundberg
being rehired in any capacity, AMA officials said Friday. Others
familiar with the talks said on Thursday that some sort of future
relationship between Lundberg and the group is possible, and they
said that possibility led Lundberg to cancel an interview he'd
scheduled for Friday with the CBS news magazine ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``George is not coming back to the AMA,'' Emerson Moran, the
AMA's interim vice president for communications, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't characterize the discussions because those have been
between counsels for both sides,'' Moran added. ``Any report that
Dr. Lundberg will become an employee of the AMA is inaccurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Lundberg, who was in Cambridge, Mass. Friday for a conference at
Harvard's Kennedy School of Government, could not be reached for
comment. Neither could his lawyer, who on Thursday confirmed that
there had been discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Moran said Friday that he could not say what the discussions did
involve, but he could say that the AMA was not wavering in its
resolve to separate itself from Lundberg, who had edited the
highly-esteemed JAMA for 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   Lundberg's firing centered around the publication in this week's
JAMA of an article in which a majority of students at an unnamed
Midwestern college agreed with President Clinton's controversial
contention that oral-genital contact does not constitute ``having
sex.'' The article came out just after Clinton's impeachment trial
began in the Senate. That timing, AMA Executive Vice President E.
Ratcliffe Anderson explained last week, suggested that Lundberg was
``inappropriately and inexcusably interjecting JAMA into a major
political debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said he had other complaints against Lundberg, but
declined to say what they were.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
