<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX VALUE POURS BACK INTO THE COMMUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the spring of 1967, and a troubled Tom Yawkey sat behind
his desk at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   His team had lost 90, 100, and 90 games the previous three
years. Red Sox attendance the prevous six years never reached 1
million, and in 1966, it dropped to a pathetic 652,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need a new ballpark,'' the Red Sox owner said. ``I'm losing
too much money. I'm not trying to make money, but I don't want to
lose any, either. I told (general manager Dick) O'Connell to put
everything we take in back into the ball club, but I can't keep on
going on like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, Yawkey forgot his troubles. The Red Sox had an
unforgettable season, vaulting from ninth place the year before to
win the American League pennant. Late in the season, when the Sox
were on the way to drawing 1.7 million to Fenway, Yawkey announced
that he didn't need a new ballpark anymore.
</P>
<P>
   But what I remember as much as anything else from that
conversation was Yawkey's lament about the politicians of that era.
After World War II, when most Americans got automobiles for the
first time and were making it their primary mode of transportation,
Yawkey asked the city of Boston to help him get some space for
parking. He suggested taking some of the land used for Victory
Gardens along the Fens. The city laughed at him. He got nothing.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if you look at the history of the Boston Red Sox, who
will be 100 years old in two years, neither the city nor the state
has ever done anything to help them out. The Sox built the park.
They pay taxes on the park. And they have surely generated billions
of dollars over the last century for the economy of this city and
state, getting nothing in return.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox soon will announce a plan for a new Fenway Park, and
already, opponents are lined up. Most troubling are the remarks of
Speaker of the House Tom Finneran, who says he will apply the same
``principles'' he used to drive the Patriots out of state. He has
painted himself into a corner with his actions against the Patriots
and now finds it hard to do something for the Red Sox, which he
should.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran has made it plain that he does not want to do anything
to help ``fat-ass'' millionaires get richer. Well, in the case of
the Red Sox, this does not apply. Tom Yawkey and his wife, Jean,
have left a legacy for Boston and the state that few can match,
though neither was a native of Massachusetts. When Tom died in
1976, he left $10 million in a charitable trust, with 5 percent to
be distributed each year to Boston and South Carolina charities.
Even before she died in 1992, Jean Yawkey left a $30 million
charitable trust that has been spinning out more than $2 million
annually, almost entirely for local charities.
</P>
<P>
   And this is what Tom Finneran should know, and understand, makes
the Red Sox stadium deal different. The estate of Jean Yawkey owns
55 percent of the team, plus the park. When the team is sold, 55
percent of the purchase price will go into her estate and then be
distributed to local charities.
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner reportedly has been offered $780 million to
sell the Yankees to Cablevision. Someday, most likely in the next
10 years, the Red Sox, by law, will have to be sold. The team
playing in a new Fenway Park would perhaps triple in value. Within
three years after moving out of old Municipal Stadium in Cleveland,
the Indians went from taking in $50 million (that's taking in, not
making) a year to $150 million a year in the new ballpark, Jacobs
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly, some 30 individuals or groups have written to the
Red Sox expressing intrerest in buying the team. When the team is
ready to be sold, there will be a bidding process. John Harrington,
who runs the team for the Yawkey Trust, has the fiduciary
responsibility, according to the wishes of Jean Yawkey's will, to
get the best possible price for the team and the park in order to
maximize the funding for the Yawkey Trust.
</P>
<P>
   Let's take a guess that five years from now, the Red Sox and a
new park sell for $600 million. Then 55 percent of the net profit,
let's say $300 million, would go into the Yawkey Trust, be combined
with the $30 million plus already there, and form a base of $330
million from which 5 percent will be donated annually to local
charities, in perpetuity. That will help a lot of local people who
are destitute at the Pine Street Inn, or sick kids under the
auspices of the Jimmy Fund, or any number of schools. And let us
not forget, the Jimmy Fund, of which we in New England are all so
proud, was built by the Red Sox _ Ted Williams, Carl Yastrzemski,
et. al. They have backboned the Dana Farber Institute, recognized
as one of the best cancer treatment centers in the world.
</P>
<P>
   There is a part of the Red Sox that transcends dollar values,
and the politicians who run this city and state should understand
that. For six months a year, the Sox give people in hospitals and
every small town and village across this part of New England
something to talk about and to look forward to watching or
listening to. They have been doing it for nearly a century. The
Yawkeys have had a continual impact, even in death, since 1932.
When they died, they left most of their money here to continue to
do good for other people. All that is worth something.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, if you are one of those people beefing about the
Red Sox and Dan Duquette, come up with the $600 million now and
you've got a deal. You won't have to wait . . . Saturday marks the
first time the Boston College women's basketball team has ever sold
out Conte Forum. The Eagles have sold more than 8,000 tickets for
the game against Connecticut, the nation's second-ranked team . . .
By the way, football coach Tom O'Brien and athletic director Gene
DeFilippo have big smiles these days because they believe that when
all the results are in Feb. 3, BC will have its best recruiting
class in years, probably the best in the Big East.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 people from South Boston toasted their national
champion midget hockey team of 25 years ago in Florian Hall in
Dorchester. South Boston has sent 10 teams to the national midget
championships over the years, but the 1973 team is the only one
that went all the way. The proceeds from thereunion will go toward
sending this year's team to the nationals . . . Who said this: ``I
just don't think it is right. This team has had great support over
the years. The team is loved in the region. The television ratings
are at the top of the league. To me, this does not fit the
guidelines we have in the league for moving.'' Bob Kraft when the
Cleveland Browns were preparing to move to Baltimore . . . How
would you like to be Pete Carroll and read that the Patriots are
thinking of bringing in Art Shell as offensive line coach? Shell,
now coaching the offensive line in Atlanta, reportedly wants out
whether the Falcons win the Super Bowl next week or not. Shell is a
head coaching candidate. If Carroll has another tough season and
gets fired, Shell would have to be given first consideration as the
next head coach if he were here. Carroll, knowing that, would be
looking over his shoulder all year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friends claim that Todd Rucci has been told he will be selected
by the Browns in the expansion draft Feb. 9 . . . Others claim that
Bill Belichick will bypass the chance to interview for head
coaching posts. He has already been guaranteed the job with the
Jets when Bill Parcells steps down as head coach . . . Antoine
Walker is the captain of the team and he is the last guy to show up
for Celtics practice. Teams should not give the title to any player
who does not act like a captain should . . . Chuck Knox is the only
coach to win three NFL division titles for three different teams
besides Parcells. Knox won with the Rams, Bills, and Seahawks
during his illustrious career.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
