</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POPE-0123-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POPE ARRIVES IN MEXICO TO CHART COURSE FOR 'THE CONTINENT OF
HOPE'
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Blessed by unusually blue, clear skies, Mexico
City welcomed Pope John Paul II on Friday for a celebrated five-day
visit that could help chart the future of the Catholic church
throughout the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the Americas ``the continent of hope,'' the frail
pontiff stepped off his Alitalia plane at the Mexico City airport
to shrieks of joy from a crowd of 4,000 Catholic schoolchildren,
Mexican Indians and others selected for the arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``May God see that this visit that I begin today encourages all
in the effort to announce Jesus Christ with renewed ardor as the
new millennium approaches,'' the 78-year-old pontiff said in
Italian-accented Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   He read his speech at the airport with shaking hands while he
was buffeted by a slight breeze that graced the normally smoggy
city.
</P>
<P>
   The pope is in Mexico, the second biggest Catholic nation in the
world, to celebrate the closure of a special conference of bishops
from the Americas designed to address challenges to the Catholic
church in this hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   Before he heads to St. Louis, Mo., for a 30-hour visit and
meeting with U.S. President Bill Clinton on Tuesday, the pope is
expected to speak on those challenges, which include human rights,
economic policies and poverty, the loss of faith and other
traditional religious doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   Stooped and moving slowly with a help of a cane, the pontiff was
welcomed to Mexico for the fourth time since 1979 by Mexican
President Ernesto Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   ``As in all the times you've visited us before, you are received
by a people that loves and admires you,'' Zedillo said. ``You
represent the eagerness for justice that should be in the heart of
all human beings and should be the daily task of all people and
countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo said Mexico is a country ``that suffers a lack of
material goods'' but enjoys ``immense spiritual richness'' and is
proud of its Catholicism, freedom of religion and its mixed ethnic
heritage.
</P>
<P>
   The president thanked the pope for choosing Mexico as the nation
to deliver ``a message of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope praised the ``rich sensibility'' of Mexico's Indian
people and recalled the Spanish missionaries who left their
cultural imprint on Mexico. He referred to Mexico's national
symbol, the dark-skinned Virgin of Guadalupe, as the ``little dark
one'' and said he would pray to her for ``the opening of a
fraternal and peaceful'' next century.
</P>
<P>
   As Mexicans waited for the pope's plane to touch down, thousands
of people flashed mirrors toward the sky, hoping that the Catholic
leader would see the reflections welcoming him.
</P>
<P>
   The devout lined the route the pontiff took to Mexico's historic
downtown plaza, where some of the first churches in the hemisphere
were erected by the Spanish and still stand. There the pope
received the keys to the city from Mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, and
later met with bishops from the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   Isabel Cuevas Benitez, 26, a Mexico City street vender, blended
her faith with business as she sold hats along the route.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the pope's visit brings peace to Mexico,'' she said.
``There is much violence and insecurity. I hope this calms the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernesto Ortega traveled with his family from the Mexican state
of Hidalgo -- northeast of Mexico City -- to see the pope, arriving
Friday at 9 a.m. (local time) to try to reserve space along the
route.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to see him. We know we can't get near enough to
ask him for something,'' he said. ``Mexico needs this visit just
like we need many other things. We hope he blesses us so we can
live in peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Also along the route was Serafina Ferrera, who had brought her
17-month-old baby Fabiola to Mexico City from the state of Hidalgo.
The baby suffers from a brain illness and Serafina was holding up a
banner that asked for the pope's blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to receive the pope's blessing because my baby had an
operation four months ago that didn't work,'' Serafina said. ``But
faith moves mountains and the pope is the person who is closest to
God.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, which the pope has said is ``always faithful,'' was the
first country the pontiff visited after he was elected pope in
1979. It was one of the first countries in the Americas converted
to Christianity nearly 500 years ago, and it remains more than 89
percent Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   But this time the pope comes to Mexico on a mission of
reconquest, seeking to shore up the Catholic church in the
Americas. About half the world's 1 billion Catholics live in the
Americas, but the church has been rapidly losing members to
Protestant faiths spread by missionaries in Latin America and to
secularism.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican views Mexico as a cornerstone of Catholicism in this
hemisphere despite an anti-clerical past. The Latin American
country is considered a bulwark against the spread of other
religions and the influence of a materialistic United States.
</P>
<P>
   The pope is expected to condemn abortion and reiterate
traditional Catholic views on the family while in Mexico, but he
may also urge more respect for the rights of the indigenous and the
poor.
</P>
<P>
   With the twilight of communism, so vigorously opposed by the
pope, the Catholic leader has issued surprisingly strong statements
against the excesses of capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday the pope celebrates mass in Mexico City's Our Lady
of Guadalupe Basilica, the second most-visited Catholic sanctuary
in the world after St. Peter's Basilica in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   The shrine commemorates Mexico's beloved national symbol, the
Virgin of Guadalupe, who is said to have appeared before an Aztec
Indian peasant in 1531.
</P>
<P>
   He will also appear at the Hermanos Rodriguez Racetrack in
Mexico City before hundreds of thousands of people on Sunday and at
the city's Aztec Stadium on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 1 million tickets for several events have been
distributed to Catholics throughout Mexico who want to see the
pope.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
