<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4906 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OCEANS23-COX     01-22 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCEANS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scientists put ailing oceans at top of public health worry list
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The massive amounts of poorly treated sewage,
farm wastes and other pollution dumped into the oceans each day are
coming back to haunt us.
</P>
<P>
   Shellfish poisoning cases are on the rise from coastal New
England to the Carolinas to the Gulf of Mexico. Leaking septic
tanks on the Florida coast are discharging viruses that cause
diarrhea, hepatitis and other infections. And nerve-damaging
pfiesteria bacteria are becoming increasingly common in the
estuaries of the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, reported Friday at the annual meeting of the
American Association for the Advancement of Science, suggest the
declining health of the world's oceans has become a pressing public
health concern.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's alarming. In some cases, we're seeing new diseases that
are new to science,'' said University of Georgia marine biologist
James Porter, one of 3,000 researchers attending the meeting. ``Our
level of ignorance of what's happening to the oceans is quite
frightening.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan Rose, a University of South Florida marine specialist, said
disease-causing viruses have shown up on the west coast of Florida
a mile offshore, according to studies done there. The viruses come
from leaking septic tanks. In addition to threatening swimmers, the
microbes can infect shrimp and shellfish.
</P>
<P>
   ''During the recent El Nino, human viruses were found to be
transported for up to a mile into approved shellfish harvesting
waters,'' Rose said. ''Forty percent of all shrimp examined in the
study yielded human viruses from contaminated waters.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose said communities along the coast and major lakes _
especially communities with large resort hotels and other
facilities that treat sewage in septic tanks _ likely will be
required within the next decade to install new technology to
prevent contamination. Such undertakings could be very expensive _
the estimated cost for the Florida Keys alone is $800 million.
</P>
<P>
   Biologist Donald Anderson of the Woods Hole Oceanographic
Institute said the United States also is experiencing a rapidly
escalating and ''very worrisome'' trend in the incidence of
problems from toxic algae in ocean waters, which some scientists
have linked to sewage and other contaminants. Those problems
include increases in:
</P>
<P>
   _ Paralytic shellfish poisoning in coastal New England and New
York, and neurotoxic shellfish poisoning along the coasts of the
Carolinas and the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ciguatera fish poisoning in virtually all of the sub-tropical
waters of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pfiesteria or pfiesteria-like organisms in the estuaries of
the Southeast and Chesapeake Bay. The organisms have been linked to
long-term nerve and brain disorders among fishermen and others
working in contaminated waters.
</P>
<P>
   ''Formerly only a few regions were affected by these harmful
algae blooms,'' Anderson said. ''Now, virtually every coastal state
is threatened, and in many cases, over large geographic areas and
by more than one harmful or toxic algae.''
</P>
<P>
   Porter said dying coral reefs in the Florida Keys are another
warning sign. ''The coral reefs are like canaries in the mineshaft,
an indicator of what's happening to the ocean,'' he said. Reefs
that have persisted for hundreds of years are suddenly dying from
diseases ''we've never seen,'' the UGA expert said, noting the
number of diseased reef sites in the Florida Keys has risen from 94
in 1996 to 131 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The new research findings highlighted the opening sessions of
the annual meeting of the AAAS, the world's largest federation of
scientists, researchers, science writers and educators from a
variety of disciplines.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
