<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4907 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USSATLANTA23-COX     01-22 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USSATLANTA23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Funeral' marks end of service for USS Atlanta attack sub
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORFOLK, Va. _ USS Atlanta, the last of five American war
vessels to bear the city's name, began a final, bittersweet journey
Friday in a fog-shrouded ceremony that removed the nuclear-powered
attack submarine from service.
</P>
<P>
   Constructed two decades ago at the height of the Cold War, the
sleek, lethal sub is enduring the maritime equivalent of being put
out to pasture. Although it served only 17 years, half its life
expectancy, the $473 million vessel is the latest victim of the
U.S. military downsizing now that the Soviet threat has diminished.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta's crew returned recently from the vessel's ninth
deployment, a six-month assignment in the Mediterranean Sea.
Dressed in dark uniforms and white caps, the sailors stood
respectfully during the decommissioning ceremony attended by 90
Georgians who flew to Norfolk from Atlanta on a Navy cargo plane.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony began with 19 cannon blasts, which made babies cry
and set the somber tone on Pier 11 of the Norfolk Naval Yard, home
of the U.S. Atlantic Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is sort of like going to a funeral rather than a birth,''
said Don Giles, 53, president of the Atlanta Metropolitian Council
of the Navy League of the United States, which organized the
Georgia delegation.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta History Center has requested several items from the
Atlanta. ``It is our hope that some of the artifacts from the
submarine will wind up in the Atlanta History collection,'' said
Myers Brown, associate curator of military history for the center.
</P>
<P>
   Among the items the center would like to have: a silver service
that had originally been purchased by the Atlanta Navy League, a
periscope, a bunk, uniforms and the alarm panel.
</P>
<P>
   The hour-long ceremony Friday resembled a funeral. Seated under
a big white tent on the pier, people wearing their Sunday best
talked in muffled voices as the U.S. Atlantic Fleet Band played
``God Bless America.''
</P>
<P>
   A dozen World War II veterans who served on diesel-powered subs
sat together, dressed in jackets of blue and gold. Big white
feathers sprouted from their hats, decorated by the dolphin
insignia of the U.S. Navy Submarine Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``This military had better open up its eyes and see what is
happening,'' said Al Keck, 70, among several veterans who
complained that the Navy's decommissioning program threatens U.S.
security.
</P>
<P>
   A Navy chaplain urged the Lord to ``bless her crew in these
final moments of her life.''
</P>
<P>
   The sub's commander, Maurice M. Montana, fought back tears when
he told the audience of several hundred about giving his three
young children a tour of the Atlanta. Its next voyage, scheduled
for Monday, will be a short one to the Norfolk Naval Shipyard,
where the year-long dismantling begins.
</P>
<P>
   A yellowish sun poked through the fog, casting a soft shine on
the sub's cold, black hull. An officer in white gloves escorted
Colleen Nunn, the wife of former U.S. Sen. Sam Nunn, down the
gangway to the top of the narrow vessel where dignataries sat on a
platform draped in red, white and blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your baby grew up, met her challenge and was a winner,'' the
Atlanta's original commander, Robin White, told Nunn, who was
cradling a bouquet of red roses. ``It is hard to realize that she
will no longer cruise the sea, a strong and frisky lady.''
</P>
<P>
   When ships are commissioned, the sailors run aboard in a
patriotic ceremony with a band playing ``Anchors Away.'' On Friday,
the tune accompanied the final act by the sub's crew, the removal
of the long, narrow commissioning pennant from atop the vessel.
</P>
<P>
   Nunn and her husband, then a junior senator, attended the Aug.
16, 1980, launch of the Atlanta. As the ship's sponsor, Colleen
Nunn was responsible then for cracking a bottle of champagne on the
sub's hull.
</P>
<P>
   It took her two swings, she recalled Friday, because she closed
her eyes the first time to avoid the spray of alcohol. The next
swat launched the vessel which, after a year and a half of
outfitting, began cat-and-mouse patrols with the Soviets in the
Mediterranean and the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our response to the Soviet threat is the USS Atlanta, shark
hunter par excellence,'' Navy Secretary Edward Hidalgo told the
launch-day crowd in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Nunn had worried that the botched christening would
be a ``bad omen . . . We prayed that her awesome combat power would
never be used.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta was the first U.S. Atlantic Fleet sub to have the
capability to employ Tomahawk cruise missles.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, the Atlanta's crew is reluctant to discuss what action
they saw.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a few ``fanciful'' scenes, Hollywood thrillers ``The
Hunt for Red October'' and ``Crimson Tide'' depicted with
reasonable accuracy life aboard the cramped sub, Lt. Gregory Tolle
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bit of nostalgia,'' said Tolle, who like other crew
members will be redeployed to other subs. ``When the Atlanta is
gone, we will not have the opportunity to come back and see how
things are going.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
