<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4909 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-BOREDOM-AZR &LR;      01-22 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-BOREDOM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPED COUNSELS VS. MASKED MANAGERS  
 (ADV: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, JAN. 24) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Senate impeachment trial is a sad and disreputable
sight. That is why most of us Americans simply cannot watch the
damned thing. It is why we flip the channel to basic cable, since
that seems to be the only way to avoid it. Let me watch Animal
Planet or the Travel Channel. Please.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton's trial could have been made interesting and
relevant, but it isn't happening, as we are suffocating under the
avalanche of pontificating talking heads, each with its take on
events. A few heads would be fine, but television is becoming ``all
pundit all the time.'' We gasp for air.
</P>
<P>
   The American public is not so dumb, on the whole, that it cannot
grasp the moral and legal complexities. They are the complexities
we face daily in our real lives. We can come to a balancing of
conflicting views and sort out a workable compromise. If only we
were treated as adults.
</P>
<P>
   What would be interesting (begin ital) are (end ital) the fuzzy
edges:
</P>
<P>
   _It is true, as Republicans would have it, that the impeachment
is not just about sex. But, contrary to their complaints, it is not
merely about lying either.
</P>
<P>
   It is about lying about sex. You cannot shave off one part of
the equation without falsifying it.
</P>
<P>
   Americans seem to feel ambivalent about that. Yes, they want the
president to behave better; they are embarrassed by his tasteless
zipper-yanking. But they also know their own sex lives could not
stand the examining we give Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   _It is also true, as Republicans would have it, that the
president is relying on legalese and hair-splitting when he makes
his defense.
</P>
<P>
   But then again, Republicans are doing their own hair-splitting
and, as most of them are lawyers, they should know better than to
bad-mouth their own bread and butter. Hair-splitting is what law is
all about. If it weren't, we wouldn't need lawyers to negotiate the
law.
</P>
<P>
   _It is true, as Democrats would have it, that the alleged lying
would almost never be prosecuted in a civil case. It is also true,
as Republicans have it, that such cases have, indeed, been tried
and won.
</P>
<P>
   _There are those who have said that the Senate cannot censure
the president for his behavior, that censure is not in the
Constitution. Well, there's a lot that isn't in the Constitution,
and furthermore, one president has already been censured in the
past. Andrew Jackson suffered that.
</P>
<P>
   Time and time again, one side plays loose with the truth and the
other side counters with its own wobble and wiggle. Each side wants
to simplify the complex case, turning it into a slam dunk for its
interests. But then, the interesting ambiguities and complexities
are nudged out in favor of sound bites.
</P>
<P>
   Each side has an unattractive intolerance for the other's point
of view.
</P>
<P>
   It seems as if the people who make the decisions in television
believe we can only be interested in it as a prizefight _ or more
accurately, professional wrestling, with clearly drawn rooting
interest: one side righteous, the other the very devil. Choose your
team colors.
</P>
<P>
   We are no longer citizens, but sports fans. In this corner, with
leather masks, the tag team of Bill Bennett and Pat Buchanan; in
the other corner, wearing capes, is Lanny Davis and Michael
Kinsley.
</P>
<P>
   They will debate to the death.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the death involved is the one we die of boredom.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, neither side is interested in the complexity of
truth; each side wants to score points and win big. That is the
nature of partisan politics; it is a constant struggle to achieve
and hold power for ``our side.''
</P>
<P>
   They are ingenuous who say otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   There is a core of Clinton haters on one side, and nothing he
does will please them. He could make every policy decision they
have advocated _ and come to think of it, he has _ and they'd only
complain that he has no principles.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a smaller core of Clinton supporters, who believe
the man can do no wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, after all, has oodles of personality. Republicans, who
basically have nothing but issues to run on, must envy him. One
supporter I know, when the scandal began, responded with a
heartfelt, ``Let my Elvis go!''
</P>
<P>
   But in the issue of impeachment and removal, most of us look for
some ray of light, and there is none, only constant droning of
partisan flacks.
</P>
<P>
   And for us, the whole process from beginning to end, has been
embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   A pox on both your houses. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
