<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITHSONIAN-RETIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITHSONIAN INSTITUTE'S CHIEF WILL RETIRE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif.)  (bl) 
By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ I. Michael Heyman, a legal scholar and university
administrator who has led the Smithsonian Institution since 1994
through a period of growth and arguments over academic freedom,
will retire, officials of the institution said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Heyman's retirement as secretary of the Smithsonian, to be
announced formally at Monday's meeting of its board of regents,
opens one of the nation's most coveted cultural positions. A search
is likely to attract candidates from science, education and the
arts.
</P>
<P>
   It is a chore that the regents are not often called up to
perform. Since the Smithsonian was founded in 1846 with a bequest
from James Smithson, a Briton who had never seen the United States,
Heyman, 68, was its 10th secretary. The Smithsonian is the world's
largest museum complex, with 16 museums and galleries, mostly in
Washington, and the National Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Heyman has had good relations with the board of regents, which
asked him to stay beyond the five years he said he had agreed to
serve as secretary.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement that he is scheduled to release Monday, he
states, ``After considerable thought, however, I have now informed
the regents that I will step down as secretary at the end of
1999.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that he looked forward to returning to California in
2000, when he will turn 70, ``and re-establishing my ties with the
University of California and the San Francisco Bay area.'' Heyman's
wife, Therese Thau Heyman, is on leave as senior curator at the
Oakland Museum in California.
</P>
<P>
   Heyman was traveling Friday and his staff said he was
unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   One Smithsonian museum director, Milo Beech, who leads two Asian
galleries, the Freer and the Sackler, praised Heyman for his manner
of making the institution a welcoming place. ``He has been
extraordinarily deft in terms of building up a public constituency
for the Smithsonian,'' he said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Beech said the matter that attracted the most notoriety during
Heyman's tenure, the dispute at the Smithsonian's Air and Space
Museum over an exhibition of the airplane that dropped the first
atomic bomb on Japan in 1945, was begun before Heyman became
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Many veterans groups and political leaders had complained that
the text for the exhibition of the airplane, the Enola Gay, was too
sympathetic to the Japanese. The pressure that these complaints
created led the Air and Space Museum to alter the text and forced
the director of the museum, Martin Harwit, to resign.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute had a long-term effect when the Republicans took
control of the House of Representatives and Speaker Newt Gingrich
appointed one of Harwit's critics, Rep. Sam Johnson, R-Texas, as a
regent.
</P>
<P>
   When another dispute over an exhibition came up, however, Heyman
supported his curators over Johnson's objections.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition was a show on sweatshops at the National Museum
of American History. Johnson protested at a regents meeting that it
was faulty because it focused on the negative aspects of the
apparel industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons Newt appointed me was to keep the
historical revisionism under control,'' Johnson said at the time.
In resisting Johnson's attempts to have the exhibition modified,
Heyman said, ``I have a great deal of respect for Sam Johnson, but
I disagree with him on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, ``Between a Rock and a Hard Place: A Dialogue on
American Sweatshops, 1820 to Present,'' went on largely unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   The Smithsonian's budget this year is $570 million, of which
$407 was provided by Congress. Alan Fern, another director, said:
``government appropriations have not kept up with the rising costs
of salaries, repairs and programs. He has worked to remedy that and
has not been completely successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The regents will select Heyman's successor.
</P>
<P>
   In his academic life, Heyman was a professor of law and city and
regional planning at the University of California at Berkeley as
well as visiting professor of law at Yale and Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   He was named vice chancellor at Berkeley in 1974 and served as
chancellor from 1980 to 1990, when he resumed his joint
professorships there. He was counselor to Interior Secretary Bruce
Babbitt in 1993-94 when he became the Smithsonian's secretary. He
received his bachelor's degree from Dartmouth College and his law
degree from Yale Law School, and was the chief law clerk to U.S.
Chief Justice Earl Warren in 1958-59.
</P>
<P>
   Fern of the Smithsonian noted that Heyman's tenure was
groundbreaking: ``He was the first nonscientific secretary we've
ever had.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
