<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4914 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-TEARDROP-GOLF-ART     01-22 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-TEARDROP-GOLF-ART-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS RIVALS FLAIL, TEARDROP GOLF YELLS FORE AND MAKES MORE DEALS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Calif., Fla.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 Graphic of chrono of deals by Rudy Stucker is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 24)  
 (af)  
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is the depth of an industrywide slump the best time to go on an
acquisition spree?
</P>
<P>
   Teardrop Golf thinks so. The club maker, which is known mainly
for its Teardrop putter, has been busily rolling up small golf
businesses while bigger competitors like Callaway Golf and Adams
Golf have been bleeding money.
</P>
<P>
   In its two years as a public company, Teardrop has acquired two
well-known but ailing manufacturers, Tommy Armour Golf and RAM
Golf, as well as a golf tour for aspiring PGA Tour players that now
bears the Teardrop name. And it is still on the prowl.
</P>
<P>
   It lost out to Golfsmith International in the bidding for the
assets of Lynx Golf, a bankrupt Canadian company, when the price
topped $9 million. But in the process, Teardrop picked up Lynx's
endorsement contract with Fred Couples, the marquee player who is
now Teardrop's top spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Companies usually do not buy in slumps, in part because
acquisition binges are hard to finance in tough times. Teardrop
remains a small company, with estimated 1998 sales of $65 million.
Its market capitalization of $27 million isn't big enough to be on
the radar of major Wall Street analysts or institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   Teardrop is expected to post a modest net income of $2.2 million
for 1998 after a loss in 1997, and its margins suffered lately as
it slashed prices on some models to clear away backlogged
inventory. As a result, Teardrop's ability to finance acquisitions
from its own resources is limited.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is paying with common stock, the currency of choice in
technology deals, so easy for Teardrop. Its stock price is stuck in
a sand trap, closing on Friday at $5.25, far off its peak of
$14.0625 a share last May, and the market has been unkind to both
small-caps and golf stocks for months. Teardrop has included stock
in several deals but has yet to make an all-stock acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves borrowing, and Teardrop has loaded up on debt. At
the end of the third quarter of 1998, it carried $21.265 million of
debt on its balance sheet, equivalent to 34 percent of current
assets and more than 127 percent of shareholders' equity _ a level
of leverage that leaves Teardrop vulnerable if things do not go as
smoothly as planned.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the cash demands don't end when the ink is dry on an
acquisition. Teardrop is also spending heavily on advertising and
marketing to ``reinvigorate the companies and recreate the ambiance
that these companies are here to stay,'' said Rudy A. Slucker,
chief executive of Teardrop, which has corporate headquarters in
Morton Grove, Ill., and executive offices in Union, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Slucker says Teardrop's stock has been depressed by ``the
Callaway syndrome,'' referring to the problems of Callaway Golf,
the behemoth of the $2.5 billion golf industry. As industrywide
club sales slid 10 percent to 20 percent last year, Callaway
dismissed its chief executive, laid off 700 employees _ a quarter
of its work force _ and closed several noncore ventures. Investors
reacted by bidding down most golf stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But Teardrop thinks it can sidestep Callaway's problems. In
1999, ``we'll either lose a little or make a little,'' Slucker
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if the industry has a terrible year, we believe we'll
have a fair year,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are not so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's debatable whether they will escape the inventory bubble
in the industry,'' said Shawn Milne, an analyst at Hambrecht &AMP;
Quist in San Francisco. Milne expects golf club sales to grow about
5 percent in 1999 from a weak 1998 and sees a risk of swollen
inventory if an expected flood of new products does not entice
golfers to buy more.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Burnson, an analyst at ABN Amro, said that in a climate of
price-cutting, golfers who favor premium brands are unlikely to
switch to Teardrop's lines.
</P>
<P>
   Specialty retailers say the company's products are not flying
out the door. For instance, sales of Teardrop putters and Armour
clubs have been mediocre at the Edwin Watts Golf Shops chain, a
retailer based in Fort Walton Beach, Fla., with 46 stores, mainly
in the the South, said Edwin Watts, a co-owner of the chain;
delivery delays for Armour clubs have not helped.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Slucker is optimistic about the prospects for his
company, even in Asia, where Teardrop expects to begin selling this
year despite the region's economic troubles. The reason? The
roll-up strategy is beginning to bear fruit, by giving Teardrop a
range of brands that can pursue complementary market strategies.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Slucker has repositioned RAM as a low-priced line
to sell in sporting goods chains, discounters and warehouse clubs,
where competition is less fierce than in specialty shops. ``They
can effectively address the mass market and the green-grass market
without cannibalizing themselves,'' said Gar Jackson, executive
vice president at Par Valu, a newsletter in Carlsbad, Calif., that
tracks golf stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But in a business littered with high-flying small companies
flattened by industry selloffs, even Slucker is hedging his bets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there may be an opportunity in 1999 for a company
that's aggressive and smart and growing,'' he said. ``I'll put my
hat in the ring for that one. I'm not saying we can do it, but
we'll try.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
