A4915 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-400(2TAKES)-     01-22 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-400(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICARE SAFETY-NET PROGRAMS UNDERENROLLED, STUDIES SAY
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ark., Ohio, Mass.) (bl) 
By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Many of the poorest among the nation's 39 million
Medicare beneficiaries, those with incomes below $10,000 a year,
are going without aid from government safety-net programs that are
intended to help them pay their health-care expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest, most generous of the programs covers doctor and
hospital care that Medicare does not cover _ typically 20 percent
to 30 percent of the elderly's health-care expenses. Known as the
Qualified Medicare Beneficiary program, it also exempts its
enrollees from paying Medicare's $45.50 monthly premium for
doctors' office visits, which is deducted from Social Security
checks. Two other programs exempt Medicare beneficiaries with
slightly higher incomes from paying the premium.
</P>
<P>
   But studies by Families USA, a consumer advocacy group, as well
as the Urban Institute and research philanthropies like the Kaiser
Family Foundation and the Commonwealth Fund, estimate that 3 or 4
million people, about 40 percent of those who are eligible, have
never enrolled in the biggest safety-net program. Somewhat higher
proportions have not joined the other programs, the groups report.
</P>
<P>
   The studies, the gist of which the Clinton administration does
not dispute, attribute the low enrollments to conflicts between
federal and state agencies that share the cost and administration
of the aid to these factors: a dearth of program leadership and
coordination, labyrinthine red tape and demeaning application
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think we have a generous safety net for health
care,'' said Marilyn Moon, a health-policy economist at the Urban
Institute and a public trustee of the Medicare trust fund. In
reality, she said, the shortfall in enrollment ``is kind of a
secret that people don't want to talk about very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the aid has been available for a decade, but until a
study last year by Families USA, little was known of the shortfall.
``We were all surprised by the low levels,'' of enrollment, said
Nancy-Ann Min DeParle, head of the Health Care Financing
Administration, which manages the Medicare, the program for the
elderly and disabled, and Medicaid, the insurance program for the
poor.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is concerned, Ms. DeParle said, ``and we have a campaign
this year to raise awareness of it.'' Congress, she noted, has
given the Social Security Administration a $6 million grant to test
ways of expanding the programs' coverage.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For the poor, the issue has become urgent, said William
executive director of the American Public Human Services
Association, formerly the American Public Welfare Association, with
Medicare looking for ways to cut costs. A bipartisan national
commission is grappling with overhauling Medicare to prevent
insolvency soon after the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent proposals before the commission ask beneficiaries to
bear more of their medical costs, which would further strain the
poor. In such a case, Waldman said, more of the poor would do
without needed medical care or stand in line for charity care.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Congress has enacted four health-insurance safety nets
for Medicare recipients, with all of them based on the federal
poverty guideline. The programs limit enrollees' assets, excluding
a home, a car, some life insurance and a burial plot, to less than
$4,000 for individuals and $6,000 for couples. Applicants must
apply for the coverage to state agencies that supervise welfare
services.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest of the programs, enacted 11 years ago, is called the
Qualified Medicare Beneficiary program. It is open to individual
recipients with incomes of less than $8,292 a year and couples with
less than $11,100 in income.
</P>
<P>
   People who qualify are exempted from paying Medicare's monthly
premium, the 20 percent share of the charges for doctors' office
visits and the initial $768 in charges for hospitalization that
Medicare requires of other recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals earning up to $9,900 annually and couples with
incomes up to $13,260, figures that are 20 percent above the
poverty guideline, can enroll in the Specified Low-Income Medicare
Beneficiaries program. This program picks up Medicare $45.50
monthly premium.
</P>
<P>
   Both programs require that the states pay 23 percent to 50
percent of their costs, which are calculated on formulas based on
the strength of the states' economies. The same formulas are used
to prescribe the states' share of the cost of Medicaid, with the
rest paid for by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Two newer programs, created by the Balanced Budget Agreement of
1997, both of which terminate in 2002, are paid entirely by the
federal government. But unlike the other programs, Congress limited
the financing, so that if demand for them was high, late applicants
would be turned away. The maximum spending is $1.5 billion over
five years.
</P>
<P>
   One, called Qualifying Individuals-1, raises the threshold for
exemption from the Medicare premium to 135 percent of the poverty
line, or $11,112 for an individual and $14,892 for couples and
could aid about 500,000 Medicare recipients. Although enrollment
began a year ago, Ms. Moon said only 16,000 people had signed up.
</P>
<P>
   The second program, Qualifying Individuals-2, subsidizes the
Medicare premium of individual beneficiaries with incomes up to 175
percent of poverty, or $14,328. This plan was the fruit of
political horse trading, and advocates of the poor point out that
it is laughably stingy. Last year it offered enrollees a $1.07
reduction in their $45.50 monthly premium, rising to $2.23 this
year. Enrollment is close to nil.
</P>
<P>
   The first two programs are stirring the most controversy because
of their requirement that the states share the cost of Medicare
benefits, previously covered entirely by the federal government,
while at the same time giving them little flexibility in managing
the benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The states have no control,'' said Bruce Bullen,
Massachusetts' commissioner for medical services and chairman of
the National Association of State Medicaid Directors. ``They must
follow these Medicare, cookie-cutter approaches to providing
services to seniors.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps as a result, said Ms. DeParle of the federal financing
agency, ``the states, shall we say, have been less aggressive in
going out and enrolling people.''
</P>
<P>
   Waldman of the human services association said, ``There's a
little bit of distrust.''
</P>
<P>
   Struck by the reports of the shortfall in the programs'
enrollments, many states say they are redoubling their efforts to
find low-income people eligible for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be unfair to allege that Ohio has done anything to
hide from these folks,'' said Barbara Coulter Edwards, Ohio's
Medicaid director. But she said, ``We are asking, `Are there some
things we could do to encourage a higher rate of participation?'''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Hanley, Arkansas' director of medical services, said the
state had enrolled 17,875 beneficiaries in the programs, 40 percent
to 45 percent of the eligible. ``We've done what we could
reasonably do,'' he said. For the programs to reach more people,
Hanley said Congress must help with more money and better
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, there is no federally organized method for seeking
out Medicare recipients who would be eligible for the two main
programs. New retirees, however, can learn of the programs when
they apply at the local Social Security office for their Medicare
card, although critics say the programs are not actively promoted.
</P>
<P>
   But to enroll in the programs, Medicare recipients are directed
to their local state welfare office, where they must fill out
applications listing their incomes and assets and submit supporting
documents. Many eligible Medicare beneficiaries refuse to apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real stigma attached'' to visiting welfare offices,
said Tricia Smith, chief federal lobbyist for the American
Association of Retired Persons. ``No one has clear responsibility
for outreach.''
</P>
<P>
   Families USA executive director Ronald Pollack explained part of
the shortfall this way: ``Social Security says, `We don't run these
programs. They're run by'' the Health Care Financing
Administration. ``HCFA says, `We have oversight, but they're
administered by the states.'''
</P>
<P>
   To streamline the process and get around the welfare stigma,
Denise Cross, Missouri's director of family services, said her
state, like some others, is encouraging application by mail and
phone.
</P>
<P>
   And Congress has granted the Social Security Administration $6
million to test new approaches, like assigning state welfare aides
to Social Security offices to take and screen program applications.
</P>
<P>
   But given the magnitude of the shortfall, critics call that
tokenism. ``I think it would take a substantial effort to get more
people signed up,'' Ms. Moon of the Urban Institute said. ``I doubt
that $6 million is going to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
