<SLUG> BC-BORDER-WOES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORDER COUNTIES SEEK MORE FEDERAL AID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ A coalition of 24 counties along the
U.S.-Mexican border on Friday decried the lack of federal money for
everything from jail cells to clean water, and leaders hope their
message will be heard in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we haven't screamed loud enough,'' said Ronald Morriss,
a supervisor from Santa Cruz County, Ariz. ``We're talking some
serious money and some serious problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Filthy air, stinking water and the impact of illegal immigration
on health care, county jails and courts topped concerns here during
a two-day gathering of the U.S.-Mexico Border Counties Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The aim is to get the attention of members of Congress so they
will approve more funds for an area stretching from the Gulf of
Mexico to the Pacific Ocean that has historically been neglected,
said the chairman of the coalition, Carlos Aguilar III.
</P>
<P>
   The thinking of the 6-month-old coalition is that by bringing
together four states, 24 counties and 13 congressional districts,
the region's problems have a shot at being solved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a disproportionate share of those problems because
we're on the border,'' said Aguilar, who is a county commissioner
in El Paso, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   His message to Washington lawmakers: ``You need to start
addressing the fastest-growing region in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The coalition's plan is to re-energize the House Border Caucus
and establish a similar group in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the coalition seeks better counting in the 2000 census,
saying the region is underfunded because population figures come up
short of the number of people living along the border.
</P>
<P>
   Other tools include improving a dialogue with counterparts in
Mexico and publishing an annual report documenting how the border
influences the economy and health care, roads and other
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Officials pointed to former Texas Comptroller John Sharp's
report in July that showed that if the Texas border region were the
nation's 51st state, it would be the poorest and least-educated,
have the highest rate of unemployment and have serious problems
with education and medical services.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 12 million people live along both sides of the
border, 6.2 million of them in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Undocumented immigrants need care in hospitals, and people
arrested by federal agents often cost counties a hefty price for
detention and prosecution, Aguilar said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that border communities are unfairly penalized for
environmental problems arising from sharing air and water supplies
with Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Mercurio Martinez, the judge of Webb County, Texas, applauded
the push for unified front to get Washington's attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes good sense for elected officials from border counties
to come together and focus on common issues, problems and work out
solutions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Bonilla, a Republican whose Texas district includes
border communities, commended the coalition for trying to unify the
region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do they need more? Absolutely. They need tons more,'' Bonilla
said. ``I commend them for trying to do something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference, which concludes Saturday, was slated to cover
issues such as water quality, telecommunications and the challenges
of tracking financial costs of illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelly, the U.S. Attorney for the District of New Mexico and
a former county commissioner, has said border communities deserve
more federal funds to offset the impact of record number of drug
and immigration arrests made by federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   As U.S. Border Patrol agents continue to steer narcotics and
immigrant smugglers from more heavily populated areas, smaller,
rural counties will continue to feel pressure, Kelly said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
