<SLUG> BC-COP-SHRINKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`COP DOCS' HELP OFFICERS COPE WITH JOB STRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARSHA GINSBURG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In these trying days of police work, San
Francisco officers have people to help them cope with a range of
emotions _ anger, fear, frustration and sadness _ they may
encounter on the job.
</P>
<P>
   The call themselves cop docs. More formally they are the
Behavioral Science unit of the city police.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with doctorates in psychology, Lt. Alan Benner and Sgt.
Forrest Fulton guide a peer program of 200 fellow police personnel
and 20 therapists to help officers get back on an even emotional
keel, especially after handling shootings and loss of life.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, one of the city's top officers died in a car crash on
his way home. Investigators suspect he fell asleep at the wheel
after a long day on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be doing a lot of work on that one,'' Fulton said.
</P>
<P>
   Using phrases like ``healing process'' and ``peer support,''
Fulton and Benner say with their program, they have come up with a
model for helping officers cope with one of society's most
stressful jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Studies point to how dangerous and stressful police work can be:
</P>
<P>
   _ While serious crime declined 7 percent nationwide in 1997, the
number of police officers killed on duty rose 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two academic studies in the Southwest over the last decade
suggested that 40 percent of police officers had used violence
against a spouse or child.
</P>
<P>
   _ Other studies show the suicide rate three to four times higher
among police officers than the general population.
</P>
<P>
   Add all that to an increasingly dangerous and sophisticated
world of police work and involved paperwork and there is the
potential for a host of problems.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the stress in police work, Fulton said, stems from what
he calls the F-word _ ``feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   The police are so often required to be in control, in charge and
self-sufficient that asking for help ``is a deficit,'' said Fulton,
a 26-year-veteran of the police department. Historically, officers
have tried to rise above the pressure, but what frequently resulted
was police officers who were marginalized in their careers or dead
at an early age from alcoholism, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to repress fear, anger and anxiety. You can't show
it visibly in front of people. You do it for so long you lose
connection (to feelings), but it's pay now or pay later. You're
going to regain those feelings,'' Fulton said.
</P>
<P>
   The peer support program, which took 15 years to perfect and is
now a role model for other cities, formally began four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   If it all sounds warm and fuzzy, Fulton said, the help provided
by the program is incredibly important. If you are a cop, he said,
``this is the stuff your life depends on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 1905EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4926 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      01-22 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEN. BYRD ADDS TO MOMENTUM FOR ENDING SENATE IMPEACHMENT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND and JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The momentum for bringing President Bill Clinton's
impeachment trial to a speedy conclusion gained steam Friday when
Sen. Robert C. Byrd, a senior Democrat, called for a vote to
dismiss the charges and end the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, the leading parliamentary expert in the Senate who has
served in the chamber for 40 years, said he would move to dismiss
the case early next week _ not because he believes the president
did no wrong but because there aren't enough votes to convict him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lengthening this trial will only prolong and deepen the
divisive, bitter, and polarizing effect that this sorry affair has
visited upon our nation,'' Byrd said, adding that he doesn't
believe witnesses will add ``anything of consequence to this
process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced that the necessary two-thirds for conviction
are not there and that they are not likely to develop,'' the West
Virginia Democrat said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' 55-45 majority falls 12 votes shy of the 67
votes needed to convict Clinton and many Republicans conceded they
don't have the votes.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, reflecting the view of some
Republicans that the trial should continue, said: ``To suggest that
because there may not be a two-thirds vote at the end of the
process is not a justification for short-circuiting the
constitutional process.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. James M. Inhofe, R-Okla., agreed. ``I'm not one who wants
to get it over with sooner rather than later,'' said Inhofe.
``Cutting it short by a month or day really doesn't interest me.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's words captured attention on Capitol Hill because of his
stature and because he has been a leading Democratic critic of the
president, sternly rebuking him for his conduct in his affair with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky and the subsequent
cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry J. Hyde, R-Ill., chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee, who led the House prosecution team, urged the Senate to
defeat Byrd's motion to dismiss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, do I know what a great annoyance we are in the bosom of
this body,'' Hyde said. ``I think dismissing the articles of
impeachment before the trial is over is sending the wrong message
to the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., described Byrd's motion as ``a highly
significant move'' because it shows ``momentum toward a prompt
resolution... I believe there are some Republicans who are leaning
to dismiss or vote `no' on the articles of impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, many senators negotiated behind the scenes looking for
ways to end a trial that has been widely unpopular in public
opinion polls at a time when the president's popularity has
continued to rise.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., suggested holding
another bipartisan meeting in the Old Senate Chamber as a
brainstorming session.
</P>
<P>
   There also appeared to be a slow trickle of Republicans who are
turning away from the idea of calling witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah, said he ``would have to be
persuaded that there should be witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more apt to cast a vote, yes, the deposition should be
held, than I am to cast a vote the witnesses should be called. But
we'll wait and see,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, the vast majority of whom have argued against calling
witnesses and shortening the trial, appeared jubilant.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my judgment, this is already coming to a rapid
conclusion,'' said Sen. John F. Kerry, D-Mass. ``Most people feel
that prolonging it serves nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., said it's ``quite obvious there are not
67 votes for conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are some that are putting forth a brave face,
but I think it's obvious this is going nowhere'' Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   But even though the votes are not there to convict it is unclear
whether a motion to dismiss would prevail. Six Republicans would
have to join all of the Democrats in order to stop the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, predicted that Byrd's motion will
fail. The Senate Judiciary Chairman said he favors at least
allowing witnesses to testify in private. He also said may offer a
plan that will allow the Senate to avoid a vote on the articles of
impeachment if its clear the 67 votes to convict are not there. The
Senate could vote to recognize the House vote to impeach as the
highest form of censure against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde wrote Senate leaders Friday saying the House prosecutors
would like to take part in questioning Clinton in the Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the president is the only individual with knowledge of
almost every material fact relevant to the trial, the House
believes that his testimony could greatly help to expeditiously and
fairly bring this matter to a close,'' Hyde wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, senators questioned the White House lawyers and the
House prosecutors about the case against Clinton. But the dozens of
questions did little to resolve the conflicts between the
prosecutors and the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The questions were submitted in writing to Chief Justice William
Rehnquist who then read them aloud.
</P>
<P>
   White House counsel Charles Ruff maintained that even if the
Senate believes Clinton committed perjury and obstruction of
justice, it is not enough to remove him from office. However, Ruff
admitted similar charges lodged against a judge could warrant
removal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you ask the same questions about the trauma a nation
suffers when you are removing a judge and you are removing a
president,'' Ruff said. ``The answer must be `no.'''
</P>
<P>
   He argued that presidential wrongdoing must be ``so violative of
his public responsibilities that our system cannot abide his
continuing in office'' to meet the constitutional standard for
removal.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., countered that Clinton engaged in
``a conscious and deliberate and settled choice to violate the laws
of the land'' in conflict with his presidential duty to ensure that
the nation's ``laws be faithfully executed.''
</P>
<P>
   Canady and other House managers renewed their call for witnesses
in response to questions from senators about the need to hear from
key players such as Monica Lewinsky, presidential secretary Betty
Currie and Clinton friend Vernon Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House definitely holds to its position that we should call
witnesses,'' said Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff said the House ``violated'' its constitutional duty by not
calling witnesses when the issue was before its chamber and
irresponsibly punted the witness issue to the Senate. Clinton's
private attorney, David Kendall, warned that it could take ``many
months'' to prepare to take written testimony from witnesses and
possibly have them appear on the Senate floor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
