<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-VOTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES TO LOOK AT LOUISIANA VOTING RIGHTS CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Friday agreed to decide
whether a school board violated the Voting Rights Act when it
intentionally left in place a federally approved election program
that discriminates against black voters after rejecting a
non-discriminatory alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, which successfully pressed the court
to hear the case, argued that the Louisiana board ran afoul of the
law by deliberately retaining a system of voting districts that
keeps minorities in a disproportionately weak political position.
The Bossier Parish School Board, which had urged the justices to
let a lower court decision stand, countered that the intention of
board members is relevant under the Voting Rights Act only if they
change an approved election system and the alteration decreases the
voting strength of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The justices are expected to render their decision in Reno vs.
Bossier Parish School Board by July.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Voting Rights Act, school boards found to have
discriminated against minorities must get the approval of the
Justice Department or a federal court before changing their voting
districts. The justices have yet to decide whether a board violates
the law when it intentionally refuses to change an approved system
of districts despite evidence that the minority vote has become
diluted due to population change and that non-discriminatory
districts can be drawn.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision to consider the administration's appeal
marks the second time the justices have considered the legality of
the Louisiana board's 1992 decision to leave in place a voting
system the federal government had already deemed _ or
``precleared'' _ as valid under the Voting Rights Act.
</P>
<P>
   In their first decision, the justices in 1997 ruled any change
in an election system is OK with the Voting Rights Act if the
alteration leaves minorities no worse off than they were under the
old, approved system. But the justices at the time left unanswered
whether the law is violated if board members had a discriminatory
intent in leaving the old system unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the school board in northwestern Louisiana retained the
school district's 12 majority-white voting areas. Board members
opted for the status quo despite the objection of the local chapter
of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People,
which argued that at least two of the jurisdictions could easily be
redrawn to be majority-minority.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel of the U.S. District Court in Washington
rejected the NAACP's challenge, ruling that the decision to retain
the 12 districts was valid under the Voting Rights Act. The law
prohibits school boards from making ``retrogressive'' changes,
which weaken minorities' voting strength, the judicial panel said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Voting Rights Act does not bar a school board, even if
its intent was to discriminate, from leaving a precleared election
system in place, the court ruled. The Clinton administration, which
supported the NAACP, appealed directly to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
