s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$A     01-22 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET INSIGHT: HOW STOCKS COULD WORK FOR SOCIAL SECURITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 24) 
(bl) 
By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's fun to talk about what to do with 15 years' worth of
projected surpluses in the federal budget, particularly when the
number in question is a tidy $4.4 trillion. That is what President
Clinton was doing last week when he lobbed his Social Security
proposals in front of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Such a discussion is much more enjoyable than contemplating how
much smaller those numbers might be if _ Heaven forbid _ the
economy fell into recession between now and 2015.
</P>
<P>
   Still, any number of important people inside the Beltway were
far from amused at Clinton's suggestion that part of the surplus he
wants to target for Social Security _ a sum of about $700 billion _
be invested in stocks and corporate bonds instead of Treasury
securities.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Diamond, an economist at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology and chairman of a panel of the nonpartisan National
Academy of Social Insurance that issued a report on the issue last
month, shared his thoughts on the topic last week via telephone
from Cambridge, England.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is the president's proposal something you can support?
</P>
<P>
   A. At the moment there are two fairly radical proposals about
Social Security: One would create individual accounts as a
substitute for defined benefits, and the other is to have the
Social Security trust fund invest part of its money in stocks and
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The trust fund proposal, which the president put forward, is the
less radical idea of the two. I favor it, and I thought the
president put it in absolutely the right context. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. But don't people like Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan have a
point when they say decisions about where to invest the money would
fall prey to political pressure? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The issue here is the design of an institution to do the
investing.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan is at the head of an institution that has a lot of
independence to handle monetary policy. Fed governors are appointed
to 14-year terms, but if the president or Congress don't like their
policies, they can't remove them.
</P>
<P>
   Congress could wipe out the Fed and change the rules. But to do
that would obviously be a massive political step.
</P>
<P>
   I believe we can create a separate institution with the same
features as the Fed.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan raises the fear that investment decisions and share
voting would be controlled in detail by the House and the Senate.
That, it seems to me, is not a likely outcome. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Aside from creating an independent institution, what else
would you do to try and depoliticize the investing process? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I would add two other features. First, restrict stock
investments to broad index funds, ones that cover a wide swath of
the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the actual investments themselves would be done by
private managers, who would commingle funds for Social Security
with those from private investors.
</P>
<P>
   There is very little point in considering anything but index
funds, which are going to do about as well as other funds and make
more sense from an economic point of view. And if you move away
from them, politics starts to enter into the equation.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. There are all sorts of index funds. What kinds would you
favor? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't think one should consider an index fund any narrower
than the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500. One could actually mix a little
bit, from the S.&AMP; P. out to the Russell 3000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why are you indisposed to the idea of individual accounts? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There are four reasons why I think using individual accounts
as a substitute for Social Security is a nonstarter.
</P>
<P>
   First, high administrative costs, which eat into returns. Risk
is Point No. 2. With a defined benefit program, ups and downs get
smoothed out. For individuals, market moves are much more
pronounced.
</P>
<P>
   The third point, one that has been raised by people like Arthur
Levitt, chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, is that
a system of individual accounts would require a massive education
effort, which is expensive. And the potential for fraud in that
sort of a system is massive. Point 4 is that over time people are
going to be living longer. Individual accounts cut benefits. When
you hit the retirement age, you look at what you can tap. The
longer you live, the less you get out of any fixed sum. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You have been studying the issues surrounding Social Security
for a quarter of a century. Have other countries decided to invest
public retirement money in stocks? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Canada has started to implement a diversified portfolio,
which I think is a good idea. The Norwegians invest some of their
oil revenues abroad through the central bank. But most European
countries have much worse problems with their systems than we do.
They are not running budget surpluses, so they are not raising the
issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
