<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0338 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4933 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NY     01-22 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST TELLS MILOSEVIC THREAT OF FORCE REMAINS REAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Western powers warned the Yugoslav
president, Slobodan Milosevic, on Friday that simply allowing the
head of the international monitoring mission to remain in Kosovo is
not enough to avoid the threat of NATO air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The six-nation Contact Group on the former Yugoslavia met in
London Friday and urged a new effort at a political solution for
this southern Serbian province where violence between Serbian
forces and the ethnic Albanian majority continues in violation of a
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The final solution will have to be political, but in order to
achieve it, a military threat may be needed,'' the NATO
secretary-general, Javier Solana, said. The cease-fire reached in
October did not provide for the political status of the ethnic
Albanians of Kosovo, who are seeking independence.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's supreme commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, underlined the
threat of force by urging Milosevic to ``comply and do it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has ``made a half-compromise'' by freezing a
deportation order and allowing William Walker, head of the
international monitoring group in Kosovo, to remain in the country,
Clark said. ``But he is still defying the will of the international
community on other issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, he said, Milosevic's forces ``are still
deploying in the field in violation of U.N. Security Council
resolution 1199 and the commitments he made to NATO, and so the
crisis continues.''
</P>
<P>
   On a cold and foggy day in Kosovo, low-level clashes continued
to keep tensions high. Serbian officials said five Serbs between
the ages of 60 and 70 had been kidnapped during the night from a
village called Nevoljane, near Vucitrn, by masked men wearing the
insignia of the Kosovo Liberation Army, the ethnic Albanian
guerrilla force known as the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the rebel group denied they were responsible,
calling the event a provocation by the Serbs. Walker, at a news
conference here Friday with Knut Vollebaek, chairman of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, said that if
the rebels were behind the action ``we would be very critical of
them.'' The organization runs the program of unarmed monitors
directed by Walker, the American delegate to the OSCE.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian forces continued Friday to move against suspected
concentrations of guerrillas. Officials of the U.N. high
commissioner for refugees said that some 5,500 ethnic Albanians
have fled Serbian offensives near the villages of Shipolje,
Vaganica and Prica in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Vollebaek, supported by Washington, Moscow and NATO's threat of
force, succeeded in winning an indefinite freeze on Walker's
deportation. His expulsion was ordered after Serbian officials said
they were outraged by his immediate and explicit condemnation of
Serbian forces in the killing Jan. 15 of 45 ethnic Albanians in the
village of Racak, the event that has prompted the current
confrontation with the West.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Walker repeated that he stands by his words, although
he noted that there were circumstances he was unaware of at the
time. He said: ``I'll continue to call them as I see them,''
adding: ``It took me last night and this morning to come to terms
with the fact that I am now a frozen persona non grata.''
</P>
<P>
   But Western diplomats said the Walker issue was a smokescreen
for the real problem, the Serbian refusal to comply with the
October agreement. The Serbs, saying they were responding to
provocations by the rebels, have moved in more specialized police
and deployed army units and tanks in excess of the limits agreed
upon in October.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The diplomats said the Racak killings crossed a moral threshold
that the West could not tolerate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walker was a way for Milosevic to get the spotlight off Racak,
so he could muddy that issue,'' one diplomat here said. Milosevic
continues to deny that Serbs had any role in the Racak killings and
maintains that the guerrillas gathered the bodies, changed their
clothes to make them look like civilians and mutilated them.
</P>
<P>
   Vollebaek, speaking Friday, implied that Milosevic was moving to
comply with another Western demand: to allow the chief prosecutor
of the international war crimes tribunal, Louise Arbour, to
investigate the killings here after she was turned away from the
Serbian border on Monday. He did not elaborate on the development.
</P>
<P>
   In Pristina, Vollebaek said that if Walker had been expelled,
the entire monitoring force _ currently about 750 people and
scheduled to grow to 2,000 _ would have been removed from Kosovo,
followed by other international humanitarian organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Without the monitors to restrain the combatants, he said, ``the
humanitarian catastrophe would be even worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington's efforts to negotiate a political deal for enhanced
autonomy for the ethnic Albanians of Kosovo, who represent more
than 90 percent of the province's population, have been very
difficult. Not only is Milosevic unwilling to restore significant
autonomy to Kosovo after having revoked it in 1989, but the ethnic
Albanians themselves have so far found it impossible to unify
around a common negotiating position.
</P>
<P>
   The West recognizes Yugoslavia's sovereignty over Kosovo and
rejects the widely held ethnic Albanian desire for independence. In
essence, the West's main complaint with Milosevic is the way his
forces behave in Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
