A4934 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-WITH-DAVIDSON-     01-22 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-WITH-DAVIDSON-ART-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH PHILLIP N. DAVIDSON: AMERICAN CENTURY VALUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mo., Ark.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of American Century Value is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 24)  
 (af)  
 By WILLIAM R. LONG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is a nice mid-cap value fund like this doing in an
aggressive growth family like American Century?
</P>
<P>
   American Century Value, managed by Phillip N. Davidson since its
inception, was started in 1993 in an effort to ``round out'' the
family of funds of the Kansas City, Mo., company, he said. ``They
had been incredibly successful, and just wanted to diversify their
offerings to their shareholders and in the 401(k) market,''
Davidson added.
</P>
<P>
   Sticking to his mandate, Davidson has followed a strict value
discipline that is sharply divergent from the more aggressive style
of American Century's better-known growth funds. Unfortunately, the
bull market has been far more generous to large-capitalization
growth stocks than to the mid-cap value category.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, American Century Value returned just 5.0 percent,
compared with 26.67 percent for the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index of
large-cap stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Davidson can take consolation in average three-year
annualized returns of 24.8 percent through Jan. 15, well above the
median 22.9 percent for the mid-cap value category. And he thinks
that funds like his will soon bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson, 43, his co-manager, R. Todd Vingers, and his three
senior analysts use computer screening to look at all American
stocks with market capitalizations above $1 billion. The screens
rank stock prices in relation to earnings, book value, dividend
yield, cash flow and debt-adjusted cash flow. (``The more debt a
company has, the more operating cash flow it has to have to be as
attractive,'' he said.)
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for consideration by the fund, he said, a company
must be in the cheapest one-third of the market on at least two of
the five screens. Generally, 250 or 300 stocks qualify, and most
are in the mid-cap category, which he defines as a market value of
$1 billion to $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you go through and start doing individual company
analysis,'' Davidson said. He looks for companies that are leaders
in their industries but that are temporarily out of favor because
of, say, a temporary dip in earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The fund, with total assets of $2.17 billion, usually holds 65
to 70 stocks, about 60 percent of them mid-caps. Generally, once a
stock's price rises to the point that it no longer meets two of the
five value criteria, Davidson sells.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point is J.C. Penney. Davidson bought the stock in the
spring of 1997 at about $45, then sold it last year as the price
approached $70. Penney climbed close to $80 last June before it
started dropping, the victim of weak sales.
</P>
<P>
   Penney ``didn't fall back into our own valuation screens until
the low $50s'' in the third quarter, Davidson said, when the fund
started buying it again. The shares closed Friday at $39.875. ``The
primary play here is that they have the traditional department
store _ it's basically no growth, but a nice cash cow _ and then
they got the Eckerd drugstores acquisition'' in 1997, which should
bolster company earnings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all stocks in Davidson's fund turn over as quickly as
Penney. Take the Mercantile Bancorp., which it has owned since 1994
and is now the fund's biggest holding, at 4.9 percent of the
portfolio. Mercantile is the dominant bank in the St. Louis market
and No. 2 in Kansas City. It has built up its market share with
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   When Davidson started buying the stock in 1994, at $20 a share,
``it was a cheap stock with a good retail deposit base,'' he said.
``And basically, what happened is all that stuff just got better
when they made these acquisitions.'' But the acquisitions slowed
earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   As Mercantile's shares slid below $40 last summer, pulling down
American Century Value's returns, Davidson bought more. The stock
closed Friday at $44.8125, still down from a high near $60 early
last year. The acquisition will ultimately benefit the bank, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another company whose acquisition shows promise, Davidson said,
is Tyson Foods, the poultry company based in Springdale, Ark. Since
completing the purchase of the rival Hudson Foods last January,
Tyson controls about 30 percent of the domestic chicken market, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson stock rose with the acquisition, then came down as
weakness in foreign economies undermined exports and higher grain
prices pushed up costs. Davidson said he started buying the stock
early in 1998 at $18 and $19 a share. The price fluctuated during
the year, and he increased his position during the summer's general
selloff. Tyson closed Friday at $20.50. Davidson expects it to rise
considerably more than the stock market this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
