<HEADLINE>
SALINAS CONVICTION SEEN AS BLOW AGAINST CORRUPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ There was no smoking gun, no confession and no
direct link between Raul Salinas de Gotari and the 1994 murder of
Jose Francisco Ruiz Massieu, his former brother-in-law and a top
political official.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the federal judge who on Thursday issued the verdict in this
country's ``trial of the century'' _ what became Mexico's version
of the O.J. Simpson trial _ said there was enough circumstantial
evidence to convict the brother of former President Carlos de
Gotari of ordering the assasination.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, while millions of Mexicans celebrated the arrival of
Pope John Paul II on a five-day visit, others were busy assessing
the political bomb that had fallen when, for the first time in this
country's corruption-riddled history, a judge sentenced a
president's relative to prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a parting of the waters in Mexico,'' Arnoldo Kraus, a
columnist for La Jornada, a left-leaning Mexico City daily, said.
``For years, this country has suffered a crisis in credibility in
politics and business. This isn't a complete antidote, but it helps
a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   In his decision, federal judge Ricardo Ojeda Bohorquez, who
ordered Salinas to serve the maximum 50-year sentence, conceded
that government prosecutors and investigators had made mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Their biggest errors, the judge said, was their failure to
produce solid evidence and their inability to establish a clear
motive for Salinas's actions in authorizing Ruiz's murder.
</P>
<P>
   That has left relatives and attorneys for Salinas, who maintains
his innocence, arguing that the decision may have been based more
on political rather than legal considerations. Even some ordinary
citizens found the ruling hard to understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a confusing decision because there was no proof to
justify this verdict,'' said one lawyer who requested anonymity.
``But what everyone knows was that (President Ernesto Zedillo) was
under heavy political pressure to win this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo, who succeeded Carlos Salinas in January 1995, has
staked much of his administration's reputation on eliminating
government corruption. Only a month after taking office, he shook
his own entrenched Institutional Ruling Party by ordering Raul
Salinas's arrrest.
</P>
<P>
   Friday administration officials, many of whom had expressed
anxiety that Salinas would be acquitted, sounded relieved that the
government's gamble had paid off _ for now. Salinas's lawyers have
said they will appeal the judge's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Ojeda based his ruling largely on connections that
prosecutors made between Salinas and Daniel Aguilar Trevino and
Fernando Rodriguez Gonzalez, two accomplices who, authorities
claim, identified the former government official as a participant.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also relied heavily on phone records showing that
Rodriguez and Manuel Munoz Rocha, a former congressman and alleged
accomplice who has since disappeared and is believed to be dead,
had called Salinas the day after Ruiz was gunned down on a Mexico
City sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   The four-year trial included testimony from a former Salinas
mistress, allegations of ties to deadly drug cartels and suspicions
about how much President Salinas, in self-imposed exile in Ireland
and Cuba, knew about the killing. The government tried to solidify
its case along the way by adding charges of tax evasion and money
laundering, but most of those charges were later dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Other charges of misuse of public funds and illegal enrichment
are still pending.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome of those lesser allegations, some anaylysts
said, Raul Salinas has already come to symbolize much of what
infects Mexico's political structure: corruption, secret plots and
the ability of powerful people to act with impunity with little
fear of ever being punished for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the brother of an ex-president who everyone thought
was an untouchable,'' Kraus said, adding that, in this case, a
guilty verdict ``is very different from what we're accustomed to in
Mexico.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
