<HEADER>
A4945 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-POPE-BOS &LR;      01-22 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE ARRIVES IN MEXICO AMID DECLINING CATHOLIC INFLUENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA AND RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Pope John Paul II arrived here Friday to a
thunderous welcome ready to do battle for the souls of the faithful
in a land where the Roman Catholic Church has been the dominant
faith since Cortes arrived in 1519 bearing the sword and the cross.
</P>
<P>
   At Benito Juarez Airport, the 78-year-old pope gingerly walked
down the stairway from his Alitalia jet and was met by President
Ernesto Zedillo, whose government has clashed with the church here.
Also greeting him were various members of the Catholic hierarchy,
including Boston Cardinal Bernard Law, and a mariachi band that
played the classic ``Cielito Lindo.''
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating issues the pontiff may raise, the Mexican president
raised several senstive topics, including the country's growing
democracy, respect for human rights and the plight of indigenous
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands of people, many cheering, some crying,
jammed the sidewalks of this sprawling city to catch a fleeting
glimpse of the pontiff as he passed by in a bus painted in the
Vatican's white and yellow colors.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the throngs of jubilant Mexicans greeting him, John
Paul and his church face difficult days in Latin America, where
Catholic hegemony is being seriously challenged for the first time
since Spanish missionaries came armed with the gospel.
</P>
<P>
   The church's claim on Mexico's soul has been steadily eroded by
the dramatic growth of evangelical Protestant denominations,
especially Pentecostal churches, who are finding willing converts
among Mexicans craving spiritual refuge from their daily travails.
</P>
<P>
   The pope did not touch on this controversial issue during brief
remarks on the windswept airport tarmac. Instead he spoke about a
rebirth of religious values, respect for human dignity and Mexico's
special place in the history of Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church wants to be closer to Christ and his word, to be a
better server of man and to be a source of unity and not division
among humanity,'' the pope said in a tremulous voice.
</P>
<P>
   Concern about the church's future in the Americas will be an
important theme of his six-day visit to Mexico and St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago when John Paul came to Mexico on his first trip
as leader of the world's 1 billion Roman Catholics, fewer than 1
million Mexicans were Protestants. Today, scholars estimate that
there are more than 7 million.
</P>
<P>
   About 8,000 to 10,000 Latin Americans convert to evangelical
Protestantism every day and by early in the next century as many as
one out of three Latin Americans may be Protestant, religious
scholars say.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing perhaps the Catholic church's best weapon in this
fierce religious struggle, the pope will pay homage Saturday to the
Virgin of Guadalupe, where a miraculous appearance by the virgin is
said to have occurred and paved the way for the spread of
Catholicism throughout Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   It is nearly impossible to overstate the symbolic and spiritual
importance of the Virgin of Guadalupe to Mexico, the patron saint
of Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Every December, on her feast day, hundreds of thousands of
followers march _ or crawl on their knees _ to the basilica in
Mexico City. Families often create small, candlelit shrines in
their homes in her honor.
</P>
<P>
   Her story has been passed down from generation to generation for
four centuries. In it, the dark-skinned, black-haired virgin is
said to have appeared to an Indian peasant, Juan Diego, on a
hillside known as Tepeyac in 1531 asking that a church be built on
that site.
</P>
<P>
   The virgin became a key figure in the church's conversion of
millions of Aztecs and other indigenous people. She has long been
called the Mother of Mexico, and her image is reproduced on
everything from gold jewelry to calendars.
</P>
<P>
   Tepeyac, now an area north of downtown Mexico City, is the home
of the basilica, which after St. Peter's in Rome is the most
frequently visited Catholic sanctuary in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But Mexico is no longer a Catholic fortress. Even some of those
who waited on the streets of the city for the pope to pass by
described the transformation of Mexico's religious landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know many Protestants and I can see thay they are very
passionate about their devotion,'' said Nora Chavez, 38, a dentist
and lifelong Catholic. ``Sometimes they even border on being
fanatics. But they study the Bible, they're well educated and they
know their beliefs very well. That's why everyday more people join
those churches while the Catholic church loses people.''
</P>
<P>
   The inroads Protestants have achieved in the region have created
tense relations with the Catholic church. In a 1992 speech John
Paul characterized evangelizing Protestants as ``hungry wolves''
preying upon the poor and the ill-educated.
</P>
<P>
   On a trip in which the 78-year-old pontiff is expected to
outline the church's future strategy for the Americas, John Paul
has called for a ``new evangelization,'' a campaign of spiritual
renewal among the many faithful who are Catholic in name only.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of Catholics who are baptized, married and
buried in the church and that is the only contact they'll ever have
with the church,'' said Brian Smith, a professor of religion at
Ripon College in Wisconsin and author of ``Religious Politics in
Latin America.''
</P>
<P>
   The success of Protestant churches in Latin America is also
mirrored in the United States, where Hispanics represent the
fastest growing segment of the US Catholic Church. But an estimated
60,000 Latinos convert to Protestantism every year in the United
States, most becoming Pentecostals.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul believes the church in Latin America has over the past
30 years lost its spiritual moorings and become too involved in
political and economic issues providing an opening to evangelical
churches with their heavy emphasis on the Holy Spirit and a
personal relationship with Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, battles over liberation theology _ the belief that the
gospel should be used as a weapon to challenge capitalist
exploitation and oppressive regimes _ tore apart the Catholic
church in the 1970s and 1980s and, some scholars say, distracted
church leaders from tending to their flocks.
</P>
<P>
   In the battle with Protestantism, the church is crippled by a
lack of foot soldiers. Because of the severe shortage of priests,
Sunday Mass can only be offered once a month in some rural areas of
Latin America. Many baptized Catholics have little knowledge in
their faithful.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, evangelical Protestant churches have mounted
aggressive campaigns to win members, setting up churches in
abandoned stores, warehouses and office buildings across this huge
metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was baptized a Catholic, but I decided to come here because
I feel a stronger connection to Jesus,'' said Rosario Morelos as
she cracked open her Bible at the start of a prayer service inside
the Interdenominational Christian Church, an evangelical Protestant
congregation housed in a non-descript office building in a working
class neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Catholic Masses at the church I used to go to did nothing
for me,'' added Morelos, 32, who is a factory worker. ``It was
spiritually dead. But here you feel the power of Jesus, of the
Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe researcher Lorena Zarate contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 1925EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4947 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-22 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STABLE NAACP LOOKS TO FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leonard Alkins has just begun his second term as president of
the Boston branch of the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   In many organizations that would not qualify as much of a
distinction. But for the long-troubled chapter of the nation's most
storied civil rights organization, it is symbolic of a restored
stability. As recently as 1994, the local branch was in
receivership, a certified problem child of the national
organization. Now, just a few years later, the local group boasts
an enlarged membership and a renewed sense of purpose.
</P>
<P>
   When he was first elected in 1995 to serve out the unexpired
term of Jack E. Robinson, Alkins was a surprise choice, a State
House veteran with little profile. Now 54, he has worked at the
State House for 34 years, the past 20 as clerk of the Joint
Committee on Rules.
</P>
<P>
   He inherited a chapter in chaos. Its finances were in disarray,
with a large assessment due to the national organization. Its
membership was an unsolved mystery because shoddy record keeping
had been the norm for years. Its building had been lost to
foreclosure. Worst of all, the chapter had virtually disappeared as
a force in local politics.
</P>
<P>
   Now local membership is up to about 700, and the NAACP is again
visible on local issues. Most of all, it has shed the stigma of
chronic disorganization that haunted it in the early 1990s, an ugly
period whose nadir was symbolized by the loss of the chapter's
headquarters building on Columbus Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Alkins points to the successful end of the chapter's lengthy
battle to integrate public housing in Boston as his proudest
accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   In the last couple of years, Alkins noted, the goal of the NAACP
lawsuit, the integration of long-segregated public housing, has
largely been achieved. ``I would say that's a major accomplishment,
seeing that case has been around for a zillion years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he enters his new two-year term at a time when, many
believe, the group is grasping for a direction. The NAACP played a
major role in pushing the city to file a US Supreme Court appeal of
a federal court decision to strike down Boston Latin School's
race-based admissions policy. But it has been frustrated in finding
a role in other local issues _ especially crime prevention and
affordable housing _ while other advocacy groups have been
successful in influencing City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   A frustrating case in point has been the NAACP's inability to
influence Mayor Thomas M. Menino's determination to end busing for
racial balance, a move the group opposes. Alkins insists that
busing has been a positive force for education, that to abandon it
would be to condemn black students to mediocre schools.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, their opposition hasn't created a ripple so far; Menino
has declined to meet with them, and often cites such advocates as
the Revs. Raymond A. Hammond and Eugene F. Rivers III as his
barometers for political sentiment in the black community.
</P>
<P>
   Menino insists that the NAACP is not representative of black
community thinking on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants a quality neighborhood school,'' Menino said
Friday. ``I have to prove to people that I will give them the same
quality neighborhood schools that people have in other
neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest challenge to the NAACP's future may be its
ability to attract younger members. The NAACP's long-standing image
as a bastion of middle-class moderation is part of the problem.
Hampering Alkins is the perception in some quarters that he is a
caretaker, not a forceful advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some members had hoped to draft outgoing state
Representative Charlotte Golar Richie to oppose Alkins this time
around, but were unable to persuade her to run against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a way to go in terms of attracting the
younger, more vibrant wing of community activists,'' said the Rev.
Alexander Hurt, a 29-year-old community activist. ``In his next
term, that's where he should set his sights.''
</P>
<P>
   Alkins, in fact, nearly stepped down last November after the
death of his father. But he said he endured the tragedy convinced
that work remained to be done, and that his father would have
wanted him to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that he would not have wanted me to step down from
doing something that he would be proud of me for doing,'' Alkins
said. ``He never quit, so I would never quit. Even if I choose not
to run next time around, if I step down it will be because I feel
there is a need for new blood.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Adrian Walker is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
