<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-HIPHOP-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIP-HOP'S TIP-TOP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending complete file)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Compared with rock 'n' roll, jazz, and salsa, hip-hop is a baby,
just a tad over 20 years old. But a look at the Billboard charts
makes it clear that hip-hop reigns. On any given week, it
dominates, with at least four albums in the Top 10. It's no longer
music of the underground.
</P>
<P>
   Rap was born in the South Bronx, where teenage boys picked up
microphones and started speaking along to records being mixed by a
DJ. It was raw, straight from the street. People called it hip-hop,
a culture that embraced the music, lingo, and fashion of the time.
Since then, hip-hop has grown, capturing the fascination of
suburban America.
</P>
<P>
   Many predict 1999 will be the year rap and hip-hop explode,
snatching the music industry's limelight, as it expands with more
artists, more producers, and more fans.
</P>
<P>
   You see, unlike other genres of music, the Hip-Hop Nation takes
care of its own, giving cameo appearances to burgeoning artists,
launching many rappers into stardom on their first album.
</P>
<P>
   As artists have caught on to where the real money is _ producing
and writing _ rappers are building their own empires, not allowing
out-of-touch record company producers to have creative control. So
funksters like Master P and Jermaine Dupri keep rolling out the
hits _ on their own labels _ creatively expanding the definition of
hip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   The list of successful hip-hoppers would fill pages, so we've
narrowed it down for you to just the most talked-about
contemporaries.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
JAY-Z His latest album, ``In My Lifetime, Vol. II . . . Hard Knock
Life,'' debuted at No. 1 on the Billboard albums chart several
months ago and it remains there for one reason: Jay-Z's flowing
lyrical style. He takes chances with his music. For example, the
title song from his latest album samples a chorus of high-pitched
girls taken from the Broadway musical ``Annie'' set to a thumping
bass line. He's known to lend rappers a hand, rewriting their stuff
to make it tighter. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MASTER P. Rapper and producer extraordinaire. An accomplished
rapper in his own right, he started his own label, No Limit
Records, and counts among his artists heavyweights Snoop Dogg, Mia
X, and his younger brothers Silkk the Shocker and C-Murder. In a
world where corporations are careful to diversify their holdings,
Master P's done the same, starting his own sportswear line and an
independent movie company. His movies are reminiscent of low-budget
flicks like ``Krush Groove,'' but, on videotape, he's making mad
cheddar (major money). &QL; 
 &QL; 
LAURYN HILL She's the queen of hip-hop trio the Fugees, a woman who
can rap and sing with equal finesse. A woman of soul and substance.
An artist who speaks with rare frankness about problems she sees in
the black community. The Fugees have temporarily disbanded so that
Hill, Wyclef Jean, and Pras Michel could do their own thing.
Wyclef's solo album stretched Caribbean-style hip-hop beyond its
dancehall rhythms, incorporating merengue beats and salsa riffs.
Pras's solo effort fell short but gave us one of the best singles
of '98, ``Ghetto Supastar.'' But Hill's solo debut, the ``The
Miseducation of Lauryn Hill'' is so vibrant and unique it didn't
surprise too many people when she was nominated for 10 Grammys. &QL; 
 &QL; 
FOXY BROWN She's the Madonna of rap. Indeed, Foxy manages to flash
even more flesh than the old Madonna, before she got spiritual. On
the mike, Foxy spits out fast-witted rhymes, most of which get
bleeped when played on the radio. To the uninitiated, Foxy is
superficial and slutty; to those who understand her game, Foxy's a
smart business woman who knows she can make crazy dollars by
self-blaxploitation. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NAS One of the best rappers in the biz, Nas has gotten a bit softer
over the years, easing up on street-beats for a more palatable
(read: commercial) sound, but his raps are still tight, exploring
social issues and creating dramatic fictional tales of mobster
life. A new album, ``I Am,'' is set for a February release. &QL; 
 &QL; 
DMX Last summer, he released his first solo album, ``It's Dark and
Hell Is Hot,'' and it tore up the charts. Now, he's got another one
out, ``Blood of My Blood. Flesh of My Flesh,'' and it's smoking.
He's a rapper with a scratchy voice, one that can bark like a
Rottweiler. He made headlines when he was arrested on rape charges
in New York, but when DNA testing cleared him, few papers reported
it. But the charge might have given him the kind of street
reputation that makes young people think a person is cool. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MA(dollar sign)E. Since being discovered by Sean ``Puffy'' Combs,
Ma(dollar sign)e has been his biggest star. Like most new artists,
he was known before he made his debut album, ``Harlem World,''
doing cameos for the late Notorious BIG. With his drawling voice
and sometimes romantic lines, he's become rap's biggest hearthrob.
But he's not relying just on rap, an industry with a revolving
door. Ma(dollar sign)e started his own talent company, named after
his first album. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BIG PUN People often take potshots at Pun (that's short for
Punisher), who tips the scales at more than 400 pounds. But make no
mistake, this Puerto Rican from the South Bronx has jazzed hip-hop
by layering salsa-style piano riffs on thumping beats. Unlike many
rappers who play down their Latino roots because they believe it
won't play well to white consumers, Pun spices his rhymes with
Spanish. Now, lots of other rappers are biting off him, flowing
with words like ``Mamacita'' (literally ``little mommy,'' a term of
endearment) and ``chula'' (a sweet, sexy girl). &QL; 
 &QL; 
PUFF DADDY He got his nickname from wearing puffy goose-down coats,
but now Sean Combs has a closet full of gear including his own
line, Sean John. He's one of tbe biggest names in hip-hop,
producing a string of sample-happy hits for the Lox, Lil' Kim,
Ma(dollar sign)e, and the late Biggie Smalls. Still, he can't help
but make a fool of himself by rapping alongside his proteges, which
only shows how weak a rapper he really is. Puff learned he can make
millions remaking songs that were hits in the '70s, long before
many of his fans were alive to hear them the first time around.
Hip-hop diehards despise him; industry leaders say he's helped
hip-hop become more pop. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MISSY ``MISDEMEANOR'' ELLIOTT For years, she stayed behind the
scenes, producing R&AMP;B hits for others. But in '97 she went solo,
proving that you don't have to be seductive like Foxy Brown or
philosophical like Lauryn Hill to make it as a female rapper. Like
Will Smith, she's devoid of any angst, which makes for
happy-go-lucky songs with pop appeal. &QL; 
 &QL; 
WU-TANG CLAN It's hard to keep up with the nine MCs who make up Wu.
With a love for martial arts, gold teeth, cosmology, and funky
rhythms, they've defined their own culture _ with their own line of
clothing, Wu-Wear, to boot. Among the members who spun out to do
their own thing are Method Man, Ghostface Killah, the RZA, Raekwon,
and Ol' Dirty Bastard. &QL; 
 &QL; 
KRS-ONE This old-school rapper has never traded in his political,
consciousness-raising raps for lyrics about flowing Cristal Rose
champagne and Bentleys. And it's a good thing, because there are
too few rappers talking about elevating the black and Latino
communities. His latest album, ``Maximum Strength,'' will be out
sometime this year. &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE BEASTIE BOYS Who would've thought that three white boys from
Manhattan would transform hip-hop? Their 1986 album, ``Licensed to
Ill'' _ a hybrid of punk and rap, with heavy doses of sophomoric
humor _ introduced a generation of white kids to hip-hop. From
there, these fans started flipping through tapes in the rap
category at music stores, discovering music with a more rebellious
edge. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MIA X The only female ``soldier'' signed to Master P's No Limit
Records, she goes off on promiscuous women and sleazy men alike.
But unlike Lauryn Hill, she comes across as insecure, changing her
point of view from one song to the next. That might have a lot to
do with the peeps she hangs with, among them, Snoop Dogg. &QL; 
 &QL; 
LL COOL J Like the Energizer bunny, he keeps going, outliving
Run-DMC, Doug E. Fresh, and a slew of other late-'80s rappers by
updating his style. He adopted his stage name in the early '80s,
years before his 1985 solo album, ``Radio,'' made him a household
name among hip-hop heads. Fourteen years later, married with
children, he still holds his own in the studio and onstage. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BUSTA RHYMES He raps faster than light-speed, making his body
tremble with every syllable. Onstage, his energy bubbling, it
almost seems like he's going to self-combust. He's a genuine
performer, giving all he can when he sings. So what if you can't
understand some of his verses? The choruses are catchy, inspired by
the dancehall and hip-soul grooves he raps to.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
