u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-NYT     01-22 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAWDRY TEDIUM OVERSHADOWED BY BYRD'S CALL TO DISMISS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It came sharp as a cry from the heart. Sen. Robert
Byrd, D-W.Va., issued a terse statement declaring he had heard
enough of the impeachment case against President Clinton midway
through another ping-pong-like revisitation by the Senate of the
trial's familiar details.
</P>
<P>
   ``End this sorry and sad time for our country,'' said Byrd in a
printed announcement, issued outside the Senate, that he would take
the lead next week in moving to dismiss the charges against
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the chamber, a great buzz of surprise swept the Capitol,
for the Byrd is one of the constitutional deans of the Senate and
the motion took on extra heft as he announced how thoroughly he was
surfeited with the scandal. The day's real debating point instantly
became the Byrd initiative, not the retelling of the tale of the
intern and the president.
</P>
<P>
   But inside the chamber, the senators could show no outward
notice of Byrd's readiness to attempt a quick way out of their
often droning servitude. The senators had to keep to the 19th
century trial ritual of sending up hand-written questions and
silently listening to the answers, thereby inviting fresh gloss on
the oft-told tale of the president and the intern.
</P>
<P>
   One cautionary answer from Clinton's team predicted ``many
months'' more of the trial if the Republican majority opts to
summon witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The questioning lent another layer of re-argument of well-known
points as each side took turns responding to largely unsurprising
softball queries lobbed up alternately by the president's partisans
and his foes. Lawyerly chipperness was clear as the contesting
counsels polished and demolished familiar positions.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the one-upmanship and skirmish points sporadically
scored in the re-debate, the exercise seemed to threaten the trial
with a lethal dose of Jarndyce vs. Jarndyce, with the circularity
of Dickens' interminable lawsuit in ``Bleak House.''
</P>
<P>
   As the fencing proceeded, the buzz from the Byrd initiative off
the floor grew to the point where Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, left
the trial to go out to the news media and insist the trial process
must go forward to completion, not be short-circuited in dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having 100 senators sit there hour after hour is burdensome,''
he conceded, looking weary as he headed back to heft that burden
once more.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Laughter eased the day at times, as when a needling question
came from Republicans about early scandal strategizing by Dick
Morris, the president's chronic eminence grise. The defense team
lawyers looked at one another in obvious hesitation. ``I couldn't
find any volunteers,'' said White House counsel Charles Ruff, who
finally fielded the question as if it were a penance for someone
else's sin.
</P>
<P>
   Gamesmanship laced the proceedings. Some questions could be seen
arriving from Senate aides watching elsewhere. More often,
individual senators suddenly became inspired or agitated enough to
jot down a fresh question and pass it on to their party leader.
Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, whose Supreme Court allots an
hour in total for most landmark oral argumentation, patiently
recited about 50 questions that revisited the gifts, the phone
calls and all the rest.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the outset of the day, the ultimate in barn-door closing
measures was announced, considering the grueling scandal year the
nation has endured by way of torrential leaks of supposedly secret
information. To protect the secret closed sessions of the trial,
staff members in attendance are being sworn to an iron-clad oath of
secrecy designed to strike dumb the likes of Linda Tripp and
cripple the kiss-and-tell publishing industry.
</P>
<P>
   The staffers who will attend the crucial closed-door court
sessions expected to begin next week must solemnly swear in writing
to ``never divulge, publish, or reveal by writing, word, conduct or
otherwise, for any purpose, at any time during or after my
employment or other association with the United States Senate, the
proceedings of any closed session of the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that allows wiggle or tattle room only time and perhaps
fresh braces of lawyers will tell. But the Senate is making the
attempt and, coincidentally, the chaplain's opening prayer Friday
was for Artesian wells for the lawmakers as their trial reserves
run dry.
</P>
<P>
   In the trial's most charming moment of relief, senators
restricted from speaking suddenly beamed and squirmed approvingly
at their desks like grade-school students informed that cookies and
milk were in the offing. Their bipartisan round of joy was offered
to Rehnquist at his decision to apply a five-minute rule on the
answers to the questions.
</P>
<P>
   As the day proceeded, however, the five-minute rule proved
loose. Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., appeared to be snoozing briefly
once more, which hardly seemed an excess under the hours of forced
passivity. Far greater excitement was growing outside the trial at
the news of Byrd's appetite to end it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
