<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-PUNISHMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT NOT INTENDED TO BE PUNISHMENT, SCHOLARS AGREE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Colin Diver, dean of the University of Pennsylvania
Law School, thinks some members of Congress need to reread the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   They keep talking, said Diver, about evicting President Clinton
from the Oval Office as the only appropriate punishment for the
crimes he allegedly committed: perjury and obstruction of justice.
And they glide over the fact that the president, when out of
office, remains vulnerable to criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them seem to want to teach him the lesson of the
century for his behavior by punishing him in this way,'' Diver
continued. ``But I really don't believe the impeachment process was
intended to be punishment in the sense that they mean and that we
ordinarily think about it legally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is, essentially, a personnel action, a means of removing
the CEO,'' he said. ``This is the system the founding fathers
created for firing the boss.''
</P>
<P>
   Many other legal scholars, political scientists, and historians
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   They stressed that the person being impeached does indeed suffer
the broad ``punishment'' of personal and historical humiliation,
and perhaps of losing his job _ a point former senator Dale Bumpers
also underscored during his closing arguments for the White House
defense team Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the analysts added that the impeachment process was devised
to protect the nation and its people from abuse by someone in
office, not to impose a legal penalty on the person charged with
committing the infractions.
</P>
<P>
   That is why, they explained, the Constitution explicitly permits
the criminal prosecution of an impeached official after he or she
leaves office. If the removal itself were a punishment for the
purported misdeeds, then any subsequent prosecution would be
prohibited because it would constitute double jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of impeachment is not to punish the individual;
that's what criminal law is for,'' said Alan Baron, who served as
special House counsel for the impeachments of two federal judges.
``It is to preserve the institutions of government from being
undermined or damaged in some fundamental way.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Mann, a presidential scholar at the Brookings
Institution, said that lawmakers who perceive impeachment as a way
to punish Clinton ``are not seeking the right means for doing so''
because ``that's not what the constitutional provision is for. It's
supposed to be a means for protecting the country from a leader who
poses a severe threat to it.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, all the Republicans calling for Clinton's removal
believe Clinton's misdeeds rise to the level of impeachable
offenses. Rep. Bill McCollum of Florida, for example, recently
predicted ``grave, damaging consequences for our system of
government'' if Clinton, like others who commit perjury, was not
subject to a ``severe punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   McCollum sought to bolster his point by explaining the severity
of punishments for convicted perjurors under the Federal Sentencing
Guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   But it is precisely such direct linkage between allegedly
wrongful conduct in office and legal sanctions that some historians
and legal observers deem off-the-mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's supposed to be a gap between crime and
impeachability,'' said Akhil Amar, a professor of constitutional
law at Yale University. ``I wouldn't say that impeachment isn't
penal at all, since you could lose your job and be shamed and so
forth. But there's another place that's all about punishment, and
that's the court system that can be used after removal.''
</P>
<P>
   Bumpers echoed those arguments during his much-praised
presentation two days ago. Asserting that Clinton had already
suffered embarrassment with his wife and daughter, among others,
the former senator from Arkansas added:
</P>
<P>
   ``These proceedings go right to the heart of our Constitution
where it deals with impeachment, the part that provides the gravest
punishment for just about anybody, the president, even though the
framers said we're putting this in to protect the public, not to
punish the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Gilbert, an expert on the presidency and impeachment at
Northeastern University, agreed that impeachment was intended ``to
safeguard the public, not to punish personal wrongdoing.'' Still,
he argued that the process was not meant only to be an
administrative action for firing a senior-level employee, but was
intended to have a punitive component, too.
</P>
<P>
   That is why, he and others said, the Constitution allows for
articles of impeachment to call for the president to be barred from
holding future office if convicted. President Andrew Johnson's
Republican accusers did not seek that sanction against him during
his impeachment trial in 1867, but the charges against Clinton do.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars said that during Johnson's trial, the word punishment
was hardly used by the House managers. Instead, they focused on how
his alleged offenses had undermined the workings of government and
on the need to remove him so that the rule of law could be
restored.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't about punishing him in the same way as the
Republicans now say they want to punish Clinton,'' said Michael Les
Benedict, a historian at Ohio State University and author of a book
about Johnson's impeachment trial. ``They talked about the effects
of his political wrongs, of his winking at treason, of subverting
the laws. . .so that there was a need to protect the nation and its
people, rather than punishment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
