<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  SHUSTER LOSES APPOINTMENT TO SELECT COMMITTEE ON INTELLIGENCE
</P>
<P>
   By Lisa Fine States News Service WASHINGTON, Jan. 22 -- It's
been a rocky road lately for Rep. Bud Shuster, chair of the
powerful transportation committee.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., denied Shuster's request
to be reappointed to a specially-selected committee that oversees
the nation's intelligence operations. Meanwhile, the House Ethics
Committee met for the first time and voted officially to reopen an
expanded investigation into Shuster.
</P>
<P>
   John Feehery, a Hastert spokesman, said the speaker made the
decision because Shuster, R-Everett, had served the maximum
allowable number of years on the committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just simply that he had served all the time allowed
under House rules,'' Feehery said. ``The investigation had
absolutely nothing whatsoever to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shuster's spokesman Scott Brenner said Shuster was disappointed
because he wanted to serve on the committee again, but understood
that ``rules are rules.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hastert's decision puts a roadblock up against Shuster's
chances of chairing the Select Committee on Intelligence in the
next Congress. At that point, he will have to step down as chair of
the transportation committee, having served the full term.
</P>
<P>
   He will need to have at least a one-year hiatus before becoming
eligible to chair the transportation committee again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gingrich had decided to grant Shuster a waiver, but Hastert
just didn't want to go against the rules,'' Brenner said. ``I think
he just wanted to give new people a chance to serve on the
committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Select Committee On Intelligence are not allowed
to serve for more than four of the last six Congresses. But former
House Speaker New Gingrich, R-Ga., waived the requirement for
Shuster.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster served on the committee from 1987 to 1993, and again
from 1995 to 1999, Brenner said. He worked on the Subcommittee on
Human Intelligence, Analysis and Counterintelligence, and the
subcommittee on Technical and Tactical Intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   The House Ethics Committee reopened its probe into Shuster's
relationship with his former chief of staff Ann Eppard, who became
a? AA
</P>
</TEXT>
