<HEADLINE>
FOOD-BORNE INFECTION HOSPITALIZES THREE IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ At least three people who have been hospitalized in
Massachusetts with a serious bacterial infection, including a
pregnant woman who miscarried, have been linked to a nationwide
outbreak involving contaminated hot dogs and cold cuts.
</P>
<P>
   An elderly man is now in a rehabilitation facility, while an
elderly woman has recovered, according to Dr. Alfred DeMaria,
director of the bureau of communicable disease control for the
state Department of Public Health. The third person was the woman
who miscarried, in her second trimester.
</P>
<P>
   While lab results have confirmed that these three people, all
from Middlesex County in eastern Massachusetts, were infected since
November with the same unusual strain of listeria in the
contaminated products, DeMaria stopped short of saying the meats
caused these cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is they're linked. One would presume it's a
result of the meat product. It's the same organism. But we don't
have a definite food product and can't say this is what they ate,''
DeMaria said. The woman who miscarried said she had not eaten any
hot dogs before becoming ill, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Four other Massachusetts cases, including three people who have
died since December, are still under investigation, and the lab
results identifying the listeria strain are not yet available.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths involved an elderly woman from Norfolk County, an
elderly man from Western Massachusetts, and an elderly man from the
central part of the state, according to DeMaria. The fourth person,
an elderly man from Norfolk County, has recovered.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the nationwide outbreak has involved at least 67 cases
in 13 states, including the death of 11 adults and three
miscarriages, according to the latest statistics from the US
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   The illnesses, dating as far back as August, have been linked to
an unusual strain of listeria that has contaminated certain hot
dogs and deli meats made under such brand names as Ball Park,
Hygrade, Sara Lee, and Mr. Turkey. On Dec. 22, the manufacturer,
Bil Mar Foods, voluntarily recalled specific lots of the products
that might be affected, with the code EST P261 or EST 6911 on the
outer edge of all packages.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, about 20 to 30 cases of listeriosis, as the bacterial
infection is called, are reported in Massachusetts each year, with
about 30 to 50 percent of them resulting in death, since those who
are most likely to get sick from the bacteria are people who have
weakened immune systems, according to DeMaria.
</P>
<P>
   Listeria can lead to meningitis, high fever, and a widespread
blood infection known as sepsis, DeMaria said.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce the risk of listeriosis, public health officials
recommend that people thoroughly cook raw meat, wash raw
vegetables, avoid unpasteurized milk, and thoroughly wash hands,
knives and cutting boards after each handling of uncooked foods.
People at risk, such as pregnant women and people with compromised
immune systems, should avoid soft cheeses like brie and thoroughly
cook leftovers and ready-to-eat foods like hot dogs.
</P>
<P>
   While packaged hot dogs are cooked, not raw, contamination
during processing could still lead to problems if they are not
thoroughly reheated until steaming hot, according to public health
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you cook everything well, there's no listeria problem,''
DeMaria said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
