u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALDOR-CLOSE-BOS &LR;      01-22 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALDOR-CLOSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALDOR THROWS IN THE TOWEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Caldor Corp., which grew from a mom-and-pop store in 1951 to a
region-wide retail institution, said Friday it plans to go out of
business, a move that would throw 20,000 employees out of work and
close all of its 145 stores.
</P>
<P>
   Operating discount department stores in nine Northeastern
states, including 22 stores in Massachusetts, Caldor said it
expects to conclude its going-out-of-business sale by mid May.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the 1990s, it has struggled in a crowded market
where there are far too many stores and not enough consumers to
keep them all prosperous.
</P>
<P>
   An abundance of stores hasn't stopped giant national discounters
from invading New England _ Target will soon join Wal-Mart and
Kmart in the Boston market. In the Darwinian world of retail, where
size matters and the weak often wither, national giants are
inexorably displacing homegrown small-fry. Such was fate of
Lechmere, another retailing mainstay that was forced to close its
doors in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   With so many choices available, the lower- and middle-income
consumers who once flocked to a Caldor now tend to go elsewhere
when they shop for bargains in family clothing and home
furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   Squeezed by behemoth outsiders and fighting to defend an
ever-narrowing niche, the beleagured Caldor has been operating
under bankruptcy protection since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month it stopped paying some vendors and it was
under increasing pressure from creditors to shut its doors.
</P>
<P>
   Its troubles in the '90s were a far cry from Caldor's heyday.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s and '70s, Caldor was ``a genuine New England
discount institution,'' said Kurt Barnard, president of Barnard's
Retail Trend Report.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, however, the institution decided to call it quits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is with great sadness and disappointment that we announce
the decision to close down Caldor's business,'' said Caldor
chairman and chief executive Warren D. Feldberg in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the nature of our capital structure and the shortfall of
our performance goals, the board (of directors) had no alternative
but to conclude that this was the most appropriate course of action
under these circumstances,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Norwalk, Conn., Caldor reports annual sales of nearly
$2.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's decision to go out of business follows Caldor's
unsuccessful attempts in bankruptcy court to win approval for a
business reorganization plan from its creditors, which are owed
about $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   Caldor's plan to liquidate its merchandise and sell its real
estate is subject to the approval of the bankruptcy court.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper accounts have identified Kohl's and Target as possible
buyers of some Caldor's prized real estate sites.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl's and Target are two Midwestern-based chains looking to
gain a foothold in the Northeast market.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Target's parent company declined to comment,
but a spokesman for Bradlees Inc., the Braintree, Mass. discount
chain also operating under bankruptcy protection, said it might
consider acquiring some of Caldor's sites and hiring some of its
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Caldor traces its origins to the early 1950s when Carl and
Dorothy Bennett opened a small camera-and-gift store in Port
Chester, N.Y. Deriving its name from its founders' first names, the
chain quickly put down roots in southern New England.
</P>
<P>
   For 30 years, the chain grew and prospered until the Bennetts
sold Caldor in 1981 to the first of several new owners.
</P>
<P>
   In those heady days, regional discount chains such as Caldor and
Bradlees flourished. But gradually giant national retailers began
to invade regional markets and steal away customers with better
bargains.
</P>
<P>
   With about $32 billion in annual sales, a big chain such as
Kmart Corp. can use its size to buy in volume and offer lower
prices to customers than small regional chains such as Caldor.
</P>
<P>
   And with more giants such as Wal-Mart and Target crowding into
the local market, it seemed Caldor's best days had passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of competition out there,'' said David Schmitt,
a senior vice president at Bradlees, a regional chain similar to
Caldor. ``And more and more, the competition is coming from the big
national players.''
</P>
<P>
   In the opinion of Kurt Barnard, president of Barnard's Retail
Trend Report, competitors narrowed Caldor's niche to the point
where it vanished. It wasn't just one rival, but a host of
competitors besieging Caldor from all sides, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Caldor lost its ability to give customers a clear-cut reason
to shop at its stores,'' he said. ``Everybody from Kmart to Ames
was taking business away from Caldor.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bennetts were ``wonderful'' merchants, he said, but
subsequent owners weren't so astute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each new management team added another nail to the coffin,''
Barnard said.
</P>
<P>
   Other regional discounters looked at mergers as a way to survive
competition from national giants.
</P>
<P>
   In November, for example, Ames Department Stores Inc. of Rocky
Hill, Conn., announced plans to acquire Hills Stores Co. of Canton,
Mass. as a way to increase its purchasing power.
</P>
<P>
   But though rumors periodically swirled that Caldor might employ
a similar strategy and possibly merge with Bradlees, no deal was
ever forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there were some signs in the spring that Caldor
could still turn things around.
</P>
<P>
   Losses narrowed and, in May, the retail finance division of
BankBoston Corp. extended to Caldor what it described as ``a $450
million replacement (debtor-in-possession) facility and
emergency-credit facility.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday a BankBoston spokeswoman said the bank would have no
comment on Caldor.
</P>
<P>
   Bradlees faces some of the same challenges as Caldor. But,
according to Schmitt, Bradlees' creditors are close to approving a
reorganization plan that would let the chain shortly exit from
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're meeting our business plan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What impact will Caldor's closing have on Bradlees?
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't take pleasure in the difficulties of our
competitors,'' Schmitt said. But if Caldor customers start shopping
at Bradlees, ``we will welcome them with open arms.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Lynnley Browning of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
