<SLUG> BC-GAGULF23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cost-saving moves help Georgia Gulf
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Gulf posted fourth-quarter net income of $12.6
million, or 41 cents per share, compared to $20.8 million, or 63
cents per share in the 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were surprised. An unexpected pair of cost-saving moves
by the Atlanta-based chemicals manufacturer added 14 cents per
share to the results reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The analysts' consensus for the fourth quarter was earnings of
28 cents a share, with a range of 20 cents to 30 cents, according
to First Call. Without the cost savings, the company would have
reported a profit of 27 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company was very open about it,'' said Graham Copley of
Sanford C. Bernstein in New York. ``The real number was 27 cents.''
Copley expressed approval that Georgia Gulf had come up with the
savings.
</P>
<P>
   The company deferred fourth-quarter maintenance in its
chlorine/caustic and methanol plants, saving $3.2 million after
taxes. ``Basically they moved 10 cents from one quarter to the
next. The ideal time to take a shutdown is when the part they're
shutting down isn't doing as much business,'' Copley said.
</P>
<P>
   The company also saved $1.3 million after taxes, or 4 cents per
share, by restructuring its executive benefit plan to reduce
pension expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in a period of declining earnings in the commodity
chemical industry, and we're trying to save wherever we can,'' said
Georgia Gulf spokeswoman Nancy O'Donnell. ``I don't think that
deferring a maintenance turnaround is particularly unusual for our
industry, but, given that we were in a quarter of cyclically low
earnings, the adjustment became material.
</P>
<P>
   ``The magnitude of the cost savings (in pension expense) is
(also) a one-time savings,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Gulf reported revenue of $196.3 million in the fourth
quarter compared to $232.3 million ia year earlier. The company
said that overcapacity and Asian financial troubles hurt operating
results both at Georgia Gulf and in most of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
