<SLUG> BC-POULTRY23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Limited buying power will stall poultry exports in near future,
official says
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Poultry exports will pick up, but not in the near
future, former Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter said in
Atlanta on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to bump along for a awhile, simply because
purchasing power around the world has diminished,'' Yeutter told
attendees on the last day of the International Poultry Exposition.
</P>
<P>
   But he predicted that some currently troubled areas of the world
could become significant poultry buyers in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Yeutter concurred with earlier predictions that agricultural
exports will continue their decline this year. Broiler exports
totalled 4.5 billion pounds in 1998, down from 4.7 billion pounds a
year earlier. The U.S. Department of Agriculture predicts that
exports will dip to 4.3 billion pounds in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   New markets have opened up in recent decades, but turmoil in
Asia and Russia have hurt the industry, he said. ``We've got to
hope we'll get some leadership in many countries that will generate
economic growth and put money in peoples' pockets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yeutter offered these predictions for future trade:
</P>
<P>
   _ Russia is likely to return to some form of totalitarian
government and offers little promise. ``The good news may be that
it can't be much worse,'' Yeutter said. ``The Russian market can
come back, but don't expect it to be a booming market.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Latin America is a bright spot. Even Brazil ``is going through
some tough times, but is fundamentally sound,'' he said. ``There's
cause for substantial optimism (across the region) as long as we
can maintain the tradition of democratic capitalism.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Asian economies ``are in trouble now but are going to come
back,'' Yeutter said. Japan, Korea, Hong Kong and other countries
have plenty of potential buying power and will offer ``some
excellent marketing opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Western Europe offers long-term promise. ``In time there will
be a free trade agreement involving the U.S.,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
