<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-NURSING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NURSING CHIEF SAYS PROPOSED RULES WILL BE REVAMPED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Responding to an uproar among Massachusetts nurses, the
state nursing board's chairwoman Friday promised to recast proposed
new rules to respond to critics who say the draft language would
undercut nurses feeling pressured to provide more care with less
support from their employers.
</P>
<P>
   Board chairman Marie McCarthy said it was ``absurd'' to think
the panel intends to discipline nurses for providing ``too much
care,'' as many feared one proposed regulation might portend.
</P>
<P>
   That regulation, she said, was only intended to get at fraud _
nurses who bill for home visits they didn't provide, for instance _
although the draft regulation nowhere mentioned fraud.
</P>
<P>
   In response to criticism of another draft regulation, McCarthy
said in an interview that the nursing board won't require nurses to
follow their employers' policies right-or-wrong.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy also said the board will probably rethink a proposed
regulation saying nurses could be disciplined for behavior that
``reflects adversely on the profession.'' Some worry such a
provision could jeopardize a nurse who protested against
deterioriating working conditions, but McCarthy insisted the board
never meant it as a catch-all trap for any behavior some might see
as ``unbecoming.''
</P>
<P>
   Informed of McCarthy's remarks, critics of the proposed
regulations said they were glad to hear the board would clarify its
language.
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely accept there was no malicious intent,'' said
Karen Daley, president of the 20,000-member Massachusetts Nurses
Association. ``But their language didn't allow that to come
through.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're going to change the language to reflect nurses'
concerns, that's great,'' added Suzanne Gordon, a journalist who
writes about nursing issues. ``But if they really want to be
helpful in this era, they have to say what they mean. Licensure
regulations are not supposed to require some sort of Talmudic
exercise in potential interpretations.''
</P>
<P>
   Following two ``town meetings'' with hundreds of nurses this
week and media coverage that upstaged a presidential impeachment
trial on some Boston newscasts, state officials reconsidered their
earlier refusal to respond to specific criticisms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Premature fearmongering'' is how one state official
characterized nursing groups' cries of alarm about draft
regulations that have been under review. McCarthy said many
interpretations were ``way off-base.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, McCarthy acknowledged that some of the board's
proposed language was open to misinterpretation. ``It's very
difficult in health care these days,'' she said. ``I imagine that
somehow we were perceived as making things even more difficult at a
time when it's already hard.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCarthy, vice-president for education at Lawrence Memorial
Regis College, also criticized the board's critics, charging that
some of their scenarios were ``outrageous.'' She was particularly
upset about opposition to a proposed regulation that would allow
the nursing board to suspend a nurse's license summarily if she or
he posed a public threat.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy made clear the board will not drop its summary
suspension proposal, saying it is necessary to protect the public.
She said it is based on a 1994 statute that amended the board's
powers, but that interpretation is disputed by some.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Legislature needs to examine that,'' said Marie Snyder, a
nurse-attorney who often represents nurses in board disciplinary
proceedings. ``For one thing, the board's resources are so limited
that it's almost impossible they could hold a hearing in the
required seven days.''
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Registration in Nursing licenses 120,000 nurses. It
accounts for more than half of all disciplinary cases handled by
the state's 33 licensure boards, according to Anne Collins of the
Division of Registration, which oversees the boards.
</P>
<P>
   The nursing board's $1 million annual budget gives it $8.33 for
each licensee, while the state medical licensure board has $59.26
for each licensed physician.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy said the summary suspension power would be used only in
``extreme'' cases, such as one nurse who lost his license after the
board determined, in a two-year disciplinary process, that he
repeatedly threatened patients at knifepoint.
</P>
<P>
   In another case, a nurse eventually lost her license after the
board found the nurse had stripped an incontinent nursing home
patient of her clothing, threw her in a laundry cart, and paraded
her through the facility's hallways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should that nurse be allowed to stay in practice?'' McCarthy
said heatedly. ``Not all nurses are wonderful people, sad to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be very few cases that will rise to that level''
requiring immediate license suspension, McCarthy added. ``But for
the life of me, I cannot understand why any professional
organization would support allowing a nurse whose behavior has been
so egregious to continue practicing with a valid license for one,
two, or three years. I'll never understand that, never.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
