<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks' Kasten crying foul in Sprewell signing
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hawks president Stan Kasten angrily charged Friday that the New
York Knicks were given special treatment by the NBA that
facilitated their dealing for Latrell Sprewell, the controversial
guard suspended last season for his attack on Golden State coach
P.J. Carlesimo.
</P>
<P>
   Three Knicks executives and coach Jeff Van Gundy were allowed to
interview Sprewell in secret in Milwaukee on Sunday, four days
before the NBA lockout ended officially with the signing of the new
labor agreement. The Knicks then dealt for Sprewell when they were
satisfied with his responses, and the league restored him to active
duty Friday morning after a meeting with commissioner David Stern
and union executive director Billy Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   NBA spokesman Chris Brienza said any team interested in Sprewell
was granted a one-time exemption from lockout rules to interview
him. He did not name other teams involved, but it is believed that
there were at least two.
</P>
<P>
   Kasten cried foul on that score, saying neither he nor Hawks
general manager Pete Babcock were aware that Sprewell was available
for private interviews. ``Other teams were in the same position.
Why weren't we given that opportunity?'' Kasten asked. However, he
did not say that the Hawks were interested in Sprewell. Last
winter, Babcock said flatly that Sprewell would never play for the
Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just another case in which teams are allowed to break the
rules with impunity,'' Kasten said. ``It's been going on for some
time. Teams have worked out players in secret, talked to players in
clear violation of the rules. We know it goes on, but the league
does nothing about it. I say this stinks.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he knows of clear evidence that teams administered
physicals and had other illegal contact with players, while the
Hawks, among others, waited until the agreement was signed
Wednesday before doing so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got my players furious with me because they know other
teams are breaking the rules and we won't do it,'' Kasten said.
``They don't understand why we're losing players to teams that
don't abide by the rules. They don't understand why being honest
should put us at a competitive disadvantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Drawing a deep breath, Kasten repeated himself. ``It stinks.
It's wrong. It's wrong. It's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Hawks did not make contact with a single player
outside the rules, no matter how much they might have coveted him.
Now, they are working from a distinct disadvantage, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, they were trying to land a formidable free-agent forward
to round out their lineup, but the pool appeared to be dwindling.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, LaPhonso Ellis became available when he was
renounced in Denver to permit the free-agent signing of Antonio
McDyess.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it appeared that Corliss Williamson, rather
than be renounced so the Kings can sign Vlade Divac, had agreed to
play for only $500,000 after averaging 17.7 points while earning
$1.2 million last season. Williamson then would be expected to sign
a lucrative contract in July.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' plan to sign Williamson that way still has to be
approved by the NBA, and Kings vice president Geoff Petrie hinted
that it might be an obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Hawks were working double sessions and preparing
for public practice at Georgia Tech's Alexander Memorial Coliseum
at 5:30 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks still have not resolved problems with their own free
agents, Alan Henderson and Tyrone Corbin. Kasten said he was trying
to deal with what he considers Henderson's high salary
expectations, although the two sides are no closer to resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is important is that Alan wants to be here, and we want
him to be here,'' Kasten said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks' roster was enhanced when guard Anthony Johnson,
center Mark West and forwards Chris Crawford and Jason Lawson came
to work. Crawford is a holdover from last season.
</P>
<P>
   And they completed the Christian Laettner trade to Detroit by
obtaining second-year center Scot Pollard and a first-round draft
choice. Guard Charles O'Bannon fell out of the deal for salary cap
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
