</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unkind cuts have turned out `Super'
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a way, Falcons defensive tackle Shane Dronett and cornerback
Ronnie Bradford have traded places with Broncos wide receiver Ed
McCaffrey.
</P>
<P>
   Dronett and Bradford began their careers with Denver and played
under current coach Mike Shanahan. McCaffrey began his career with
the New York York Giants and played one year under current Falcons
coach Dan Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   But Reeves cut McCaffrey before the 1994 season.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan cut Bradford in Denver before the '96 season and didn't
re-sign Dronett the same year.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in Super Bowl XXXIII in Miami on Jan. 31, Bradford, playing
for Reeves, at times will guard McCaffrey, playing for Shanahan.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5, 215-pound McCaffrey caught 49 passes for the
Giants in '92, the year before Reeves was hired as coach. In '93,
he caught 27 passes.
</P>
<P>
   He was cut before the next season. After playing for San
Francisco, where Shanahan was offensive coordinator in '94, he
followed Shanahan to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   His next stop after the Super Bowl will be the Pro Bowl after
career-highs of 64 catches, 1,053 yards and 10 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really never even saw (the cut) coming,'' McCaffrey said
earlier this season. ``I pretty much had to just pack the bags and
start flying around the country trying to find a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves regrets the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've ever made a mistake that bad,'' he said.
``I've had guys go play somewhere else, but not go on to the level
where they could be...a major contributor on a Super Bowl team.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradford played in just four games for the Broncos in '95,
Shanahan's first year there, after playing 12 in '94.
</P>
<P>
   He was cut during training camp in '96.
</P>
<P>
   ``They asked me to move to safety, which I did without
hesitation,'' he said. ``I thought I played well in the preseason,
and was going to be a part of the team. It bothered me, but I think
it made me a better man. I wanted to get back to the point to prove
to myself, and to them, that I could play at this level.''
</P>
<P>
   After starting 11 games for Arizona in '96, Bradford signed a
two-year contract with the Falcons. The Super Bowl will be his 25th
start in 35 games for Atlanta; injuries have kept him out of 10
games.
</P>
<P>
   Dronett has had the best year of his seven-year career,
registering 82 totals tackles, 6.5 sacks, three fumbles forced, and
two recovered.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, he can thank Broncos defensive-line coach George Dyer
and defensive coordinator Greg Robinson for moving him from end to
tackle before the '95 season, although it was a disaster at first.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries and inexperience were factors as Dronett's starts
dropped from 15 in 1994 to two in '95; his total tackles dropped
from 63 to eight and his sacks from six to zero.
</P>
<P>
   Denver made no attempt to re-sign him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching TV a month after the season, and I saw they
signed (defensive tackles) Michael Dean Perry and James Jones for
big (money), so _ I was done,'' Dronett said.
</P>
<P>
   He split 1996 with the Falcons and Lions before signing a
two-year contract before this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all worked out,'' Dronett said. ``Not there, but it worked
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
