<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4988 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IOC-MEETING-0123-COX     01-22 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOC-MEETING-0123-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OLYMPIC SCANDAL ESCALATES AS SYDNEY OFFICIAL ADMITS OFFERING
MEMBERS MONEY, SECOND IOC MEMBER RESIGNS
 &HT;    EDs: Replaces IOC-BRIBERY-$ADV23., sted of
IOC-BRIBERY-$ADV24-1STLD.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (s) Sports categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ As top Olympic officials gather here to
cope with the still-growing Salt Lake City bidding scandal, a new
and potentially more perilous controversy surfaced Friday over
allegations of vote-buying in Sydney's campaign for the 2000 Summer
Games.
</P>
<P>
   An Australian International Olympic Committee member on Friday
admitted to a Sydney newspaper that he offered $70,000 in
inducements to two African IOC members the night before Sydney won
the 2000 Games by two votes.
</P>
<P>
   John Coates, the president of the Australian Olympic Committee,
told The Sydney Herald that he offered $35,000 each to the National
Olympic Committees of Kenya and Uganda through their respective IOC
members, Charles Mukora and Francis Nyangweso.
</P>
<P>
   Coates, one of the leaders of the Sydney bid, said he offered
the money in the hope that it would help persuade the IOC members
to vote for Sydney. ``I thought it was necessary for us to show our
commitment to those NOCs with a view to winning those votes,''
Coates said. ``My view was that it might encourage them to consider
their votes for Sydney.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevan Gosper(CQ), Australia's senior IOC member, acknowledged in
Lausanne that the offer could be seen as a bribe and bring demands
for Sydney to be stripped of the Games. ``I think that's possible
given the narrowness of the margin,'' Gosper said.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney won the Games in 1993 by narrowly defeating closest rival
Beijing by 45-43 on the final ballot the day after Coates made the
offer. Because the vote is taken in a secret ballot, it is
impossible to determine how the members actually voted.
</P>
<P>
   Gosper, an IOC executive board member, said Coates's statements
``lead to the conclusion that he was trying to influence an outcome
even if he didn't put money into the pockets of IOC members.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Sydney newspaper account, Coates denied the money was a
bribe and said it would go toward helping sport in Kenya and
Uganda. ``You have these developing countries which don't have
sponsors or fund-raising potential,'' he said. ``This was an
opportunity to leverage the bidding process.''
</P>
<P>
   Gosper said the matter would be reviewed by the executive board
this weekend and probably would prompt an IOC investigation.
However, Gosper said he would ask the executive board to first
confirm that Sydney and Salt Lake City -- which is hosting the 2002
Winter Olympics -- would not be stripped of the Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would bring some stability at a very difficult time,'' he
said. ``Time has moved on, huge investments have been made, people
have certain expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no precedent for the IOC's taking the Games away from a
city once they have been awarded. Such a move could be legally
complicated because of a host of contracts not only between the
Sydney organizing committee and IOC, but between broadcasters and
sponsors of the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Friday, as Olympic officials were becoming aware of the
new allegations from Australia, a second IOC member resigned over
allegations related to the Salt Lake City bid.
</P>
<P>
   Bashir Mohamed Attarabulsi of Libya delivered his resignation to
IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch in person Friday, one day
before a special IOC commission is to conclude its inquiry into the
Salt Lake scandal. More resignations were expected, perhaps before
Saturday morning when the IOC executive board is scheduled to hear
accused IOC members make their case.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, Gosper and other IOC members were meeting with
Samaranch in his private suite at the Lausanne Palace Hotel. There
was a sense of heightened gravity over the new allegations, which
come as the IOC was trying to get beyond the Salt Lake City crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Details of Sydney's offer were contained in a package of
previously confidential Sydney bid documents released to Australian
news media by Coates, who was in Australia and not immediately
available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The files contained letters outlining the offers dated Sept. 23
, 1993, the date the IOC selected Sydney. The letter to Uganda's
Nyangweso said that ``if Sydney is successful'' the Australian
Olympic Committee would pay $5,000 a year to Uganda's National
Olympic Committee up to and including 2000 to help support the
Uganda National Games.
</P>
<P>
   The Sydney newspaper said the two committees have been receiving
their $5,000 checks yearly as promised.
</P>
<P>
   The documents also disclosed that Coates had written to Mukora
and Nyangweso a month before the vote, offering to put them up at
Sydney's expense at the luxury Dorchester Hotel in London on their
way to Monaco for the vote.
</P>
<P>
   In the Salt Lake City scandal, Attarabulsi, an IOC member since
1977, stepped down because of revelations that his son, Suhel,
received tuition to attend an English language center at Brigham
Young University and a community college, plus $700 a month for
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I accepted his resignation and I thanked him for his 22 years
as a member of the IOC, what he did for sport in his country and
for us,'' Samaranch told the Associated Press Friday. ``He's a good
man. He did (make) a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Finland's Pirjo Haeggman became the first IOC casualty of the
scandal when she resigned Tuesday. She was implicated because her
ex-husband got jobs through Olympic bidding committees from Salt
Lake City and Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   IOC Director General Francois Carrard told reporters that both
resignations were ``in the higher interest of the Olympic
movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch said 13 members were implicated in the IOC's
investigation into cash payments, college scholarships, free
medical treatment, lavish gifts and other inducements related to
Salt Lake's winning bid for the 2002 Games.
</P>
<P>
   The 78-year-old IOC president has called a special IOC assembly
here for March 17-18 to vote on expulsions and ratify new
site-selection procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch said his priority is to restore ``the prestige'' of
the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch, who has been president since 1980, reiterated he has
no intention of
</P>
<P>
   resigning.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
