<TEXT>
<P>
   Sydney's campaign questioned
</P>
<P>
   By Bert Roughton Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ As top Olympic officials gather here to
cope with the Salt Lake City bidding scandal, a new and potentially
more perilous controversy is surfacing over allegations of
vote-buying in Sydney's campaign for the 2000 Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   An Australia IOC member on Friday admitted to a Sydney newspaper
that he offered $70,000 in inducements to two African IOC members
the night before Sydney won the next Olympics by two votes.
</P>
<P>
   John Coates, president of the Australian Olympic Committee, told
The Sydney Herald that he offered $35,000 each to the National
Olympic Committees of Kenya and Uganda through their respective IOC
members, Charles Mukora and Francis Nyangweso.
</P>
<P>
   Coates, a leader of the Sydney bid, said he offered the money in
the hope that it would help persuade the IOC members to vote for
Syndey. ``I thought it was necessary for us to show our commitment
to those NOCs with a view to winning those votes,'' Coates said.
``My view was that it might encourage them to consider their votes
for Sydney.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevan Gosper, Australia's senior IOC member, acknowledged in
Lausanne that the offer could be seen as a bribe and bring demands
for Sydney to be stripped of the Games. ``I think that's possible
given the narrowness of the margin,'' Gosper said.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney won the Games in 1993 by defeating closest rival Beijing
45-43 on the final ballot the day after Coates' offers. Because the
vote is taken in a secret ballot, it is unknown how the members
voted.
</P>
<P>
   Gosper, an IOC executive board member, said Coates' statements
``lead to the conclusion that he was trying to influence an outcome
even if didn't put money into the pockets of IOC members.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Sydney newspaper account, Coates denied the money was a
bribe and said it would go toward helping sport in Kenya and
Uganda. ``You have these developing countries which don't have
sponsors or fund-raising potential,'' he said. ``This was an
opportunity to leverage the bidding process.''
</P>
<P>
   Gosper said the matter would be reviewed by the executive board
this weekend and probably would prompt an IOC investigaion.
However, Gosper said he would ask the executive board to first
confirm thatSydney and Salt Lake City would not be stripped of the
Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would bring some stability at a very difficult time,'' he
said. ``Time has moved on, huge investments have been made, people
have certain expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no precedent for the IOC taking the Games away from a
city once they have been awarded. Such a move could be legally
complicated because of a host of contracts not only between the
Sydney organizing committee and IOC but between broadcasters and
sponsors of the Games.
</P>
<P>
   As Olympic officials were becoming aware of the new allegations
from Australia, a second IOC member resigned over allegations
related to the Salt Lake City bid.
</P>
<P>
   Bashir Mohamed Attarabulsi of Libya delivered his resignation to
IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch in person Friday, one day
before a special IOC commission is to conclude its inquiry into the
Salt Lake scandal. More resignations were expected, perhaps before
this morning when the IOC executive board is scheduled to hear
accused IOC members make their case. One of those is Mukora,
implicated in the Austrlian case.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, Gosper and other IOC members met with Samaranch in
his private suite at the Lausanne Palace Hotel. There was a sense
of heightened gravity over the new allegations, which come as the
IOC was trying to get beyond the Salt Lake City crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Details of Sydney's offer were contained in a package of
previously confidential bid documents released to Australian news
media by Coates, who was in Australia and not immediately available
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The files contained letters outlining the offers dated Sept. 23
, 1993, the day the IOC selected Sydney. The letter to Nyangweso
said that ``if Sydney is successful'' the Australian Olympic
Committee would pay $5,000 a year to Uganda's National Olympic
Committee up to and including 2000 to help support the Uganda
National Games.
</P>
<P>
   The Sydney newspaper said the two committees have been receiving
their $5,000 checks yearly as promised.
</P>
<P>
   The documents also disclosed that Coates had written to Mukora
and Nyangweso a month before the vote, offering to put them up at
Sydney's expense at the luxury Dorchester Hotel in London on their
way to Monaco for the vote.
</P>
<P>
   In the Salt Lake City scandal, Attarabulsi, an IOC member since
1977, stepped down because of revelations that his son, Suhel,
received tuition to attend an English language center at Brigham
Young University and a community college, plus $700 a month for
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I accepted his resignation and I thanked him for his 22 years
as a member of
</P>
<P>
   the IOC, what he did for sport in his country and for us,''
Samaranch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good man. He did (make) a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Finland's Pirjo Haeggman became the first IOC casualty of the
scandal when she resigned Tuesday. She was implicated because her
ex-husband got jobs through Olympic bidding committees from Salt
Lake City and Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   IOC director general Francois Carrard told reporters that both
resignations were ``in the higher interest of the Olympic
movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch said 13 members were implicated in the IOC's
investigation into cash payments, college scholarships, free
medical treatment, lavish gifts and other inducements related to
Salt Lake's winning bid.
</P>
<P>
   He has called a special IOC assembly for March 17-18 to vote on
expulsions and ratify new site-selection procedures based on an IOC
investigative report on the Salt Lake situation scheduled to be
released Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch said his priority is to ``restore the prestige'' of
the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch, who has been president since 1980, reiterated he has
no intention of resigning, though U.S. Olympic Committee executive
director Dick Schultz said Friday in New York he senses a ``palace
revolt'' to oust the 78-year-old Spaniard.
</P>
