<HEADER>
A4993 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IOC-AGENTS-COX     01-22 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-AGENTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Operating in Olympic grey area
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When an IOC investigative panel completes its report this
weekend on the Salt Lake City influence-peddling scandal, a portion
will deal with agents, or middlemen, offering to secure votes for
bid cities in exchange for cash payments.
</P>
<P>
   That is outright corruption. But not everyone playing the game
is blatantly soliciting a bribe. Some of the cadre of
well-connected consultants operate in a gray area, selling their
access to the IOC and its influential members in exchange for a
lucrative job with a bid city.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Olympic officials say they were approached during the
bid process for the 1996 Games by people claiming to be close to
the IOC, including one who sought a $250,000 payment. But none of
the individuals directly suggested an ability to deliver votes. Nor
did Atlanta hire any of the individuals, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   On the $250,000 offer, Andrew Young, who was chairman of the
Atlanta Olympic bid committee, recalled, ``What he said is, 'I'll
answer your phone calls, answer your questions.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Young declined to indentify the person.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Gatlin, executive director of the Atlanta bid committee,
confirmed the contact and said it wasn't uncommon to be approached
by ``insiders'' after the group opened an office following the 1988
Seoul Olympics. Atlanta officials never were interested in their
services, Gatlin said, and rarely did it even get to the point
where a fee was mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``People started drifting in, (saying) 'I can do this or that
for you,' `` said Gatlin, later a senior vice president with the
Atlanta organizing committee. ``It wasn't like, 'I will deliver
this item.' It wasn't a clear-cut thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was, 'I know what is going on. I've been around this a long
time. I know the individual members and what their interests are.
The things they like. Where they live.' ``
</P>
<P>
   People connected to the Atlanta bid say they also heard from
Goran Takac, son of Artur Takac, an IOC adviser and longtime friend
of IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch. Goran Takac operates
Studio Six, a business near the IOC headquarters in Lausanne,
Switzerland, that has contracted to produce films and books for bid
cities. He also has served as a consultant to bid cities.
</P>
<P>
   The books often contain an endorsement from Samaranch, according
to those who have seen them.
</P>
<P>
   During a visit to Lausanne with the Atlanta bid group in early
1990, Goran Takac approached them about a consulting position,
according to former U.S. Olympic Committee executive director
Harvey Schiller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he wanted, like, 18 or 20 grand a month,'' Schiller
said. ``Now, he never made an offer of buying votes or anything. He
just wanted to be a consultant, and we made a decision not to hire
any outside consultants.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Henderson, head of the Toronto bid for the 1996 Games, said
Takac called on his group about putting a ``European flavor'' to
its brochures. He, too, rejected the overture.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC report to be released this weekend makes clear that the
influence-peddling didn't begin with the Salt Lake City bid, but
instead dates back to the early 1980s, involving some bid cities
and IOC members. The report highlights activities of at least two
agents attempting to sell votes to bid cities.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Hodler, a senior IOC official who helped expose the
scandal, has identified Mahmoud El Farnawani as an agent who
offered to sell blocs of votes for money.
</P>
<P>
   El Farnawani denies Hodler's charge and says that bid cities
hire him to make introductions and help forge relationships with
IOC members from North Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake officials acknowledge paying El Farnawani, a former
national volleyball coach in Egypt who now lives outside Toronto,
$58,000 in 1994 for his help in providing access to IOC members. El
Farnawani said he was paid ``about as much'' by Sydney officials in
1992 and 1993 to assist in their successful bid for the 2000 Summer
Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job was to introduce those people that I know for a long
time, because of my involvement in sports in Africa before leaving
Egypt in '67 after the six-day war,'' El Farnawani said. ``I was
only introducing the IOC to the bid committee and vice versa -- to
get to see and talk, to know what kind of costumes and habits they
should observe. This way, the IOC is not a complete stranger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some IOC (members) like me like a brother. So (bid groups)
capitalize on that and ask me to be their (adviser).''
</P>
<P>
   El Farnawani, 66, denies any knowledge of tuition payments by
the Salt Lake group for the son of his good friend, Bashir Mohamed
Attarabulsi, the IOC member from Libya who resigned Friday. Suhel
Attarabulsi reportedly attended Brigham Young University for free
and received $700 a month for expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not an agent,'' El Farnawani said, bristling. ``I am an
adviser, a consultant, but I am not selling goods. I am not selling
anybody. I am selling access.''
</P>
<P>
   El Farnawani was a volunteer with the unsuccessful Toronto bid
group that missed out on the '96 Games to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was against Atlanta and hated Atlanta,'' said El Farnawani,
who claims that he would have received licensing rights to pins
sold at the Games if Toronto secured the bid.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Battle, a key member of the Atlanta bid committee, said,
``We never ran up against any of these so-called agents,'' but he
acknowleged being aware of El Farnawani's presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always assumed he was a guy who was close to these Arab
members. If you've got somebody who could introduce you to
somebody, that is helpful. I never assumed he was delivering
money.''
</P>
<P>
   48pt xxxxxxxxxxxx
</P>
