<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4994 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IOC-SUSPECTS-COX     01-22 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-SUSPECTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ScandaBy Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   She shopped for kitchen utensils with the Russian Vitaly
Smirnov's wife. She took Bashir Mohamed Attarabulsi of Libya and
his spouse to Chastain for a Peter, Paul and Mary concert. She
stayed in Agustin Arroyo's house in Ecuador as a guest and welcomed
several others into her own Buckhead home for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   As much as anyone who worked to bring the 1996 Summer Games to
Atlanta, Ginger Watkins personally knew many of the 13
International Olympic Committee members known to be under fire for
their alleged involvement in the Salt Lake City bribery scandal.
Two, including Attarabulsi, have resigned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me sad,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Watkins, an original member of Atlanta's big group and
later a managing director for ACOG, nor any others associated with
the city's Olympic efforts who were interviewed this week cited any
unethical behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins said she considered many of them ``above reproach.''
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, did they not come to Atlanta with their hands out?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe there was a naivete about all of us that made us less
approachable,'' she said. ``Sometimes that works in your favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Constant media reports about the accused 13 have rekindled
memories within Atlanta's inner Olympic circle.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins remembered Pirjo Haeggman of Finland, the first IOC
member to step down this week, as ``easy to relate to. She was a
mother, an athlete, and so you could talk to her about her
children.''
</P>
<P>
   She recalled Attarabulsi's wife wearing to Chastain ``the
cultural costume (of Libya) the whole time. It was 110 degrees and
she's completely covered.''
</P>
<P>
   And Watkins reminisced about Raquel Arroyo's love of singing.
``Any time music was played anywhere, she would get up and sing,''
she said. ``She did it in restaurants in Atlanta; she did it
everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Gatlin, the bid commitee's paid executive director, said of
Arroyo, ``If you were ever at a party or you ever had a party, he
was there.'' He described Attarabulsi as ``one of the nicest guys
on the committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis Guirandoun'Diaye of the Ivory Coast was a natty dresser
(who smoked) big cigars,'' said Gatlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed those people,'' recalled Charlie Battle, a former
attorney who was the Atlanta bid committee's primary international
emissary. ``I sort of characterize some of them as rogues. They are
colorful characters.''
</P>
<P>
   But not crooks, Battle added. Not even corrupt opportunists. He
described Attarabulsi as ``the nicest man in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Payne, a former attorney who headed the bid effort and the
Atlanta Games, said he's ``wracked my brain'' trying to think of
inappropriate requests from any IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you get 100 people from 70 different cultures of the
world who are coming here to make a decision on whether they like
you and are going to vote for you,'' he said, ``you have a
predictable percentage that don't like their hotel room, there's
too much noise on the floor, they don't like the person who drove
them around.''
</P>
<P>
   But did any want scholarships? A free liposuction? Cash in a
brown paper bag?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even remember people saying I want muslin sheets and
the following liquors in my hotel room,'' Payne said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta did engage in gift-giving, though perhaps not to the
extent as the Dutch when Amsterdam was trying to win the 1992
Summer Games. They
</P>
<P>
   gave various IOC members diamonds, expensive porcelain,
paintings and exclusive art books, along with trips to exclusive
(and legal) brothels in Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's gifts tended toward the personal. A copy of the movie
``Gone With the Wind'' for one. A carved walking stick for another.
A print of a building at Amherst, the alma mater of Prince Albert
of Monaco. ``That was a lot more important than a diamond necklace
or a leather suitcase,'' Payne said.
</P>
<P>
   Battle mentioned the day his wife, Lola, took one IOC member's
wife shopping for linens. They were billed to Mrs. Battle's credit
card. ``But that night, the guy gave me $400 in cash or whatever it
was,'' Battle recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you do get in an awkward position vis-a-vis
hospitality,'' he said. ``But that's just a question of trying to
be nice and how far do you extend it. We certainly never felt any
pressure to give anyone any money.''
</P>
<P>
   David Sibandze of Swaziland was treated for heart problems at
Piedmont Hospital, a courtesy that is similar to some accusations
against the Salt Lake group for offering medical care. But the
Atlantans take the position that if a guest gets sick during a
visit, you take care of him.
</P>
<P>
   Gatlin remembered Sibandze as traveling with a large entourage
of family and friends. ``He probably cost more in airplane tickets
than anybody,'' Gatlin said. ``If people wanted to dig, he was less
of a noble-seeming chartacter than the others.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne placed a few phone calls to his alma mater, the University
of Georgia, to help get Smirnov's stepson into school but said no
one with the Atlanta group paid his way.
</P>
<P>
   Gatlin said he can understand why some IOC members accepted
scholarships from Salt Lake officials for their relatives. ``They
want their kids to get an education,'' he said, adding that he
knows of no IOC members asking Atlanta for free schooling.
</P>
<P>
   The highest-ranking IOC member linked to the Salt Lake scandal
is Kim Un-Yong, a member of the executive board.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting that he's on the list,'' Battle said. ``He
was very nice and helpful to us during the Seoul Games. I always
felt good about him supporting us. He knew a lot about Georgia. He
trained at Fort Benning.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Mike Fish contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
