<SLUG> BC-STOLEN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SICILIAN PROBER OF STOLEN ART FACES INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WALTER V. ROBINSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Sicilian magistrate, who has spent the last two decades
vigorously prosecuting grave-robbers who excavate antiquities for
illcit smuggling abroad, now faces an inquiry that he himself has
been involved in the illegal antiquities trade.
</P>
<P>
   Silvio Raffiotta, the magistrate in the province of Enna in
central Sicily, is under investigation by a magistrate in the
Catania province, according to Saturday's Italy Today section in
the Italian edition of the International Herald Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   Associates of Raffiotta said they were dumbfounded at the
investigation given his record. They suggested that the numerous
enemies he has made by curbing the illicit trade are now seeking to
embarrass or destroy him.
</P>
<P>
   Raffiotta, for nearly a decade, has been preparing a legal case
against the New York Metropolitan Museum of Art, collecting
evidence the museum in the early 1980s acquired, for $2.74 million,
a collection of dazzling 3d Century B.C. Hellenistic silver. The
horde, according to an affadavit by graverobber Giusseppe Mascara
and work done by American archeologists, was illegally excavated at
the partially excavated ruins of Morgantina, the last Greek
city-state in Sicily to fall to the Romans in 211 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   The Met has rebuffed Italian demands to return the silver.
</P>
<P>
   Raffiotta, an amateur archeologist, has written two books about
the archeological site, which a Princeton team stumbled upon when
Raffiotta was a boy growing up in nearby Aidone.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the magistrate created new adversaries, politically
powerful construction companies that want to build a dam, which
Raffiotta has stopped because its construction would destroy an
archeological site.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the inquiry became public Friday, he blocked a sale
of ancient coins, including the most remarkable coin ever minted at
Morgantina, said Malcolm Bell, a US archeologist who directs the
four-decade-long official dig at Morgantina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot believe there is anything to this investigation,''
Carla Antonaccio, a classical archeologist at Wesleyan University
who is co-director of the Morgantina excavation. ``Silvio Raffiotta
is a man of total integrity, and totally dedicated to stopping this
sort of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   From Italian press accounts, it was unclear Friday what
Raffiotta is under investigation for. The disclosure, however,
follows the arrest in Catania in December of a collector and two
university professors for illegally selling ancient artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas P. Hoving, a former Metropolitan director who was
involved in the Morgantina dig as a Princeton graduate student in
the 1950s, said Friday: ``Even in Sicily, this investigation
doesn't ring true.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How great an actor he would have to be, to spend his whole
career courageously pursuing the looters, while secretly involved
with them. He is not an actor, but a prosecutor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 2006EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
