A4997 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-REFORM-NYT &LR;      01-22 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR OFFERS PROPOSAL TO CHANGE MEDICARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La.)  (lb) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Higher-income Medicare beneficiaries would have to
pay higher premiums under proposals outlined Friday by Sen. John
Breaux, the chairman of a bipartisan commission seeking ways to
avert a financial crisis in the health-insurance program for the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   In his State of the Union message on Tuesday, President Clinton
proposed using some of the federal budget surplus for Medicare.
Breaux, D-La., said this would help shore up Medicare but would not
solve its long-term financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-member commission plans to meet on Tuesday and is to
submit final recommendations to the president and Congress by March
1. Breaux's proposals are the text from which the panel will work,
and he said he thought he could get the necessary 11 votes on the
panel.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux said his proposal would transform Medicare into an arena
for competition between the fee-for-service federal program and
dozens of private health plans. Instead of paying separately for
each medical service, the government would offer a fixed amount of
money to each beneficiary to buy insurance, and the original
Medicare program would be one option among many.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux said that private health plans would have to offer
benefits at least equivalent to those offered in the government-run
program. A new federal agency, the Medicare Board, would be
established to supervise and negotiate with the private health
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Federal payments to health plans would be set through
competitive bidding, Breaux said. Health plans would submit bids to
the Medicare Board, and the government would pay a fixed percentage
of the average premium charged by all plans participating in
Medicare. The government's contribution would have a limit, and
beneficiaries would pay costs above that limit.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Breaux said, ``higher-income Medicare beneficiaries
should be required to pay a larger share of their Medicare premiums
than moderate- and low-income beneficiaries.'' The extra revenue
would subsidize the premiums of low-income beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The eligibility age for Medicare would be increased to 67 from
65, over 24 years, from 2003 to 2027.
</P>
<P>
   John Rother, director of legislation and public policy at the
American Association of Retired Persons, said of the proposal: ``It
could be positive for beneficiaries, or it could be negative,
depending on how it's structured. We don't have enough details,
enough numbers, to know.''
</P>
<P>
   To judge the impact on consumers, Rother said, it is necessary
to know how much of the average premium they will pay.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux bristled at suggestions that he was proposing a
``voucher'' system.
</P>
<P>
   ``A voucher just says to somebody, `Here's X amount of money, go
find yourself a health plan,''' Breaux said. ``My proposal uses the
strength of the federal government to negotiate on behalf of people
so they can get the best deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaux said that Medicare's financial problems were more urgent
than those of Social Security.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 2006EST &QL; 
