<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5003 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-UNIVERSAL-SAVINGS     01-22 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-UNIVERSAL-SAVINGS-ART-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USA ACCOUNTS ARE NEW VOLLEY IN RETIREMENT SAVINGS DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 24)  
 (af)  
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his State of the Union address and, again, before a roaring
crowd in Buffalo, N.Y., President Clinton last week floated the
idea of Universal Savings Accounts, a new type of subsidized
savings for low- and moderate-income workers akin to a 401(k) plan.
</P>
<P>
   The government would use 11 percent of the projected budget
surplus to match money the workers would save on their own in the
USAs.
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, the plan appears designed to appeal to both
political parties. It is intended to help workers at the low end of
the spectrum who now have only Social Security at retirement. That
should appeal to Democrats. For Republicans, there is the draw that
these accounts would be controlled by individuals, not the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the president's plan will get bipartisan support, or any
support at all, is unknown. Right now, the USA proposal is high in
concept and low in details, and the administration says it will not
have more specifics for at least a month.
</P>
<P>
   In general, though, both liberal and conservative economists say
they find such accounts an intriguing way to increase the savings
rate. They also say the proposal is another volley in a larger
debate about investing government retirement funds in the market.
</P>
<P>
   Still, basic questions remain. Is this the best way to spend
part of the budget surplus? How would the matching formula work?
What can the savings accounts be used for? How may the money be
invested? And will the public support a new government program that
redistributes wealth to lower-income citizens?
</P>
<P>
   ``These accounts are still a very nebulous concept,'' said Steve
Moore, director of fiscal policies at the Cato Institute, a
free-market research group in Washington. ``I like the idea of
setting up savings accounts. We want to create a culture of savings
in this country. But it's bad in the way it's done. It looks more
like a new entitlement program than an IRA. I don't see the
rationale of creating a new income distribution program.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The administration envisions the program, which would cost
nearly $500 billion over 15 years, or $33 billion a year, as
offering $100 grants to workers to start accounts. The government
would then match workers' contributions at a variable rate based on
income. About 100 million Americans who earn less than $80,000 to
$100,000 a year _ the precise cutoff has not been set _ would be
eligible for the accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic idea is to get more people to do more saving on
their own,'' said an administration spokesman. ``There are so many
things to help the rich save. We think there is a big hole in
savings at the low end.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, 41 percent of all workers earn less than $15,000 a
year; of those, only 8 percent have a retirement program at their
workplaces, according to the Employee Benefits Research Institute,
a Washington research group.
</P>
<P>
   The match rate for the new accounts would be progressive, with
the lowest-paid getting the most. The investment options would be
modeled closely after the federal employees' Thrift Savings Plan,
which offers three government-run investment funds _ a stock index
fund, a bond index fund and a Treasury bill fund.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the administration said a worker earning $40,000 a
year could deposit up to $600 a year. At that income level the
government would match 50 cents on the dollar, providing $300 more
to the account. Counting the $100 starting grant, that comes to
$1,000 in the first year, $400 of it from the government.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Thompson, a Washington representative for Merrill Lynch &AMP;
Co., the nation's largest broker, praised the plan as ``opening the
door to private investments.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Merrill and other Wall Street firms would prefer that the
government use a portion of Social Security payroll taxes to
finance the accounts, rather than using the budget surplus, and
would like the program to be open to workers of all income levels.
Thompson said he was concerned about how the accounts would be
financed when the budget surplus ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would rather see all people given the option of investing a
portion of their payroll taxes, maybe one or two percentage points,
in accounts that would be similar to IRAs, and invest that money
however they see fit,'' Thompson said. This idea is similar to one
proposed by some Republicans as an alternative to Clinton's plan to
strengthen Social Security by allowing the government to invest in
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Other sellers of investments had little to say, for the moment.
``We don't have enough information to judge yet,'' said John
Collins, a spokesman for the Investment Company Institute, the
trade association for the mutual fund industry. In general, brokers
and mutual fund companies want the opportunity to sell investment
products to USAs, but worry that a program restricted to
lower-income people would result in many small accounts with low
balances, which are costly for brokers to administer.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Aaron, an economist at the Brookings Institution, wants to
see the funds less restricted in another way: what savings can be
used for. ``Done right, USA accounts are a very good idea,'' Aaron
said, but the money should be available for more than just
retirement _ education, medical care, down payments on first homes
and and business start-ups, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be a device to help make savings fashionable and
educate people on the power of compound interest,'' he said, adding
that USAs are much ``sweeter'' for lower-income people than are
individual retirement accounts, which offer only a tax deduction.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Mitchell, a senior fellow at the Heritage Foundation, a
conservative research group, also reacted favorably to the plan,
though with reservations. ``I'm not sure what these accounts offer
that isn't already out there in the market,'' Mitchell said. ``I
like that Clinton recognizes that private investment is the key.
But it will not succeed unless we put a chunk of the payroll taxes
into it, because the poor will not be able to build up a good
balance. They cannot use disposable income for this because they
don't have enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
