<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MASSACRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORENSICS EXPERTS BEGIN EXAMINATION OF BODIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Kosovo-Kidnaps)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ For those who have given up on President
Clinton's question of ``what the definition of is, is,'' the
conflict in Kosovo presents another linguistic and
politically-loaded question: what is a massacre?
</P>
<P>
   The word almost got chief Kosovo Verification Mission monitor
William Walker expelled from Yugoslavia, after the US ambassador
accused the Serbs of massacring 45 ethnic Albanians, who were found
on Jan. 16 dressed in civilian clothes and scattered on a muddy
hillside.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said the bodies, which included those of three women and
a 12-year-old boy, were mutilated and shot at close range in the
head or neck, suggesting a massacre.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs say the Racak villagers were killed in gunfire after
Serb police went to the town to look for members of the Kosovo
Liberation Army, an Albanian group bent on independence for the
Serbian province of Kosovo, under suspicion of killing Serb police.
</P>
<P>
   The people were shot dead in the ensuing violence, but this just
makes them a lot of dead people lying in one place _ not victims of
a massacre, the Serbs insist.
</P>
<P>
   Finnish forensics experts set to work Friday on examining the
corpses strewn at the Racak site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, what the definition of a massacre is,''
Walker told reporters Friday at the well-guarded Organization for
the Security and Cooperation in Europe's office in Pristina, the
capital of troubled southern Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
   Walker was celebrating his first day as an unmarked man, hours
after Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic agreed to
unconditionally freeze the order expelling the diplomat. The U.S.
ambassador had been declared ``persona non grata'' by the Serbs
after accusing them of the Racak carnage.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over Walker's comments _ and the negotiations
with Milosevic that followed it _ had the effect of making the
gruesome discovery more about Walker than about the question of
what happened to the people found shot dead in a gully.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, warned that NATO might strike over his failure to
comply with an October cease-fire agreement, was under heightened
threat because of his decision to expel Walker.
</P>
<P>
   When Milosevic agreed early Friday to let Walker stay, the
threat of a NATO strike eased, although world officials said it
remains pending on the Serb leader's cooperation with a cease-fire
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Western and Russian diplomats approved a peace plan for
the Yugoslav province of Kosovo even as NATO continued to build up
military forces and warned Milosevic he hasn't done enough yet to
remove its threat of airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, drafted by US envoy Christopher Hill, was approved by
the six-nation Contact Group for former Yugoslavia, and will be
presented separately next week to Milosevic and ethnic Albanians
fighting for independence for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign ministers of the Contact Group, including Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright, are expected to meet in London next
Friday to issue formal invitations to peace negotiations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
