<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARAGON23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Paragon to pay Proctor &AMP; Gamble, ending 5-year patent dispute
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Diaper maker Paragon Trade Brands of Norcross ended
its five-year fight Friday against Proctor &AMP; Gamble's claims of
patent infringement.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement essentially calls for Paragon to pay licensing
fees to Proctor &AMP; Gamble to use the diaper patent in question. It
also means Paragon will have to pay an unspecified amount of a
December 1997 judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Paragon reached an agreement in principle with the
Cincinnati-based consumer products giant as part of its Chapter 11
bankruptcy reorganization. The lengthy dispute centers around P&AMP;G's
so-called leakproof diapers. Paragon filed for bankruptcy
protection in January 1998, a week after a Delaware judge ordered
the company to pay $178.4 million for infringing on P&AMP;G's patents.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's action ``provides the basis for resolution of all of
P&AMP;G's claims,'' Paragon officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the settlement are still being worked out and are
expected to be released within a few weeks, the companies said.
Procter &AMP; Gamble said it expects to get millions of dollars from
licensing fees and the December 1997 judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Proctor &AMP; Gamble, maker of Pampers and Luvs, and Kimberly-Clark,
maker of Huggies, together account for 74 percent of the $3.6
billion annual disposable baby diaper market. Paragon, with 1997
sales of about $560 million, has 74 percent of the store brand
market.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, while a costly one for Paragon, clears the way
for the company to try to emerge from bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased we could get to this point,'' said Alan
Cyron, Paragon's chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Cyron said he hopes the company can emerge from bankruptcy by
the end of the year. The settlement must be approved by the
bankruptcy court.
</P>
<P>
   Paragon stock closed Friday on the New York Stock Exchange at
$4, up $1.37 1/2, or 52 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The decision ``assures Proctor &AMP; Gamble will receive
compensation for its diaper technologies. Paragon will join
virtually every other competitor of ours in licensing these
technologies,'' Proctor &AMP; Gamble spokesman Scott Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   Paragon must still resolve similar infringement claims with
Kimberly-Clark, which had asked for as much as $2.3 billion.
Paragon officials said they believe ``considerable progress'' has
been made in that case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in discusions with Paragon,'' Kimberly-Clark
spokesperson Tina Barry said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Paragon was spun off from Weyerhauser in January 1993. Its
chairman is Bobby Abraham, a former Weyerhauser executive. The
company has 1,300 employees in the United States and Canada. About
200 of those workers are at the company's headquarters on
Technology Parkway near Jimmy Carter Boulevard. It has plants in
Macon, Waco, Texas, Gaffney, S.C., Harmony, Pa., and Brampton,
Ontario, Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Paragon makes premium and economy disposable diapers, training
pants, and feminine care and adult incontinence products sold in
the United States in Canada mostly in grocery and food stores, mass
merchandisers, warehouse clubs, toy stores and drug stores under
the stores' brand names. The company also has joint ventures in
Mexico, Argentina, Brazil and China to sell diapers and other
absorbent personal care products.
</P>
<P>
   _ Contributing: Staff writer Shelia Poole
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
