<HEADER>
A5008 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACHMENT-T     01-22 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACHMENT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST VIRGINIAN SENATOR, ROBERT BYRD, TO LEAD EFFORT FOR DISMISSAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton picked up a key ally in his
effort to end the Senate impeachment trial Friday as lawyers
sparred over the evidence in an unusual question-and-answer
session.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., announced that he would lead the
effort to dismiss the case Monday. Byrd, a stickler for Senate
rules and procedure, said he is convinced that Clinton's critics
will never get the two-thirds majority to force the president from
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have also become convinced that lengthening this trial will
only prolong and deepen the divisive, bitter and polarizing effect
that this sorry affair has visited upon our nation,'' he said in
disclosing his intention to offer a dismissal motion.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's decision was significant because the conservative
lawmaker had been considered a possible vote for impeachment. The
81-year-old senator, a former Ku Klux Klan member who loves to
quote leaders from ancient history, has little in common with the
baby-boomer president whose affair with a 22-year-old White House
intern led to his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd distanced himself from Clinton before the trial started by
sternly warning White House officials to avoid lobbying lawmakers.
When Clinton invited loyal Democrats to the White House after the
Dec. 19 House impeachment vote, Byrd called the pep rally ``an
egregious display of shameless arrogance.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans moved quickly Friday to try to blunt the impact of
Byrd's announcement, dispatching Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas to make
the case against dismissal at a hastily arranged news conference.
The other Texas senator, Republican Kay Bailey Hutchison, also
opposes Byrd's motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a system of justice where we render a verdict
first and then we get the facts,'' Gramm said, predicting that the
Senate will defeat Byrd's motion. ``We shouldn't judge whether or
not to follow a constitutional process based on how people are
likely to vote at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the lead House prosecutor, used a
similar argument in pleading with senators to reject the dismissal
motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know _ oh do I know _ what an annoyance we are in the bosom
of this great body,'' he said. ``But we're a constitutional
annoyance, and I would remind you of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde also asserted that dismissal would send ``a terrible
message.'' The impeachment articles accuse Clinton of perjury and
obstruction of justice in his efforts to hide his illicit affair
with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're saying, I guess, perjury is OK if it's about sex.
Obstruction is OK. ...,'' Hyde said, noting that judges have been
impeached for perjury. ``This country can survive with a few bad
judges, a few corrupt judges. We can make it. But a corrupt
president? Survival is a little tougher there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate will take up the dismissal motion Monday, along with
a Republican alternative that would permit prosecutors to call
witnesses before the Senate renders a verdict in the case. The
deciding votes may not come until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is in flux right now,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch,
R-Utah. Although Hatch said he has ``heard an occasional Republican
say that they might consider'' dismissal, no GOP senator publicly
endorsed Byrd's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans hold a 55-45 advantage in the Senate, meaning that
Democrats need at least six Republican votes to throw out the
impeachment case. Clinton's critics expressed confidence that they
have the votes to block dismissal, while conceding that they remain
short of the two-thirds majority _ 67 votes _ to remove Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In another development, Hutchison said she will lead a
bipartisan effort to open the Senate's deliberations to the public
when and if lawmakers debate the two impeachment articles. Senate
rules require all impeachment deliberations to be held privately,
but lawmakers can vote to waive the requirement.
</P>
<P>
   The 2-week-old trial moved into a new phase Friday as senators
got a chance to submit written inquiries to lawyers for both sides.
In a proceeding that had some of the trappings of a deadly serious
game show, Democrats and Republicans took turns lobbing softball
questions to whichever legal team echoed their views.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, a group of Republican senators asked prosecutors
if a White House argument was ``just a red herring.'' Prosecutors
agreed that it was.
</P>
<P>
   But there were a few unscripted exchanges. White House lawyer
Charles Ruff looked in vain for someone on Clinton's team to
explain why the president sought advice from pollster Dick Morris
when the sex scandal broke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't find any volunteers,'' Ruff said to bipartisan
laughter. ``I think the honest answer has two pieces to it: I don't
have a clue, and ... it seems to me of absolutely no relevance
whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, the combatants adopted the time-honored tactic of
answering questions that had not been asked to drive home their
points.
</P>
<P>
   When a Democrat asked if prosecutors would impeach Clinton for
any criminal act, including driving while intoxicated, Rep. Lindsey
Graham, R-S.C., delivered an impassioned plea for Clinton's ouster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I know what he was up to. His political and legal
interests are so paramount in his mind, the law be damned. And
anybody that got in his way be damned,'' Graham said, comparing
Clinton's actions to the Watergate scandal that led to Richard
Nixon's resignation in 1974. ``We need to try this case, ladies and
gentlemen, because you need to know who your president is.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
