<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MOTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP MOVES SWIFTLY TO COUNTER BYRD ATTACK ON TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The news spread instantly among Democrats in the
Senate chamber: Senator Robert C. Byrd would file a motion to
dismiss the impeachment trial. The respected West Virginia Democrat
had finally staked out a position. The end was perhaps in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, however, Republican leaders were scrambling to
diminish the significance of the announcement _ and prove that
Byrd's stature did not automatically grant him power to proclaim
the end of ``this sad and sorry time.'' And so, as with so many
other announcements during the impeachment process, the battle
lines remained drawn.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Phil Gramm, a Republican from Texas, quickly convened a
press conference after hearing the news, at the urging of Majority
Leader Trent Lott. Afterward, Gramm admitted Byrd posed a serious
threat to the lifespan of the trial, saying he ``carries a lot of
weight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the weight he carries is as a defendant of the process and
precedent,'' Gramm continued. ``And I think Senator Byrd, in this
case, is on the opposite side of both the process and the
precedent.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, a 41-year veteran of the Senate, issued a page-long
statement Friday afternoon announcing his intent to file the
motion, a routine legal formula that would prompt a Senate vote.
With 51 votes in favor of the motion, the case would then be
dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Although few Democrats expected to prevail in such a vote,
several said the division between the parties appeared to be
growing smaller Friday, and one Republican aide said the vote
``might be closer than everyone is expecting.'' Byrd's decision to
play a leading role _ particularly coming after his earlier
warnings that he would not be easily swayed by White House
influence _ bolstered that view even more.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy, who has long encouraged a swift
dismissal of the impeachment case, described Byrd's statement as
``very important.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's rather interesting that a few weeks ago, there
was considerable speculation whether Byrd would be the one
Democratic holdout for impeachment here,'' Kennedy said. ``I think
he has the respect of Republicans and Democrats for his loyalty to
the institution of the Senate and to the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, a strict interpreter of Senate rules who has gone as far
as banning a seeing-eye dog in the chamber, began discussing the
move with the Senate minority leader, Thomas A. Daschle of South
Dakota, on Thursday, an aide said. After Byrd issued his news
release Friday afternoon, he left the Senate floor and retreated to
his office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can obviously follow the floor action from his office,''
said a Byrd spokesman, Tom Gavin.
</P>
<P>
   By issuing the statement, Byrd not only set in motion the next
phase of the proceedings but also shed light on his own views of
the trial _ views that he has kept mostly to himself over the last
few weeks, even as other senators have held dueling news
conferences in the Capitol halls.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying out a longer trial, Byrd said, ``will only prolong and
deepen the divisive, bitter, and polarizing effect that this sorry
affair has visited upon our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan to make this motion not because I believe that the
president did no wrong,'' he wrote. ``In fact, I think he has
caused his family, his friends, and this nation great pain. I
believe he has weakened the already fragile public trust that has
been placed in his care. But I am convinced that the necessary
two-thirds for conviction are not there and that they are not
likely develop.''
</P>
<P>
   Revealing his own passion for public decorum, Byrd added that he
saw no need for witnesses, saying they would only ``foster more of
the same hallway press conferences and battle of press releases
that are contributing to the division of our parties and our
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have heard the public, and while it is clear that there is a
great rift of public opinion on this matter, there is also a
consensus that the nation is sorely in need of leadership and
healing,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Byrd's colleagues learned about the motion to dismiss
from one another. Minutes after the news reached the Senate floor,
Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a Democrat from New York, said he
was ``surprised.'' Senator Patrick Leahy, a Democrat from Vermont,
called it ``an interesting thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's 51 votes, that's the end of it,'' Leahy said.
``Certainly, he's well-respected on both sides, but ultimately,
everybody has to decide whether we've had enough and it's time to
bring this to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd spent the rest of the day in his office working on the
motion, Gavin said, and was expected to work with leaders in the
Democratic Party over the weekend to add the finishing touches
before filing the motion Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans continued to craft their response to the motion,
too. Senator Orrin Hatch, a Republican from Utah, said he did not
think Byrd is in a position to end the trial. And Representative
Henry Hyde, the lead prosecutor, issued his own statement urging
the Senate to ``reject this motion and continue an expeditious
search for the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We always knew that there would be a motion to dismiss in this
process,'' Hyde said. ``Now we know who will offer that motion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 2018EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5012 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-INVEST-ART-2     01-22 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-INVEST-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: a mania.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The recent Internet frenzy has come in two phases. The first
began on Oct. 8, after stock prices had fallen sharply on worries
about the turmoil in emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
   When the Federal Reserve cut interest rates three times in a
matter of weeks, investors began to believe the U.S. economy could
withstand any pressure. At about the same time, technology
bellwethers Intel and Microsoft reported robust earnings and said
they expected profits to continue to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that got technology stocks going, and they kept going,''
said Charles Morris, manager of the T. Rowe Price Science and
Technology Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said he has little doubt that the madness swept up stocks
like Cisco and Oracle. ``Everyone got caught up in the Internet
excitement, and that has dragged along all of the technology stocks
associated with it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks shifted into overdrive on Dec. 16, when a
little-known Wall Street analyst, Henry Blodget, stirred investors'
speculative juices with a seemingly outrageous prediction.
</P>
<P>
   Blodget, a 32-year-old financial analyst at CIBC Oppenheimer,
forecast that Amazon.com, whose shares were then trading for $242,
would reach $400 in 12 months. They surpassed that level in early
January, and the stock split.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Amazon shares have since fallen, they are up 52
percent since Blodget's report when adjusted for the split. But he,
too, says Internet stocks are ahead of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's a sector in history that's been valued
at these heights,'' he said. ``It's totally frightening.''
</P>
<P>
   Blodget said part of the reason for the rapid climb is that
there are only about four dozen ``pure play'' Internet stocks, and
fewer than 10 of those have moved much beyond the planning stage.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most promising are those like Yahoo, which operates an
entry site, or ``portal,'' to the Internet. Investors hope that the
services offered by portal companies, like free e-mail and
connections to shopping sites, inspire loyalty among users, which
the companies can capitalize on by selling advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Other big favorites are online shopping sites like Amazon.com,
which, although unprofitable so far, hopes to capture customer
loyalty as it expands.
</P>
<P>
   Because many young companies have relatively few shares
outstanding, big investors like pension and mutual funds have found
it hard to buy large stakes without significantly moving share
prices. Broadcast.com, for example, has 17 million shares
outstanding, but until this month only 2.5 million of those were
available to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   With an average of 900,000 of its shares trading each day, the
price rose exponentially, from less than $40 three months ago to
$289.50 this month, before falling back to $136.25 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   So limited is the supply of pure Internet investments, in fact,
that many institutional investors have tried to ferret out Internet
opportunities among elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   That is what caused people to bid up shares of CBS, which owned
50 percent of Marketwatch _ a stake reduced to 38 percent in the
recent public offering. In addition, CBS owns 10 percent of
Sportsline USA, which operates sports-related Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, a brokerage firm, rose
last week after it said it would make a public offering of shares
of its online brokerage unit. And since December, when Sotheby's
made clear its intention to use the Internet for some auctions, its
shares have risen 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy trading in stocks like Broadcast.com appears to be
driven by individual investors: the average size of Internet trades
is in the hundreds of shares, far smaller than the thousands
typical for companies like Microsoft or Intel, according to Birinyi
Associates, a research firm.
</P>
<P>
   And those individual investors are starting to feel a bit of
pain as some of the frenzy has subsided.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried, but I was kind of expecting this,'' said Nichols,
who recently graduated from Georgia Tech and took an accounting
job. ``But I'm in for the long term.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
