<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5013 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      01-22 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: CLINTON BEATS DOLE II  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK RICH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ Draft-dodging Bill Clinton beats World
War II hero Bob Dole at the polls. Philandering Bill Clinton
vanquishes Republican Puritans in the Senate. What's next? As our
marathon culture war reaches its catharsis in Washington, it may be
Hollywood's turn to provide the farcical coup de grace. The talk
here _ not for attribution, since no one wants to offend Steven
Spielberg _ is that ``Saving Private Ryan,'' the patriotic shoo-in
of the summer, might lose the Best Picture Oscar come spring to a
movie drenched in sex (and lies about sex) whose lovable hero
shamelessly cheats on the wife and kids he's left at home.
</P>
<P>
   The dark horse, of course, is ``Shakespeare in Love,'' in which
young Will forsakes Anne Hathaway for a young woman betrothed to
another man. In my unscientific survey of Academy voters on Golden
Globes Eve, there remains a minority that feels this little ``art''
movie has no chance because: (a) comedies rarely win Best Picture;
(b) Spielberg-Hanks is a local combination to rival Mother Teresa;
(c) the Academy's old guard loves the likes of ``Braveheart,'' and
(d) both New York and L.A. critics have given ``Ryan'' their top
award. But ever since New Year's, when Variety's front page
questioned the front-runner's invincibility, ``Shakespeare'' has
been gaining ground as the anti-``Ryan'' alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare's'' proponents argue that ``Ryan'' is ``20 great
minutes followed by disappointment,'' that the literary pedigree of
``Shakespeare'' appeals to Hollywood's grandiose cultural
self-image (``We like to impress the world with our aspirations and
loftiness''), and that the mogul behind ``Shakespeare,'' Harvey
Weinstein of Miramax, is ``like the Wehrmacht'' when staging an
Oscar campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But one likely Oscar nominee who is not connected with either of
these two movies _ and who is no fan of either Spielberg or
Weinstein _ feels that ``Shakespeare'' will win for cultural
reasons that transcend industry politics. ``I think people are a
little weary of the deadly earnest after this year in particular,''
he says. `` `Shakespeare' is fun, clever and has pretty people. It
says something uplifting about art and the human spirit. It
sparkles and bubbles.''
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea if he's right about how his peers may finally
vote. But I do think he's right about why this movie is proving a
surprise hit with audiences throughout the country. Though
``Shakespeare in Love'' may not be built for the ages as its
namesake's plays are, it's hard to imagine a more fitting balm for
America at this moment. After a full year of listening to
politicians and the media wallow maliciously in a sex scandal,
there's something cleansing, even exhilarating, about watching a
movie that celebrates eroticism by reconnecting it to poetry (not
Walt Whitman's), humor and love.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare'' comes down against both camps in our yearlong
battle over Monicagate. Yes, it celebrates an extramarital affair
facilitated by a Betty Currie-like Nurse, but it's the linking of
two romantic souls in bed in a fairyland 16th-century London, not
the tawdry gratifying of furtive body parts in the Oval Office. Yet
a villain of the piece is a purse-mouthed Elizabethan censor and
busybody who seems to combine equal parts of Kenneth Starr, Linda
Tripp and all the Sunday TV sermonizers.
</P>
<P>
   Up until now, the standard cultural take on the past year has
been the rise of what the writer John Gregory Dunne has aptly
labeled ``virtual patriotism.'' The nation's psychic antidote to
Clintonian sordidness, we've been told and told, is nostalgia for
World War II and the selfless (i.e., non-boomer) generation that
fought it, as captured in ``Ryan'' and best-selling books by
Stephen Ambrose and Tom Brokaw. But now, thanks to Henry Hyde's
cheesy exploitation of the war dead in his impeachment-trial
summation _ and the rhetorical counter-fire it prompted from
Charles Ruff and Dale Bumpers _ Omaha Beach has become another
tainted pawn in the capital's odious political discourse.
</P>
<P>
   The nonpartisan, sex-life-and-art-affirming ``Shakespeare in
Love'' arrived at just the right moment to capture ``Private
Ryan's'' fallen flag and take us about as far away from that soiled
Washington as a movie possibly can. Here in the capital of show
business, whose leaders cannot afford to ignore the public will as
politicians do, there is little doubt that that's where the country
wants to go.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
