<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5015 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV24-B     01-22 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV24-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RED FLAG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, January 24, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What was the significance of the single most headline-making
proposal in Bill Clinton's State of the Union address last week? I
refer, of course, to his recommendation that the government put
$700 billion into the stock market over the next 15 years as part
of a plan to put the Social Security system back on sound footing.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that this was a president whose proposal to
reorganize the health care system along somewhat similar lines _
with an expanded governmental role at its center _ produced the
1994 Republican landslide, it seemed like an incautious thing to
do.
</P>
<P>
   It was a little like waving a red flag at a herd of bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, Federal Reserve Board chairman Alan Greenspan, who
had already warned against the proposal when trial balloons were
floated, went boldly on the record in congressional testimony the
next day. ``I do not believe that it is politically feasible to
insulate such huge funds from government direction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Burton Malkiel, Princeton professor and author of ``A Random
Walk Down Wall Street,'' chimed in a couple of days later with a
summary judgment: ``A bad idea with unpredictable and probably
damaging consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   And Representative Bill Archer of Texas, chairman of the House
Ways and Means Committee, issued an immediate press release: ``No.
No. A thousand times no. If you thought a government takeover of
health care was bad, just wait until the government becomes an
owner of the nation's private companies.'' But the little red flag
may have been something quite other than it seemed. For one thing,
the president quickly glossed over it.
</P>
<P>
   His proposal to invest ``a small portion'' of the budget surplus
for the next 15 years in the private sector ``just as any private
or state government pension would do'' took up exactly one sentence
in the address.
</P>
<P>
   For another, moments later he spent two full paragraphs on a new
and little-noted suggestion: ``In addition to saving Social
Security and Medicare, I propose a new pension initiative for
retirement security in the 21st century. I propose that we use 11
percent of the surplus to establish Universal Savings Accounts _
USA accounts _ to give all Americans the means to save.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these new accounts, Americans can invest as much as they
choose, and receive funds to match a portion of their savings, with
extra help for those least able to save. USA accounts will help all
Americans to share in our nation's wealth, and enjoy a more secure
retirement,'' Clinton continued.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on here?
</P>
<P>
   The real reason for the pitch for a vastly expanded savings
system is Clinton's determination to head off a long-standing
Republican attempt to dismantle the 60-year-old Social Security
system in favor of individual accounts. His strategy appears aimed
at compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The deep political question at the heart of the dispute is
summed up perfectly in the names given to these competing visions
by their sponsors: Social Security vs. personal security. The
outcome envisaged by Clinton's address is both. Instead of
dismantling the famous ``three-legged stool'' of retirment benefits
_ Social Security, company plans, and private savings _ Clinton
wants to reinforce one leg to full strength and begin to beef up
the other.
</P>
<P>
   It was in January 1996 in San Francisco that Martin Feldstein
formally proposed privatizing Social Security from the pulpit of a
prestigious lecture series. A Harvard professor, Feldstein had
served as chairman of the Council of Economic Advisers under Ronald
Reagan; he was a frequent adviser to George Bush. His was the voice
of serious conservative economic thought.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Security system had a problem, Feldstein said: people
were living longer, there were more of them, and taxes would have
to rise significantly if benefits remained at current levels well
into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   The real problem, however, Feldstein said, was ``the low
implicit return'' that individuals received on the dollars that
they paid into the system. That could only be changed, he argued,
by changing the fiscal underpinnings of the system from a
pay-as-you-go system, in which taxes collected from workers went
directly to retirees, into funded program in which individual
accounts were invested in stocks and bonds, like any private
retirement program.
</P>
<P>
   It was an election year. Republicans of all sorts were
maneuvering for advantage in the race against Clinton. Primary
challengers Steve Forbes and Lamar Alexander were jockeying to
force Bob Dole to abandon his promise to balance the budget and,
instead, embrace a tax cut. Feldstein's proposal became a stock
promise in the Republicans' campaign.
</P>
<P>
   One presidential and one congressional election later, with the
political winds having moderated (and now threatening to shift
altogether), Feldstein recently offered a modified version of his
earlier plan. Speaking to what must be presumed to be the
mainstream of the Republican Party, Feldstein said he still urged
the creation of Personal Retirement Accounts in which the
government would park some portion of the Social Security taxes it
collects.
</P>
<P>
   But he reckoned such a start-up would serve only as a supplement
to the current system, frozen at current levels. Projected
surpluses could be used after all to beef up the Social Security
Trust Fund, as Clinton wished.
</P>
<P>
   And the proceeds of investments of the new retirement accounts
could be used to meet whatever shortfall might occur in order to
maintain total retirement benefits at their current levels for the
next 75 years.
</P>
<P>
   That was the political background to Clinton's proposal
Wednesday night to create a system of ``universal savings
accounts.'' Among defenders of Social Security, the fear all along
has been that individual accounts, were they to be established,
might quickly become rival contenders for resources. So a good deal
of thought went into making the new program sound as different as
possible from the existing one.
</P>
<P>
   What will happen now? It's anybody's guess whether the
Republicans will fold their hand on the Social Security issue and
go along with Clinton's proposal _ after all, their numbers are not
likely to grow in the next Congress _ or engage in the bitter
competition among themselves that has been the hallmark of the
impeachment debate.
</P>
<P>
   But in either event, you can bet that the idea that the
government should invest in stocks will go nowhere. The red flag is
a bargaining chip, designed to be traded away.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion by wires as the lede at about 70.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
