<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5018 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABORTION-ROE-ART-NYT &LR;      01-22 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-ROE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO SIDES OF ABORTION ISSUE HOLD RALLIES ON ROE ANNIVERSARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., N.J., Ohio)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As an estimated 100,000 abortion opponents paraded
past the White House Friday calling President and Mrs. Clinton
murderers, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton denounced violence
against abortion practitioners as ``domestic terrorism'' and said
the Clinton administration would propose spending $4.5 million in
next year's federal budget to improve safety at abortion clinics.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last 10 years there have been 7 murders, 38 bombings,
146 cases of arson and 733 cases of vandalism,'' she said in a
speech marking the 26th anniversary of the legalization of
abortion. ``Wherever one stands on the issue of abortion, surely we
should all agree that when doctors are murdered, clinics are
bombed, splattered with acid or set on fire, this is not free
expression. This is domestic terrorism and it's got to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said the federal money would be given to vulnerable
clinics for extra security measures, including proper lighting,
motion detectors, closed-circuit cameras, security systems and
bullet-resistant windows. Under the proposal, the Justice
Department would make security assessments and make the upgrades
available to clinics deemed to be at high risk of violence.
</P>
<P>
   As the first lady spoke, abortion opponents swarmed across
Washington in their annual demonstration against Roe versus Wade,
the 1973 Supreme Court decision that made abortion legal. About
7,000 attended a ``Mass for Life'' Thursday night and camped out at
local churches and at Catholic University. They joined tens of
thousands of others for the annual March for Life rally Friday on
the Ellipse behind the White House, then marched to the Supreme
Court and Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the trip to be with the others _ hoping, praying,
expressing together,'' said Saundara Innhoff, 42, of Logan, Ohio,
on her way from St. Matthew's Cathedral to the Elipse.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Mrs. Clinton's remarks on the need for extra
security at clinics, Richard Doerflinger, a spokesman for pro-life
activities at the National Conference of Catholic Bishops, said:
``There have been far more women killed in abortionist clinics than
abortionists shot.'' He cited a recent article in the Arizona
Republic that said six women had died in a cross-country chain of
abortion clinics, including one in Phoenix, owned by a New York
doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Doerflinger said, violence against abortion workers
was relatively rare compared with assaults on other health-care
workers, particularly in emergency rooms. ``There are a couple of
senseless and tragic killings that happened at abortion clinics,
but this is a very tiny part of the problem that all medical people
face,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the Clinton administration's budget proposal was
not a proper use of federal money. ``Giving $4.5 million to an
already lucrative industry to do what it will no doubt do anyway
with its own funds is a strange budget priority,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Smith, R-N.J., who is a leading abortion
opponent in Congress, said to those gathered on the Ellipse:
``Those who fashion themselves as advocates of children and
pro-women while promoting or even acquiescing to abortion are
either hypocrites or are living in an unhealthy state of denial.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who every year tries to block federal money for family
planning programs overseas, referred to the Clintons by name,
adding: ``The scandals that have rocked the White House pale to
near insignificance when compared to the anti-child policies so
methodically pursued by our abortion president and his
administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who support abortion rights have been among Clinton's most
loyal political allies throughout the year-long Lewinsky scandal.
And they made up a good part of the audience of more than 2,000
people whom Mrs. Clinton addressed Friday at a luncheon sponsored
by the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League.
</P>
<P>
   With constant references to clinic violence setting the tone for
the event, Mrs. Clinton spoke gravely and at length, with none of
the cheerleader spirit that has marked so many of her recent
political outings.
</P>
<P>
   She said the administration was doing everything it could think
of, including promoting abstinence programs, to reduce teen
pregnancy and the need for abortion. And she said that boys and men
needed to learn to be responsible for their acts, saying they
should look in the mirror before imagining their ``sexual prowess''
and understand what it means to take care of a child.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said that clinic violence, including the October
killing of Dr. Barnett Slepian, an abortion doctor in suburban
Buffalo, N.Y., should inspire abortion-rights advocates to stand
firm ``in our efforts to make sure that doctors are trained and
available to provide safe and comprehensive health care to women
all over our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the federal money would be given to vulnerable clinics
for extra security measures, including proper lighting, motion
detectors, closed-circuit cameras, security systems and
bullet-resistant windows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
