<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5021 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NISSAN-DAIMLER-255&AMP;AD     01-22 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NISSAN-DAIMLER-255&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAIMLERCHRYSLER IS NONCOMMITTAL ON ANY NISSAN DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
 (bl)  
By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ A much-anticipated news conference here Friday by
DaimlerChrysler AG failed to clarify the future of the debt-laden
Nissan Motor Co. or its more-troubled truck-making affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   In a news release, DaimlerChrysler said only that its two
chairmen, Juergen Schrempp and Robert Eaton, met with Nissan Motor
President Yoshikazu Hanawa on Thursday and that they had
``constructive discussions'' regarding the truck affiliate, Nissan
Diesel Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese automaker, with $20 billion in debt, has embarked
this month on an unusual campaign to sell itself. DaimlerChrysler
had already been holding talks with Nissan Motor about the
disposition of Nissan Diesel.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's DaimlerChrysler statement said only that the executives
had ``explored possible cooperation projects,'' a wording that
suggested DaimlerChrysler might be seeking a relationship with
Nissan Motor that was somewhat less involved than taking an equity
stake in the company or buying it outright.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to clarify the phrase, Schrempp said, ``I guess it leaves
everything open.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Nissan Diesel, its fate lies as much in the hands of its
banks, which are considering a proposal to forgive some of the
truck maker's debt, as in Nissan Motor's.
</P>
<P>
   The DaimlerChrysler statement was issued shortly before trading
on Tokyo's stock market ended for the day. Nissan's shares closed
with a gain of 15 yen, at 430 yen, or $3.77. They have increased 24
percent this year. Nissan Diesel's shares gained 4 yen Friday, to
229 yen.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange on Friday, DaimlerChrysler fell
$1.6875, to $103.9375.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Schrempp and Eaton spent much of the news conference avoiding
questions about Nissan and being cryptic. One Japanese reporter
even suggested that the Tokyo stock market would plummet if they
persisted in being so cagey.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the two of us are playing chess and I tell you about my
next two or three moves,'' Schrempp replied in answer to one of the
questions, ``I'd never have a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Eaton, he stuck to the script, saying, ``Once again, we
will have no further comment on Nissan and Nissan Diesel other than
what is in the press release.''
</P>
<P>
   Schrempp also tartly noted that if there had been leaks about
the Daimler-Chrysler merger before it was announced last May, there
might not have been a merger. Rumors about Nissan Motor have been
rampant for months.
</P>
<P>
   But the two executives did make clear their designs on Asia,
which is the Achilles' heel of the global vehicle empire they are
trying to build. DaimlerChrysler aims to derive 20 percent to 25
percent of its revenue from Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Schrempp said there were two necessary elements to being a
successful transportation company now: covering a range of
automotive products and having exports to and manufacturing in all
markets. He outlined three possible avenues of expansion in Asia:
through organic growth, purchase of an equity stake in another
company or an outright acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the difference is in the timing,'' he said. ``Our only
problem is that we are very impatient.''
</P>
<P>
   That suggests that DaimlerChrysler will continue to be
aggressive here, whether its intended prey is ultimately Nissan or
not. Eaton also met with Katsuhiko Kawasoe, the president of
Mitsubishi Motors Corp., although he sought to portray the meeting
as a courtesy he would extend to any partner of DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi Motors and Chrysler have had a long relationship:
Chrysler sells engines to the Japanese car company and Mitsubishi
makes Chrysler cars at a plant in Normal, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts and investors have wondered why DaimlerChrysler
has not shown more apparent interest in Mitsubishi, whose truck
making unit is considered superior to Nissan Diesel. Although
Mitsubishi's debt levels are higher than Nissan's, outweighing
equity by more than five times, its condition is considered less
critical because it enjoys the support of the Mitsubishi keiretsu,
the cluster of Mitsubishi companies and affiliates that includes
the Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi, Japan's largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi thus does not have to sell in a fire sale, which may
be one reason why DaimlerChrysler prefers to flirt with Nissan
Diesel. But Nissan Diesel's banks will be hard pressed to forgive
debt.
</P>
<P>
   The Industrial Bank of Japan, one of its main lenders, suffered
a ratings downgrade Friday. Moody's Investors Service lowered the
Industrial Bank's long-term deposit rating and its financial
strength rating, reflecting a deterioration of asset quality and
capital. Fuji Bank, Nissan Diesel's other bank, is also weak. In
fact, Nissan Motor, which is part of the keiretsu clustered around
Industrial Bank and Fuji, is providing a 100 million yen cash
infusion to Fuji to shore up the bank's capital base.
</P>
<P>
   The car company, meanwhile, is grappling with $24 billion in
debt. If Nissan sold all of its shares at current market prices, it
could repay less than half of its outstanding debt, which makes
debt forgiveness of some sort a necessity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
