<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0391 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5026 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-JUMAINE23-COX     01-22 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-JUMAINE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jones a shooting star with a bright future
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ It was a bright, clear and stifling Sunday, like
most summer days in the south Georgia town of Camilla, and Rebecca
Clayton showed up early for church. She was eager to introduce a
new addition to her family, her ``baby,'' to the close-knit
congregation of Oak Grove Missionary Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Jumaine Lanard Jones was 13 years old then and
already stood 6 feet 3. He was still a baby to his ``Auntie,'' and
she was going to make sure his first days in Camilla started out
the right way.
</P>
<P>
   It was the beginning of a worship ritual that would repeat
itself every weekend for the next five years. It was there at
church that Rufus McDuffie, basketball coach at Mitchell-Baker High
School, first met Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``His aunt brought him over and introduced him to me,'' McDuffie
recalled. ``She said, `I've got you a basketball player, coach.' I
looked and saw this tall, skinny kid, skinny as a rail. I said, `I
don't know about that, but we'll see what we can do.'''
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, people are still seeing what they can do with
Jones. Only now, as Jones is a star power forward for the
University of Georgia, it's the Bulldogs' opponents that are at a
loss for what to do with him.
</P>
<P>
   Still just a sophomore, Jones will start his 53rd game for the
Bulldogs when they play Mississippi this afternoon in Oxford, Miss.
Now 6-7, the 210-pound Jones enters today's game as the SEC's
leading scorer (19.7 per game), third-leading rebounder (9.3) and
No. 1 threat to make the jump to the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jumaine Jones is a problem for anybody in the country (to
defend),'' said Arkansas coach Nolan Richardson, whose team was
victimized for 25 points by Jones last weekend. ``He's going to be
a first-rounder one day. ... He's on a different plateau.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones' ability to score has a lot to do with what McDuffie did
in the months and years that followed that Sunday-morning
introduction. When he arrived in Camilla, Jones already possessed a
deadly arsenal of post moves and could dunk the ball with ease. But
taking note of Jones' wiriness and being unsure of his eventual
height, McDuffie encouraged Jones to take his game outside the
paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw him as a ninth-grader, I never dreamed he'd turn
into the player he has,'' McDuffie said. ``He didn't impress me
that much. He was real skinny and he couldn't shoot. I told him,
'If you're going to go to college, you're going to have to be able
to play outside,' so we worked on his outside shot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach McDuffie used to make me shoot for hours in the gym,''
Jones said. ``I'd be like, 'Come on, not today, coach.' But he'd
say, 'Get out there and start shooting.' ``
</P>
<P>
   That Jones eventually grew four more inches was a bonus. It
wasn't long before his outside game caught up with his inside game
and, soon, he was an offensive force. As a junior, Jones began to
produce gaudy numbers _ 28.5 points, 14 rebounds a game _ and
back-to-back trips to the state Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   McDuffie's stern guidance was a welcomed addition in Jones'
life. He never knew his real father, who left when Jones was 3, and
Clayton's husband had died before Jones came to live with her in
Camilla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach McDuffie was definitely a father figure to me,'' Jones
said. ``I spent a lot of weekends with him. His daughters are like
sisters to me, and I hung out with his son, Kevin. He was always
concerned about what I did in school, although I didn't always
appreciate it then.''
</P>
<P>
   Just the fact that McDuffie had Jones to work with was somewhat
of a miracle. Jones was in Camilla living with his aunt only
because his mother, Mae Jones, wanted him to escape his Cocoa,
Fla., neighborhood. Although Jumaine was still in middle school,
his mother recognized the signs that her son could be heading down
the wrong path if his life didn't undergo radical change.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of crime in my neighborhood, and a lot of my
friends in middle school were getting into a lot of trouble,''
Jones explained. ``My mother didn't want me to be around that. She
figured if you hang around people, sooner or later you were going
to get into trouble, too. I always knew right from wrong, but she
was concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones didn't go kicking and screaming to Camilla, a small
farming town located in South Georgia. In fact, he was all for the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved Camilla because I used to come stay with my Auntie
every summer,'' Jones said. ``She was one of my favorite aunts, and
I always loved staying with her and playing with all my cousins.
When I was young, I was always asking my mom if I could stay the
whole year.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones' basketball abilities soon had college recruiters calling.
And while he had his choice of high-profile programs to join _
Kentucky, Connecticut and N.C. State, to name a few _ he said he
always wanted to go to Georgia. That Tubby Smith had the Bulldogs
in the national limelight didn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   So Jones signed with the Bulldogs in the early period, December
of his senior year. He briefly reconsidered his decision when Smith
left for Kentucky. But with McDuffie's encouragement, he honored
his original commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Tubby left, a lot of people were mad at him,'' Jones
said. ``I figured he got recruited just like I got recruited, and I
couldn't be upset with him because of that. Coach (Ron) Jirsa had
been recruiting me all along, and we had a close relationship. So I
figured I couldn't go wrong sticking with Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   After a promising beginning his freshman year, Jones ground
through a bumpy period in SEC play before asserting himself as one
of the league's best young players the latter half of the season.
He averaged 14.7 points and 8.5 rebounds a game and was named
co-freshman of the year with Tennessee guard Tony Harris.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Jones has been even better. He's been limited to
single-digit scoring just three times all season and has recorded
``double-doubles'' in points and rebounds 10 times.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers think that Jones' best basketball is ahead of
him. And many of them say he's not ready to make an early leap to
the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still developing,'' Kentucky's Smith said. ``He needs to
learn a lot about the game. He's got the work ethic and attitude,
so it's just a matter of time....I think he's a player who will be
able to play at the next level. When? I don't know. That's a big,
big step from college to (the) professional level.''
</P>
<P>
   Jirsa also says that Jones is ``a year or two'' away from being
ready for the pros and cites his star's need to improve his
ball-handling skills and perimeter defense. But he also warns that
the NBA might not wait that long to come calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tend to draft on potential rather than where a player is
at any given moment,'' Jirsa said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones does not disguise his desire to play in the NBA but says
he is concerned only about the Bulldogs now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just worried about my team right now,'' Jones said. ``I'll
talk to coach Jirsa and my family about it after the season....
Making it to the NBA is one of my dreams. You can never pay back
your family, but I'd like to help take care of them after all the
years they've taken care of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
