<HEADER>
A5027 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHL-OLYMPICS23-CO     01-22 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-OLYMPICS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Olympic play main topic of governors' meeting
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ One year ago, the NHL devised a ``North America
vs. World'' format for its All-Star Game in an attempt to tease
fans' interest before the Winter Olympics in Nagano, Japan. As it
turned out, a rebroadcast of ``Animal House'' would have been a
more appropriate prelude to the U.S. team's performance.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend in Tampa, the NHL will try again with its
us-against-them format. The next Olympics is three years away.
Whether there will be a next Olympics for NHL players will be
discussed today, when the league's Board of Governors meet in a
Tampa hotel.
</P>
<P>
   While the NHL's global-marketing heads want the league to give
the Olympics one more try in 2002, given the prime-time stage in
Salt Lake City, team executives are less enthusiastic, because NBC
has not guaranteed how much television coverage hockey will get.
NHL commissioner Gary Bettman was expected to speak with network
chairman Dick Ebersol before addressing the owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feelings are mixed on the subject,'' Florida Panthers
president Bill Torrey said. ``The whole Olympic thing has taken on
another color with recent developments (of corruption within the
IOC). Do we want to get involved right now? And the whole reason
we'd be doing this would be for more exposure. But (if) we're not
going to get it, maybe we need to move on to other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Torrey prefers sending amateurs to the Games, saying, ``In 1980
when the U.S. upset the Russians, it did so much to increase
interest in the game. Kids wanted to learn the game. But if we go
on using pros, all of that gets removed. It's not the same feeling
with pro players.''
</P>
<P>
   Thrashers general manager Don Waddell said, ``If the next
Olympics were anywhere else, they probably would have gassed it by
now. But because they're in the U.S., this could be the last chance
to get it major exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   League officials are not expected to make a final decision
today, but the situation could be clarified. It will be the last
time the owners will be together until June. When they last met, in
early December, Bettman said a decision would be made in ``60 to 90
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's meeting is ``just another step in the decision-making
process,'' NHL spokesman Frank Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend will include a skills competition and Heroes of
Hockey game Saturday night at the Ice Palace, with the All-Star
Game Sunday. Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock will coach the North
American team and Buffalo's Lindy Ruff will be behind the World's
bench.
</P>
<P>
   While the league prefers to market its star forwards _ Wayne
Gretzky, Eric Lindros, Paul Kariya, et al. _ goalies continue to be
the story this season, with only 5.3 goals per game being scored.
Buffalo's Dominik Hasek, who starts for the World, already has
eight shutouts, a goals-against average of 1.86 and a saves
percentage of .939.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there's a team that has a weak goaltender
anymore,'' Ruff said. ``There used to be games you could go in and
say, `This is a game we can win.' But now you can go into any
building, and there's a chance you're going to get beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek's spectacular play aside, the NHL would prefer Sunday's
game have a 9-8 score than 2-1. Better for marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Yzerman out
</P>
<P>
   After suffering a broken nose and a cut when he was hit in the
face by a puck Thursday night, Detroit forward Steve Yzerman was
dropped from Sunday's North American team and replaced by Los
Angeles left wing Luc Robitaille. Robitaille is third in the league
in goals with 25 and recently passed 500 goals in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Ground zero
</P>
<P>
   North Americans coach Hitchcock will be trying to break a career
slump in All-Star games. Hitchcock is 0-11 as a coach in All-Star
games at the amateur and pro level. Last year, he coached the World
team in a 8-7 loss. ``Last year was the closest I've come,'' he
said. ``If I don't coach this team to a win, I think I'll coach the
media team next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Briefly ...
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's ``Heroes of Hockey'' old-timers game does not include
any former Atlanta Flames. But the ``NHL Heroes'' team has the
father-sons trio of Gordie, Mark and Marty Howe. ... It shouldn't
come as a surprise that Phil Esposito is not in the old-timers
game. Esposito was fired as Tampa Bay's general manager this
season, and his presence would have been awkward, to say the least.
... John Cullen, who made a comeback from non-Hodgkin's lymphoma
this season, only to be demoted to the minors by the Lightning,
will play in the old-timers game. After a stint in the minors, he
returned to Tampa Bay as an assistant coach. ... In an attempt to
improve coverage, the league's broadcasting department is freezing
13 microphones just under the ice surface at the Ice Palace for
ESPN and Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
