<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5028 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ORGAN-SHORTAGE-ART     01-22 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ORGAN-SHORTAGE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVAILABILITY OF DONOR ORGANS MYSTERIOUSLY PLUNGES IN NEW YORK AREA
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The number of vital organs being donated in the New
York area has fallen so precipitously in recent weeks that
transplant programs across the region have virtually ground to a
halt, hospital officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage of livers, hearts, kidneys and other organs has
been a growing national problem in recent years, in part because of
falling murder rates and improved auto safety. But officials said
Friday that since the beginning of the year, the supply in New York
had taken a severe, and still unexplained, downward turn.
</P>
<P>
   The gap between supply and demand tends to be greater in New
York than in the nation as a whole. But since the start of the
year, there have been just nine organs donated in the New York
region; last year at this time, there had been 22 donors, which is
about average, said Denise Payne, executive director of the New
York Organ Donor Network, which procures and distributes organs in
New York, Long Island and five counties in the north. ``If it keeps
on like this for months, we would be concerned,'' she said, adding
that she knew of no similar sudden problems in other parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Several New York doctors said Friday that there had already been
a great deal of suffering as a result of this shortage.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last 5 or 10 years, I cannot remember such a dearth of
organs,'' said Dr. Lewis Teperman, the director of transplantation
of New York University Hospital, which has done no liver
transplants this month. In the last few days, he said, two patients
have died at New York University Hospital alone, and another woman
is beyond hope, he said, as others await donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is so frustrating is that we have here one of the best
survival rates in country with transplants,'' Teperman said. ``But
I can't help them if I don't get an organ. This should be a time of
good news, and instead I am pronouncing people dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Among heart specialists, there are similar worries. ``Clearly
hearttransplantation at this point in time is the pinnacle of
treatment,'' said Dr. Nillo Edwards, who heads the heart transplant
program at New York Presbyterian Hospital. ``However, having more
organs available is clearly what we need today.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last five years, the nation's supply of donated organs
has gone up a few hundred each year. At the same time, demand has
risen twelvefold, said Dr. Ronald Busuttil, chief of liver
transplantation at the University of California at Los Angeles
School of Medicine and president-elect of the American Society of
Transplant Surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   The rising demand is primarily the result of two factors: the
aging of the population and improved technology that has made many
more people candidates for transplants.
</P>
<P>
   With livers, for instance, the types of people who just a few
years ago were not usually transplant candidates _ alcoholics,
people with tumors, those with hepatitis B _ now are strong
candidates. Further, a national epidemic of hepatitis C has
increased the need for liver donations by more than 500 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The vastly improved transplant capability is the same for all
other organs. Further, while people over 50 were rarely candidates
a few years ago, now people well into their 60s are getting donated
organs, and as the population ages, there will be even more need.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this rising demand, though, supply has barely increased.
The reasons are many _ a decrease in the number of deaths in car
crashes because of air bags, lower rates of violent crime and a
distinct lack of public awareness efforts. Further, as the
population ages, there are fewer young people, who tend to make the
best donor candidates, to contribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't consider making a donation,'' said Busuttil.
``And consent rates are low, which may be due to the way families
are approached. Also, people who would be potential donors are not
identified.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that in areas where donations are extremely low,
procurement centers may not be working effectively.
</P>
<P>
   In response, federal officials, led by Health and Human Services
Secretary Donna Shalala, want to change the current system of organ
matching, in which people needing organs draw from their region.
They want to replace it with a national system in which those who
are most needy get organs first.
</P>
<P>
   This effort, which is controversial among donor expertise
groups, would be made in large part to correct a wide disparity
among states. Indeed, the United Network of Organ Sharing released
a report this week that found that waits varied wildly between
states, saying that in New York City, patients wait 10 times as
long as in other urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   Donations are lower in New York for a variety of factors as
well, said Ms. Payne. Among them are a higher number of people with
transmittable diseases like AIDS, a dramatic decrease in violent
crime and rise in emergency room technology and success rates.
``The decrease in violent crime is wonderful for society,'' said
Ms. Payne. ``But it has impacted our donor pools.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Giovanna Frontino waited at the bedside of her niece,
Antonia Verde, at New York University Hospital, praying for a liver
to arrive. Ms. Verde, 25, has a blood illness diagnosed when she
was three months old that has required almost monthly transfusions
throughout her life. As a result, doctors say, iron overload has
destroyed her liver, and she has been in the intensive-care unit of
the hospital for two weeks awaiting a donor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so hard,'' said Ms. Frontino. ``Her mother never leaves
the hospital. This has made me so much more aware of the problem
with organ donors. So we are waiting and waiting. But we are
optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   There was less optimism a few beds away, where Gerard Jean-Louis
sat at the bedside of his wife, Antoine, 63, whose liver has been
destroyed by hepatitis. ``They say it is too late for her now,''
said Jean-Louis. ``The doctor said there is nothing they can do
because they keep on looking for the organ.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
