<HEADLINE>
STOCK MARKET LOWER AS IBM FALLS SHARPLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The stock market finished lower Friday as IBM fell
sharply after mainframe sales in the fourth quarter disappointed
some investors. The economic crisis in Brazil also was bothersome,
helping send bank and financial stocks lower.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the selling, investors did not seem to extrapolate the
problems at IBM to the expectation of poor results elsewhere. And
that is why although the Dow Jones industrial average, which
includes IBM, dropped 1.6 percent, the rest of the major stock
indexes were down far less.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of tech companies have already reported good
earnings,'' said Douglas Cliggott, a U.S. equity strategist at J.P.
Morgan Securities. ``So the market said tech was strong and a
couple of disappointing revenue or earnings numbers have not led to
widespread selling.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a volatile day of trading, however. The market opened
down across the board, with the Dow 175 points, or 1.9 percent,
lower by 10:30 a.m., while the Nasdaq index dropped 40 points, or
1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the fall in IBM, market-opening declines in
Amazon.com, Yahoo, Excite and other Internet stocks set a gloomy
tone early. The selling came on top of sharp losses Thursday and a
general Internet selloff for the last week and a half.
</P>
<P>
   At their intraday lows Friday, Yahoo was 43 percent below its
intraday high of 445 on Jan. 11 and Amazon.com was 50 percent below
its high of 199 1/8 on Jan. 8. But the concerted selling recently
seemed to get prices back down to levels that attracted investors
again, and these and other Internet stocks turned around to end the
day higher.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo, which fell 12 at the opening, rallied to close up 21 at
286, and Amazon.com rose 17, to 123, after beginning the day down 7
5/8. This Internet turnaround helped the Nasdaq rebound. It was up
20 points at one moment but finished the day down just 5.84 points,
or one-quarter of a percentage point, at 2,338.88.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index declined 9.97 points, to
1,225.19.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow finished down 143.41 points at 9,120.67. It had rallied
in the early afternoon but then fell the rest of the day.
</P>
<P>
   IBM, which is the heaviest-weighted stock in the Dow, accounted
for almost half of the day's decline as it plunged 17\, or 8.76
percent, to 179}. Although IBM's fourth-quarter earnings, which
were released after the market closed Thursday, beat expectations,
analysts said that they were disappointed that both mainframe and
server sales were down because IBM cut prices to compete with
Hitachi and Fujitsu.
</P>
<P>
   Other stocks leading the Dow lower were American Express and
J.P. Morgan, which weaken when the crisis in Brazil looks worse,
and the Dow's two drug stocks, Merck and Johnson &AMP; Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   In the bond market, concerns about Brazil helped push prices
higher as some investors sought the safety of Treasury securities.
Brazil's Bovespa index dropped 1.8 percent, and the country's
currency, the real, continued to decline in value. It is now down
29.4 percent since it was allowed to trade freely last week.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year bond rose 28/32, to 102 22/32. The
bond's yield, which moves in the opposite direction from the price,
fell to 5.07 percent, from 5.13 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
