A5030 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLBROOKE-LOBBYING-NY     01-22 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLBROOKE-LOBBYING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON U.N. NOMINEE DENIES HE VIOLATED LOBBYING LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
  mk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Richard Holbrooke, President Clinton's choice to be
the top American diplomat at the United Nations, denied Friday that
he had violated federal lobbying laws, the issue that has held up
his nomination since the summer.
</P>
<P>
   In his first public comments since the disclosure that he was
negotiating with the Justice Department over its investigation of
an alleged ethics violation, Holbrooke did not describe the terms
of a possible settlement, but said he was confident that the
inquiry would end soon.
</P>
<P>
   He said his lawyers were involved in ``intense discussion'' with
the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Department officials said a settlement with Holbrooke, the
architect of the Dayton peace settlement of 1995 that ended the war
in Bosnia, would probably be reached within days. The officials
said he had been asked to pay a civil penalty, but they would not
discuss the amount.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials and former American diplomats say the
investigation has centered on allegations that Holbrooke violated
lobbying laws in his contacts with the U.S. ambassador in South
Korea in early 1996. That was soon after he had resigned from the
State Department to become an investment banker in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to going before the Senate for what I'm sure
will be a tough but fair confirmation process, and I hope to serve
soon at the U.N.,'' he said in an interview on the ABC News program
``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   After resigning from the State Department in 1996 to join the
investment banking company Credit Suisse First Boston, Holbrooke
was named a part-time Clinton administration envoy to the Balkans
and to Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The so-called contacts that I had in the three years since I
left the State Department with government officials have all been
in my capacity as a senior adviser, official, to the secretary of
state,'' he said. ``So any contacts I had _ any contacts I had _
were under that hat and did not violate any laws.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Holbrooke said the veteran diplomat was not
available for an interview and had no comment beyond his remarks on
television.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials say Holbrooke has been accused by Justice
Department prosecutors of having committed a civil violation of
lobbying laws when he contacted Ambassador James Laney in South
Korea soon after resigning as assistant secretary of state for
European and Canadian affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Laney, who has since left the post, said in an interview this
week that Holbrooke had contacted him in a letter on the banking
company's stationery, seeking his help in obtaining an appointment
with president Kim Young-sam during a South Korean trip that
Holbrooke planned to take that spring.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting never took place, although Laney did sponsor a
luncheon for Holbrooke and a handful of senior South Korean
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said prosecutors in the Justice Department's public
integrity division believed the contacts with the ambassador
amounted to a violation of laws limiting lobbying contacts by
former government officials with their former colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Laney and another senior American diplomat, Winston Lord, the
former assistant secretary of state for East Asia, have insisted
that Holbrooke did nothing wrong in contacting the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Lord has said that when Holbrooke resigned from the State
Department in 1996, he asked Holbrooke to remain in contact with
State Department officials as he traveled through Asia and to meet
with Asian leaders to discuss diplomatic developments in the
Balkans and elsewhere in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Lord and Laney, who have both been interviewed by the Justice
Department, agreed that Holbrooke could have easily set up his own
meetings with senior officials in South Korea without the embassy's
help, especially after he gained worldwide celebrity in 1995 as a
result of the Dayton peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   They said his contacts with Laney had been a simple courtesy to
the ambassador and to the embassy. ``Given his stature, Dick didn't
need Laney's help to see anyone,'' Lord said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
