<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0396 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5033 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GORES24-COX     01-22 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GORES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Jan. 24, 1999
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Bob Deans
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nibbling on fried chicken in the holding room of a
Buffalo hockey arena in winter isn't everyone's idea of a party.
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton celebrated the sixth anniversary of his
presidency last Wednesday, though, it wasn't the setting that
crystallized the moment quite so much as the company.
</P>
<P>
   For there he was, in snow-covered Buffalo, N.Y., basking in the
support of his closest confidants and political soulmates _ First
Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and Gore's
ebullient wife Tipper.
</P>
<P>
   As they stepped into the Marine Midland Arena to the thunderous
cheers of some 21,000 fans, said Gore, ''All four of us just gasped
at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   In their singular gasp, Bill and Hillary, Tipper and Al, two
very different couples joined at the political hip, might well have
expressed the astonishment of the nation at the twists and turns of
what has been, by any measure, a breathtaking year.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, through long months of a sex and deception scandal that
may finally be nearing an end, the First Foursome has survived the
strains remarkably intact, without a moment's ill-will _ publicly
at least _ expressed or implied.
</P>
<P>
   Seated side by side across the flag-bedecked dais in Buffalo
last week, exchanging compliments at the podium and hugs all
around, the four baby boomers sent a message of reassurance to the
American public as powerful in its own way as the politically
defiant State of the Union address Clinton had delivered the night
before.
</P>
<P>
   ''They looked great together,'' said Gettysburg College
presidential expert Shirley Anne Warshaw.
</P>
<P>
   ''It shows solidarity in the administration, it shows two
families connected,'' she said. ''That's what this president needs
to convey to the American public, that 'I may have strayed in my
marriage, but I'm committed to my family and committed to family
values in general.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lest the symbolism escape notice, Clinton himself drove home the
point.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think you could see, you know, that Tipper and Al and
Hillary and I, we are sort of like a big family,'' Clinton gushed.
''We like going places together...We work together. And we have
tried to model what we want America to do.''
</P>
<P>
   A family role model isn't the first thing that comes to mind for
many Americans at the mention of Clinton's name.
</P>
<P>
   A year-long investigation into his relationship with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky and his efforts to deceive the
public about it led the House to impeach him last month on charges
of perjury and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   And no one would suggest that the backing of his closest allies
has enabled Clinton to erase the stain he's left on his own legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''They obviously can't eclipse this whole impeachment thing,''
said Boston University presidential historian Robert Dallek.
''They're certainly not going to eclipse it in the history books.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Senate prepares to weigh the impeachment charges this
week, however, in the light of Clinton's stunning popularity, it's
clear the reflected stability and fire-tested loyalty of the Gore
family, and the steadfast support of Mrs. Clinton, have stood
Clinton extremely well in his efforts to persuade Americans to put
the matter behind them.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly helpful, Warshaw said, has been the public backing
of Mrs. Gore, an effervescent mother of four who burnished her own
family-values image a decade ago with her crusade against vulgar
pop song lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   ''She is both politically important and also she's a very
educated, strong woman,'' said Warshaw, who's newest book, ''Keys
to Power: Managing the Presidency,'' is due out this spring.
''She's a soccer mom, she's all of those women the president wants
to cultivate, and she's behind the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the endorsement of the first lady, who gets
sustained ovations wherever she speaks, and in Buffalo was hailed
as a potential U.S. Senate candidate in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ''We love you,'' one man hollered as Mrs. Clinton took the
podium, in a cheer that seemed to echo the sentiments of the 67
percent of Americans whose support she enjoys _ up from an all-time
low of 48 percent in September 1994, following her ill-fated
efforts to reshape the health care industry.
</P>
<P>
   ''That just suggests that what she's been doing, which is
standing by her husband, corresponds with what the public thinks
she should do,'' said Frank Newport, editor in chief of the Gallup
Poll, the Princeton, N.J., public opinion firm that provided the
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   The message to the public, said Warshaw, is clear.
</P>
<P>
   ''It represents that, if these people _ people both politically
and personally closest to him _ can forgive him his indiscretions,
then surely the American people can forgive him,'' she said. ''It's
a terrific image.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Gore nor Mrs. Clinton, moreover, appears to be paying a
political price for helping to prop up Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton credits his wife's advocacy on issues like education,
health care and racial equality for her popularity, and misses no
chance to praise her accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's fair to say that at least no one since Eleanor
Roosevelt has done as much with the Office of First Lady as Hillary
has done,'' Clinton told the Buffalo crowd, ''and I am grateful for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts, however, suggest the country's views on Mrs.
Clinton are far more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not like Eleanor Roosevelt,'' said Dallek, author of a
two-volume biography of Lyndon Johnson. ''What gives Hillary
Clinton cache at this point is the consequence of backing her
husband in the midst of a private scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Mrs. Clinton's motivations, few would expect Gore to be
anything but supportive in Clinton's hour of need.
</P>
<P>
   Who might have suspected, however, Gore would be helped by it?
</P>
<P>
   And yet, in a crowded pack of Democratic presidential hopefuls,
Gore leads with a commanding 47 percent of the party's support. His
nearest rival is House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., with
13 percent, according to a Gallup poll conducted two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate Gallup poll three weeks ago, 57 percent of
Americans surveyed said they had a favorable view of the vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey having a margin of error of plus or minus 3
percentage points, that's statistically equivalent to Clinton's own
58 percent showing, suggesting that the public's views of Gore are
closely wedded to Americans' regard for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for both is that in the more widely discussed job
approval rating _ a measure of how Americans feel Clinton is
managing the country's affairs _ the president has held up far
better. In Gallup's most recent poll, conducted Jan. 15-17,
Clinton's job approval rating was 67 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That's down from his 73 percent peak a month ago. Given his
personal predicament, however, Clinton's popularity remains
remarkably high.
</P>
<P>
   For the politically nimble First Foursome, it's enough to take
the breath away.
</P>
<P>
   end
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
