</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: ALTERNATING Q&AMP;A FORMAT APPEARS TO AID CLINTON
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ What had been designed to be a question-and-answer
time for senators who swore an oath to be impartial jurors in
President Clinton's impeachment trial turned on Friday into
rebuttal time for the opposing legal teams.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for this outcome was a last-minute change in the
questioning format that ultimately might have worked to the White
House's advantage, senators said.
</P>
<P>
   Majority Leader Trent Lott and Minority Leader Tom Daschle had
originally agreed to have Democrats and Republicans use up to eight
hours each to question the White House counsels and the House
impeachment managers. The two sides were to have alternated every
two hours.
</P>
<P>
   But Daschle suggested that the two parties alternate every
question instead. Lott agreed, telling reporters Thursday that
under the original format, ``It'd all go one way for a while, and
then the other way for a while, and we don't want this to be a
purely partisan procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trial, Lott has tried mightily to avoid the
partisan taint that stained the House impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of Republicans and Democrats alternating questions
was to prevent either side from gaining an edge. But overall, it
probably worked in Clinton's favor, senators said, because the
aggressive White House defense this week reversed much of the
momentum that the House managers created in their opening arguments
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats and Republicans insisted Friday they did not
coordinate their questions in advance with the White House counsels
and the House prosecutors, respectively, or coach them.
</P>
<P>
   But the way each side was prepared to respond _ armed with
charts and scripted remarks _ it sure seemed like they did.
</P>
<P>
   Under the trial rules, senators submitted written queries,
screened by their party leaders, to Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist, who read them aloud, identifying the authors. Senate
leaders had been collecting and culling proposed questions from
senators all week _ 70 were submitted by Republicans, 200 by
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But just as legislators often discard prepared texts and speak
off the cuff, senators Friday seemed to improvise and spoon-fed
questions on tan-colored cards to one side or another.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans posed sympathetic questions that the House managers
eagerly seized on to vent frustrations that had built up while they
sat silently during the White House's three-day defense.
</P>
<P>
   Four Senate arch-conservatives _ Wayne Allard of Colorado, Jim
Bunning of Kentucky, Paul Coverdell of Georgia and Larry Craig of
Idaho _ startled Democrats by opening Friday's proceedings with the
first of many leading questions:
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it the opinion of the House managers that the president's
defense team in the presentation mischaracterized any factual or
legal issue in this case?''
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., quickly scribbled
out a query asking the White House counsels to rebut the House
response. The White House lawyers handled the question with relish.
</P>
<P>
   As the partisanship in the questioning became obvious, senators
did not pretend to veil the motivations behind their queries. ``You
can read some people's thinking by the questions they ask,'' said
Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 2045EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5036 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      01-22 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Keep Uncle Sam off Wall Street  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The president's plan to get government into the stock market is
fraught with both political and economic peril, because any
nationalization of American industry would be hostile to everything
the United States symbolizes.
</P>
<P>
   There are myriad examples of how excessive government control of
an economy destroys the political, economic and social welfare of
most citizens. The most destructive cases in recent history have
been the Soviet Union, China's Maoist-style communism, Cambodia's
killing fields, North Korea's degradation and Cuba's
impoverishment.
</P>
<P>
   The damage, however, doesn't necessarily have to be linked to
savagery and cruelty. The latest example of what can go wrong is
Indonesia, where government rulers nurtured a system of crony
capitalism directing wealth to a favored few officials and
private-industry insiders while leaving most average citizens to
fight over their table scraps.
</P>
<P>
   Those who would defend a Washington presence on Wall Street say
the proposed numbers would make up only a small part of corporate
America's overall capitalization. As a numbers exercise, this is
true, but it misses the point. In the realm of equity ownership,
control of only a small percentage of corporate stock can allow for
inordinate control of a company's management. When this dynamic is
combined with government's overarching power, the threat of
selective federal control of corporate America is amplified many
times over.
</P>
<P>
   In a nation with a politicoeconomic system as refined as ours,
the danger is not so much totalitarian oppression as it is the
inequitable distribution of capitalism's rewards. The example of
Indonesia, despite its less advanced state, shows how government
power over private enterprise distorts capital allocation when the
process is based on political rather than economic considerations.
</P>
<P>
   Without putting too fine a point on it, the private sector hews
to much higher standards of fiduciary responsibility than the
public sector when it comes to the stewardship of other people's
money.
</P>
<P>
   There are good reasons for this. First, the success of the
enterprise often depends on honorable conduct because a reputation
for dishonesty reduces access to always-scarce capital. Meantime,
there are laws and government regulations to encourage honesty
among those who otherwise might have difficulty curbing their
larcenous instincts.
</P>
<P>
   The result, to be sure, isn't always a perfect world, but it is
one a good deal more worthy of trust in fiduciary affairs than
government. If, for instance, any U.S. corporation tried to operate
a pension fund like the federal government runs Social Security,
the executives responsible would have long ago been jailed for
fraud and grand larceny.
</P>
<P>
   Can anyone imagine a Congress, an administration or a federal
bureaucracy that wouldn't exert influence on a corporate enterprise
partly owned by Washington when it suited the vested interests of
those in power? Given the insatiable need for campaign funding,
government ownership of companies would make political extortion
more endemic than is already the case.
</P>
<P>
   Government ownership of stocks, in short, would make government
officials the robber barons of the 21st century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
