<SLUG> BC-INVEST-DIARY-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON INVESTING AND FUNDS WATCH  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 24) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why Companies Were Stingy with Payouts &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many investors who live off their dividend checks didn't have a
heck of a lot to cheer about in 1998. Despite the overall upbeat
performance of United States stocks, the total number of dividend
increases actually fell in 1998, to 2,047, from 2,139 the year
before, according to Standard &AMP; Poor's.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the total number of unfavorable payout actions _
either reductions in dividends or outright omissions _ increased to
145 in 1998 from 98 in 1997. That is the highest number of such
negative dividend actions since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't been a very generous dividend environment for
quite awhile,'' said Arnold Kaufman, editor of The Outlook, a
Standard &AMP; Poor's newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   On one count, dividend-minded investors did make out a mite
better: The actual total amount of dividends paid on the S&AMP;P 500
index of large-capitalization stocks rose 4.5 percent in 1998,
compared with a 4.1 percent rise the year before. Still, that's far
below the average increase of 5.3 percent in the postwar period.
</P>
<P>
   So why the corporate stinginess when it comes to payouts? One
reason is that companies know many investors simply aren't
interested in dividends, because they are well aware of the taxes
they must pay when dividends are paid. Generally speaking, such
investors would rather see companies reinvest excess cash in their
businesses or use it to repurchase shares.
</P>
<P>
   Worries that the corporate earnings picture would darken in 1999
probably also played a part. Economists are expecting earnings
growth of just 5 percent or less in 1999, Kaufman said, so it made
plenty of sense for companies to hoard their cash instead of
showering it on shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   All this could change. If the markets turn in a tame performance
this year, investors may begin to clamor for higher dividends to
compensate. ``We see the market gains as being very much more
moderate than in the past four years, perhaps even single digits,''
Kaufman said. ``If investors see that, they may put more pressure
on companies to raise dividends.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Teitelbaum &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS WATCH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   QFRs to the Rescue &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A surprising number of funds from Fidelity Investments managed
to turn in impressive performances in 1998, with 10 of the fund
giant's United States diversified offerings managing to beat the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index for the year.
</P>
<P>
   While there are probably a number of contributing factors, some
fund managers credit the firm's increased emphasis on a kind of
audit that has been pushed by Robert C. Pozen, who took over the
post of president in 1997. Every three months, each of the fund
company's managers sits down with Pozen to discuss each fund's
quarterly fund review, or QFR.
</P>
<P>
   The QFR's show not only by how much managers beat or
underperformed rival managers and their benchmark indexes, but why.
If similar funds topped them, did they ignore sectors or countries
that did well and that others had in their portfolios?
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps in, say, the third quarter of 1998, a fund manager
lagged behind the S&AMP;P but did about the same as rival managers
because all of them underweighted utility stocks, which sharply
outperformed the broad market that quarter. The QFRs ``make you
think about places you may be missing'' in stock selection, said
Stephen DuFour, the Fidelity Balanced fund manager.
</P>
<P>
   But Fidelity officials, who bristle at any suggestion that they
are ``closet indexers,'' say the QFRs aren't intended to encourage
actively managed funds to have closer correlation with their
benchmark indexes. To say the QFRs push managers ``to avoid great
disparity'' within indexes ``is not true,'' said Karen Firestone,
who runs the Fidelity Large Cap Stock fund, one of the 10 that beat
the S&AMP;P.
</P>
<P>
   Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
