<HEADER>
A5044 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-ART-740     01-22 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-ART-740(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE QUESTIONS GO BACK AND FORTH IN THE SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Conn., Fla., Miss., S.C., S.D., Tenn., W.Va.)  (Eds: See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-SCENE,
IMPEACH-CASE, IMPEACH-SCHOLARS) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(fe) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Assuming a more active role, senators posed
questions to defense and prosecution teams for the first time on
Friday, producing the semblance of debate in the impeachment trial
of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican prosecutors sought to repair the damage done by
White House lawyers to their carefully constructed chronologies
about the search for a job for Monica S. Lewinsky, whose sexual
relationship with Clinton led to the two articles of impeachment,
and the concealment of presents given to Ms. Lewinsky by the
president. They denied that their charges of perjury and
obstruction of justice had been loosely drawn or constitutionally
defective.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton wants all the benefits of a criminal trial
without bearing any of its burdens,'' Rep. Charles T. Canaday, a
prosecutor from Florida, asserted, as Charles F.C. Ruff, the White
House counsel, argued again that the impeachment articles were so
vague they would be thrown out of court but continued to resist all
Republican demands that witnesses be summoned.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry J. Hyde of Illinois, the chief prosecutor, pressed
his case for witnesses, arguing that only witnesses could resolve
conflicts in testimony on several key points, even after Sen.
Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., issued a statement promising to move on
Monday to dismiss the case.
</P>
<P>
   But Hyde wanted none of that and even proposed that senators ask
the president to testify, an idea the White House has dismissed out
of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think by dismissing the articles of impeachment before you
have a complete trial, you are sending a terrible message to the
people of the country,'' he said. ``You're saying, I guess, perjury
is OK if it's about sex. Obstruction is OK, even though it is an
effort to deny a citizen a right to a fair trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde continued: ``I know _ oh, do I know _ what an annoyance we
are in the bosom of this great body. But we're a constitutional
annoyance, and I remind you of that fact.''
</P>
<P>
   David E. Kendall, Clinton's personal lawyer, said it was
inconceivable that anything could be gained by questioning Ms.
Lewinsky or Vernon E. Jordan Jr., the presidential confidant who
sought a job for her, or Betty Currie, Clinton's secretary, who hid
the presents under her bed. The Senate already has before it five
volumes of testimony, he said _ thousands of pages.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel, Kenneth W. Starr, `` called many, many,
many witnesses many, many, many times,'' Kendall reminded the
senators.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff, almost always gentlemanly and composed, came close to
losing his temper on the witness issue at one point. If the
Republicans so badly needed witnesses to nail down their case and
clear up inconsistencies, he demanded, how could they have called
for Clinton's removal from office without summoning witnesses of
their own before the House Judiciary Committee?
</P>
<P>
   ``The House of Representatives,'' he charged, ``violated their
constitutional responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   The questions were posed by the senators through an arcane
process that forbade them to speak directly and required them to
submit their queries on lined cards to the respective party
leaders: Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi for the Republicans and
Sen. Thomas A. Daschle of South Dakota for the Democrats. The
leaders screened them and sent them, one by one, with the parties
alternating, to Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, who then read
them to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Most went from Democrats to Democrats, Republicans to
Republicans. They were frequently vague and unchallenging, enabling
the House managers and the White House lawyers to veer off in
almost any direction they wished to. When Sen. Christopher T. Dodd
of Connecticut, a Democrat, objected that an answer to a question
he had put to Rep. Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas, a Republican, was
not responsive, Rehnquist overruled his objection with the comment
that he was not inclined to ``police the responsiveness'' of
answers.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the Republicans from the House were prepared for some
of the questions, because they read out prepared answers and used
charts.
</P>
<P>
   The result was nothing like the cross-examination of a criminal
trial. It was more like the rebuttal and surrebuttal of a college
debate. But the two sides engaged each other more directly than
they had since the trial began eight days ago, and there was more
real debate than usual in the modern Senate, with its serial
speeches.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist, a stickler for form and punctuality at the Supreme
Court, added to a feeling of relaxation in the Senate chamber on
Friday. At the beginning, he told the lawyers, ``The chair will
operate on a rebuttable assumption that each question can be fully
and fairly answered in five minutes or less.'' In fact, many were
and many were not. Rep. Ed Bryant of Tennessee, the first manager
to speak, took nine minutes on a broadly phrased question, and
Rehnquist did not cut him or anybody else off.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 questions were asked during the four-and-a-half-hour
proceeding, and more will be put during a session expected to last
most of Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides debated whether overt threats were required to
prove intimidation of a witness, the Democrats saying yes and the
Republicans no. There was more argument about whether private acts
or only official acts could be subject to impeachment. And the
lawyers squabbled over whether the standards for the impeachment
trials of federal judges differed from those governing presidential
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more telling moments came when Sen. Joseph I.
Lieberman of Connecticut, a Democrat, asked Rep. Lindsey O. Graham
of South Carolina, a Republican, whether he thought a president
should be impeached any time he committed a criminal offense,
regardless of its nature.
</P>
<P>
   No, Graham replied, ``I would want not my president removed for
trivial offenses.'' But it was no trivial offense, he suggested,
when Clinton ``coached'' Ms. Currie with a series of questions
about Ms. Lewinsky shortly after his deposition in the Paula Jones
case, intended, he later said, ``to refresh my memory.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe he was refreshing his memory when he asked his
secretary, `I never touched her, did I?' '' Graham said. ``I
believe you should only remove a president who in a calculated
fashion puts the legal and political interest of himself over the
good of the nation in a selfish way _ that you only should remove a
president who, after being begged by everybody in the country,
`Don't go into a grand jury and lie,' and he in fact lied.''
</P>
<P>
   The question of Clinton's deposition in the Jones case, which
brought the Lewinsky matter to light, came up repeatedly. The
Republicans contended that Clinton had lied in it; the White House
lawyers said he had evaded, answered incompletely, misled but had
not committed perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he had, Clinton's lawyers said, it was a moot question,
because the House had rejected the Judiciary Committee's article
covering the Jones case. Not so, said the Republicans. Because the
president affirmed his statements in the Jones case when he
testified before the Lewinsky grand jury, he had piled perjury upon
perjury. But he had not affirmed them, Ruff insisted.
</P>
<P>
   So it went all afternoon, back and forth, with a little
name-calling to enliven things. The Republicans built ``straw
men,'' said Ruff; the White House had provided ``a lesson in legal
schizophrenia,'' said Rep. James E. Rogan, perhaps the most
hard-edged of the prosecutors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
