<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GLORIA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUMET'S REMAKE OF `GLORIA' REVIVES A STRONG PREMISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though it came out as recently as 1980, John Cassavetes'
``Gloria'' is actually a prime candidate for a remake. Generally
regarded as one of the maverick director's low points, it's a movie
that failed both at the box office and with the critics.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, everyone seemed to love its premise _ an
ex-gang moll and a child marked for gangland execution on the run
together _ and it worked as a vehicle for the director's wife, Gena
Rowlands, who earned a best actress Oscar nomination.
</P>
<P>
   So why not try it again? This time with a more reliable genre
director _ Sidney Lumet, say? _ and with a star like Sharon Stone,
who, though six years younger than Rowlands when she played the
part, is no stranger to playing aging gun molls, witness her best
actress Oscar nomination for `Casino.''
</P>
<P>
   And, happily, the mix of Stone, Lumet and ``Gloria'' gels. It
definitely has its weak moments, but ``Gloria'' powers along rather
nicely as a thriller, and Stone _ complete with Brooklyn accent _
is surprisingly believable in the (heavily reworked) role.
</P>
<P>
   This Gloria is not a grandmotherly ex-moll who lives next door
to the endangered child, but a fairly smashing looking younger
woman just released from three years in a Florida prison _ having
taken the rap for her Irish gangster boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   When she confronts the boyfriend (Jeremy Northam) in his
Manhattan digs, she discovers his men have just killed the entire
family of a turncoat gang bookkeeper, except for a seven-year-old
boy (Jean-Luke Figueroa) they hold prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   Furious with her ex-beau for never visiting her and sure the boy
is about to be murdered, she steals him (and an incriminating
computer disk his father gave him) and takes off. The rest of the
movie has the gangsters trying to track the fugitives down, as they
bond as surrogate mother-and-son.
</P>
<P>
   If the film has any real problem, it's that it comes off as
being too calculated a star vehicle, with too many ``big'' scenes
designed to showcase Stone's talent _ to the point that she
frequently seems to be overacting. The film would benefit from a
few more low-voltage moments.
</P>
<P>
   The script also suffers from a strange schizophrenia, in that
Stone looks like a million dollars, but people _ a hotel clerk, a
pawnbroker, everyone she encounters, in fact _ constantly react to
her with instant contempt, as if she's a frumped-up Rowlands, a
complete nonentity.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, she gets on a bus but is short two quarters of the
fare. Turning to a bus-load of New York men, she asks for help. All
eyes look at her, then blankly out the window. Since she could have
just stepped out of a Victoria's Secret catalog, the scene is
absurd: the woman would be drowning in quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she gives a solid, watchable performance. She may not
have the instant sympathy of a Meg Ryan or Gwyneth Paltrow, but she
projects a street-smart intelligence and tough-cookie determination
as charismatically as any actress in films today. Her scenes with
her young co-star are warm and credible, without ever being
maudlin.
</P>
<P>
   While it's not in the league with his classics (a long list that
includes ``12 Angry Men,'' ``Dog Day Afternoon'' and ``Network''),
director Lumet gives the film zip, style and uniformly good
performances _ not just Stone but Northam and (especially) George
C. Scott as an aging Irish Godfather.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite these obvious selling points, Columbia has
apparently decided to throw this movie away. Indeed, it must be the
first major studio star vehicle since ``The Avengers'' to open
without a press screening. (Why? Columbia's official response is a
damning: ``No comment'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Gloria'' may be no masterpiece, but it's a lot better than
half the junk that studio has released with both a press screening
and a mouthful of superlatives. Whatever Columbia's reasons for
dumping the movie, a director with the track record of a Lumet
certainly deserves a little more respect.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria. Directed by Sidney Lumet. Screenplay by Steven Antin.
Cast: Sharon Stone, Jean-Luke Figueroa, Jeremy Northam, Cathy
Moriarty, George C. Scott. Columbia Pictures. 108 minutes. Rated R
for violence and language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
