<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISSBANKS-JEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS BANKS AND VICTIMS OF NAZIS REACH ACCORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lawyers for Holocaust victims, Jewish groups and
Swiss banks agreed late Thursday on some key elements of the $1.25
billion settlement of a lawsuit against the banks, including
identifying who can qualify for payments.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement involves two Swiss banks, UBS and Credit Suisse.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting at U.S. District Court in Brooklyn, the lawyers agreed
on several broad classes of Holocaust survivors or heirs who can
qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Included are the heirs of those who deposited money in Swiss
banks before World War II and later died in the Holocaust, as well
as those whose looted assets may have passed through Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement defines the victims or targets of Nazi persecution
as Jews, Jehovah's Witnesses, Gypsies, homosexuals and the
physically or mentally disabled, said lawyers familiar with the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Others eligible for payments include those who were forced to
work for companies that kept money in Swiss banks or that used
slave labor. Jews who fled to Switzerland to escape the Nazis and
were then deported by the Swiss would also qualify.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss banks were accused of profiting from the assets of
Holocaust victims, including those stolen from the victims. Under
the agreement, all companies incorporated in Switzerland or having
headquarters there would be released from further liability.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, The Associated Press reported, Swiss government
officials said in a statement, ``This settlement provides a closure
of all the financial claims raised against Switzerland.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement still must be approved by U.S. District Judge
Edward Korman. Perhaps the most contentious phase of the case, how
to best distribute the money, will soon unfold.
</P>
<P>
   Because unclaimed Swiss bank accounts will account for only a
portion of the $1.25 billion settlement, the court must decide how
to distribute the rest. In recent months individuals and groups
have been proposing different plans for how to do so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
