<HEADER>
A5054 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPERDEATH-AWARD-COX     01-22 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPERDEATH-AWARD-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Byrd family honored
</P>
<P>
   By Brad Mayhar
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 cox news service
</P>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Seven months after the dragging death of James
Byrd Jr. and four days before the start of the capital murder case
for the first of three suspects charged in 49-year-old's brutal
death, members of the Byrd family received a national honor for the
way they responded to the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from the Victorian Foundation on Thursday
presented the Byrd family with its annual Victoria Award for its
commitment to non-violence in dealing with the loss of its loved
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Byrds could very well have used the death of their loved
one, James Byrd Jr., to endorse all types of violence _ and been
justified in the eyes of many,'' Robin Zaruba, vice president of
the Victoria Foundation, said during a ceremony at the Holiday Inn
Express.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, like the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., they have seen a
mountaintop, and it has been their wisdom and fortitude that has
kept them on that mountaintop and not in the valley below, where so
many go in times of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The Victoria Foundation chose the Byrds over several nominees,
including Oprah Winfrey, Racehorse Hanes, Walter Umphrey and the
Rogers Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals who display high degrees of humanitarian and
vocational merit receive the award each year. Past recipients
include Bob Hope and entertainer Howard Hewitt.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's sister, Mary Verrett, acknowledged members of the
community for lending their support throughout the past seven
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``No man is an island,'' she said. ``We feed upon one another. I
not only accept this award for the Byrd family, but for the people
of Jasper, and for people all over the world who have had to
undergo trials and tribulations.''
</P>
<P>
   A life-changing event prompted Victoria Foundation president and
CEO, Ricky Jason to found the organization in 1995 as a means to
recognize individuals who make significant contributions to assist
their fellow man. After spending much of his childhood legally
blind, Jason's life changed forever when he received a corneal
transplant from renowned surgeon Dr. Richard Levacy.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Jasper, Beaumont and Port Arthur NAACP
chapters, attended the ceremony, as did Jasper city officials.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Moore serenaded the Byrd family with his song ``I Won't
Complain'' from the Byrd-inspired album ``Love, Peace and
Harmony.'' Members of Houston-based Color Blind Entertainment set
up a table in the hotel lobby to sell cassettes, CDs and T-shirts
featuring Byrd's portrait.
</P>
<P>
   Jason, who also serves as co-founder of Color Blind
Entertainment and owns the original portrait of Byrd, set up the
painting next to the panel of Byrd family members.
</P>
<P>
   Since its unveiling at Lamar University in Beaumont a few months
ago, the portrait has appeared at the NAACP Image Awards, the YMCA
Awards, Rice University and has been viewed privately at a Beaumont
prison by blues legend B.B. King's son, Riley.
</P>
<P>
   The portrait soon will go on display at its final stop in
Jasper. Jason said the family has not decided on a specific display
location for the painting.
</P>
<P>
   After just two weeks on display at Lamar's Dishman Art Gallery,
the portrait and frame _ which have a combined value of $500,000,
according to Jason _ sustained a cut in the right side of the
frame.
</P>
<P>
   Jason believes someone intentionally damaged the frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to leave it like that to show there's still
some hate,'' he said. ``We're not going to take it out of the
frame.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities believe someone also may have stolen a nameplate at
Byrd's grave site. The Byrd family has since replaced the
nameplate, Jason said.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper city officials earlier this week held a ceremony to tear
down an iron fence that separated black and white graves for more
than than 160 years in the same cemetery where Byrd was laid to
rest.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say Byrd died on June 6, 1998, after he was chained
behind a pickup and dragged down a county road. The murder trial of
William King, one of three white suspects in the slaying, begins
next week.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have not announced trial dates for two other
defendants in the murder case _ Shawn Berry, 23, and Russell
Brewer, 31. Prosecutors believe racial hatred provoked the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Mayhar writes for the Lufkin Daily News
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
