<HEADER>
A5055 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-DEATHVALLEY-CHEST-L     01-22 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-DEATHVALLEY-CHEST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERT BEGINS AUTHENTICITY TEST ON TREASURE-FILLED CHEST FOUND IN
DESERT
</HEADLINE>
 
(Resending to correct garbled version.) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY CHARLES F. BOSTWICK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A National Park Service expert departed Death
Valley National Park on Friday with photographs and tiny samples of
a battered chest and its contents that may have been left by a lost
Gold Rush expedition 149 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Western Archeological and Conservation Center conservator
Gretchen Voeks will consult with experts and examine reference
books to try to authenticate dates for the find, park officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's going to follow up with a couple of things, possibly do
chemical analysis on some of the things she found,'' said Death
Valley National Park spokesman Tim Stone. ``She actually asked us
not to say much. ... She just doesn't want to say anything that's
negative or positive now.''
</P>
<P>
   The age of some of the objects may be verified by next week,
though chemical analysis of the samples Voeks scraped off objects
could take two weeks or so, Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   The chest was found in November in a rocky alcove high in the
Panamint Mountains, Death Valley's western wall. Pearblossom
archeologist Jerry Freeman said he found the chest while
researching the possible route taken by the lost gold miners trying
to escape Death Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman, his two adult daughters and two friends returned in
December on a backpacking expedition retracing the lost miners'
route. They retrieved the chest, at times having to lower it with
ropes down 20-foot cliffs, said Allan Smith, a documentary
filmmaker who was on the trek.
</P>
<P>
   The place was so hard to reach, he has no doubts the chest is
authentic, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The chest was turned over Jan. 5 to the National Park Service,
and officials are trying to verify its authenticity. Park officials
said the find, if authentic, would make a fabulous addition to
knowledge about the first white people to see North America's
lowest, hottest, driest spot.
</P>
<P>
   The chest contained gold and silver coins, bowls, books, a
flintlock pistol, plus a letter signed with the name of William
Robinson, one of the lost gold miners. He died 26 days and 200
miles later at the edge of what is now Palmdale. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 2104EST &QL; 
