<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CONSERVATIVES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVES DISAGREE ABOUT CLINTON TRIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Va. _ When conservative evangelist Pat Robertson
suggested recently that Clinton was winning the public relations
war and that his Senate impeachment trial should be dismissed, it
jolted the Republican establishment.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it was fear of conservative backlash that some say
motivated GOP lawmakers to continue to press the case against
Clinton even though polls have shown the public wants the matter
swiftly concluded.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear that all conservatives are singing from the same
hymnal.
</P>
<P>
   Across the Potomac River from the Senate proceedings, at the
annual meeting of the Conservative Political Action Conference, a
number of participants said Friday they were shocked and bewildered
that Robertson was willing to admit defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Many said they wanted the Senate to finish the trial and call
witnesses even if it appeared that there were not enough votes to
oust the president. The group applauded former Vice President Dan
Quayle, who is considering a bid for the White House, when he
commended the ``courage'' of Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill, and the GOP
managers for pressing the case against the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is too early to surrender,'' said Andrea Sheldon,
executive director of the Family Values Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon said that even if Clinton is not ousted, she is
confident that his reputation has already been ruined.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a loser,'' she said. ``You think some kid is going to
grow up and say I want to be Bill Clinton, I think his mom would
slap him.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Robertson's comments, Sheldon said that good friends are
entitled to disagree.
</P>
<P>
   But others were not as diplomatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was crummy. I think he (Robertson) ought to keep
his mouth shut,'' said Van Arden, a stock broker from San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Arden said Republican senators who vote to end the trial early
could face retribution from angry voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Republicans back off and put their tails between their
legs, it will be much worse in terms of the electorate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But many of those attending the conference of admitted Clinton
haters also acknowledged that there was a strong possibility that
the president would serve out his term.
</P>
<P>
   Many said they, like most Americans, were weary of the scandal.
Others, particularly women, said there was no need to cross-examine
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky about the intimate
details of her relationship with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like Clinton. But we still need to move on,'' said
Kathryn Baillie, a first-year law student at Regent University, the
Virginia Beach school founded by Robertson. While Baillie said the
Senate needed to finish the trial she added that it was not
necessary to hear from Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sick of hearing about what happened to Monica Lewinsky.
She consented to it. She is no less guilty than Clinton,'' said
Baillie.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Atkiss, a college student from Dallas, said he was
``pleasantly surprised'' by Robertson's comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was refreshing to see him with a realistic outlook,'' said
Atkiss, a senior at the University of Florida. ``It is something
most conservatives already know but don't want to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon and Pam Watts, a couple from Washington state, differed on
how the trial should proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Watts said the senators should call witnesses, including
Lewinsky, and ask the intimate questions.
</P>
<P>
   But his wife disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need to be hearing all these details. We got the gist
of what happened,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rotterman, a GOP consultant from North Carolina, however,
said that if the Republicans grill Lewinsky during prime time that
could change public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows what the reaction of the public will be if Monica
Lewinsky gets up there and cries and says she was done wrong,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rotterman also said he did not believe the party will be hurt in
the 2000 elections because of the impeachment trial even though
polls now show voters unhappy with the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years is an eternity in politics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the impact of prolonging the Clinton trial has been on the
minds of Republican National Committee members meeting Friday in
Washington. They have watched in dismay as their party lost House
seats last year, in part attributed to the party's focus on
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   While the chairman of the RNC, Jim Nicholson, beat back a
challenge from Florida GOP Chairman Tom Slade on Friday, party
officials made it known that they expected him to do a better job
getting out the party's message, other than impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Tim Lambert, an RNC member from Lubbock, Texas,
who voted for Slade, said that he is not convinced that will be
possible until the trial is over.
</P>
<P>
   Texas GOP Chairwoman Susan Weddington, however, said the party
could do a better job of talking about public policy issues while
the trial is ongoing. Saying she was surprised by Robertson's
comments, Weddington said that it was important that the Senate
``adhere to the constitutional process.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the Senate trial, Weddington said, ``you want it to go away
but you want it completed in a proper way.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
