<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUISVILLE NOT AN `ULTIMATUM GAME'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE _ The Bruins have described today's game as yet
another test of their mental mettle _ flying across country,
playing their first nonconference road game, facing a Top 25 team,
and so on. Truth is, it's not a test at all. It's a quiz, lacking
the NCAA Tournament repercussions that accompanied past matchups
with Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, a victory would look good for the Bruins. Despite its loss
Thursday to Cincinnati, Louisville has a solid power rating, an
upset of Kentucky and two victories over DePaul to its credit.
</P>
<P>
   But UCLA's youth reduces the consequence of its January games _
whether the opponent is Arizona, Stanford or Louisville _ and
places its postseason fate on success (or failure) in February and
early March.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to discount this Louisville game, but I wouldn't
say it's an ultimatum game for UCLA,'' said a member of the NCAA
Selection Committee who requested anonymity. ``There's a long road
ahead. UCLA is so young, you have to look at growth. I'm looking
for improvement from them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific-10's overall strength also undermines the
significance of today's game. In recent years, with a weak Pac-10,
UCLA had few opportunities to face highly rated teams in league.
That placed abnormal emphasis on intersectional matchups with
Louisville and Duke. But this year, Stanford, Arizona, Cal,
Washington and Oregon provide the Bruins with 10 chances to improve
their power rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``UCLA will have plenty of other opportunities in league play,''
the Selection Committee member said. ``The conference's power
rating will help this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The reduced significance does not temper UCLA's task, however.
The Cardinals are not particularly big _ their tallest starter is
6-foot-7 _ but they play tenacious defense and shoot well from
3-point range (37 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Because the Cardinals are banned from postseason play for
recruiting violations _ they are awaiting the results of an appeal
_ their urgency is unending and reflected in their spirited play.
The ban seemingly has had the greatest impact on Louisville's
seniors, guard Cameron Murray and center Alex Sanders, who combine
for 25 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team really seems to be playing hard and improving game
to game,'' UCLA coach Steve Lavin said. ``You look at them and it's
not as though they have the same personnel as Duke, Kansas or
Kentucky. And yet they beat Kentucky.''
</P>
<P>
   To combat the 10 a.m. tipoff (PST), the Bruins traveled Thursday
and practiced in Freedom Hall on Friday. They will be without
starting center Dan Gadzuric, who sprained his right ankle at USC.
Freshman guard Ray Young will start in Gadzuric's place, giving
UCLA a small, quick lineup that will mirror Louisville
athletically.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tough for our young guys,'' said UCLA's only
senior, guard Brandon Loyd. ``It's a different atmosphere than
we're used to. Just like the Oregon State game (UCLA's first on the
road) was hard, this will be hard. It's not the friendly confines
of Pauley.''
</P>
</TEXT>
