<HEADLINE>
NICHOLSON RE-ELECTED AS REPUBLICAN PARTY CHAIRMAN
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Colo., Calif., Ind., Fla., Ariz., N.Y., Mich.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Jim Nicholson overcame an energetic challenge and
was overwhelming re-elected as chairman of the Republican National
Committee on Friday after pleas from his supporters that he should
not be blamed for the party's discouraging performance in
November's elections.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson, a real-estate developer from Colorado, is now poised
to guide the party through what will be a crucial two-year period
as Republicans try to win back the White House and hang on to their
slim majorities in the House and Senate in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Republican Party chairman Tom Slade ran an aggressive
challenge against Nicholson, pointing to the party's defeats and
arguing that the chairman fell short as a national spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, many party members _ conceding that Nicholson
had his flaws _ said they stood by him because he had raised record
millions of dollars for the party and because they liked him
personally. The vote, by secret ballot, was 127 for Nicholson and
36 for Slade.
</P>
<P>
   In a victory speech at a party convention here, Nicholson
expressed gratitude for his election, saying, ``If I were told I
had only two years left to live, I would want to live them as
chairman of the Republican National Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   He then launched into a critique of President Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore _ and a defense of the party's pursuit of the
impeachment matter. ``In politics,'' he said, ``character is doing
what's right even when everyone is looking at the polls. We cannot
be a political party that decides what it believes based on the
polls. Yes, we Republicans do worry that people won't understand.
But Democrats live in mortal fear that people will understand.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairman also asserted that while Clinton ``has few ironclad
beliefs,'' one that he does have is that ``winning is the sole
judge of right and wrong.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At a conference of conservatives across the river in Virginia,
former Vice President Dan Quayle, who is assembling a presidential
campaign, joined the chorus and derided Gore as promoting a
platform of ``New Age socialists.'' Gore's office shot back,
attacking Quayle as ``a medieval conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson was a little-known party veteran when he was elected
two years ago on the sixth ballot after party members could not
choose between two more prominent contenders. Despite his
re-election, many prominent fund raisers and party members said
they had qualms about his leadership and what they complained was a
failure to articulate a clear agenda for the party. And many party
members said they worried that the impeachment trial could end up
damaging the party.
</P>
<P>
   Even Nicholson's most enthusiastic backers were mindful of the
problems facing him and Republicans. In nominating Nicholson,
Arizona state party chairman Michael Hellon sounded defensive,
saying, ``The complaint I hear most often is that we lack a
coherent message. I agree. But that wasn't Jim Nicholson's fault.''
He blamed the party's leaders in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Another backer of Nicholson, New York state chairman William
Powers said everyone knew that Republicans did not do as well in
the 1998 elections ``as we would have liked, and we need to learn
from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Slade said after the election that the party was loathe to oust
Nicholson because ``it's hard to get a group of people wanting to
kick out of office a genuinely nice man.'' He also said the
chairman helped himself by dispensing ``huge amounts of money'' to
state parties.
</P>
<P>
   Some party members have expressed concern that Nicholson may not
be forceful enough to serve as something of a referee for the
growing field of presidential candidates. Republicans here also
speculated that Nicholson survived because. after the ouster of
Speaker Newt Gingrich in the wake of the elections. there was no
outcry for another dramatic move.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee, meanwhile, is planning to
announce on Saturday changes in its top leadership. The biggest
beneficiary may be Vice President Al Gore, who has begun assembling
a presidential campaign organization.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana Democratic Party chairman Joseph Andrew will take over
as national chairman and will run the party's day-to-day
operations. Andrew is so close to the vice president that Gore had
offered him a job as his deputy chief of staff. Andrew will replace
Steve Grossman, who resigned as national chairman in December.
</P>
<P>
   Former Colorado Gov. Roy Romer will stay on as general chairman.
But in an effort to reach out to minorities, two other Gore allies
have been tapped for newly-created positions of party co-chairs:
Detroit Mayor Dennis Archer, one of the nation's leading black
politicians, and Rep. Loretta Sanchez of California, who is
Hispanic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
