<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 24) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few Willing Wallets On an Opening Night &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to find a business leader or social bigwig at the
opening-night party of the Winter Antiques Show who actually bought
something. Evelyn Lauder, wife of Leonard Lauder, chairman of the
Whitney Museum, proudly displayed her acquisition, a 1939 sharkskin
paper cutter. But browsing was the order of the day at the party in
the Seventh Regiment Armory in Manhattan this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a voyeur,'' confessed art dealer Joan Washburn. Morley
Safer, the ``60 Minutes'' correspondent, said, ``I'm not buying;
I'm admiring,'' And Ronald O. Perelman, owner of Revlon, uttered
the classic ``I'm just looking.''
</P>
<P>
   Other shoppers held out at least a thread of hope to the charity
event's organizers. Agnes Gund, president of the Museum of Modern
Art, said she and her husband, Daniel Shapiro, a lawyer, had just
bought a country hideaway, ``so I am looking for furniture.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Stribling, the real-estate executive, said she
particularly liked a pair of 19th-century Italian chairs. Her
husband, Guy N. Robinson, a partner in Highland Asset Management,
retorted that the couple had plenty of furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Tober, chairwoman of the American Craft Museum in
Manhattan and former editor of Bride's and Your New Home magazines,
said she had ``edited the whole show down to a wish list of three
things'': a set of china, an art nouveau choker and a David Webb
bracelet. When someone reminded her husband, Donald G. Tober,
chairman of Sugar Foods, that the couple's wedding anniversary was
just around the corner, he rolled his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   With a similar marital event looming for John D. Gilliam, chief
financial officer of the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation, and his
wife, Deane Gilliam, Gilliam took preventive action, asking: ``What
are you going to buy me, Dear?''
</P>
<P>
   But with the help of ticket prices as high as $1,000, the
benefit for the East Side House Settlement in the South Bronx did
net $1 million. And some patrons admitted buying, too. Arie L.
Kopelman, president of Chanel and chairman of the show committee,
said he had bought ``the most beautiful British Colonial inkstand,
made about 1840,'' with silver mounts and a candle holder on top.
</P>
<P>
   C.J. Satterwhite &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starting From Scratch, Again &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The art publisher Nicholas Callaway insists that his effort to
publish high-quality books about golf will be revived, even though
the enterprise is looking more and more like a missed swing.
According to publishing industry sources, the project's de facto
editor in chief, David McCormick, was given 20 minutes this month
to clean out his desk in the old mill building at South Street
Seaport that housed a dwindling staff of 20 editors, writers and
designers for Callaway Golf Media Ventures. Soon afterward, the
staff's computers were removed. McCormick didn't return phone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   The project started more than a year ago as a joint venture of
Callaway Editions and the Callaway Golf Co., founded by Callaway's
father, Eli Callaway. But with sagging sales, the golf maker cut
back its involvement in the project, which had an initial budget of
$18 million and had commissioned writers like George Plimpton, Mark
Singer and John Seabrook.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, most of the staff members were laid off but allowed
to keep using the office. McCormick was kept on as a consultant
until his last week. Many of the commissioned writers were left in
limbo about whether to finish their pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Callaway said he expected the project to be revived and
publishing its first list of three books next year. A company
spokesman said a deal was in the works under which Callaway Golf
would transfer its share of the company to Callaway Editions for a
nominal price, forgive its debts, give it some operating money and
license its name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan for the list is that it's going to be varied and
growing,'' Callaway said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Doreen Carvajal &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Guru to Wall Street's Gurus &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of the savviest players on Wall Street are paying homage to
one of the most popular professors at the Columbia Business School
_ by going to his classes. Among those showing up this month for
Bruce Greenwald's two-day crash course in value investing were
Herbert Allen III, son of Herbert Allen, head of Allen &AMP; Co., the
investment bank; Michael Overlock, former head of investment
banking at Goldman Sachs, and Brad Patelli, a vice president with
Angelo Gordon, the arbitrage firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wanted to take it,'' said Patelli, who recalled that
demand was so strong for the course when he was a student at the
school that he couldn't get in.
</P>
<P>
   Geraldine Fabrikant
</P>
</TEXT>
