A5063 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORNADO23-COX     01-22 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South's warm winter stirs deadly tornadoes
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Gita M. Smith
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After a week of balmy weather, Southern states
inherited the wind. Tornadoes ripped through Arkansas, Tennessee
and Alabama Friday, and gale winds downed power lines and trees
across Mississippi and Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta area forecasters kept a wary eye on states to the west
Friday night, hoping trouble wasn't aimed this way. But unusually
high January temperatures this week left the South vulnerable to
severe storm fronts, so today's heavy rains fit the pattern,
forecasters say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spring came a bit early,'' said Frank Taylor with the National
Weather Service in Peachtree City. ``When it's warm in winter, you
have a potential for storms. Severe weather in Mississippi and
Alabama have a history of producing tornadoes, hail and wind damage
over here.''
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms and flash flood warnings for the metro Atlanta
area that began Friday night will continue through this morning, he
said, with temperatures in the mid-50s.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the rains hit Georgia, high winds were blamed for
fires and downed power lines in Rockdale and Cobb counties Friday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Wind knocked down power lines at South Cobb Drive and Austell
Road shortly after 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours earlier, wind fanned flames on Pickens Road in Newton,
causing a trailer to burn to the ground and a three-acre wooded lot
to also burn. Fire fighters from seven station houses in the
Newton-Rockdale area answered the 3:30 p.m.call.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for Falcons fans planning Sunday send-off
celebrations is that skies are expected to clear tonight and Sunday
should be sunny with afternoon highs around 53 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Across the South, a punishing storm system killed eight people
in two states and left thousands of people without power early
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Wave after wave of twisters hit central Arkansas, starting late
Thursday, collapsing roofs, knocking down power poles and leaving
trees strewn about the grounds of the governor's mansion in Little
Rock. Seven people died.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters estimate 30 tornadoes hit the state, though it will
be days before field checks can confirm an exact number.
</P>
<P>
   In Tennessee, a tornado touched down in Clarksville on Friday,
ripping roofs off buildings. It was the second time in less than a
week that tornadoes hit the state.
</P>
<P>
   Just last Sunday, twisters killed nine Tennesseans.
</P>
<P>
   Severe weather also pummeled Mississippi and Louisiana, but
there were no immediate reports of serious injuries. In western
Alabama, residents of Tuscaloosa and west-central counties were
under tornado warnings Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   In Clarksville, a city of 89,000 about 40 miles northwest of
Nashville near the Kentucky state line, a twister hit about 4:15
a.m. Friday, heavily damaging the downtown and causing a dozen
minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The roof was ripped off the Montgomery County courthouse, much
of a historic church was knocked down, trees and utility poles were
blown over, and about 25,000 customers were without power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like somebody walked through with a broom and knocked
over whatever was loose enough to knock down,'' said Fred Dye,
photo editor at The Leaf-Chronicle of Clarksville, whose building
was heavily damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Sunday deaths in Jackson, Tenn., were blamed on a
faulty civil defense siren in Jackson that could have warned people
to seek cover, but didn't sound in time.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the alarm failure didn't matter because there was no
siren within earshot. But many were within the estimated one-mile
hearing radius, said Madison County Commissioner Jim Ed Hart.
</P>
<P>
   ``The residents deserve better. Nobody should put up with
that,'' he said. Eight of the city's 20 sirens failed in tests
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The carnage was worst in Arkansas. Two people were killed in the
Little Rock area when trees fell on them, and a 67-year-old
pharmacist at a supermarket died of his injuries.
</P>
<P>
   In Beebe, 30 miles to the northeast, a 2-month-old son of a
firefighter was blown out of his home and killed and a woman was
found dead at her home.
</P>
<P>
   At Center Hill, Searcy school board member Wanda Wilson died
when her mobile home was hit, Superintendent Tony Wood said. And
south of Searcy, an unidentified body was found, said Lt. Bill
Lindsey of the White County sheriff's office.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas utilities officials said the storms left 72,000
customers without power, and authorities opened five shelters from
the Little Rock area to Newark, 90 miles to the northeast. At least
60 people were injured, including 45 in Little Rock. Parts of the
state also reported grapefruit-size hail.
</P>
<P>
   In Alexandria, La., violent winds ripped apart businesses and
downed electrical lines, cutting power to hundreds of residents.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the state was under a tornado watch as cool, dry air
moving south clashed with warm moist air from the Gulf of Mexico.
The National Weather Service reported possible tornadoes in seven
parishes Friday, and Monroe Regional Airport reported some hangars
and planes were damaged by high winds. However, it appeared
Louisiana had escaped the devastation from tornadoes in Arkansas
and Tennessee. Severe storms and flood-producing rains pounded
Mississippi Friday after a night of tornadoes and gusting winds
left scattered damage. The Delta took the hardest beating, though
tornado watches remained in effect for much of north and extreme
west Mississippi until midday.
</P>
<P>
   Wind gusts of up to 60 mph were reported Thursday night in the
Greenville and Vicksburg areas. The storms knocked down trees,
power lines and damaged some homes in Hollandale, Miss. Power was
also knocked out in Indianola and Mayersville. Utilitiy companies
and the Georgia Emergency Management
</P>
<P>
   Agency stayed on alert Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our people on alert and we are watching the progress
of the storms headed this way from Mississippi and Alabama,'' said
Georgia Power spokesman James Peters.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
