<HEADLINE>
COMPENSATION GROWING FROM TOP TO BOTTOM  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 24) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Md., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You have a 50-50 chance of getting a salary increase of 4
percent or more this year, according to Watson Wyatt Worldwide, a
compensation company based in Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey of 397 companies in five industry sectors, Watson
Wyatt found that the median salary increase budgeted for 1999 was 4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Differences in merit pay increases among industries are
insignificant,'' Watson Wyatt said after surveying companies in
services; finance, insurance and real estate; manufacturing; health
and social assistance, and wholesale and retail trade.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety percent of the companies surveyed thought that their
workers regarded merit increases as an entitlement, usually tied to
age and seniority. But Rick Beal, a Watson Wyatt pay expert, said
corporations that ``shift resources away from paying people for
showing up'' and move more compensation to pay-for-performance
plans will be better able to cope with the aging work force. In the
next decade, the number of workers 56 and older will grow by half,
the firm said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, things remain a bit different atop the corporate pyramid.
The average pay for a chief executive last year was $7.57 million,
up 19 percent from 1997, according to Pearl Meyer &AMP; Partners, an
executive compensation firm in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Salaries for chief executives continue to hover around $1
million, the firm said _ apparently influenced by a federal law
that limits the tax deduction for such salaries to that figure. But
total pay is rising at nearly five times the rate of the average
worker's pay because grants of stock options to chief executives
are exploding and now comprise half the average chief executive's
pay package.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
