<SLUG> BC-OLY-SALTLAKECITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALT LAKE CITY STRESS: THE MORE INVESTIGATIONS, THE MORE ANXIETY
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By KIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ When the 2002 Winter Olympics were finally
awarded to this city after years of struggle, many residents said
Utah's capital, long regarded as clean and quiet and little else,
had finally arrived on the world stage, equal to the best.
</P>
<P>
   But now, many people here say that the other shoe has dropped.
With revelations in recent weeks that money and gifts had been
given to International Olympic Committee officials to influence the
bidding process, and with state, federal and independent
investigations churning behind closed doors, Salt Lake City, its
residents say, has also revealed itself to be no better, either.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan De Vries, for one, is glad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people think of it as the capital for the Mormons, the
headquarters of the church, and we shouldn't have any problems,''
said De Vries, a computer programmer who works and lives in the
city. ``But we do. We've got gang-related problems. We've got
corruption in politics. We've got this, that and the other, just
like any other city.''
</P>
<P>
   De Vries said he hoped the collective soul-searching that has
become part of the debate here on the Olympics will have a positive
effect on how the city regards itself in the future. ``Maybe it
will help us focus on our other problems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Ostradicky, a land surveyor who was on her way downtown
to work this morning, said reaching for the Olympic rings had
simply proved the city had feet of clay. ``I guess we are just
normal humans like everybody else, and business is business,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake Organizing Committee has admitted to giving
hundreds of thousands of dollars in gifts, medical treatment,
tuition reimbursements and other perks to IOC members or their
families. But the gifts, the officials have said, were humanitarian
aid, or tokens of good will, and not bribes.
</P>
<P>
   But the multiple investigations under way have accentuated the
sense of held breath. In one downtown building, for example, a team
of United States Justice Department lawyers from Washington has
been questioning witnesses this week in the local FBI offices. Six
floors below, a separate independent ethics investigation by the
organizing committee was conducting its work. A few blocks away, at
the State Capitol, the attorney general had begun her investigation
into possible violation of state laws.
</P>
<P>
   With so many questions still unanswered, perception has
heightened this city's Olympic anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents and local leaders say, for example, that they
think some members of the national and world news media have
falsely elevated the city's supposed ethical and moral purity as a
device to make the bribery allegations appear more newsworthy and
more shocking than they are _ that it could happen (gasp) even
here.
</P>
<P>
   Others say they think that Salt Lake City should genuinely be
held to a higher ethical standard, because of its religious
heritage.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is somewhere in the middle. Economists and
securities law experts say, for example, that Salt Lake City's past
ethical pedigree is not as pristine as local idealists or outsiders
have suggested.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, for example, it was one of the centers in the
nation, along with Denver, in penny stock trading, which was
notorious for its swindles and scams, in which low-priced shares in
often nonexistent companies _ especially in things like gold mines
and oil wells _ were sold to gullible investors.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints,
Michael Otterson, also said it would be the ``height of arrogance''
for him to say that Salt Lake City was more moral or ethical than
other places. What the church does, he said, is teach principles,
and then allows people to govern themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In the Olympic bidding process, Otterson said, the church took
no formal position and donated no money. Individual corporations
owned by the church, however, including The Deseret News and the
company that owns the local CBS television affiliate, did make
contributions to the bid committee totaling about $211,000. And
Otterson said many church members were involved in the bidding
process, including the former president of the organizing
committee, Tom Welch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church believes in following the highest moral and ethical
principles,'' Otterson said.
</P>
<P>
   Just as big a question as right and wrong, however, is who is
talking and who is not. The lawyer for Welch, who ran the Olympic
bid committee until his resignation in 1997 after being accused of
spousal abuse, said his client had not been subpoenaed. The lawyer,
Thomas Schaffer, said Welch had not been questioned by any state or
federal authorities or asked to appear. He said the facts, in any
case, would show Welch had done nothing illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Welch's secretary, Stephanie Pate, however, was interviewed by
Justice Department lawyers and FBI agents Wednesday, with
questioning to resume next week. Her lawyer, David Watkiss, said
his client had done nothing illegal and had not witnessed anything
illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Residents here Friday said that rumor and perception were making
them confused about what to think of themselves. ``In some ways,
when the world is looking at you like this, you could look at it as
a compliment, too _ that Salt Lake lives at a higher standard than
the rest, so they shouldn't have been involved,'' said Duane
Carter, who works in computer security for a local utility company.
``But right now, it's kind of an embarrassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Donna Caporale, an insurance agent, said she believed there
might be a badge of honor, of sorts, yet to be found. The fact that
questions about the Olympics happened to blow up here is partly a
result, she said, that people began admitting what they had done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not too smart,'' she said. ``Or we're too honest.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
