<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-FILMPRODUCTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REEL WORK WINDS DOWN IN L.A. COUNTY IN 1998
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Year-end statistics released Friday for
entertainment production in Los Angeles County don't show a pretty
picture, with off-lot activity falling 4.2 percent in 1998 after
three years of supercharged growth.
</P>
<P>
   The most distressing data, based on permits issued by the
Entertainment Industry Development Corp., comes in three key areas:
feature films, down 13.1 percent; commercials, off 7.5 percent; and
TV, down 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But industry trackers say they're not alarmed, pointing out that
1998's total of 45,653 production days is still a whopping 71
percent above the 1994 level and projecting this year's total will
remain steady with 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``These numbers are pretty much what we expected,'' said Cody
Cluff, EIDC's director. ``The big key will be what happens in
feature films. Most of them are budgeted lower than what we've seen
in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Both The Walt Disney Co. and Warner Bros. have trimmed
big-budget projects from their schedules to focus more on
moderately priced movies, but demand for TV and commercials
continues to be strong, Cluff said. There have usually been 100 and
150 crews working outside studio lots in the county on most days
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are really pretty good,'' Cluff said. ``Communities
treat filming pretty well, and crews are well-behaved.''
</P>
<P>
   Patti Stolkin Archuletta, director of the California Film
Commission, stressed that a leveling off was inevitable. ``We
aren't in a panic,'' she added. ``What we're finding is that we're
not seeing a lot of longer shoots on features. There's no question
that studios are keeping a close watch on the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   The entire 1998 decline can be traced to 25.7 percent and 18.1
percent drops in activity in September and October, respectively,
fueled by back-to-back plunges of 41 percent and 44 percent in
movie production. Some cited runaway production to Canada, which
has far lower costs, and places like New York, which trumpeted
increased production numbers this week.
</P>
<P>
   But Cluff believes that little of the gains in Canadian activity
are coming at Hollywood's expense, and scouts say the flight from
Hollywood is not significant. ``I don't think leaving town is that
prevalent right now,'' said Walter Roshetski, director of
commercial locations for Burbank, Calif.-based Universal Locations.
``I'm not worried about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Roshetski said producers remain attracted to shooting locally
because the presence of film crews is no surprise to residents, who
tend to be mostly cooperative. ``If you go to Chicago or New York,
you may see some shooting, but you're always seeing trucks in Los
Angeles,'' he added. ``It's a way of life out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Thompson, head of L.A.-based Real to Reel scouting service,
said activity has been solid this month and should pick up soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting a lot of TV, like `Providence' and `The
X-Files,' and a lot of commercials, particularly this time of year
because the weather is so much nicer than other parts of the
country,'' he added. ``We are anticipating a rush because we're
getting into pilot season.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said producers and directors are seeking significant
numbers of warehouses, hospitals and relatively simple homes. ``So
our plan is to increase our portfolio of everyday `Father Knows
Best' homes,'' he added. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
