<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5082 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CASE-2TAKES-N     01-22 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CASE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DEFENSE RELIES ON TRIVIALIZING PROSECUTION'S CASE
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-ASSESS,
IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-LEWINSKY, IMPEACH-SCHOLARS) 
 (bl) 
By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In defending President Clinton, his lawyers have
portrayed the case against him as one cobbled together from events
that were often trivial and open to varying interpretations. Above
all, they have argued that the charges fall below the
constitutional standard for removing him from office.
</P>
<P>
   While not defending Clinton's personal behavior, the lawyers
have repeatedly told senators that they are being asked to overturn
an election on what the lawyers contend were flawed conclusions and
disputed facts.
</P>
<P>
   It was a ``staggering thought,'' said White House lawyer Gregory
Craig, that a president could be turned out of office over such
ambiguous issues as the number of times he engaged intimate
relations with Monica Lewinsky. The House managers cited as perjury
the discrepancy between Clinton's statement that he had
inappropriate contact with Ms. Lewinsky on ``several occasions''
and her testimony that there were 11 sexual encounters.
</P>
<P>
   The president's lawyers argued that that the case for removal
was wrong in three fundamental ways: the conclusions that the House
managers drew from the facts were wrong, the accusations did not
meet the legal requirements to prove the charges of perjury or
obstruction of justice, and none of the accusations rose to the
high level of wrongdoing needed to overturn an election.
</P>
<P>
   THE PERJURY CHARGE: `Silly,' `Frivolous' Math
</P>
<P>
   In arguing that the president did not commit perjury before the
grand jury, Craig derided many of the House managers' accusations
as meaningless and trivial. In one instance, the managers asserted
that Clinton had committed perjury with his statement that he and
Ms. Lewinsky had engaged in sexual talk on the telephone ``on
occasion'' while she testified it had occurred 17 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any dispute over this immaterial issue is silly,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   Another example involves the prepared statement Clinton read to
the grand jury Aug. 17 in which he acknowledged intimate conduct,
saying: ``I regret that what began as a friendship came to include
this conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   The House managers told the Senate that such a statement
amounted to perjury because Ms. Lewinsky has testified that their
relationship began with flirting, ``including Ms. Lewinsky showing
the president her underwear,'' and not as a friendship.
</P>
<P>
   That, Craig said, was ``fundamentally frivolous.''
</P>
<P>
   An issue that the White House lawyers did not portray as trivial
was whether Clinton lied when he told the grand jury that he had
not engaged in ``sexual relations'' with Ms. Lewinsky, as the term
was defined in his deposition in the Paula Jones sexual misconduct
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of this issue is the conflicting testimony about
the explicit details of the intimate acts between Ms. Lewinsky and
the president. Without being specific, Clinton essentially
portrayed the relationship to the grand jury as one in which she
stimulated him sexually but he did not reciprocate. Ms. Lewinsky
has testified that the president touched her intimately on several
occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The true nub of the managers' allegation that the president
committed perjury is that he described some of the contact one way
and she described it another,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   The president's defenders told the Senate that such a
discrepancy could not amount to perjury because courts have ruled
that perjury cannot be based simply on two differing sworn
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ed Bryant, R-Tenn., one of the 13 House managers, or
prosecutors, emphasized Friday that Ms. Lewinsky had told her
version of the intimate contact to as many as 10 people at the time
it occurred, the kind of testimony that lends weight to one side in
a swearing contest. He also cited as corroboration White House logs
and Secret Service testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The president's lawyers also complained strongly that the
perjury case was unfair because it included statements made by the
president in the Jones deposition Jan. 17, even though the House
voted down an impeachment article specifically accusing the
president of lying at the deposition.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers' claim that the deposition testimony may be
included rests solely on one statement Clinton made in his grand
jury appearance _ that he had tried to testify truthfully in the
Jones deposition six months earlier. In that deposition, the
managers noted, Clinton said that he could not remember if he had
ever been alone with Ms. Lewinsky or had exchanged gifts with her.
</P>
<P>
   The White House argued that the effort to ``bootstrap'' the
deposition testimony was improper and that, moreover, Clinton told
the grand jury that he was alone with Ms. Lewinsky and did exchange
gifts with her.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers also charged that Clinton had committed
perjury when he stood silent at the Jones deposition as his lawyer,
Robert Bennett, declared there was no sex between the president and
Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   When asked in the grand jury appearance if Bennett's statement
that there ``is no sex of any kind'' was flatly untrue, Clinton
began his answer with the widely criticized phrase, ``It depends
what the meaning of `is' is.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's lawyers have offered two defenses in rebuttal.
First, they argue that Clinton did not speak up because he was not
paying close attention to Bennett at the time. David Kendall,
another of the president's lawyers, also said that Clinton's
parsing of the word ``is'' was an effort to explain Bennett's
thinking, not a legalistic maneuver on the president's part.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   THE OBSTRUCTION CHARGE: What Human Beings Do
</P>
<P>
   Deputy White House counsel Cheryl Mills argued that the
president had not obstructed justice when his secretary, Betty
Currie, collected some gifts he had given Ms. Lewinsky that were
under subpoena by the Jones lawyers. Ms. Mills said there had been
no direct testimony that Clinton initiated or had anything to do
with their retrieval and that Mrs. Currie repeatedly testified that
it was Ms. Lewinsky's idea to get rid of them.
</P>
<P>
   She also argued that there had been no proof of obstruction in
Clinton's questioning of Mrs. Currie about Ms. Lewinsky the day
after he was asked about her in the Jones deposition. Mrs. Currie
has testified that the president put questions to her like,
``Monica came on to me and I never touched her, right?''
</P>
<P>
   The managers have asserted that Clinton's colloquy with Mrs.
Currie amounted to witness tampering, because he was trying to use
Mrs. Currie to support his denials of a sexual relationship with
Ms. Lewinsky. The White House counters that she was not then a
witness, and that Clinton was merely trying to refresh his memory.
</P>
<P>
   In her presentation, Ms. Mills stressed another explanation:
that Clinton was trying to prepare himself for an anticipated
``media firestorm.''
</P>
<P>
   The House managers have asserted that Clinton played a major
role in encouraging Ms. Lewinsky to file what they say was a false
affidavit in the Jones case and also rehearsed cover stories with
her.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall argued that the affidavit was not false, because Ms.
Lewinsky shared the president's view that oral sex was not sex
under the Jones lawyers' definition. As for the cover stories, he
said that they were conversations that occurred ``when they were
both trying to conceal their improper relationship from others
while it was going on. Cover stories are an almost inevitable part
of every improper relationship between two human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendall also attacked the managers' contention that Clinton's
help in finding Ms. Lewinsky a job was aimed at buying her
cooperation in concealing her relationship with the president. He
cited Ms. Lewinsky's testimony that no one had ever urged her to
lie and that she had begun her job search well before she emerged
as a possible witness in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   THE STANDARD: Defining High Crimes
</P>
<P>
   The legal arguments over whether the crimes of perjury and
obstruction as charged against Clinton are enough to warrant
removal from office involve less the facts of the case and more the
history and interpretation of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers asserted that the president's actions
amounted to the high crimes and misdemeanors outlined in the
Constitution and required for his removal from office. Given the
murkiness of what qualifies as a high crime, the managers invoked
recent and ancient history and analogies that were homespun and
academic.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's a high crime?'' asked Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C. ``How
about if an important person hurts somebody of low means? It's not
very scholarly, but I think it's the truth. I think that's what
they meant by high crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig made the case that impeachment should be reserved for
``assaults on the system of government'' and that nothing in the
impeachment case qualified as that.
</P>
<P>
   He argued that if the president's misconduct ``does not
implicate the office or the powers of the presidency, the remedy is
in a legal process involving prosecution, conviction and punishment
in the courts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These articles do not justify the nullification of the
American people's free choice in a national election.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
