<SLUG> BC-DUSTIN-DRAG-DAMAGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUSTIN HOFFMAN WINS SUIT IN PHOTO ALTERATION
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif.)  (bl)  
By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a decision that could affect the way magazines satirize
public figures, a judge Friday ordered Los Angeles magazine to pay
$1.5 million in actual damages to Dustin Hoffman for publishing a
computer-altered image of the actor in an evening dress and high
heels.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1997, the magazine used a computer-generated photograph
of Hoffman in a fashion spread titled ``Grand Illusions,'' in which
famous movie stills were altered by computer, changing the way
actors were dressed.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman's head, taken from a still from the 1982 movie
``Tootsie,'' in which he dressed mostly in women's clothing, was
placed on a body wearing a Richard Tyler designer dress and Ralph
Lauren shoes.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Dickran Tevrizian scheduled another
hearing for Thursday to determine the amount of additional punitive
damages to the actor. Hoffman filed a $5 million lawsuit against
the magazine last year, alleging violation of publicity rights in
his suit against Fairchild Publications, the owner and publisher of
Los Angeles magazine. Fairchild is owned by Capital Cities/ABC,
which is turn owned by Walt Disney Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In his lawsuit, Hoffman also alleged that the magazine violated
the Lanham Act, which monitors product endorsement, and that the
magazine engaged in unfair competition when it created and
published the picture.
</P>
<P>
   In the first paragraph of the decision, Tevrizian praised
Hoffman's acting career and wrote, ``It can be said that Mr.
Hoffman is truly one our country's living treasures.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman's attorney, Charles Shephard, said that while Los
Angeles magazine had argued that it should be allowed to depict
Hoffman in whatever manner it wished, the court ruled that ``the
photographs were manipulated and cannibalized to such an extent
that the celebrities were commercially exploited and robbed of
their dignity, professionalism and talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Taylor, who was also depicted in the fashion spread,
has not sued the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer Beck, the editor in chief of Los Angeles magazine, would
not take any phone calls relating to the matter Friday. Julie
Hoover, a spokeswoman for ABC, issued this statement:
</P>
<P>
   ``We are disappointed with the result and plan to appeal.
Editorial use of the material in question is protected by the First
Amendment, and we strongly believe our use was appropriate and
protected.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC plans to appeal the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawyers think the decision may cast a creative pall over
the magazine industry. Richard Emery, a New York lawyer
specializing in First Amendment issues, said the decision could
cause ``a tremendous chilling effect on magazine creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's a shame that Dustin Hoffman, whose life blood is
satire, among other things, would resort to this sort of device on
his own behalf,'' he added. ``There is a fundamental hypocrisy
there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
