<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5097 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS &LR;      01-22 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS TALK OF ENDING CLINTON TRIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As chapter two in President Clinton's impeachment
trial unfolded Friday, Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., surprised the
Senate by announcing he would offer a motion to dismiss the case as
early as Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The statement by the influential elder senator, who had been
undecided about conviction, pointed to a movement among some
senators to end the trial without calling witnesses, despite the
prosecution's best efforts to head it off.
</P>
<P>
   While indicating that they would likely vote against Byrd's
motion, key Republicans suggested that it was time to start looking
for an exit strategy nonetheless. Sens. Orrin Hatch of Utah and
Olympia Snowe of Maine agreed with Byrd that there are not enough
votes to convict Clinton. Hatch offered his own plan to end the
trial, suggesting that senators allow both sides to sum up their
cases early next week. Senators would then vote on a motion to
adjourn with language attached that recognizes the House articles
of impeachment as ``the highest vote of condemnation and of censure
for the president's despicable acts.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk of ending the trial came as senators moved Friday into the
first of two days of questioning. Senators were allowed to submit
written questions to House prosecutors and White House lawyers
through Chief Justice William Rehnquist.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's motion to dismiss would need a simple majority of 51
senators and would end the trial without a final up or down vote on
whether Clinton should be convicted of the two articles of
impeachment the House filed against him last month.
</P>
<P>
   Although Byrd said that, in his view, the president was guilty
of wrongful conduct in his attempt to hide his illicit relationship
with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky, he added that he
saw no reason to prolong the trial absent the two-thirds majority
required to convict.
</P>
<P>
   Most Democrats and a few Republicans are expected to vote
against conviction, making the likelihood of attaining the 67 votes
necessary to remove Clinton from office a mathematical
impossibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced that the necessary two-thirds for conviction
are not there and that they are not likely to develop. I have also
become convinced that lengthening this trial will only prolong and
deepen the divisive, bitter and polarizing effect this sorry affair
has visited upon our nation,'' Byrd said.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's statement drew support from many of his Democratic
colleagues who are eager to wrap up the case with their party's
presidency still intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have had a fair process ... The time has now come
for us to dismiss the case,`` said House Minority Leader Tom
Daschle, D-S.D.
</P>
<P>
   A few more Republicans also joined the growing opposition to the
idea of calling witnesses, although they said they would not
necessarily support Byrd's motion for an outright dismissal of the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Wayne Allard of Colorado, for example, said, ``Right now I
don't see a real demanding need for witnesses.'' He said that both
sides have done a good job of making their cases and that most of
what he needs to know to make a decision on Clinton's guilt or
innocence has already been presented.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to questions from senators, the House's chief
prosecutor, Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde of Illinois,
literally begged the senators not to adjourn the trial before
allowing them to put on a complete prosecution, including taking
more testimony from Lewinsky and other key witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   He said that not allowing witnesses to appear at the trial would
be ``sending a terrible message to the people of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're saying, I guess, perjury is OK if it's about sex,
obstruction is OK,'' Hyde told the senators.
</P>
<P>
   Without mentioning Byrd by name, he cautioned that approving a
motion to dismiss would amount to a ``cavalier treatment of our
articles of impeachment.'' Dismissing the case, he said, would
``throw out the window the fact that the president's lies and
stonewalling have cost millions of dollars that could have been
obviated.'' He said it also would cause ``damage to sexual
harassment laws'' and make it ``more difficult to prosecute people
in the military or elsewhere for perjury.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are serious consequences,'' Hyde said, adding that while
the House impeachment case may have been an ``annoyance'' for the
Senate to deal with, it was at least ``a constitutional annoyance''
that should be played out to the end with witnesses and a final
vote on whether to convict and remove the 42nd president from
office.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde drew support from Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, who told
reporters during a break in Friday's proceedings that it was
impossible to ``have an impartial trial without calling
witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   He reminded senators that they have a responsibility to history
to conduct the impeachment process through to the end so that
future congresses will have a complete blueprint to guide them.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the Senate had held final votes on the guilt or
innocence of 13 federal judges brought before them on impeachment
charges, he said Byrd's motion was ``inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's private attorney David Kendall, however, argued that
calling the same witnesses who testified before a federal grand
jury in the investigation of the Clinton-Lewinsky matter would only
give senators ``a 6th, 7th and 8th account'' of what's already
known.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calling witnesses will add nothing to the record already
before you,'' Kendall said.
</P>
<P>
   He warned that bringing in witnesses would only delay the
conclusion of the trial for ``many months,'' because Clinton's
legal team would have to be given a chance to depose and cross
examine them before they appear.
</P>
<P>
   The clash over whether to simply end the trial or continue with
the calling of witnesses came as the House prosecutors and
Clinton's lawyers slogged their way through five hours of rebuttal
and counter-rebuttal in response to questions thrown at them by
Democratic and Republican senators. The question-and-answer session
will continue at 10 a.m. CST Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The questions were spoon-fed, for the most part, to each side by
lawmakers sympathetic to one argument or the other. But the answers
broke little new ground, even though they did on occasion cause
senators to sit up and take note as the defense and prosecution
engaged in a clash over evidence and legal precedents.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Rep. James Rogan of California, one of the House
prosecutors, assailed the White House defense arguments as nothing
more than ``legal schizophrenia'' meant to confuse and obfuscate
the evidence in the case.
</P>
<P>
   White House counsel Charles F.C. Ruff countered with his own
observation that the House prosecutors, ``in their straw-man
building role,'' have tried ``to suggest that our position somehow
is so distant from constitutional reality ... that we could not
conceive of a situation in which private conduct, no matter how
egregious, would lead to removal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not the case,'' Ruff said.
</P>
<P>
   As the day's proceedings wound down, at least one of the
prosecutors, Rep. George Gekas of Pennsylvania, appeared to sense
that he and his colleagues were fighting a losing battle.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by The Associated Press if there were enough votes among
the 55 Republicans and 45 Democrats in the Senate to convict
Clinton, Gekas replied, ``As of now, no.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
