<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5101 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-POPE-NYT &LR;      01-22 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE, IN MEXICO, URGES MORAL PRESSURE ON U.S.  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Thousands of glinting lights, reflections of
mirrors held up by Mexican followers, welcomed Pope John Paul II's
plane as he arrived in Mexico Friday to address Latin and North
America as a whole. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First the pope gave a word of warning about the responsibilities
of the world's last superpower. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``After the collapse of the Soviet Union, the United States
remained alone,'' he told reporters traveling on his plane. ``I do
not know if this is good or not, but that is the way it is.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Paul, 78, who will meet with President Clinton next week in
St. Louis, chose Mexico as a meeting place for bishops from all the
Americas to underscore his point that the churches should work more
closely together.
</P>
<P>
   But he also wants his bishops to pool their strengths to exert
greater moral pressure on Washington. In his arrival speech at the
airport, where 4,000 school children, church bells and mariachi
bands welcomed him, the pope sounded a theme that will be a
leitmotif of his pastoral visits to Mexico City and St. Louis,
calling for ``a just society, open to technological progress that
is in harmony with necessary moral progress.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stooped and frail, his hands shaky with the symptoms of
Parkinson's disease, the pope nevertheless looked hale and alert as
he answered reporters' questions before landing. He said that after
this, his 85th papal trip, he still wanted to travel, and named
Russia and China, ``the biggest ones,'' as leading his list. ``So
far, I haven't lost the desire or the will,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He reported that he was ``quite pleased'' with the results of
his trip to Cuba a year ago, noting that afterward President Fidel
Castro allowed Christmas to be celebrated freely, ``and that is a
great step forward.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There has been little progress in Chiapas, a southern Mexican
state where guerrillas have been fighting government troops. Roman
Catholic priests who minister to the Indian population there have
been accused by the government of supporting the leftist
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   The pope did not share his own views of Bishop Samuel Ruiz
Garcia, who is accused by some in the government of being too close
to the rebels, but he did make clear that his views on liberation
theology ``or its offshoots'' have not changed since he condemned
it in Mexico 20 years ago, on his first papal trip. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some thought of substituting liberation theology with
the theology of an indigenous movement,'' he said. Such thinking
was too indebted to Marxism to work, he said, adding, ``I think the
true solution can only be solidarity and dialogue.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In his arrival speech, delivered before President Ernesto
Zedillo, the pope omitted a passage in his written text that
mentioned Chiapas along with other regions of Mexico. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the plane, the pope was presented with a huge velvet sombrero
by a Mexican reporter, who sought to recreate the moment in 1979
when the pope happily donned a sombrero and delighted millions of
Mexicans. This time, the pope hesitated, and when she urged him to
put it on, placed it with a trembling hand over his head for a
second. It was a poignant moment, and the pope seemed wistfully
aware of the passage of time and youthful vigor.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what had changed since his first visit, he replied slowly,
``Above all, we are all older, you, and also I.`` But he noted one
change for the better. ``When I came in 1979 the priests who came
to see me were forbidden to walk around in their cassocks,'' he
said, referring to the period before 1991 when the Mexican
Constitution was fiercely anti-clerical. Mexican policy toward the
church has changed, he said, but the Mexican people have not.
``They are still enthusiastic.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With church bells clanging a welcome in thousands of villages,
Mexican television reported that one million people turned out to
catch a glimpse of the pope. Zedillo embraced him on the airport
runway. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Your Holiness is welcomed by a people that suffers material
wants but has an immense spiritual richness,'' Zedillo said. ``That
spiritual wealth strengthens the Mexican people's perseverance as
it seeks to multiply opportunities, diminish inequalities and
achieve a dignified life for all.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pope quickly got a taste of Mexico's vigorous new pluralism
when, after an hour's drive to Mexico City's historic center, past
thousands of Mexicans waving yellow-and-white Vatican flags, he
heard the mayor excoriate Zedillo's economic policies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The city's mayor, Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, who is expected to run
for president next year at the head of a leftist party, said the
government's current economic policies have brought ``tremendous
deterioration in Mexicans' quality of life.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, as everywhere else, the pope also intends to remind
people of the dangers of materialism. In this country of contrasts,
his message against consumerism and heartless profiteering clashed
with the unbridled marketing surrounding his visit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Billboards lining the streets from the airport welcomed him with
the words, ``Mexico Always Faithful.'' There were two images: the
pope's and the Pepsi logo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A full-page advertisement for Sealy mattresses in one newspaper
showed a reflective angel looking skyward through the clouds, under
a bold headline: ``Starting today we're going to experience
unforgettable dreams.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kodak used a photo of the pope in advertisements Friday,
offering to develop snapshots of the pope for free. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One Mexican snack food company, Sabritas, which is owned by a
division of Pepsico, has in recent weeks packaged its potato chips
with a wrap-around strip featuring John Paul's photo. And in a
televised commercial for Sabritas products, Norberto Rivera
Carrera, the archbishop of Mexico City, appeared personally to
thank the company for helping to underwrite the pope's visit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amid an outpouring of articles in Mexican newspapers criticizing
the Sabritas and other advertisements, Rivera defended the
commercials, telling reporters that the archdiocese had requested
financial help but had in no way intended to endorse any
corporation's products. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But many church officials expressed irritation with the
advertisements. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The archbishop of Merida, Yucatan, Emilio Berlie Belaunzaran,
waded into the debate this week, pleading with Mexicans ``not to
banalize the image of the pope.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
