u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-OSERLUND-NYT &LR;      01-22 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OSERLUND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FAIR PLAY FOR OSTERSUND  (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Jan. 23,
1999:
</P>
<P>
   The early round of housecleaning the International Olympic
Committee will undertake this weekend should sweep the shakedown
artists from the governing body of the Olympic movement. But far
more needs to be done to clean up after the bribery scandal
engulfing the organization's choice of Salt Lake City for the next
Winter Olympics. The committee will need to devise an ethically
tight process for choosing future sites, and should reconsider its
award of the Winter Games to Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Word that a top Australian Olympic official offered $35,000
apiece to two IOC members the night before Sydney won the 2000
summer games by a two-vote margin over Beijing should add a sense
of urgency to the IOC meeting in Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   The privilege of being the host of the Olympic Games should
never be sold to the highest bidder in a silent auction.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's housecleaning will be cold comfort to the Swedish
town of Ostersund and its dreams of being host to the 2002 Winter
Olympics. Unlike some of the protagonists in Salt Lake City's
successful campaign for the 2002 games, the folks of Ostersund say
they abided by the rules. They spurned offers to buy delegate votes
with lavish gifts, money, cars and other bribery. Embracing this
kind of influence-peddling, including scholarships and jobs, helped
Salt Lake ingratiate itself with some delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Cities that have conducted bribe-free campaigns to win the
Summer or Winter Games should have been able to compete on a level
playing field, not one tilted by money and other forms of
corruption. The decision by the IOC's internal investigative panel,
headed by the Montreal lawyer Richard Pound, to broaden its inquiry
beyond Salt Lake to include the host-city competitions for the
Games held between 1996, the year the Summer Games were in Atlanta,
and 2006 is a wise one.
</P>
<P>
   The findings of Pound's panel of inquiry should allow the IOC to
determine which host-city competitions were fatally tainted by
bribes-for-votes. In cases where cities advanced to the finals or
won the right to be a host city because of influence-peddling, the
IOC will need to reopen the competition for those Games. Site
selection for both the 2000 and 2002 Games should begin anew.
</P>
<P>
   Those with oversight responsibilities for amateur and
professional sports now devote a good deal of their time to trying
to banish unscrupulous athletes who take performance-enhancing
drugs. The IOC cannot expect to command the respect and confidence
of nations if it enforces one ethical standard for athletes but
tolerates an anything-goes milieu for competitions to be the host
city.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 2146EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0448 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5104 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-TERROR-NYT &LR;      01-22 0387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TERROR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THWARTING TOMORROW'S TERRORS  (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Jan. 23,
1999:
</P>
<P>
   Biological and chemical terrorism and disabling attacks on
American computer networks are not just the stuff of novels and
films. Nerve gas already has been released in the Tokyo subways.
Hackers and virus programs have struck supposedly secure computer
systems. President Clinton is right to plan a coordinated federal
response to what could become a major problem.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the $2.8 billion program Clinton unveiled
Friday to detect, prevent or limit the damage from such terrorist
attacks is on the mark. The money would finance research into new
vaccines; the stockpiling of antibiotics and other medications
likely to be needed in response to terrorist attacks; federal
training of state and city medical response teams, and research and
training in new computer security methods. A strong federal role is
needed in all these areas, and the spending levels are about right
for current needs.
</P>
<P>
   The administration promises to protect constitutional liberties
and individual civil rights as it assumes a larger role in
terrorist surveillance. Still, two areas bear watching. There have
been discussions in the Pentagon, but no decision, about creating a
new domestic military command to combat terrorism. That would erode
the long-established legal principle that America's armed forces
should not be involved in domestic law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   There is also potential danger in federal monitoring of civilian
computer networks for intrusion by hackers. Such monitoring could
lead to improper government surveillance of private correspondence
on the Internet and elsewhere. The right role for Washington here
is financing research and providing technical advice to the private
sector about computer security techniques and software.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Clinton program warrants rapid Congressional
approval and funding. Lethal germs and deadly nerve gases are now
easily prepared in bathroom laboratories, and computer hacking
skills are common among high school students. Protecting the
American public from biological, chemical and computer attack
should not get bogged down in Washington's partisan warfare.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
