<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5108 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SCANDAL-NYT &LR;      01-22 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCANDAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC SCANDAL WIDENS: PAYMENTS LINKED TO SUMMER GAMES IN SYDNEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah, Australia)  (See also OLY-SALTLAKECITY) 
(fe) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Olympic bribery scandal expanded to a new front on Friday
when documents were made public showing that the Australian Olympic
Committee offered tens of thousands of dollars to two African
members of the International Olympic Committee the night before the
decisive vote on the site for the 2000 Summer Games. Sydney was
awarded the games after it defeated Beijing by two votes.
</P>
<P>
   The documents released on Friday contain two letters from John
Coates, the president of the Australian Olympic Committee and the
head of Sydney's bid to be named host of the 2000 Games, offering
payments of $5,000 a year for seven years each to national sports
programs run by Charles Mukora of Kenya and Maj. Gen. Francis
Nyangweso of Uganda. The letters were delivered Sept. 23, 1993 in
Monte Carlo, Monaco, hours before Sydney edged Beijing, 45-43, in
voting among members of the I.O.C.
</P>
<P>
   Australian officials said Friday night that the payments had in
fact been made for the years 1994 through 1998 and that they had
insured that the payments went to the sports programs and not the
two officials. Because voting on awarding the games is secret, it
is impossible to say for certain if the two Africans ultimately
backed Sydney. Attempts to reach Mukora and Nyangweso Friday night
were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   An official with the I.O.C. said the group was investigating the
actions of the Australian Olympic Committee and that the affair
would be taken up at a Sunday meeting of the 11-member executive
board of the international committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any proof or documents will be looked into,'' said Franklin
Servan-Schreiber, a spokesman for the I.O.C.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure of possible misconduct by the Australian Olympic
Committee is only the latest blow for the international body, an
organization that has already concluded that officials with the
Salt Lake City effort to be awarded the 2002 Winter Games had given
hundreds of thousands of dollars in cash and other benefits to
I.O.C. members in an effort to gain favor.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bashir Mohamed Attarabulsi of Libya resigned Friday in
the wake of investigations into the Salt Lake City bid. His son,
Suher, has said that he received tuition assistance to two Utah
universities, as well as $700 a month in living expenses from Salt
Lake City Olympic officials. Suher Attarabulsi once even listed his
home address as the office of the Salt Lake Olympic committee. The
resignation was the second this week by a committee member,
following the departure of Pirjo Haggman of Finland, who resigned
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 11 other committee members face suspension or
expulsion in connection with the Salt Lake scandal when the
executive board meets this weekend in Lausanne, Switzerland, to
hear a report of wrongdoing in Salt Lake City's bid for the 2002
Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Sydney Friday night, Coates said the
Australian Olympic Committee had negotiated deals in the summer of
1993 with a handful of African and other countries to provide
sports scholarships and other assistance. He said he decided to
commit to precise cash payments the night before the vote because
he felt demoralized about Sydney's chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was leveraging our bid,'' Coates said, defending both the
initial arrangements to provide assistance and the promises of
specific dollar amounts. ``But that was within the I.O.C.'s
guidelines and is within the I.O.C.'s guidelines until they rule
otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   According to one senior U.S. Olympic official, the latest
revelations could lead to additional calls for Juan Antonio
Samaranch, the powerful president of the I.O.C., either to take
drastic action aimed at reform or to perhaps resign. Accused
members who do not resign this weekend will be suspended, Samaranch
has said, and will face expulsion by a vote of the entire I.O.C.
membership in March.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Schultz, the executive director of the U.S. Olympic
Committee, said Samaranch was wounded and might soon face what he
called a ``palace revolt.'' He said his survival would probably
depend on whether a thorough housecleaning is carried out in the
wake of the Salt Lake City scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's assume a lot don't resign,'' Schultz said of the members
implicated in wrongdoing. ``If there is unanimity to vote these
people out and make changes, I think he will end up in a strong
position. If they can't do that, not only Samaranch but the whole
I.O.C. is in trouble. That will look bad all around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Schultz became the first high-ranking Olympic official to speak
publicly of the precariousness of Samaranch's hold on the Olympic
leadership after 18 years as president. The 78-year-old Spanish
marquis has said that he will serve out his current term, which
ends in 2001. The U.S. Olympic Committee has strongly expressed its
support for Samaranch, and Anita DeFrantz, an international vice
president from Los Angeles, has also said that she firmly believes
he should remain in office.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, in an interview with The Associated Press in
Switzerland, Samaranch appeared committed to remaining in his job.
``In this moment, I have to be at the head of the I.O.C. more than
ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters in Lausanne, Switzerland, where the I.O.C.
has its headquarters, the senior International Olympic Committee
official from Australia said that the news was so disturbing that
it could raise calls for the games to be removed from Sydney. The
official, Kevan Gosper, said he did not previously know of the
inducement offers but described them to the Associated Press as
being ``beyond good will'' and called for all Sydney documents to
be made public and for a full-scale investigation of the city's bid
process to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Thomas, a spokesman for the Sydney Organizing Committee,
said the idea of taking the Games from Sydney was not realistic.
``We are 20 months away,'' he said. ``How else could they put on
the games?''
</P>
<P>
   Schultz said in an interview that he believed, at this point,
that the 2000 Summer Games would not be removed to another city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't think so,'' Schultz said. ``I would hope not. It
will be a spectacular site for the games. They've invested so much
money in new facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it would be impossible to move the 2000 games at such a
late date, ``I suppose nothing is impossible. But you'd have to go
someplace where they've got their venues in place, like Seoul.''
The South Korean capital was host the 1988 Summer Games and is
preparing to be a co-host, with Japan, of the 2002 World Cup in
soccer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
