<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE CENTRAL BANK OF BRAZIL ACTS TO STABILIZE CURRENCY
</P>
<P>
   Faced with another steep decline in the value of its currency,
Brazil's central bank used more of its dwindling reserves of
dollars to buy Brazilian money in the foreign exchange market. The
bank's action helped stabilize the value of the currency, the real.
But it did little to calm the nerves of financial analysts and
economists on edge over the country's future.
</P>
<P>
   The main stock market index, the Bovespa, fell 1.79 percent, to
7,190.21, its second consecutive drop.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET FEVER STARTS TO COOL DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Internet fever has been growing as shares of newly public
companies have soared. But this week, a bit of the air leaked out
of what many Wall Street pros call the Internet bubble and many
analysts are warning of a steep decline that could rattle the wider
market.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING SETTLES DISCRIMINATION SUIT
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Boeing announced a proposed $15 million settlement
to a racial discrimination suit brought by hundreds of its workers
in the Seattle and Philadelphia areas who contended that
discrimination and retaliation were common at Boeing plants.
</P>
<P>
   DUSTIN HOFFMAN WINS MAGAZINE SUIT
</P>
<P>
   A judge has ordered Los Angeles magazine to pay $1.5 million in
actual damages to the actor Dustin Hoffman for publishing a
computer-altered image of him in an evening dress and high heels.
The magazine had used Hoffman's head, taken from a still from the
1982 movie ``Tootsie,'' and placed it on a body wearing a Richard
Tyler designer dress and Ralph Lauren shoes.
</P>
<P>
   MANAGERS BLAMED FOR AIRPORT WOES
</P>
<P>
   A report by a government commission laid blame for the problems
when Hong Kong's $20 billion airport opened on its expatriate
managers. The report said they should have asked for a two-month
delay in the opening to fix bugs in its flight information screens,
baggage-handling systems and cargo terminal.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHER HEALTH PREMIUMS PROPOSED
</P>
<P>
   Medicare beneficiaries with relatively high incomes would have
to pay higher premiums under proposals outlined by the chairman of
a congressional commission seeking ways to avert a financial crisis
in the health insurance program for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the poorest among the nation's 39 million Medicare
beneficiaries, people with incomes below $10,000 a year, are going
without aid from government safety net programs intended to help
them pay their health care expenses.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL'S MARKET SHARE DECLINES
</P>
<P>
   Intel's share of the microprocessor market fell to 75.7 percent
from 87.1 percent in the fourth quarter as its rival, Advanced
Micro Devices, stole business, a research firm said.
</P>
<P>
   DAIMLERCHRYSLER TALKS WITH NISSAN
</P>
<P>
   The two chairmen of DaimlerChrysler held ``constructive
discussions'' with the president of Nissan Motor, Yoshikazu Hanawa,
about its truck affiliate, but did not disclose any details. The
Japanese automaker, with $20 billion in debt, has recently put
itself up for sale. DaimlerChrysler had already been holding talks
with Nissan Motor about its Nissan Diesel division.
</P>
<P>
   SIEMENS NET INCOME RISES 12 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Higher sales in Europe sent net income for the German
electronics company Siemens up 12 percent in the fiscal first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   BANKERS TRUST TO PAY BONUS
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Trust, which Germany's Deutsche Bank is about to
acquire, has agreed to pay employees about $1.1 billion in bonuses
for 1998, when it lost $6 million. The bonuses, to be awarded this
month, include cash, stock and partnership shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
