<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-FOODSTAMPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FOOD STAMP INFRACTIONS  (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Jan. 23,
1999:
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's boast about cutting New York City's
welfare rolls suddenly has a thinner ring to it. As Rachel Swarns
wrote in The New York Times on Wednesday, federal investigators
from the Department of Agriculture found that the city's new
rigorous welfare-to-work program was in ``substantial
noncompliance'' with the federal Food Stamp Act.
</P>
<P>
   In a draft report, the department criticizes the city for not
immediately telling welfare applicants they could apply for food
stamps. It also chastises the state for not monitoring the program.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the state is criticizing the city from the other
direction _ arguing that Giuliani's welfare workers are giving too
many of the state's food stamps to ineligible immigrants. As for
the federal program, state officials say they found city workers
denying emergency access for eligible applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the mayor is charging federal officials with issuing
a ``political document'' to impose ``user-friendly'' welfare
regulations on the city. A welfare system friendly to users is
nearly the opposite of Giuliani's ideal.
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan federal court, advocates for the poor are arguing
this week that the mayor's welfare plan is so severe that many
applicants walk away without even realizing that they qualify for
help with their grocery bills. On Thursday, city officials promised
changes in the application process, including new forms for
applicants and retraining for workers. But the city could still
require a second visit to secure food stamps, a delay that may
violate federal law.
</P>
<P>
   As the mayor and his administrators have insisted, their goal is
to encourage welfare recipients to become independent, mainly by
finding work. For many women with children, this is especially
difficult because to work they need child care _ one promise by the
city and state that is still far from reality. Those unable to find
work are being pushed to look for help from the nearest friend,
family member or charity. As a last resort, after much effort and
several visits to the city office, welfare is available.
</P>
<P>
   New York City's new welfare workers, now called ``financial
advisers,'' should understand that food stamps and Medicaid can
often help people climb back into the workplace. Promoting
independence, however lofty a goal, cannot always mean a bracing
lecture and a quick shove out the door.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 2153EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0455 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5113 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-PARRACK-NYT     01-22 0387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-PARRACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDWARD T. PARRACK, 84, EX-HEAD OF KETCHUM ADVERTISING AGENCY 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Edward T. Parrack, an advertising executive who supervised some
of the best-known campaigns in the early years of television, died
Jan. 13 at his home in Oakland in western Pennsylvania. He was 84.
</P>
<P>
   As an account executive of Ketchum MacLeod &AMP; Grove, an
international advertising and public relations agency based in
Pittsburgh, he helped organize the commercial sponsorship of the
nationally televised political conventions that nominated Dwight
Eisenhower and Adlai Stevenson. Along the way, the conventions
helped to make household names of Walter Cronkite, the CBS newsman,
and Betty Furness, a spokeswoman for Westinghouse appliances.
</P>
<P>
   Parrack also arranged for the sponsorship of the first televised
broadcasts of football by teams affiliated with the National
Collegiate Athletic Association, said Gerald Voros, a longtime
colleague at Ketchum.
</P>
<P>
   Parrack joined Ketchum in 1936 after graduating from the
University of Pittsburgh. He became assistant to George Ketchum,
the president and a founder of the agency, in 1940. He was chief
executive from 1962 until shortly before he retired in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   As president and later chairman, he helped to transform Ketchum
from a medium-sized Pittsburgh agency that specialized in big
hometown accounts like Gulf Oil, H.J. Heinz and Pittsburgh Plate
Glass into an international business with offices in London and
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Ketchum acquired Botsford, Constantine &AMP; McCarty, a West Coast
agency in 1969. Three years ago, Ketchum itself was bought by the
Omnicom Group, based in New York, the world's largest advertising
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Parrack was born in New York in 1914 and moved to Pittsburgh as
a teen-ager in 1926. During World War II, he was a Lend-Lease
officer for Poland, Greece and Yugoslavia, and in 1945 he was a
special assistant to the secretary of state, Edward R. Stettinius,
at the San Francisco conference that created the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   He was a life trustee of the Carnegie Institute and served on a
number of hospital and private school boards.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife, Elizabeth Felix Parrack of
Pittsburgh; a son, Edward Jr. of New York; and two grandsons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
