<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-BYRD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BYRD SAYS HE'LL ATTEMPT TO END IMPEACHMENT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Impeach-Questions)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's impeachment trial took a twist
Friday as Senator Robert C. Byrd, dean of Senate Democrats and one
of Clinton's harshest critics, abruptly called for dismissing the
charges to ``end this sad and sorry time for our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's move came at a critical juncture, as senators face a
potentially explosive decision next week on whether to prolong the
trial for weeks, if not months, by calling witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   By seeking the dismissal, as early as Monday, Byrd was seen by
members of both parties as galvanizing Senate Democrats against the
impeachment charges and increasing the pressure on Republican
leaders to engineer a relatively swift conclusion to the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, a former Senate majority leader who is influential among
members of both parties, had opposed dismissing the charges until
Friday. Although senators in both parties said Byrd's proposal is
not likely to attract the 51 votes required to dismiss the charges,
they agreed the move may hasten the push for a bipartisan pact to
end the proceedings soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Byrd's decision really increases the possibilities,''
said Senator John F. Kerry, who is pushing for a bipartisan plan to
wrap up the two-week trial. ``It gives greater weight to the
dismissal vote in a way that may compel some people to find some
other resolution faster.''
</P>
<P>
   The development unfolded as Clinton's lawyers and 13 House
Republicans who are prosecuting the impeachment case submitted to
five hours of questioning by senators. The Senate will conduct a
final round of questions and answers Saturday, scheduled to begin
at 10 a.m., in a prelude to next week's showdown.
</P>
<P>
   Although both sides scored points in the initial question
period, many senators said Byrd's move and private negotiations
over the next phase of the trial had greater potential to affect
the outcome of the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's proposal ``is a profound idea,'' said Senator Richard C.
Shelby, an Alabama Republican who is seen as leaning against the
impeachment charges. ``He is an institution here, a man of great
respect, who surprised a lot of people by doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   But GOP conservatives, who propelled the impeachment charges
through the House and hold considerable sway in the Senate, lashed
out at Byrd's move as a way for Democrats to skirt a direct vote on
the two articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great defender of Senate procedure has lost his way,''
said Senator Rick Santorum, a Pennsylvania Republican. ``Here's a
man who talks about honor in the Senate, and he wants to
short-circuit the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy fired back, telling reporters ``our
founding fathers would be rolling over in their graves'' if the
Senate voted for the articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the House Republicans remained steadfast. Responding to
questions from senators, the GOP managers launched their final push
to extend the trial with witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The witness issue is crucial because Republicans face the
possibility of a public backlash if they approve prolonging the
trial with witnesses on a party-line vote. Polls show the public
wants a speedy end to the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the GOP dilemma, Jim Nicholson, who was reelected
party chairman Friday, acknowledged Republicans ``have sustained
political damage'' because of the impeachment saga. But he asserted
that Democrats ultimately will be hurt for defending Clinton and
``failing to stand up for basic democratic...values.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Senate floor, Representative Bill McCollum of Florida
voiced the prosecution's enduring desire to extend the trial,
saying ``The House definitely holds to the position that we should
call witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the lead House manager, Representative Henry J. Hyde,
urged Senate leaders in a letter Friday to invite Clinton to
testify. The letter followed several days of closed-door debate by
the House team over whether to seek the president's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is charged with lying under oath to a federal grand jury
and obstructing justice by trying to cover up his affair with
Monica S. Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the president is the only individual with knowledge of
almost every material fact relevant to the trial, the House
believes that his testimony would greatly help to expeditiously and
fairly bring this matter to a close,'' Hyde's letter stated.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Senate's interest in calling witnesses,
particularly Clinton, has waned in recent days, although a short
witness phase still appears likely.
</P>
<P>
   Exploiting the trend, Clinton's private lawyer, David E.
Kendall, argued during the question period that witnesses ``would
add nothing'' to the process except satisfy the House managers who
are ``hoping maybe something will turn up.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendall also raised the specter of a trial grinding on
indefinitely. ``I think you are looking realistically at a process
of many months,'' he said, causing a buzz among Republican
senators.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby is one of several GOP senators who have expressed little
or no interest in summoning witnesses. Among the others are
Senators James M. Jeffords of Vermont and Robert F. Bennett of
Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the declining interest in a full slate of witnesses, Hyde
expressed rare public frustration on the Senate floor during the
question period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know, oh do I know, what an annoyance we are in the bosom of
this great body,'' Hyde said of the House managers. ``But we're a
constitutional annoyance, and I remind you of that fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Hyde had many Senate allies, including at least two
Republican moderates from New England who said they want to call a
small number of witnesses: Senators John H. Chafee of Rhode Island
and Susan M. Collins of Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Chafee predicted Byrd's motion to dismiss the charges will fail,
clearing the way for witnesses. Speaking to reporters after the
question period, Chafee warned the House managers to use restraint
in requesting witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're going to find the senators are very fussy,''
Chafee said. ``They aren't just going to approve every Tom, Dick
and Harry they want for a witness.''
</P>
<P>
   During the question period, the first of its kind in the Senate
since the impeachment trial of President Andrew Johnson in 1868,
both the White House and House managers conceded they had
mischaracterized elements of their earlier presentations to
senators or of their trial briefs.
</P>
<P>
   The legal teams alternately responded to questions that were
written by Republicans and Democrats and read aloud by the
presiding officer, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not accurately reflect the fact that the Jones lawyers
indeed issued'' a subpoena for Currie, White House counsel Charles
F.C. Ruff told the senators. ``For that misleading statement, I
apologize.''
</P>
<P>
   The House managers conceded that their official report to the
Senate misstated the time a federal judge had issued an order
permitting Jones' lawyers to interview Lewinsky about her
relationship with Clinton. The time was important because it
concerned an allegation that Clinton and his friend, Vernon E.
Jordan Jr., had intensified their search for a job in New York for
Lewinsky to influence her testimony in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the order was issued, the House managers
acknowledged, Jordan was on a plane to Holland and could not have
intensified his role to find a job for Lewinsky that day, as they
had alleged.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the corrections by both sides, the question period
generated little new information, although it provided senators an
opportunity to indirectly underscore their positions.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Sam Brownback, a Kansas Republican, said the question
phase helped him ``narrow some of the areas where there are factual
contentions.''
</P>
<P>
   But Senator Patrick J. Leahy, a Vermont Democrat, took a
different view, describing the back-and-forth nature of the
proceeding as ``a ping-pong experience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same-old, same-old,'' Leahy said.
</P>
</TEXT>
