u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPREWELL-N     01-22 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPREWELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS' FANS WILLING TO FORGIVE SPREWELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To some hard-core Knicks fans, he is the long-sought
scorer who deserves a second chance. To other Knicks disciples, he
is a short-tempered embarrassment who doesn't belong in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But, like it or not, Latrell Sprewell has come to town.
</P>
<P>
   In a trade made official Thursday, Sprewell, the talented but
troubled shooting guard, will be in a Knicks uniform when the
National Basketball Association begins its strike-shortened season
next month. To get Sprewell, who choked and punched his coach with
the Golden State Warriors, P.J. Carlesimo, in December 1997, the
Knicks traded the popular shooting guard John Starks and the backup
forwards Chris Mills and Terry Cummings. Sprewell has not played in
a pro game since his infamous altercation with Carlesimo.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Knicks fans seem willing to give Sprewell, 28, the
opportunity to prove himself on an aging Knicks team desperately
searching for an NBA championship. In more than 20 interviews
Wednesday at Madison Square Garden, on Wall Street, aboard subway
trains and in lunch joints around the city, most everyone thought
Sprewell could improve Patrick Ewing's chances for his first
professional title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love him, we need him, he's a winner,'' said Jeffrey Dupree,
a sandwich maker at Cosi Sandwich Bar on Pine Street in Lower
Manhattan, who became giddy at the thought of Sprewell in a Knicks
jersey. ``Sprewell is just like Michael Jordan, he's just going to
get better and better. I bet we win a championship with him.''
</P>
<P>
   If most Knick supporters weren't as sure as Dupree, many said
they were eager to see how the slashing, fluid Sprewell, who has
averaged more than 20 points a game over five NBA seasons, would
stand up under the city's intense media spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's New York, everyone is going to be watching him,'' Clifton
Sewell, of the Crown Heights section of Brooklyn, said as he rode
the No. 1 train toward Lower Manhattan on Wednesday morning.
Sewell, who said he had been a Knicks fan ``forever,'' said
Sprewell deserved a shot with the Knicks. ``Hey, everybody makes
mistakes,'' Sewell said. ``Let's not judge him too early.''
</P>
<P>
   But sitting across the aisle, Robert Margulies, a lawyer and
30-year fan of the team, was not as forgiving. ``I'm sure he's a
great player, maybe a better player than Starks,'' Margulies said,
folding the sports page into his black overcoat. ``But the Knicks
shouldn't have made that deal, because of the kind of person he
is.'' The trade for Sprewell, he said, sends a ``bad message to
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet Knicks-conscious kids seemed unfazed by Sprewell's
misbehavior. At the Frederick Douglass Playground on Amsterdam
Avenue at 101st Street, Luis Morales, 17, was shooting hoops with
three friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he can win a title, then it's all right,'' Morales said
when asked about Sprewell's pummeling his coach. ``He ain't going
to make the same mistake twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not? ``He lost $10 million,'' Morales said, referring to the
money Sprewell lost as a result of being suspended by the Warriors
last year. ``Knicks are going to be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lawrence Andrews, 19, support for Sprewell was conditional.
``If he helps the Knicks win a championship,'' he said, ``then I'm
with him. But I didn't want Starks to go. He was my man.''
</P>
<P>
   Many fans felt the same way about Starks, whose scrappy,
mercurial play endeared him to some and enraged others. ``That's my
guy,'' sighed Dale Polerstock, who arrived at Madison Square
Garden's closed box office Wednesday morning from Huntington, N.Y.
``I didn't want to lose Starks,'' he said. ``He was the heartbeat
of the club.''
</P>
<P>
   At the NBA Store on Fifth Avenue at 52nd Street, WFAN radio's
veteran Knicks analyst John Andariese fielded fans' questions
during a live broadcast Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, the place was buzzing all day,'' Andariese said,
noting that the comments about Sprewell, Topic A, were mostly
negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in this part of the country don't know about him as a
player, they just know the bad things that happened,'' Andariese
said after the broadcast. ``A lot of his talents suggest Jordan.
He's got a very fluid body. The man can fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Mario Cuomo, the former governor and a notable Knicks
aficionado, gave an unequivocal thumbs-up for Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad they have Sprewell,'' Cuomo said Thursday in response
to a telephone inquiry. ``They have got to take a gamble here. This
is a wild situation, and a speculative one. If the Yankees are
willing to bet on Albert Belle from Cleveland, then why not the
Knicks on Sprewell?''
</P>
<P>
   But maybe it was Nate Newton, a delivery man from Hunts Point in
the Bronx, who best summed up Knicks fans' overall view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sprewell could be a good addition,'' he said. ``Just don't
choke our coach.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
