<HEADER>
A5117 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-SFCHRON &LR;      01-22 1305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 California Wines Reach Worldwide  &HT;       
 By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
California vintners are making a big splash overseas.
</P>
<P>
   According to the most recent figures from the U.S. Department of
Agriculture, California wine exports jumped 26 percent to more than
36 million gallons in the first 10 months of 1998 compared to the
same 1997 period. These sales will account for close to 10 percent
of total 1998 revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Exports to the biggest offshore markets were even more
impressive. Sales to Japan more than doubled to 12.2 million
gallons in the first 10 months of 1998. And sales to the United
Kingdom jumped 37 percent to 15.1 million gallons from 11 million
gallons.
</P>
<P>
   E&AMP;J Gallo Winery, it turns out, is not only the top U.S.
producer but the largest exporter. The Modesto vintner sells about
20 million gallons, or close to 15 percent of its production,
overseas, which is more than all other California wineries
combined. As a sign of its clout, Gallo recently had a front aisle
display at Harrods' new wine shop in London and claims to be
England's top-selling brand.
</P>
<P>
   While Gallo sells the most overseas, Wente Vineyards of
Livermore sells the largest portion of its production overseas _
close to half a million gallons, or nearly 60 percent of its annual
sales.
</P>
<P>
   It is finally dawning on California producers that ``they have
barely scratched the surface of export sales compared to many other
wine-producing nations,'' said Jon Fredrikson, president of the San
Francisco wine consulting firm Gomberg, Fredrikson &AMP; Associates.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; It's easy to see why California vintners want to sell
overseas:
</P>
<P>
   _ Per-capita wine consumption in the United States has declined
in recent decades. Last year, for example, total domestic shipments
grew only about 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Foreign producers from Europe, South Africa, South America and
Australia are aggressively selling their wine here and in other
parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
   _ There could be a future &UR;  &LR; wine glut &UR;  &LR; in this country as more
than 20,000 acres of new California vineyards come into production
each year.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most world-class wine producers, California vintners have
had the luxury of being able to sell all the high-priced wine they
made on their home turf. Overseas markets were viewed as a safety
valve during years of surplus production.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of WINE23 (80702 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  But that strategy has shifted with the globalization of the wine
industry. As overseas markers continue to grow, particularly in
Asia, and U.S. producers have to contend with more imports from
more countries, California vintners feel the need to fight back and
target other countries for exports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past 10 years, most California wineries have looked
at exports as a way to get rid of excess supply,'' said Ken Lizar,
vice president of E.&AMP;J. Gallo's international division. ``But we've
made it a priority.''
</P>
<P>
   When there was a temporary shortage of Cabernet Sauvignon a few
years ago, Gallo put some U.S. customers on allocation before it
restricted supplies to key export markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gallos decided quite a while ago to make E&AMP;J Gallo a
global wine brand, and you can't do that by going in and out of
supply,'' said Lizar. As a result, over the past five years,
Gallo's exports have tripled from 5 percent to about 15 percent of
total volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Gallo did in the '50s to become the biggest wine seller
across the United States, they are now doing in foreign markets,''
said Fredrikson.
</P>
<P>
   In competing overseas, Gallo and other producers are taking
advantage of their ability to prominently place their brand names
on their bottles. That's not the case in most countries, where
local wines are marketed primarily by grape type or growing region,
like Bordeaux and Burgundy.
</P>
<P>
   Lizar said that kind of marketing advantage has made Gallo ``the
No.1 brand'' in Britain, where Gallo accounts for three of every
five bottles of California wine sold.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the importance of brand recognition worldwide, some
local vintners lobbied for and just won government approval to put
the ``San Francisco Bay'' appellation on their wine labels.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gallo sells to 86 nations, it focuses on big-volume
markets including Great Britain, Japan, Canada and Germany. By
contrast, Wente Vineyards is carving out a market in 147 countries.
</P>
<P>
   To attract international travelers and get its brand known in
developing countries, Wente has signed up more than 30 national
airlines to serve its wines and is opening wine bars and duty-free
wine shops at airports from Nairobi to Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of WINE23 (80702 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Wente also recently formed a joint venture with India's largest
wine producer to get a crack at selling to India's 17 million
millionaires and a middle class nearly as large as the entire U.S.
population.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see establishing a strong international brand as part of
our long-term viability,'' said Eric Wente, chief executive of the
family-owned winery that started in Livermore 115 years ago. Wente
figures it is small enough to tailor its strategy country by
country and said marketing costs tend to be lower than in the U.S.
market where there is rampant price discounting.
</P>
<P>
   But opening new markets is not without surprises and dangers.
When Wente introduced its wines at Nairobi's Carnivore Restaurant a
few years ago, Senior Vice President John Schwartz recalls he had
to make a quick call on which wines go best with antelope and
zebra. Another time, Wente sparkling wine blew their corks during a
freeze in St. Petersburg, Russia, and three months ago the winery
pulled out of Moscow because of economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the uncertainties, California vintners feel exporting is
worth the risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Following my father's vision, to be a real factor in the fine
wine business, you need to be in the better restaurants and hotels
of the major wine-drinking countries around the world,'' said
Michael Mondavi, chief executive of Robert Mondavi Corp. The Napa
producer, which pioneered promoting California wines overseas 27
years ago, increased foreign sales by more than a third last year
to about 9 percent of production.
</P>
<P>
   Mondavi sells in 77 countries and has its wines strategically
placed _ from the Peninsula Hotel in Hong Kong to Paul Bocuse
Restaurant near Lyon, France.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is comparable to 40 years ago, when the vast
majority of good-quality California wines were consumed in
California and then gradually spread across the U.S.,'' Mondavi
said. ``Now we are looking at the premium wine market from a global
perspective, and Mondavi wants to export a minimum of 20 percent of
sales by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram Chateau &AMP; Estate Wines company also is making a big push
overseas too. Seagram's Mumm Napa Valley sells half of its annual
production of 200,000 cases of sparkling wine to 40 countries, and
about 8 percent of Sterling Vineyards' production goes the same
route.
</P>
<P>
   ``We export to develop brand equity,'' explained Seagram export
director Jonathan Pey. ``Consumers increasingly are linked
globally. They fly from Toronto to Tokyo and we want to make sure
our brands are wherever they there.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 3 of WINE23 (80702 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Unequal taxation is major problem for U.S. exporters. Gallo's
Lizar insists that one reason the United States imports about 10
times as much wine as it exports is that this country imposes an
average duty of about 3 percent, or 58 cents a case, on imported
wine while European countries charge about three times that amount.
</P>
<P>
   And the situation is worse in other parts of the globe. Lizar
said China imposes a 114 percent excise tax and duty while Taiwan
charges about 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there were a level playing field, we should be exporting
three times as much wine,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
