<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-TAXREBATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TAX REBATES IN NEW JERSEY  (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Jan. 23,
1999:
</P>
<P>
   Like two-thirds of the nation's governors, Christie Whitman of
New Jersey is now wrestling with the ``problem'' of fat budget
surpluses brought on by a booming economy. This month, to no one's
great surprise, Mrs. Whitman proposed in her State of the State
message to send money back to taxpayers in the form of a rebate for
their local property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is certain to be popular, but there is a worrisome
catch. The cost of the rebate would grow from $200 million the
first year to $1 billion annually in five years, raising questions
about whether the money will be there to pay for it if the economy
turns down.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Whitman's zest for tax-cutting is a signature of her career
and crucial to her claim for consideration as a nominee for vice
president in the next national election. She first ran in 1993 on a
pledge to cut the income tax, and then kept her word by using
budget gimmicks to make up for the lost revenues. Her past tax cuts
now amount to about $1.2 billion in annual lost revenue. Currently
she proposes to cut taxes in the next five years by nearly as much
as in the last five.
</P>
<P>
   But since Mrs. Whitman cannot run for a third term, it will
probably be up to her successor to deal with any adverse long-term
consequences of her actions. That should give pause to the State
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   In her re-election campaign in 1997, Mrs. Whitman discovered
that voters were less grateful about the enacted state income-tax
cuts than angry over rising property taxes and insurance rates. Her
victory over a little-known Democratic opponent was close and
hard-fought. Mrs. Whitman's response, an average $600 rebate for
homeowners, is politically understandable. But it fails to address
the basic structural problems that drive up property tax rates,
which include the duplications and inefficiencies in New Jersey's
566 municipalities and 611 school districts.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's State of the State address featured several
commendable but modest spending initiatives, including more money
to maintain parks and open space, as well as an expansion of health
services for children and the elderly. Some of the money for the
health programs may come from $7.5 billion that New Jersey is to
receive over the next 25 years in the tobacco suit settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, Mrs. Whitman's preference for being known as a
tax-cutter rather than a spender is likely to be noticed by the
national Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
