<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Pacific Exchange, NASD Interested in Talks  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Pacific Exchange yesterday welcomed comments from a top
official of the National Association of Securities Dealers that the
association's Nasdaq Stock Market is open to buying the San
Francisco bourse.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he is interested in talking, we're interested in talking,''
Pacific Exchange spokesman Dale Carlson said in response to a
remark by Frank Zarb, chairman and chief executive of NASD, which
operates the Nasdaq market.
</P>
<P>
   Zarb told Bloomberg News earlier this week that NASD was ``open
to conversations'' about acquiring the Pacific Exchange, the
nation's third-largest options market, noting that the association
needs to study the economics of a transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Exchange said it is interested in combining with
another securities market following the breakdown of its planned
merger with the Chicago Board Options Exchange, the No. 1 U.S.
options market.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago exchange pulled out of the deal earlier this month,
citing delays caused by a federal antitrust probe and the need to
concentrate on countering competitive threats from electronic
options trading systems.
</P>
<P>
   Stock and options markets around the world have carried out a
series of mergers amid growing competition and the rapid
development of electronic trading systems that bypass traditional
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Since the collapse of the CBOE merger, Pacific spokesman Carlson
said the exchange has received ``two or three'' inquiries about an
acquisition from parties he declined to identify.
</P>
<P>
   After its experience with CBOE, Pacific wants to be sure that it
reaches an agreement with an organization ``with the resources,
wherewithal and strength to fulfill whatever commitment we agree to
make,'' Carlson stressed.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific and Nasdaq had held talks about a combination, but they
were halted when the exchange chose CBOE as its partner, Carlson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The two also held conversations about a separate sale of
Pacific's stock exchange operations up through the end of 1998, he
added. Pacific's stock trading floor is much smaller than its
options operations and was not part of the CBOE merger.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq has been expanding in the options business. When it held
acquisition talks with the Pacific last year, ``we were quite
excited,'' said a Nasdaq official who asked not to be identified.
``Then they just dropped off the screen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
