<HEADER>
A5122 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-MURRAY-LOUISVILLE     01-22 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MURRAY-LOUISVILLE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURRAY BECOMING ACCUSTOMED TO PRESSURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He grew up in a high-profile basketball family with a
high-profile older brother and played for a high-profile high
school program. Cameron Murray has become accustomed to pressure.
</P>
<P>
   But after five years of college, two schools and an array of
injuries that always seem to strike at the most inopportune times,
Murray reached a crossroads heading into this, his final season.
</P>
<P>
   So Louisville's 6-foot, 175-pound senior point guard prepared
for 1998-99 unlike anything he had done before.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a lot hungrier this past summer,'' said older brother
Tracy Murray, a former UCLA standout now with the Washington
Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the urgency sprouted from the possibility of Cameron's
basketball finality. He is not counting on an NBA career, although
he won't pass up an opportunity to impress any team that should
come calling.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers spent most of their summer together at Tracy's
Marina del Rey home, one pushing the other toward personal goals,
although Tracy admitted Cameron had a little more fire in his
belly.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy remembers waking up mornings with his younger brother
knocking on his bedroom door, urging him to get up. Cameron already
had been awake for hours, had run on the beach, climbed the sand
dunes and now wanted to continue the workout on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was something totally different than I've seen from him
as far as intensity,'' said Tracy, like Cameron a Glendora High
graduate. ``He did so much on his own, and it's because he wanted
to prove he had his game back.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Cameron's senior year is shaping up as his best, which
includes the two seasons he spent at USC, where he averaged 8.0
points and 4.3 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who arrived in Louisville this year 17 pounds lighter
but with more muscle mass, has led the 24th-ranked Cardinals to a
surprising 10-4 record and into the thick of the Conference USA
title race. The team's only losses have been at home Thursday night
against fifth-ranked Cincinnati and on the road at Mississippi,
North Carolina and Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who will lead Louisville into Saturday's noon
nonconference game against No. 12 UCLA at Freedom Hall, is the
team's leading scorer at 13.5 points per game. He also leads with
4.3 assists per game, and minutes played, 29.8 per game. He is
shooting 52 percent from the field, up from 33 percent last season,
and 48.6 percent on 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't care if he's the high point man on his team,''
Cameron's father, Bob Murray, said. ``As long as he keeps everyone
happy and they win, that's what's important.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping himself happy also is a priority for Murray after
suffering through some down times during his first four years in
college. Especially difficult was his time at USC, which ended with
Murray leaving the team late in his sophomore year, shortly after
coach Charlie Parker was fired.
</P>
<P>
   Even last season, his first on the court for Louisville after
sitting out 1996-97 following his transfer, burdened him in ways
unlike never before.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, stepping in for four-year starter DeJuan Wheat, suffered
the wrath of fans and was the focal point for blame, along with
guard Marques Maybin, as Louisville stumbled to a 12-20 record. It
was the worst mark in coach Denny Crum's 28-year career.
</P>
<P>
   Because Crum's system demands more from his guards than any
position, Murray was an easy target for those looking for a
scapegoat. It was a season he termed ``embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult playing for coach (Crum) because he does demand
a lot and is extremely critical of the guard play,'' Murray said.
``If you win, (the guards) get the credit, but if you lose, you
also get the credit for losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray said he didn't expect the losses to pile up the way they
did, but he did anticipate it would take fans time to warm to him
after watching Wheat for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get focused on one person for four years, it's hard
to get used to someone else,'' Murray said. ``It was hard and
something I had to adjust to. But this season, the crowd has really
let me into their family and they respect the way I play.''
</P>
<P>
   That never was more apparent than earlier this season, when
Louisville beat rival Kentucky for the second consecutive year with
Murray at the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing he can always say is that he was 2-0 against
Kentucky,'' Tracy said of his brother. ``He played two great games
against them.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the sweetness of the victory was his performance in
light of a medical report five days earlier. Murray was diagnosed
with a stress fracture in the fifth metatarsal bone of his left
foot.
</P>
<P>
   He still finished with a 14-point, 10-assist performance in an
83-74 victory against the third-ranked Wildcats. He will have
surgery on his foot after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to play through it and keep it off my mind,''
Murray said. ``Beating Kentucky felt good. It kind of eases my pain
of not having been able to beat UCLA yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray said is as happy as he has been in college, especially
with those 7-21 and 11-19 seasons at USC, along with last season's
disaster, in his rear-view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, he's as tough as he's ever been,'' Bob Murray said.
``I knew he would have some trouble getting used to Crum's system,
but he's adjusted well and this is Cam's team.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, problems persist.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the NCAA placed Louisville on three years
probation. The basketball program was banned from postseason
competition for one season and stripped of two scholarship because
of two rule violations committed by former assistant coach Scooter
McCray. He was found to have provided improper benefits to the
father of junior forward Nate Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The school appealed the decision last week and could have a
ruling on its fate by the end of the month. Murray, along with
seniors Alex Sanders and Eric Johnson, are most interested in the
outcome. Especially Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders and Johnson have participated in the NCAA tournament.
Murray is waiting for his first chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I found out about the probation, I was extremely
disappointed,'' Murray said. ``We had set some high goals during
the summer after all the adversity we went through, and this sort
of took away some of the spark.''
</P>
<P>
   But Murray insists there is plenty to play for, regardless of
the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Playing in the tournament) is something I always wanted, but
it doesn't make me feel bad if I don't get the chance,'' Murray
said. ``If you don't turn negatives into positives, you won't come
out on top in life. (Probation) won't stop us from winning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 2159EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
