<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5123 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH23-COX     01-22 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Byrd seeks impeachment trial dismissal to `end this sad and
sorry time'
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Momentum gathered Friday for putting a speedy end
to the Senate impeachment trial, as senators began questioning both
sides in the case.
</P>
<P>
   In a significant development for the president, Sen. Robert Byrd
(D-W.Va.) issued a statement saying he planned to make a motion to
dismiss the two articles of impeachment against Clinton as early as
Monday to ``end this sad and sorry time for our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced that the necessary two-thirds for conviction
are not there and are not likely to develop,'' said Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have also become convinced that lengthening this trial will
only prolong and deepen the divisive, bitter and polarizing effect
that this sorry affair has visited upon our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   A former Democratic majority leader and an author of Senate
history, Byrd is widely respected among both Republicans and
Democrats. He is considered one of the Senate's leading
constitutional scholars. Because of his conservative views and his
frequent criticisms of Clinton, Byrd was also seen as one of the
Democrats most likely to side with Republican claims that the
president should be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   While it is far from certain that Byrd can sway at least six
Republicans to vote for dismissal _ the number needed assuming no
Democrats vote no _ his surprising statement was a clear signal
that Democrats are virtually united in wanting a quick end to the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Majority leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.) was so concerned about the
impact of Byrd's statement that he asked Sen. Phil Gramm (R-Texas)
to hold an impromptu news conference during one of the afternoon
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The resolution (to dismiss) will be defeated,'' Gramm
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell of Georgia said he would be among those
voting against the motion to dismiss.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, however, are far from united in what they believe
should come next. Under the bipartisan agreement on trial
procedures worked out two weeks ago, senators will first consider a
motion to dismiss. If that fails, they then proceed to a vote on
witnesses that, if successful, will prolong the length of the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans want to allow the House prosecutors to call
whatever witnesses they want. Others have said they want no
witnesses, while still others said they believe a few witnesses,
limited to narrow areas of testimony, would be helpful.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, Republicans want to avoid the perception that they
are ending the trial before all the evidence about the president's
guilt or innocence has been put before the Senate. And many want an
up or down vote on the articles of impeachment themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think we are going to have an idea where we are
going until Monday,'' said Sen. Thad Cochran (R-Miss.). Lott
suggested senators should consider another bipartisan meeting like
the one that produced the initial framework for the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome Monday or Tuesday, Democrats are already
talking about censure alternatives. Sen. Dianne Feinstein
(D-Calif.) said she was prepared to offer a censure resolution the
moment the trial was over.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch (R-Utah) also revived a proposal he has to call
for a motion of adjournment at the point when it appears that the
Senate cannot convict the president. Hatch, who favors deposing
some witnesses, said adjournment would let the House's impeachment
vote stand as the ``ultimate censure'' and end Democratic efforts
to ``cover their backsides'' with a censure motion.
</P>
<P>
   There were other signs Friday that House prosecutors were losing
their battle to convince more undecided Republicans that the
president should be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ted Stevens (R-Alaska) said he was still wrestling with the
question of whether Clinton should be removed, even if all the
allegations against him are true.
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. Susan Collins (R-Maine) suggested she wasn't convinced
by the perjury evidence against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's grand jury testimony is replete with lies,
with half-truths and evasions,'' Collins said. ``I'm considering
whether despite that they meet the test under our perjury laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins added that she was more impressed with the case for
obstruction of justice and would like a separate vote on each
article.
</P>
<P>
   GOP senators also appeared unsympathetic to the prosecutors'
request that Clinton be invited to testify in his own impeachment
trial. In a letter to majority leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.) and
minority leader Tom Daschle (D-S.D.), Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde
(R-Ill.) wrote that prosecutors believed Clinton's testimony
``could greatly help to expeditiously and fairly bring this matter
to a close.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that is going to go anywhere,'' said Senate
Judiciary Chairman Hatch.
</P>
<P>
   As early as Tuesday, there was speculation that a liberal
Democrat sympathetic to the president would be the person to make
the motion to dismiss when the time came. The fact that it came
from Byrd will give it an added element of seriousness, several
senators said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll have more impact than anyone else would,'' said Sen.
Craig Thomas (R-Wy.).
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knows the Constitution better than Robert C. Byrd,''
said Sen. Kent Conrad (D-N.D.).
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, who issued his statement less than an hour after asking
White House lawyers if Clinton had not broken the public trust,
said he believes Clinton badly damaged the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has caused his family, his friends and this nation great
pain,'' he said. ``He has weakened the already fragile public trust
that has been placed in his care.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said continuing the trial would only divert attention
away from more pressing concerns such as social security reform,
education, health care and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is necessary that we begin now the process of healing and
reconciling the differences caused by these events and address
together the issues, challenges and opportunities facing our
nation,'' Byrd said.
</P>
<P>
   In his response to Byrd's statement, Gramm said it would be an
affront to the notion of justice and impeachment precedent to
dismiss the case before having an opportunity to convict or acquit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice is a process and not a verdict,'' Gramm said. ``We
have had a trial and voted guilty and not guilty'' in each of the
13 impeachment trials where the defendant had not resigned to avoid
trial, Gramm said. ``In each case, we have gone the distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
