<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-REEVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER SERIOUS HEALTH SCARE, REEVES IS FEELING BLESSED
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By SAMANTHA STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Atlanta Falcons coach Dan Reeves sat in his office after
practice Friday and spoke about his remarkable recovery from
quadruple-bypass heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was actually a miracle,'' said Reeves, who will lead the
Falcons into their first Super Bowl, against the Denver Broncos, on
Jan. 31 in Miami. ``With the circumstances that led up to my heart
surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   Circumstances nearly killed him.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves felt a burning sensation in his throat all season.
Stubbornly, he told himself that it was all in his mind. Didn't he
have a physical before the season and everything had checked out
fine? A visit to the doctor could wait until the season ended.
After all, the Falcons were battling the San Francisco 49ers for
supremacy in the National Football Conference West and even the
Minnesota Vikings for the best record in the NFC.
</P>
<P>
   But, after a victory over the Saints in New Orleans on Dec. 13,
the burning sensation became unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt strong,'' said the 55-year-old Reeves. ``It was like I
wanted someone to agree with me that there was something wrong or
that I was fine. Dr. Harrison, the team's internist, is usually not
on the trips, but he was with us for New Orleans. I told him about
the symptoms and asked if I should wait until after the season to
see a specialist. He said, `That's dumb. Let's do it tonight.'''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves went to the hospital the next morning with his wife, Pam,
and the rest of his family. Doctors found three arteries blocked
and told him quadruple-bypass surgery was required.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't any different than preparing for a game,'' Reeves
said. ``We had a word of prayer as a family before I went into the
operating room. I was calm. I've had surgeries in my football
career, and I don't think you go into surgery any different than
you go into a game. You expect to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Reeves, the Falcons-Saints game was on a Sunday
and not on ``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had waited one more day, I don't know if Dan could have
survived an extra day,'' Harrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Each year in the United States, more than 500,000
quadruple-bypass surgeries are performed.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Kauten operated on Reeves at the Fuqua Heart Center at
Piedmont Hospital in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used a new technique on Coach Reeves called harvesting a
vein,'' Kauten said. ``We wanted to get him up and mobilized
without leg problems. Many heart patients complain of their legs
hurting worse than their chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make one small incision in the leg and use an endoscopic
technique to scope and dissect down through the scope so there is
no swelling. Then we hook it to the heart. It gets nourishment from
vessels that feed inside the vein itself. We clamp off the aorta
and the blood goes back to the heart. It opens all the bypasses
within 30-60 seconds. Coach Reeves has a strong heart and he flew
off the bypass.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves' prognosis for the future is good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very optimistic,'' Kauten said. ``He's young. His first
episode of heart disease was at 46 and that is almost always due to
heredity. He has to take care and stay in shape.
</P>
<P>
   Kauten said Reeves belongs on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where he does his work,'' he said. ``It would be more
stressful to be up in a box seat. For Minnesota, I was more curious
that no one would run into him or hug him or knock him down.
Someone knocked his headsets off and I jumped.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves' mentor, Tom Landry, the former head coach of the Dallas
Cowboys, called to tell him to calm down on the sidelines. Reeves
plans to run on the treadmill at his Miami hotel, reluctantly
giving up mayonnaise and ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said he is motivating his players as a head coach they
trust, and not a man who survived quadruple bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only so many ways you can say things. Having the
surgery hasn't changed anything in the locker room. They don't give
me a big ol' bear hug now that my chest is cut open. I still walk
on the field. I try not to cough or sneeze _ that hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves is not quick to join the thousands of Falcon fans who
believe that divine intervention occurred last Sunday when the
Falcons upset the heavily favored Vikings, 30-27, to win the NFC
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think God takes sides,'' Reeves said. ``There are many
Christians on the Minnesota Vikings team. On my side, I ask for
wisdom and I pray. You hope the Lord blesses you. Why he smiled on
us, I can't say. We took the opportunity when they missed the field
goal. God doesn't choose sides.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 2205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
