<HEADER>
A5129 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIRECTV-PRIMESTAR-NYT     01-22 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIRECTV-PRIMESTAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRECTV TO BUY PRIMESTAR FOR $1.8 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a major consolidation of the satellite-TV broadcasting
industry, Hughes Electronics Inc.'s DirecTV Inc. subsidiary has
agreed to buy troubled Primestar Inc., its major competitor, for
$1.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase of Primestar by Hughes, a unit of the General
Motors Corp., would leave only one other significant competitor in
satellite-TV broadcasting, the Echostar Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, which is paying for Primestar with $1.6 billion in cash
and $220 million in GM stock, would be in a stronger position to
compete against Echostar as well as cable-TV operators, which
dominate the $44 billion pay-TV market.
</P>
<P>
   The deal partly bails out Primestar's owners, which include
shareholders and a group of cable-TV companies. But they are
unlikely to make much money from the sale, analysts said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Stock in TCI Satellite Entertainment, the publicly traded
portion of Primestar, fell $1.47 a share Friday, to close at $1.09.
It had traded at a 52-week high of $8.43 last April 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a great deal for equity owners,'' said Theodore
Henderson, who follows the company for Janco Partners, an
investment firm. Tom Wolzein, an analyst at Sanford Bernstein &AMP;
Co., said: ``This is the satellite industry cleaning house. Now you
have two players. That is probably more appropriate to what the
industry can do. The competitive edge of satellite offering lots of
channels becomes less.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal will not work out too well for John Malone, chairman of
Tele-Communications Inc. and TCI Satellite Entertainment. Malone
had 4.24 million shares of the satellite company when it was spun
off from Tele-Communications, at the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Wolzien said if Malone had sold them when the spinoff occurred
they would have been worth about $50 million, compared with today's
value of $5 million. Malone subsequently acquired another 1.4
million shares at just under $8 a share. Today his two stakes, once
worth about $60.7 million are worth about $6.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes is essentially buying access to 2.3 million medium-power
satellite subscribers whom it hopes to convert to high-power
satellite customers within the next two years. The purchase could
expand the number of DirecTV's customers to 6.8 million from 4.5
million, if they all convert to high-power satellite service, which
uses smaller satellite dishes increasingly favored by consumers.
</P>
<P>
   But Hughes is also acquiring Primestar's high-power satellite
assets, which include 11 high-power satellite licenses and two
satellites capable of delivering TV programs to the small satellite
dishes that DirecTV provides to customers. Hughes will use those to
increase its channel capacity for subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   The payment is complex, with DirecTV paying $500 million in cash
for the high-power assets that it will use to increase channel
capacity for subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes is also paying $1.1 billion in cash and $220 million in
GM stock for the medium-power assets.
</P>
<P>
   Primestar, which rents out satellite dishes rather than sell
them, incurred huge debt largely by purchasing those dishes.
Primestar customers have high disconnect rates that helped push
losses to $98 million on revenues of $371.3 million for the three
months ended Sept. 30, 1998, and the company was rapidly running
out of cash for operations.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes will not assume Primestar's $1.8 billion in debt. Rather,
Primestar will use the proceeds of the sale to buy back its debt at
a discount. It's unclear how Primestar bondholders will react to
that plan.
</P>
<P>
   One bondholder said some creditors found it objectionable
because the plan gave priority to the the cable partners, who are
junior to the bondholders. Currently the cable partners bear the
responsibility for $575 million of credit.
</P>
<P>
   The $500 million that DirecTV is paying for the high-power
satellite operations applies to that, so that cable companies will
not be responsible for the payment.
</P>
<P>
   How good a deal Hughes is getting depends on how successful the
company is in converting subscribers to high-power satellite
service. Hughes is paying $1.3 billion for 2.3 million medium-power
satellite subscribers, or $579 a subscriber.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if only half of them convert to high power, then Hughes is
paying twice as much,'' said Douglas Shapiro, who follows the
company for Deutsche Bank Securities.
</P>
<P>
   If Hughes succeeded in converting all the subscribers, it would
end up with 6.8 million of the industry's 8.8 million subscribers.
Echostar owns the balance. Even though Hughes stock rose $1.875 a
share Friday, to $46.625, some analysts said there was no need to
do the deal since Primestar might have gone out of business anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Star's major setback came last spring when the Department
of Justice thwarted a merger between Primestar and ASkyB, the News
Corp.'s high-powered satellite business, arguing that a consortium
of cable operators including Tele-Communications, Time Warner, Cox
Communications and Comcast should not be allowed to own crucial
assets in a rival technology to cable. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 2206EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0471 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5130 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-BYRD-TEXT-NYT     01-22 0381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-BYRD-TEXT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXT OF BYRD'S LETTER ANNOUNCING EFFORT TO END TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-ASSESS,
IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-CASE, IMPEACH-SCHOLARS) 
(bl)  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Following is the statement issued Friday by Sen.
Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., about the impeachment trial of President
Clinton:
</P>
<P>
   I have met with the Senate Republican and Democratic leaders to
inform them that I plan to offer a motion to dismiss the charges
and end this impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   In the agreement entered into between Republican and Democratic
senators a few days ago, provision was made for a motion to dismiss
that could come as early as the beginning of next week.
</P>
<P>
   I plan to make this motion not because I believe that the
president did no wrong. In fact, I think he caused his family, his
friends and this nation great pain. I believe that he has weakened
the already fragile public trust that has been placed in his care.
</P>
<P>
   But I am convinced that the necessary two-thirds for conviction
are not there and that they are not likely to develop. I have also
become convinced that lengthening the trial will only prolong and
deepen the divisive, bitter and polarizing effect that this sorry
affair has visited upon our nation. I am well acquainted with the
charges and the evidence. I do not believe that witnesses will add
anything of consequence to this process, but, to the contrary, they
will only foster more of the same hallway press conferences and
battle of press releases that are contributing to the division of
our parties and our nation.
</P>
<P>
   I have heard the public, and while it is clear that there is a
great rift of public opinion on this matter, there is also a
consensus that the nation is sorely in need of leadership and
healing. Pressing issues are facing this nation _ issues including
Social Security, education, health care, jobs and national
security.
</P>
<P>
   Given the importance of these matters, I see a motion to dismiss
as the best way to promptly end this sad and sorry time for our
country. It is necessary that we begin now the process of healing
and reconciling the differences caused by these events and address
together the issues, challenges and opportunities facing our
nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
