<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5132 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-POPE-CROWD-HNS     01-22 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POPE-CROWD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDREDS OF THOUSANDS GREET POPE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Please note slug and byline changes) 
 
By RICHARD VARA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Pope John Paul II on Friday effortlessly captured
hundreds of thousands of enthusiastic hearts with his frail
presence as he began a five-day pastoral visit to Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's fourth visit to this fervently Roman Catholic country
was greeted with whooping cheers and enthusiastic waving of Vatican
and Mexican flags from hundreds of thousands of faithful followers.
</P>
<P>
   His first blessing may have been the day's clear blue skies _
unusual for this time of year when the city of 20 million is
normally shrouded in a brownish-gray smog.
</P>
<P>
   Many homes on the pope's processional route were festooned with
the Vatican's yellow and white colors. Pictures of the nation's
spiritual patroness, the Virgin of Guadalupe, hung from balconies
or were prominently displayed in windows.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before the Vatican plane arrived Friday afternoon at
Benito Juarez International Airport, many thousands staked out
street vantage points for what at best would be a fleeting glimpse
of the leader of nearly 1 billion Catholics worldwide
</P>
<P>
   Many along the parade route carried small mirrors, hoping to
reflect the sun toward the sky in greeting as the pope's jet flew
overhead on its landing approach. Unfortunately, the plane flew by
too quickly for most to react.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the waiting crowds engaged in raucous yelling and
cheering led by seemingly tireless students, many of whom had
arrived at dawn. The result was an intensely emotional reception
from Mexicans who are struggling with many national problems,
including a crisis-plagued economy that has left many impoverished.
</P>
<P>
   The papal convoy's speedy procession through the street
disappointed many. They were unable to get a good look at the
pontiff. Especially let down was Maria Esther Perrea Porra. She and
eight members of her family had traveled from Pierra Blanca, a town
in eastern Veracruz state, to see their religious leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see him at all,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not dishearten her, her sisters or the other
members of her family. All said they intend to try to get a glimpse
of the pope at another procession Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologist Naomi Campos drove an hour by car to bring her son
and daughter for the pontiff's procession from the airport to a
central city ceremony and then to the apostolic nunciature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him once before and it was very exciting,'' said Campos
with 14-year old David and 10 year-old Aline standing close by. She
wanted the same experience for her children. But more than that,
she welcomed a papal boost to the national psyche.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want bad thoughts lifted for at least a week,'' said Campos.
``I hope the people change their thinking and pessimistic
feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   She also hopes the pope can divert the nation's attention away
from economic and other problems to positive thoughts of peace and
happiness.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Beatriz Nunez, 34, a special education teacher from San
Luis Potosi, expected the papal visit to spark a national spiritual
renewal. ``He is coming to us with so much hope that we have to
respond,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She traveled the 300 miles from her northern Mexico city with 60
other students and young professionals to help at papal events. She
planned to sleep out in the open Saturday night at the Hermanos
Rodriguez Racetrack, which will be the site of a papal Mass. She
and her friends will assist at the Sunday service, which is
expected to draw more than 125,000 worshipers.
</P>
<P>
   Nunez's fellow teacher, Gaby Garcia, 26, also of San Luis
Potosi, considers the pope a ``living saint'' and hopes that
Mexicans will use him as a spiritual role model.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to see what we can do to be like him. We have to
struggle to reach holiness,'' she said. ``It is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
