<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5136 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      01-22 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE HAS STRONG VIEWS ON U.S. `AGGRESSION' 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Journalists all over the United States are scrambling for ideas
to fill out their coverage of Pope John Paul II's visit to St.
Louis next week. Pity them. It is really not so easy to come up
with a fresh approach after the news media blitz that surrounded
the pope's trip to the United States less than four years ago and
the many overviews of his papacy, which marked its 20th anniversary
last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Well, here's a suggestion. On Dec. 17, Dr. Joaquin
Navarro-Valls, the pope's spokesman, who will be accompanying him
on his U.S. visit, made a brief statement about the bomb and
missile strikes against Iraqi targets that had begun a day earlier.
The statement included this sentence: ``The Holy See hopes that
this aggression ends as soon as possible and that international
order is re-established.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This aggression''? A very strong term, to put it mildly. Given
the Roman Catholic Church's teaching on just and unjust war, it
appears to mean that American and British forces were acting
immorally in hitting Iraqi targets while Iraq's military was simply
exercising justifiable self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   The condemnation was echoed, although in words less stark than
Navarro-Valls', by a flurry of other Vatican statements, some from
the pope himself.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this flew beneath the radar _ pardon the metaphor _ of
the American news media, the Catholic press included. The Catholic
News Service did begin an article on the attacks with a sentence
saying that ``the Vatican called the move an act of aggression,''
and a few Catholic papers picked up that blunt language in their
headlines. But even that did not seem to stir up much reaction, pro
or con, among the American Catholic population.
</P>
<P>
   Church leaders' concern was manifest, however, in a letter that
Archbishop Edwin O'Brien, who is responsible for the pastoral care
of Catholics in the U.S. armed forces, sent to Catholic military
chaplains.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien was visiting troops in the Middle East when the action
against Iraq occurred, and his letter almost certainly reflects a
desire not to appear to be blessing the bombs and missiles that the
pope was at that very moment decrying. The result is a carefully
composed statement.
</P>
<P>
   First, O'Brien praises ``the courage and professionalism'' of
American troops risking themselves ``in the role of peacekeeper''
in Bosnia, the Middle East and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Second, he affirms that ``once civilian leadership decides a
policy requiring military action, it is the sworn obligation of all
in our armed forces to execute their mission in complete obedience
unless in a specific instance the required action is judged clearly
illegal or immoral.''
</P>
<P>
   Third, he reviews all the misgivings about military action
against Iraq voiced by the Vatican, and last fall by the American
Catholic bishops, and whether that action meets ``just-war
requirements'' that civilians not be made targets, that expected
good results outweigh the expected harm and that there be likely
prospects of success.
</P>
<P>
   And finally he leaves military personnel with a two-sided
admonition. ``In executing orders that might violate just-war
requirements,'' he reminds them, they ``are not exempt from making
conscientious decisions.'' But when they lack sufficient evidence
to reach a clear conclusion of their own, they may follow ``the
presumably better-informed decision'' of their military superiors.
</P>
<P>
   This letter resurrects a perennial debate, of course, about the
relevance of just-war teachings not so much to policy-makers as to
those in the military. Moralists of differing views may ponder why
a Catholic bomber pilot should prefer the ``presumably
better-informed decision'' of a military superior in a moral
judgment call to that of the pope _ and also ponder the prospect of
chaos within the chain of command if the pilot did not.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraq episode also illustrated the pope's profound
ambivalence about the use of military force. John Paul II swings
between just-war teaching and something approaching pacifism,
between declaring that ``the aggressor must be disarmed'' in regard
to Bosnia and that war ``will never be an appropriate way to solve
problems'' in regard to the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the episode adds to the impression that the extent of
contemporary Catholics' adherence to papal positions will never be
separated from the strength of the arguments backing them.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican is understood when it denounces economic sanctions
on Iraq for the toll they take on innocent civilians. It is
understood when it abhors military destruction. But it does not
offer any comprehensive moral analysis of what should be done about
a regime like Saddam Hussein's and the proliferation of weapons of
mass destruction. Is this not really a problem? Or if it is, should
it be left in God's hands?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is because the Vatican's positions appear ad hoc and
incomplete that Catholics here so easily deflect even the language
of American ``aggression.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
