<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5138 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KELLOGG-CEREAL-$ADV24     01-22 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELLOGG-CEREAL-$ADV24-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG KELLOGG SHAREHOLDERS SEEK MORE SNAP, CRACKLE AND POP
</HEADLINE>
   ART ADV: A photo and a graphic are being sent. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DANA CANEDY and REED ABELSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATTLE CREEK, Mich. _ The Kellogg Co. has been scrambling to
revive its stagnant breakfast business, but its approach so far has
been about as successful as trying to freshen soggy cereal by
pouring on more milk.
</P>
<P>
   Now, key investors seem to have run out of patience, some senior
executives have left in frustration and major shareholders and
analysts wonder how long the company can remain independent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hate to see a takeover, but I don't know if that would not
be better all around,'' Agnes Gund, the president of the Museum of
Modern Art in New York, whose family is Kellogg's second-largest
shareholder, said earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Her brother, Gordon Gund, a Kellogg board member who owns the
Cleveland Cavaliers basketball team, said he, too, had been
concerned about the company's performance. But he insisted on
Friday that Kellogg has a strategy that will lead to a turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Kellogg's missteps in the marketplace _ its slow
response to changing eating habits and overestimation of what
shoppers would pay for flakes of wheat and corn _ are well known.
The stock is now trading no higher than it did in 1995, and the
company has warned investors that 1998 profits may be as much as 20
percent lower than in 1997. The company is expected to report its
annual results on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Amid mounting displeasure among shareholders, Kellogg's board _
after years of watching people eat less and less of the company's
Corn Flakes, Frosted Flakes and Raisin Bran _ announced earlier
this month that it would replace Arnold G. Langbo, the chief
executive for the last seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no secret that the numbers have not been good,'' said
Dorothy A. Johnson, president and chief executive of the Council of
Michigan Foundations, who joined the Kellogg board last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Johnson, who has been a trustee since 1980 of the W.K.
Kellogg Foundation, Kellogg's largest shareholder, acknowledged
that she was aware of the frustration felt by many of the company's
investors. The board has ``devoted numerous extra hours to it,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gund said the decision to replace Langbo was prompted by
his own desire to speed his retirement. ``This is a very orderly
transition and is a good one,'' Gund said. ``I feel very confident,
as do the other board members.''
</P>
<P>
   But it remains to be seen whether the appointment of Carlos M.
Gutierrez, a long-time Kellogg manager, as chief executive is just
another example the company's inability to think outside the
proverbial box. While current Kellogg executives and most board
members declined repeated requests for interviews, discussions with
several former senior executives as well as analysts and money
managers paint a portrait of a proud, insular organization that has
long relied on tradition and shopworn tactics to solve its
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kellogg is a funny company,'' explained one former executive
who became so disillusioned with Kellogg that he sold his shares.
Like all the executives interviewed, he would speak only on the
condition of anonymity. ``As recently as the mid-90's, we were
still asking what Kellogg would have done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg, of course, was Will Keith Kellogg, the visionary
business manager who along with his brother, Dr. John Harvey
Kellogg, invented flaked cereal in 1894 at the Battle Creek
Sanitarium, where they offered rich and famous patients a regimen
of exercise, fresh air and strict diet. The flakes spawned what in
1922 became the Kellogg Company and established Battle Creek as the
cereal capital of the world.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, falling back on the Kellogg heritage served the
corporation well, as it capitalized on its wholesome reputation for
nutritious products at a fair price. But in recent years, the
company has found it hard to react to the pressures of the modern
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Now the question is whether Gutierrez, who has been at Kellogg
23 years, and its board, heavily influenced by its two largest
shareholders and a former chief executive, are willing to break
with tradition to turn around the company and prevent it from being
sold. If so, the fire will have to come from within: Those
shareholders, which together own nearly half of the company's
shares outstanding, make it possible for Kellogg's management to
ignore the rumblings of all but a few investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Carlos to succeed, he has to operate very different from
the past,'' said another former executive. ``If he becomes another
Arnie, I don't think he can turn it around.''
</P>
<P>
   There certainly are striking parallels in the backgrounds of
Carlos Gutierrez and Arnold Langbo. Both started their careers as
sales representatives and have never worked anywhere else. Both
have extensive experience in virtually all aspects of the company's
management structure. Neither has a college degree.
</P>
<P>
   But there also are important differences. Gutierrez, a native of
Cuba who was raised in Mexico, has far more international
experience, having run Kellogg's Mexican and Asia-Pacific
divisions. He is also expected to focus more than his predecessor
on expanding sales, rather than cutting costs, although last week
the company announced it would slash a fifth of its European
salaried workforce.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is that Gutierrez, who is to take over as chief
executive in April, may not have nearly as much time as Langbo did.
If the company's results do not soon improve, Kellogg may explore
other options, including a possible merger, several analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kellogg looks like an attractive candidate,'' said Jaine I.
Mehring, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney. ``It has a leadership
position in what is a very large category that is important to
retailers and has something that really few other companies have,
and that is truly global brand equity.''
</P>
<P>
   One name frequently mentioned as a merger partner is the much
larger Unilever, whose international distribution network would
help push Kellogg's strong global brand name into more households
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gund, saying on Friday that she did not want to foster
conflict within her family, emphasized that she and her siblings
did not favor a sale of the business.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg has been unable in recent years to capitalize on the
power of its brand. While it remains the nation's top-selling
cereal maker, it lost more than two percentage points in market
share from 1994 to 1997, according to Information Resources Inc., a
research firm in Chicago. Competitors, like General Mills Inc.,
that lost share in that period rebounded last year. But Kellogg
lost nearly another two percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that Langbo, who joined Kellogg in 1956 and will
remain chairman until next year, has lacked creativity in solving
Kellogg's problems. He has tried to cut costs by slashing jobs, to
lure back customers by throwing money at advertising and promotion
and to restore profits by raising prices. The last few years have
been difficult for all cereal makers, as companies that offer
cheaper supermarket or other private-label brands have taken an
increasing share of the market. Consumers also have favored bagels
and other convenience foods to a bowl of cereal in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Langbo seemed unable to rise to the challenge.
Hand-picked by his predecessor, William E. LaMothe, who remains on
the Kellogg board, Langbo is described by former colleagues as
unwilling to delegate, choosing for years not to appoint a chief
operating officer, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg has been unable to get a grip on just how much people
are willing pay for its cereals, especially when other boxes of
corn flakes seem more like its brand than ever before. A few years
ago, the company set off a price war, hoping to make up the lost
profits through volume, but then struggled to raise prices again.
In the end, the approach gave consumers sticker shock at grocery
checkout lanes and benefited competitors like General Mills, whose
strategy depended less on its pricing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been so much discounting and repricing going on that
it is very confusing to consumers, and General Mills seems to have
taken advantage of that,'' said Timothy Ghriskey, a senior
portfolio manager at the Dreyfus Corp., which sold its 540,000
shares of Kellogg months ago. General Mills also has benefited from
marketing that stressed nutrition even as it promoted the addition
of frosting and honey flavor to old-line cereals like its Cheerios,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   A Kellogg spokesman insisted that Langbo has positioned the
company for future growth. The company has added an advertising
agency to push its nutrition message more aggressively. Kellogg has
also purchased several factories to produce convenience foods. It
is rolling out a product line it calls Ensemble _ frozen entrees,
cookies, muffins, and other foods, for both breakfast and other
meals, that the company will promote as being healthful. And it is
adding 200,000 distribution points in places like convenience
stores to increase sales of single-serving snacks, like Rice
Krispies Treats.
</P>
<P>
   In Langbo's defense, Gund also was quick to blame industry
trends, like people eating on the run, for the company's troubles.
While he said the change in leadership ``was appropriate'' he added
that he would not ``speculate on the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The stock market, nonetheless, has judged Langbo harshly. During
his tenure, the stock significantly underperformed other food
stocks, retdd sloturning an average 3 percent a year, compared with
13 percent for the Standard &AMP; Poor's index of food stocks. While
the board stood by, many investors abandoned the company, selling
their shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``You either expect to get change or go onto something else,''
said Charles Mayer, a portfolio manager with Invesco Funds in
Denver, which continues to own stock in Kellogg. Even steadfast
investors, he said, had made their feelings known to the company.
At its closing price Friday of $38.125, Kellogg has a market value
of $15.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   What has protected the company for so long from investors' wrath
is its domination by two friendly shareholders. The W.K. Kellogg
Foundation, created in 1930 by Will Keith Kellogg, owns about a
third of the company. The Gund family received shares in 1928 after
selling what is now known as Sanka, the decaffeinated coffee brand,
to Kellogg; the Gunds now control about 12 percent of the shares
outstanding, worth about $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation and Kellogg continue to be closely tied, and many
directors sit on both boards. Langbo, for example, serves as
co-trustee of the foundation's trust, which controls its Kellogg
shares and whose bylaws require a company representative on the
trust board.
</P>
<P>
   Three foundation trustees are also company directors: LaMothe,
the former chief executive of Kellogg; Ms. Johnson, the head of the
Council of Michigan Foundations, and Dr. William C. Richardson, the
chief executive of the Kellogg Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Here are other ties as well. Donald H. Rumsfeld, the former
Defense Secretary, for example, used to serve on the board of
Sears, Roebuck with LaMothe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cozy relationship between the company and the foundation
and Battle Creek made it difficult for the board to see the forest
for the trees,'' said one of the former executives.
</P>
<P>
   By way of contrast, the Lilly Endowment, which owns 16 percent
of Eli Lilly, has no representatives on the drug maker's board.
</P>
<P>
   What is also striking is the presence of LaMothe _ who presided
over the company in its heyday _ on Kellogg's board. He is viewed
by outsiders as having considerable sway over other board members.
``He is so tied up in the corporate history that they don't know
how to make an independent decision,'' said one former executive.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge will be compounded for Gutierrez, who will be
looking at two ex-chief executives when he sits down for board
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Gund insisted that Gutierrez ``is going to express his own views
and not be influenced by anyone else.'' What is more, Gund said,
both former chief executives are likely to step down from the board
next year.
</P>
<P>
   He also took issue with criticism of the board, saying that
``there is no insular issue here.''
</P>
<P>
   The directors, he said, were independent: ``We want to do the
very best we can for this business and shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders are restless. Ms. Gund says her family became
increasingly concerned about the stock's performance because it
threatened to hamper their philanthropic activities. Ms. Gund said
that she and other family members had expressed their concerns to
Gund several months ago.
</P>
<P>
   In its latest annual report, the foundation made reference to
the stock's volatility and said that it ``has a significant impact
on the foundation's grant-making capacity.''
</P>
<P>
   While the foundation _ which supports numerous causes, including
those related to health, education and youth _ has been able to
increase the amount it gives, the value of its assets has declined.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Gutierrez represents the potential for a new
direction. He is described by colleagues and others who have met
him as a driven and intelligent executive who was clearly the best
choice among the inside candidates.
</P>
<P>
   One colleague recalls Gutierrez's spending an hour on Sundays,
after buying his children dessert at McDonald's, watching consumers
buy cereal at a supermarket. ``There were people running the
company the last five years who didn't understand why that was
important,'' this person said. Gutierrez, he said, realized that
adding frosting to flakes or spending more on Tony the Tiger
commercials was futile unless the company figured out why
once-loyal shoppers were switching to its competitors' products.
</P>
<P>
   Gutierrez also seems decisive. Money managers and analysts
credit him with being the force behind a shake-up at Kellogg's
headquarters in September, in which all managers were forced to
justify their jobs and hundreds were subsequently dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   In his first significant management appointment, Gutierrez took
the step _ unusual at Kellogg _ of naming an outsider to a top job,
bringing in a Procter &AMP; Gamble manager whom the company found
through a search firm to oversee the company's Asia-Pacific
operations. He is expected to hire another outsider, possibly later
this month, to run the company's all-important North American
division.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is revolutionary for this company,'' said Ghriskey of
Dreyfus.
</P>
<P>
   One reason, as even Battle Creek community leaders acknowledge,
is that it is a challenge to lure executives to this sleepy town
tucked beside the Battle Creek River, 113 miles west of Detroit and
170 miles northeast of Chicago. It is a community where nearly
every resident either works for Kellogg or knows someone who does,
and where schools, auditoriums and museums are named for the
company.
</P>
<P>
   It is against this backdrop that Gutierrez, who himself was
anointed by Langbo, will soon reign. That is why some people are
skeptical about how hard he is likely to push for change. Beyond
wooing executives from other companies and expanding lines of
noncereal foods, ``I really doubt he will significantly rock the
boat,'' Ghriskey said. ``He's someone from inside, he's a longtime
crown prince, and he pretty much toes the company line.''
</P>
<P>
   While the company insists that this year will be a turning point
and Gutierrez ``is not looking for a honeymoon period,'' investors
are waiting to see the tangible results of any new strategies.
</P>
<P>
   One advantage Gutierrez has is that there now appears to be no
one else at Kellogg prepared to run the company. Describing him as
the last inside hope, one former colleague remarked, ``Carlos knows
he is holding the cards right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
