<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Limit on Viagra Prescriptions
</P>
<P>
   The government has ruled that the National Health Service will
limit treatment with the impotence drug Viagra to patients whose
conditions stem from surgery or serious injury. It is the first
instance in its 50-year history that the service has excluded care
for cost reasons. Frank Dobson, the health secretary, said
unlimited prescriptions would increase tenfold the $20 million now
spent on impotence treatments.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   Israel: A Drift Away From Likud
</P>
<P>
   Yitzhak Mordechai, the popular defense minister, seems poised to
abandon the Likud Party to join a new center party, or perhaps even
lead it. He declined to meet a deadline Friday to place his name on
a Likud list of parliamentary candidates for the May 17 elections.
But a statement from his office warned reporters not to jump to
conclusions, and said he was still a member of Likud.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe: Publisher Arrested
</P>
<P>
   The publisher of The Standard, Clive Wilson, was arrested,
barely 24 hours after two of the newspaper's journalists were
released from detention during which they were tortured by military
interrogators. The two journalists had been asked to disclose their
sources for a Dec. 10 story on the arrest of 23 soldiers for
reportedly plotting a coup against President Robert Mugabe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
