<SLUG> BC-ARK-TORNADOES-ART-1STLEDE-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORNADOES KILL EIGHT IN ARKANSAS AND TENNESSEE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS 1st graf; Minor changes in wording elsewhere.)  
 (ATTN: Tenn.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By STEVE BARNES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ The storm system rose out of Texas and
Oklahoma and crossed into Arkansas on Thursday. By the time it
exhausted itself, the tornadoes it spawned had killed seven people.
An additional person was killed in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   As many as three dozen tornadoes lashed Arkansas between about 5
p.m. and 8:30 p.m., officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just didn't stop,'' Teri Magsam of the Arkansas Office of
Emergency Services said Friday. ``They just kept on coming in, one
after another.''
</P>
<P>
   In White County four people died, including 2-month-old Kirk
McAfee, who was killed when his family's home in Beebe, a community
of 4,000 people, 35 miles northeast of Little Rock, was flattened.
The infant was either sucked or blown out of the home and was found
about a block away.
</P>
<P>
   Paul McCullock's family barely survived the tornado that
shattered their house. ``We got in the center hallway with the
mattress off the bed and began praying to beat the band,''
McCullock said.
</P>
<P>
   A new junior high school that McCullock's daughter attended was
a pile of bricks and shingles.
</P>
<P>
   A tornado tore apart the home of Wanda Willis, 65, a member of
the school board in nearby Searcy, and tossed her body into a
field, said Tom Martin, chief of the Center Hill community's fire
department.
</P>
<P>
   Also killed were a woman known only as Flo Taylor, estimated by
the authorities to be in her 50s, and a fourth person found Friday
but not identified.
</P>
<P>
   Winds whipped across the grounds of the governor's mansion in
Little Rock. There was no damage to the building, but the tree
house in a backyard oak where Chelsea Clinton had once played was a
shambles.
</P>
<P>
   But only blocks from the governor's mansion, a supermarket
collapsed from the force of the winds, and on Friday morning one of
several people initially trapped in the wreckage, Robert Howard,
67, the store's pharmacist, died of his injuries. A 34-year-old
Little Rock woman, Lisa Jacko, died on Thursday night when a tree
struck the car she was driving a short distance from the store.
</P>
<P>
   Just across the Arkansas River from Little Rock, there was more
death and destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandmother was in her wheelchair and my uncle was in the
back bedroom and he was coming down the hallway when the tree fell
and crushed him,'' said Eva Weikel, the niece of James Looper, 63,
who died in the wreckage of his mobile home in North Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   The storm then moved into Tennessee, where a woman was killed by
a tornado west of Nashville when she went outside to get her dogs,
The Associated Press reported. The storm tore apart the historic
district of Clarksville, Tenn., early Friday, wrecking the
121-year-old courthouse and cutting power to 25,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   Tornadoes killed nine people in Tennessee on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The storms cut off electricity to more than 70,000 Arkansas
homes and businesses on Thursday, and by late Friday afternoon
42,000 people were still without power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the most unusual storms I've ever seen this time
of year _ strong and volatile,'' said George Wilken, a
meteorologist with 33 years' experience at the National Weather
Service in North Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Tornadoes rarely occur in the South during winter, but when they
do, they are often very powerful, Wilken said. The latest storm
system, he said, was created when unusually warm, moist Gulf air
moved north under a cold air mass.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of Arkansas' 75 counties have declared local
emergencies and three were designated major disaster areas by Gov.
Mike Huckabee. ``It's just devastating,'' he said. ``We've seen
more damage that we expected. We weren't prepared for what we saw
in White County.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 2235EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
