<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0482 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5150 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     01-22 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 SPORTS COLUMN: SPREWELL HAS APOLOGIZED ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RYE BROOK, N.Y. _ Billie Holiday tartly sang ``Don't Explain,''
and after listening to questions fired at Latrell Sprewell Friday,
the new Knicks player might be wise to heed that advice, sooner
rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of speculation, heated debate and controversy
before he even signed a contract, the National Basketball
Association's most controversial player, wearing his trademark
cornrows, met the news media Friday. He didn't snarl, he didn't
growl. Instead, Sprewell set the tone by saying he was sorry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to start by apologizing to coach Carlesimo for the
incident in December of '97,'' he said, adding an apology to the
Warriors' organization and a thanks to fans, family and the Knicks
``for giving me a second opportunity to come out and show you
people the real Latrell.''
</P>
<P>
   Apologies set the tone for most of the 45-minute news
conference, as they had set the tone for the last few days. The
round of apologies began last Sunday when Sprewell met with the
Knicks' hierarchy in Milwaukee. A day later, coach Jeff Van Gundy
and Sprewell shared a flight to New York. Thursday morning,
Sprewell met with NBA commissioner David Stern, who pronounced him
redeemed.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there was Friday's session, sometimes humiliating,
often paternalistic, with Sprewell apologizing and assuring the
moral media that he will behave. At times it seemed as if we were
in the principal's office with Sprewell, the Coasters' ``Charlie
Brown,'' being scolded for a multitude of classroom sins:
</P>
<P>
   Can you control your anger? Will you snap again? Do you realize
many people don't want you here?
</P>
<P>
   I just hope contrition doesn't so set the tone for Sprewell's
stay in New York that he loses the edge, which is why his new
bosses brought him here in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy opened Friday's Sprewell greeting with a farewell to
John Starks, who was traded to Golden State. ``Because of his
effort over the past eight years,'' Van Gundy said, ``he's done
unbelievable things for my career and I'll always be appreciative
for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nice sentiment. But Starks couldn't do for the rest of Van
Gundy's career what a focused Sprewell can do. At a time when
rumors of Phil Jackson's return to New York as a coach are in the
air and, of course, the ambitious John Calipari is in the region
with the Nets, Van Gundy needs some powerful afterburners to
separate him from the pack nipping at his heels.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell is no saint; what we looked for Friday was contrition,
and Sprewell was filled with it. ``I made a mistake,'' he said.
``We all make mistakes in life. I've paid the price. I'm sorry for
what has happened in the past. I'm just asking for some
forgiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks made a bold basketball decision and, in a perverse
way, an even better public relations move. Everyone talks about fan
apathy, but if the reaction to Sprewell's signing _ pro and con _
is any indication, fan anticipation is in late-season form. The
Feb. 7 home opener against the Miami Heat will be as electric as
any big game. Pat Riley? Alonzo Mourning? Sprewell?
</P>
<P>
   Please.
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked Sprewell Friday if he knew what to expect on
opening night. He said he did not, but I'm not sure Knick fans know
how they will react, either. Sprewell, a three-time NBA all-star,
is different from any player the Knicks have had in decades. He is
aggressive, like Starks, and also has Starks' defensive capacity.
He has an edge, obviously, a scorer's attitude and a consistency
that is the opposite of Starks' unpredictability.
</P>
<P>
   But can Sprewell withstand the withering New York pressure?
``Nothing is worse than the first week after the incident,''
Sprewell said, referring to the aftermath of his choking of P.J.
Carlesimo. ``There was so much said about me, so much negative
publicity, and I've heard it all. If I can handle that, I'm pretty
sure that I'll be ready to handle anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure will very likely be greater than he realizes: This
is not West Coast space; it is East Coast density. At the same
time, Sprewell is freer than he has been in his career. He knows
that a lot of fans _ and the news media _ will resent him
regardless of what he says. Other fans will give him the benefit of
the doubt. The vast majority of fans are mercenaries, willing to be
won over by performance.
</P>
<P>
   There is no more for Sprewell to say, and there are only so many
times he can apologize before it becomes debilitating and hollow.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell apologized about six times Friday. My advice from this
point forward is simple: Don't explain. Just play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
