<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRINCE-OF-WHALES-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METHOD TO SOME, MADDENING TO MANY , MAX IS MAD ABOUT SAVING WHALES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ ``Max!'' has become an eye-rolling epithet in some
Boston quarters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Max is barred from the New England Aquarium after ranting at
visitors about whale-watching cruises. He is on notice not to enter
government offices where he has made workers cry. He has been
arrested 130 times, by his count. A federal court decision called
him a ``highly aggressive and abrasive individual.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his wildness, though, Max also gets credit from some for
pushing forward the desperate cause of the planet's most endangered
whale, the North Atlantic right whale, where others feared to
tread. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Max is Richard Max Strahan, self-titled ``Prince of Whales,'' a
longtime radical campaigner whose solicitation table covered with
graphic photographs of bloody whales injured by ships or fishing
gear is a fixture in Boston gathering spots, and who has himself
become a self-representing fixture in the Boston courts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Strahan is better known as Mad Max, in part for his tendency
to lash out at anyone who disagrees with him: judges; environmental
colleagues favoring more moderate or scientific means of saving the
right whale; even passersby who pause at his table near Faneuil
Hall Market or in South Station to eye the photos but refuse to
give money or sign a petition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you hurt your own cause by alienating so many people,'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Strahan was asked recently after a diatribe aimed at a
retreating back. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, oh oh, God!,'' Strahan snapped back. ``Boring story, I've
heard that one.'' He went on:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's not about me, it's about them. It's about them! The
system! Maybe the issue is that I'm just a plain old Joe who's
doing this Good Samaritan thing to save the whale, and when I do
the most basic common sense things like say, `Hey, let's put a
speed limit on a boat,' and, `If you want to go whale-watching,
let's license it, let's obey the law,' maybe that's my major thing.
That's why they call me the Wyatt Earp of whales, because I'm just
saying, `Let's obey the law.' And maybe when I ask that simple
thing, everybody just freaks out!'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, part of the problem is how Strahan asks. He asks
often, filing scores of lawsuits based mainly on the Endangered
Species Act. He demands radical measures, from banning commercial
fishing _ because fishing gear can entangle whales _ to closing
ports _ because ships occasionally collide with whales. He often
asks not very nicely, such as when he refers to government
officials, in court papers, as vermin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He has the front-toothless, snarl-haired mien of a street
person, though snug in bright fleece and down. He seems to lack a
phone or office (but has e-mail), and he refuses to talk about
where or how he lives, leading to persistent rumors that he is
homeless and that his group, GreenWorld, consists mainly of him.
</P>
<P>
   He is reviled by some environmentalists, who say he does far
more damage than good, and by fishermen, who fear that he is out to
destroy their livelihood. He can drive to distraction just about
everybody he deals with, from lawyers to environmental allies to
scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Yet much as they might like to, his critics cannot simply
dismiss him as a ``kook.'' Some even grudgingly respect him, in
part because he is a largely self-taught expert on environmental
law and his own legal rights, in part because he has become an
undisputed catalyst in saving the right whale, but most of all
because, despite everything, he has had some success.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, he sued the Coast Guard to stop its ships from running
into and killing North Atlantic right whales, distinguished by
wrinkles on the throat and chest. Their numbers have shrunk from
the thousands to a current official count of 300; in 1996 the
service was ordered to change its practices.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, he sued Massachusetts, seeking a ban on commercial
fishing in state waters because the lines and gear can hurt right
whales. The suit helped lead to a partial ban on fishing with gill
nets and lobstering in the months when the whales spawn near shore
and to changes in fishing gear. Late last year, the U. S. Supreme
Court declined to hear the state's appeal of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I disagree with his lawsuit, and firmly believe the
state should have won every step of the way, you have to give the
guy credit,'' said Sal Giorlandino, the assistant attorney general
who represented the state in the suit. ``He did bring a lawsuit,
which other people did not bring, people who thought about suing
and didn't. So he deserves the credit for pushing the issue
forward, though I disagree with his claims and the outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Others have failed to reach Giorlandino's philosophical
acceptance of Strahan's wild ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sues everybody who could be his ally,'' said Dr. Scott D.
Kraus, senior scientist at the New England Aquarium, which Strahan
sued for barring him after he accosted visitors about the evils of
whale-watching boats. ``It's not just abrasive personality. I could
deal with that. He inhibits people who could do good work.''
</P>
<P>
   Strahan also has repeatedly subpoenaed all of the aquarium's
whale data for other cases. ``It takes away from the time we could
be spending doing something for the animals,'' Dr. Kraus said. ``I
think you're glorifying someone who's destructive.''
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Coastal Studies in Provincetown, Mass., which,
like the aquarium, studies whales at sea, is also named by Strahan
in his suit against whale-watching. He says the whale-watching
boats hurt whales by getting too close, disrupting their lives and
sometimes hitting them.
</P>
<P>
   Some opponents question Strahan's sanity. Two state officials
recalled that Strahan told a judge in federal court that he had
been a Supreme Court Justice in a previous life and written the
very decisions under discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one, absolutely no one, should underestimate the man,''
said Giorlandino. ``He might throw 10 legal arguments at you, 10
claims, and 9 might miss. But it only takes one.'' &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Local newspapers have repeatedly questioned what happens to the
money that Strahan gathers in his panhandling style, barraging
passersby with information on whales and then asking them,
clipboard in hand, to sign a petition and contribute cash for his
campaign. He refuses to register as an official charity and to
report his proceeds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Strahan refused to talk about the finances and membership of
GreenWorld, his group, saying that it is a radical organization,
not the Sierra Club.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only on one thing do all sides, the pro-Max, anti-Max and Max
himself, agree: the plight of the North Atlantic right whale is
dire and previous efforts to protect it have fallen far short.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While other advocates of the whale talk about federal budgets or
habitat studies, however, Strahan offers a particularly Max-like
plan: lawsuits to shut down East Coast ports, arguing that their
shipping traffic hurts the endangered whales. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``No ports, no ship traffic, no dead whales,'' he said in a
recent e-mail. ``A winning suit.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
