<HEADLINE>
HOW TO RUN FOR OFFICE WITHOUT SEEMING TO TRY
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Suppose that you are a high-level Cabinet official
wondering if you should run for elective office. Do you have a
chance? Can you raise money? Will the potential of your candidacy
excite party leaders and newspapers? Most important, is there a way
to answer these questions without risking the embarrassment of a
failed run for office?
</P>
<P>
   The answer to that last question is yes, and it's not hard to
do. All it takes is a friend or two to whisper to a reporter or two
that you are thinking about the race. A few subsequent mentions in
newspapers should allow for a painless testing of the waters.
</P>
<P>
   So it was with Donna Shalala, the secretary of health and human
services, who was one of several prominent public officials _
including the wife of a certain president of the United States _
who showed up on lists of potential candidate for Senate in 2000,
after Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., retires from the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But now, two months later, Ms. Shalala has joined another list:
of prominent Americans who are forgoing the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of her friends in New York urged her to run, but she's
decided to continue her public service as secretary of health and
human services,'' said Ms. Shalala's spokesman, Melissa Skolfield.
The secretary has decided, Ms. Skolfield said, that she would
rather devote her energies into staying at Clinton's side for the
final two years of his term.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shalala's policy interests aside, it would be fair to say
that her rumored candidacy made hardly a ripple in New York waters,
even at a time when Democrats have looked with increasing despair
at their possible candidates for a race that could include, on the
Republican side, New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. But this was
one trial balloon that, by all appearances, never quite left the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   The Rising Lowey Balloon
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shalala's statement followed a similar declaration by two
other almost-candidates: Andrew Cuomo, the U.S. secretary of
housing and urban development, and state Comptroller H. Carl
McCall. That leaves Rep. Nita Lowey, D-Westchester. Ms. Lowey
floated her own trial balloon to win attention.
</P>
<P>
   New York being New York, Ms. Lowey had barely got off the
telephone with reporters before someone laid a claim for her job.
Mark Weprin, the Queens Assemblyman _ and son of former state
Assembly Speaker Saul Weprin _ called reporters to say that he was
ready to run for Ms. Lowey's Congressional position, assuming that
Ms. Lowey runs for Moynihan's position (which, just to set things
straight, assumes that Hillary Rodham Clinton won't be running for
Moynihan's old job).
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Weprin is talking up Ms. Lowey qualifications
to run for the Senate, which would, not coincidentally, leave her
job (the one Weprin wants) vacant. ``I actually think Nita might be
a better candidate than Hillary,'' Weprin said. ``Hillary comes
with a lot of baggage. She's got the carpetbagger issue. The fact
that Nita is from Westchester is really going to sell in a lot of
parts of the state. On paper, she's stronger than Chuck Schumer was
two years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki PAC Lunch
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of ambitions, Gov. George Pataki spent Friday in
Washington, tending to his presumed national ones. He held the
first fund-raising lunch for the national political action
committee he set up to pay for his exploratory trips around the
country. The lunch cost $1,000 a person and drew about 40 people,
most of them Washington business leaders, according to Pataki's
communications director, Zenia Mucha. It was, in keeping with
Pataki's custom, closed to the press.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mucha reports that in his speech to contributors, and in a
separate Washington speech to Republican leaders from across the
country, Pataki did not mention his concerns about the Republican
drive to remove Clinton from office. But, she said, he did ``talk
about the need for the Republican Party to unify behind a message
and talk about how important it is that we go back to core
Republican principles.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's Open Option
</P>
<P>
   What will Mrs. Clinton do? Speaking at a breakfast sponsored by
the New York City Partnership and Crain's New York Business on
Friday, Sen. Charles Schumer said he discussed the matter with the
first lady recently. ``She has said to me, and she said it to many
others, that she is not going to begin really thinking about this
until after the impeachment process closes,'' he said. ``I take her
at her word.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Schumer said, ``The first lady and her people
have not tried to end the speculation about her candidacy, which I
guess is an indication that it's not off the table.''
</P>
</TEXT>
