<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-RADIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: AN OLD DOOR TO LISTENERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On stage at Cooper Union's Great Hall _ the very
place where Abraham Lincoln delivered a speech that helped him get
elected in 1860 _ Hi Brown paced among a quintet of actors in front
of a few slender microphones. They were about to record ``The Naked
Truth,'' a radio dramatization of another talk delivered there, by
Victoria Woodhull, a feminist who scandalized the country with
ideas about free love and women's rights in 1873.
</P>
<P>
   The hall was still great. The audience was modest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of an audience is not new,'' Brown said to the 20
people who sat before him. ``We used to do this way back when I
used to do the `Philip Morris Playhouse' at the Ed Sullivan
Theater. We wore tuxes and whatnot and had 300 people fighting over
tickets. The audience does not please me as much as having
thousands of people listening for the first time at home.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody listens anymore,'' he said softly. ``We've lost the art
of listening.''
</P>
<P>
   With a lead-in like that, who wasn't going to pay attention? The
few people who had braved a nasty night spent the next hour hearing
voices from another era. In the fall, thousands more can hear them
on WNYC radio in a series marking the 140th anniversary of Cooper
Union, in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Hall on Astor Place was where the spoken word sparked
passions that propelled social movements like women's suffrage,
labor unions and civil rights. The series is called ``They Were
Giants.''
</P>
<P>
   That title also applies to Brown. He wasn't yet a teen-ager when
he literally talked himself into a radio gig reading poems. In the
1930s he went on to direct and produce radio shows like ``Dick
Tracy,'' ``Terry and the Pirates,'' ``Inner Sanctum Mysteries'' and
``CBS Mystery Theater.''
</P>
<P>
   The creaking door that opened those last two series inspired
millions of nightmares while giving Brown a lasting claim to a
legendary chapter in American popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   What is not as lasting, unfortunately, is the attention span of
radio audiences, who now have slim pickings between shock jocks and
nonstop Monica. Whatever happened to storytelling?
</P>
<P>
   ``The spoken word has been around since the guy came home, sat
by the fireplace and said, `Let me tell you about the people who
came before us,''' Brown said. ``We don't have time anymore. You're
overloaded with TV, motion pictures. Everything is special effects.
Everything is handed to you on a silver platter. There's no chance
for your imagination or your creativity. In radio drama, you have
to listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown taught millions how to listen. Who wouldn't, considering
the roster of actors he employed over the years? Boris Karloff,
Peter Lorre, Claude Rains, E.G. Marshall and Agnes Moorehead all
played in his radio dramas.
</P>
<P>
   He had an eye for talent even in his earliest days, when he
secured the rights to ``Dick Tracy'' while still in college. He
talked a friend from English class into writing the gang-busting
scripts. His name? Irwin Shaw. Some friend.
</P>
<P>
   With an apartment overlooking Central Park, Brown has come a
long way from cartoons. Now the drawings that he dotes on are
impressionist paintings that hang in every room. Radio has been
good to him. Just as it was for families who used to huddle
together in their more modest homes decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Depression years, people didn't have 5 cents for
movies,'' he said, tapping a marble table for emphasis. ``What did
they have? They turned on the radio. The only escape they had was
the soap operas.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he wants people to escape the cultural abyss that often
passes for entertainment. His work on the Cooper Union series was
paid for by his own foundation, like an investment in audience
development.
</P>
<P>
   He intends to revive ``Mystery Theater'' on public radio soon.
He figures that with billions of dollars spent each year on audio
books, there is an eager audience for radio dramas. And he doesn't
mean dusting off some old tapes, either. He has new tales lurking
behind the creaking door. He insists he could go on for another 10
years. He is utterly persuasive.
</P>
<P>
   ``People change, dialogue changes,'' he said. ``There were great
painters who were impressionists, but you don't write off Jackson
Pollock, either. I just don't want to live in the world of 1932 to
1950.''
</P>
<P>
   Will a new generation get hooked on radio? Will mystery lovers
shudder once again, or will they be condemned to a cruel, cruel
fate of Monica madness? And what about Hi Brown, who went from the
Depression to the impressionists?
</P>
<P>
   Tune in tomorrow, and listen closely. The door may be creaky,
but Hi Brown is anything but.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
