<HEADLINE>
OF FOOLS, FUMBLES AND A FINE FIGHTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The long and short of it:
</P>
<P>
   _The seven-point spread favoring Denver over Atlanta in the
Super Bowl is too high. And oddsmaker Roxy Roxborough expects it to
rise because ``fans are much more familiar with John Elway, Terrell
Davis and the Broncos than they are with Chris Chandler, Jamal
Anderson and the Falcons.''
</P>
<P>
   _It's not the Falcons who'll have to pick up their game next
Sunday. It's Pat Summerall and John Madden, Fox's over-the-hill
gang in the booth. Either Summerall is missing half of what's going
on or he's playing the ``understated'' routine to such an extreme,
it brings back memories of NBC's no-play-by-play experiment. And
Madden didn't seem to be kidding when he exclaimed, ``I thought the
ground couldn't cause a fumble!'' after someone in the NFC
Championship Game fell down _ without being tackled _ and the ball
was jarred loose.
</P>
<P>
   _Received an envelope from the USOC that read, ``Your Olympic
name labels are enclosed.'' And those names would be what _
``Bugsy,'' ``Scarface'' and ``Prettyboy''?
</P>
<P>
   _The more you know, the more you think Tonya Harding belonged in
the Olympics all along. And a really good tire iron would come in
handy about now.
</P>
<P>
   _If you're feeling a certain cynical glee over the Olympics
scandal, it's probably because the Games present themselves as such
a bastion of righteousness, with the trumpet fanfares and Dick
Enberg saying ``grandeur'' every five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   _Has anybody looked into possible corruption in X Games site
selections?
</P>
<P>
   _The wit and wisdom of Pat Summerall and John Madden:
</P>
<P>
   Summerall: ``7:40 (left in the game). When they start this
(play), it'll be less than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Madden: ``There gets to be a point where time is of the
essence.''
</P>
<P>
   _While Francois Botha taunted Mike Tyson as no Tyson opponent
before him, Tyson behaved like the frightened fighter in Las Vegas
last weekend. Not frightened for his safety but afraid that if he
followed his corner's plan and boxed straight up, he'd find out his
fundamental skills are as gone as the critics say. So he relied on
erratic haymakers and got lucky when Botha walked into one.
</P>
<P>
   _A friend says I'm puritanical to argue that this
thrown-together NBA season will reward the good guys _ those who
can stand the four- or five-games-a-week grind because they worked
out in the uncertain offseason. That's who I'm rooting for, all
right: the Indiana Puritans.
</P>
<P>
   _David Claerbaut, author of a book called ``The NBA Analyst,''
sets out to do for basketball stats what Bill James did for
baseball stats. Claerbaut says Shaquille O'Neal is ``a genuinely
great player,'' but five things keep him from the Michael
Jordan-Karl Malone class: He lacks a perimeter game; he can't make
free throws; he doesn't get the ``big rebound''; he's not a leader,
and ``he seems to lack court sense.'' If all that is true, then the
standard for genuinely great players must be pretty low.
</P>
<P>
   _Speaking of Jordan, how about the notion that a whole sport
depends on one player? A recent news item on Mark McGwire's
Associated Press Male Athlete of the Year Award said his 70 home
runs ``helped save the game of baseball.'' Worse-case scenario, if
the home run record hadn't happened, if players never signed
another autograph, if everybody stayed mad at everybody, do people
really think baseball was about to disappear? Or when you equate a
fractional decline in major-league attendance with impending doom,
are you making the same mistake as those who spotted a 10 percent
shift in national voting patterns and proclaimed it a Republican
Revolution?
</P>
<P>
   _The wit and wisdom of Pat Summerall: ``Randy Moss _ he's got
good speed.''
</P>
<P>
   _For what it's worth: Eric Karros, Chan Ho Park, Eric Young and
Dave Hansen are the veteran regulars at the Dodgers'
three-times-a-week workouts at Dodger Stadium. Kevin Brown worked
out on the first day and went home to Georgia. Manager Davey
Johnson appeared the first day and went home to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   _Question inspired by the impeachment trial: Are we going to
have to call him Mr. Mgr. Davey Johnson?
</P>
<P>
   _Baseball's young, hip, multicultural image took a hit when
photos of Bud Selig, George Will and George Mitchell appeared on
the same page in the current Baseball Weekly.
</P>
<P>
   _For those who wrongly excuse fighters' misdeeds on the grounds
that everybody in boxing is dirty: Vladimir Cerin, a thoroughbred
trainer at Santa Anita, named his daughter after Alexis Arguello,
the three-division champion of the 1970s and '80s. His
!ital!daughter!off!. Cerin, who used to condition human athletes,
said Arguello was ``the classiest fighter I ever met. He was always
apologizing about knocking people out.'' (Alexis Cerin is a pretty
good athlete herself _ a senior midfielder on Arcadia High's
undefeated girls' soccer team.)
</P>
<P>
   _Don't be surprised if NBA fans come back faster than baseball
fans did. That's a backhanded compliment to the NBA. Baseball fans
were still innocent enough before the 1994-95 strike to think the
American Pastime wouldn't do that to them. Basketball fans held no
such illusion about the leaders of their game.
</P>
<P>
   _When Larry Robinson benches a Kings veteran, then tells
reporters he talked with the player to make sure no feelings were
hurt, is it possible he is just too nice to be a head coach?
</P>
<P>
   _The wit and wisdom of John Madden (on players' motivation in
conference-title games): ``I don't care what people say. They say,
`You can't smell Super Bowl.' I guarantee you, you can smell Super
Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   _Or something.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
