<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5157 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NETS-NYT     01-22 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Wash.)  
 McILVAINE, NEWEST NET, KNEW IT ALL ALONG  By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Three clues were all Jim McIlvaine
needed to predict his next stop in the National Basketball
Association.
</P>
<P>
   He knew the Seattle SuperSonics wanted to cut salaries, that the
Nets wanted to block more shots, and that John Nash, the Nets'
general manager, respected him as a person and as a player. So as
early as last summer, McIlvaine began envisioning himself playing
the baseline alongside Jayson Williams, making outlet passes to Sam
Cassell and helping the metropolitan area's other basketball team
move beyond the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting in Leo's Italian Restaurant in Hoboken with my
buddy during the lockout,'' McIlvaine said Friday, moments after
his first workout with the Nets. ``I was in for a union meeting and
I told him I was going to get traded. He said, `Where do you think
you're going to go?' And I said, `Well, I might end up here,
because John Nash drafted me and I could fit in pretty decently out
here.'''
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, McIlvaine, who served on the negotiating
committee for the players union, was running wind sprints inside
the Champion Center. He had been traded to the Nets, shipped out of
Seattle on Monday for Michael Cage and Don MacLean. Just as he had
thought.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, already equipped with two capable centers in Williams
and Rony Seikaly, brought the 7-foot-1-inch McIlvaine in to do
three things: block shots, change trajectories and bang bodies. It
is a role for which he is well suited. In four NBA seasons,
McIlvaine has averaged 1.8 blocks in less than 15 minutes a game.
That is nearly as much as the Nets' starting frontcourt of
Williams, Keith Van Horn and Kendall Gill averaged together last
season.
</P>
<P>
   With little reason to fear going inside, Nets opponents drove to
the basket unceasingly last season, usually dunking or laying the
ball up, as the Nets blocked only 314 shots, fourth worst in the
league. Now, with McIlvaine in the fold, the path to the basket
will not be as inviting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gives us a presence that we didn't have last year,''
Cassell said. ``Sometimes a blocked shot means as much as a field
goal. A blocked shot can change a game around drastically.''
</P>
<P>
   After two disappointing seasons in Seattle, McIlvaine, 26, is
hoping his career also changes. When Nash, then the general manager
of the Washington Bullets, selected the Marquette product in the
second round of the 1994 draft, expectations were low. But it
quickly became evident that McIlvaine possessed a gift for
rejecting shots. His talent became appreciated throughout the
league in his second season when he averaged 2.1 blocks a game in
what amounted to little more than a quarter's worth of play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play help-side defense and keep my eyes on my man and the
ball at the same time,'' McIlvaine said, explaining why he blocks
so many shots. ``Plus, I'm tall. That helps.''
</P>
<P>
   After his break-out season, McIlvaine became perhaps the most
coveted 2-point scorer in recent NBA history, signing a free-agent
contract with Seattle worth $35 million over seven years. The
Sonics had just lost in the NBA finals to the Chicago Bulls and saw
McIlvaine as the final piece to their championship puzzle. But they
were mistaken. Inserted into Seattle's starting lineup, McIlvaine's
deficiencies _ little offense, little rebounding _ became glaring,
and he suffered under the spotlight of high expectations.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Nets, there are no such expectations. He is a
third-string center who will play 10 to 15 minutes a game and be
asked only to do what he does best.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it easy when you have a well-defined role and things
are laid out for you,'' McIlvaine said.
</P>
<P>
   After going through the deaths of two close friends _ his agent,
Ron Grinker, and the Washington assistant coach Derek Smith _ in
the last two years, McIlvaine said he believed he was destined to
experience brighter days in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my wife that I think I've got two basketball angels
looking over me,'' McIlvaine said, ``and wherever I go they'll make
sure everything works out for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets are hoping that is another McIlvaine prediction that
comes true.
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   If MICHAEL CAGE, a 14-year veteran, does not retire and is
waived by Seattle, look for him to fill the Nets' 12th roster spot.
. . .SAM CASSELL left Friday's morning practice early with leg
cramps. It did not appear serious. . . . The Nets' individual game
tickets go on sale next Friday at 9 a.m. at TicketMaster,
TicketMaster On-Line and at the Continental Arena box office.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
