</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-MEXICO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE BEGINS FOURTH VISIT OF `THE BLESSED LAND' OF MEXICO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
and RICHARD VARA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Pope John Paul II flew into Mexico's tumultuous
capital Friday to begin his fourth visit to a nation he calls
``always faithful'' to the Roman Catholic creed.
</P>
<P>
   Walking slowly but firmly with the aid of a cane, the
78-year-old pontiff descended from his jet to the sounds of
mariachi music played by a band on the tarmac.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a source of immense pleasure to find myself once again in
this blessed land, where the Holy Mary of Guadalupe is venerated as
a beloved mother,'' said John Paul, referring to Mexico's patron
saint _ the Virgin of Guadalupe _ in his arrival speech before a
large crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic officials hope this papal visit will help set the
church's course in the Americas into the next millenium. John
Paul's church is beset by dropping attendance at Mass, internal
divisions between the conservative hierarchy and grass-roots
Catholics intent on social change, and a growing conversion to
Protestant faiths.
</P>
<P>
   In his arrival remarks, John Paul emphasized the importance of
Catholicism to Mexico following Spain's conquest of the indigenous
nations that once reigned here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't possible,'' John Paul said, ``to understand Mexico
without the faith brought from Spain to these lands.''
</P>
<P>
   In greeting the pope, President Ernesto Zedillo said Mexicans
were ``proud to be a mixture of races, languages and cultures.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Favor us with your message,'' Zedillo told the pope. ``But
also do us the favor of enjoying our colors, our flavors, our
songs.''
</P>
<P>
   After the speeches, two groups of children _ four of mixed race
and four Indians _ marched solemnly to the seated pope with gifts.
A clearly pleased John Paul affectionately kissed the children on
the cheeks and foreheads, stroked their hair, whispered in their
ears.
</P>
<P>
   Following the ceremony, John Paul rode into the heart of Mexico
City, where he was presented the keys to the city by Mayor
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, and then into the southern suburbs, where he
was to sleep at the house of the papal nuncio, or Vatican envoy to
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands of people began lining the pope's route
hours before his airplane landed. As news spread that John Paul had
arrived, hundreds of people along one downtown street began
chanting, ``The pope is here. We feel his presence!''
</P>
<P>
   John Paul rode in a glass-sided bus for the trip to the city
center, then switched to the traditional pope mobile, a small truck
with a glass-enclosed platform on which the pontiff sits.
</P>
<P>
   ``My batteries are charged and ready,'' said Olga Alegria, who
rode a bus for 36 hours from the northern city of Hermosillo to
stand on a downtown street corner. ``I hope to realize my dream, to
touch the pope.''
</P>
<P>
   As the papal caravan neared, the crowd's excitement surged. Some
people poured into the street, despite heavy security, in hopes of
getting closer to the pontiff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so excited,'' Teresa Contreras, 47, said after John Paul
passed her place on the sidewalk. ``At that moment I was bursting
with love.''
</P>
<P>
   Catholic officials have said that the pope's trip to Mexico and
his 30-hour visit to St. Louis next week are meant to emphasize the
Western Hemisphere as a single entity.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexico to which John Paul arrived Friday has in many ways
changed dramatically since his first visit to the country in 1979.
The population has grown by nearly 30 percent to 95 million, more
than three-quarters of whom live in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   The once authoritarian government controlled for 70 years by
Zedillo's Institutional Revolutionary Party has grudgingly given
way to a pluralistic system that looks more like democracy with
each election.
</P>
<P>
   A 5-year-old trade pact with the United States and Canada has
brought more prosperity to northern and central cities, while
further eating at the economy of the largely rural and Indian
south. Income levels are skewed between the wealthy few and the
impoverished many.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas, the opposition Mexico City mayor who is the political
left's best hope to win presidential elections next year, told the
pope that the two decades since his first visit have brought many
negative social and economic consequences to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``As in many places, the imposition of anti-social economic
policies during this time has resulted in the sustained fall in
income for the majority of the population,'' Cardenas said in a
dour-faced speech.
</P>
<P>
   The last two decades, he added, have brought a ``constant
increase in the number of Mexicans living in poverty, an
unprecedented concentration of riches in the hands of a few, as
well as the penetration of corruption and the complicity of crime
in the nation's vital (affairs).''
</P>
<P>
   For many, Mexico's new consumer society was starkly evident in
the many billboards, ads and trinkets promoting the companies that
are helping pay for the papal visit.
</P>
<P>
   In his recent trips to poor countries in Latin America and
Africa, the staunchly anti-communist pontiff has criticized the
unbridled capitalism that has swept most of the world since the
collapse of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   During his five-day visit here, John Paul will put his seal of
approval on the results of a meeting of the hemisphere's bishops,
who met last year to chart the Catholic Church's mission in the
region during the next millenium.
</P>
<P>
   In his arrival speech, John Paul said that the bishops hope
their blueprint for action ``responds fully to the redeeming plan
of God and human dignity in the framework of just, reconciled and
open societies with a technical process that must converge with
necessary moral progress.''
</P>
<P>
   As elsewhere in Latin America, Protestant faiths during the past
two decades have made inroads into Mexico's once-solidly Roman
Catholic population, especially in the impoverished indigenous
communities of the south. Much of the current social violence in
southernmost Chiapas state, in which rebels have taken up arms
against the government, has divided Maya Indian villages between
Catholic insurgents and pro-government Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul referred to the Protestant conversion Friday by
emphasizing the important contributions that Catholicism has made
to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition to their evangelizing effort, which made
Catholicism an integral and fundamental part of the nation's soul,
the (Spanish) missionaries left profound cultural traces and
prodigious examples that today are sources of legitimate pride for
all Mexicans,'' he said at the airport ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The pope will say Mass on Saturday for Catholic clergy at the
Basilica of Our Lady of Guadalupe near downtown Mexico City.
Catholic faithful believe the church marks the spot where an
olive-skinned Virgin Mary appeared to a poor Indian farmer soon
after the Spanish conquest. A symbol of the mixing of European and
indigenous cultures, the Virgin of Guadalupe has become the patron
saint of Mexico and is revered throughout Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday morning, John Paul will say Mass for the general
population at an automobile race track. On Monday he is to deliver
a message to the hemisphere's youth in the giant Azteca sports
stadium on the city's south side. On Tuesday, the pope is scheduled
to fly to St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
