<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5161 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT     01-22 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTS, CAMERA, APOLOGY: SPREWELL TAKES THE STAGE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.Y., Calif.) (bl) 
By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RYE BROOK, N.Y. _ Latrell Sprewell's image reclamation project
began Friday afternoon about half past three as a curtain parted
and his lanky figure appeared in tan pants and a peach sweater.
</P>
<P>
   The pastel colors seemed fitting for a man trying to present a
softer side to counter the vision of an angry player known for his
furious dunks and his violent attack on coach P.J. Carlesimo 14
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   For a half hour, Sprewell sat on a dais and apologized a lot,
smiled a lot and displayed unwavering poise through the stickiest
of questions after he was introduced at a news conference as the
New York Knicks' latest acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   As he paged back to Dec. 1, 1997 _ the day he choked Carlesimo
and left the Golden State practice only to return and threaten his
coach _ he discounted the notion that he had a problem controlling
his rage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fair to say I had a bad day,'' said Sprewell, who
is expected to begin practicing with the Knicks on Saturday once
all parties in the trade _ John Starks, Terry Cummings and Chris
Mills, who were sent to Golden State _ pass their physicals.
``That's not me. I don't have a problem. I don't walk around angry.
It's not like every time someone says something to me I get up in
their face. I really wouldn't say I had a problem. I'd say I had a
bad day.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell has had a few of those. Last March, Sprewell lost
control of his car and was charged with reckless driving. He was
sentenced to three months of house arrest. On July 31, a federal
judge dismissed his $30 million lawsuit against the NBA, a suit
Sprewell filed with the belief that the league conspired against
him when it handed down a year's suspension that was reduced to
seven months by an arbitrator. He has since re-filed that lawsuit.
In October, Sprewell sued his agent, Arn Tellem, for malpractice
because he failed to negotiate a salary protection clause in his
deal with the Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell sounded contrite Friday, but expressed no intention of
dropping his pending lawsuits and beginning his second basketball
life completely unencumbered by his past problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognize I should have been punished,'' Sprewell said.
``But I felt that the punishment was a bit severe.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell was officially reinstated after a 20-minute meeting
this morning with commissioner David Stern. Sprewell said he
expressed to Stern how wrong he was for his attack on Carlesimo and
reassured him that he would be a positive influence in the NBA.
Friday was the first step in revealing that side of his
personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real me is the caring person,'' said Sprewell, who is
expected to play in a three-guard lineup. ``It's not the person
that has been portrayed in the media. I'm not someone who has an
attitude problem. I'm not mean. People may think that because of
the aggressive way I play the game. That's just the way I play. I
don't walk around the streets like that.''
</P>
<P>
   No one would know. Sprewell has been out of the public eye,
spending his basketball exile at his family's home in Milwaukee. It
was the land of home-cooked meals and comfortable surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   But Sprewell is a professional athlete. For him to sit dormant
for a year is like keeping a sports car garaged. Will he sputter or
backfire once he is rolled out onto a showroom floor like Madison
Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Although he stayed active with daily weight training at the
closest Bally's sports club, his basketball void was hardly filled.
Most days, he said, he played one-on-one with his brother or jumped
into a pickup game at the YMCA. He was a three-time All-Star
playing with guys on their lunch break. Often, just because he was
the tallest person in the game, at 6 feet 5 inches, Sprewell played
center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't played against NBA players since December of '97,''
said Sprewell, who rated his playing condition at 7 or 8 on a scale
of 10. ``I'm not going to sit here and say I'm in great playing
condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy sat next to Sprewell as the player
talked about his return. Whatever dust was on Sprewell's game, Van
Gundy was excited to have his talent. He said he was especially
impressed with how little Sprewell expressed concerned with playing
time and personal statistics. On first impressions, Van Gundy
viewed this player as an all-star of a coach's dream, not of the
Carlesimo nightmare. On first impressions, Van Gundy seemed
undaunted by the challenge of mixing Sprewell into the team
chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Van Gundy said he was neither awed by
Sprewell's polished delivery Friday or skeptical of his sincerity.
He was just realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find him to be very sincere and direct and honest,'' Van
Gundy said. ``But the only way for him to show it is to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; CHRIS DUDLEY &LR;  missed practice Friday because of the flu.
</P>
<P>
   _ The league rescinded the latter half of the two-game
suspension the Heat's  &UR; ALONZO MOURNING &LR;  received after his fight
with  &UR; LARRY JOHNSON  &LR; in Game 4 of last year's playoff series.
Neither played in Game 5. After the Knicks advanced past the Heat
in the playoffs, Johnson sat out his second game in Game 1 against
Indiana. Johnson lost $206,000 for those two games.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning, who would have been forced to sit out this year's
season opener, saved $161,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
