<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DWI-SEIZURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC CONSIDERS PLAN TO SEIZE CARS OF ACCUSED DRUNK DRIVERS
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By ALAN FINDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Legal scholars and criminal lawyers questioned Friday
the legality of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's plan to seize the cars of
people charged with drunken driving, as mayoral aides acknowledged
that city lawyers were still reviewing the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir said Thursday that, starting in
February, officers would seize the car of anyone charged with
drunken driving, including first-time offenders. If the car were
owned by someone other than the accused driver, or if the accused
were eventually acquitted, the car would be returned. Otherwise, it
would be forfeited to the city.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, after meeting with police commissioner, Giuliani
approved the concept of the plan, said Colleen Roche, the mayor's
press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor and the police commissioner are in complete
agreement about the use of forfeiture,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Roche said city lawyers were still examining some legal
issues and other city officials were reviewing practical matters,
including where all the cars would be stored.
</P>
<P>
   State law allows the forfeiture of vehicles owned by drivers who
repeatedly drive while intoxicated, but the law is rarely enforced.
Safir, in discussing his proposal Thursday, said police would rely
on what he called a creative interpretation of the city's
forfeiture laws, which give officers the authority to seize
property, like firearms, drugs and burglary tools, used in the
commission of crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But many lawyers said Friday that it was uncertain whether the
administrative law could be read to permit the seizure of the car
of a first-time offender _ especially before the person is tried
and convicted. Several lawyers also wondered about the propriety of
seizing a leased car or one that was purchased with a bank loan.
The companies leasing or financing the car might well go to court
to challenge a seizure, saying they owned the car, not the driver,
the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My take on it is that it may be extremely harsh,'' said Burt
Neuborne, a professor of law at New York University Law School.
``One sympathizes with the desire to curb drunk driving, but the
imposition of a forfeiture in a situation like that may really
impose an excessive penalty and may do so without adequate
statutory authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Laws in 22 states authorize municipal officials to confiscate
the cars of drunken drivers, but virtually all those laws involve
repeat offenders, said officials with the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration, a federal agency. Federal officials said
they were unaware of any city's using its own laws as the basis for
forfeiture.
</P>
<P>
   Several lawyers wondered how the city would store cars while a
driver's case was adjudicated, who would pay for insurance while
the cars were stored and what the city would do if a
drunken-driving case were resolved through a plea bargain, as they
often are.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concerns are, what are the procedural aspects?'' said
Charles Adler, chairman of the criminal law committee of the
Association of the Bar of the City of New York. ``Are people going
to be required to waive their right to return of the car in order
to be able to negotiate the charge? Typically these charges are
negotiated. Very few cases go to trial. Is the routine disposition
of a case going to involve the person giving up the car?
</P>
<P>
   ``If the city wants to use that as a deterrent, then it ought to
put in place streamlined procedures that assist people who have
legitimate claims easily and quickly. What concerns me most is:
What are the safeguards for fairness going to be?''
</P>
<P>
   Many lawyers predicted that first-time offenders would fight the
confiscation of their cars in court. ``I think it's inevitable that
there is going to be litigation,'' said Norman Siegel, executive
director of the New York Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other states, it's based upon conviction,'' Siegel said.
``Here, he is seizing this based upon arrest. That undermines the
presumption of innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani had initially thought that Thursday's announcement was
premature, in part because the city's lawyers had not reviewed the
plan, mayoral aides said. But the mayor evidently became convinced
that Safir's idea was a useful tool to discourage people from
drinking and then driving.
</P>
<P>
   Safir, speaking with reporters after he met with Giuliani at
City Hall, said the initiative would go forward, although he
revised his earlier comments to say that no starting date had been
set. ``We just want to make sure we do this carefully and we do
this correctly,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
