<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5165 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PRISON-ABUSE-625&AMP;A     01-22 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PRISON-ABUSE-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. IS ASKED TO INVESTIGATE ABUSE AT PRISON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. _ As lawyers of other former inmates came
forward with accounts of what they say is rampant abuse at the
Nassau Correctional Center, Democratic county legislators called
Friday for a federal investigation into the treatment of prisoners
at the jail, where the police say a man was fatally beaten on Jan.
8.
</P>
<P>
   Alleging a number of complaints about corrections officers,
legislators Lisanne Altmann of Great Neck and Roger Corbin of
Westbury asked that the U.S. attorney, Zachary Carter, begin an
investigation of the East Meadow jail, following the Jan. 13 death
of Thomas Pizzuto, a Hicksville man whose family says he was
brutally beaten by guards after demanding to receive methadone
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The call for a wider-ranging federal inquiry, on top of separate
investigations of Pizzuto's death by four local and state agencies,
came as lawyers for a number of former inmates and their families
described life inside the 2,200-bed jail as replete with violence
and intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers said that complaints by inmates as well as
well-meaning guards were discouraged and frequently squashed, and
asserted that a strict code of silence had made it all but
impossible to prosecute abusive guards. Prosecutors investigated 15
complaints by prisoners of abuse last year, which resulted in no
arrests.
</P>
<P>
   In the Pizzuto case, law-enforcement officials confirmed that
guards forced the 38-year-old to sign a statement falsely saying
his injuries were accidental; the explanation was that he fell in
the shower, according to the Pizzuto family's lawyer. Investigators
say they have encountered difficulty in obtaining information from
guards who were in a position to see or hear about the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Nassau County sheriff, Joseph Jablonsky, refused to be
interviewed Friday. Instead, Jablonsky, who has overseen the Nassau
Correctional Center since 1988, issued a four-sentence statement
saying that the jail ``has a proud record of service,'' and that
``any allegations of improper care will be fully investigated, and
appropriate action will be taken if required.''
</P>
<P>
   But the president of the corrections officers union, Mark
Barber, conceded that there might have been abuses in the past and
attributed any problems in the culture inside the jail to a failure
by the authorities inside and outside the Sheriff's Department to
investigate allegations thoroughly enough. ``I welcome the Pizzuto
investigation,'' he said, adding that he had instructed all his
members to cooperate with law-enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for former inmates on Friday described numerous
instances of abuse and neglect at the jail in recent years.
Frederick Brewington, a civil rights lawyer in Hempstead, said that
one of his clients, Gary Boylan, 46, of Hicksville, who suffers
from Parkinson's disease, was ``beaten into a coma'' by guards on
Sept. 14, while he was being held on a charge of reckless
endangerment of a minor, which was later dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Boylan had suffered a seizure while driving and had asked a girl
``to get help,'' the lawyer said. She misunderstood his plea as
``get in,'' and he was arrested, Brewington said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next time his mother sees him it's two days later, and
he's in the hospital,'' he said. ``He had hundreds of stitches in
his head. They beat him into a coma that lasted four days. His
face, neck, back, arms _ he was injured all over. People told his
mother that he had a seizure and fell and hurt himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewington said that his client, who suffered permanent head
injuries, had been attacked by guards who should have been
protecting him. ``Somebody in the jail thought he was a child
molester, and they were going to give him an attitude adjustment,''
he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Brewington also asserted that prisoners were frequently denied
needed medical treatment. He cited the death last July of
Christopher Jackson, 28, of Locust Valley, a sickle-cell anemia
patient who was awaiting trial on a minor drug charge when he
became ill and lapsed into a coma.
</P>
<P>
   Brewington, who is suing the county on behalf of Jackson's
family, said the state Commission of Correction was expected to
issue a report soon on its inquiry into allegations that Jackson
had asked for treatment but was not hospitalized for three days,
until his mother urged officials to get her son a blood
transfusion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
