</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-DISCRIMINATION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING SETTLES DISCRIMINATION SUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE - In what civil-rights leader Jesse Jackson called ``a
significant step on the long journey to making Boeing the best it
can be,'' the aerospace giant Friday announced it has settled two
class-action lawsuits brought by African American workers who said
the company discriminated against them.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson helped negotiate a consent decree filed Friday in
federal court in Seattle. It requires Boeing to pay $15 million to
settle the lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Boeing must improve the way it selects and promotes
workers, adopt a new system for handling complaints about
discrimination, harassment or retaliation, and hire a consultant to
assess how well the changes work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made significant progress on every front ... to foster
an environment of inclusion,'' Boeing Chairman Phil Condit said at
a morning news conference at the company's Seattle headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's settlement represents one more step toward (Boeing)
becoming a company of inclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   The news conference was held in an auditorium where Boeing in
past years has held its annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of shareholders, this time Condit faced many of the
black employees who brought suit against the company, claiming they
were routinely harassed on the job and lost promotions to
less-experienced white workers.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also spoke. He first met with Condit last September and
played the key role in the two sides reaching a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing's capacity to do good is enormous,'' Jackson said,
referring to Boeing's position as the world's largest aerospace
company.
</P>
<P>
   Several times in his remarks, Jackson mentioned Airbus, the
European airplane maker that is Boeing's only remaining rival in
building planes with more than 100 seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inclusion is the key to economic growth,'' Jackson said.
``Let's get together ... then when Boeing meets Airbus in the Super
Bowl it can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Also speaking were two Seattle attorneys who represented the
workers who brought suit.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Oscar Desper, said Boeing would be watched closely
to see that it complies with the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be around to watch and make sure this consent decree
is just not a piece of paper, but that changes in fact will be
made,'' said Desper, whose father worked for Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the 35-page consent degree, Boeing denied it ever
engaged in any pattern of racial discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by a reporter why that language is in the decree, Condit
said it was better for Boeing to settle the lawsuits and not spend
time battling in court.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was time for Boeing to move forward.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits were filed last year. The initial suit was brought
by 43 black workers who said discrimination was common at Boeing
plants in the Puget Sound area.
</P>
<P>
   Later, black workers for Boeing in Philadelphia and in Wichita,
Kan., joined in the suit. A second suit also was started. The suits
complained of a racially hostile work environment that saw blacks
the object of slurs, crude drawings and intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 13,000 blacks work for Boeing around the country. The
total work force numbers about 228,000.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed settlement, 20,000 current and former
employees of Boeing and its subsidiary companies, including
McDonnell Douglas, would be eligible to share in $7.3 million in
payments.
</P>
<P>
   About half the money, or $3.77 million, will go to 264
individually identified plaintiffs, who generally will get payments
of $10,000 to $30,000, with some individuals getting as much as
$50,000.
</P>
<P>
   More than $4 million will go to plaintiffs' lawyers for fees and
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also agreed to spend $3.65 million on improved training
and changes in the way it selects managers and makes other
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Desper, the lawyer for the small Seattle firm that brought the
main case, said it was not about money.
</P>
<P>
   ``This started as a dream for justice. This was for justice. It
was not for the money,'' Desper said, his eyes filling with tears
and his voice breaking with emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is just the first step toward reconciliation for all
races of people at The Boeing Co. so that everyone can be treated
the same, from the janitor to the top, whether they are female,
Asian or black ... that you are treated the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the plaintiffs in the Boeing auditorium for the
announcement was Solomon Williams, who has worked at Boeing for 22
years. He is the lead operator of a milling machine at the
company's Auburn plant.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled to reporters how he and other experienced black
workers were passed over for promotions.
</P>
<P>
   The promotions went to young white males who had little if any
experience, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we questioned this, the response was, `We have a gut
feeling they (the white workers) can do the job.'''
</P>
<P>
   He said conditions at his Boeing job site have improved since
the discrimination suit was filed, but not significantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``After they discovered there was a problem, they started making
superficial changes,'' Williams said. ``They made a few more blacks
inspectors, a few more blacks supervisors. But it's not widespread
enough yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Williams said he feels ``vindicated'' by the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me want to go and do an even better job, because I
know I will be graded by my performance and not who I play golf
with, who I go hunting with or who I go fishing with. ... If you
were not in the good old boys club, you didn't move ahead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 2252EST &QL; 
