u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUNDAY-FINAL-BUDGET-N     01-22 2209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-FINAL-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (af)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Jan. 24,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ELIMINATE: STEVE-LACY-JAZZ and MODERN-MUSEUM-FILMS. &UR;  &LR; ADD:
TV-FUTURAMA.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FEATURE stories &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MUSICAL-MAKEOVERS (subslug) (New York) _ The birth of a new
musical: it's all so ``Act One,'' all so invigorating. Hey, hold on
a sec. Did I say new? The show in question is ``Annie Get Your
Gun,'' and while the frantic pre-Broadway preparations, with
Bernadette Peters as pistol-packin' Annie Oakley, are indeed
occurring in 1999, the date on the musical's copyright is 1946.
Although it was a critical and popular success in the '40s, running
on Broadway for 1,147 performances, the show, with music and lyrics
by Irving Berlin and book by Herbert and Dorothy Fields, has long
been considered unrevivable, in large part because of its
hopelessly outdated portrayal of Indians. The solution that the
show's producers, Fran and Barry Weissler, came up with for ``Annie
Get Your Gun,'' which begins previews on Feb. 2 at the Marquis
Theater on Broadway, is one that has become increasingly common in
musical theater: wholesale renovation. ``Basically, it's a new
book,'' said Peter Stone, the veteran librettist, with credits
stretching from ``1776'' to ``Titanic,'' who was hired to bring the
structure and sensibility of ``Annie Get Your Gun'' into line with
musicals of the late 1990s. By Peter Marks. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   STANDUP-COMEDIANS (New York) _ There's only one thing more
humiliating than being a stand-up comic. And that's trying to be a
stand-up comic. That's the lesson I learned after six months trying
to make it as a comedian. Ask Jerry Seinfeld, Rosie O'Donnell or
any successful stand-up: the bottom rung of the comedy ladder can
be uglier, crueler and more demeaning than in any other line of
entertainment _ be it actor, model, musician, writer or clown.
Sexism and racism run rampant, club-owners ask struggling comedians
to scrape gum off the bottom of tables to get a booking,
competition between comics is fierce, and newcomers have to pay to
perform. By Neil Strauss. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   FILM AND VIDEO
</P>
<P>
   DRY-CLEANING-FILM (Paris) _ Miou-Miou, 48, has appeared in good
films and bad, hits and flops, yet for 25 years France's affection
for her has not wavered. True, being loved has been no guarantee of
good screen roles or healthy box-office returns. Yet, for an entire
generation of French moviegoers, she remains reassuringly familiar.
Her very stage name, Miou-Miou, given to her by a lover when she
was barely 18, makes her sound like the gamine next door. Her
latest film is Anne Fontaine's ``Nettoyage a Sec,''or ``Dry
Cleaning,'' which was well received in France 15 months ago and
opens on Feb. 5 in New York. By Alan Riding. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-SEX-FILMS (Undated) _ When it comes to issues of sexual
identity, European films can be difficult for American viewers to
talk about or even understand fully. We assume that Europeans,
whose leaders can carry on extramarital affairs without falling
from grace, are more sophisticated, more laissez-faire about sex in
general and, specifically, about the blurring of hetero-, bi- and
homosexuality. But we can't quite figure out how they achieve this
nonchalance. By Will Joyner. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   DANCE
</P>
<P>
   BALLET-BRITISH-COLUMBIA (Vancouver, British Columbia) _ Back in
1985, when the latest of a series of West Coast balletic phoenixes
rose tentatively from the ashes of Pacific Ballet Theater, nothing
so ambitious as a passport appeared on the agenda for the new
Ballet British Columbia. It was to be a Vancouver-based company
with a regional mission, to bring ballet to the various centers of
its home province. Less than a decade later, the company was
dancing at Whitman Hall at Brooklyn College, where it was
characterized by Anna Kisselgoff in The New York Times as ``a
handsome group of 16 classical dancers whose bold demeanor evokes
the tough, frank manner of contemporary ballet troupes in Europe.''
In its return one-week New York engagement starting Tuesday at the
Joyce Theater, the program will consist of contemporary Canadian
works, according to its artistic director John Alleyne. By William
Littler. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   THEATER
</P>
<P>
   AKALAITIS-THEATER (New York) _ Ms. JoAnne Akalaitis, 60, has
been called a theater radical whose work grows increasingly
distilled, profound and challenging, as well as a bloodless
modernist who disrespects Shakespeare, debases the Greeks and
shamelessly distorts Jean Genet and Tennessee Williams. The
symbolist gestures she favors _ sometimes her actors move in a kind
of slow-motion Kabuki style or fall to the ground as if pulled by a
demonic force _ have been celebrated as inspired and decried as
gimmicky. Fans say her penchant for updating classics makes them
see the works anew; critics complain that she has a narrow academic
vision and that her changes are gratuitous and distracting. Ms.
Akalaitis is currently working on the ``The Iphigenia Cycle.'' By
Nancy Hass. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY-THEATER (Undated) _ Vincent Canby reviews ``Fosse'' and
``Art.'' (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL-MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-SYMPHONY (Undated) _ Sir Colin Davis and the London
Symphony will appear at Avery Fisher Hall in New York City for
three concerts focusing on another enigmatic post-Romantic
composer, Sir Edward Elgar. The series, part of a larger festival,
``The Glory of Britain: Sir Edward Elgar,'' presented by Great
Performers at Lincoln Center, opens Sunday afternoon with Elgar's
Introduction and Allegro, and Cello Concerto (with Steven Isserlis
as soloist). By Anthony Tommasini. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   GERMAN-SONGS-CLASSES (New York) _ At a lecture before a recent
lieder recital in Los Angeles, Graham Johnson made a case for
balkanizing Schubert, after a fashion. Johnson, a piano
accompanist, scholar and teacher based in London, suggested that
the six songs Schubert wrote to texts by Heine included in the
posthumous song cycle ``Schwanengesang'' be split off and viewed as
a free-standing work. The idea is vintage Johnson, unconventional
yet compelling. Monday, at the Juilliard School, Johnson begins a
series of five master classes for singers and accompanists focusing
on German song. By David Mermelstein. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   POP-MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   VERNON-DUKE-MUSIC (Undated) _ There is something so improbably
consoling about the sadness at the heart of the best Vernon Duke
melodies. This redemptive afterglow could be a consequence of sheer
melodic sophistication; Duke knew how to construct a song,
elegantly, with surpassing craft and harmonic flair. An
aristocratic White Russian emigre turned Broadway songwriter, he
seems to have had a rather good time of it all, dressing with
notorious sartorial dash, charming in a polyglot of romance
language chorus girls and theatrical producers alike. Among some of
his popular songs were ``Autumn in New York,'' ``April in Paris''
and ``I Can't get Started.'' By Barry Singer. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   ART
</P>
<P>
   PHILLY-INDIAN-ART (Undated) _ Thirty years ago, the Philadelphia
Museum of Art presented a ground-breaking exhibition titled
``Unknown India: Ritual Art in Tribe and Village.'' Organized by
the art historian Stella Kramrisch (1896-1993), it brought together
work from outside India's ancient classical traditions. Much has
changed since the 1960s. Qualitative distinctions between fine art
and folk art have been rethought. Vernacular art is taking its
rightful place in elite collections. Maybe that's why the small
exhibition at the Philadelphia Museum until Feb. 3, ``Threads of
Cotton, Threads of Brass: Arts of Eastern India and Bangladesh from
the Stella Kramrisch Collection,'' carries a thrill of delight
rather than a shock of surprise. The show is, in a sense, a reprise
of ``Unknown India'' three decades later and in miniature. By
Holland Cotter. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   TV-DILBERT (Culver City, Calif.) _ If anyone in the television
industry is afraid of corporate downsizing, it is UPN. The
struggling four-year-old broadcaster is widely seen to be on the
verge of eradication after a string of hitless seasons and notable
public relations fiascoes, like last season's ``Secret Diary of
Desmond Pfeiffer,'' a very short-lived alleged Civil War satire.
For public consumption, network officials grit their teeth and deny
it, but it is widely believed in the industry that the success or
failure of ``Dilbert'' an animation show by Scott Adams, will be a
definitive marker of UPN's ultimate _ or, ominously, short-term _
viability. By Andy Meisler. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TV-FAMILY-GUY (Los Angeles) _ One of the things Seth MacFarlane
liked about animation when he was growing up was the way it
elasticized reality. Anvils dropped without consequence and skunks
sang in French, creating a sort of pluperfect pliability where he
could retreat from a world in which people treated him, shockingly,
like a child and enter one where he was in complete control. There,
in the manner of a visiting deity, he spoke for everyone, he had
all the money in the world, and a thought never entered anyone's
head that he didn't put there. This was, of course, perfect
training for Hollywood, where MacFarlane _ now 25, but still
growing _ remains in almost complete control of the new world he
has created: an animated half-hour comedy called ``Family Guy''
that will have its premiere on Fox next Sunday following the Super
Bowl. By Bruce Newman. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TV-FUTURAMA (Santa Monica, Calif.) _ Matt Groening, 44, the
creator of the ``Simpsons'' is preparing to introduce a new series
called ``Futurama.'' The series is scheduled for a March premiere
on Fox. ``Futurama'' is set in the year 3000 in New New York City,
which is built atop the ruins of the original New York. By Anita
Gates. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-COMEDY (Moscow) _ It's not hard to make fun of what is
happening in Russia these days. New jokes about the new rich (now
the new poor after last summer's sudden financial crisis) are
posted on the Internet. President Boris Yeltsin's fumbling speech
is always an easy laugh. There may be more comedy routines about
bank failures than there are solvent banks in Russia. But real
humor _ the deep, biting, funny-sad satire that makes Russians
laugh, usually at themselves _ has become rarer, or at least so
says Mikhail Zhvanetsky, the country's premier stand-up comedian
and humor writer. By Celestine Bohlen. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   NY-RUSSIAN-COMEDIANS (New York) _ Everyone's a comedian. Wander
along the boardwalk in Brighton Beach, as a team of young immigrant
comics does for their twice-monthly television show. Shove a
microphone at any ordinary-looking guy in a fur hat. Has he got a
joke for you? Has he got a joke for you! Humor, the elixir that
helped relieve the aches and pains of life in the former Soviet
Union, has survived the Russian immigrants' voyage to Brooklyn. Not
only are the streets filled with wags; the Russian newspapers are
filled with page after page of jokes. The Russian-language
television and radio station, WMNB, broadcasts two locally produced
comedy shows. Transplanted Russian comics work the private-party
circuit, while the most successful of the New York City immigrant
troupes, Kanotiye, fills the 600-seat National restaurant in
Brooklyn every time the group opens a new variety show. By Susan
Sachs. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES
</P>
<P>
   MEDIEVAL-ARCADE-ANTIQUES (New York) _ A few months ago, Ward and
Co., New York dealers of ancient and medieval art, sent out a
lavish, fold-out booklet of photographs to display some of the rare
objects from its collection. Most of the objects were from
prehistoric or classical times, but an arresting one was from the
medieval world: an arcade, or arch, from a 12th-century Romanesque
choir screen from the church of the Abbey of Cluny in Burgundy.
This architectural fragment was enticing because it conjured up an
entire structure yet stood on its own as a piece of sculpture. By
Paula Deitz. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (`t' category)
</P>
