<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS WIN SECOND STRAIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
 (bl)  
By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Jersey Devils coach Robbie Ftorek evaluates his players over
10-game spans. Although their last 10 games have been their worst
this season, they made it respectable by winning the last two games
of their three-game California trip that was completed at the Forum
in Inglewood, Calif., on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   After losing at San Jose in the opening game of the trip, the
Devils (25-14-5) defeated the Mighty Ducks at Anaheim on Wednesday
night and edged the Los Angeles Kings by 3-2 on Thursday night to
go 4-5-1 in their last 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   Although their last two victories came with a great deal of help
from the Mighty Ducks and the Kings, Ftorek gave all the credit to
his players as he summed up the three-game trip following the
narrow victory over the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the way we bounced back after losing the first game,''
Ftorek said. ``Yeah, this is the worst 10-game segment, but we made
strides to improve our game. And I think we'll be better once we
get into divisional games.''
</P>
<P>
   He apparently meant conference games because the Devils have
only eight games left against Atlantic Division opponents after the
break for tomorrow's All-Star Game. Knowing that the Devils
traditionally play better against teams in their conference, Ftorek
and the Devils should be pleased going into the All-Star Game
break. The Devils are 9-2-1 against Atlantic Division opponents and
10-7-4 against other Eastern Conference teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils will have four representatives at the All-Star Game.
Martin Brodeur will be the starting goaltender on the North
American team, which includes Scott Stevens, the Devils' captain.
Bobby Holik is on the World All-Stars, where Ftorek will serve as
the assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The break will be good for us,'' said Brian Rolston, who has
been playing well in recent weeks and has been given more ice time
by Ftorek. ``It'll give us a chance to rest our bumps and
bruises.''
</P>
<P>
   Rolston could have added that it would give the Devils players
time to recover from the flu, which hit at least five members of
the team. Patrik Elias was the worst, missing the last five games,
and he has lost 10 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Rolston, who played nearly 25 minutes against the Kings, took
five shots and assisted on Holik's goal, which gave the Devils the
lead. Scott Niedermayer scored the winner for the Devils, and
Brodeur was brilliant down the stretch. He appears to be in top
form.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good right now,'' said Brodeur, who made his 14th start
in the last 15 games. ``I hope it continues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
