<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFUSION FOLLOWS FANFARE OVER HIGH-SPEED INTERNET LINK FOR NYC
SCHOOLS
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and executives from
Cablevision Systems announced with much fanfare this week that the
company would provide high-speed Internet access to more than 900
public and private schools in the Bronx and Brooklyn, there was
just one problem: Nobody told the teachers, principals and students
who will eventually use it.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those principals say their schools do not have enough
computers to take advantage of the new technology.
</P>
<P>
   Out of nine principals and district superintendents canvassed at
random Friday in the Bronx and Brooklyn districts where Cablevision
plans to install the high-speed cable modems, not one knew when or
how the technology would come to their schools or how it would be
used in teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know a lot about it,'' said Alan Fierstein, the
principal at Eugenio M. DeHostos Middle School in Williamsburg,
Brooklyn. ``I saw it on TV the other day. I wasn't notified of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   And some principals and Board of Education officials expressed
confusion about how the Cablevision plan would fit in with the
board's efforts to install Internet-ready computers in every public
school by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if that's something we need in this school or
not,'' said Esther Forrest, the principal at the Bronx New School,
a magnet school emphasizing math and science, when asked about the
Cablevision plan. The Board of Education program, called Project
Smart Schools, equipped each of her classrooms with two Macintosh
computers last year. ``We're already hooked up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   School board officials said they were told almost nothing about
the Cablevision plan. ``We're really left out of the loop on this
whole thing,'' said a Board of Education official who insisted on
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of classroom technology in October by the journal
Education Week found that students in New York State had less
access to computers and the Internet than their peers nationwide.
And in New York City, many schools have even less. At Public School
155 in Brownsville, Brooklyn, for example, the principal, Stan
Lovelle, said he was pleased to hear of the Cablevision plan but
added that the school had only three Internet-ready computers for
about 800 students.
</P>
<P>
   In a ceremony Thursday at Intermediate School 220 in Borough
Park, Brooklyn, Cablevision announced that it would wire every
school in its New York City service area _ the Bronx and much of
Brooklyn _ with high-speed cable modems, which operate up to 100
times as fast as telephone-based modems and could connect
classrooms of students to an array of Internet-based educational
tools.
</P>
<P>
   The cable-modem plan is part of the company's operating contract
with the city, but Cablevision says it will go well beyond that
contract. It will also provide the technical infrastructure to
allow teachers to hold classes remotely, through computers, company
officials said. All the schools will be connected to the company's
network by 2003. The company estimated the value of its
contribution at $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider this to be a long-term partnership, not simply
attaching a wire to the school and moving on,'' said Charlie
Schueler, a spokesman for Cablevision.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the technical questions, teachers also face other,
perhaps more formidable barriers to turning the Internet's digital
medium into a useful tool for pupils. The problem now, experts
said, is too many connections and not enough content to connect to.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet right now is more like a multimedia television
set,'' said Frank Moretti, executive director of the Center for New
Media Teaching and Learning at Columbia University. ``There's a
whole level of enterprise that really hasn't taken place yet,'' he
said, especially in the areas of student-oriented software and
curriculum. Cutting-edge hardware is a positive step, Moretti
added, but ``it's not an educational panacea.''
</P>
<P>
   But for many schools, Cablevision may provide a doorway to the
digital world.
</P>
<P>
   Ira Weston, the principal of Paul Robeson High School in Crown
Heights, Brooklyn, said he was unaware of the Cablevision plan but
called it a wonderful idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would give my students exposure to the Web and to the
world,'' Weston said. Though the school has 250 computers in
libraries and classrooms, only three can connect to the Internet,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   School administrators also noted that as advanced as
Cablevision's high-speed connections may be, unfettered access to
the Internet can actually turn into a liability in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``High-speed Internet access is wonderful,'' said Nelson Abreu,
the principal of Roberto Clemente Middle School in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   But only if it is regulated, he said, adding: ``I would not want
my schoolchildren to have access to the Internet carte blanche. I
don't think any intelligent person would.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
