r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARCRAZY-AZR &LR;      01-22 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARCRAZY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX AREA GOES CAR CRAZY WITH CLASSIC AUTO AUCTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The traffic is heavy, but certainly not boring.
There's a gleaming Cadillac from the '50s, looking all big and
chunky next to the modern compact cars.
</P>
<P>
   A high-performance 1969 Chevy Camaro, painted bright yellow,
rumbles along noisily. A car-carrier totes a black-and-white
Studebaker high above the gridlock. And, amazingly, a valuable
Ferrari Testarossa goes skittering by in the opposite direction
with a smoky roar, it's rear haunches looking impossibly wide.
</P>
<P>
   Must be auction time.
</P>
<P>
   It happens every January, when the big classic car auctions come
rolling in. The Phoenix area goes bonkers for vintage vehicles of
every shape and stripe, with old classics, sports cars, even
antique pickup trucks, seeming to come out of the woodwork. Many
sit on the side of the road wearing ``For Sale'' signs, their
owners eager to cash in on the frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   In the newspaper's classifieds, the usual single column of
classic vehicle ads suddenly blossoms into nearly two full pages.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend is the big one, the Barrett-Jackson Classic Car
Auction and Exposition, once a minor Scottsdale event that in the
past 28 winters has grown into an international classic-car fest of
multimillion-dollar proportions.
</P>
<P>
   More than 120,000 people are expected to wander through the rows
of veteran vehicles up for auction at WestWorld in north
Scottsdale. About 800 cars and trucks are lined up, everything from
old Fords and Chevys to exotic Bugattis, Ferraris and Duesenbergs.
</P>
<P>
   Among the crowd is a significant smattering of millionaires and
well-known celebrities, such as TV star Tim Allen, who has a Shelby
Mustang up for auction, and Peter Fonda, who is hawking a replica
of his famous Captain America custom Harley-Davidson, made famous
in the '60s film classic, ``Easy'' ``Rider.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Exposition tent are the real high-roller cars, displayed
with frightening price tags on their windshields. These are the
thoroughbreds, the big classic Packards and Cadillacs from the
'30s, one-of-a-kind custom Rolls-Royces and Mercedes-Benzes, garish
concept cars, rare Europeans and some real pieces of automotive
history.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Sinatra's T'bird is there, a 1956 two-seater painted the
same custom slate grey in which Frank himself ordered it. It's
flanked by two other automotive members of the notorious Rat Pack
that once roamed Las Vegas: a 1962 Dual Ghia that belonged to Dean
Martin (martini bar not included) and a custom-bodied 1964
Rolls-Royce Silver Cloud III that Sammy Davis Jr. tooled around in.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone agrees, Frank's wheels are the hottest. Ordinarily, a
restored '56 Thunderbird would be parked down on the polo field
with the rest of the semi-affordable iron. But Sinatra's cachet
boosts the value immeasurably, turning a $35,000 classic into a
six-figure collector's item.
</P>
<P>
   The original invoice with Sinatra's name on it is propped up in
the front seat, next to the album cover for the LP record, ``Come
Fly With Me.'' The original price, with all the options and extras,
came to $3,146. ``It's going to bring an inordinately high
amount,'' said Dave Dubie, a Scottsdale classic-car professional
who's working at the Exposition tent. ``It's going to shock
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any other T'bird, I don't care how nice it is, would never
bring more than $40,000, maybe $50,000. But with this chemistry,
with Sinatra's name attached to it . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Dubie shrugs. Auction officials expect the Sinatra 'Bird to
bring well in excess of $125,000.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the way it goes with so many of the vintage cars, how
the celebrity touch or some other piece of historic magic boosts
the value of an automobile. Two years ago, Jerry Seinfeld sold a
1954 Porsche 356 Speedster for a record price: $82,950.
</P>
<P>
   At this auction, John Lennon's Roll-Royce limousine is up for
sale. And Fonda is expected to autograph the gas tank of the
Captain America chopper for whomever is fortunate enough to win it.
</P>
<P>
   The bidding reaches a fevered pitch as people vie for their
hearts' desires. Friday morning, an automobilia auction is under
way. People are in hot pursuit of old automotive artworks, toys and
collectibles, some going for top dollar, some surprisingly cheap.
</P>
<P>
   There, up on the big auction stage where thousands of expensive
cars have gone on the block, a veteran classic-car auctioneer holds
up a small metal toy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What am I bid for this exquisite Rolls-Royce Dinky toy, only
missing one headlight?''
</P>
<P>
   It sold for 50 bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Katz of Boston was waiting in line to claim his automobilia
prize, as pair of 1920s car trunks, the kind that fastened to racks
at the rear of automobiles in the days before cars had built in
trunks. He crowed about paying just $200 for something that easily
could have gone five times that much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stole them, a hundred bucks apiece,'' Katz said. ``I have a
'24 Packard coupe and a '30 Packard rumble-seat roadster, and these
will go great on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz said he travels to Scottsdale every year for the auction.
This year he was here to buy _ what else? _ another Packard.
</P>
<P>
   Also waiting to pick up his automobilia was Jerry Capizzi of
Chicago, who had paid $40 for a simple brass oil can, vying for it
only because it was embossed with the Ford logo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Ford fanatic,'' Capizzi said. ``I have Ford blue in my
veins.''
</P>
<P>
   Out among the expensive automotive jewels are quite a few
automobiles that regular folk can afford. Old Fords, small British
and Italian sports cars, befinned '50s behemoths, even Volkswagen
Beetles and a restored microbus will cross the block.
</P>
<P>
   It's a great opportunity to pick up a gem, or get a bit too
caught up in things and end up with a real expensive white
elephant.
</P>
<P>
   But of course, beauty is in the eye of the beholder. For Cameron
Thieriot of Occidental, Calif., his auction prize was a Porsche,
but not quite what you'd expect.
</P>
<P>
   It's a 1962 Porsche diesel tractor, 15 horsepower, painted red
and described in the auction literature as ``very unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   So why would someone travel from Occidental, Calif., to buy a
Porsche tractor at auction?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to paint it a Porsche color,'' Thieriot said, ``and
use it for my vineyard.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
