<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEWAY-FIX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR ACCELERATES IMPROVEMENT PLANS FOR SOUTHLAND FREEWAY
INTERCHANGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ At Gov. Gray Davis' urging, a plan to ease
gridlock on the 101-405 freeway interchange will be moved up by at
least a year so construction could begin by early 2001, state
officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is to add a lane to the connector road from the
northbound San Diego Freeway to the eastbound Ventura Freeway and
build another on the northbound 405 from Mulholland Drive to
Ventura Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   State Transportation Commissioner David Fleming predicted that
the improvements will sharply reduce congestion on California's
fourth-busiest interchange, which was designed 44 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big step. Clearly, it's going to eliminate half or more
of this gridlock,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With strong support for the improvements from L.A.-area
legislators, Davis has recognized that congestion on the 101-405
freeway interchange must be solved, his spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Davis has outlined the need to update California's
transportation system, it's one of his priorities, and the 101-405
interchange is one of the busiest in the state,'' said Chris
Campana, spokesman for the governor. ``Right now, money is
available, and I think today's action is an indication that funds
will be moving more quickly to critical projects.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Harris, director of the state Department of
Transportation's District 7, which includes Los Angeles County,
said Davis and area leaders pushed for the project to move faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the direction of Gov. Davis, Caltrans is stepping up its
efforts and commitment to provide congestion relief to the
motorists using the 101-405 interchange,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Caltrans, adding lanes to the interchange would
cost an estimated $14 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration feels confident that the projects will be
funded,'' Harris said. ``So why wait?''
</P>
<P>
   Caltrans' move follows a Metropolitan Transportation Authority
committee's unanimous vote Thursday to contribute a 20 percent
match to the $14 million proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The California Transportation Commission still must approve the
project, but Fleming said that is a certainty.
</P>
<P>
   Provided the project does not need a more detailed environmental
impact study, the two widening projects could be completed within
18 months, Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Also strongly pushing for acceleration of the project were
Assemblyman Wally Knox, D-Los Angeles; state Sen. Richard Alarcon,
D-Pacoima; and Maria Contreras-Sweet, secretary of the state's
Business, Transportation and Housing Agency
</P>
<P>
   ``This is major, major progress by Gov. Davis in less than a
month,'' said Knox, who was recently named chairman of a special
Assembly committee that will study the 101-405 congestion.
</P>
<P>
   Knox also credited the public for putting pressure on
transportation officials. ``The public response has been absolutely
overwhelming,'' Knox said.
</P>
<P>
   Knox and Fleming said legislation is needed to allow emergency
improvements at congested interchanges.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the transportation system was a hospital in California,
we've got a hospital without an emergency room. We need to build
emergency facilities for people who are in critical condition,''
Fleming said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't going to be elective surgery. It's going to require
some immediate first aid _ and that's what we're trying to do,''
Fleming said. ``There has to be long-range solutions, as well as
short-range _ to stop the bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   In the next few weeks, Caltrans will begin the design and
environmental review of proposed improvements to the clogged
interchange, Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Some steps will overlap: Caltrans will begin the environmental
review at the same time it does preliminary engineering for the
design of the lanes.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the environmental document phase precedes the
preliminary engineering phase, said Harris, who added that no
environmental rules will be relaxed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
