<HEADLINE>
NEW COACH WILL TRY TO SELL ISLES ON TRAPPING DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Coach Bill Stewart turned around the St. John
Flames, taking them from the basement of the American Hockey League
to Calder Cup contenders in one season. His formula for success was
simple: defense, defense, defense.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who replaced Mike Milbury as head coach of the New York
Islanders on Thursday, may be in the National Hockey League now,
but his philosophy is the same. ``I think you have to have a system
if you don't have the most talented team,'' Stewart said after his
debut, a 5-2 victory over the Penguins in Pittsburgh. ``You have to
do what suits your team.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart prefers the word ``system'' to ``neutral-zone trap,''
but the object is the same. The object is to strangle the
opposition by cutting off the passing lanes and forcing turnovers
in the neutral zone. This defensive strategy is often used by teams
with limited talent.
</P>
<P>
   The St. John Flames followed Stewart's blueprint, improved 27
points in the standing last season and recorded the lowest
goals-against average in the history of the AHL. But for Stewart's
system to be effective in the NHL, players like Zigmund Palffy,
Mariusz Czerkawski and Robert Reichel have to buy into it. If they
don't, the result will be the same as it was for the Islanders last
season, when they did not make the playoffs and coach Rick Bowness
lost his job.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart did not have enough time to install his system before
Thursday's game. But when the Islanders (14-29-3) return from the
All-Star Game break on Monday, Stewart will begin the hardest sell
of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who is negotiating a two-year contract with the
Islanders, played 10 seasons as a defenseman in the NHL, with
Buffalo, St. Louis, Toronto and Minnesota. He is considered to be a
good communicator, and very intense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got a bunch of misfits to want to play,'' said the
Islanders' Steve Webb, who played for Stewart at Muskegon of the
Colonial League during the 1995-96 season. ``It was amazing what he
did there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 2314EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
