<SLUG> BC-GLF-HOPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNK LEADS HOPE CLASSIC BY A STROKE 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By CLIFTON BROWN    
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA QUINTA, Calif. _ Ten years ago, Fred Funk was a 32-year-old
golf coach at the University of Maryland hoping to reach the PGA
Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Call Funk a late bloomer. Call him determined. But 10 years
after finally making the tour, Funk has evolved into one of the
game's most consistent players, and he has begun 1999 as if it
might be a career-best year.
</P>
<P>
   Starting the day with a two-stroke lead, Funk shot a
six-under-par 66 to maintain a one-stroke lead through three rounds
of the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic. Funk stood at 17 under par (199)
for the five-day, 90-hole tournament, one stroke ahead of Steve
Pate, and two strokes ahead of both John Daly and Tom Pernice Jr.
</P>
<P>
   For Funk, it was a continuation of strong early-season play. He
has broken 70 in eight of his 11 rounds this year. He tied for
fifth place at the season-opening Mercedes Championships and tied
for 12th last week at the Sony Open in Hawaii. Having already won
$147,550 this year, Funk is eyeing this weekend's $540,00
first-place check.
</P>
<P>
   At 42, making the tour was worth the wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``My expectations are to improve each year, and so far I've been
able to do it,'' said Funk, who earned a career-best $1.21 million
last year. ``No question I'm a late bloomer. I wasn't that good
when I was in my 20's. In college, as a junior player, I just
wasn't that good.''
</P>
<P>
   Conditions were ideal today. Jonathan Kaye set the course record
with a 10-under-par 62 at Tamarisk Country Club, one of four
courses on which the tournament is being played. Kaye broke the
previous record of 63, set by Johnny Miller and matched by Bob
Estes.
</P>
<P>
   Birdies could be had and Funk took advantage at the Palmer
Course at PGA West. He had an eagle, seven birdies, a bogey and a
double bogey. Instead of losing his composure after a bad hole,
Funk responded. After he three-putted for bogey at No. 1, Funk made
an eagle at the par-5, 514-yard No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Funk was tested again at the par-3 No. 5, when he missed the
green with his tee shot, chipped on, then three-putted for a double
bogey. But he regained his momentum, playing six under par over the
final 11 holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the key stretch of my tournament,'' Funk said. ``I
turned the whole tournament back into a positive when I was going
the wrong way.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly also remained in the hunt with a 66 at Indian Wells Country
Club. Having not won an official event since the 1995 British Open,
Daly is eager. ``I think I'm due,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, with two rounds left, nothing has been finalized, and a
host of players entered the weekend with a legitimate chance to
win. One player to watch will be David Duval, the tour's hottest
player, who moved into a tie for sixth place (11 under par) after
shooting a 64 at Indian Wells. Duval has eight victories in his
last 27 starts. If Duval remains in contention into Sunday's final
round, no one will have more confidence.
</P>
<P>
   But Funk also likes his chances. He played in Sunday's final
twosome with Duval at the Mercedes Championships, and though Duval
pulled away and won the tournament by nine strokes, Funk learned
from the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played pretty good, and I felt comfortable,'' Funk said. ``I
just didn't putt well that day. Even though I don't have the game
David Duval has, I can beat anybody on a given day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
