<SLUG> BC-LA-DRIVERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY THINK DRIVING UNSAFE, WITH THEMSELVES PLAYING A ROLE, SURVEY
FINDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY MICHAEL COIT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Forget crime, it's down sharply. Americans' big
worry these days is driving _ 98 percent of the nation's drivers
want something done about the threat to their personal safety posed
by speeding and unsafe driving.
</P>
<P>
   The survey released Friday by the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration found concern about unsafe and aggressive
driving is increasing.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, those surveyed admitted they too were part of the
problem _ entering intersections as signals turned red, rolling
through stop signs and speeding on freeways.
</P>
<P>
   The results back what California Highway Patrol and local police
officers are already doing: cracking down on motorists who make
streets and highways more dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go to community meetings all the time and it's kind of
amazing,'' said Sgt. Michael Harrington, motor supervisor for the
Los Angeles Police Department's Valley Traffic Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``With gangs, narcotics, robberies, all these other issues that
we would think would be quality-of-life issues, usually what comes
up first in these meetings is traffic. They are concerned with the
speed on their streets and the safety of their children.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Dominguez of Lancaster, Calif., agreed with those surveyed
who said more people are driving more aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some days they just try to run you off the road,''
Dominguez said of his daily drive to work. ``You're not fast enough
when they're coming up on your tail. Too slow is 65.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey, released at the start of a two-day symposium on
aggressive driving, was conducted in two parts by telephone in 1997
to learn more about the public's experiences and beliefs. A total
of 6,000 interviews were completed with drivers 16 and older. One
focused on speeding and one on other forms of unsafe driving.
</P>
<P>
   The results led federal transportation officials to assert their
commitment to stricter enforcement of the nation's traffic laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aggressive driving patterns, such as speeding and red-light
running, are violations of the law, and this symposium will
consider how the courts can best enforce them and thus improve
safety for all motorists,'' said Rodney E. Slater, U.S.
transportation secretary.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the respondents reported that they see
vehicles traveling at unsafe speeds all or most of the time they
drive on residential streets, and interstate and non-interstate
highways.
</P>
<P>
   The other types of unsafe driving they encounter on the roads
they regularly drive are: cars weaving in and out of traffic, 24
percent; tailgating, 17 percent; driver inattention, 15 percent;
unsafe lane changes, 10 percent; unsafe passing, 9 percent;
ignoring stop signs, 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   One-third said it was more dangerous now. The reasons they gave
were: more traffic and cars, 33 percent; careless and inattentive
drivers, 20 percent; faster drivers, 18 percent; increased speed
limits, 16 percent; aggressive driving, 14 percent; young drivers,
10 percent; and drunk drivers, 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about aggressive driving specifically, 30 percent
thought drivers in their area were driving a lot or somewhat more
aggressively than a year ago. Speeding and unsafe driving actions
by other people were considered major threats by 61 and 66 percent,
respectively, of those questioned.
</P>
<P>
   The potential perils of driving from the L.A. suburb of Woodland
Hills to Redondo Beach four days a week on the perpetually packed
San Diego Freeway drives Bonnie Dirks to be a particularly
defensive driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too many cars. The changing the lanes or trying to get
ahead is a concern,'' Dirks said. ``They're all huffing and
puffing, and are usually on the phone telling people they will be
late.''
</P>
<P>
   Motorists surveyed also acknowledged that they can be part of
the problem. About two-thirds reported they at least occasionally
exceed what they consider to be the maximum safe speed on roads
they regularly use.
</P>
<P>
   The leading violations admitted by those surveyed were: entering
an intersection just as the light was turning red, 30 percent;
slowing, but not completely stopping at a stop sign, 26 percent;
and driving 10 miles per hour over the speed limit on an
interstate, 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Getting motorists to admit speeding or unsafe driving is an
important element in making streets and highways safer, said
Officer Ed Sandoval with the Glendale regional office of the
California Highway Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Sandoval seems to always find signs of hope when teaching
traffic school to motorists eligible for the diversion program.
</P>
<P>
   ``In talking to them, the majority of them are there for speed.
I always ask them, How many of you felt that you deserved more
tickets than you have at this present time, and everybody raises
their hand,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're aware of their habits and that there are times they
are out there contributing to the problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 2323EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
