<DOCNO> NYT19990122.0507 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5296 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-PRICE-DEATH-630&AMP;A     01-22 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PRICE-DEATH-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PLAYER'S UNSETTLING END LEAVES QUESTIONS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Pa., Texas)   By LENA WILLIAMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ After the death of her parents, Katrina
Price did as she always had done to salve her soul in times of
trouble: she turned to basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The sport was both her passion and emotional outlet from the
moment she began playing the game as a young girl on the
playgrounds of Waco, 150 miles from here. Basketball remained with
her through high school in Bellmead, Texas, where she was an
academic and athletic standout, through college at Stephen F.
Austin State University, where she again starred on the court and
in the classroom, then began her pro career with the Philadelphia
Rage of the American Basketball League.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm on the court, I can block everything out,'' the
5-foot-10-inch guard often told friends and teammates.
</P>
<P>
   But last month, the ABL abruptly shut down. Price, at 23, found
herself for the first time facing life without the game.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday she died of a gunshot wound to the head in an
apartment she shared with a sister here. The police believe she
shot herself.
</P>
<P>
   Her family and many in this small east Texas community known for
its piney woods, collegial atmosphere and American Indian name, are
grief-stricken and stunned. They also wonder whether the prospect
that she might never play again competitively _ and never to redeem
what had been an unimpressive rookie year _ may have been too
daunting for her to bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she had so many mountains to climb with losing both of
our parents,'' Glenda Shead, one of the nine sisters, said Tuesday
in an interview with The Associated Press. ``She was not busy
playing basketball anymore and I think she had some time to think
about everything that had happened to her. We just didn't know
something like this was going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Others also speculate what happened to Price, the high school
salutatorian who graduated from college cum laude with a bachelor's
degree in education and a player whose numerous accolades included
career scoring leader at Stephen F. Austin, a USA Today
all-American and the seventh overall draft pick of the ABL last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The death of the popular 5-foot-10-inch player known as Sugar, a
nickname included in her obituary and one that befitted her
on-court style as well as her demeanor, has left many here,
including the police, with unsettling thoughts and unanswered
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Price reportedly left two notes addressed to the family.
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Armor Webb, 25, befriended Price when the two played for
opposing junior high school teams and the two became best friends
when they played together at Stephen F. Austin a few years back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been lying awake at night thinking about the last time we
talked,'' Armor Webb recently said at a restaurant near where she
works as the director of cardiac rehabilitation at a doctor's
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was right before we played Northwestern State,'' she said
of the game the Stephen F. Austin women played on Saturday. ``I
asked her about the ABL folding and she said, `Man, I don't want to
talk about it.' But the tone she used wasn't _ what _ down or
anything. It was just Katrina talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Armor Webb has replayed that conversation and others over in her
head to try to make sense of her friend's death. For instance, she
noticed that Price had recently lost weight. She asked about it but
Price shrugged it off, saying she had been working off a few pounds
in order to get quicker on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this had been anyone other than Katrina, it may have
worried me,'' said Armor Webb. ``In hindsight, maybe I should have
asked more about the ABL, but Katrina was also a private person. In
all the years I've known her, I can't say whether or not she had a
boyfriend. But believe me, no one would have thought she was
capable of something like this.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Basketball was the thread that bound Price and her eight sisters
together, especially after their parents' deaths, her mother,
Daisy, of cancer in 1993 and her father, Leo, of a heart attack her
senior year in college. The sisters, ranging in ages from 20 to 40,
were her biggest fans and often attended games, even those hours
away from the university.
</P>
<P>
   Price, who had received her undergraduate degree in kinesiology
in 1998, had enrolled in Stephen F. Austin to pursue a master's
degree in education
</P>
<P>
   Around 5 a.m. last Monday, a despondent Price reportedly
telephoned Shead in Kilgore, Texas, telling her she was deeply
depressed.
</P>
<P>
   Price apparently had composed herself after the hourlong
conversation and told her sister she was going back to bed,
according to Armor Webb. Approximately one hour later, Price's
younger sister, Lucrettia, was awakened by the sound of a gunshot.
</P>
<P>
   The police arrived around 7 a.m. and found Price's body in a
bedroom. A shotgun was under her body.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Ralph Ervin, one of several Nacogdoches police officers
conducting the investigation into Price's death, said the police
believed the fatal shot was self-inflicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to find out how she came into the possession of a
shotgun,'' said Ervin.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is legal in Texas to possess a shotgun similar to
the one found next to Price, the police are attempting to discover
where the weapon was purchased.
</P>
<P>
   Just as it has for so many in this city, Price's death has
touched even professionals like Ervin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only two numbers that have been going through my head
these past few days are 23 and 44,'' said Ervin, referring to
Price's age and team jersey number. ``I saw her play. She was an
extremely talented young lady.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 200 people attended a memorial service held in Bellmead,
last night at La Vega High School, Price's alma mater. Among those
seated on the stage in the school auditorium was the mayor of
Bellmead, who read a proclamation from the city council declaring
Friday as a day of mourning for Katrina Rosha Price, the
superintendent of schools in La Vega and several members of a local
school board.
</P>
<P>
   Seated in the audience were classmates, parents, teachers and
basketball fans. Many of them broke down when one of the Price
sisters began screaming while a soloist sang ``Wing Beneath My
Wings,'' a song that pays tribute to those who willingly avoid the
limelight and let other share the glory.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday friends, relatives and fans will gather for her
funeral. Saturday's game between the Lady Jacks and the University
of Texas at Arlington was postponed due to another tragedy. The son
of the Texas-Arlington coach, Eddie McCarter, was killed during a
carjacking in Birmingham, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Armor Webb plans to attend the service in Oakwood although she
knows it will not bring the closure she is seeking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may never know what happened to Katrina,'' said Armor Webb,
currently on the Stephen F. Austin team and Price's best friend.
``The only thing I can think of is that maybe she felt everything
was going to be all right now because she was going to be with her
mom and dad.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
