<HEADLINE>
INS SPEEDS UP PROCESS OF APPROVING APPLICANTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY YVETTE CABRERA  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When legal U.S. residents were faced with losing
federal benefits, L.A.-area resident Miguel Contreras Vallarta
decided it was time that he became a U.S. citizen. But he had one
major worry.
</P>
<P>
   Contreras, who emigrated from Mexico, had heard the horror
stories of friends who applied for citizenship only to wait as long
as two years before the Immigration and Naturalization Service
processed their paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to measures adopted by the INS to address the
nationwide backlog of 1.8 million people waiting to become
Americans, immigrants like Contreras are waiting dramatically
shorter periods and are, in fact, naturalizing ahead of those
applicants caught in the backlog.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God I was lucky ... the process wasn't delayed,'' said
Contreras, 30, who waited about 10 months before taking his
citizenship oath last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy because I've been in this country for 16 years,
and I wanted to take advantage of the situation since they were
taking away benefits from residents.''
</P>
<P>
   Immigration agencies like the San Juan Macias Orientation
Immigrant Center in Pacoima, an L.A.-area suburb, said the reduced
waiting period is unprecedented. Immigrants who applied at the
center's citizenship drive last May are today U.S. citizens,
according to center spokesman Felipe Kofman.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as new applicants are concerned, the steps that the INS
has taken are incredible from what they were,'' Kofman said.
</P>
<P>
   Measures the INS has implemented to reduce the backlog _ which
in the Los Angeles district numbers at 382,500 applications _
include hiring 300 employees nationwide to ensure applications are
complete, creating a national telephone customer service center and
computerized fingerprinting services, and centralizing the INS' 25
million paper files to reduce retrieval time.
</P>
<P>
   While computerized fingerprinting services have allowed the INS
to speed up the citizenship process, that same automated system is
causing problems in the process as well.
</P>
<P>
   This month, INS service centers mistakenly sent 5,000 notices
nationwide informing applicants who filed before an increased
naturalization fee took effect that they owed an additional $130
and that their citizenship process would be delayed until they
paid.
</P>
<P>
   The citizenship processing fee hike from $95 to $225 went into
effect Jan. 15. In fact, those applicants, 2,500 of whom reside in
the INS Los Angeles District, did file before Jan. 15 and were only
obligated to pay the $95 fee, said Jane Arellano, assistant
district director for adjudications in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an automated system error, and possibly somebody wasn't
careful when they generated the notices,'' Arellano said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The INS plans to send a second notice after Feb. 1 informing
applicants that the proper fee was received, that the application
process will continue and that no additional money is required,
Arellano said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to receiving 30 of these notices for applicants who
filed from the San Juan Macias center, Kofman said his office was
flooded with phone calls from concerned applicants this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's probably going to be a lot of folks who didn't apply
at a center like our own, and when they receive the notice, they'll
be totally shocked,'' said Kofman, who advised applicants to keep
the notices as proof of payment.
</P>
<P>
   Kofman's center has also received calls from applicants caught
in the backlog who are displeased that newer applicants are being
processed faster. Arellano said the INS did not intend to process
applicants out of turn and is remedying the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We identified that July 1998 filings were getting scheduled
for interviews, but we've since stopped that because we do want
backlogs and older cases to have precedence,'' Arellano said.
</P>
<P>
   Applications weren't being processed chronologically because the
fingerprints of older cases were outdated and had to be refiled,
Arellano said. In addition, criminal records, required of all
applicants, are often difficult to obtain and delay the process for
the backlogged applicants. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
