<SLUG> BC-NY-CHILDWELFARE-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE APPROVES SETTLEMENT IN CHILD-WELFARE SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By NINA BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge on Friday approved the sweeping
settlement of a 1995 federal class-action lawsuit against New York
City's troubled child-welfare system, rejecting a last-minute
objection by advocates for gay and lesbian youths in foster care,
and in the process ending 26 years of litigation that sought the
system's overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement in Marisol vs. Giuliani opens the city's
Administration for Children's Services to intense independent
scrutiny by a panel of experts over the next two years. It also
sets a moratorium on new class-action lawsuits during that period.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, the agreement dissolves the Wilder Settlement,
the decree in a lawsuit originally filed in 1973, which was
supposed to ensure that all children in need of foster care were
placed fairly and according to their needs.
</P>
<P>
   In approving the settlement, Judge Robert Ward of U.S. District
Court in Manhattan effectively closed the door on Joel A. vs.
Giuliani, a lawsuit brought last week as a class action on behalf
of a group of gay, lesbian and bisexual youths in foster care.
</P>
<P>
   That lawsuit was brought by the Urban Justice Center, a
nonprofit advocacy organization for the homeless, and lawyers at
Paul, Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton &AMP; Garrison, working pro bono. It
charges that because of the plaintiffs' sexual orientation, they
are routinely subjected to physical abuse by peers and
child-welfare staff members.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agreements provide no direct, concrete or effective relief
from the daily devastation suffered by class members,'' Doug
Lasdon, director of the Urban Justice Center, contended, calling
the settlement's promise ``wholly illusory.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge disagreed, finding that the special needs of the
children in the Joel lawsuit would be covered in the Marisol
settlement. Its plaintiffs can still seek relief and damages
through the courts as individuals.
</P>
<P>
   The Marisol lawsuit was filed shortly after the notorious
beating death of Elisa Izquierdo, a 6-year-old who was killed by
her mother while under the city's watch.
</P>
<P>
   The suit sought the takeover of the child-welfare system by a
receiver. But at Friday's hearing a succession of advocates and
city officials praised the settlement as a more effective means of
building on the reforms being instituted by Nicholas Scoppetta, the
agency's commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   The Marisol and Wilder lawsuits were brought by Marcia Robinson
Lowry, now the director of a national advocacy organization,
Children's Rights Inc. Marisol, a child who almost starved to death
in a closet while she was in the city's child-protection system,
has now been adopted by a loving family ``because of this
lawsuit,'' Ms. Lowry said.
</P>
<P>
   But in urging Ward to approve the accord at a hearing Friday,
she invoked the fate of her original plaintiff, then a 13-year-old
girl named Shirley Wilder, who died last Sunday at 39, alone in a
hospice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in foster care shouldn't mean that you grow up to die
alone,'' Ms. Lowry said, obviously fighting back tears. She told
the judge that the new settlement was ``the best chance for making
sure that other children don't have the experience Shirley had.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-22-99 2339EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
