s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARMAKERS-SALES-$ADV2     01-22 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARMAKERS-SALES-$ADV24-ART-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW DEAL ON CAR DEALERS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Okla., Calif., Texas, Australia, Britain, Canada, New
Zealand)  (Eds: For release Sunday, Jan. 24) 
(ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TULSA, Okla. _ Donald Thornton, a successful Ford dealer here
for many years, still recalls his anger on the day three decades
ago when his daughter Kathy, then 7, came home from a birthday
party in tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``This little kid next to her _ the little worm, I could choke
him _ leaned over and said, `My daddy says all car salesmen are
crooks,''' Thornton recounted recently, sitting at the scarred wood
desk across which he has been selling cars since 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. and General Motors Corp. have long worried that
the little boy's father was right _ at least in some cases.
Unscrupulous dealers have tarnished car brands and undercut their
rivals, eroding profits for automakers and honest dealers alike.
</P>
<P>
   So, after nearly a century of relying on independent dealers to
sell their cars and trucks, the two automakers, the world's
largest, have begun separate moves into the retail end of the
business. They have started setting up retailing ventures in
partnership with dealers like Thornton who have tried to pursue
more ethical ways of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   The ventures, in which the automakers typically hold 20 percent
to 30 percent of the stock, buy up all the automakers' dealerships
in a city and then set uniform business practices at every site. In
most cases, they also set the same prices for vehicles at all of
their outlets and do not allow negotiation. By eliminating local
competition among dealerships, the automakers may be able to
increase profits at the retail level. Some of that money, they
hope, will be invested in better showrooms that will make their
cars and trucks look more attractive, thereby increasing sales.
</P>
<P>
   Even some consumer advocates are pleased, welcoming almost any
change as an improvement over traditional sales tactics, despite
the slightly higher prices that might result.
</P>
<P>
   But setting up and running the retailing operations has proved
harder than anticipated. Ford dealerships here in Tulsa have lost
close to two dozen of their 160 sales representatives over a switch
from commissions to salaries, and more than a dozen of their 180
mechanics who were leery of management changes. Ford's market share
here has fallen. Whatever consumer advocates say, many customers,
after decades of haggling to buy cars, distrust any dealership that
will not allow them to bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Byrd, 57, a mail carrier, checked prices at downtown Ford
dealers last fall and was angry that no one would negotiate. ``I
would call it price-fixing,'' Byrd said, standing in the showroom
of a dealership in Claremore, northeast of Tulsa, where he had gone
instead to buy a white Ford F-350 pickup truck for less.
</P>
<P>
   Auto executives and antitrust lawyers say that consolidating the
ownership of a single automaker's dealerships and setting common
prices is ethical and legal, although half the states put some
limits on manufacturers' ownership of dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   James F. Rill, the assistant attorney general for antitrust in
the Bush administration, said that each partnership is a single
legal entity no matter how many dealerships it owns and so cannot
be accused of illegal collusion to fix prices. Because most cities
also have dealerships that sell Chevrolets, Dodges, Hondas and
other brands, he added, the partnerships cannot be accused of
monopolizing local auto markets.
</P>
<P>
   Given the level of competition among brands, it is hard for any
dealer to raise prices beyond what a given car or truck justifies.
</P>
<P>
   Despite initial problems, Ford has big plans for expansion,
while G.M. is moving in the same direction but more cautiously.
Both are trying to act quickly because they are alarmed by Republic
Industries, the auto retailer based in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., that
has bought nearly 400 franchises _ mostly big, highly profitable
dealerships _ in the last two years. Ford and GM are wary of losing
too much control over their retail distribution networks to H.
Wayne Huizenga, the billionaire chairman of Republic, or to other
consolidators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an opportunity for us to react now, or wait and watch
some of the publicly traded corporations take some of the
strongest'' dealerships, said Ross H. Roberts, president of Ford
Investment Enterprises, the new subsidiary that is setting up the
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Ford wants to strengthen already successful franchises in
growing, midsize cities by having them work together. GM's strategy
is more defensive, aimed at fixing weak dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   Ford already has helped create companies that own all of its
Ford and Lincoln-Mercury dealerships in Tulsa and Oklahoma City,
and both of its Lincoln-Mercury dealerships in San Diego. Ford has
plans for similar partnerships in Salt Lake City and Rochester,
N.Y., in the next two months. The automaker is negotiating more
retailing partnerships in nine other United States cities this
year, as well as in cities in Australia, Britain, Canada and New
Zealand, Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   GM has set up retailing companies to own dealerships in
Baltimore, Houston and the San Fernando Valley in California, and
is considering a number of ventures elsewhere, said Ronald
Zarrella, the GM president for North American operations.
</P>
<P>
   But only the San Fernando Valley operation, which involves 10
franchises at five dealerships that used to have extremely low
market shares, is trying to set no-haggle prices. The Baltimore and
Houston ventures are aimed at consolidating the ownership of
Pontiac-GMC dealerships and helping black dealers expand in those
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's approach is influenced by the iconoclastic sales
techniques that GM pioneered for its Saturn models. All Saturn
stores already use one-price selling, and in many cities, all
Saturn stores are owned by the same dealer, eliminating
competition. GM is also setting up Saturn Retail Enterprises, a
separate company that plans to buy as many as 150 of the 400 Saturn
dealerships nationwide. The retailer may make an initial public
offering of stock in a year or two but is not trying to change
Saturn's approach to selling, said Donald Hudler, president of the
new company.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan has long owned a minority stake in a third of its
dealerships in Japan, according to Minoru Nakamura, the chief
executive and president of Nissan North America. But, he said,
these dealerships tend to perform worse than the truly independent
dealerships, and Nissan might sell its stakes if anyone wanted
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you own, you work 24 hours a day, seven days a week,''
Nakamura said. At dealerships with partial corporate ownership, he
added, ``you work eight hours and take weekends and holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler experimented several years ago with different ways to
sell cars and concluded that dealers did best when left alone _
particularly in weak markets, where an entrepreneur might be able
to cut costs, lay off staff and lower prices more easily than a
corporation could.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Ford's headquarters in Dearborn, Mich., and car
dealers in Tulsa vow that the new ventures will be entrepreneurial
and flexible. ``I've got 100 percent of my dealership assets
invested in this operation,'' said Fred J. Hall, the chief
executive of the Oklahoma City retailing company, which started
operations on Jan. 7. ``That makes me want to work very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In addition to fixed prices, the Oklahoma dealerships have
changed the way sales representatives are paid _ salaries plus
bonuses based on the number of vehicles sold, instead of sales
commissions. Consumer advocates loathe the industry's traditional
commissions, typically 20 percent to 35 percent of a dealership's
profit on a vehicle. That pay structure, they say, gives sales
representatives an incentive to quote as high an initial price as
possible on each vehicle, so as to maximize profit for both the
dealer and the employee making the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also say the commission system prompts sales agents to
give most of their attention to customers who are interested in
high-profit models, like the Ford Expedition, Chevrolet Suburban
and other sport utility vehicles. Buyers of small cars can be
largely ignored, because little if any money is made on these
typically overstocked vehicles that sell for close to the dealers'
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Industry consultants say that no-haggle dealerships charge $100
to $200 a vehicle more than a good bargainer would pay by
negotiating. Yet Jack Gillis, an automotive retailing expert at the
Washington-based Consumer Federation of America, said the
elimination of haggling and of commissions was good for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the reaction from customers in Oklahoma to the new Ford
partnerships has, indeed, been mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Michael L. Robine, a 31-year-old computer programmer who
recently bought a Ford F-150 pickup truck at a Ford outlet in
Oklahoma City, was happy not to have to spend hours negotiating the
price for a new set of wheels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found a truck that I liked and the price was pretty good _ I
even checked on the Internet,'' he said as he waited for the
paperwork on his shiny, bright red pickup to be completed. ``I
wonder if you can get a better price if you really sit down with
someone and negotiate. But I'm not someone who really likes to get
in a fight, and sometimes that's what it can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Marcia Lynch, a 56-year-old teacher, was furious earlier
this month when she took her 1995 Ford Windstar minivan to two Ford
dealerships in Oklahoma City, only to be offered the same trade-in
price at both, with no room to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was `You do it our way or no way,''' Mrs. Lynch said. ``And
I don't like that. I feel it's degrading and demeaning.'' She said
she got a better deal by trading in her old minivan for a new one
at Cooper's dealership in Midwest City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although the Oklahoma City partnership has not been running long
enough for its success or failure to be judged, the Tulsa
partnership, Ford's first, has had serious problems, executives in
Tulsa and in Dearborn acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Employees who were used to ordering new vehicles from the
factory for single dealerships were suddenly asked to work together
in ordering for all six Ford and Lincoln-Mercury dealerships in
Tulsa, and they did not increase the size of their orders
accordingly. As a result, the Ford operations did not have enough
vehicles to sell when a strike crippled GM Ford's local market
share actually fell then, even as it was rising nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Rival dealers, including some Ford dealers, have responded
aggressively to the new venture in Tulsa. Advertisements have
warned, ``One price is a high price,'' as some dealers have vowed
to beat the partnerships' fixed prices, even if by only $50 or
$100. Similar tactics stopped many dealerships' experiments with
fixed-price selling several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The rivals here have hired sales representatives and mechanics
away from the Ford retailing experiment. But Robert L. Rewey,
Ford's group vice president for marketing, sales and service, said
that the departure of sales agents from the Tulsa dealerships had
provided an opportunity for the new venture to hire more women and
members of minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors are also taking advantage of the Ford partnerships'
pledge to pay customers the appraised value of their used vehicles,
regardless of brand, even if the customers do not actually trade
them in on new cars or trucks. Dealers like Rodney O. Maupin, who
sells Chevrolets and Nissans in Tulsa, now send customers over to
the Ford dealerships to collect cash for their vehicles and then
bring it back as a down payment on a new Chevy or Nissan. Maupin
said he had sent only a few customers, though other dealers had
sent more.
</P>
<P>
   Ford plans to keep the cash policy because it builds good will
with customers.
</P>
<P>
   But the carmaker is also trying to learn from some of the
mistakes made here in Tulsa. Here, there was a delay of nearly
three months in starting the operation after it was announced, but
in Oklahoma City, six months later, the retailing venture was in
operation in less than four weeks. Hall met all 1,000 employees of
the 12 franchises in Oklahoma City to explain the changes. Partly
as a result of these moves, fewer than a half-dozen people have
left, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Tulsa venture also confused customers by changing the names
on its dealerships twice. First, the venture eliminated familiar
names like Don Thornton Ford, instead calling all of its outlets
Experience. A few months later, it renamed them as the Tulsa Auto
Collection, after Ford executives in Dearborn decided that the name
sounded more elegant and reflected the fact that the dealerships
were selling a bevy of Ford brands, including Jaguar, Mazda,
Lincoln and Mercury.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the dealerships in Oklahoma City have been renamed
just once, as the Fred Jones Auto Collection. That has a familiar
ring, since half the city's Ford franchises already were named for
Jones, who was Hall's grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   The natty Hall, 47, who was a deputy assistant secretary of
state in the Reagan administration and is the third-generation heir
to a family fortune from the airline, auto parts and auto
dealership industries, is cited by Ford officials as a model
retailing executive. He introduced fixed-price selling in his
family's dealerships in Tulsa and Oklahoma City in 1993, increasing
their sales, and played a large role last year in persuading Ford
to turn Oklahoma into the test bed for its new ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said he would not sell cars by any other means, especially
high-pressure haggling. ``I will not go the other way _ it is
anathema to my moral fiber,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Thornton, the Tulsa Ford dealer whose daughter cried upon
hearing her father being called a crook, is equally convinced,
after selling cars for most of his adult life, that fixed-price
selling must replace longstanding techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton experimented with fixed-price selling in the early
1990s and switched to a less stringent policy of low prices with a
narrow range of negotiation after other dealers undercut him; his
former showroom is hung with dozens of plaques and banners from
Ford, awards for seldom having customer complaints. Now he sees
citywide ventures with automaker support as a way to bring order to
the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton emphasized that he did not have to try Ford's
experiment. ``I was as happy as a pig in slop,'' he said. ``I was
64 years old. I had two sons-in-law in the business. I was doing
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   But two-thirds of car buyers these days, especially young
professionals, do not want to negotiate, and dealerships must
adjust, Thornton added. ``This,'' he said, ``is the wave of the
future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
