<HEADLINE>
QUARTEY VOWS TO BREAK DE LA HOYA'S BONES
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a few minutes, his manager, Fred Levin, was to be
honored for his public service and installed as a chief in the
Akuapem traditional area of Ghana in a ceremony Friday at the
United Nations. But first, Ike Quartey wanted to discuss how he was
going to break every bone in Oscar De La Hoya's body when the two
meet in a 12-round World Boxing Council welterweight championship
bout Feb. 13 in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to break all his bones, like a chicken, and divide
it into pieces,'' said Quartey, a native of Ghana, who also
received an award at the ceremony from Koby Koomson, Ghana's
ambassador to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey added about De La Hoya: ``I think he's a chicken. Of
course, I want to hurt him. I'm going to beat him. I'm too strong,
too fast. It's going to be a knockout fight.''
</P>
<P>
   The bout between Quartey (34-0-1) and De La Hoya (29-0) was
postponed from Nov. 21, when De La Hoya was cut on the left eyelid
in a sparring session at his California training camp. Quartey is
viewed as De La Hoya's toughest test yet.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Arum, the president of Top Rank, De La Hoya's promoter, said
about 12,000 tickets for the 19,000-seat arena have been sold. Arum
said the delay benefited De La Hoya in at least one way: after an
appearance on a Spanish-television talk show in which he sang, he
has been pursued by four Spanish-language record labels that want
to sign him to a recording contract.
</P>
<P>
   Arum said De La Hoya would sign a deal before the fight and
would spend three weeks in March recording his first album.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
