<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-22 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5316 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA--CLEMENSASTROS-HN     01-22 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA--CLEMENS </SLUG>
 ASTROS-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Clemens rekindles his interest in Astros
<TEXT>
<P>
   By EDDIE SEFKO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   LA QUINTA, Calif. _ The Astros' quest for Roger Clemens is
regaining strength.
</P>
<P>
   The five-time Cy Young Award winner and Houston resident said
Friday that the Astros are back in the hunt for his services. And
he wouldn't rule out starting spring training next month with the
Astros rather than with the Toronto Blue Jays, his current club.
</P>
<P>
   In his first public comments on the subject since saying Dec. 22
that he had no interest in playing for the Astros and rescinding
his request that the Blue Jays trade him, Clemens said he is open
to all possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're back in it,'' Clemens said of the Astros.
``The communication lines are still open and as long as that's the
case, anything can happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that door is shut by any means. I did voice some
displeasure over the way things were handled and how things were
turned around on me. But right now, I would say that anything is
possible and in that regard, the Astros are a possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is playing in the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic, a pro-am
event on several golf courses in the Palm Springs area.
</P>
<P>
   After completing his round Friday with pro Fred Couples and
Atlanta Braves pitcher Tom Glavine, Clemens said he doesn't want to
hold a grudge against the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was upset (last month) because of some of the things that
were said, and I came home early from vacation because of the
situation,'' Clemens said. ``I felt like it was necessary to tell
the Astros that I wasn't happy about the way the situation was
handled.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, 36, was asked if it would take some fence-mending, or
perhaps an apology, by Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker to
help facilitate his agreeing to a trade that would bring him to
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a process that will be done behind the scenes,'' he
said. ``That's the business side of the scene. All I'm worried
about is getting ready for the season, to play a game I love
playing. I have no control over the marketplace and that other end
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens was quick to emphasize he considers himself a Blue Jay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm in Toronto,'' Clemens said. ``That could change
in a couple of weeks. Or it could not change in a couple of weeks.
The only thing I'm doing right now is concentrating on my regular
workout schedule that I always start after the first of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm in Toronto, we'll try to win a championship there. If
I'm somewhere else, whether it's Houston or wherever, I'm still
going to start the season with the goal of trying to win a
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Spring training begins in a month. Any trade for Clemens likely
would mean the Astros parting with a significant amount of young
talent, as well as probably reworking Clemens' contract, which
calls for the pitcher to earn $16.1 million over the next two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 22, Clemens and his agents, Randy and Alan Hendricks,
called a news conference at which Clemens rescinded his Dec. 2
request to be traded by the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Also at the news conference, Clemens said he did not want to be
involved with the Astros as long as Hunsicker and club president
Tal Smith were running the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very upset at what Mr. Smith and Mr. Hunsicker said and
how they directed things towards me as a person,'' Clemens said
four weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   `I'd like to play in Houston. But we'll just have to see where
it goes from here. Like I said, if I'm in Toronto, I'll be happy
there, too.'Roger Clemens
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know them personally; they don't know me as a person.
I am not interested in working with or alongside those two
individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said Friday he still would consider it an honor to play
in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to play in Houston,'' he said. ``But we'll just have
to see where it goes from here. Like I said, if I'm in Toronto,
I'll be happy there, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens won his fifth Cy Young Award last season after going
20-6 with a 2.65 ERA. He has been one of the game's dominant
pitchers since coming out of the University of Texas in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   He alson won the 1997 Cy Young Award with the Blue Jays and won
Cy Youngs with the Boston Red Sox in 1986, 1987 and 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Trade talks in December centered on the Astros, New York
Yankees, Cleveland Indians and Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. was negotiating with Clemens'
agents in early December. After making an offer to McLane, Randy
Hendricks said he left the winter meetings in Nashville, Tenn.,
expecting to get a counteroffer from the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Hunsicker _ who had not been in contact with
McLane _ said the Astros were ending trade talks with the Blue Jays
and general manager Gord Ash.
</P>
<P>
   According to Clemens, the Astros and Blue Jays were close to
completing a trade before things fell apart. That led to him
rescinding his trade request and saying he was prepared to stay
with the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   It now appears Clemens is open to a resumption of trade talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
