<HEADER>
A5319 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPE24-COX     01-22 1499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Living in a new generation of the Catholic Church
 &HT;    By Charlise Lyles
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Andrea Truini remembers vividly the trip she took
to Vatican City in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was so excited about seeing the pope,'' she said.
``There were giant speakers, this little itsy-bitsy man and
hundreds of people swarming the piazza to see him. They had such
high appreciation for what he stood for.''
</P>
<P>
   Now a 21-year-old University of Dayton senior, Truini, of
Rochester, N.Y., still holds fast to that feeling. ``He is the Holy
Father, the one with a red phone line to God,'' she said on a
recent afternoon while sipping a Coke in the student union.
</P>
<P>
   But she also holds fast to pro-choice beliefs, defends friends
who are gay and believes that ``not using contraception because the
church says so is unrealistic for today's society. Telling people
not to have sex is not something the church should do.''
</P>
<P>
   When Pope John Paul II, 78 years old and ailing, makes his fifth
and likely final visit of his papacy to the United States this week
in St. Louis, he will beseech young adult Catholics like Truini to
embrace the Roman Catholic church's ``immutable'' teachings of
chastity, homosexual sex as sin, the absolute sanctity of life and
nonordination of women.
</P>
<P>
   Can they live their faith and bring those teachings into the
next millennium?
</P>
<P>
   They are the so-called Generation X, born after 1964, ages 18 to
35. They have come of age with divorce, open expression of
homosexuality, abortion, birth control, sexual freedom, women's
rights, euthanasia, assisted suicide, rampant consumerism and
materialism.
</P>
<P>
   And more than any other generation of Catholics, they have
witnessed their own church's sins come to light as case after case
of sexual abuse by priests has made newspaper headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Diocese of Dallas agreed to pay the victims of
sexual abuse by the Rev. Rudolph Kos $22.5 million, and the Vatican
took the rare step of defrocking Kos, 53. He is serving a life
prison sentence, convicted of sexual assault and indecency for
molesting four boys more than 1,350 times between 1987 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the 20- and 30-something crowd, an estimated one-fourth of
the nation's 61 million Catholics, say they accept church teaching
and Pope John Paul II as its highest teacher precisely because of
the taxing moral issues of their time. And they seek to play a
vibrant role in parishes that are home to the 547,000 registered
Catholics in the Archdiocese of Cincinnati, which includes Dayton.
A nationwide survey of 848 confirmed Catholics, age 20 to 39,
showed that 30 percent attend Mass weekly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is at least some evidence that young people
identify themselves very strongly with a Catholicism you might call
more traditional,'' said Sandra Yocum Mize, assistant professor of
religious studies at UD. ``They find themselves attracted to the
challenges the pope has issued: a challenge to chastity, to bring
Christ into the world, to stand against abortion, to stand for the
poor and against other kinds of social injustice. They are not a
majority, but they are a visible and vocal minority, certainly on
this campus.''
</P>
<P>
   Those less visible may have drifted from the church because
fewer Catholics are attending Catholic elementary and high schools,
said Dean Hoge, a sociology professor at Catholic University of
America in Washington, D.C. But the Cincinnati archdiocese's 134
Catholic elementary and high schools continue to be a mainstay of
religious education, where Catholics make up 87 percent of 57,994
enrolled students.
</P>
<P>
   Others point to an interfaith marriage rate of 50 percent, and a
shortage of parish priests as a hindrance to young adults becoming
active in the church. The number of priests has steadily dwindled.
Fewer priests make meaningful relationships more difficult and role
models less available, some priests say.
</P>
<P>
   Others may have been turned off by guilt and an inability to
reconcile personal behavior with strict church teachings, or
angered by abuse that the church has been slow to confront.
</P>
<P>
   Still others may have never bonded to the church because their
parents opted out. In Dayton and Cincinnati, a dramatic radio and
television advertising campaign and program titled ``Come Home''
calls them to return.
</P>
<P>
   But the call may be in vain, especially to a generation of women
who have grown up with more equal rights than any other in history.
``What should they do when they see unequal and unjust treatment in
their own church?'' asks Francis Kissling, president of Catholics
for a Free Choice in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the vehemence with which the pope has spoken against
women's ordination. He has said this is a closed topic _ no one
should talk about it,'' said Kissling. ``These kinds of statements
really are a barrier in terms of women's feeling of inclusion
within the church.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Sister Maureen Fideler of the Maryland-based advocacy group
Catholics Speak Out: ``To young women 18 to 30 it makes absolutely
no sense that women can't be priests. It makes no sense in terms of
the Gospel and no sense in terms of their life experience. The
majority believe that some day they are going to wake up and change
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Truini, the UD student, is puzzled over all the fuss. ``I've
never understood the desire to be a priest,'' she said. ``You can
do just as much and have a family, which would mean more to me than
being a celibate mother of a church.''
</P>
<P>
   Truini believes women can be just as effective in the role of
nuns, but says she knows few Catholic women who are genuinely
interested in religious life.
</P>
<P>
   Truini sees abortion, birth control and sexual orientation as
private matters. ``Sometimes the church's views are a little
outdated,'' she said. ``If you disagree with the teaching, you have
to go back to the Gospel and read it with your own viewpoint
because the Bible is a timeless story.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pope John Paul's uncompromising stance on abortion compells
Tim Bete, 36, of the Church of the Ascension in Kettering, and his
UD colleague, Carl Brown, 27, to make the six-hour trek by car to
St. Louis to see the Holy Father.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has written on the `culture of death.' Some people think of
pro-life as only abortion,'' said Bete. ``But he is able to
champion pro-life as birth, end-of-life issues, quality of life, as
well as death.''
</P>
<P>
   Bete, a father of two children, ages 3 and 1, added, ``The
church's teaching on contraceptives is hotly debated and something
he hasn't equivocated on. I think he is respected because he hasn't
bowed to what secular society doesn't even think is an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who is married and the father of an 18-month-old
daughter, agrees. ``It's the church that says contraception and
abortion hurt women. They do not provide choices to women, but lock
them into roles that are obsessively focused on sex and allow men
to be irresponsible,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Bete and Brown say they brainstorm for ways to share their faith
with others. Elsewhere in the United States, young Catholics are
engaged in the same effort.
</P>
<P>
   In the Archdiocese of Atlanta, where about 300,000 Catholics are
5 percent of the population of northern Georgia, ministries reach
the 20- and 30-something crowd with church advertisements on bar
restroom doors and in gym locker rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge, said Janice Murphy of the Office of Adult
Ministry in the Atlanta archdiocese, is to attract those who have
defined their spirituality outside the institution of the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel they can be spiritual enough by themselves, or in
nature,'' she said. ``They have a distrust for organized religion
in this generation. In a way, some don't want to be affiliated with
the pope. They see the church as just money-making, a business,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   At UD Campus Ministry, the Rev. Jim Fitz observes the same. ``I
see a great desire for spirituality and a sense of purpose and
meaning in life,'' said Fitz, 52.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is not the sense of commitment to institution that I
had. The institution is not as important to them. For example, a
number of young people are very committed to service and
volunteering. But students committed to working for institutional
change, such as justice issues like you had with civil rights in
the 1960s, I don't see that.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, 36, believes her generation craves the church's
2,000-year tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is rich in the lives of the saints, and in sacraments. I
think a lot of people our age want something to hold on to because
the world is so fast-changing, so fast-food,'' she said. ``They are
looking for a faith that stands up for something, not just health
and wealth, but stands up for human rights, social justice issues
and the sanctity of life. That's what I like about being Catholic.
I like being challenged to stand up for those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
